<SLUG> BC-FBN-MNF-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLER JOINS MNF TEAM IN FUNNY DECISION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Are you ready for some football, cha cha?
</P>
<P>
   Ending months of wild speculation about who would join Al
Michaels in the ``Monday Night Football'' booth, ABC revealed
Thursday that the wild guessing was justified as comedian Dennis
Miller emerged as the anointed one for one of the nation's most
high-profile sports TV positions.
</P>
<P>
   Also added to the broadcast team as an analyst is former NFL
quarterback great Dan Fouts. The new sideline reporters are former
Rams star and Hall of Famer Eric Dickerson, a longtime resident of
Calabasas, and ESPN's Melissa Stark, replacing Leslie Visser.
</P>
<P>
   Even though ``Monday Night Football'' finished third in
prime-time ratings overall last season, viewership has slipped the
past five seasons to a record low 13.7 points last season when
Michaels did the broadcast with former NFL quarterback Boomer
Esiason. The ratings had been up to 17.8 when Michaels worked with
former players Dan Dierdorf and Frank Gifford in 1994. A rating
point represents 1 percent of U.S. TV homes.
</P>
<P>
   But a year after Dierdorf and Gifford were let go, Esiason also
was released. Don Ohlmeyer, who guided ``Monday Night Football''
during its Howard Cosell-led heyday in the 1970s, was rehired in
March as the show's producer.
</P>
<P>
   Industry talk of who would work with Michaels and put a new
spark into the 27-year-old series ranged from conservative radio
talk-show host Rush Limbaugh to sports-talk host Jim Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Even Gifford's wife _ morning TV host Kathie Lee Gifford _ had
been mentioned as a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Miller, the former anchor of ``Weekend Update'' on
NBC's ``Saturday Night Live'' and now host of his own show on
cable's HBO, who was at the top of Ohlmeyer's list of potential
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   After an audition with Michaels 2 weeks ago in Los Angeles,
Miller remained Ohlmeyer's top choice and was signed to a
undisclosed contract Thursday morning before the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think at the time he'd be interested or capable of
doing it,'' Ohlmeyer said. ``About four or five weeks ago, he let
us know he was interested. He did the tape with Al, and the rest of
it is history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected to be entertained by Dennis and Al, which I was,
but I was knocked out by the observations he made. He brought a
fresh way of doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he thought his tryout went well, but he wasn't sure
if it was what Ohlmeyer wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do the best I can to be me. I think it'll play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get across that I know football. I won't ever try to
question anything like a player's fortitude. I'll try to stay in
the background and not pontificate on what someone should be or
shouldn't be. I'm a little odd and idiosyncratic with some quirky
ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Michaels, entering his 15th year as the show's play-by-play
announcer, gave Miller his stamp of approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew having watched him for years that he was very
perceptive. I walked out of that audition thinking he knew as much
about the National Football League as anyone brought in or I talked
to in the last several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was completely up to speed. I walked out during a break and
we (he and Ohlmeyer) looked at each other and we were completely
speechless. It wasn't something either of us expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohlmeyer said the audience will decide whether Miller's acerbic
approach works, but noted that ``football is a serious game, but
it's not played in St. Patrick's Cathedral. People want to watch
football and have an enjoyable time. We make the game relevant to
the hard-core fan, acceptable to the occasional fan and
unpredictable to both. This announcing team I think will be
unpredictable.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson, who has little broadcasting experience, said he is
``grateful for the opportunity'' and that ``unlike Dennis, I do
know football a little better. I know how players think. I'll have
different insight from the guys in the booth.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as long as it gets viewers talking about the show the way
they did when Cosell reigned with ``Dandy'' Don Meredith and
Gifford decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of creating a buzz _ there's nothing wrong with
that,'' Ohlmeyer said. ``There will probably be a buzz about this
(hiring) for a while, but I don't think we created anything just
for the buzz.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this doesn't work out, no amount of buzz will save us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
