<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2343 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-LAZIO-INVEST-NYT &LR;      06-23 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-INVEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEC LOOKS INTO LAZIO INVESTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD J. LEVY and FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission is investigating whether
Rep. Rick A. Lazio, the Republican candidate for Senate in New
York, violated insider trading laws when he made a nearly 600
percent profit in less than seven weeks by investing in securities
of a company controlled by some of his biggest campaign
contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio released a statement Thursday night saying that the
commission had asked him for copies of ``account statements and
trading records.'' He said he would provide all information
requested and would answer any questions from the commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reiterate today what I stated last week, that there is no
incidence in my financial transactions that involve any
improprieties,'' he said. ``I have repeatedly conducted myself,
privately and publicly, with the highest degree of integrity and
professionalism.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission's inquiry seems to be at a preliminary stage, and
many such requests for information do not lead to charges.
</P>
<P>
   A commission spokesman, Chris Ullman, declined to comment. ``We
can neither confirm nor deny the existence of any investigation,''
Ullman said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's campaign manager, Bill Dal Col, asserted that the
commission was undertaking the investigation at the behest of the
campaign of Lazio's Democratic opponent, Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Dal Col said the Clinton administration had a history of
``abusing federal authority'' for political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Dal Col questioned why word of the inquiry surfaced on the same
day that the independent counsel, Robert W. Ray, announced that he
had found substantial evidence that Clinton had played a role in
the firings at the White House travel office, though he declined to
file charges.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, a spokesman for Clinton, responded by saying
that ``desperate campaigns make desperate charges.''
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry appears to have been opened by the commission's
enforcement division, which is headed by Richard Walker, a lawyer
who joined the commission in 1991. The commission is composed of
five members appointed by the president and confirmed by the
Senate. No more than three members can be from one political party.
</P>
<P>
   One of Clinton's staunchest supporters, H. Carl McCall, the
state comptroller, called on the commission to investigate Lazio
earlier this week, citing an article about Lazio's investments in
The New York Times last Friday. But it appears that the commission
had begun its inquiry before being contacted by McCall.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said last week that he did not have inside information
when he earned a profit of roughly $13,500 in 1997 from speculative
options trades in the stock of the company, Quick &AMP; Reilly, his
first such options purchase in his life.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he had merely made a wise bet and that he was a
modest investor who had had mixed luck in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has declined to release his brokerage records or tax
returns, though his campaign says he will eventually release the
tax records. He reported the outlines of the Quick &AMP; Reilly trades
on disclosure forms that he is required to file with the House of
Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Salmans, a spokesman for Quick &AMP; Reilly, which was an
independent brokerage company before being acquired by the Fleet
Financial Group, declined to comment on whether Quick &AMP; Reilly
executives had been contacted by the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Two members of the Quick family who have been executives at the
company, Peter and Christopher C. Quick, have said they did not
discuss the firm's stock with Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of Quick &AMP; Reilly have been among Lazio's biggest
supporters, having donated at least $35,000 to his congressional
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The largest contributor is a senior executive, Pascal J.
Mercurio, who along with his wife has given $7,750 to the
campaigns. The Mercurios live in Lazio's district in Suffolk
County.
</P>
<P>
   Reached by telephone last week, Mercurio hung up when asked
about his relationship with Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio first bought Quick &AMP; Reilly stock in early 1997 and then
added more shares in June 1997, on the same day Quick &AMP; Reilly
hired an investment banker to seek buyers.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Aug. 1 of that year, Lazio bought options on Quick &AMP;
Reilly stock _ prompted, he now says, by rumors that the company
might be a takeover target. On Monday, Aug. 4, in a transaction
that Lazio acknowledged last week but had failed to report on his
disclosure forms, he bought more options.
</P>
<P>
   He spent a total of $2,300 on the options, which are securities
that allow an investor to buy shares at a specified price for a
limited amount of time. If the price does not rise, the options
become worthless.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, on Aug. 11, news leaked out that the company had
hired investment bankers, and the prices of the stock and options
jumped. The company was later acquired by Fleet Financial.
</P>
<P>
   A review of public information and trading records shows that
speculation about Quick &AMP; Reilly being a takeover target had just
started to grow when Lazio made his first options purchase on Aug.
1.
</P>
<P>
   Total volume in options to buy Quick &AMP; Reilly stock came to
1,500 contracts on Aug. 1, nearly triple the volume of the previous
day, and 1,542 contracts the following Monday, according to figures
from the Options Clearing Corp., which overseas the settling of all
options trades.
</P>
<P>
   Both figures represented just a quarter of the activity on Aug.
12, when volume soared after news of the potential takeover
surfaced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
