A2345 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      06-23 0182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT, U.S. AGREE ON SCHEDULE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft and the government agreed Thursday on an
expedited schedule for submitting briefs to the Supreme Court that
will enable the court to decide whether to accept the antitrust
case as soon as late August.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson sent the case to the
Supreme Court for direct review under a little-used law known as
the Expediting Act.
</P>
<P>
   After that, using the normal rules, Microsoft and the government
would have had 90 days to file briefs and replies on the question
of whether the court should take the appeal or send it to the Court
of Appeals, pushing that decision into late September.
</P>
<P>
   But in a notice to the court, U.S. Solicitor General Seth P.
Waxman said that ``the parties have agreed to a briefing schedule''
under which the last brief would be filed on Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   If the Supreme Court decides to take the Microsoft appeal, then
the litigants will get another briefing schedule, this one on the
main issues in the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 0014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
