<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2347 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBN-LANDRY-LADN-(SLAN     06-23 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LANDRY-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANDRY'S LIFE CELEBRATED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTLAKE VILLAGE, Calif. _ Danny Villanueva spent only three
years under the famous watchful eyes of former Dallas Cowboys coach
Tom Landry, a period he fondly recalls as being one of the most
memorable of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He meant a lot to me, and everybody else who played for him,
because he taught us so much,'' said Villanueva, a resident of
nearby Camarillo and placekicker for the Cowboys 1965-67, who was
one of about 300 guests on hand Thursday night for ``A Tribute to
Tom Landry'' at the Hyatt Westlake Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   The event was presented by California Lutheran University, the
Thousand Oaks, Calif., campus where Landry and the Cowboys held
training camp before the start of every NFL season from 1963 to
1989.
</P>
<P>
   Landry, who coached the Cowboys for 29 years (1960-88), died in
February. Thursday's event, which included dinner, speeches and a
multimedia presentation, was a chance for family and friends to
remember and celebrate the coach's life and many achievements,
which included Super Bowl victories after the 1971 and 1977
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very lovely to come back here, where we had so many great
memories,'' said Alicia Landry, the coach's widow. ``We were able
to have lunch at the (Cal Lutheran) campus, and we walked by the
dorms where I visited Tom for so many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was busy, working with the team, but we were always able to
spend some time together, and this has always been such a nice,
peaceful, beautiful area.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost every guest at the tribute had some connection to Landry,
including former players and recipients of the Landry Medal, given
by the university 18 times over the past 20 years to honor people
who ``are an inspiration to America's youth.'' Every guest also had
at least one Landry story to share.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I ever saw Tom,'' former longtime Cal Lutheran
football coach Robert Shoup said, ``he was standing ... by this
cliff that's pretty well known on campus, and he looked like George
Washington on Mount Rushmore.''
</P>
<P>
   Villanueva, one of the speakers at the event, recalled his first
encounter with Landry and the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still remember getting the phone call from the Rams, telling
me I had been traded,'' Villanueva said. ``I was sad to be leaving
Los Angeles, which had sort of become my adopted hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the Rams told me I had been traded and they told me to
stay by the phone because Tom Landry and (former Cowboys president)
Tex Schramm would be calling. I talked to Tom and he made me feel a
lot better, because he told me that the Rams hadn't offered me
around but that he wanted me and had come after me. That made me
feel pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when I got to Cal Lutheran, it didn't take long for me to
realize that this was a team with a purpose, and that Tom really
had them ready to make a breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Villanueva kicked a game-winning field goal in the
1966 regular-season finale, sending the Cowboys to the playoffs for
the first time in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt so happy to be able to do that for Tom,'' Villanueva
said. ``Tom was like family to me, and for three years out there at
Cal Lutheran, my teammates were like family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Tom last year at an awards dinner and we talked briefly,
but I never really got to thank him and tell him what he meant to
me. I regret that now, because he was a great man.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
