   OIL-NORRIS-COLUMN (New York) _ For those who remember the 1970s,
there is something familiar about oil ministers meeting in Vienna,
Austria, to decide whether to open the production taps a bit
further as analysts debate whether 700,000 additional barrels a day
will make much difference. The answer is, it won't. Because if that
extra supply would change things very much, that supply would
vanish. The oil crisis, circa 2000, is not a supply-side
phenomenon. By Floyd Norris.
