<HEADER>
A2354 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLA     06-23 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STICKING WITH PEREZ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ No longer do the Los Angeles Dodgers have the power to
do what they wish with left-hander Carlos Perez. If they try to
send him to the minors now, he'll have to agree to it.
</P>
<P>
   Perez's binding contract with the Dodgers extending his
agreement to waive his right to refuse an assignment quietly passed
Tuesday. Perez can refuse an assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to be worrying about it,'' Perez said. ``I'm glad
I'm part of the team, and like I always say, I want to help this
team win. We won two of three in Houston, so that's good.''
</P>
<P>
   It puts everyone involved in a potentially troublesome situation
if Perez doesn't improve in his next few starts because the only
way the Dodgers can rid themselves of him, if he declines a
minor-league assignment, is to release him or trade him.
</P>
<P>
   And that will be something the Dodgers don't need. They've made
a pair of trades in the last 10 days that were aimed, at least in
part, at providing payroll flexibility. However, Perez signed a
three-year, $15.6-million contract before going 2-10 with a 7.43
ERA in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, manager Davey Johnson, general manager Kevin
Malone and managing general partner and CEO Bob Daly are willing to
keep trotting Perez out there for his starts. The Dodgers are 6-7
in games Perez starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made a commitment to keep him in the rotation,'' Dodgers
senior vice president Derrick Hall said. ``The team's been winning
with him when he starts. However, with that commitment, they're
certainly hoping Carlos will contribute effectively in that role
and help the team in what we expect to be a pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, who was 33-35 when he signed the deal, is being paid $5
million this season and he's guaranteed $7.5 million next season.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Perez (4-3) has more wins this season than many
expected. But he hasn't won since May 20, a span of five starts,
and his ERA is 5.73. And during that time, he is 0-1 with a 5.70
ERA.
</P>
<P>
   A player with five years of major-league service time can refuse
a minor-league assignment, but Perez waived that right when he
signed an agreement in late April. That expired May 31, which is
when Perez made a similar agreement but not for as much time. The
deal was thought to be extended to June 25, but it was learned the
date was June 20.
</P>
<P>
   __ White's rehab crawls on: Injured Dodgers center fielder Devon
White said he will try hitting off a tee when the club returns to
Los Angeles next week, but he remains noncommittal about being able
to return this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still weakness in there,'' said White, who added he
wasn't ready to face live pitching.
</P>
<P>
   __ Leyritz available: Recently acquired catcher/infielder Jim
Leyritz was available for the game. He met with manager Davey
Johnson beforehand to discuss his role with the Dodgers and was
told to take grounders at first and catch as many pitchers as he
can in the bullpen to familiarize himself with the staff. Johnson
added he could use Leyritz in the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't any consistency (with the Yankees),'' said
Leyritz, who was batting .218 with a homer and four RBI. ``I went
through one stretch where I didn't play for 21 days, played one
game and didn't play for eight days. It was real inconsistent.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Right-hander Gregg Olson will throw a bullpen
session today and if all goes well, he'll begin a rehab assignment
when the club returns home Monday. . . . The Dodgers signed three
of their top five picks from this month's draft, but No. 1 pick Ben
Diggins remains unsigned. Agreeing to terms were right-handed
pitcher Joel Hanrahan (second round), catcher Koyie Hill (fourth)
and right-handed pitcher Heath Totten (fifth).
</P>
</TEXT>
