A2355 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-LEGIS-NYT &LR;      06-23 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LEGIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCORD REACHED IN ALBANY ON GUN CONTROLS AND SEX CRIMES
</HEADLINE>
  By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki and the Legislature Thursday
agreed to adopt the nation's most far-reaching package of gun
controls and a sweeping overhaul of sex crimes laws that imposes
tougher penalties and provides new services for victims.
</P>
<P>
   Racing to close this year's legislative session, the lawmakers
also agreed on a package of measures to improve school safety. One
would require that schools fingerprint job applicants, including
prospective teachers, and conduct criminal background checks on
them. Another would increase penalties for students who assault
teachers and teachers who assault students, and yet another would
make it easier for teachers to remove disruptive students from
their classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of a hate crimes law remained uncertain late into the
evening as the Democratic Assembly speaker, Sheldon Silver, and the
Republican Senate majority leader, Joseph Bruno, continued to
squabble over the packaging of a bill whose contents they have
agreed on.
</P>
<P>
   And it appeared very unlikely that the Assembly would pass a
bill backed by the Senate and the governor to reform the rules for
Republican presidential primaries, over fears about how the bill
would affect Democratic primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of deals were struck and hundreds of bills passed on what
had been billed as the last day the Legislature would be in session
this year, after frenzied, nearly round-the-clock negotiations in
the last week by the governor, the legislative leaders and members
of their staffs. Thursday's actions decided several important
issues, including these:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Assembly declined to pass either the Senate's or Pataki's
version of a bill that would have required legislative approval for
a proposed Indian casino in Monticello, in the Catskills. Silver
said the Assembly could decide to return in a special session in
December to vote on the Senate bill.
</P>
<P>
   _ The governor and both houses agreed to a bill that greatly
broadens state laws against money-laundering, including applying
those laws to wire transfers.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Assembly passed a Senate bill that would make it legal for
mothers of newborn infants to abandon their babies in safe places,
like hospital emergency rooms or police stations. Similar laws have
been enacted in Texas and in Germany, and advocates say they reduce
the number of newborns killed by their mothers. The Assembly vote
sends the bill to the governor, who has not said what he will do
with it.
</P>
<P>
   _ All three sides agreed on a measure to aid the New York Stock
Exchange's expansion plans, including authorizing a city agency to
sell $255 million in bonds and authorizing a state agency to
acquire property across the street from the current exchange.
</P>
<P>
   _ All three sides agreed to a bill allowing towns and villages
to regulate, or even ban, the use of personal watercraft, a
provision long sought by some communities and by environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Assembly refused to pass a bill permitting $125 million a
year in tax cuts by New York City because it included a decrease in
hotel taxes that the Democrats opposed.
</P>
<P>
   The gun control bill agreed to Thursday night closely mirrors
the one that Pataki, a Republican, proposed earlier this year,
stunning Republicans and Democrats alike, and prompting gun control
advocates to declare him a leader in their cause. Gun owners'
groups and the firearms industry have derided the measures as
either an intrusion on their rights or meaningless posturing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This important legislation will help make our streets safer by
reducing gun violence in communities across the state,'' Pataki
said Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The bill will make New York the first state in the country to
require ``ballistic fingerprinting'' of all new guns sold. Each gun
would be test-fired before sale so that the telltale markings it
leaves on bullets and shell casings could be recorded and entered
into a state computer database, for later comparison to slugs and
shells found at crime scenes.
</P>
<P>
   The bill requires background checks on all gun buyers at gun
shows, to weed out people with criminal records who are prohibited
from owning guns. Federal law requires licensed gun dealers to
conduct background checks on buyers, but most of the sales at gun
shows are by private citizens who are exempt from that rule.
Sixteen other states have requirements.
</P>
<P>
   New York will become the fifth state to ban assault weapons. A
1994 federal law banned them, but local prosecutors need a state
law to bring charges in state courts.
</P>
<P>
   The bill requires that every new handgun be sold with a trigger
lock, making New York one of six states to do so. It raises the
minimum age for obtaining a handgun permit and buying a handgun
from 18 to 21, the age required by 10 other states. And it requires
that owners report lost or stolen guns to the police within 24
hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``These tough anti-gun measures will help keep firearms out of
the hands of young people and protect schoolchildren and all New
Yorkers,'' Silver said.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lawmakers have long called for tougher criminal
penalties for sex crimes, and this year, Silver signaled led this
year that he agreed, but insisted that they be tied to broader
services for victims of those crimes. Talks on the issue
languished, until given new impetus by the June 11 assaults on
women in Central Park after the National Puerto Rican Day Parade.
</P>
<P>
   The bill agreed on and passed Thursday creates a crime of
``forcible touching,'' a felony, to apply to cases like the ones in
Central Park, which until now have often been treated as
misdemeanors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
