<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TWINS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS COME UP EMPTY IN CLUTCH SITUATIONS, LOSE TO TWINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Sitting in last place and trying to keep from
being buried by the rampaging Oakland Athletics, the Rangers find
themselves with little margin for error.
</P>
<P>
   Key hits must be delivered. Good pitches must be made. Rundowns
must be executed properly. Otherwise, dire consequences can be
suffered as the Rangers found out last night in a 3-2 loss to the
Minnesota Twins at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers failed to execute a tricky rundown in the top of the
ninth inning that allowed the go-ahead run to score, then watched
in frustration as they failed to exploit a first-and-third, one-out
situation in the bottom of the inning with their two best hitters
at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Ivan Rodriguez popped out to shortstop off Twins
reliever Bob Wells, and Rafael Palmeiro flied out to right to end
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a frustrating year,'' said Palmeiro, who had a
run-scoring single in the third but also popped out with runners at
first and second with two out in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's who you want to have up there in the ninth,'' Rangers
manager Johnny Oates said. ``I'll take my chances with those guys
in the same situation tomorrow night.''
</P>
<P>
   Starter Matt Perisho delivered seven strong innings but it
wasn't enough to allow the Rangers to complete a three-game sweep
of the Twins. Instead the Rangers dropped to 8 1/2 games behind the
Athletics in the American League West.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't feel bad,'' shortstop Royce Clayton said. ``We just
won two of three games. It's not easy to sweep a big-league team. I
don't care who they are.''
</P>
<P>
   With the score tied 2-2, Butch Huskey started the Twins' ninth
with a double to right field off Rangers reliever Tim Crabtree.
Corey Koskie then flied out to left and Denny Hocking walked on a
full-count pitch, barely checking his swing on a 97 mph fastball
from Crabtree.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Moeller followed with a high chopper to the right side.
Second baseman Frank Catalanotto charged it and fielded it in the
baseline just in front of Hocking, who immediately started
retreating to avoid being tagged. When he did, Catalanotto flipped
to first for the out.
</P>
<P>
   That left Hocking hung up between first and second and Huskey,
dangling off third, watching the rundown carefully. First baseman
Rafael Palmeiro threw to Clayton, who started running Hocking back
to first.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to get the out in front of you until he breaks for
home,'' Clayton said.
</P>
<P>
   As Clayton went after Hocking, Huskey inched farther off third.
When Clayton threw back to first, Huskey broke for home and slid in
just ahead of Palmeiro's throw
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really not a gamble,'' Huskey said. ``You work on that
play all the time in spring training. You just have to have the
instincts on when to go. I caught a break because it's a harder
throw for a left-handed first baseman.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Oates, ``I thought \Rthe Twins\S executed very well. Other
than totally disregard the runner between first and second, there's
not much else we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Perisho, trying to clinch his spot in the Rangers' post-All-Star
break rotation, went seven innings in the longest outing of his 13
major-league starts. He allowed two runs on five hits and two walks
with four strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Coomer homered in the second inning for one run and, after
the Rangers forged a 2-1 lead, the Twins got another run off
Perisho in the sixth when Koskie beat out a two-out bunt down the
third-base line to score Matt Lawton from third base.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way they got their runs, they earned them,'' Perisho said.
``I never imagined he would bunt in that situation. I've faced him
a lot in Triple A and even a few times up here ... when he laid
down that bunt, it totally blew my mind.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
