<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ROGUES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: UPDATING DIPLOMACY'S LANGUAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, June 23:
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to ridicule the State Department for replacing the
evocative term ``rogue nations'' with the more diplomatic and
touchy-feely ``states of concern'' when referring to trouble spots
like North Korea, Iran, Iraq, Libya, Sudan and Cuba. But beyond the
blurring of semantic clarity lies a welcome recognition that the
world has changed in ways that make the ``rogue'' category a poor
guide to intelligent foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright unveiled the new
terminology in a radio interview Monday. Like rogue nations, states
of concern have unpredictable, authoritarian leaders, histories of
sponsoring terrorism and, Cuba excepted, programs for building
biological, chemical or nuclear weapons. But as the department's
new language recognizes, the strategy of lumping all these
countries together as international rogues, unreachable through
normal tools of diplomacy and fit only for isolation and military
containment, has grown out of date.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea is an obvious case in point. Its once-reclusive
leader just held a successful meeting with his South Korean
counterpart, and both sides now talk of national reconciliation and
economic interchange. Pyongyang has honored its agreements with
Washington to suspend nuclear weapons development and
flight-testing of long-range missiles. In response, Washington has
eased economic sanctions and made North Korea Asia's largest
recipient of American assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Other nations formerly known as rogues have not come that far.
But for years Washington has been engaged in a delicate courtship
with reform-minded elected officials in Iran. Indirect diplomacy
with Libya, through the United Nations, helped bring the Lockerbie
bombing suspects to trial. Many members of Congress have begun to
recognize that a less restrictive policy toward Cuba could increase
America's ability to influence political change there as the Castro
era draws to a close.
</P>
<P>
   Some states of concern still require ostracism, containment and
military threats. One clear example is Saddam Hussein's Iraq, which
defies United Nations Security Council resolutions, reneges on its
diplomatic promises and would quickly divert any export revenues it
could get its hands on into weapons programs. Every serious foreign
problem facing America requires its own specific policy
prescription. No longer talking about rogue states will make that
easier to explain.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 0054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0023 </DOCNO>
