A2365 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      06-23 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE TO FASTEN THE BLAME FOR SURGING GASOLINE PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although Big Oil and OPEC get all the blame for soaring gasoline
prices, history will reveal government as the true culprit.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect a public revelation any time soon, though. Everyone
in Washington is working overtime to persuade voters that pump pain
is caused by those who produce and sell petroleum, not those who
tax and regulate it.
</P>
<P>
   This is the way it always happens during shortages and price
spikes. Big Oil is flayed for gouging, but the question always
remains: If gouging is so easily done, why doesn't it happen all
the time?
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, nobody connects obviously misguided federal policies
with marketplace disruptions. 'Twas ever thus, since the first oil
crisis in '73. Few Americans, however, ever perceive the line
between meddlesome government and roiled energy markets.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with the reformulated gasoline anti-pollution
mandate that recently went into effect in some areas. It's costing
more to implement than regulators forecast, but nobody knows how
much more it will ultimately cost. Why? Nobody knows how much
already scarce refining capacity must be diverted to meet mandated
demands.
</P>
<P>
   So are the feds considering a suspension of the mandate, at
least during peak driving season? Silly question.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the federal gasoline tax, much of which is
collected but goes to general budget outlays instead of road
construction. Thus the highway trust fund has about $25 billion
worth of IOUs from the Treasury. Question: If the feds aren't going
to use all the pump taxes to fix roads, why not partially repeal
the levy and give motorists a break?
</P>
<P>
   Nobody talks about government's oil reserve, either. Surging oil
prices normally would encourage U.S. producers to bring more oil to
market. But what happens if American producers invest a lot of
money developing new supply sources and government decides to dump
its oil cache onto the market? Prices probably tank, and the
industry's investment comes a cropper.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, nobody is pushing to develop northern Alaska's fields
as a way to counter foreign oil clout. Washington, in fact, seems
more interested in keeping potential domestic supply sources out of
production rather than using them to increase supply and decrease
reliance on predatory foreign producers.
</P>
<P>
   Americans don't hear much about how government policies and
actions exacerbate an already difficult situation. Instead, they
get a lot of congressional grandstanding about how obscene profits
should justify legislation to counter soaring gasoline prices.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody, however, has profited more obscenely from oil than the
federal government. The federal government collects
petroleum-related taxes, politicians profit substantially from
industry campaign contributions, and regulators enjoy their profit
in the form of increased power, which is coin of the realm in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   One thing to remember is that no politician or bureaucrat ever
wrested a single barrel of oil, and their actions are more likely
to make gasoline prices go up than down. Whatever the price of
gasoline is at any given time, you can bet it would probably be
lower were it not for political lust for money and power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 0055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2366 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-INADEQUATE-JAILS-KAN &LR;      06-23 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INADEQUATE-JAILS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INADEQUATE JAILS A PROBLEM THROUGHOUT RURAL MISSOURI, KANSAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIT WAGAR  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The slaying of two Randolph County Jail
guards Thursday stunned sheriffs in Missouri and Kansas, who said
that without new security it also could happen to them.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Robert Dawson of Macon County, which borders Randolph
County on the north, said he requested more security as soon as he
heard about the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to the County Commission this morning about adding
bullet-proof glass, new steel doors where there are wooden ones now
in the processing area and lobby, and maybe additional cameras,''
he said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The jail, which is about 90 years old, has few features designed
to keep intruders out.
</P>
<P>
   ``With old jails, security is a common problem in out-state
Missouri,'' Dawson said. ``And the problem is money.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of security became apparent early Thursday when guards
at the Randolph County Jail let a man and a woman into the
facility. One of them pulled a gun and opened fire, killing the two
guards.
</P>
<P>
   State and local officials blamed the aging and sometimes
dangerous condition of many jails in rural Missouri on a lack of
money and political will.
</P>
<P>
   When county commissioners have a choice of financing jail
improvements or paving roads, the latter almost always wins, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   So new jails are often financed with bonds or a local tax
increase that must be approved by voters. Jail supporters have had
mixed success in referendums.
</P>
<P>
   In Lafayette County, Mo., which has a 61-year-old jail, Lt.
Darren Hewitt said two efforts to raise taxes to pay for a new jail
failed. The most recent attempt was November, when it failed by a
4-1 ratio.
</P>
<P>
   O.J. Stone, president of the Missouri Deputy Sheriffs
Association, said taxpayers often begrudged tax increases for
jails. The attitude is that criminals don't need luxurious
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bond issues are a tough sell,'' Stone said. ``The public has a
lot of projects to fund, and when you say you need a bigger, better
jail, people don't want to hear it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, jails are becoming fuller as the state prison
system houses more inmates in them to relieve crowding, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The extent of the problem varies widely from county to county
because the state plays almost no role in local decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Corrections Department spokesman Tim Kniest said state officials
had no authority or responsibility to see that conditions at county
jails met minimum standards.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Vermeersch, executive director of the Missouri Sheriffs
Association, said the only jail standards in Missouri were those
that sprang from constitutional prohibitions against cruel and
unusual punishment. So no group keeps track of how many substandard
jails Missouri has, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stone said many Missouri jails dated from the 1930s and lacked
serviceable utilities and air conditioning. Many have antiquated
cells that are too small for inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeersch said his group has talked about asking for state help
to upgrade jails and hire more jailers. Sheriffs have received
several new duties in recent years without new revenue to hire more
deputies.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriffs must register sex offenders, fight domestic violence
and track the race of drivers stopped for traffic offenses. County
commissioners are sympathetic, but they are politicians who prefer
financing high-visibility projects, Vermeersch said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something has to give, and often that means no more
deputies,'' he said. ``Commissioners feel they have to support a
new bridge or road over law enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Steve Gaw, a Moberly Democrat who represents
Randolph County, said state officials recognized the problem. Gaw
said he and House Majority Leader Wayne Crump, a Potosi Democrat,
discussed the possibility of a revolving fund for jail construction
within the state's capital improvement budget.
</P>
<P>
   But the idea was floated late in this year's legislative
session, and they decided that it could not be done without setting
up a formal program. So the idea was scrapped for this year.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's shootings will force state officials to take a new
look at the state's role in financing county jails, Gaw said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this will prompt a growing examination of how to deal
with older facilities that do not meet modern standards,'' Gaw
said. ``I think it's something that county government and the state
have to look at together and possibly look to federal funding as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   The growth in law enforcement costs, especially those related to
juvenile crime, make such a review long overdue, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jailers in Clay, Ray, Carroll and Platte counties said they
doubted the Randolph County shootings could be repeated in their
jails.
</P>
<P>
   But in Caldwell County, Sheriff Wayne Adkinson said the
130-year-old jail offered little security.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get the County Commission to build us a better
jail, but until then there's nothing we can do,'' he said. ``We
could definitely have a problem here.''
</P>
<P>
   In Lafayette County, Hewitt said doors were opened for visitors
a hundred times a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing to do but buzz them in and see what they
want,'' Hewitt said. ``We never know what they'll want. That's just
the chance we have to take.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas has almost no standards for jails. The ones that exist
were enacted in 1868, seven years after statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1996, the state Department of Corrections made annual
county jail inspections using a set of advisory standards.
Violations could prompt nothing more than recommendations for
change, said Bill Miskell, a Corrections Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   It was up to county officials to decide whether to comply. That
program had been in existence 10 or 15 years before it was
scrapped, Miskell said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 0057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2367 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-PUZZLE-LADN-(SLAN     06-23 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PUZZLE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIECING IT TOGETHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ During the last week of spring training, the Los
Angeles Dodgers targeted late June as the time teams would know
where they stood and what they would need for a second-half run at
the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Through the evaluation, the Dodgers figured reliever Alan Mills
or utility infielder Jose Vizcaino were expendable and decided that
with Geronimo Berroa's injury, Jim Leyritz's right-handed power bat
was a must.
</P>
<P>
   Questions remain about the leadoff and center-field spots, the
closer's role and whether the Dodgers will get production out of
the fourth and fifth starters in the rotation. But those are
questions that must be answered and they'll likely be answered
internally. And that's when the Dodgers will know whether they have
all the parts to make a run at the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all the pieces to the puzzle are here, but you never
know what (management) is going to do by the July 31 (trade)
deadline,'' Dodgers reliever Jeff Shaw said. ``They may go out and
pick somebody else up, another pitcher. There's only a couple of
question marks. Arizona has played well at home (25-10) and they
have not run away from us. It's going to be a jockeying thing
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers withstood injuries to right-hander Kevin Brown,
third baseman Adrian Beltre and Kevin Elster, who has since lost
his starting shortstop job and is in a platoon with Alex Cora.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers will get healthier Monday when catcher Todd Hundley
should return. But no one knows whether center fielder Devon White
will return from a partially torn left rotator cuff or whether
he'll need season-ending surgery.
</P>
<P>
   There was also the distraction of the impending suspensions, but
even so, the Dodgers are 2 games behind Arizona in the National
League West.
</P>
<P>
   But it's hardly time to make the big push. That happens in a
month when teams go through another evaluation period in
preparation for the July 31 trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have to wait and see for the next month or so and
see how teams load up and that will help determine what we need to
do,'' Dodgers right fielder Shawn Green said. ``You have to see
who's available. Starting now, it becomes a lot more clear as each
week goes by. There's no telling what's going to happen in our
division the next month.''
</P>
<P>
   But that could prove to be a problem for the Dodgers. While
Arizona and Colorado have the organizational depth to make a
blockbuster deal at the trading deadline, the Dodgers fall short.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I know, (general manager) Kevin (Malone) is always
working the phones, but the (minor-league) system is still not
where it needs to be, so there's not a lot of depth to where you
can talk about moving some of them,'' said Green. ``It's a couple
years behind to where you have the insurance policies at Triple-A
to have all the parts.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz, or Berroa, provide the right-handed bat off the bench
that makes opposing managers choose between facing Dave Hansen or,
at this time, Leyritz. But Shaw has blown six of 18 save chances
and is no longer the end-all, be-all closer. Instead, he'll get
help from Mike Fetters, Terry Adams and Matt Herges.
</P>
<P>
   White's uncertain status has turned center field into a platoon
among Todd Hollandsworth and F.P. Santangelo and left the Dodgers
without their choice for leadoff hitter.
</P>
<P>
   And the fourth and fifth spots in the rotation, occupied by
Carlos Perez and Orel Hershiser, remain suspect. Perez is 4-3, but
he's won once since May 3. Hershiser's lone win came during the
nostalgic home opener, and he's made only four starts and has a
10.80 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always believe in having two aces on a team, and the way
Chan Ho (Park) is pitching, he's proven he can be an ace,'' said
Dodgers left fielder Gary Sheffield, knowing Kevin Brown's status
as an ace is a given. ``But you have to go out and prove you can do
it. You can have the stuff all day long, but you have to be able to
do it and execute.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
