r f BC-SPRINT-SUITORS-2NDTAK     06-23 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-SUITORS-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTWOOD, Kan. _ Atlanta-based BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth went head-to-head against WorldCom in bidding for
Sprint in October, but lost out to WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has acquired little in the United States while its
regional Bell brethren Bell Atlantic and SBC Communications have
gone on an acquisition spree, buying up territory and customers.
</P>
<P>
   Since Sprint accepted WorldCom's offer, however, BellSouth has
expanded its operation in Latin America and entered into an
agreement with SBC Communications to join their wireless operation
and form a nationwide carrier. That would complicate any new offer
for Sprint, on top of regulatory concerns.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth is still not allowed to offer long distance to its
customers until it proves its local markets are open to
competition. That doesn't preclude a deal for all or parts of
Sprint, however. And with Bell Atlantic's recent acquisition of GTE
Corp., there is a precedent for how regulators would treat such a
deal.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the question of money. BellSouth has already
indicated that there's a limit to what it's willing to pay for
Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts still hold out the possibility that Sprint will
reverse course, pull out of its merger with WorldCom and go looking
for its own deals. That would certainly please employees, if not
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   If the WorldCom deal collapses, Sprint's stock would probably
fall, but it wouldn't be impossible for the company to fund an
acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   ``These deals can come together in a lot of ways,'' said Jeanne
Schaaf at Forrester Research, a market research firm. ``The best
bet for Sprint is to go with a brand new player who can continue to
breathe some life into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Candidates? Global Crossing or Equant. Bermuda-based Global
Crossing is building a worldwide undersea cable and data network,
and could provide Sprint with international reach, Web hosting and
media expertise.
</P>
<P>
   Amsterdam-based Equant owns the world's largest data network,
reaching businesses in more than 220 territories and countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sprint is a pretty strong player when it comes to
innovation,'' Schaaf said of telecommunications companies. ``What
they need is a partner with speed, aggressiveness, not one of these
old-style telcos.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
