<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-SUITORS-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT LIKELY TO ENTERTAIN SUITORS IF WORLDCOM DEAL FALTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTWOOD, Kan. _ Whether Sprint Corp. submits to antitrust
regulators, agreeing to sell its entire long-distance division, or
the company decides to scrap its proposed merger with WorldCom
Inc., the for sale sign is probably going out again in Westwood.
</P>
<P>
   Despite employees' hopes and executives' statements, few
analysts think Sprint is prepared to go it alone in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very rare that a company would agree to be bought then
not be open to other offers that would come along,'' said Mel
Marten, an analyst with Edward Jones brokerage company in St.
Louis. ``It might not happen the next day, but an offer will
definitely come at some point.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason is simple. All phone companies are trying to put
together a full package of services, including local, long
distance, Internet, wireless and international.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint, which employs nearly 20,000 people in the metro area,
doesn't have much in the way of local or international services,
and it needs a partner to get them. Sprint could be a buyer, but
most analysts think that's unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   A decision from Sprint's board on how to proceed with regulators
could come in the next few days. No matter what the outcome, the
same short list of potential acquirers are considered potential
bidders for part or all of the company.
</P>
<P>
   When handicapping the field, most observers tend to look
overseas first.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, the value of shares in European
telecommunications firms has almost doubled, while those of their
U.S. counterparts stagnated. With their shares trading at much
higher multiples of earnings than U.S. companies, European
companies can use their more valuable stock as currency to buy
companies relatively cheaply in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Few companies are more flush with cash than Deutsche Telekom.
And having failed in recent merger attempts with Telecom Italia and
Qwest Communications, the German giant is eager to do a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``DT has been champing at the bit to do something big,'' said
Brian Adamik, an analyst with the Yankee Group, a market research
firm. ``The time has never been better for an international company
to come over and buy someone.''
</P>
<P>
   European analysts who follow the company think it could raise
$50 billion in cash to make an acquisition, which would allow it to
buy Sprint's long-distance business from WorldCom without the
complications that a stock transaction would bring in a three-way
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also think the company could probably afford to make an
acquisition with stock as large as $200 billion, large enough to
swallow either WorldCom or Sprint should their deal collapse
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The German company makes no bones of its desire to enter the
U.S. market. And if past statements are any indication, it will be
looking for three things: Internet, wireless and a systems
integration business.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint fills two of the three needs, offering the fastest
growing wireless business in the country, Sprint PCS, and one of
the top four Internet backbones in the world. It also has a systems
integration business, Sprint Paranet, though it's a small player
that has struggled of late.
</P>
<P>
   If Deutsche Telekom decided to buy WorldCom, as some analysts
have suggested could happen, it would get the biggest Internet
backbone in the world, but no wireless assets. WorldCom also sold
its systems integration business last year.
</P>
<P>
   Another complicating factor in a Deutsche Telekom//WorldCom
tie-up would be WorldCom's extensive European networks, an overlap
that regulators would probably want to eliminate.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Deutsche Telekom already owns a 10 percent stake in
Sprint dating from their ill-fated international venture with
France Telecom, Global One, which was dissolved earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Both the French and Germans have agreed to sell their 10 percent
stakes in Sprint upon the successful completion of the WorldCom
deal, but if that deal falls through, the Deutsche Telekom may be
looking to buy.
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, so could France Telecom. France Telecom Chief
Executive Michel Bon, however, has not been nearly as aggressive as
his German counterpart Ron Sommer in statements about expansion to
the United States. France Telecom may also lack the financial and
management flexibility that Deutsche Telekom has to make a large
acquisition right now.
</P>
<P>
   France Telecom is still in the midst of acquiring the United
Kingdom provider, Orange PLC, and getting the house in order at
Global One, which it inherited after Sprint and Deutsche Telekom
left the partnership.
</P>
<P>
   France Telecom is also rumored to be interested in taking over
the Dutch communications provider Equant.
</P>
<P>
   ``France Telecom could take a hard look at Sprint,'' said David
Neil, an analyst with the Gartner Group in Toronto. ``You don't get
too many opportunities to go out and buy a company like it. But
they might have enough on their plate already.''
</P>
<P>
   The international long shot is Nippon Telegraph and Telephone
Corp., the largest phone company in the world by sales, but one
that has remained on the sidelines as other carriers have expanded
internationally.
</P>
<P>
   After years of dominating the insular Japanese market, however,
Nippon is showing signs of going global, with recent purchases a
U.S. manager of corporate Web sites, and 15 percent of a mobile
phone company in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Under Japanese law, however, Nippon must apply to issue more
shares for acquisitions, and can't swap shares if it brings foreign
ownership above 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their political process is working against the company, but if
they can get beyond that I'd put them at the top of the list,''
said Richard Nespola, chief executive of the Management Network
Group Inc., a telecommunications consulting firm based in Overland
Park, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   A quiet player on the domestic front so far, but a perennial
favorite when analysts talk about anyone acquiring Sprint, is
Atlanta-based BellSouth. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
