r a BC-JAILERS-SLAIN-2TAKES-     06-23 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAILERS-SLAIN-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO GUARDS KILLED IN ATTEMPTED JAILBREAK IN CENTRAL MISSOURI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT STEARNS  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Mo. _ The last thing the two unarmed Randolph County
Jail guards ever did was buzz open the jail's front door about
12:40 a.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes and several shots later, one was dead and the
other dying, and the man and woman who had come through the jail's
door were frantically searching for the key to a cell holding a
friend. They left the central Missouri jail without finding it,
sparking a massive manhunt that ended when two persons were
arrested about eight hours later in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Killed were Leon Egley, 33, the jail supervisor, and Jason
Acton, 36, a sheriff's deputy. They were the only two on duty at
the time in the jail.
</P>
<P>
   Charged with two counts of first-degree murder in their deaths
was Michael Andrew Tisius, 19, of Moberly, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Also charged was Tracie Ann Bulington, 27, of La Plata, Mo.
Bulington was charged with two counts of second-degree murder,
armed criminal action, burglary and aiding the escape of a
prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   The two were arrested about 9:35 a.m. Thursday in a restaurant
parking lot along U.S. 36 on the eastern edge of Wathena, in the
northeast corner of Kansas. They offered no resistance, Doniphan
County Sheriff Mike Batchelder said.
</P>
<P>
   Batchelder said the two were unarmed. The Missouri Highway
Patrol found what is thought to be the murder weapon, a revolver,
along U.S. 36 west of Macon, Mo., which is north of Huntsville. A
car that authorities think Tisius and Bulington were driving was
found in Elwood, Kan., east of Wathena.
</P>
<P>
   Tisius and Bulington waived extradition and were expected in
Moberly by Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say the two had been planning for weeks to free Roy
Vance, an inmate from Macon County being held on a drug charge.
Macon County Sheriff Robert Dawson said Vance was transferred after
he tried to escape the Macon County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   Randolph County Sheriff Don Ancell said a man and woman were
buzzed in the front door of the 91-year-old jail, which sits on
Main Street in downtown Huntsville, a town of about 1,600 people.
The two then opened fire on Acton and Egley.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is, there's no barrier between the lobby and the
dispatch area,'' said Ancell, who complained bitterly about the
state of the old jail.
</P>
<P>
   Acton died at the scene; Egley at a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Ancell said the two guards had no reason to be suspicious when
the buzzer rang at such a late hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not unusual at all,'' he said. ``This is the information
center for the Randolph County sheriff's office. People stop in all
the time at all times to report incidents, ask for directions _
maybe they're stuck on the highway.''
</P>
<P>
   Ancell said jail guards were unarmed for a simple reason: ``Jail
and guns don't mix.'' The victims
</P>
<P>
   Leon Egley ``had a heart as big as Texas,'' said his friend John
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Egley had worked as jail supervisor since 1997. Single, with no
children, he lived in a second-floor apartment on Main Street just
a few blocks from the jail.
</P>
<P>
   A quiet man, Egley appeared to have two passions in life:
Huntsville and helping people. His sister-in-law, Diana Egley, said
his job at the jail let him combine both.
</P>
<P>
   Egley also was an enthusiastic member of the Huntsville City
Council. He was appointed by Mayor Carl Gordy in 1998 and elected
on his own just a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would take the ordinance books home at night to read,''
Gordy said.
</P>
<P>
   He brought the same passion to his job at the jail, said his
mother, Doreen Little, as she sat in a chair in front of her son's
old apartment building, fighting off the heat and the grief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every job has its ups and downs,'' Little said. ``But he liked
it. He felt like he was helping people.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he liked helping people so much that he often worked
odd shifts at the jail _ something out of the ordinary for a
supervisor whose normal hours were 8 to 5.
</P>
<P>
   That was the case the night he died.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had no business being on third shift,'' said County Clerk
Jim Sears. ``He would every so often work third shifts when there
were new people to help break them in and to relate to the issues
they had.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Acton was one such new person. He had just started work in
May. He lived near Rocheport, Mo., but had planned on moving closer
to Huntsville in a few months after he got married.
</P>
<P>
   He preferred the peace and quiet of Randolph County, he told
Carol Summers, the deputy county clerk.
</P>
<P>
   And Ancell said Acton quickly impressed his superiors on the
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I start most everyone in the jail,'' Ancell said. ``I was
going to put him on the road (as a sheriff's deputy) before long.
He would have made a...good officer. He had his head on straight.''
The accused
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear how well Tisius and Bulington knew Roy Vance.
Ancell said he thought Bulington was romantically linked to one of
the men, but he didn't know which one.
</P>
<P>
   Tisius drifted from job to job and occasionally wound up in jail
himself, said Ancell and Tisius' former neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have to case the place,'' Ancell said. ``He's been
in here three or four times'' for minor offenses.
</P>
<P>
   His last local address was in Moberly, about five miles from
Huntsville. For more than a year, Tisius shared an apartment in a
house near downtown Moberly with a girlfriend _ not Bulington _ and
their toddler girl, said Christina Rozkiewicz, who lives in the
house's other apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Tisius and his girlfriend split up in May, Rozkiewicz said.
Tisius told Rozkiewicz he was moving to Iowa with his stepfather.
</P>
<P>
   Life in Randolph County seemed to have dried up for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was working everywhere,'' said Tony Davis, Rozkiewicz's
roommate. ``McDonald's, a factory, a nursing home. He kept losing
his jobs because he kept getting arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Davis said, ``he seemed real nice and polite.
Anytime we asked him to turn down the radio, he wouldn't mouth off
or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Police had no more information on Bulington. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
