<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2375 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-     06-23 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
I-45 rivalry won't be instantly bitter
<TEXT>
<P>
   By MICKEY HERSKOWITZ
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ To a team famished for good news, or even mediocre
news, the disclosure that the Astros likely will launch an annual
rivalry with the Texas Rangers next year is a trifle hard to
catalog. Travel-weary players gladly will accept a series against a
club only an hour away by air, but getting into this ``natural
rivalry'' thing, working up a real passion, might not happen
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, next year is beginning to look uncomfortably close at
hand for the Astros, who have tumbled into Dante's Inferno, 19
games below .500 less than three months into this hellish season.
</P>
<P>
   Houston fans can start practicing, but how easy will it be to
refer to ``the hated Texas Rangers'' or exercise their lungs with
such sentiments as, ``Curse you, Pudge Rodriguez,'' or, ``Johnny
Oates can't lead a frog across the street?''
</P>
<P>
   Die-hard Astros fans view the American League as being as remote
as a Third World nation and did not see this bitter feud coming.
Therefore, we might explain that Rodriguez is the best catcher in
baseball, and Oates is a cheerful, pleasant cuss who has led the
Rangers to division titles in three of the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the Astros have found any kind of rivalry elusive,
including the unnatural ones. They had a nice vendetta going with
the Dodgers when both teams were in the National League West and
Tommy Lasorda was guilty of assorted war crimes, such as snubbing
Joe Niekro in the All-Star Game. Today the Astros' enemies are
everywhere, but the team that tops their hit list is St. Louis,
based largely on the fact Houston was once a farm club of the
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of two teams fighting for the state championship of
Texas has an obvious appeal, but the hatred that lasts a lifetime
grows out of competition. In basketball, the prospect of playing
Dallas never has caused the Rockets to foam at the mouth, because
the Mavericks are rarely contenders, and the series has been so
one-sided.
</P>
<P>
   After 24 seasons without a playoff team, the Rangers had their
breakthrough in 1996. As fate would have it, they met the Yankees
in each of their three appearances, never advancing to the next
round, winning one game while losing nine.
</P>
<P>
   Without comparing which city has suffered the most, the Astros
twice were within three outs of the World Series in 1980, and they
blew their next best chance against the Mets in 1986, losing the
sixth game of the National League Championship Series in 16
innings.
</P>
<P>
   You get the feeling Texas teams should not be required to play
New York teams in the playoffs. Perhaps Bud Selig can look into
this matter as his next miracle.
</P>
<P>
   It is Selig who will approve the annual pairing of the Astros
and Rangers for 2001, a Space Odyssey. Selig gave his marker this
week to the rival owners, Drayton McLane Jr. and Tom Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   The matchup has been close to an obsession with McLane since
baseball adopted interleague play four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that will be one of the best rivalries in baseball,''
Drayton has said. ``That was (always) the goal. We're really the
only natural, connected rivals that have not yet played. And we're
all disappointed we haven't gotten it solved up until now. But it
really looks promising, and I think it will bring a new dimension,
just as we're seeing in these other metropolitan cities.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Cubs and White Sox have competed for customers
and media space for most of a century; the Yankees and Mets, the
Dodgers and Angels for roughly 40 years. The Texas teams will be
starting from scratch, unless you see major significance in the
fact that in exhibition games the record is a tie, 6-6-1.
</P>
<P>
   McLane has been a persistent force in getting this deal done,
receiving an exemption that lets the teams play whether the Rangers
remain in the AL West or move to the AL Central.
</P>
<P>
   The timing is less than perfect, given Houston's nose dive and
the struggle of the Rangers to rise above .500. Both are in last
place in their divisions. The teams also have in common the
following: Interstate 45. Nolan Ryan. New ballparks.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros had a head start, arriving on the scene in 1962. The
Rangers came along 10 years later, having been blocked partly by
the political maneuvering of Judge Roy Hofheinz, who resisted
having a team in North Texas that would cut into Houston's radio
network.
</P>
<P>
   You doubt such stalwarts as Jeff Bagwell and Craig Biggio or
such newcomers as Julio Lugo and Richard Hidalgo quickly will
capture the spirit of this rivalry. For one thing, how much could
they know about the Metroplex?
</P>
<P>
   I mean, if Dallas is such a swell place to live, how come its
baseball team is in Arlington and its football team wound up in a
town called Irving?
</P>
<P>
   Bring 'em on.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
