<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2376 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBO-ASTROS-RANGERS-HN     06-23 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ASTROS-RANGERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
It's a natural
<TEXT>
<P>
   Commissioner on verge of allowing Astros, Rangers to meet
annually
</P>
<P>
   By CARLTON THOMPSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ According to a published report, the Astros and Texas
Rangers have been given the status of natural geographic rivals and
will play each other at least six times during the 2001 season,
regardless of any realignment that might take place.
</P>
<P>
   That might be the case, but Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr. said
nothing has been finalized.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commissioner (Bud Selig) has not told me that it's a done
deal,'' McLane said. ``You'll have to check with him on that. If he
tells you it's a done deal, call me so I'll know. In baseball,
nothing is done until it is done.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig has the authority to put the Astros and Rangers on the
field during the regular season under expanded powers that allow
him to act in the best interest of the game. McLane and Rangers
owner Tom Hicks believe playing each other during the regular
season is in the best interest of their franchises, and Selig
agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Selig said. ``The Rangers and the Astros should
play. And frankly, we've already gone one step further. They ought
to be described as a natural geographical rivalry, like you have
with the Mets-Yankees, Cubs-White Sox and so on.''
</P>
<P>
   Teams paired on baseball's natural rivals list will play each
other each season even after the division matchups begin to rotate
for interleague play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way it is, we don't get to play our natural rival, and
we're trying to reconcile that,'' McLane said. ``The commissioner
has said that he is going to try to make it happen, and I hope it
does.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy that we're in the same state and haven't played
each other in a regular-season game. I'd like to see it happen, but
it's still in the discussion stages. Nothing is set. Nothing moves
instantly in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros manager Larry Dierker is excited about the thought of
Texas' two teams playing during the regular season, but he wonders
how it will impact the shaky integrity of the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be good for the Astros and good for the
Rangers, but we already have a convoluted schedule,'' Dierker said.
``It's not a fair schedule in terms of making the playoffs if
you're playing teams that the other teams in your division aren't
playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the idea of us playing the Rangers, but I wish they
could come up with something simple, elegant and fair. I don't know
how you do that with 30 teams. This would just increase the
likelihood that the schedule would be unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros righthander Chris Holt, who is from Dallas, hopes the
possibility of a home-and-home series between the Astros and
Rangers becomes a reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd definitely like that,'' said Holt, who lives in Dallas
during the offseason. ``I'd be looking forward to the chance to get
to play at home. It would be great if they'd allow us to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the only teams that don't get to play their natural
rivals. I think it would be great for the state of Texas and great
for the game. Hopefully, it will get done.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 0119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
