<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2377 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-NADER-CHALLENGE-SFCHR     06-23 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NADER-CHALLENGE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 AN ALTERNATIVE AIMS FOR AUTHENTICITY  &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ No one doubts consumer activist Ralph Nader will
beat Jello Biafra this weekend for the Green Party's presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   And it's taken for granted that Northern California, with its
legion of liberal and disaffected voters, will be a Nader
stronghold this November.
</P>
<P>
   The hard questions about Nader are much more basic: Why is he
running for president, and could his candidacy cost Vice President
Al Gore the election?
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I worried about taking votes away from Gore? No.'' said
Nader, who has added universal health care, public financing of
elections, licensing of gun owners, withdrawal from the World Trade
Organization, and a one-third cut in the defense budget to his
familiar agenda of consumer protection. ``I'm worried about Gore
taking votes away from me.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader is serious. In fact, Nader is alway serious.
</P>
<P>
   More than three decades after his bestselling book, ``Unsafe at
Any Speed,'' shook the sensibilities of the nation's auto industry,
Nader is traipsing to every state in the union, sleeping on
supporters' couches and riding in the back of crowded airplanes to
painstakingly  &LR; take on the political mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't 17 cents worth of difference'' between Gore and
Texas Gov. George W. Bush,'' Nader said in an interview. ``Bush and
Gore are competing for the presidency to see who will take the
marching orders from their corporate paymasters.''
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of Princeton University and Harvard Law School, Nader
is not so caught up in his quest as to believe he has a chance to
win. His purpose is to establish the Greens as a ``significant
third party'' that will qualify for federal matching funds, and
serve as a ``lever to pull the Democratic Party to the left, or
make it shrink year by year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If (Gore) doesn't want to compete on the agenda that I am
running on, he has to incur the consequences,'' Nader said.
</P>
<P>
   There is purpose, but no joy in Nader's words. He is driven by
goals and displays no pleasure in engaging in politics.
</P>
<P>
   During a news conference Thursday at the Washington headquarters
of the International Brotherhood of Teamster _ where union
President James Hoffa showered him in praise _ Nader didn't crack a
smile for the first 28 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by a collection of brawny men who looked like they
subsist on cigars and steaks, the 66-year-old consumer crusader,
who looks like he favors strained spinach and wheat germ, finally
allowed the faintest of grins when he talked about the restaurant
his parents owned many years back in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to say when you went into Nader's restaurant you
paid a nickel for a cup of coffee and got 10 minutes of political
discussion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nader is intent on giving the country an earful between now and
November. Four years ago _ and only at the urging of others, he
insists _ Nader allowed his name to be used by the Green Party as
its presidential candidate, spending less than $5,000 and making
almost no campaign appearances.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he expects to raise $5 million with the help of
celebrity backers like Willie Nelson, Susan Sarandon, Phil Donahue,
Linda Ronstadt, Warren Beatty, the Indigo Girls and Pearl Jam.
</P>
<P>
   By sundown Friday, he will have visited all 50 states in his
quest to give voters a true alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, the American people are going to fall asleep watching
the drab debate the dreary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His message contains equal parts liberalism, socialism and
populism: American workers earn less money and work longer hours;
corporate greed deprives the poor of health care; and elections are
for sale, as corporate America has infested the political system,
creating a ``democracy gap'' that divides citizens from their
government.
</P>
<P>
   While Nader has long railed against the corporate powers, he
holds particular contempt for Democratic politicians who raise
substantial sums from big business and hew toward the political
center.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, he says, has ``broken more of his written promises than
any politician in modern history.''
</P>
<P>
   California Gov. Gray Davis, Nader told the Bay Guardian last
month, is a ``cash register politician'' who should be ``indicted
for extortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader himself has become wealthy over the course of his
anti-corporate crusade. He is worth $3.9 million, according to a
recent report by the Washington Post, enriched by smart investments
in high technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Number one, they're not monopolists,'' he told the Post,
defending his investments, ``And number two, they don't produce
land mines, napalm, weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course being rich hasn't changed his spartan lifestyle. Nader
rents an apartment near Washington's Dupont Circle, owns a small
black and white TV, and hasn't owned a car in 40 years. The money,
he says, helps finance his quests.
</P>
<P>
   So what of the prospects of his protest candidacy taking votes
away from Democrats and handing the election to Bush?
</P>
<P>
   So far, the polling is inconclusive. A Field Poll released this
week showed Nader drawing 7 percent of the vote in California, but
not affecting the dynamic of the race between Gore and Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The closer the race gets, the less likely voters are to cast
ballots for a third party alternative.
</P>
<P>
   However, Republican strategists believe Nader may be just the
advantage they need in a close election.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the Nader vote is coming straight out of the Democrat's
hide,'' said GOP pollster Stephen Kinney. ``Bush is in the ballgame
to take the West Coast, thanks to Nader to a great degree.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader points out that it is not a ``zero sum game.''
</P>
<P>
   While he acknowledges he could cost Gore some votes, most people
who vote for him for president will cast a ballot for a Democrat
for Congress, boosting the chances of Democrats to regain control
of the House, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is very uncommon for third-party candidates to alter a
presidential election. One has to go back to 1912, when Teddy
Roosevelt ran as a Bull Moose progressive, taking votes from
Republican William Howard Taft and throwing the election to
Democrat Woodrow Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   The Green Party will nominate its candidate this weekend.
Nader's competitors include Jello Biafra, the former lead singer
for the punk rock group The Dead Kennedys, who ran  &LR; finished fourth
in the 1979 San Francisco mayor's race, and Stephen Gaskin, the
founder of The Farm, which at one time was the largest hippie
community in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Nader's chances of becoming president may be no greater than
those of Biafra or Gaskin. But his chances of enlivening the debate
are significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``This campaign really can't lose,'' he said. ``If America's
working people are taken for granted, then America's working
families will be taken.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
