<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2386 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-PUZZLE-LADN-(SLAN     06-23 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PUZZLE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEN TO MANAGER DAVEY JOHNSON... 
PIECING IT TOGETHER
</HEADLINE>
 ... CORRECTIONS AN ATTRIBUTION FROM(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ During the last week of spring training, the Los
Angeles Dodgers targeted late June as the time teams would know
where they stood and what they would need for a second-half run at
the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Through the evaluation, the Dodgers figured reliever Alan Mills
or utility infielder Jose Vizcaino were expendable and decided that
with Geronimo Berroa's injury, Jim Leyritz's right-handed power bat
was a must.
</P>
<P>
   Questions remain about the leadoff and center-field spots, the
closer's role and whether the Dodgers will get production out of
the fourth and fifth starters in the rotation. But those are
questions that must be answered and they'll likely be answered
internally. And that's when the Dodgers will know whether they have
all the parts to make a run at the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all the pieces to the puzzle are here, but you never
know what (management) is going to do by the July 31 (trade)
deadline,'' Dodgers reliever Jeff Shaw said. ``They may go out and
pick somebody else up, another pitcher. There's only a couple of
question marks. Arizona has played well at home (25-10) and they
have not run away from us. It's going to be a jockeying thing
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers withstood injuries to right-hander Kevin Brown,
third baseman Adrian Beltre and Kevin Elster, who has since lost
his starting shortstop job and is in a platoon with Alex Cora.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers will get healthier Monday when catcher Todd Hundley
should return. But no one knows whether center fielder Devon White
will return from a partially torn left rotator cuff or whether
he'll need season-ending surgery.
</P>
<P>
   There was also the distraction of the impending suspensions, but
even so, the Dodgers are 2 games behind Arizona in the National
League West.
</P>
<P>
   But it's hardly time to make the big push. That happens in a
month when teams go through another evaluation period in
preparation for the July 31 trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have to wait and see for the next month or so and
see how teams load up and that will help determine what we need to
do,'' Dodgers right fielder Shawn Green said. ``You have to see
who's available. Starting now, it becomes a lot more clear as each
week goes by. There's no telling what's going to happen in our
division the next month.''
</P>
<P>
   But that could prove to be a problem for the Dodgers. While
Arizona and Colorado have the organizational depth to make a
blockbuster deal at the trading deadline, the Dodgers fall short.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I know, (general manager) Kevin (Malone) is always
working the phones, but the (minor-league) system is still not
where it needs to be, so there's not a lot of depth to where you
can talk about moving some of them,'' said manager Davey Johnson.
``It's a couple years behind to where you have the insurance
policies at Triple-A to have all the parts.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz, or Berroa, provide the right-handed bat off the bench
that makes opposing managers choose between facing Dave Hansen or,
at this time, Leyritz. But Shaw has blown six of 18 save chances
and is no longer the end-all, be-all closer. Instead, he'll get
help from Mike Fetters, Terry Adams and Matt Herges.
</P>
<P>
   White's uncertain status has turned center field into a platoon
among Todd Hollandsworth and F.P. Santangelo and left the Dodgers
without their choice for leadoff hitter.
</P>
<P>
   And the fourth and fifth spots in the rotation, occupied by
Carlos Perez and Orel Hershiser, remain suspect. Perez is 4-3, but
he's won once since May 3. Hershiser's lone win came during the
nostalgic home opener, and he's made only four starts and has a
10.80 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always believe in having two aces on a team, and the way
Chan Ho (Park) is pitching, he's proven he can be an ace,'' said
Dodgers left fielder Gary Sheffield, knowing Kevin Brown's status
as an ace is a given. ``But you have to go out and prove you can do
it. You can have the stuff all day long, but you have to be able to
do it and execute.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
