<HEADER>
A2387 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-L.A.-SUBWAY-ART-650&AMP;A     06-23 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-L.A.-SUBWAY-ART-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES SUBWAY REACHES END OF THE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On Saturday morning the Los Angeles Red Line, long
derided as the subway to nowhere, will at last be a subway to
somewhere: from downtown to suburban San Fernando Valley, to be
precise.
</P>
<P>
   The opening of the last 6.3 miles of track under the Hollywood
hills will complete the most expensive subway in the nation's
history, 17.4 miles at a cost of more than $4.5 billion, originally
planned as the first stretch of a more extensive system.
</P>
<P>
   But as it turns out, the start of service to North Hollywood
marks an end as well as a beginning, and the city's first subway
line will almost certainly be its last. Fifteen years of
construction delays, accidents, cost overruns and a changed
political climate have led voters to block further use of local
sales tax revenue for subway construction, and forced leaders to
look elsewhere for mass transit solutions to growing problems with
traffic and urban sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, on the very day the three new subway stops open, the
Metropolitan Transportation Authority will introduce the next big
proposal: 80 express buses outfitted with transponders that signal
wire loops in the pavement to hold green lights (or shorten red
ones) so buses can speed through intersections.
</P>
<P>
   The new service, the most extensive use of such new technology
in the nation, will begin on major thoroughfares that link up with
the subway: Ventura Boulevard in the San Fernando Valley and
Wilshire Boulevard from the Pacific Ocean in Santa Monica to the
city of Montebello, 26 miles to the east.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation officials hope to lure at least 100,000 riders a
day to the completed subway line, a trickle in a county that has 10
million residents and 6 million motor vehicles. Since ground was
broken for the subway in 1986, bus ridership on the city's
transportation system, the nation's most crowded, has fallen from
about 500 million passengers a year to fewer than 400 million as
money has been shifted to pay for subway construction and fares
have risen to $1.35 from 50 cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they get 100,000 riders a day, given the billions that have
been spent, that would flunk any cost-benefit analysis that we
could imagine,'' said Peter Gordon, a professor of urban and
regional planning at the University of Southern California who is a
longtime subway critic. ``So it's hard to take the project
seriously as a transportation project. It's a pork-barrel jobs
project and a political project.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowning insanity,'' Gordon added, ``is that there are
still toilet-trained adults walking around who say: `Isn't this
cool? Haven't we done a good thing?'''
</P>
<P>
   The new subway is undeniably cool, with quiet,
stainless-steel-skinned trains whooshing through twin tunnels in
the Santa Monica Mountains, at their deepest 900 feet below
Mulholland Drive.
</P>
<P>
   Each new station is designed to be an architectural jewel, with
visual motifs representing each neighborhood's history. For
example, ceilings in the North Hollywood stop are painted in
concentric rings of soft yellows, orange and green, a testament to
the area's citrus-growing past.
</P>
<P>
   A raft of dignitaries, including Mayor Richard Riordan, are
expected at the dedication on Friday, but even the subway's biggest
boosters strike an ambivalently celebratory note.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do I feel?'' asked Rep. Julian Dixon, an 11-term Democrat
from central Los Angeles who helped win federal money for the
project after some Los Angeles politicians tried to block it. ``I'm
glad that we now have the beginnings of a comprehensive rail system
that has meaningful transportation destinations. But I'm
disappointed that there's a prohibition on local money, and I think
ultimately we're going to have to re-examine that issue because
cars on the streets and congestion are a growing problem that has
to be dealt with.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Long a dream of former Mayor Tom Bradley, the subway was
enthusiastically embraced by the establishment before falling
victim to infighting, route changes and seemingly endless setbacks,
from the giant sinkhole that opened on Hollywood Boulevard in 1995
to the deaths of three construction workers in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   When construction began, the mix of hard rock and soft shale
under the mountains made digging difficult; at one point a boring
machine was stuck for weeks. By 1998, cost overruns and a
threatened cutoff of federal money led to the scrapping of planned
extensions to East Los Angeles and central Los Angeles and a
planned light rail line to Pasadena, leaving just the 17-mile Red
Line.
</P>
<P>
   The Pasadena line has since been revived, and is to be finished
by 2003. The overall system also includes two surface light rail
lines.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, transit experts have been pressing for
enhanced bus service. The new express bus, dubbed Metro Rapid, is a
first test of such options; if it proves successful, officials hope
to expand it.
</P>
<P>
   In the pilot project, which officials call a ``rubber-tire
railway,'' a radio transmitter underneath special low-riding buses
sends a signal that can turn a red light at an approaching
intersection green, or hold a green light for up to 10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Each bus' signal identifies it by number, and the coded
information is transmitted through copper wire and fiber-optic
cable to the command center of the city's Department of
Transportation. If a bus is late, the computer tells the light to
wait.
</P>
<P>
   Some rider groups oppose the new bus service, contending that it
is not extensive enough and that it will result in the elimination
of some existing express bus service in the San Fernando Valley.
Others worry about the effect on north-south cross traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something we're definitely going to monitor,'' said
John E. Fisher, an assistant general manager of the transportation
department. ``It could be a possible minor problem on Wilshire, but
we don't believe that an extra five seconds will be much of an
impediment. And all traffic on the east-west streets will get the
benefit if a green light gets lengthened for the bus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
