<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2389 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-KOREAN-PRESBYTERIANS-     06-23 2392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREAN-PRESBYTERIANS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ASIAN PRESBYTERIANS AT ODDS WITH RELIGION'S LIBERAL TRADITION  &HT;     By DON LATTIN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At first glance, Immanuel Presbyterian Church
seems like a brick-and-mortar testament to ethnic diversity, a
place where Caucasians, Koreans, Filipinos, blacks and Latinos come
together for Sunday worship.
</P>
<P>
   Look a little deeper, however, and you'll find a Sunday morning
apartheid undermining the foundations of the Presbyterian Church
(USA), one of the nation's most established mainline denominations.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, thousands of Presbyterians from across the United
States will gather in Southern California for the denomination's
annual policymaking convention. But the real future of the
organization, which has a strong liberal Protestant tradition, will
not be decided in cavernous convention halls, but in multiracial
congregations like Immanuel, located in the sprawling Koreatown
district of downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   This classic Gothic church, built in 1922 for a huge Caucasian
congregation that disappeared decades ago, stands at ground zero of
an evangelical Christian revival exploding across Asian American
neighborhoods in Southern California. Here at Immanuel, the largest
congregation of worshippers may be Korean speakers, but they do not
belong to the 2.5 million-member Presbyterian Church (USA).
Instead, they belong to a conservative Korean American denomination
that rents space.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, mainline Presbyterian leaders have been trying
to attract ethnic minorities, part of continuing attempts to
reverse a steady membership decline. But the multicultural crusade,
favored by liberals and conservatives alike, has hit a theological
roadblock.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Asian American Christians sought by Presbyterians
are conservative evangelicals who oppose the denomination's liberal
leanings _ including measures to ordain gay ministers and allow
``holy union'' ceremonies for same-sex couples.
</P>
<P>
   Immanuel is more ethnically diverse than most of the nation's
Presbyterian congregations. It attracts about 160 Caucasian and
Filipino worshippers to its English-language service on Sunday, and
60 Latinos for Spanish services.
</P>
<P>
   But the truly thriving flock of Presbyterians gathering below
Immanuel's stained-glass windows and spectacular chandeliers is its
tenants _ Yul Lin Mun Korean Presbyterian Church.
</P>
<P>
   The Korean-speaking congregation, led by the Rev. Hung Sung
Park, has quadrupled in size since it began meeting here in 1993,
and it now packs the main sanctuary with more than 1,000
worshippers for its 1 p.m. Sunday service. This is such a devout
flock that around 100 members also show up every weekday for 6 a.m.
sunrise prayers.
</P>
<P>
   Yul Lin Mun, which means ``Open Door,'' is part of the Korean
American Presbyterian Church, which does not ordain women and views
homosexuality as inherently sinful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's against the Bible,'' said Park, speaking through an
interpreter. ``Churches should not bend to society.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Caucasian pastor of Immanuel, the Rev. Frank
Alton, has gotten used to the Sunday morning segregation at his
sanctuary and to renting space to a congregation that dwarfs his
own flock.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first few years I was here, I was very intense about
trying to bring us all together,'' Alton said. ``But they're not
used to mixing with other groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Korean Christian churches are blossoming across the Golden
State, with Southern California home to an estimated 700 Korean
congregations.
</P>
<P>
   They are the fruits of labors of 19th century Presbyterian
missionaries in Korea. Through luck, clever planning or the power
of the Holy Spirit, these missionaries from the United States
arrived at just the right moment in that nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   More than anywhere else in Asia, Presbyterianism took root in
Korea. Some say the Protestant faith dovetails nicely with
Confucian values in traditional Korean society, along with a
respect for elders and an orderly worship style that's not too
expressive.
</P>
<P>
   Today, in an evangelical twist on East meets West, many Korean
Americans see themselves as the true missionaries of Christ,
destined to bring a spiritually adrift America back to its
religious heritage.
</P>
<P>
   At Fuller Theological Seminary in Pasadena, nearly a third of
the conservative school's 3,000 students are of Korean heritage _
an ethnic explosion that has occurred in just the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We regret that America is being de-Christianized by the forces
of secularism,'' said Professor Seyoon Kim, a New Testament scholar
at Fuller. ``Korean Christians pray for the revival of Christian
faith in America and Europe. We see this as part of our mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the Presbyterian Church (USA) convenes its weeklong
General Assembly in Long Beach, an annual policymaking convention
of voting delegates from across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Their first order of business is to elect a new assembly
``moderator,'' and two Korean Americans are among the four
candidates for the key post.
</P>
<P>
   Youngil Cho, a church elder from Raleigh, N.C., or Syngman Rhee,
a professor at Union Theological Seminary in Richmond, Va., would
be the first Korean American to hold the office.
</P>
<P>
   Both men came to the United States in the aftermath of the
Korean War _ and could assume the moderator's post this weekend, on
the 50th anniversary of a Cold War conflict that is only now
winding down.
</P>
<P>
   Among the issues facing this General Assembly are the two
controversies fueling a fiery debate between liberals and
evangelicals in the Presbyterian church and in other mainline
Protestant denominations _ gay marriage and the ordination of
homosexuals as pastors and church elders.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Cho said he opposes the ordination of gays and
lesbians, as well as ``holy union'' ceremonies for homosexual
couples. ``But we welcome everybody to church,'' he said. ``We are
all sinners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Koreans are committed to the Lord and doing what God wants,''
said Cho, the more conservative of the two Korean-born candidates.
``We must believe the Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhee, a former president of the liberal-leaning National Council
of Churches, could not be reached for comment. But in a prepared
statement, he promises a ``ministry of reconciliation'' to bring
together the increasingly factious denomination.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent survey of Latino, African American and
Korean American members of this predominantly white denomination,
Korean Americans were most likely to disapprove of gay couples (95
percent), to call themselves ``born again'' (75 percent) and to
believe in hell (82 percent).
</P>
<P>
   The Korean Americans' traditional views on sex and marriage have
produced something of a conundrum for liberal Presbyterians _ who
are pushing for both racial diversity and a more tolerant policy
toward gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We strongly believe in developing racially inclusive churches,
but every time we succeed on that front, there's another vote
against us (on gay rights issues),'' said Pamela Byers of San
Francisco, executive director of the Covenant Network of
Presbyterians, a liberal lobbying group in the denomination.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Korean Presbyterian ministers across the state say
their members have little interest in the gay rights debate and
other social justice issues that now consume the Presbyterian
Church (USA).
</P>
<P>
   ``Korean American Christians in the Bay Area are focused more on
moral and ethical issues,'' said the Rev. Myong Bae Choi, who has
pastored the 155-member Alameda Korean Presbyterian Church since
1986. ``They stress more their children's education and good moral
conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   The largest Korean-speaking congregation in the Presbyterian
Church (USA) is in Southern California. Torrance First Presbyterian
holds Sunday services for about 4,000 adults and children at a
sprawling complex that brings together a converted warehouse,
parking lots and another large building with a white arch. It all
looks more like a community college campus than a church.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the PC-USA ordains homosexual pastors or blesses gay
unions, most Korean American churches will reconsider being a part
of the denomination,'' said the Rev. Michael Hwang, an associate
pastor at the Torrance church.
</P>
<P>
   Hwang's fast-growing congregation has prospered as Korean
Americans in Los Angeles have climbed the economic ladder and moved
out of Koreatown. About 1,000 members of Torrance Presbyterian now
live on the posh hillsides of the Palos Verdes Peninsula, which
rises above this hazy South Bay  &LR; suburb like a beacon of upward
mobility.
</P>
<P>
   Hwang, who plans to help out at the opening worship service at
the General Assembly meeting this weekend, had not even heard of
homosexuality when he came here from Korea in 1981 at the age of
22.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe there were homosexuals in Korea, but nobody told me
about them,'' he said. ``Our culture is very closed. We don't talk
publicly about personal issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Korean immigrant community is centered around the
church,'' said Hwang. ``Christian history, for us, is only 200
years old. As newborn Christians, we don't know much about liberal
theology, but our hearts are pure and evangelical.''
</P>
<P>
   Across town, at Immanuel, Alton has a slightly different take on
the Korean churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like the Caucasian church back in the 1950s,'' he
said. ``They're ethnically homogeneous, and the services are very
similar. The church works like in the '50s. It's where you go to
network. They're aligned with business interests, but they're not
getting politically involved with social justice issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Alton said the suburban flight in the Korean community also
reminds him of the 1950s. It picked up in the aftermath of riots
that swept Los Angeles eight years ago _ sparked by the verdict in
the Rodney King case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still call it `Koreatown,' but the population is only about
15 percent Korean,'' Alton said. ``There are more Latinos and
African Americans, but the property ownership is more and more
Korean.''
</P>
<P>
   Presbyterians, who trace their roots back to John Calvin, the
16th century Swiss church reformer, were among the first Protestant
churches to firmly establish themselves in colonial America.
</P>
<P>
   Its largest denomination, the Presbyterian Church (USA), dates
back to an association of churches organized in Philadelphia in
1706, and it is the product of at least 10 denominational mergers
over the past 250 years.
</P>
<P>
   But this mainstay of the American ecumenical movement faces a
serious problem. Since the 1960s, it has been losing about 30,000
members a year.
</P>
<P>
   To stop the exodus, church leaders have embarked on an ambitious
campaign to attract ethnic minorities _ including Asian Americans,
Latinos and African Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Today, these ``racial ethnic church members'' comprise only
about 5 percent of the overwhelmingly white denomination. But the
goal is to increase minority membership to 10 percent by 2005 and
20 percent by 2020.
</P>
<P>
   There has been some success on that front in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   In the San Francisco Presbytery, the last five churches to join
the denomination have had ethnic congregations _ a Latino church in
Oakland, an Indonesian congregation in San Francisco, a Korean
flock in Fremont and two Chinese churches in Walnut Creek and
Fremont.
</P>
<P>
   ``They bring in a whole new set of perceptions and
understandings about how to be a Christian in the world,'' said the
Rev. Jim Glasse, a retired Presbyterian minister in Orinda who
helped the churches join the denomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all wrestling with the delicate and difficult balance
of retaining ethnic identity and becoming part of the American
scene,'' Glasse said. ``They can't all become Scot-Irish
Presbyterians.''
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic infusion, he said, has been a morale booster to a
denomination in decline. ``The conventional wisdom is that mainline
denominations don't make sense anymore,'' he said. ``It's
reassuring that somebody still wants us.''
</P>
<P>
   Church growth experts say Asian Americans could be the secret to
stopping the mainline Presbyterian decline _ especially in
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``If spiritual revival has occurred among any group of people in
the United States in the past decade, it is undeniably among
Asians,'' reports the Barna Research Group, an evangelical
pollster.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Asian Americans calling themselves ``born-again''
Christians has jumped from 5 percent in 1991 to 27 percent in
February 2000, according to a recent report by Barna. That is the
percentage of Asian Americans who say they have a personal
commitment to Jesus Christ and expect to reach heaven because they
confessed their sins and accepted Christ as their savior.
</P>
<P>
   You can see this revival, up close and personal, at Young Nak
Presbyterian Church of Los Angeles, whose 7,500 members make it the
biggest congregation outside Korea.
</P>
<P>
   It is the largest of 263 churches in yet another Korean
denomination, the 29,000-member Korean Presbyterian Church in
America.
</P>
<P>
   Young Nak rises above the Los Angeles River, a trickle of water
in a ridiculously wide concrete canal. It is tucked between
Chinatown and Lincoln Heights, a poor Latino neighborhood northeast
of downtown Los Angeles. Its complex of cinderblock buildings takes
up an entire city block _ a fenced-off island of Korean faith and
culture in this endless multicultural metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   Two nights ago, the place was buzzing with midweek activity.
Inside the main building, the sweet and spicy smell of kim chee, a
Korean cabbage dish, filled the fellowship hall as ladies donned
choir robes and their husbands chowed down.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs, well-dressed couples filed into a huge sanctuary for
Wednesday night worship. Across the parking lot, on the other side
of the block, a youth group getting ready for a summer mission to
Mexico barbecued sausages and salt-covered tri-tips.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Paul Kang, who ministers to young adults, sat down with
a plate of barbecue and explained how California's Korean Christian
revival is really not all that complicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone comes here from Korea. He knows no one, but there's a
pastor waiting to meet him at the airport, ready to help him find
an apartment,'' he said. ``They might be Buddhists, Christians or
nonbelievers. It doesn't matter. We call it evangelism.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
