<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2392 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLA     06-23 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREIFORT SUFFERS THIRD STRAIGHT LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Chan Ho Park has done his part, becoming a nice
complement for staff ace Kevin Brown in the starting rotation. But
for the Los Angeles Dodgers to make a playoff run, they need three
dependable starters.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Dreifort is supposed to be that third guy and six weeks
ago he was poised to do it. Then, something changed and no one
quite knows what.
</P>
<P>
   For the fifth time in six starts Dreifort lost, giving up three
first-inning runs as the Dodgers dropped the series finale Thursday
to Houston 6-3 at Enron Field, ending the club's winning streak at
three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was probably overthrowing a little bit (in the first
inning),'' Dreifort said. ``It wasn't that I wasn't comfortable the
first inning. I didn't get the ball where it needed to be. It's not
that big of a deal. You come out, you have a lot of energy. That's
the way (stuff) goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody that comes out is going to have adrenaline. It cost
me, it cost us, three runs in the first inning.''
</P>
<P>
   The first-inning meltdown surprised pitching coach Claude
Osteen, who said Dreifort was phenomenal in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   But that changed the moment Dreifort stepped on the mound. He
issued a pair of one-out walks before Lance Berkman hit a three-run
shot onto the home run porch in left-center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely having early-inning problems,'' Osteen said.
``He didn't look comfortable out there to me. The stuff he had
warming up in the pen, the control he had, it wasn't the same as he
took out there in the first inning. Maybe the stuff was, but he
never seemed to get settled. He was all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Dreifort allowed five runs, only three _ via the homer _
were earned. He pitched seven innings, walked three and struck out
three.
</P>
<P>
   It's hardly what the Dodgers expected of Dreifort, especially
after he pitched a two-hit shutout May 12 in St. Louis. But since
then Dreifort has won just once, a June 7 victory at Texas. He's
allowed at least three earned runs in seven of his last eight
starts and has lost three straight to fall to 4-6.
</P>
<P>
   The defense also didn't help keep this one close. With runners
on second and third and one out in the sixth, Julio Lugo hit a soft
liner to Mark Grudzielanek at second. But Grudzielanek misjudged
the speed of the ball and it went through his legs, allowing two
runs to score and giving the Astros a 5-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to keep that ball in there and make a play and get an
out,'' Grudzielanek said. ``That probably cost us the game, or a
chance to win it, at least. I came up. It was a changeup and it
kind of deceived me a little bit. You can't do that. You can't let
it go through your legs and to the outfield.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers trailed 6-1 in the ninth but got the tying run to
the plate. Gary Sheffield led off the inning with a solo homer, his
24th, and the Dodgers loaded the bases with none out. But catcher
Chad Kreuter grounded into a double play to kill the rally and give
the Astros the 6-3 win. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 0129EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
