<SLUG> BC-HOLY-AMMANCHI-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIAN SPIRITUALIST VISITS LOS ANGELES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MONROE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ She's known as Amma or, more descriptively, ``the
hugging saint.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday morning, the Indian spiritualist likened to Mother
Teresa and Mahatma Gandhi began her day with a grand entry into the
Warner Center Marriott's main ballroom. White-robed initiates lined
her path as some 300 devotees uttered a rhythmic Sanskrit chant of
salutation.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief meditation, the diminutive woman from the Indian
state of Kerala began the ritual of the (italics on) darshan
(italics off), a blessing given with a hug. She would stop only
when the last person came before her.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, when an estimated 2,000 people came to greet
her, she had hugged until 2:30 a.m. In San Francisco the night
before that, she hugged until 4:30 a.m., with some of the blessing
recipients walking away in tears -- a scene repeated thousands of
times a week in halls all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trembling,'' said Anne Jones, a Simi Valley resident,
after embracing Amma, also called Ammachi -- names that mean
``mother.'' Jones gasped as she tried to describe the rush she
felt, like a moment of religious epiphany mixed with a roller
coaster thrill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just such a warm tender embrace,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The hug contains Amma's message and says all about her appeal,
her followers said as the spiritualist held court Thursday on her
second day in Los Angeles. Amma is visiting the area in a 10-city
swing through America, a tour she has taken every summer since
1987.
</P>
<P>
   In every one of those summers, the numbers coming to see her
have grown steadily, said organizers of her U.S. tours. Between
hugs, Ammachi said through a translator that more people are
looking for the simple goals of peace and love.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of freedom in this country, but it's only a
physical freedom,'' she said. ``The heart is being imprisoned.''
</P>
<P>
   Amma seeks no money on her tours, nor does she bear the message
of any religion. Nevertheless, donations have funded more than two
dozen orphanages in India and a free hospital in her home state.
Established in her name are two spiritual centers, one in San
Ramon, Calif., and the other in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   During this year's stay in America, she will be among the
spiritual leaders of the world who will address the United Nations
General Assembly at the Millennium World Peace Summit of Religious
and Spiritual Leaders in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her appeal is growing all over because what she portrays is
unconditional love,'' said Omana Philip, an Anaheim Hills resident
who said her Christian faith was strengthened by Amma, who was
raised as a Hindu.
</P>
<P>
   Amma, born Mata Amritanandamyi, will return to the Marriott on
Sunday for a public program starting at 6:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   XXX &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
