A2399 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-MARS-WATER-SFCHRON &LR;      06-23 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARS-WATER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SCIENTISTS SHOW EVIDENCE OF UNDERGROUND WATER ON MARS  &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Space scientists offered powerful details Thursday to support
their theory that vast amounts of water on ancient Mars may have
disappeared underground eons ago, then resurfaced, and could even
be evident now.
</P>
<P>
   And because water is the key ingredient for life, its discovery
so near the Martian surface should shape future reconnaissance
missions as preludes to a manned search for life on the planet in
coming decades, the scientists agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the new findings will be published in next week's
issue of the journal Science, but because some content circulated
widely this week, NASA officials released the complete report
Thursday. At the same time, the researchers described their
findings at a Washington press conference carried to Space Agency
centers on television.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle reported some of the new discoveries Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Malin, the founder of Malin Space Science Systems, a
small 12-person company in San Diego, is the star of the discovery
team, and his staff scientist, Kenneth Edgett, was his co-star at
the press conference. They are the sole authors of the new report
in Science.
</P>
<P>
   Malin's company developed the imaging camera carried aboard the
Mars Global Surveyor. The camera has been orbiting the Red Planet
since September 1997, and has already  &LR; taken more than 65,000
high-resolution pictures of its surface.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency is saying the Surveyor spacecraft's images
``could turn out to be a landmark discovery in the history of Mars
exploration.'' Edward Weiler, chief of the Office of Space Science
at NASA headquarters, called the new images ``incredibly compelling
evidence for liquid water on Mars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The presence of liquid water on Mars has profound implications
for Astrobiology, the question of life not only in the past, but
perhaps even today,'' Weiler said. ``If life ever did develop
there, and if it survives to the present time, then these landforms
would be great places to look.''
</P>
<P>
   The discovery could rejuvenate NASA's Mars exploration program,
which lost two spacecraft flying to the planet last year. The Mars
Polar Lander, a $165 million craft, vanished just before landing in
December, and the $125 million Mars Climate Orbiter was lost in
September due to a navigational error.
</P>
<P>
   The new evidence for water near the surface, Weiler said, could
call for changes in the search strategies built into the missions
of Mars landers due to be launched as early as 2005 and 2008. It
also calls for a series of reconnaissance missions before any
consideration of manned expeditions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 250 of Malin's images, the pictures show an extraordinary
variety of gullies, channels, trenches and fan-shaped regions where
surging water may have dumped debris just the way flash floods on
Earth fling boulders as big as cars downstream.
</P>
<P>
   ``The features appear to be so young that they might be forming
even today,'' Malin said. ``These are new land forms that have
never been seen before on Mars, but we think we are seeing evidence
of a groundwater supply similar to an underground aquifer. The
gullies could be on the order of a million years old, or they could
have formed yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   In most of the features where water appears, it seems to have
seeped or gushed and then flowed downhill from crater rims that are
located far away from the Martian equator and closer to the
northern and southern polar regions. Scientists studying Mars from
past missions have long suspected that the dry deserts and rocky
highlands of Martian equatorial regions are far than the
less-heavily cratered areas nearer the poles where water _ it now
appears _ is a major feature.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think about the requirements for supporting life on
Mars, the key comes down to liquid water,'' said Bruce Jakosky of
the University of Colorado's Laboratory for Atmospheric and Space
Physics. ``This doesn't tell us that life does exist on Mars, but
it's the smoking gun that tells us Mars has all the elements for
life.''
</P>
<P>
   If water is emerging even now from the rims of Martian craters,
it should evaporate swiftly _ sublimate is the operative word _ but
it might still lie in liquid form only a few yards below the
surface, the scientists believe.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Carr, a planetary geologist at the Menlo Park regional
office of the U. S. Geological Survey, has been studying the
problem of water on Mars for more than 25 years. ``This is most
exciting, and quite compelling for an interpretation that water
does exist,'' he said of the Malin images.
</P>
<P>
   He noted, however, that with Martian surface temperatures as low
as 180 degrees Fahrenheit any water in the ground should be frozen
for two to four miles deep _ apparently incompatible with liquid
water existing at the surface. But the Malin images, he conceded
make the idea of flowing water ``perfectly plausible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
