<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-REDSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX DEFEAT YANKEES, 4-2 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They scored 22 runs on Monday, beat Pedro Martinez on
Tuesday, and yet the Yankees walked out of here barely in second
place on Thursday night, over the cracked foundation of Fenway
Park, with nothing more than a split of the four-game series with
the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   It is the nature of the Yankees right now, an inconsistency that
is becoming the most consistent aspect of the team. Ramiro Mendoza
and Andy Pettitte might have been spectacular Monday and Tuesday,
but on Thursday night, the 22-year-old rookie Jake Westbrook was
knocked out before the end of the third inning in a 4-2 loss to the
Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra keyed two Boston rallies with doubles, and
Ramon Martinez pitched six and two-thirds solid innings in getting
the victory for the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, now a half-game behind Boston and in a virtual tie
with Toronto, begin a three-game series Friday night in Chicago,
and once again, they will be forced to plug their injury-plagued
rotation. Ben Ford, 25, has eight major league appearances and two
professional starts after 282 relief appearances, and he will be
promoted from Class AAA Columbus to start against the White Sox.
Westbrook was informed after Thursday night's game that he is being
sent back to Columbus, as expected.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee players became aware of a possible trade for Juan
Gonzalez after the game. Ricky Ledee, one of the players who would
go to Detroit for the slugging outfielder, was surrounded by
reporters, and his teammates whispered among themselves, asking
why. Players spoke carefully in response to news of the pending
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez ``is an mvp-type player,'' said David Cone, the
Yankees' pitcher. ``We have a great clubhouse that could really
help him.''
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Posada is a friend of Ledee's and seemed sad to hear the
Yankee outfielder's name mentioned in the trade talks. But Posada
acknowledged Gonzalez's potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very special,'' Posada said. ``He's one of those people
that brings a presence every time he goes to the plate. He would
fit right in the lineup. He's a good hitter. He drives in 120-plus
runs every year, hits 30-plus home runs. We'll see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees ate, showered and dressed, unsure of who will be
playing the outfield in Chicago Friday and disappointed at the
outcome of the series here.
</P>
<P>
   ``After beating Pedro on Tuesday, we had visions of winning
three and maybe four games here,'' said Joe Torre, the Yankees'
manager. ``Winning two is a disappointment. We need to put together
a streak for confidence. I thought we had something going after
winning the first two.''
</P>
<P>
   They could have won three, but fell behind early on Thursday
night. Westbrook lasted only one and two-thirds innings in his
first start against the White Sox last week, allowing six runs. But
Westbrook came back the next day and, at the end of a one-sided
defeat, pitched two and one-third scoreless innings, and the
pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre hoped Westbrook could build off the
confidence gleaned in that second appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Westbrook did look good early on Thursday night, striking out
the leadoff hitter Jose Offerman on a called third strike before
retiring Jeff Frye and Trot Nixon for a 1-2-3 inning. The fact that
John Hirschbeck, who calls one of the most generous strike zones in
baseball, was the umpire behind home plate was good fortune for
Westbrook.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams had bashed a very long two-run homer in the top
of the first inning, his 16th, and the Yankees had a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the Red Sox began smashing line drives in the second inning
and drove Westbrook from the mound before the end of the third.
``His fastball was good,'' Torre said. ``I think he just got in
trouble with his secondary pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra began the second with the first of two doubles
against Westbrook, and Carl Everett singled home Garciaparra and
eventually scored on a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Frye doubled inside the first-base line with one out in the
third inning. Westbrook walked Nixon and Garciaparra pushed Frye
across with a double. Jason Grimsley quickly jumped to his feet in
the bullpen and started throwing, while Stottlemyre walked slowly
to the mound; it was evident that Westbrook's outing was going to
end soon.
</P>
<P>
   Everett was walked intentionally, and with the count 1-0 on
Brian Daubach, Grimsley nodded in the bullpen that he was ready.
The bullpen coach Tony Cloninger relayed word to Jeff Nelson, who
picked up the phone to inform Stottlemyre and Torre in the Yankees'
dugout.
</P>
<P>
   But Torre did not make a change immediately, possibly because he
had watched Grimsley walk three in a span of five hitters Wednesday
night and did not want to call on him with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach singled to left field, driving home Nixon with Boston's
fourth run. Ledee threw home and the ball beat Garciaparra, who
appeared to elude the tag but was called out.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees were down by 4-2, would never recover and took
that long walk out of Fenway after the game, into the muggy Boston
night. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
