<SLUG> BC-QUACKENBUSH-WHISTLEBLOWER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 INSURANCE PAPERS LEAKED TO COMMITTEE  &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ A San Francisco lawyer has admitted leaking
confidential documents to a legislative committee probing the
actions of embattled Insurance Commissioner Chuck Quackenbush,
sources told The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Department of Insurance lawyer Cindy Ossais reportedly told the
California Highway Patrol _ after being read her Miranda rights _
that she turned the controversial documents over to a former
consultant with the Assembly Insurance Committee in January.
</P>
<P>
   Ossais, a 10-year veteran with the department, has been placed
on paid administrative leave, said Dan Edwards, a spokesman for the
department.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly investigators say Ossais is a brave whistle blower, who
turned over the documents out of concern, but Quackenbush's aides
say it shows the whole investigation has been a political show.
</P>
<P>
   ``They pressed and pressed us to give them something that was
already in their possession,'' Edwards said. ``They wanted to try
to make it legitimate.''
</P>
<P>
   Ossais is expected to be a key witness Monday, when the Assembly
Insurance Committee resumes its hearings into the actions of
Quackenbush and his top aides.
</P>
<P>
   Ossais referred all questions to her attorney, Doron Weinberg,
who did not did not return calls Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators are investigating allegations that Quackenbush
coerced insurance companies into paying $12 million to two
nonprofit foundations he created. The payments allegedly allowed
the insurers to avoid paying as much as $3.7 billion in fines for
improperly handling policyholder claims after the 1994 Northridge
earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the payments to the foundations were used to promote
Quackenbush's own political agenda and that none of the money went
to earthquake victims.
</P>
<P>
   The documents provided to the committee, called market conduct
exams, are sensitive audits detailing insurers' alleged
claims-handling violations following the 1994 Northridge
earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   The exams have assumed a significant role in the deepening
political scandal surrounding Quackenbush. They deal with the same
insurance companies that were allegedly convinced to contribute to
the foundations, allegedly to avoid fines.
</P>
<P>
   The documents say state regulators found that some insurance
companies had tendencies to lowball policyholder claims and delay
payments.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush had refused to give the exams to the Legislature,
even though he has the power to make them public.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Assembly committee has had possession of the
documents for months, it has not used them during the
investigation, said Rich Zeiger, a spokesman for the committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we are entitled to them as a part of our oversight
role,'' Zeiger said. ``However, we decided not to use them and no
member of the committee has seen them.''
</P>
<P>
   The former staffer who received the documents now works for a
lobbying firm in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   While the Assembly did not do anything with the documents, a
Senate committee did release the executive summaries earlier this
month. The Department of Insurance tried to get a temporary
restraining order to block further release.
</P>
<P>
   While Sacramento Superior Court Judge Joe Gray originally denied
the department's request, late Tuesday he said he was reconsidering
that ruling.
</P>
<P>
   He said he will consider making the Senate return all copies and
provide a list of who the reports have been given to. A hearing is
scheduled for next week.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush had asked the California Highway Patrol _ which has
legal jurisdiction over state property _ to investigate the leaks.
</P>
<P>
   California Highway Patrol Commissioner D.O. ``Spike'' Helmick
confirmed Thursday that the investigation had turned to one person.
He said recommendations on possible criminal action will be given
to the department within the next 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exactly to what degree charges might be involved is
questionable,'' he said. ``But I don't think she should have
released'' the documents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
