<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PLAY BALL, `DIMAGGIO CLIPPERS'  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The girls who play softball at North Beach
Playground have an identity crisis.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to order new uniforms for the two 14-and-under
softball teams, but who are they?
</P>
<P>
   The girls want to be the DiMaggio Clippers, but they might have
to settle for calling themselves the North Beach Prospectors.
</P>
<P>
   When you're a kid playing softball, you don't want to mess up
your season by getting sued by some clown in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll probably order shirts with just numbers on 'em,`` says
Dan Harrington, assistant recreation director at North Beach
Playground.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington is the guy who thought up the idea of naming the
playground after North Beach's most famous native son, Joe
DiMaggio. Joe was alive then but ailing, and Harrington figured,
``Maybe we can help keep him alive, get some positive endorphines
flowing through his bloodstream.''
</P>
<P>
   But wheels grind slowly. Joe died and S.F. supervisors voted to
put his name on the playground where he and his brothers played as
kids. Then Joe's attorney Morris Engelberg sued, likening North
Beach Playground to the city dump in terms of an honor to DiMag.
</P>
<P>
   The kids didn't understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought this was a pretty cool park,'' some of the regulars
said to Harrington.
</P>
<P>
   While the legal wrangling continues, the youngsters _ and adults
_ play on at one of the city's great cultural/economic melting
pots.
</P>
<P>
   One of the ``North Beach Playground'' signs was removed recently
_ nobody knows by whom _ so only one remains.
</P>
<P>
   Never has a controversy been so noncontroversial. Not one person
in the world has stepped up to be counted with Mr. Engelberg.
</P>
<P>
   The city should put up the DiMaggio sign and take the small risk
that it might be ruled illegal. Show some Joltin' Joe and
S.F.-style chutzpah.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe, while the city awaits justice, we could name it the
``Morris Engelberg Sucks Playground.''
</P>
<P>
   THE DEFENSE hasn't had its shot yet in the big Wonder Bread
discrimination trial here in San Francisco. But the plaintiffs put
on a powerful show.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen African American men who work at Wonder Bread's S.F.
plant or in Bay Area distributing centers are claiming systematic
discrimination and asking $260 million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Willie Wilkerson was on the stand. Attorney
Angela Alioto asked Wilkerson how it felt to be an employee for 28
years and to be passed over for promotion in favor of a person who
had been at the company six months.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkerson looked at the floor for a long moment. Then he looked
up at the ceiling. His eyes were filled with tears and he finally
said, ``No human being should be treated like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge immediately called a 10-minute recess.
</P>
<P>
   ``Willie's two minutes on the stand,'' Alioto says, ``made the
struggle, the last 21/2 years of sweat, worth every second.''
</P>
<P>
   The case is expected to go to the jury in about two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   WHY RADIO station KNBR calls talk-show co-host Ralph Barbieri
``The Razor,'' I have no idea.
</P>
<P>
   Barbieri, who teams with Tom (Mr. T) Tolbert nightly, isn't one
of those throat-slitting, cheap-shot sports-radio doofuses. He's a
sensitive guy, and now the Razor has a little shaver to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody worked harder to get a kid than old Ralph. When he passed
45, unmarried and childless, his biological clock was ticking like
Big Ben. He wanted a baby.
</P>
<P>
   When his now-ex-girlfriend became pregnant, he was thrilled.
When she had an abortion, Barbieri was beyond devastated.
</P>
<P>
   But more determined than ever. Adoption didn't work, so Barbieri
went the scientific route. It's not uncommon to try to create a
child via three-way team _ sperm donor, egg donor and surrogate
mother. But the recipient of the final product is almost never a
partnerless, heterosexual male.
</P>
<P>
   Word quickly spread around the press boxes that old Ralph had
become the Nutty Professor, trying to grow a kid in a flower pot in
his basement. But it was all legit and normal.
</P>
<P>
   And complicated. It took years, as Barbieri hand-picked a
legal-medical-maternal team as well-organized as an Everest assault
group.
</P>
<P>
   Odds against success were huge. But miracles happen, and the
miracle that happened Wednesday is named Tayte (cq)  &LR; Ali Barbieri.
</P>
<P>
   Tayte is Native American for ``windy'' or ``good talker.'' It's
in the genes.
</P>
<P>
   E-MAIL VIRUS, the great modern chess game, bad guys against good
guys, dueling technology.
</P>
<P>
   To counter the recent round of virus attacks, The Chronicle
installed new filtering software.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know how many e-mail bugs have been stopped, but the
coffee tastes better.
</P>
</TEXT>
