r k BC-MUGABE-BOGUS-BALLOT-E     06-23 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUGABE-BOGUS-BALLOT-ECONOMIST-600&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOOD 'N' BALLOTS: ZIMBABWE'S UNFAIR ELECTION  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for this weekend's election, Zimbabwe)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (NOTE: 100-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 600; TOTAL UNCUT IS 1,050
WORDS.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   HARARE _ All he does is stuff envelopes for Zimbabwe's main
opposition party, the Movement for Democratic Change (MDC). But
since the MDC represents the first serious threat in 20 years to
President Robert Mugabe's party, ZANU-PF, Deligent Marowa's humdrum
job is hazardous.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, six thugs kidnapped him at gunpoint, handcuffed him,
beat him, drove bicycle spokes up his urethra and left him for
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, he made it to a hospital. The same pistol-toting thugs
tried to abduct him from his sickbed, but fled when another patient
raised the alarm. Marowa can walk again, but he will never have
children.
</P>
<P>
   The ordeal was intended to frighten Marowa into abandoning the
MDC. It had the opposite effect. Brandishing his X-rays like a
banner of protest, he declares: ``We have to throw these criminals
out of power. And we will.''
</P>
<P>
   In a free and fair election, the ruling party would stand no
chance. Mugabe's government is violent, corrupt, incompetent and
detested. But ZANU enjoys the advantages of incumbency.
</P>
<P>
   The state-owned media applaud its unrealistic manifesto _ free
land, free houses, jobs for all, cheap food and gasoline, and so on
and so forth _ while ``uncovering'' MDC plots to bring back
colonialism and forced labor.
</P>
<P>
   ZANU receives public finance; opposition parties do not. A fifth
of the country's parliamentarians are appointed by the president.
Constituencies are gerrymandered, the electoral roll is out of
date, and a ZANU hack is in charge of the count.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite this head start, the ruling party could still lose
its majority (it currently controls 147 of the 150 seats).
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe himself does not have to run for re-election until 2002,
but a defeat for his party would weaken him considerably, and
perhaps even prompt ZANU to oust him.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid this, Mugabe is trying to terrorize the voters. He is
an old hand at this. When ZANU was a guerrilla movement, suspected
``sellouts'' had their ears and lips cut off.
</P>
<P>
   At independence in 1980, Mugabe would have won a free election,
but cheated anyway. His more violent followers prevented rivals
from campaigning in almost a third of the country, and murdered
several of them.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1980s, Mugabe's soldiers killed thousands of
dissidents in Matabeleland, and tortured many more.
</P>
<P>
   This year's campaign of intimidation has been less murderous,
but more systematic. Bands of ruffians, some of them veterans of
the liberation war, others merely pretending to be, have invaded
over 1,000 farms.
</P>
<P>
   The invaders say they are reclaiming land stolen from their
ancestors by white colonialists, but they make little effort to
cultivate it. Instead, they beat up farm workers, burn their shacks
and force them to attend ZANU rallies _ where they are whipped if
they chant the slogans with insufficient ardor.
</P>
<P>
   All this is organized and paid for by the security services,
reportedly commanded by the man behind the Matabeleland atrocities,
a cousin of Mugabe's.
</P>
<P>
   Various cruelties have been inflicted on teachers, nurses and
others who, because they can read and write, are assumed to be
opposition supporters. At least 30 people have been killed, and
many women gang-raped. Worse will follow, or so goes the warning,
if ZANU loses the election.
</P>
<P>
   Many ordinary Zimbabweans, however, refuse to be cowed. Despite
the perils, the MDC has put up candidates in every constituency.
Several of them, having been assaulted or threatened with death,
are in hiding. But still they campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In areas where it is too dangerous to stick up MDC posters by
day, they do it stealthily by night, or drop leaflets from light
aircraft. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (100-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 600) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Although the state media refuse to air their message, the
independent press continues to maul Mugabe, and nongovernmental
organizations spread the word that the ballot will be secret.
</P>
<P>
   Many farm workers, despite their welts and bruises, remain
quietly defiant. On a road between tobacco fields in rural Macheke,
the scene of several farm invasions, a freshly-beaten worker
muttered: ``The so-called veterans can't just carry us where they
want, as if we were bags.'' Another said: ``If it is time to die,
we can die.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,050) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere at ZANU rallies is joyless. Despite generous
handouts of beer and T-shirts to those who show up, few do. Rows of
shiny portapotties stay fresh and unused. Sparse crowds clap
listlessly.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, MDC rallies throb with enthusiasm. Throngs of
people wave red cards to signal, in a footballing analogy, that it
is time Mugabe was sent off.
</P>
<P>
   Speakers at ZANU rallies, especially Mugabe himself, blather on
about the party's heroic deeds during the liberation struggle, but
gloss over the two decades in which ZANU has been in charge of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Some bigwigs are so out of touch that they are genuinely baffled
by their unpopularity. Vice President Simon Muzenda has told
disgruntled party members that they should vote for the candidates
ZANU chooses, even if ZANU were to choose a baboon.
</P>
<P>
   Who will win? It is impossible to predict. Pessimists fear that
pluck and popularity will not be enough to defeat a cunning old
despot who is determined to use all the machinery of the state to
preserve his power.
</P>
<P>
   Optimists counter that Mugabe cheated during a referendum in
February, and still lost. This showed Zimbabweans that change was
possible, giving heart to the opposition. But it also jolted ZANU
out of its complacency.
</P>
<P>
   The party is cheating much more energetically now than before
the referendum. A recent opinion poll suggested that the MDC would
win 70 seats. This would give it a majority of the seats contested
but not, because of the 30 MPs Mugabe can appoint, a majority in
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Conducted in an atmosphere of intimidation, the poll probably
underestimated opposition support.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the election result will depend on the answers to
two questions. First, will the presence of the international
observers, invited by Mugabe to maintain the illusion of fairness,
prevent excessive ballot-stuffing? They will be fairly sparse on
the ground; a large number of other would-be monitors have been
banned.
</P>
<P>
   Second, has Mugabe's thuggery so frightened people that they
will be afraid to vote his party out of office? Or has it so
enraged them that they will risk its retribution? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
