<SLUG> BC-SKYTEAM-AIR-ALLIANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR AIRLINES FORM AN INTERNATIONAL ALLIANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By KRUTI TRIVEDI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines, Air France, Aeromexico and Korean Air announced
an alliance on Thursday that will stretch across three continents
and attempt to compete with pacts already formed by rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines will share perks, pool frequent flyer miles
programs and coordinate schedules in the alliance, called
``Skyteam.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts who follow Delta, the No. 3 U.S. airline, said
its participation is primarily a marketing strategy aimed at
helping Delta catch up to its larger domestic rivals, United
Airlines and American Airlines, which have established global
partners. The alliance should also help Air France compete with
Germany's Lufthansa, a United partner, and British Airways, an
American partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a defensive position,'' said Kevin Murphy, an analyst at
Morgan Stanley. ``They're banding together to preserve market
share.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the strongest group of carriers is the Star Alliance,
which includes United, Lufthansa and Singapore Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   For passengers, the advantage of flying an airline that
participates in an alliance is the convenience. Passengers need to
book only one ticket and check in baggage once, regardless how
manytimes they change carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize that Star Alliance is the best-functioning
alliance today,'' Leo F. Mullin, Delta's chief executive officer
told reporters in New York. ``We believe that we are going to start
close to second place day one.''
</P>
<P>
   Other airline alliances said they saw little significant threat.
Chris Chiames, a spokesman for American, said ``we're pleased to
finally welcome this grouping of airlines to the world of
alliances.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Star Alliance, Skyteam will offer frequent flyer perks
like priority check-in and luxury lounges. Passengers with more
than 100,000 miles will be guaranteed an economy class seat.
</P>
<P>
   Although Skyteam is entering the game at a later stage than its
major competitors, analysts said it should be able to compete
effectively with United's Star Alliance, American's One World, and
Continental's Wings Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They start out behind the other three major alliances which
have been in operation for a while,'' said Philip Baggaley, a
managing director at the Standard and Poor's Corp. ``However, both
Delta and Air France are strong across the Atlantic. At least it
has gotten Delta and Air France more firmly into the alliance
game.''
</P>
<P>
   But Skyteam could face problems in Asia, where it does not have
a strong hub. Neither Delta nor Air France has booked passengers on
Korean Air since April 1999, when safety issues led both airlines
to suspend dealing with the Asian carrier. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
