<SLUG> BC-HENSLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEER MAGNATE JIM HENSLEY DIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN STANLEY  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Hensley, head of one of the nation's largest beer
distributorships and father-in-law of U.S. Sen. John McCain, died
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Hensley, 80, was founder and chairman of Hensley &AMP; Co.,
Anheuser-Busch's largest franchise. Based in west Phoenix, the
business employs more than 500 people and does about $220 million
in annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Delgado, company president, praised Hensley's high standards
and sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Hensley and his brother, Eugene, founded United Liquor Co. in
Phoenix before World War II. After a stint in the Army Air Corps,
Hensley founded his namesake company in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   The soft-spoken Hensley, a resident of Phoenix, shunned the
spotlight but was well known to generations of Arizona politicians
and innumerable charities. Through the Hensley Family Foundation,
he gave to many charities and supported groups ranging from NASCAR
to Gilbert Rodeo Days.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1982, the company has contributed $80,000 to McCain's
campaigns. McCain's wife, Cindy, is a vice president of the company
but is not involved in daily operations.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral arrangements for Hensley, who died after a long illness,
are pending. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 0140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
