<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINO-BIRD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FOSSIL FIND REVIVES DEBATE OVER BIRD EVOLUTION  &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fossil of a controversial birdlike reptile that existed some
220 million years ago has convinced a team of scientists that the
creature had feathers, glided from trees and may have led to the
evolution of modern birds.
</P>
<P>
   The concept has revived a fierce debate among researchers who
hold that the fossil had scales, not feathers, and that it was the
dinosaurs of antiquity that were the true ancestors of the entire
bird family.
</P>
<P>
   Fossil hunters from the Universities of North Carolina and
Oregon, as well as other research centers in the United States and
Russia, report their findings Friday in the journal Science. They
claim that an examination of the fossil of a small reptilian
creature discovered in Central Asia more than 20 years ago carries
 &LR; reveals the imprint of the oldest feathers ever found, with hollow
shafts on both sides of its body almost identical to the shafts on
modern birds' feathers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any question any longer that this thing
was ancestral to flying birds,'' said Alan Feduccia of the
University of North Carolina. ``We know that the feathers evolved
from the scales of reptiles, and while this creature that we
studied could not have been able to fly, it most probably was a
glider.''
</P>
<P>
   The environment of that ancient period, known as the Triassic,
must have supported vast forests dominating the landscape, Feduccia
and his colleagues argue. It would be logical to theorize, they
say, that winged creatures living in those trees would learn to
glide from tree to tree _ much as some large modern reptiles with
outspread scaly webs between their feet do.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are some amazing fossils, and at the very least, they
prove that feathers did not evolve in dinosaurs,'' said John Ruben,
a paleontologist at Oregon State University. ``The supposed link
between dinosaurs and birds is pretty entrenched in paleontology,
but it's not as solid as the public has been led to believe.''
</P>
<P>
   The fossil reptile has been named Longisquama insignis, and its
supporters argue that its feathers _ and thus true flight _ must
have evolved long before any small swift-running dinosaurs could
have developed feathers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here you've got an animal that isn't a bird, and it isn't a
dinosaur, and yet it has feathers,'' said Nicholas R. Geist, a
fossil researcher at Sonoma State University and co-author of the
Science report.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is going to be a major monkey wrench in the theory about
the dinosaurean origin of birds,'' he said. ``It is going to cause
some people to take a real good second look at their data.''
</P>
<P>
   But other scientists are not impressed by the evidence. They
maintain that the condition of the Longisquama fossil is too poor,
and the remains too fragmentary, to constitute convincing proof.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Padian, a noted paleontologist at the University of
California in Berkeley, scoffed at the idea that the fossil reptile
was a feathered creature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those imprints look as much like feathers as a duck-billed
platypus looks like the beak of a duck,'' he said. ``And there's
absolutely no evidence that the creature's feather-like scales
could be used in flight.''
</P>
<P>
   Luis Chiappe of the Natural History Museum of Los Angeles and
another noted dinosaur fossil researcher who saw the report, agreed
with Padian.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interpretation that these scales are feathers is extremely
unconvincing,'' Chiappe said. ``They may look like the feathered
leaves of a fern, but they certainly do not look like true feathers
at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be a fantastic creature with weird long scales on its
body, but I am not convinced it is feathered. And there certainly
is strong evidence from many dinosaur fossils that there were
indeed feathered dinosaurs.''
</P>
<P>
   The first dinosaur fossils were discovered in Europe more than
100 years ago, and now they have been found on virtually every
continent. A century ago, scientists argued about the fossils, and
for the past 10 years, the argument over dinosaurs and birds has
been shrill and persistent.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of paleontologists, however, now argue that
feathered dinosaurs racing across the land at least 150 million
years ago were the creatures that first evolved the ability for
true flight, the animal ancestors of modern birds.
</P>
<P>
   To scientists like Padian and Chiappe, today's birds are in fact
modern dinosaurs _ most probably descendants of animals like the
meat-eating, flying dinosaur called Archaeopteryx that lived 150
million years ago and whose fossil remains have been known of for
nearly 150 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
