<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON IN TOWN
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JON KAMMAN  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton, whose Phoenix fund-raising visit was
sponsored in part by a Republican, returned the bipartisan favor
Thursday by hailing cross-party cooperation to improve Arizona
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thrilled when I found out that your Republican governor
and . . . all the Democratic legislators were pushing an education
initiative to lower class size, raise teacher pay and improve the
quality of education,'' he told a $5,000-a-plate luncheon audience
of 70 at the Ritz-Carlton hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The luncheon was hosted by sports mogul Jerry Colangelo, a GOP
stalwart.
</P>
<P>
   Scottsdale Democrat Fred DuVal, who introduced Clinton, said
Colangelo's gesture ``proves that he places civic leadership above
partisanship.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with a $500-a-person reception attended by more than 300,
Clinton's visit raised $570,000 for the Democratic National
Committee, a state party record, DuVal said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Clinton's remarks rallied support for Al Gore, whom he
called ``by far the most significant vice president in the history
of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Before departing for San Diego, Clinton spent more than an hour
touring the Heard Museum's collection of Native American art and
artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   Casual visitors were surprised to encounter the president in the
galleries.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton asked a family of four from Baltimore, ``Having fun?''
and quickly added, ``It's a great city.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
