A2432 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-BALL-MUDVILLE-LADN     06-23 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALL-MUDVILLE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINOR BASEBALL TEAM EYES WEST COAST COUNTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID GREENBERG 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VENTURA, Calif. _ A group that includes the son of former Los
Angeles Dodgers owner Peter O'Malley has unveiled plans to bring a
minor-league baseball team to Ventura County and build an early
20th century-style ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Top of the Third Inc. purchased the Stockton Ports in May 1998
and renamed them the Mudville Nine in hopes of building a $15
million to $20 million stadium for its planned move within a couple
years. Supporters did not reveal plans for any public financing
they might seek or say specifically where the ballpark complex
might be located.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ventura County is a great market for a minor-league baseball
team,'' Tom Seidler, president of the team, a Single-A affiliate of
the Milwaukee Brewers, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a vibrant community with a healthy economy. There are a
lot of families here, and there is no professional or major college
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, it's wholesome family entertainment at
affordable prices at a time when major league (tickets) are getting
more expensive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mudville Nine is a part of the California League, an
advanced Single-A professional league. Ballplayers who advance to
this level generally have two to four years of professional
experience, and a typical team features a couple of future major
leaguers on its roster.
</P>
<P>
   Current Dodger Gary Sheffield and Oakland Athletic John Jaha, as
well as former California Angel Don Baylor are among the alumni of
the team that won nine championships in the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Lancaster JetHawks, the Seattle Mariners' Single-A
franchise, have sent a half-dozen prospects to the big leagues
since arriving in the Antelope Valley in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura County previously played host to the Pacific Suns, an
independent league team that played one season in Oxnard. Burdened
with high payroll costs and spotty attendance, the team went
bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   But Mudville Nine officials -- including Kevin O'Malley, the
team's vice president and general manager -- say they expect no
such problems if the franchise moves to Ventura County. They
envision building a two-deck, 4,000- to 5,000-seat ballpark --
possibly surrounded by themed early 20th-century retail shops,
restaurants and offices.
</P>
<P>
   Franchise officials originally planned to build the early
20th-century stadium in Stockton, replacing the 2,800-seat Billy
Hebert Field. Built in 1927, it is now the oldest minor-league
field west of the Mississippi River.
</P>
<P>
   But two years of government red tape and poor fan support forced
management to look elsewhere, posing the possibility that the
51-year-old California League would lose one of its original host
cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody doubts that Billy Hebert Field is not a long-term
viable field for professional baseball,'' Seidler said. ``It has
all the problems that a 73-year-old stadium would have. We are
exclusively looking at Ventura County.''
</P>
<P>
   The move first must be approved by the 10-team California
League, however, and its president, Joe Gagliardi, said Thursday's
announcement was premature.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, they haven't moved, and this league hasn't
authorized them to move,'' he said. ``They aren't going anyplace
right now, because there they don't have a site down there. That's
all that they're doing ... investigating.''
</P>
<P>
   But Seidler said he believes the California League wants a team
in Ventura County and that the mve will be approved once a site
for the stadium is secured.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a story waiting for a home. We're trying to bring
`Casey at Bat' to Ventura County,'' said Seidler, referring to the
legendary poem the Stockton team was named after.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got everything the other minor-league ballparks have. And
then, above and beyond, it appeals to the imagination and offers a
more immersing experience. There's definitely some romance and
nostalgia that appeals to people.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will probably capture that,'' he said. ``It will be the
kind of place that people will want to visit.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
