<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 01:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2433 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-BUDGET-CALIFORNIA-SFC     06-23 1373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ASSEMBLY SENDS $94 BILLION BUDGET TO GOV. DAVIS  &HT;     By GREG LUCAS and LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Assembly Republicans cast the votes needed Thursday
to send a $95 billion budget to Gov. Gray Davis after Democrats
embraced a big cut in the license fees Californians pay on their
cars.
</P>
<P>
   The reduction in the fees _ vehicle owners will pay about 30
percent less next year _ broke a weeklong stalemate in the Assembly
over how large a tax cut the budget should include.
</P>
<P>
   ``The investments we make in this budget are critical. I think
they're the ones our voters asked us for,'' said Assemblywoman
Denise Ducheny, D-San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The massive plan, beefed up by a cash surplus of $12.3 billion,
dictates state spending for the fiscal year beginning July 1. It
now goes to Davis, who has the power to cross out individual
spending items.
</P>
<P>
   As the Assembly began debating the budget Thursday, the
Democratic governor said he would veto the license fee cut that
cemented the deal unless lawmakers added $100 million in tax
credits benefiting high-tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also said the fee cut, which would drain nearly $3.6
billion from state coffers, also could accidentally trigger a $1.1
billion loss of sales tax money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these defects are cured, I will sign the bill,'' Davis
said. ``If not, I will veto it.''
</P>
<P>
   He got at least part of what he wanted when the Assembly
approved the $100 million in tax cuts and pledged to eliminate the
threat of a sales tax loss. The Senate still must approve this cut.
</P>
<P>
   The overall spending plan, approved a week ago by the Senate,
won the same bipartisan support from the 80-member Assembly on a
vote of 61 to 17.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-six Democrats voted ``aye,'' as did 14 Republicans and one
independent.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans still weren't happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``These fiscal priorities represent a Democratic majority that
increases government spending by 20 percent,'' said Assemblyman
Tony Strickland, R-Moorpark.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly's bipartisanship came only after a compromise was
reached on tax cuts. Davis said the license fee deal, which
provides hefty breaks to the millions of owners of cars, trucks,
motorcycles and trailers, was broader than the two tax breaks it
replaces _ a sales tax rebate and a modest drop in state income tax
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, the owner of a $20,000 car would see his annual
license fee _ calculated at 2 percent of a vehicle's value _ halved
from $260 to $130 beginning next year.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, lawmakers echoed the spending priorities set by Davis
when he outlined his budget plan in January: education,
transportation and tax cuts. But other parts of state government
also benefit from California's record surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some good stuff in there for mental health,
developmental disabilities, child care and seniors,'' said Senate
President John Burton, D-San Francisco, one of the architects of
the compromise budget.
</P>
<P>
   University of California funding rises 18.5 percent over last
year. Money for the California State University system climbs by 13
percent, and community college funding will increase more than 21
percent.
</P>
<P>
   There also is $575 million earmarked to make housing _ for
ownership and rental _ more affordable for lower-income
Californians.
</P>
<P>
   Another $140 million will expand local juvenile crime prevention
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Reimbursement rates for doctors and hospitals that provide care
for the poor under Medi-Cal will increase as an inducement to
provide more service.
</P>
<P>
   And $5.8 billion in bond money _ much of it from park and water
measures approved by voters in March _ will be spent on land
purchases, habitat restoration and various water projects.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest losers in the budget were cities and counties that
saw more than $2 billion in property tax revenue stripped away by
the state during the recession of the early 1990s to allow
lawmakers to balance the state's books.
</P>
<P>
   Although cities and counties saw some increases in money for
crime prevention and law enforcement this year, they only received
$200 million in new money to spend as they wish _ a fraction of the
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at some of the big-ticket spending items.
</P>
<P>
   -- Public schools get $30.6 billion, including $1.8 billion of
discretionary spending, including pay increases for teachers or
other staff.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative budget writers estimate per-pupil spending will rise
by 11 percent over last year to $6,716 _ an additional $691 per
student.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers spent more than Davis suggested on child care, summer
school and after-school programs.
</P>
<P>
   -- The spending plan also includes incentives for people to
teach.
</P>
<P>
   There's a tax credit against 50 percent of the money teachers
earn from pay increases based on years of experience. A teacher
with four or five years experience would get a credit of $250. A
teacher with 20 or more years experience would receive $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Current and new teachers also will receive an extra retirement
bonus. Teachers pay 8 percent of their salary into retirement. The
state will now contribute an additional 2 percent for each teacher.
</P>
<P>
   -- Despite misgivings over its workability, lawmakers largely
approved the governor's transportation plan.
</P>
<P>
   That plan, which some GOP and Democratic lawmakers oppose as a
glorified pork barrel reward, is a series of transit and highway
projects picked by Davis.
</P>
<P>
   He proposes spending $5.3 billion in seed money over the next
five years _ $2 billion in the coming budget year _ to begin
construction on the projects, although that construction won't
occur without another $10 billion in state and local revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The budget takes half of the sales tax paid on gasoline _
roughly $500 million _ and earmarks it for transportation projects
other than those picked by Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk is split between state highways and local streets, with
some for projects of regional benefit.
</P>
<P>
   -- Davis got roughly $500 million more than the $2.7 billion in
tax cuts he sought, although the cuts bear no resemblance to what
he proposed.
</P>
<P>
   The governor wanted to give single taxpayers a $150 one-time
rebate, double for married couples. Lawmakers rejected that in
favor of a sales tax rebate, which they said would benefit more
Californians. But the sales tax rebate was axed Thursday in favor
of the license fee cut.
</P>
<P>
   For the past week, the Assembly wrangled over the effect of new
tax cuts in the budget on a scheduled 10 percent reduction in the
license fees in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said the new tax cuts should be counted against the
license fee increase. Republicans said they should not.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate ended the impasse by substituting the sales tax
rebate and a small cut in personal income tax rates sought by Davis
with a 32.5 percent cut in license fees beginning next year.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the state's vehicle owners are paying 35 percent less
in annual license fees than they were two years ago. In 1998,
lawmakers approved a five-year plan to lower license fees 67.5
percent by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's compromise accelerates that timetable. Next year,
vehicle owners will pay about two-thirds less than they did two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the rebate will come in a check, part will already be
calculated into the license fee bill sent by the Department of
Motor Vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the owner of a $20,000 car two years ago would pay
$400 in license fees or 2 percent of the car's value. Under the
cuts that have already been phased in, the fees have dropped to
$260. The new cut would drop the fee to $130, according to the
Department of Motor Vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Another tax break in the budget would increase the state's child
care credit up to $432 for state residents earning $10,000 or less
a year.
</P>
<P>
   For Californians earning between $30,000 and $100,000, the
credit ranges from $288 to $192, falling as income increases.
</P>
<P>
   There is also one-time aid for low-income seniors who are
renters and homeowners. The state will up the subsidy it pays for
rent and property taxes _ but only for one year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is as good as any budget and certainly no worse than
any,'' said Sen. Steve Peace, D-El Cajon, chair of the Senate
Budget Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
