<SLUG> BC-PARKS-THEME-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMUSEMENT PARK PRICES HIT RECORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON Z. COHEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- A day at Magic Mountain costs a family of four an
average of $181.50, making it one of the nation's most expensive
amusement parks, according to a recent survey.
</P>
<P>
   But Six Flags California officials point out that discount
tickets make the actual cost much less for many park visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 25 U.S. theme parks, conducted by Amusement
Business magazine, calculated the cost for regular admission for
two adults and two children, parking, two hot dogs, two hamburgers,
four orders of fries, four soft drinks and two T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   The average price nationally for a family of four was $151.44, a
record high.
</P>
<P>
   Bakersfield resident Charles Rose, visiting Magic Mountain with
his three children, said he isn't bothered by the cost of going to
an amusement park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get discount tickets, and it's a pretty good discount,''
Rose said. ``We're not going to overindulge them.''
</P>
<P>
   Many customers take advantage of discount ticket offers, said
Six Flags publicist Amy Means. The park offers discounts through
employers, restaurants, grocery stores and soft drink bottlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our promotional offers do very well in the marketplace,''
Means said. The park does not release figures regarding the
percentage of admissions using discounts.
</P>
<P>
   The regular price of admission at Magic Mountain increased from
$36 to $40 in the past year, making it one of the more expensive
parks to enter.
</P>
<P>
   The costliest admission, however, belongs to Busch Gardens in
Tampa, Fla., and Universal Studios Florida in Orlando. Both parks
cost $46 for an adult admission.
</P>
<P>
   Universal Studios Hollywood is not one of the 25 parks included
in the survey. Its regular adult admission price is $41.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim's Disneyland, the other Southern California park in the
survey, charges an adult admission of $41.
</P>
<P>
   The least expensive admission was Nellie Bly Park in Brooklyn,
N.Y., which charges no admission, but gets $9.50 for a three-hour
ride pass.
</P>
<P>
   Universal Studios Florida also was the most expensive park
overall, with a cost of $227.50 for a family of four. Least costly
overall was Nellie Bly Park, with its free parking and $2 hot dogs.
The park also sells T-shirts for $4 and french fries for $1.
</P>
<P>
   Although Magic Mountain is slightly more expensive, it's well
within Monica Bodell's budget. With four children in tow, Bodell of
Manhattan Beach said she would spend $225.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm delightfully pleased that I spent less,'' she said. ``I
budgeted between $300 and $350.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
