r s BC-OLY-WRESTLING-FREESTY     06-23 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WRESTLING-FREESTYLE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRESTLER AKIN ATONES FOR '96 LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEIDI PEDERSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Lou Rosselli had already prevented Eric Akin from
achieving one Olympic dream. Akin had spent the past four years
making sure Rosselli wouldn't keep him from another.
</P>
<P>
   Rosselli, then the national champion, had defeated Akin in the
heartbreakingly close 114.5-pound final at the 1996 Olympic
wrestling trials. Akin returned the favor last night at Reunion
Arena by beating Rosselli in the 119-pound challenge tournament at
the 2000 U.S. Olympic freestyle trials to stay alive in the quest
for Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have to say that Lou Rosselli still owns me. I've gotten
better because I've been training for him for the last four
years,'' said Akin, who was a four-time NCAA All-American for Iowa
State. ``He's the most dangerous athlete in my weight class.''
</P>
<P>
   After overtime in their semifinals match ended 1-1, Akin beat
Rosselli on a referee's decision. Akin, who finished second at
nationals this year to Sam Henson, advanced to the challenge
tournament finals against Stephen Abas. Rosselli drops to the
consolation bracket.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of each weight class in the challenge tournament will
face that weight class's respective national champion in the trials
finals tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Another runner-up from the 1996 trials, two-time world champion
Terry Brands, dominated his two bouts at 127.75 pounds. He beat
Army's Jeff Bedard, 10-0, for a technical fall in his first match
since he won the 1999 World Trials, then defeated Sunkist Kids'
Yero Washington, 8-0.
</P>
<P>
   Brands, the 1999 national champion, had retired because of
injury shortly before the 1999 World Championships. He petitioned
into the trials. He'll face Eric Guerrero in the challenge finals.
Guerrero beat Danny Felix, who defeated Guerrero at nationals, and
Tony Purler.
</P>
<P>
   Akin wasn't the only former Iowa State standout to produce
excitement yesterday. Former Cyclones wrestler Mike Van Arsdale
defeated ISU junior Cael Sanderson, 7-3, in the 187.25-pound
semifinals. Van Arsdale, 35, won the 1988 NCAA title, while
Sanderson, 21, is undefeated in college and already a two-time NCAA
champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's tough as hell,'' Van Arsdale said. ``I'm just older and
stronger than him. I opened up and let myself go. ''
</P>
<P>
   Van Arsdale will face 1997 NCAA champion Lee Fullhart in that
challenge final.
</P>
<P>
   California native Stephen Neal, the 1999 world champion in the
super-heavyweight class, will wrestle Tolly Thompson in that
division's challenge final. Neal, who had shoulder surgery after
last year's Worlds and lost at this year's U.S. Nationals to Kerry
McCoy, said he is again in winning shape. He defeated Airron
Richardson, 8-0, in the semifinals, while Thompson defeated Tom
Erickson, 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for the tech and didn't get it. You win by eight
and that's good enough, I guess,'' Neal said. ``But I need to be
attacking more and not standing around. That's why I'm glad I have
this mini-tournament, to work on things.''
</P>
<P>
   With the depth of the U.S. freestyle ranks, wrestlers had to be
at their best even when facing lower seeds. Hawkeyes' Mike Mena,
seeded fourth, fell to 10th-seed Sheldon Thomas, 5-2, in the
quarterfinals. Thomas was a 1996 NCAA champion for Clarion (Pa.)
University.
</P>
<P>
   Mena said it would be difficult to put his heart into the
consolation rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected more of myself, more than anything. I just felt
slower than normal,'' Mena said. ``This really should be single
elimination. If you're out of the Olympic team, what are you still
wrestling for?''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
