<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS OWNER MAKING PITCH FOR MUTOMBO TRADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Dikembe Mutombo a member of the Mavericks?
</P>
<P>
   That's what Mavericks owner Mark Cuban is hoping will happen.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban said he has contacted Atlanta about the possibility of
acquiring the Hawks' 7-foot-2 All-Star center for Shawn Bradley,
Robert Pack and John ``Hot Rod'' Williams. But Cuban doesn't know
whether the Hawks plan to unload Mutombo and build for the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been hitting Atlanta hard trying to push them \Rfor
Mutombo\S,'' Cuban said. ``They aren't sure if they are going to go
young, and for cap space, which would let them make the deal, or
build around Mutombo.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding Mutombo would solve most of the Mavericks' problems,
because he is the one inside defensive presence, rebounder and
intimidator the franchise has always lacked. Mutombo, who turns 34
on Sunday, is a six-time All-Star who won NBA Defensive Player of
the Year honors in 1995, '97 and '98. He is widely respected for
his shot-blocking skills, which will enable the Mavericks' guards
and forwards to take chances filling the defensive lanes.
</P>
<P>
   Mutombo, expected to earn $13 million next season, is in the
final year of his contract. Bradley, Pack and Williams are also in
the final year of their contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks have a new coach in Lon Kruger Whether that means
trading Mutombo to the Mavericks, Cuban can only wait and see.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of now, they don't want to trade him,'' Cuban said. ``Other
deals are contingent on other teams getting deals done, so
nothing's close right now.'' \Nsubheds:Nuggets dispute report Kim
Hughes, the Denver Nuggets' player personnel director and assistant
coach, took exception to a published report that the Mavericks have
offered guard Robert Pack, forward John ``Hot Rod'' Williams and
center Sean Rooks to Denver for forwards Chris Gatling and Popeye
Jones and a second-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they like Popeye, because nine months ago they asked me
about Popeye and we didn't want to give him up, because he is such
a good solid guy,'' Hughes said yesterday. ``But they haven't
talked to us about Gatling, so I don't know where that's coming
from.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said the Nuggets do not plan to trade either of their two
second-round picks. He also said the Nuggets have talked to every
team in the league, but to four about a possible trade. He said he
already has 10 deals on the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who gave out that information \Rabout a
Nuggets-Mavericks trade\S, whether it's an agent a fan or \RMark\S
Cuban,'' Hughes said. ``But it seems amusing to me that if in fact
Dallas is talking about this, which I don't know, then they're
talking about a trade before the Denver Nuggets know about it
\Rhappening\S.''
</P>
<P>
   Gatling, who has a home in North Dallas, was not amused when his
name popped up as trade bait, but he looked at it philosophically.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the trade were made, ``I'll be in a better situation,
because I can turn the key because my house is there. It's not an
inconvenience at all. My cars are there. Everything is there. That
is where I live. It'll be like going home.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said the Nuggets have no intentions of trading Gatling.
Gatling, who is in the final year of his contract and is seeking an
extension, said this may work to his advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that \Rthe media\S knows about it and all the other teams
know about it, it just opens up \Rthings\S,'' Gatling said. ``So,
they're saying, `Wow, they want to trade Gatling. We want to get in
on that deal. We can use him.'
</P>
<P>
   ``You might get LA \RLakers\S calling, Portland calling.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
