<SLUG> BC-LITTON-CEO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTON PICKS ITS NEW CEO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Litton Industries Inc., the nation's largest
builder of non-nuclear ships for the U.S. Navy, has named former
TRW Inc. executive Ronald D. Sugar as successor to Chief Executive
Officer Michael Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar, 51, was named president and chief operating officer of
Litton and will succeed Brown as chief executive officer by Dec.
31, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to become a contributing member of the management team
and think about how we want to take the company forward over the
next few years,'' Sugar said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, 59, will retain the chairman's title. He succeeded former
chief executive officer John Leonis in 1998 and became chairman
when Leonis reached the company's mandatory retirement age of 65 in
1999, said Randy Belote, a spokesman with Litton in Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar, the former head of TRW's Cleveland-based aerospace and
information systems unit, will also be nominated for election to
the company's board of directors at the Litton annual shareholders
meeting in December.
</P>
<P>
   As president and chief operating officer, Sugar said his first
priority will be to learn how the giant defense and electronics
company operates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take some time but I'm a quick learner,'' Sugar
said. ``I will spend the time getting to know the customers and
products.''
</P>
<P>
   Before joining TRW, Sugar held positions at The Aerospace Corp.,
Hughes Aircraft Co. and Argosystems Inc. He was recently appointed
by President Bill Clinton to the National Security
Telecommunications Advisory Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was with TRW for nearly 20 years,'' he said. ``That really
allowed me to see all the different dimensions of a large business.
It's the kind of background that will serve me well as the
president of Litton.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Belote said the company's Agoura Hills-based Data
Systems division had been awarded a $17 million contract from the
U.S. Navy for continued production of 10 AN/UPX 24(V) Interrogator
Sets.
</P>
<P>
   Deliveries for the 30-month contract will begin in September
2001, he said. The contract also includes retrofit kits for field
change installation on systems now operational on guided missile
cruisers and destroyers.
</P>
<P>
   The system provides target data to a ship's command, control,
communications, computer and intelligence systems through a digital
interface, and generates antenna and interrogation commands in
response to system requests for priority target identification.
</P>
<P>
   Based in Woodland Hills, Litton has more than 40,000 employees
and $5 billion in annual revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Litton closed down $1.44 Thursday at $43.63 on volume
of 229,300 shares on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
