<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELCHER TURNS IN ANOTHER GOOD EFFORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Tim Belcher allowed only three hits through
six-plus innings to lead the Anaheim Angels to a 4-3 victory over
the Kansas City Royals Thursday night before 17,805 at Edison
Field.
</P>
<P>
   In his two starts since returning from elbow surgery, Belcher is
2-0 with a 3.18 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   He got plenty of help Thursday, particularly from reliever Mark
Petkovsek, who threw three perfect innings of relief. Petkovsek
retired all nine batters he faced without allowing a ball hit out
of the infield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like either start was all that dominating,''
Belcher said. ``I didn't go as deep into the game as I'd like to
go, but for my first two starts, I'll take it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels offense scored just enough, led by Bengie Molina's
two-run homer, an RBI single by Orlando Palmeiro and a three hits
by Darin Erstad.
</P>
<P>
   It was Belcher's first career victory over the Royals, after
going into the game 0-7 against them in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher retired the first two batters of the game before giving
up a two-out walk to Carlos Beltran. And it cost him because
Jermaine Dye followed with a 410-foot home run to center and a 2-0
Royals lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels tied it in the second inning on Molina's two-run
homer, his fifth of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels then took the lead in the third after Erstad led off
with a single to left. And when left fielder Johnny Damon let the
ball skip past him, Erstad raced all the way to third. Orlando
Palmeiro followed with an RBI single, and Mo Vaughn hit a
ground-rule double to right, sending Palmeiro to third.
</P>
<P>
   One out later, Garret Anderson drove him Palmeiro with a
groundout, giving the Angels a 4-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Belcher changed speeds, mixed his pitches and
got a tough Royals hitters _ they rank third in the A.L. in hitting
_ to get themselves out. Belcher walked a batter in the third. He
hit a batter and walked a batter in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't allow another hit until Joe Randa led off the
seventh with a single. And when Mark Quinn followed with a double
to center, driving Randa to third, Belcher was done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't seen him in eight or nine years (before this
season),'' Angels manager Mike Scioscia said of Belcher, his
teammate for four seasons with the Dodgers (1988-91). ``What he has
lost in stuff, he's made up for with a mental approach. With any
support from the lineup and the defense, he'll surprise some people
with the number of wins he puts up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 0205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0067 </DOCNO>
