<HEADLINE>
...CORRECTS OHLMEYER SPELLING 
MILLER WILL LEAVE THEM RANTING FOR MORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dennis Miller's sports resume . . .
</P>
<P>
   Lemme see, it's gotta be around here somewhere . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Master of ceremonies for ESPN's first ``ESPY'' awards show.
Made several cracks about Jimmy Johnson's hair that even the coach
laughed at.
</P>
<P>
   __ A member of ``Saturday Night Live'' when Wayne Gretzky
hosted.
</P>
<P>
   __ Sometimes wears a Pittsburgh Pirates hat when showing up to
work on his HBO show.
</P>
<P>
   __ Also hired Chet Forte, the former ``Monday Night Football''
director, to cut his show for a while. Didn't really work out that
well.
</P>
<P>
   All right? Is that enough for ya, babe?
</P>
<P>
   Any more hoops you wanna make the Mr. Bobble-head shimmy through
just to satisfy your insatiable urge to fill predetermined comic
quotas?
</P>
<P>
   Why not order just one more cavity search, just so you can feel
better about yourself while at the same time underscore your
power-hungry need to filter all the riff-raff out of the process of
putting on the most successful prime-time sports show in the
history of the idiot box?
</P>
<P>
   I don't want to get off on a rant here, but Don Ohlhmeyer's game
plan for deciding on Miller as Al Michaels' new bobo for ``Monday
Night Football'' wasn't like deciphering the Rosetta stone.
</P>
<P>
   It's the infotainment factor of the TV age we live in, cha cha.
</P>
<P>
   Football knowledge on a weekly telecast is great, but if you can
find a way to drop in a Nietzsche reference in the same breath at
Ray Nitschke, you've found a nice niche, you knucklehead.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Miller fits _ he doesn't fit the traditional role,
that monotonous rhythm that develops between the play-by-play man
and his analyst that you can set an egg timer to.
</P>
<P>
   When Ohlhmeyer first thought of adding Miller to the ``MNF''
telecast, it was more as an infrequent contributor, he admitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, you were gonna pigeon me in that Jimmy Kimmel role _
thanks,'' Miller cracked during a conference call with reporters
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Turned out, Miller knew enough to host his own sports-talk show,
which is something anyone in these parts already knew based on the
frequent appearances he'd make with Forte and Steve Hartman when
they co-hosted the ``Loose Cannons'' show for XTRA-AM (690) several
years ago before Forte's death.
</P>
<P>
   Turned out, Miller was available. His HBO show runs from January
to August. His Monday nights in the fall are open, unless he's
pimping for another long-distance carrier or bag of candy-coated
chocolates.
</P>
<P>
   Turned out, Rush Limbaugh and Jim Rome had too many other
commitments.
</P>
<P>
   So while Dan Fouts will be there to provide the other bearded
opinion in the booth, Miller's stand-up act will have a new
platform, despite what he says about probably reining in the
obscure references for the general masses.
</P>
<P>
   At least it should be interesting. That's all any viewer can ask
for in a prime-time dumping ground of Ted Danson comebacks.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Miller's act won't work with middle America and he's
become almost a parody of his former sharp-tongued self, let
everyone else go to the sports bar to watch ``MNF'' if they can't
listen to him.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: It'll work. It's fresh.
</P>
<P>
   But then again, Ohlhmeyer could be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   __ How 'bout ``The Big Scab'': Striking members of the Screen
Actors Guild (SAG) and the American Federation of Television and
Radio Artists (AFTRA) have for the last two months been pretty loud
about feeling they've been treated unfairly by the advertising
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Shaquille O'Neal missed a few meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The two unions continue to fire off some serious threats at
O'Neal for his stooping to do the trite ``I'm going to Disneyland''
plug at the end of Game 6 at the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's agent, Leonard Armato, manages to keep a straight face
when he contends that the spots are practically public-service
announcements since Shaq is donating the proceeds to his charity
for disadvantaged kids.
</P>
<P>
   SAG officials say the media-savvy Shaq, who should know better
considering his movie career, could be fined, suspended or expelled
for this selfish indiscretion. But somehow, you know he'll get
around this, just as other athletes such as Marion Jones, Keyshawn
Johnson, Eddie George and Michael Johnson have done.
</P>
<P>
   Their agents and the companies paying them defend the
appearances by saying they're not taking jobs away from actors and
are contractually bound to shoot the spots.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods and Nomar Garciaparra, on the other hand, recently
declined doing commercials because of the strike.
</P>
<P>
   __ Tribal matters: Fox Sports Net's ``11 p.m. Regional Sports
Report'' dives off the dirt cliff Wednesday in these parts, hoping
not to make the thud you've been seeing during those inspired
commercials, on which the network might spend up to $10 million, to
announce its arrival.
</P>
<P>
   The half-hour edition wants not only to give viewers ``sports
news from the only region you care about _ yours'' but directly
compete with the local sportscasts in L.A. (which occasionally
stretch to three minutes long on a slow car-chaseless night) as
well as snuff out the ESPN ``SportsCenter'' late-night show that
continues to be more of a national focus.
</P>
<P>
   Executive producer Milt Weiss has already hired two anchors _
Barry LeBrock and Gaard Swanson _ but a third candidate, John
Fricke, hasn't been able to get out of his contract with Clear
Channel radio. He has six months remaining on that deal to continue
on XTRA-AM (690) as the morning show co-host. Reporters Lisa
Guerrero and Suzy Shuster have also been hired.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss said he must have viewed hundreds of tapes of potential
on-air talent. But even in this personality-driven market, he says
the content of the show is what will distinguish it from other
Roggin-esque presentations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be less talent and more content,'' said Weiss, in
Seattle earlier this week for that regional's show launch. ``If you
don't have the information or superior highlights . . . that's the
key as far as I'm concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   __ All in the family: It was crazy enough that Keith Olbermann's
mom was hit in the face _ right between the eyes in fact _ by a
wild throw from Yankees second baseman Chuck Knoblauch during a
game against the White Sox last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Even more weird, Olbermann had to narrate the clip of the
incident during Fox's baseball studio show later that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``And his throw . . . !ital!hits my mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Marie Olbermann was sitting in the season seats at Yankee
Stadium behind the first-base dugout that the family has had since
1972.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's fine,'' Keith said this week. ``Two mild shiners.
Nothing broken. She even went back for Sunday's game, and more
applause.''
</P>
<P>
   To him, the most surreal thing about all this was seeing his mom
in the New York newspapers _ she made the front page of the Daily
News, plus three stories inside, and page three of the Post. But
Olbermann also said it's been kind of disheartening to find out
that no one from the team called to inquire about her injury.
</P>
<P>
   Only Yankees manager Joe Torre _ who did play-by-play of the
Angels in the late '80s for KTLA at the same time Olbermann was an
anchor at the station _ seemed concerned enough to ask reporters
the next day about her condition.
</P>
<P>
   But she's getting some media exposure out of this. Olbermann
promises an ``exclusive interview'' with his mom on this Saturday's
Fox pregame show before the Dodgers game in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHAT SMOKES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ TV Guide's somewhat gutsy move for putting out
special-edition Lakers covers on the June 24-30 issue. The series
released with pictures of the Lakers' Shaquille O'Neal, Kobe
Bryant, Rick Fox and Glen Rice proclaiming ``Dynasty Two'' was
actually distributed to newsstands Monday afternoon _ well before
Game 6 and before it was known if a Game 7 was needed. What if the
Lakers blew those last two games? Then they'd really be collector's
items (at just $1.79 a piece). Lakers play-by-play man Chick Hearn
wrote the story inside, comparing this team to Lakers teams of the
past, couching it with such phrases as ``the Lakers became a
championship-caliber team'' because of Phil Jackson. While the
greater Southern California market got this cover, the rest of the
country had to deal with the new cast from MTV's ``Real World.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ The quiet departure of Ferdie Pacecho from boxing telecasts
after nearly 25 years. When Showtime does the delay telecast of
Saturday night's (9 p.m.) bout in Scotland between Mike Tyson and
Lou Savarese, ``The Fight Doctor'' won't be there, having announced
his retirement during last week's broadcast of the Andrew
Golota-Orlin Norris bout. Showtime plans for a Pacecho special
called ``The Twelve Greatest Rounds of the 20th Century'' to air in
the fall. For now, the Showtime boxing team will exist with Steve
Albert and Bobby Czyz. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ Meanwhile, HBO's replay of last week's Shane Mosley-Oscar De
La Hoya bout, which drew $37 million from 700,000 buys at $49.95 to
make it the second-biggest nonheavyweight title bout ever, is
Saturday at 10:45 p.m. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ Did you know: Tiger Woods was shown 407 times totaling 93
minutes and 23 seconds during his four-hour round Sunday at the
U.S. Open, according to sophisticated data collected by New York
Times reporter Richard Sandomir. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ NBC's Bob Costas said it on Wednesday as a guest on CBS'
Craig Kilborn's show, in reference to the rioting that took place
outside Staples Center after Game 6: ``An ESPN truck was torched .
. . by Fox Sports West.'' &QL; 
WHAT CHOKES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ Isiah Thomas' agenda. Throughout the NBA Finals, the NBC
studio analyst danced around media speculation about his probable
future as Larry Bird's replacement as coach of the Indiana Pacers.
But then remember, Thomas predicted the Pacers would beat the
Lakers in six games. Why? ``I think the Pacers are the smartest
team playing basketball right now,'' he said before Game 1. ``If
they can keep games close, I think they can win because of their
intellectual capacity.'' Now, NBC's intellectual capacity has to be
questioned for allowing him to stay on during the series. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ Wonder how ESPN2 reached 70 million quicker than any other
cable channel in history? By airing quality programming such as
``Magic The Gathering'' tournaments, as it did Tuesday this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
