<HEADLINE>
RAMON PITCHES SOX BACK INTO FIRST PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Red Sox4Yankees2
</P>
<P>
   On a night the Yankees may have tilted the balance of power
further in their favor by adding strongman Juan Gonzalez from
Detroit, Ramon the Elder reminded the Bombers that the road to
another World Series may yet have to pass through the brothers
Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who were entertaining thoughts of a four-game sweep
when they beat Pedro the Younger Tuesday night, instead left town
with a split after falling, 4-2, to Ramon and the Red Sox. The
Yankees may have left with a consolation prize, however: They
reportedly came to terms Thursday with the Tigers on a deal for
Gonzalez, contingent on the two-time American League most valuable
player agreeing to waive his no-trade clause and coming to terms on
a new contract extension. That may not be a slam dunk; there were
already reports Thursday night that Gonzalez had turned thumbs-down
on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rich get richer, don't they?'' said Sox outfielder Darren
Lewis of the Gonzalez reports. ``He (Yankees owner George
Steinbrenner) ain't afraid to spend his loot, is he?''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Sons of Jimy Williams left for Toronto a
half-game ahead of the Yankees and Blue Jays after winning the last
two games of the series, though Nomar Garciaparra gave another full
house at Fenway Park (33,744) a severe fright that summer was about
to come to a sudden end.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, backpedaling into short center field in the seventh
inning to catch a popup by outfielder Ricky Ledee, collided with
center fielder Carl Everett as he made the catch, tumbling backward
over the fallen Everett. Garciaparra flipped the ball into the
infield from his knees before rolling over in pain, clutching his
right ankle.
</P>
<P>
   While trainer Jim Rowe sprinted Wendell Kim-like to
Garciaparra's side, teammates and Williams gathered around the Red
Sox shortstop, whose two doubles had contributed mightily to two
rallies. But after a brief but anxious interlude in which the
tropical night air was sucked out of the Back Bay, Garciaparra rose
to his feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he was all right,'' said Lewis, the closest eyewitness.
``Carl started sliding even before he hit Nomie. When I was talking
to him, he was cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a California boy, tough. Old school. It's either-or in
California. You're either real soft or pretty tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, who was swathed in icepacks after the game, hobbled
to his cubicle and cracked jokes about the play with Everett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt pain in my calf and my ankle,'' said Garciaparra, who
lined a double into the left-field corner to start the Sox' two-run
second, then hit a gapper for another RBI double in their two-run
third. ``Right now it feels all right, but it's the thought of
waking up tomorrow with it stiffening up that scares me.''
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't a trace of fear Thursday night in Martinez, who
struck out a season-high seven batters and allowed just four hits
in 6 2/3 innings to run his record to 6-4, including two wins
against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez gave up a two-run home run to Bernie Williams in the
first inning _ the Bombers hit 10 home runs in the series to none
for the Sox _ but did not allow another Yankee to advance past
second base until he was lifted with two outs and a man on first in
the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   When Shane Spencer singled with one out in the seventh, Williams
headed for the mound, mindful that Martinez, who would wind up
throwing 123 pitches, was pushing his limit. Catcher Jason Varitek,
the third party to the conference on the mound, said he assumed the
manager planned to summon a fresh arm to face the
lefthanded-hitting Ledee.
</P>
<P>
   That typically is the Williams way, but not Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically in my mind I wanted him to get Ledee,'' Williams
said. ``In my mind I left him in there to get the out. I know he's
a tough lefthanded hitter; we were leaving it open at first base,
and I knew where he was in the pitch count, but I went with the
man. That's basically what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon, remember, has had plenty of practice at being The Man
well before little brother came along. ``He's got to give me a
chance,'' Martinez said. ``And that's what he did, he gave me a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez coaxed the popup out of Ledee that caused the pileup in
center field, then was startled to see Williams come out again,
this time with the hook.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting better and better,'' said Martinez, who has now
allowed three runs or fewer in nine of his 13 starts, and is 6-1 in
those outings. ``By the time he came out, I had thrown a lot of
pitches, but it still felt fine.''
</P>
<P>
   It felt even better that the Red Sox came away with the split,
after some deft relief work by Bryce Florie, Rich Garces, and Derek
Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's big because of the way we played the first two games,''
said Varitek, whose sacrifice fly accounted for one of the four
runs off Yankees rookie Jake Westbrook, stand-in for the disabled
Roger Clemens (groin).
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to play well, and it really starts with our
pitching. We're not going to score too many runs. We might one day,
when more than one or two people get hot, but that's what this team
is built on. We need to pitch well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
