<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 02:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2447 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-GOALIESDRAFT-BOS &LR;      06-23 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GOALIESDRAFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHANCE TO NET A STAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gerry Cheevers figures he was 25 years old by the time he fully
grasped the job. There is a protracted learning curve in the art of
paddle and glove.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's when you finally have that feeling that you're better
than the shooter,'' recalled the Bruins' Hall of Fame netminder.
``Every time he comes down the ice _ even if it's Pavel Bure today
_ you've got the confidence to think, `OK, I've got him.' ''
</P>
<P>
   John Davidson figures he was about a year older, maybe 26, when
he could say his game was fully shaped. By then, he was six years
beyond the day in June when the St. Louis Blues made him the No. 5
pick overall in the 1973 amateur draft.
</P>
<P>
   The first netminder ever to jump directly from junior hockey to
the NHL, Davidson wishes his transition into the pro game had been
slower.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted it, and I thought I was ready for it,'' recalled
Davidson, now a renowned analyst whose best years ultimately came
with the Rangers. ``But I don't think I was ready _ for the amount
of games, for the pressure, everything. Today, I'd recommend what
the Devils organization does with just about all of its players,
give them a couple of years in the minors and then bring 'em up.''
</P>
<P>
   In the hours leading up to the National Hockey League entry
draft that begins Saturday morning in Calgary, the name creating
the greatest buzz has been Rick DiPietro, the 18-year-old netminder
from Winthrop who decided weeks ago to forfeit his final three
years at Boston University and launch his pro career. DiPietro will
go high in the first round, with the chance of being only the
second netminder selected first overall.
</P>
<P>
   No matter where he is selected, however, history shows that
DiPietro cannot reasonably be expected to make an immediate leap
from Babcock Street to the NHL. He will sign a three-year
entry-level contract, making him an instant millionaire, but he
could be fortunate to get his first NHL action before his contract
expires June 30, 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The game's philosophy is changing. Once, goalies rarely were
picked in the first round. But in the past three seasons, no fewer
than eight netminders have been selected in the opening round. One,
Roberto Luongo, chosen fourth overall by the Islanders in '97, is
widely considered a potential franchise goalie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there's been a reluctance to use a high pick on a
goalie over the years,'' said Cheevers, now one of the Bruins' top
scouts. ``But my feeling is, if you're high on a kid, and you think
he's gonna do the job for you, then so what if he's 18 or 19? If
you solve that problem with a kid that young, you've solved it for
a long, long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Caron, now retiring at age 70 as a St. Louis Blues
executive, was of that mind in 1970 when, as overseer of the draft
for the Canadiens, he selected Flin Flon netminder Ray Martyniuk
with the No. 5 pick overall. It was a bold move. At the time, only
a half-dozen netminders ever had been chosen in the first round.
Ken Dryden, originally a Bruins draft pick (14th overall, a
third-rounder, in '64), had yet to arrive in the Forum as the
Canadiens' savior.
</P>
<P>
   ``You draft a kid, and he's a prospect,'' Caron said the other
day, thinking back some 30 years. ``If he doesn't make it in a
couple of years, he goes from prospect to suspect. And if he
doesn't make it in another year or two, he's gone from prospect to
suspect _ to reject.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, such was the career path of Martyniuk. He kicked
around in the minors for a few years but never made it. All the
more bitter for Habs fans was how history played out: Darryl
Sittler, selected eighth in the draft by Toronto, went on to become
a Hall of Fame pivot.
</P>
<P>
   Caron went to Flin Flon to scout Bobby Clarke, selected 17th
overall by the Flyers in '69, but was taken by Martyniuk's skills.
In St. Louis, Caron recalled, Scotty Bowman was saying that
Martyniuk was the best young netminder in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   But all the hype and hope meant nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning teams always lead you to a lot of high selections,''
reflected Caron, noting what a powerhouse the Flin Flon Bombers had
been with the likes of Clarke and Martyniuk. ``That's fine. But you
must make sure that the reason a team is a winner is because your
candidate played a key role in the club's success.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidson figures league expansion and subsequent parity have
made it even more essential, in fact imperative, for clubs to
consider using their top pick on a goalie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' he said. ``Every team now has a quality goalie.
If you don't have one, you're dead. Obviously, you've got to look
at the overall draft, and what else is available. But to me,
there's no reason not to take a goalie. Look at what Grant Fuhr did
for the Oilers.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuhr, selected eighth overall by Edmonton in '81, was the
backbone of four Stanley Cup championships and is a certain Hall of
Famer. In '83, the Sabres made Tom Barrasso, only days out of
Acton-Boxboro High School, the fifth pick overall. By the fall, he
was a regular in the Buffalo net, was the rookie of the year, and
went on to win a pair of Cups (with Pittsburgh). The Flyers used
the 22d pick overall in '95, a first-rounder, to select Brian
Boucher from Woonsocket, R.I. With Boucher in net this spring, the
Flyers came within one victory of reaching the Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't kid yourself,'' said Caron. ``What Boucher did this year
will play in DiPietro's favor.''
</P>
<P>
   For every Fuhr, Barrasso, and Boucher, however, there are
countless other highly touted teenage netminders, including some
first-rounders who never made it or have yet to see their NHL
careers truly blossom. Witness, in recent years: Jimmy Waite, Eric
Fichaud, Jocelyn Thibault.
</P>
<P>
   So sure were the Canadiens that Thibault, a No. 10 pick by
Quebec in 1993, would be a franchise goalie, they dealt Patrick Roy
to get him. Thibault, now 25, is with the Blackhawks, still trying
to play up to his billing. Roy, at age 34, remains the franchise
netminder in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's the same thing that you get with every position,''
said Davidson. ``There are going to be busts. If you feel sure
about a guy, and you feel his game is complete, I think you have to
do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a risk. But it could be a bigger risk not to take him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
