<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 02:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2448 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GEN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LAD     06-23 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRIDAY NOTES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The beating Sugar Shane Mosley administered to Oscar De La Hoya
last Saturday night might not have equaled the humbling the Top
Rank promoter Bob Arum gave the Staples Center's president, Tim
Leiweke.
</P>
<P>
   According to California State Athletic Commission records, the
match didn't quite do at the gate what the wide-eyed Leiweke
thought it would do when last March he guaranteed Arum $5 million
to stage it at the new downtown facility.
</P>
<P>
   Although Staples Center officials announced afterward that the
fight was a 20,744 sellout, the CSAC reports only 15,643 tickets
were paid for, meaning 5,131 fans or a fourth of the crowd watched
the proceedings free of charge.
</P>
<P>
   In the stirring parlance of boxing, this is what's known as a
papered house.
</P>
<P>
   And many of the tickets that were sold, especially in the $900
and $700 range, were discounted to as low as $250. It's known one
Las Vegas casino even was given a 2-for-1 ticket bargain.
</P>
<P>
   The net from the fight after taxes was $5,804, 189.80, which did
not meet the lofty pre-fight expectations of Leiweke, who had
optimistically predicted an $8 million gate.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Leiweke, it didn't reach such a plateau and
insiders are claiming the Staples Center's first foray into boxing
resulted in a seven-figure loss.
</P>
<P>
   For months, or ever since the De La Hoya-Mosley match was
officially announced on March 20, you were told that it was certain
to be a sellout.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, only a couple of days after tickets went on sale to the
public, the propaganda minister of Arum's organization, Bill
``Bozo'' Caplan, frantically called around to various media outlets
to announce more than 18,000 already had been peddled.
</P>
<P>
   This gave the impression the fight was a runaway attraction, and
that those who were interested in seeing it better rush out
immediately and purchase tickets.
</P>
<P>
   A time-honored PR person's ploy.
</P>
<P>
   Harmless enough, for sure, but a deception, nevertheless.
</P>
<P>
   Repeated phone calls to Tim Leiweke were not returned, and it's
not surprising.
</P>
<P>
   The guy's probably embarrassed by the way he got skinned by
Arum, although he's certainly not the first boxing tenderfoot to
endure such treatment.
</P>
<P>
   You can be sure of one future certainty.
</P>
<P>
   The De La Hoya-Mosley rematch won't be at the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think Tim Leiweke and the Staples Center are in business
to blow money. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Bob Arum finally made his first mistake with Oscar De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   He should never have matched him against Sugar Shane Mosley in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley simply is a better fighter than De La Hoya faster,
quicker, wiser, tougher, stronger and more durable.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost laughable to me to hear the litany of excuses being
offered on behalf of De La Hoya in the wake of his split decision
loss to Mosley, including the lamest of all by De La Hoya, who
incredibly felt he was jobbed by the officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the only way I can win a fight anymore is to knock my
opponent out,'' groused De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   No, there is another way you can win, Oscar beat the guy you're
fighting in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   You didn't do this against Felix Trinidad, when you embarrassed
your sport and yourself by giving a rousing impersonation of the
Italian Army, circa World War II, by going into a full retreat
during the final three rounds.
</P>
<P>
   And you certainly didn't do it against Mosley, who exposed you
for what you are at this juncture of your career a formidable
fighter simply no longer formidable enough to beat the best in your
division.
</P>
<P>
   And anyone who doesn't think Sugar Shane Mosley isn't the best
welterweight in the world at the moment will be given a free class
in the Marty Sammon School of Fight Scoring. . . .
</P>
<P>
   What fight was Marty Sammon watching last Saturday night? Any
imbecile who thought De La Hoya deserved a two-point victory and S
with his 115-113 scorecard should never be allowed to judge a fight
again. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I'm wrong. Oscar De La Hoya could well beat Sugar
Shane Mosley in Las Vegas, where Bob Arum is a dominant figure and
where the officials almost always dutifully follow his cue (except,
of course in the De La Hoya-Trinidad fight when Don King was
involved in t too).
</P>
<P>
   Mosley will beat De La Hoya again, but could lose the decision,
an injustice that almost happened last Saturday night. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Oscar De La Hoya, who has to blame someone for his
demise, is set to get rid of his longtime trainer, Robert Alcazar,
done several times in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``If De La Hoya is going to bring in still another new trainer,
why doesn't he bring in the best, D. Wayne Lukas?'' cracked the old
Olympic Auditorium publicist, Van ``Hate 'Em All'' Barbieri, fresh
as ever. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Notice how almost all the media analysis of the De La
Hoya-Mosley fight is from De La Hoya's perspective, which I find
odd since Mosley was the deserved winner and clearly the superior
fighter. . . .
</P>
<P>
   If I'm Bob Arum, I don't dare match De La Hoya against Mosley
again, for another De La Hoya loss would irreparably damage De La
Hoya as a pay-per-view phenomenon, if he's not already tarnished in
the aftermath of his latest disappointing performance. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Sugar Shane Mosley reminds me of a combination Pernell Whitaker
and Aaron Pryor, with a pinch of Sugar Ray Leonard. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Finally, Mike Tyson is getting terrific press coverage for
his Saturday night Showtime fight in Scotland against Lou Savarese
for roughing up the English promoter, Frank Warren. Tyson's
deportment outside the ring these days is far more compelling than
what he does inside. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ The bottom line Monday night after the Lakers won their world
title is that tyranny raged around the Staples Center, and that the
have rounded up these cowardly punks and given Shaquille O'Neal the
opportunity to dunk them through a basketball hoop. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Dancing Barry Clifford, the Long Beach-based maitre d' to the
stars, is now strutting his stuff at upscale Sorrento's in Laguna
Beach, where Mark McGwire often dines with his parents during the
off-season. . . .
</P>
<P>
   The late Syrian dictator, Hafez Assad, may have had his faults,
but never have I felt safer walking the streets at night in a major
city than I did last January when I visited Damascus. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hennessy's terrific story Thursday on the phony passing
himself off for years as a Navy Seal Vietnam War hero reminded me
of a long ago incident at the old Adams Gym on PCH where I met a
creep passing himself off as a player with the Los Angeles Rams.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, I was the Rams beat writer for the Los Angeles
Herald Examiner, and knew every player on the team. Brazenly, I
informed the impersonator of this fact, and the guy never was seen
again at the gym after my cruel admission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
