NYT-06-23-00 1039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2546 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-US-MEXICO-$ADV25-COX     06-23 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-MEXICO-$ADV25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. WATCHING MEXICAN ELECTION CLOSELY, EXPECTS LITTLE CHANGE IN
RELATIONSHIP
 &HT;    (800&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With MEXICO-PRI-$ADV25.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., June 25 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The party that has governed Mexico for seven
decades has become as familiar to U.S. policymakers as the litany
of difficult issues dividing the giant neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   If the ruling party is tossed out in July 2 presidential
elections, though, American officials would quickly praise the
result as a healthy development in Mexico's democratic evolution, a
badly needed breath of fresh air for the rough-and-tumble politics
south of the border.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, though, turning the tables on 71 years of one-party
rule in Mexico would present new challenges to the United States,
even as it opened the door to a whole new chorus of long-stifled
political voner carrier of the long-ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party, known by its Spanish acronym, PRI; or
opposition candidate Vicente Fox Quesada, of the National Action
Party, or PAN.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mexican people will vote and make their own decision,''
President Clinton told reporters earlier this month, when Mexican
President Ernesto Zedillo (of the PRI) paid a visit to the White
House for his 11th bilateral meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, the answer is little different.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Labastida nor Fox has promised any significant departure
from policies that have led to increasingly close ties between the
United States and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   And U.S. diplomats and senior administration officials insist
that the bricks helped, said Leiken, author of the forthcoming
book, ``Melting Borders,'' a look at the Mexican community in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main impediment to change, in terms of corruption, is the
lack of alternacy in power _ the kind of immunity and impunity that
that has created among important political figures,'' he explained.
``When you have a one-party system, it lends itself to that.''
</P>
<P>
   A Fox victory wouldn't wipe out Mexican corruption, certainly,
nor would it run off the druglords.
</P>
<P>
   A government shake-up would, however, present a new
administration with the necessity to start with a clean slate. At a
minimum, that would force organized crime to dance the risky ballet
involved in courting contacts in a new government.
</P>
<P>
   That in itself could be a stride in the right direction for two
countries so dependent on each other in the drug war, as in so many
other endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   One thing's certain, said Goodman, no matter who wins on July 2:
``We really need them, and they really need us.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnes.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.wola.org
</P>
<P>
   www.american.edu/media
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
