<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2547 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-SYRIA-INTERNET-$ADV26     06-23 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYRIA-INTERNET-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INTERNET WINDS ITS WAY INTO SYRIAN CONSCIENCE
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    For Use Mon., June 26 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria _ Barely big enough for nine computers, Zoni
Internet Service offers Syrians an on-line window to the outside
world.
</P>
<P>
   A marker board lists cloaking sites, like ``besilent.com''.
Customers use them to get around firewalls to ``hotmail.com'' and
other mail systems blocked by the Syrian government's server.
</P>
<P>
   But, even more significant than the fact that Zoni gets away
with this, is that many other sites do not appear to be impeded by
the government at all.
</P>
<P>
   Customers can go to the Amnesty International homepage to read
up on torture in Syrian jails. They can get most newspapers and
news magazines on-line anywhere. They cannot get sites from Israel
but they can call up the Israeli Embassy Website in Washington,
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Zoni is one of at least three non-government Internet shops
opening in the last nine months in Damascus. Tucked away on the
fourth floor of a dingy office building, it has the feel of
something slightly illicit but is brimming with optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here in Syria, many things will change,'' says 32-year-old
owner Yamor Alzoni, a bearded, practicing Muslim on the crest of
his country's Internet wave.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Syrian government is for it or not _ and the signals
are mixed _ Internet use is slowly expanding in a country known for
slow change and controlled speech.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Syrian officials are showing a hesitancy typical of
authoritarian regimes confronted with a new technology. They don't
want to be left behind by the on-line world, but they seem intent
on trying to chaperone and manage their people's activity there.
</P>
<P>
   Syrians must have government licenses to get a password for
using the Internet. Officials say there are only about 7,000
Internet-licensed hook-up ``points,'' including those in schools or
other places with multiple users, for this country of more than 17
million.
</P>
<P>
   Saying the country's phone system has not been able to handle
more Internet users, officials limit the licenses to institutions
and the elite, like professors or business owners.
</P>
<P>
   Zoni's clients are largely foreigners checking E-mail messages.
The US$6.50-per-hour fees deter most Syrians. The country's per
capita Gross Domestic Product (GDP) in 1998, the last year
available, was estimated at just US$2,500.
</P>
<P>
   Further slowing Internet use, there's a gray area for Syrians
hoping to get on-line from home.
</P>
<P>
   Saadalla Aghad Kalaa(cq all), head of the media committee for
the government-backed Syrian Computer Society, said the country is
not ready yet to plunge into unfettered home Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having the Internet at home is something that could hurt this
traditional society,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Syrians can use the Internet at home, he hesitates and
says in his precise English, ``It is not forbidden, but it is not
allowed.''
</P>
<P>
   Syria has begun loosening some controls on information.
Television satellite dishes were in effect legalized, albeit
slowly, in the mid-1990s. They sprout up by the thousands on
apartment-block rooftops in the city that claims to be the oldest
continually lived -in capital on earth.
</P>
<P>
   The computer society is headed by Bashar Assad, son of, and
likely successor to, the late Syrian President Hafez Assad. His
patronage has raised hopes that he will welcome the new computer
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Kalaa said the society and government have 200 computer training
centers around the country and expect to license more than 200,000
Internet hook-ups next year.
</P>
<P>
   But Syria is famous for restrictive, socialist-style planning.
</P>
<P>
   While other countries thrive off the freedom and spontaneity of
Internet use, Syria dribbles out the licenses. It tries to herd
users _ may of whom have computers at home _ into post offices,
schools or other centers where the Internet is available.
</P>
<P>
   Kalaa hosts a weekly television show that demonstrates the uses
of computers and the Internet. But, he says callers to the show
have a regular complaint: ``Why are you showing us this if we can't
use it at home?''
</P>
<P>
   Kalaa says it is a balancing act, trying to introduce the new
technology without angering older-generation Syrians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell them, 'Even if you cannot use it, you must not stop
it,''' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Alzoni, the Internet shop owner, said government officials have
now denied him permission for a second branch. He believes it is
more out of the government's desire to control Internet monopolies
than any desire to restrict information.
</P>
<P>
   He notes that he's also been told that he cannot run an Internet
``cafe.'' Government departments keep a close eye on cafes and
coffee shops, places where people can gather and conspire. That
seemed to bother officials more than the new technology.
</P>
<P>
   So, Alzoni said, he called his business an Internet ``service''
and kept it open.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow's E-mail address is: larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
