<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2548 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-BRITAIN-SPEER-$ADV24-     06-23 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-SPEER-$ADV24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEW PLAY EXAMINES THE TWO FACES OF NAZI ARCHITECT, SPEER
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., June 24 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ How can an apparently honorable man take part in an
unspeakable evil and then find a way to live with himself?
</P>
<P>
   This is the central question of ``Albert Speer,'' a new play in
London that pursues its unsettling answers through a 3 1/2-hour
examination of the confessions and equivocations of Nazi leader
Adolph Hitler's pet architect and armaments minister.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Trevor Nunn, the play is based on the successful
1995 biography by Gitta Sereny, ``Albert Speer: His Battle with
Truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Sereny, an Austrian-born Briton, wrote the 720-page book nearly
20 years after a three-week interview she had with Speer, who died
in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his high position in the Nazi regime and his
willingness to write about his experiences, Speer long has been an
important figure in the effort to understand the inner workings of
the Third Reich.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the confessional and analytical nature of his books,
he has been widely regarded as ``the good Nazi.'' He maintained to
his death that he was unaware of the Holocaust until after the war.
</P>
<P>
   However, this assertion has come under attack in recent years by
Sereny and other writers who doubt that Speer could have been so
comfortably ignorant.
</P>
<P>
   This perspective is embraced by playwright David Edgar, best
known to Americans for his adaptation of Dickens' ``Nicholas
Nickleby'' in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar explores the Speer story in two acts. The first represents
Speer's version, a portrayal that is faithful to his books,
``Inside the Third Reich'' and ``Spandau Diaries.''
</P>
<P>
   The scene opens with Speer's reporting to Spandau prison in
Berlin to begin the 20-year sentence handed down during the
Nuremberg trials. In the background of the scene are Nazi war
</P>
<P>
   criminals dangling by their necks _ a fate escaped by Speer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an intelligent rendering of Speer by Alex Jennings, the
first act is stolen by Roger Allam's mesmerizing Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   Allam plays the Fuehrer as an intensely charming prophet with a
grand vision of a strong, pure Germany that will need _ and here's
where the young architect Speer comes in _ a spectacular new
capital on the magnitude of ancient Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Hitler comes across as an engaging, good listener with Old World
manners and a gift for flattery. He casts a Faustian spell over the
ambitious young Speer and elevates him to be the second most
powerful man in the Reich.
</P>
<P>
   At one point Speer tries to explain how Hitler's charismatic
appeal worked on intelligent, stable Germans _ such as Speer:
``Eighty million people didn't follow him because he was evil but
</P>
<P>
   because they thought he was extremely good!''
</P>
<P>
   In her book, Sereny describes an emotional even ``erotic''
relationship between the two men. Hitler saw the handsome young
Speer as the Aryan of his warped dreams. To Speer, Hitler was the
father-figure he never had. In the play, Speer's own father regards
his son's role in the Reich with icy contempt.
</P>
<P>
   This theme unfolds as a dark love story that only begins to
unravel in the horror of the last years of the war when Hitler's
loathsome insanity becomes obvious even to Speer.
</P>
<P>
   The moment of revelation comes during one of the play's most
memorable moments. Hitler _ now clearly disjointed and drained _
sits slumped against Speer's white model of the majestic dome that
he designed as centerpiece of the imperial Reich capital that never
was.
</P>
<P>
   Hitler rages at the cowards and inferiors who failed him in his
quest to rid the world of the ``Jewish-Bolshevik conspiracy.''
Speer, at last recognizing Hitler for what he was, bravely resists
the Fuehrer's final demand that he destroy Germany to deprive the
weaklings left behind with any means to recover from the war.
</P>
<P>
   Act 1 closes with a chilling 1943 speech made by Heinrich
Himmler, the Nazi SS leader who directed the program of mass
killing. Himmler reveals the full horror of the ``Final Solution.''
</P>
<P>
   The second act, which shows Speer after his release, shifts from
Speer's account of what happened and begins to chip away at his
story.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of the play, Speer is portrayed not as sinner
seeking redemption but as a man seeking comfort in denial.
</P>
<P>
   Described by one character as a ``rent-a-penitent,'' Speer makes
the university and bookstore circuit dogged always by questions
about his role in the Reich. The questions in time overcome his
comfortable and practiced responses.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he is forced to confront himself and the ghost of
Hitler in dreams that allow him no escape from his reality.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, he confesses that he must have known _ even though
he could never bring himself to acknowledge what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sensed, and turned away from what I sensed,'' Speer says
with horror.
</P>
<P>
   ``Albert Speer'' is scheduled to run through July 8. For
tickets, call 011-44-207-452-3000
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s e-mail address is BertR(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.nt-online.org,
</P>
<P>
   http://www.londontown.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 1041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2549 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-KOSOVO-PRISONERS-$ADV     06-23 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PRISONERS-$ADV25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOR FAMILIES OF KOSOVAR ALBANIANS JAILED IN SERBIA, AGONY LIES
IN THE WAITING
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., June 25 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERDORE BORDER CROSSING, Yugoslavia _ She called it the ``worst
torture.''
</P>
<P>
   Alma Berisha's 45-year-old husband, Renor, was rounded up and
jailed 14 months ago by Serb paramilitaries. For months she and her
family awaited word of his fate. They then paid thousands of
dollars in bribes for his freedom. And then they had to wait some
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't know the agony of not knowing if someone is alive or
dead,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   In the closing days of last year's 78-day NATO bombing campaign
against Yugoslavia, Serb military and paramilitary gangs wreaked a
final round of terror as they retreated, rounding up thousands of
Kosovar Albanians and throwing many of them in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Today, more than 1,100 ethnic Albanians, including old men,
women and teenagers under 18, remain in limbo in Serb jails, in
part because Western diplomats, rushing to finalize a cease-fire
agreement with the Serb-dominated Yugoslav government, deleted from
the document thorny provisions covering prisoner exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   While politicians defended this choice as politically expedient,
it has fostered a web of corruption within Serbia that charge
families between US$7,000 and US$15,000 to secure the release of
their relatives. In the last year, close to 1,000 Kosovar Albanians
have been freed from Serb jails, and Red Cross officials estimate
that 90 percent of those releases came after bribes paid by
families.
</P>
<P>
   The system, aid officials here say, is unjust, but they complain
that the strained political relationship between the international
community and Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic keeps their
hands tied in the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the hands of Belgrade,'' Nic Sommers, spokesman for
the International Committee of the Red Cross in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   For the Berisha family, left with no political lifeline to help
free Renor, a former schoolteacher in his hometown of Djakova, in
western Kosovo, the choice was simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you speak of money or a life, there is no choice. You
pay,'' Alma Berisha said.
</P>
<P>
   After her husband's disappearance on May 13 last year, Alma
finally learned Renor was alive on Sept. 25. His name had been
published by the Red Cross, who gained access to many prisoners
after the war.
</P>
<P>
   The spunky 31-year-old with short curly, black hair, traveled to
the prison four times to visit Renor, reporting back to the family
that he was in good health and was treated humanely. But he had no
hope for release until February, when an Albanian lawyer named Ismi
Bytygi called the family.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer said he could make a deal with the Serbs to free
Renor. The cost: US$7,500.
</P>
<P>
   The Berishas scrounged together the cash, gave it to the lawyer.
And, for three more months, no word came.
</P>
<P>
   The tension during this time was unbearable, Alma recalled. Her
4-year-old son, Renlend, insisted his home set a plate at his dad's
place at the dinner table ``so we could feel nearer to him,'' she
said. But the empty place hung heavily on her.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the worst torture. This waiting time,'' Alma said
during an interview with Cox Newspapers last month at their family
home.
</P>
<P>
   Later that night, without any warning, the family received a
phone call they had been waiting for: 17 Albanians would be
released at the Merdore Border Crossing the next day, and Renor
would be among them.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly, the Berishas flew into motion. With less than 24 hours
to prepare, Alma was overcome with apprehension. She elected to
stay home with Renlend and other women in the family to prepare the
welcome home feast, while her brothers-in-law and her older son,
12-year-old Shefki, drove the four hours to the border to greet
Renor.
</P>
<P>
   When they reached Merdore in the early afternoon of May 30, a
crowd of about 100 people _ family members who also were waiting
for their relatives _ had already gathered.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere along the two-lane road felt like an airport when
an arriving plane is late. People attempted nervous small talk, not
daring to speak what each feared, that their husband, son or sister
would not appear.
</P>
<P>
   All of the 17 families said they paid to free their relatives.
None believed that the money was used for court fees or defense
investigations, but simply got passed along as bribes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who cares whose pockets I line or where it all ends up. What
is money, when you are talking about a human life?'' said one man
who paid US$10,000 to have his 21-year-old son released.
</P>
<P>
   As shadows lengthened across the grain fields dotted with red
poppies and the heat slipped from the late spring day, the tension
collapsed into wails of joy, like a clap of lightning followed by
raindrops.
</P>
<P>
   A three-vehicle convoy of white minibuses had been glimpsed down
the road across the stretch of no-man's land. Slowly, 15 men and
two women got out of the vehicles and walked single file under a
concrete railroad bridge and across the border to freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Renor came into view at the end of the line. He walked strongly,
with hands swinging, past Serb guards and into the arms of his
family.
</P>
<P>
   The Berishas smothered him in kisses, while he scooped his son
into his arms. Minutes later, the former schoolteacher, who looked
pale but otherwise healthy was still too overcome with emotion to
speak.
</P>
<P>
   The only member of the family who could find words through the
tears was Shefki, who wore a wide grin across his freckled face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I'm very happy. My dad has missed so much,'' the lanky
youngster said. ``He's not fat anymore. Now, I'll have to tease him
about something else.''
</P>
<P>
   (Margaret Coker's E-mail address is: megc(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.icrc.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 1041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
