<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2552 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-MEXICO-PRI-$ADV25-COX     06-23 1428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-PRI-$ADV25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AFTER 71 YEARS IN POWER, MEXICO'S RULING PARTY BETTING ON ROOTS
TO WIN AGAIN
 &HT;    (1100&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With US-MEXICO-$ADV25.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., June 25 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Alfredo Mondragon is from a Mexico so far removed
from modern times, he doesn't know his age and he can't express why
he supports this country's Institutional Revolutionary Party _ the
PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just what we do,'' the Mazahua Indian from rural Mexico
state said. He stood motionless in soiled work clothes among a
throng of 100,000 cheering for the party's presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   High school teacher and union member Flavio Bernal, on the other
hand, has no trouble defending his party with a militant's
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Mexico we live with social peace that the PRI has
guaranteed,'' the 31-year-old Guadalajara resident said, pumping
his fist. ``We know the party has made mistakes, but we don't give
up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indian peasant and the earnest teacher _ both bused to
Mexico City for a recent rally _ are just two faces of a vast quilt
of support that helps sustain the PRI, the world's longest ruling
political party. For 71 years the PRI (pronounced, ``Pree'') has
controlled this country's presidency and most other political
offices.
</P>
<P>
   But the PRI faces its toughest test ever when Mexicans elect
their next president on July 2. Its candidate, veteran government
economist Francisco Labastida Ochoa, is locked in a bitter fight to
the end with Vicente Fox Quesada, a former Coca-Cola executive and
rancher who has mounted the most effective opposition campaign in
Mexico's modern history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since I entered politics in 1988, my mission has been to
drive the PRI from Los Pinos (the Mexican White House),'' said Fox,
candidate of the conservative National Action Party and coalition
Alliance for Change. ``Mexico can't live with the PRI anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   After seven decades in power _ and half the population in
poverty _ the PRI has a lot of incumbent baggage to carry. If it
loses the election, most political analysts agree, the party would
slide into crisis and jettison its national leadership. But don't
expect it to die.
</P>
<P>
   ``That party has a structure and breadth nobody is going to give
up,'' said Mexico City analyst Joel Estudillo.
</P>
<P>
   The party's boosters argue that while Mexico may be riddled with
problems, the party rose from ashes of the 1910 Mexican Revolution
and managed to turn a feudal backwater into an industrial,
oil-producing nation. The party's enemies, however, say the PRI has
perpetuated corruption and enriched an elite. They blame the party
for forcing millions of Mexico's poor to emigrate to the United
States, and plunging the country into repeated economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Among its detractors, the PRI is often scornfully referred to as
``the system'' or ``the official party'' or simply, ``the
dinosaur.''
</P>
<P>
   Its core support, some analysts say, is now only about 30
percent to 35 percent of Mexico's 58.7 million voters. But a
well-known leftist candidate, Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, is also running
for the presidency, so the opposition vote is split, which helps
Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of this divided opposition vote, most opinion polls
show that Fox and Labastida are in a dead heat now among likely
voters. Fox is trying to syphon votes from Cardenas and both are
fighting for the undecided, which could be as much as 20 percent of
the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI has enormous advantages in this war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now the party is pointing a shotgun and firing
everywhere,'' said Mexico City political analyst Edna Jaime. ``It's
using everything possible to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The PRI has sought to project a ``new PRI,'' more democratic and
more willing to engage in fierce but fair competition with rivals.
</P>
<P>
   For this election, the PRI hired cutting-edge U.S. campaign
strategists, like James Carville, President Clinton's advisor, to
help poll voters and fashion messages. The Austin, Texas-based
Public Strategies Inc., which shapes communications for campaigns,
has assisted in developing international relations.
</P>
<P>
   But in April, when it appeared that Fox was dramatically gaining
ground, the party also called in some controversial old-fashioned
party leaders to join the cause. At least one advisor, Manuel
Bartlett, has a reputation for strong-arm tactics. It's never been
proved, but many Mexicans even think he engineered outright fraud
in the 1988 presidential race to give the PRI the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win an election you have to be inclusive,'' said Javier
Trevino, a Harvard University-educated international affairs
advisor to Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign needs everyone in the party on board to help,
Trevino said, and election rules are so tight today nobody can
commit fraud at the ballot box.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the election we are going to continue to transform the
PRI,'' he added. ``But first we have an objective, which is to win
the election.''
</P>
<P>
   A key part of that strategy remains the PRI's traditional
network of ``corporatist'' organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Over seven decades, the PRI has built a web of pro-party unions
and associations that incorporate farmers, oil workers, industrial
workers, industrialists and government employees into the party's
ranks.
</P>
<P>
   True believers say they support the party because of its rebel
roots and flexible, mixed ideology, borrowing from socialism and
capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Members of my family died in the revolution,'' said Victor
Montelongo, an organizer for a PRI farmers' group in Guanajuato
state.
</P>
<P>
   Some sympathizers say they don't trust anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``The devil you know is better than the devil you don't,'' said
Rosa Espinoza, a secretary with the Mexican Confederation of
Workers, a massive pro-PRI union.
</P>
<P>
   And many support the party because it means perks in a poor
country.
</P>
<P>
   Government workers often receive housing subsidies, loans and
other benefits to offset low salaries. Poor people who seize land
to build houses on are incorporated into the PRI's ranks by local
party bosses, who help them obtain public services or tap into
electrical lines for free power.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of a great political culture of patronage,'' said
Jaime, the political analyst. ``The PRI hasn't been a military
dictatorship. It's been authoritarian but also inclusive.''
</P>
<P>
   As Mexico's political system has modernized in recent years and
opposition parties have begun to run more municipalities and
states, the PRI's patronage structure has begun to dissolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that doesn't mean it doesn't exist anymore,'' Jaime said.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida's final big rally in Mexico City on June 18 was packed
with people from PRI-affiliated groups, including unionized
teachers bused in from Jalisco, oil workers from Veracruz,
government workers all of stripes, and farmers and Indians from
Puebla and the state of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   A Zogby International poll of 1,330 likely voters surveyed
between June 10 and June 19 found Labastida had a 53-to-29-percent
advantage over Fox in rural areas, which are about 30 percent of
the electorate. The poll also found Labastida now has a three-point
lead over Fox, who, in a poll by the same company in May had a
five-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Many of Mexico's peasant farmers, who are on the lowest rungs of
the educational ladder, still regard the PRI and the government as
synonymous. They feel they owe the party their vote _ the PRI
distributed land after the revolution _ and they are grateful for
the few cash benefits the federal government gives them as
subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our grandparents voted for the PRI and so do we,'' said
Rosario Parra, 49, a Nahuatl Indian who was bused by the party from
rural Puebla to the PRI rally in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PRI has given us things like Procampo (cash subsidies for
farmers) and Progresa (a new program that offers cash for the
poorest of families),'' Parra added.
</P>
<P>
   A special watchdog congressional commission has cess because he
could lose.
</P>
<P>
   At his Mexico City rally, Labastida said: ``Only those who
already sense defeat proclaim anticipated fraud, which only exists
in their imagination or because of their sense of desperation.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' e-mail is: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.wola.org (Washington Office on Latin America)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
