<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2553 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-US-MEXICO-$ADV25-COX     06-23 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-MEXICO-$ADV25-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. WATCHING MEXICAN ELECTION CLOSELY, EXPECTS LITTLE CHANGE IN
RELATIONSHIP And, with Americans and Mexicans making 300 million
legal border crossings each year, not to mention illegal smuggling
and immigration, it's getting harder all the time to distinguish
between Mexican problems and American ills.
</P>
<P>
   Against that backdrop of growing integration between two very
different countries that just happen to be neighbors, Mexico
analysts in this country have long regarded Mexico's one-party rule
as a mixed blessing.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, it's brought stability _ of a sort _ to a
country with which the United States shares a 2,000-mile-long
border.
</P>
<P>
   That's no small achievement, given the vast disparities between
the two countries, the pernicious influence of druglords in Mexico
and the history of political violence and repression across much of
Central America and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   And the PRI has provided a known entity to U.S. policymakers.
They'd had years to get to know Zedillo. A Yale-trained economist,
Zedillo had held two cabinet positions under Mexico's former PRI
leader, President Carlos Salinas de Gortari, by the time Zedillo
took office in December 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's political predictability, though, has come at a price,
beginning, said Goodman, with a lack of imagination and energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you just have one set of decision-makers, you end up in
paralysis,'' said Goodman, dean of international studies at
American University in Washington. ``That's been a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The impact has gone far beyond questions of good governance.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Zedillo's efforts to root out corruption and bear down
on drug kingpins, Mexico has made little headway against violent
and well-funded druglords.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the Mexican government) has not disrupted the activities
of the major drug cartels,'' the State Department reported three
months ago in its annual review of international counter-drug
efforts. ``Chronic problems of corruption, weak police and criminal
justice institutions, budget constraints and severe poverty in
rural areas where drug crops are cultivated hamper Mexico's ability
to combat drug trafficking effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   One-party rule hasn't helped, said Leiken, author of the
forthcoming book, ``Melting Borders,'' a look at the Mexican
community in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main impediment to change, in terms of corruption, is the
lack of alternacy in power _ the kind of immunity and impunity that
that has created among important political figures,'' he explained.
``When you have a one-party system, it lends itself to that.''
</P>
<P>
   A Fox victory wouldn't wipe out Mexican corruption, certainly,
nor would it run off the druglords.
</P>
<P>
   A government shake-up would, however, present a new
administration with the necessity to start with a clean slate. At a
minimum, that would force organized crime to dance the risky ballet
involved in courting contacts in a new government.
</P>
<P>
   That in itself could be a stride in the right direction for two
countries so dependent on each other in the drug war, as in so many
other endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   One thing's certain, said Goodman, no matter who wins on July 2:
``We really need them, and they really need us.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnes.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.wola.org
</P>
<P>
   www.american.edu/media
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
