</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 11:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2563 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-KOREA-ANNIVERSARY-$AD     06-23 1772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-ANNIVERSARY-$ADV25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KOREAN WAR, 50 YEARS LATER: U.S. SACRIFICE TO FIGHT BACK
COMMUNISM A 'BARGAIN'
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With KOREA-SIDE-$ADV25.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., June 25 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS and JULIE CHAO 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL _ Wearing a crisply-pressed suit, a cellular phone at his
side, Son Byung Chan paused last week from the life he's built as a
successful consultant in this hard-driving capital and cast his
memory back half a century.
</P>
<P>
   The rice grew tall in the broad muddy paddies on the outskirts
of Pusan that June, and Son, then just seven years old, raced
barefoot with friends down dusty roads.
</P>
<P>
   The joys of summer, though, were soon swept aside.
</P>
<P>
   In the pre-dawn hours of June 25, 1950, nearly 100,000 North
Korean troops, backed by Russian built T-34 tanks and rolling
artillery, stormed across the border that had divided Korea since
the closing days of World War II into the Soviet-controlled North
and the U.S.-backed South.
</P>
<P>
   The attack opened three years of war that devastated Korea, left
more than 3 million dead, set the Cold War in stone and fired the
ideological animosities between East and West that, across the
Korean divide at least, have yet to be fully extinguished.
</P>
<P>
   The tides of history and the ravages of war unfolded before
young Son in startling glimpses of shattered lives.
</P>
<P>
   The bleeding bodies of wounded soldiers stretched out across the
classrooms of his elementary school. The fevered voices of refugees
huddled each night in the upper floor of his family's small wooden
home. The sweet and foreign taste of his first chocolate bar, the
gift of an American soldier a long way from home.
</P>
<P>
   From those uncertain beginnings, Son forged a life that has
taken him from adversity to prosperity, in a remarkable journey
that has paralleled his country's own epic rise from the ashes of
war to its position today as the thriving democratic home to the
world's 11th-largest economy.
</P>
<P>
   For Son, as for the nation, the transformation has played itself
out in the shadow of South Korea's giant ally, the United States,
whose presence on the craggy peninsula has become as much a part of
the country's psychic landscape as green rice stalks shimmering in
the summer sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``American soldiers have been staying in Korea for so long,''
Son said, ``if Americans moved out, for some time I'd feel
something odd, something missing.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifty years after the Korean War, some 37,000 American troops
stand sentry still on the divided Peninsula, where 54,000 U.S.
servicemen lost their lives fighting to push back North Korean
troops and their Chinese comrades in arms.
</P>
<P>
   For its sacrifice, the United States gained a staunch and
reliable ally in Asia's volatile northeast corner, even as it built
a citadel of capitalist-fed democracy on the frontiers of global
communism. Wedged between the eastern rim of China and Russia,
South Korea stood for four decades on the front lines of the Cold
War.
</P>
<P>
   From U.S. bases in South Korea, American warplanes armed with
nuclear bombs were, until the 1991 collapse of the Soviet Union,
poised on alert around the clock. Pilots suited up and waited in
their cockpits for orders _ that never came _ to attack Russian
naval and submarine forces in Vladivostok, less than an hour's
flight away for an F-16.
</P>
<P>
   Supersonic spy planes took off from South Korea to overfly
Soviet positions, and U.S. soldiers and Marines trained in
large-scale war games across the width and breadth of South Korea,
while American Air Force and Navy pilots flew mock bombing runs and
waged practice dog fights in the skies overhead.
</P>
<P>
   None of that, and none that followed, would have been possible,
however, if the U.S.-led United Nations forces hadn't turned back
North Korea in a conflict that marked a turning point in Western
efforts to stem the advance of communism at its geo-strategic
zenith.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stopped North Korea and, at that time, it's ally China, and
its founder and supporter, Russia, from taking all of the Korean
Peninsula,'' said retired U.S. Army Col. William Taylor, a senior
adviser for international security affairs at the Center for
Strategic and International Studies in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   That was anything but a foregone conclusion in the opening weeks
of the Korean War, when North Koreans rolled over the lightly-armed
South Korean forces, pressing fleeing civilians and retreating
troops to the fringes of Pusan on the peninsula's southern tip.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. forces led a larger United Nations contingent in a
three-year war to push back North Korean forces and their Chinese
allies.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting ended July 27, 1953, with a cease-fire _ though no
formal peace treaty has ever been signed _ along frontlines roughly
the same as the border that divided the two Koreas before the war.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 1 million Chinese soldiers are estimated to have been
killed in the fighting, along with half a million North Koreans,
nearly 300,000 South Koreans and up to 2 million Korean civilians
on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the country was left in cinders, its cities leveled to
rubble, its countryside almost completely denuded by fighting and
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country was so empty, `` said Rev. Cho Young Joon, pastor
of Chung Dong First Methodist Church in Seoul. He remembers
boarding a plane in 1960 to fly to the United States and seeing his
war-torn country from above for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing much remaining,'' Cho recalled last week, in
an interview with Cox Newspapers. ``Just red dirt.''
</P>
<P>
   In lieu of a peace treaty, each side threw up massive defenses
along the 140-mile-long border dividing Korea into North and South.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, in the wake of this month's historic summit in
Pyongyang between South Korean President Kim Dae Jung and North
Korean leader Kim Jong Il, the badly misnamed demilitarized zone,
or DMZ, remains the most heavily defended place on earth.
</P>
<P>
   The final faultline in a Cold War otherwise consigned to
history, the DMZ is a landmine-ridden, barbed-wire bounded swath
less than 5,000 yards wide. North Korea has nearly 1 million combat
troops arrayed near the DMZ, faced off against several hundred
thousand South Korean and American forces just across the verdant
no-man's line dividing the two.
</P>
<P>
   In few places are the stakes as high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tensions on the Korean Peninsula remain the leading threat to
peace and stability in East Asia,'' states the most recent White
House national security annual review.
</P>
<P>
   Combining military deterrence with diplomacy, the United States
has been fundamental to South Korea's stunning post-war
development.
</P>
<P>
   In two generations, per capita income has risen from US$50 a
year to nearly US$10,000. The the country's economic output rose
last year to US$407 billion; it's on track to add nearly US$30
billion more to that amount this year.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea has become a leading U.S. trading partner as well.
Two-way commerce last year hit US$54 billion, roughly 2.5 percent
of total U.S. imports and exports.
</P>
<P>
   Credit for the gains belongs largely to the Confucian work ethic
in a country where the 14-hour day and the six-day work week are
accepted as something of an article of faith.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. alliance, though, has been critical in providing a
security backdrop, as well as billions of dollars in assistance.
Direct U.S. aid ended in the early 1980s, but the United States put
up more than US$10 billion four years ago as its share of the US$57
billion international aid package put together to rescue the
flagging South Korean economy in the wake of a currency and stock
market crisis.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea has recovered smartly, though not, in all areas, to
pre-crisis levels.
</P>
<P>
   During their summit earlier this month, the leaders of North and
South Korea pledged to expand cultural ties, work toward reuniting
some of the tens of thousands of families that were divided by the
Korean War, and try to set relations on a cooperative footing.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton followed by implementing a policy he first
declared last September, saying he would rescind key parts of the
trade embargo President Harry Truman placed on North Korea when it
attacked the South 50 years ago. Within days Atlanta-based
Coca-Cola Co. began selling its soft drinks in the North, and U.S.
airlines, shipping companies, exporters, importers and banks are
expected to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether a charm offensive, from both sides
of the DMZ, can melt away half a century of hostility and set the
stage for peaceful reunification of a culture that was already
4,000 years old, after all, before the shooting began.
</P>
<P>
   Many appear willing, though, to at least give peace the benefit
of the doubt. The fervent anti-communist rhetoric of past war
commemorations has been tempered by renewed hopes for peace and
possible reunification.
</P>
<P>
   In hopes of pressing the momentum for peace, South Korea has
scrubbed plans for large-scale battle re-enactments and a huge
parade featuring South Korean war veterans that had been scheduled
for Sunday in downtown Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, after the summit, the atmosphere is totally changed
here,'' said Kim Sung-Hwan, deputy director-general for the Foreign
Ministry's North American bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is likely to sound a hopeful note, as well, when he
speaks Sunday to more than 10,000 American veterans of the Korean
War expected to descend upon the national memorial to those who
served there, in the shadow of the Lincoln Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, though, Clinton will pay homage to those
Americans who gave the supreme sacrifice to help turn back
communist aggression on the Korean peninsula. It's a salute, said
Taylor, that's well-deserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stopped the first major communist military offensive in the
post World War II world,'' said Taylor, who served in Korea in
1961. ``In the process, we have provided, since 1953, the backdrop
for the development and growth of a country that today is a
thriving democracy and a South Korea that has long been called an
economic miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   For Americans, he added, ``It has been a fair bargain.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   (Julie Chao's E-mail address is: juliec(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information on commemoration activities, see:
</P>
<P>
   U.S military Korea page:
</P>
<P>
   www.korea.army.mil/50anniv/index.htm
</P>
<P>
   Korean War Commemoration Committee:
</P>
<P>
   www.koreanwar.go.kr/
</P>
