<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Surviving takes skills in real life
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Perhaps the most pointed critique of the
``Survivor'' phenomenon comes from none other than the real-life
Gilligan: ``I wouldn't go on that island even for a million
dollars,'' said Bob Denver, from the safety of his West Virginia
home. ``I don't eat rats.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor, apparently, does he like to associate with them.
</P>
<P>
   What's so appalling about ``Survivor'' is not the
much-ballyhooed complaint that we have become a nation of voyeurs _
hey, it's not as if we're spying on anybody's actual lives here _
but its mean-spiritedness. In an unholy marriage of ``Deliverance''
and junior high school, competitors are encouraged to work as a
team _ and, if they fail, to ``vote'' each other out of their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, CBS camera crews coax contestants to bad-mouth
each other behind their backs: ``I don't think Ramona is pulling
her weight;'' ``I'm going to vote Stacey off because I don't like
her and I never will.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Farley, past president of the American Psychological
Association made a dead-on observation when he told USA Today:
``This is intentional public humiliation. They drum you out,
blackmail people. It is so destructive, so negative. After
thousands of years of great ideas, of thinking we are rising up
from a primitive past to a higher place, then we get this.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked one of our most well-mannered Daytonians, Betty Darst,
what she thought of the show. ``Sounds as though we are going back
to the days of the Roman Coliseum,'' said the Beavercreek woman.
</P>
<P>
   Well-known locally for her portrayals of the Wright brothers'
sister, Katharine, and Greene County pioneer Becky Galloway, Darst
spends a lot of time, figuratively speaking, in an era of more
refined manners: ``These people had courage and leadership and
talent for nurturing other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Becky Galloway's father used to say: ``You can judge what's
important to a person by what they bring over by covered wagon,''
Darst said. ``In the Galloways' case it was more than 750 books.''
</P>
<P>
   What does ``Survivor'' say about what we value _ and don't value
_ in our society?
</P>
<P>
   No, the problem isn't voyeurism, despite this week's Time
magazine cover story, ``Voyeur TV: We Like to Watch,'' complete
with a fetching photo of a contestant in her pink bikini. These
are, after all, artificial situations set up to be spied on. I
suspect CBS would consider it downright rude if we didn't.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is the winner-versus-loser mentality that permeates
every frame. The notion that we can best ``survive'' without each
other.
</P>
<P>
   Who wouldn't, on any given day, ``vote'' someone out of our
lives?
</P>
<P>
   The boss makes you late for your anger-management session? Cast
her away.
</P>
<P>
   The 4-year-old refuses to put his shoes on during the frantic
morning rush hour, when tempers snap like toothpicks? Kick him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' offers the Jerry Springer solution to all that ails
us _ just humiliate those closest to you. Cut them out of the will.
Cut them out of your life. And cut them down while you're at it.
</P>
<P>
   Real life, of course, works just the opposite. With time and
trials, we vote ourselves off our private island of
self-absorption. We evolve from the social hierarchy of junior high
school and develop the skills we truly need to survive in the adult
world: Compromise. Teamwork. Compassion.
</P>
<P>
   All of which seem in scant supply on Pulau Tiga. The Survivors,
many of them, seem trapped in that worst of all tropical hells:
adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   I'll cast my lot with Gilligan: The best hope for us castaways
is to stick together.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
