<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Risk is no surprise to sportswriters
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTEVILLE, Ga. _ Pardon me, but I can't get all worked up
over John Rocker's confrontation with the Sports Illustrated writer
in Turner Field. Having been a sportswriter in an earlier life, I
thought those things came with the territory.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Van Brocklin was the Atlanta Falcons coach newspaper
writer Furman Bisher deftly introduced to Atlanta as ``Hitler with
a hangover.'' The Dutchman, more mildly described as ``volatile,''
once interrupted dinner by grabbing the Atlanta Journal's Frank
Hyland by the throat in an attempt to strangle him for something he
had written. On another occasion he challenged Ron Hudspeth to
``stack chairs'' and duke it out in barroom fashion.
</P>
<P>
   When I was covering the Falcons, Van Brocklin and I had several
stimulating conversations in the bowels of old Atlanta Stadium.
There were no witnesses, but I wouldn't have minded five or six. I
was impressed by the story about him strolling down Seventh Avenue
in New York and pausing to stuff NFL Commissioner Pete Rozelle into
a trash can.
</P>
<P>
   Professional athletes usually are big, strong and aggressive. If
you don't get it fairly right and reasonably fair there is a
possibility of bodily harm. That's why sportswriters, like
paratroopers and jet pilots, often get paid more than reporters who
cover the symphony.
</P>
<P>
   Every newspaper reporter or editor should be required to serve a
tour on a sports beat. The definition of editorial writers as
people who ride down into the valley after the battle and shoot the
wounded isn't all wrong. It's one thing to sit in a newspaper
office, several floors up, firing bazookas out the window at
targets as far away as Washington. It's something else to go
face-to-face in stadium tunnels with big, strong and aggressive
subjects who generally are neither Phi Beta Kappas nor candidates
for diplomatic postings.
</P>
<P>
   I'm indebted to Lee Walburn, the current editor of Atlanta
Magazine, for one of my tedious moments in sports. Lee, another
alumnus of the Furman Bisher School of Journalism, was, in one of
his incarnations, chief publicist for the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Giants had been in town. The Giants had a
particular distaste for Atlanta sportswriters. We suspected it was
because of Willie Mays' jealousy of Hank Aaron, who, besides
hitting all those home runs, was a respected gentleman who never
threatened a sportswriter with anything more lethal than a thrown
strawberry.
</P>
<P>
   I avoided baseball assignments, largely because watching
baseball before October is about as exciting as watching okra
sprout. Any game I was forced to cover went into extra innings,
which knocked out any chance of watching Johnny Carson.
</P>
<P>
   I had been unable to wiggle out of going to the stadium to do
what we called a sidebar on the Giants. A sidebar is a feature
story that fills up space around the game story.
</P>
<P>
   After the Giants left town, Walburn, who never passed up a
chance to make mischief, called to say the Giants didn't like what
I had written and were saying I better not show up at the stadium
the next time they came to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   About a week before the Giants were due back, Walburn called
again. ``You remember what they said about you not showing up,'' he
said. ``You aren't going to let them get away with that, are you?''
</P>
<P>
   I would have been perfectly happy not to show up, but under
Walburn's prodding I agreed to uphold the honor of Atlanta
sportswriters.
</P>
<P>
   I knew I would have a problem with Herman Franks, the Giants'
crusty manager. Herman had all the qualifications of a mid-20th
century baseball manager. He could cuss, chew tobacco, spit and
scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Sportswriters assigned to do sidebars have to go on the field
before games and ask questions about sore arms, pitching rotations,
batting slumps and all that stuff. When writers interviewed Franks,
his tactic throughout the conversation was to spit tobacco juice
into the dirt around their feet. Although he was a very accurate
spitter, the little wet plops narrowly missing your shoes were
disconcerting.
</P>
<P>
   In my early years on the farm, I had some experience with
chewing tobacco. I had studied the techniques of expert spitters
who spent winter afternoons sitting around the potbellied stove in
Mr. Marvin Lamb's store, peppering the sandbox. In anticipation of
my encounter with Franks, I bought a six-pack of Red Man. Without
my wife's knowledge, I slipped into the back yard each night after
supper to practice chewing and spitting.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants were back in town. We were standing between third and
home plate. Franks zeroed in on my right foot, I fired back at his
left. The infield dirt around us rolled up in spent spitballs. The
contest must have lasted 10 minutes, until we both ran dry. Walburn
claimed I won. More likely it was a draw. Either way, many people
consider the spitting contest with Herman Franks in Atlanta Stadium
the highlight of my checkered career in journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Postscript: After Norm Van Brocklin was no longer coach of the
Falcons and I was no longer a sportswriter we became good friends.
It's wise to remember that in these things the best of us usually
aren't all good, and the worst of us usually aren't all bad.
</P>
<P>
   To contact Jim Minter, write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, 692 N. Glynn St., Suite A, Fayetteville, GA
30214.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
