<HEADER>
A2569 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD0624-CO     06-23 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD0624-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    Love of woodcraft shouldn't exceed common sense
 &HT;    Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There tends to be a great deal of romance surrounding
any ancient craft such as woodworking or pottery.
</P>
<P>
   This is all well and good, but a woodworker needs to recognize
it for what it is and not get too bound up in it.
</P>
<P>
   It's usually at its strongest in the beginning stages of
experience, and when coupled with the natural urge to save a buck,
it can lead to a lot of misfortune.
</P>
<P>
   This is all brought to mind by a post to an Internet woodworking
group by a man who just bought an old house and is getting into
woodworking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old guy who lived there before me was a tinkerer and he
kept everything, especially wood. Well, I have these two pieces
that are about 3 by 11 inches and 7 or 8 feet long. It's some kind
of hard wood. I want to use it for a work bench, as he did, but
they are all beat up. They have gouges, holes and some nails.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to clean these boards up, but I don't know the best
way. I would like to take them someplace and have them planed down
on all sides, but there are nails in there that I can't get to.
Will a shop still do this, with the possibility of screwing up
their cutters? Can I do this myself with the aforementioned tools
(radial saw, cheap table saw and bandsaw)?''
</P>
<P>
   My friend, let it go. There's lots of hard wood (he means really
hard hardwood) around that doesn't have nails in it.
</P>
<P>
   You might find a millwork shop willing to clean up those boards
if you agree to pay for any damage to their machine. Since you seem
pretty sure they're going to encounter a nail, then you can count
on paying up. If they're as bad as you indicate, you'll probably
pay up several times.
</P>
<P>
   By the time you're through paying for what those boards might
have spent enough to build a whole workbench out of cocobolo, and
be the envy of everyone on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the boards didn't have nails in them, working wood this
old is no fun. The stuff is terribly hard on sawblades and any
other edged tool. It produces a very fine dust that can drive you
crazy. You can get Z into it, if you need screws, only with great
difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   T'aint worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Next comes an interesting question from a man who needs ``to
apply pressure to a sheet of plastic that measures approximately 8
inches square. The plastic is approximately 1/16 of an inch thick.
The plastic will be heated to approximately 250 degrees F while a
curing process completes, which will take approximately 10 minutes.
Only a few pounds of pressure per square inch will be needed, not
much more than you could apply by hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to ensure that the pressure is applied evenly across
the surface of the plastic.'' I'd try to rig up something like a
simple veneer press. Take a couple of pieces of good 3/4-inch
plywood, preferably Baltic birch or Appleply, get a clamp with at
least a 4-inch throat _ the simple wooden European clamps would be
adequate _ sandwich the metal-clad plastic between the plywood and
apply pressure in the dead center of the sandwich. Just make sure
the metal is perfectly flat.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
