<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Saturday, June 24 and Sunday, June 25,
2000 are moving today to clients of the New York Times News
Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL-BOYS - Is the Central Park fiasco just a case of boys
being boys. If so, what's wrong with our boys? (The Atlanta
Constitution). 8.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN - WACO, Texas - ATLANTA - The inscription on the
Statue of Liberty that encourages the world's huddled masses to
become American citizens should be considered a historic curiosity,
not an immigration policy. (Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of
the Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ Professional athletes usually are big, strong
and aggressive. That's why sportswriters, like paratroopers and jet
pilots, often get paid more than reporters who cover the symphony.
(Jim Minter is a former editor of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN - DAYTON, Ohio - Perhaps the most pointed
critique of the ``Survivor'' phenomenon comes from none other than
the real-life Gilligan: ``I wouldn't go on that island even for a
million dollars,'' said Bob Denver, from the safety of his West
Virginia home. ``I don't eat rats.''(McCarty, Dayton Daily News).
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Tom Teepen says that when the Supreme Court was
called on to referee between two powerful religions, the justices
wisely chose to shield high school football in Texas from
gratuitous Christian praying. (Tom Teepen is national correspondent
for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Howard Kleinberg says Kayhleen Turner could
have kept her clothes on and the London theatrical version of the
1967 film ``The Graduate'' would have been just as good as it was
with her unclothed and in the shadows for 20 seconds. (Kleinberg,
Cox News Service.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ Recent advances in miniature radio technology
make it possible for people to have smart cards that embed their
medical and insurance history on a chip. The medical card could
then be ``read'' when you visited your doctor's office or a
hospital emergency room. (Andy Glass is a columnist for Cox News
Service in the Washington bureau.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
