<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Saturday, June 24
and Sunday, June 25, 2000, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   AUTOMOTIVE NEWS
</P>
<P>
   GRANDAM-REVIEW _ A review of the Pontiac Grand Am. (DeVault,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ ATLANTA _There tends to be a great deal of
romance surrounding any ancient craft such as woodworking or
pottery. This is all well and good, but a woodworker needs to
recognize it for what it is and not get too bound up in it. It's
usually at its strongest in the beginning stages of experience, and
when coupled with the natural urge to save a buck, it can lead to a
lot of misfortune. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GLIDERS _ Five minutes after takeoff, when we reach 3,000 feet
in a pristine sky, glider pilot Rich Carraway releases the line
from the tow plane and banks our two-seater sailplane gently to the
north _ free, as the poet said, of the surly bonds of earth.
Nothing but the wind whispering now around our clear plastic
canopy. We're in a peaceful bubble floating over a checkerboard of
Warren County farms and forests just a few miles east of Caesar
Creek Lake. Even for a shameless wuss like myself, who has a
paralyzing fear of heights, my 20-minute ride as a guest passenger
with the Caesar Creek Soaring Club was as gentle and agreeable as
many of the club's 200-plus members. (Dayton Daily News). 27. WITH
PHOTOS. FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   HOWARD-FINSTER _ SUMMERVILLE, Ga. _ Word was out that the Rev.
Howard Finster, the godfather of saving souls, the hardest working
man in the folk art business, had been seriously sick. So the
faithful flocked to Paradise Garden, his wild 3-acre folk version
of the Garden of Eden, during last month's Howard Finster Fest, a
show and sale that offered a thoroughly mixed bag of 60 artists but
only one Howard. With the ailing 83-year-old artist recovering from
double pneumonia and congestive heart failure and battling
diabetes, many visitors worried it might be the last chance to see
Finster, get his autograph, hear one of his classic sermonettes.
And, some feared, it might be the final opportunity to visit
Paradise. (Pousner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 77. WITH PHOTOS.
FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GEHRY-MUSICPROJECT _ SEATTLE _ Architect of the hour Frank Gehry
has projects all over the world. His latest since Bilbao is
something called Experience the Music project in Seattle, paid for
by Microsoft millionaire Paul Allen. Main story will wrap up
history and a review of the building. (Fox, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 36. FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   PRESBYTERIAN-ASSEMBLY _ Presbyterians open their general
assembly the weekend of June 24, 25 in Long Beach, Calif., facing
some of the same sticky issues about gay relationships that are
troubling other denominations. (White, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 10.
</P>
<P>
   SALVATION-ARMY _ ATLANTA _ The international congress of the
Salvation Army is meeting in Atlanta _ its first time ever in North
America. One reason is probably that the Army already has a large
presence here _ a training center in South Atlanta and a temple on
North Druid Hills Road. Through the lives of a couple of officers
and site visits, we profile the Army here and look ahead to the
conference that will bring thousands of soldiers for Jesus from all
over the world. (GWhite, Atlanta Journal-Coinstitution). 35.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SALARMY-OVERVIEW _ ATLANTA _ The Salvation Army is known
worldwide for its efforts to help the needy. We offer an overview
of international and local efforts, plus a detailed listing of
programs and how people can contribute time and/or money. (Henry,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
