<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2574 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN0624-C     06-23 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN0624-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Suggestion that U.S. take steps to limit influx might not be a
bad idea
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The inscription on the Statue of Liberty that
encourages the world's huddled masses to become American citizens
should be considered a historic curiosity, not an immigration
policy.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way I read an opinion piece in the Washington Post by
two crusty old politicians worried that America's quality of life
is deteriorating in proportion to population growth.
</P>
<P>
   The double authors of the June 20 article are Alan K. Simpson,
the former cowboy senator from Wyoming, and Richard D. Lamm, the
former governor of Colorado. Simpson is a Republican and Lamm is a
Democrat. That makes the warning about the dangers of large-scale
immigration a bipartisan effort, for whatever that's worth.
</P>
<P>
   Other than their party affiliations, the two men have a lot in
common. They both come from America's West, which includes a
certain shared mindset for citizens who reside from the Great
Plains up to, but not including, the masses of Americans huddled
along the Pacific coast.
</P>
<P>
   Both men were political mavericks capable of ignoring for New
York Mayor Fiorello LaGuardia's advice: ``A politician can't be so
far ahead of the band that he can't hear the music.''
</P>
<P>
   Simpson, who now is director of the Institute of Politics at
Harvard University's John F. Kennedy School of Government, and
Lamm, who now is director of the Center for Public Policy and
Contemporary Issues at the University of Denver, show that they
continue to march to their own internal drummers far ahead of the
band.
</P>
<P>
   EITHER WRONG OR FAR AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   That does not necessarily mean that their ideas on immigration,
the environment, public health, urban congestion and the rest are
wrong; it may mean that it's going to take time for the rest of the
country to catch up with them.
</P>
<P>
   The two men warn that new census figures show a population of
571 million Americans by the year 2100. The doubling of America's
population, the men write, is a projection, not an inevitability.
</P>
<P>
   Actions taken by Americans today can avoid the problems caused
by the projected population explosion, according to Simpson and
Lamm. Those problems will include the burdens placed on the
nation's health care system, schools, environment, parks, housing,
highways and all the other structures of society.
</P>
<P>
   If American women continue to average two children in a
lifetime, as they do now, the nation's population will stabilize in
the middle of the next century. The projected doubling of the
America's population by the next century will come from
immigration, which is something that can be controlled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question immigration has been good for America, and of
course we are all immigrants, directly or indirectly,'' Simpson and
Lamm write. ``But the challenge of public policy is to recognize
when circumstances change _ when, as the poet warns, `time makes
ancient good uncouth.'''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the words on the base of the Statue of Liberty
were valid back when our young country was trying to settle a new
land, but not necessarily valid today.
</P>
<P>
   The mighty woman with a torch who stands in New York harbor is
named ``Mother of Exiles,'' according to Emma Lazarus' famous poem
engraved on the pedestal below the statue.
</P>
<P>
   The part of the poem that has guided America's immigration
policy says: ``Give me your tired, your poor, your huddled masses
yearning to breathe free, the wretched refuse of your teeming
shore. Send these, the homeless, tempest-tost to me, I lift up my
lamp beside the golden door!''
</P>
<P>
   These two crusty Westerners warn that without tighter controls
on America's immigration policies, it will be this country's
huddled masses who will yearn to breathe free.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
