<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2579 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-LATHAM-COLUMN24-COX     06-23 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What choice would you make if you could only have 2 books?
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We'll call it Jane's Decision, because I don't know her real
name. I only know her story.
</P>
<P>
   The story came to me through the Internet which, I suppose,
might make it suspect in the eyes of some. After all, anything can
be said on the Internet, right? Indeed, I have no way to know for
certain whether this is fact or fiction.
</P>
<P>
   My senses, though, lead me to believe it is fact. For one thing,
it is difficult to make up stories this good or this touching.
Either way it hardly matters. As a novelist friend of mine once
told me, it is easier to to tell the truth with fiction than with
non-fiction. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   Jane made her decision years ago and she was nothing more than a
child, under 10 years old at the time. It wasn't something she
wanted to do, but ultimately either she would have made a decision
or it would have been made for her. Sometimes children have to make
adult decisions. Sometimes it is adults who force them to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Such it was with Jane, whose mother announced one day _ this
would have been in the '60s, naturally _ that the family was
selling the house and moving. Under ordinary circumstances, this
could have been an exciting time, if somewhat scary. These were not
ordinary circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Because the family wasn't going to buy another house. No, they
were going to see the world, be children of the universe: The
mother and step-father bought a bus.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds faintly amusing, doesn't it? Just to hear it like that
you get a feeling for the absurd, but nothing that might be truly
damaging.
</P>
<P>
   Until you consider logistics. When one lives in a bus, travels
and eats in a bus, does everything in a bus, logistics is pretty
much everything.
</P>
<P>
   Logistics landed on Jane's head the day her mother told her that
certain things would have to be cut back if everything was to fit
on the bus.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Jane's books were, well, a nuisance. They didn't
fit in the plans. After all, she had between 300 and 400 books, a
library she had built from books given to her since birth.
</P>
<P>
   Jane was willing to do her part. She could get rid of some of
the books. Truth to tell, some of them were pretty raggedy anyway.
</P>
<P>
   So Jane's question was: How many can I keep?
</P>
<P>
   Her mother's answer was: Two.
</P>
<P>
   Two?
</P>
<P>
   Two.
</P>
<P>
   Those who own more than a few books can begin to appreciate
Jane's Decision. Think of owning 300 and having to dispose of all
but two in the space of just a few days.
</P>
<P>
   She pleaded with her mother to let her keep more, but there was
only so much room on the bus. The books would have to go, sold in a
yard sale.
</P>
<P>
   And so Jane made her decision, book by book, agonizing choice by
choice. Characters whose lives she'd never hold in her hands again.
</P>
<P>
   So you're probably wondering which two books did she choose to
keep?
</P>
<P>
   One was ``Black Beauty'' that had been a scruffy copy when she
first got it, a hand-me-down but a book she purely loved.
</P>
<P>
   And the second book? A photo album that contained the only
picture she had of her brother who died when she was seven years
old.
</P>
<P>
   Two books. Jane's Decision had been both difficult and easy.
Difficult to cast the others aside, but an easy choice of which
ones to keep.
</P>
<P>
   From the item I received, Jane's library today is back near the
300 or 400-book range. Her tastes have changed, of course, but one
thing hasn't changed.
</P>
<P>
   In bookcase in her house, in a place of honor and safety there
are two books tucked aside. One is an ancient, but still readable,
copy of ``Black Beauty.'' The other isn't really a book at all, it
is a photo album with a very special picture inside.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know Jane, don't even know her real name, but I'm
guessing that should that terrible choice have to come again, the
decision would be exactly the same.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall, Texas News
Messenger. His email address is platham(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
