<HEADLINE>
DOWSING ON MARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reports that water may have flowed on Mars bring closer the
answer to the much more tantalizing question of whether some form
of primitive life may have developed there. It is a question that,
by itself, justifies the efforts of NASA and other space programs
to explore Earth's fascinating neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   That water has been present on Mars in the past, in large
quantities, had become generally accepted in the scientific
community. Long stretches of beachlike terrain are taken as
evidence of lakes or even oceans that have long since dried up. But
photographic surveys by the Mars Global Surveyor have spotted
evidence of water flows on steep slopes that may be much newer, an
indication that water might still exist fairly close to the
surface. It may have been drawn from relatively shallow reservoirs
secure from a harsh environment that could not retain the earlier
abundance of water.
</P>
<P>
   Space programs that envision human visits to Mars will gain
plausibility if there is water on the planet. It could serve the
human need for water and, by electrolysis, be broken down into
hydrogen and oxygen to fuel voyages back to Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The greater interest, on a scientific scale, is in discovering
whether some form of life developed. On Earth, primitive life forms
apparently began in oceans still being rocked by deep-water
volcanic activity. Even today, ocean vents have been host to simple
types of life, suggesting that it can begin under difficult
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, evidence of past life on Mars would reinforce
theories that life throughout the universe would not only be
possible but likely wherever water and an even slightly
accommodating environment are found. With the detection of other
planetary systems _ albeit of a very different character than our
own _ evidence is mounting to support that speculation.
</P>
<P>
   The Mars Global Surveyor has balanced some of the disappointment
of losing two other Mars probes last year. Its success, and the
promise of being able to learn much more, call for persistence in
pursuing the program despite its setbacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
