   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-EXECUTIONS (Austin, Texas) _ Knocked by death penalty
protesters while on the presidential campaign trail, Texas Gov.
George W. Bush has vowed to uphold the state's capital punishment
law even if it costs him politically. Experts say it is unlikely to
cost him very much. By PEGGY FIKAC.
</P>
<P>
   FACTORY-MURDERS (San Leandro, Calif.) _ Jean Hillery was a
grandmother of four and master swimmer who volunteered to teach
young kids at a local pool near her Alameda, Calif., home. Thomas
Quadros of Hayward, Calif., was an avid Red Sox fan and golfer who
helped build a skateboard park last year. Bill Shaline, a father of
three from Sacramento, Calif., loved his job of more than 30 years.
The three investigators, together having more than 60 years of
experience working to ensure meat safety, were gunned down
Wednesday at a San Leandro sausage factory. By KATHERINE SELIGMAN.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FIGHTER-JETS (San Antonio) _ With the advent of the turbojet
engine to power fighter planes, aerial combat never would be the
same. The two jets most often associated with Korea are the F-86
and the MiG-15, and the fast and agile Sabrejet in time ruled the
sky, earning an 8-to-1 kill ratio, said the Air Force's Pentagon
historian, Dick Hallion. By SIG CHRISTENSON.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-PARADE (San Francisco) _ If size matters, San Francisco's
30th annual Gay Pride Parade on Sunday is the biggest in the world,
with 220 contingents and half a million to three-quarters of a
million people taking part or watching. Once again this year, it
promises to induce gasps, laughter, tears and some yawns with its
four hours of political courage and sheer outrageousness. By CAROL
NESS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCE (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-FORD-TRUCK (San Antonio) _ After a few minutes _ no,
actually, just a few seconds _ behind the wheel of the Ford F-150
SVT Lightning pickup, this week's test drive, I was glad of two
things. One: That it is not often that I get vehicles like this to
test drive, otherwise I would get into trouble. And two: That there
was no traffic cop riding behind me when I goosed the gas the first
time. By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-IRENE (Undated) _ Let's get right to the disclaimer.
The following people may be offended by ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene'' :
African-Americans, lesbians, animal lovers, the disabled, midgets,
parents, albinos, Germans, members of Mensa and anyone with good
taste. In other words, there's something for everybody in the new
comedy from brothers Peter and Bobby Farrelly (``Kingpin,''
``There's Something About Mary''), who have built a career on
grossing out audiences. By KRIS WORRELL.
</P>
<P>
   MARC-ANTHONY (San Antonio) _ While the Latino music explosion
has been much talked about, salsa/pop singer Marc Anthony says that
his English-language, self-titled pop CD was not a radical step for
him. By RAMIRO BURR.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-CHICKEN (Undated) _ Speaking frankly, here, the
chickens in ``Chicken Run'' don't look all that chickeny. Their
beaks are rubbery. Their cans are bell-shaped. They have teeth. And
they're accessorized scarves, pearls, Coke-bottle glasses, cute
little beanies. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RUN-OLYMPICS (Eugene, Ore.) _ With the temperature of the track
season about to go from lukewarm to lava-hot, it says here that
Marion Jones, Michael Johnson and Maurice Greene are three points
of a triangulated star system in U.S. track and field. For that,
the country should be thankful. By JOHN CRUMPACKER.
</P>
<P>
   REDFISH (Aransas Pass, Texas) _ Rats to bulls, there's nothing
like redfish fishing on the flats in the summertime. The bronzed
and brawny heavyweights spend the first years of life cruising the
shallow bay waters, rooting crabs from the sea grass, smacking gold
spoons, popping leaders, breaking hearts. Early in life, redfish
are called rats, or rat-reds. The name is not derogatory. Rather,
it denotes fish under the 20-inch minimum legal possession length
set by the state. Any redfish too small to be kept legally is a
rat. By RON STRAIT.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WONG-COLUMN (Piedmont, Calif.) _ It may not be obvious, but
football star Steve Young's retirement announcement and the New
York Central Park assaults have something in common _ male bonding.
The Young event showed male bonding at its sweetest and gentlest.
The New York incident was male bonding at its most vile.
Nonetheless, both high-profile occurrences reminded the world that
men commune with one another in ways that subordinate women. By
WILLIAM WONG.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-PRESIDENT (Taipei, Taiwan) _ I sat and watched the man at
the podium, acutely aware that he could involve his country _ and
ours _ in a nasty, perhaps nuclear, Asian war. He is the new and
freely elected president of the Republic of China, also known as
Taiwan. By HENRY E. CATTO JR.
</P>
