<HEADER>
A2621 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-FRANKEL-PRIVACY-CENTE     06-23 1324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANKEL-PRIVACY-CENTERPIECE-ADV25-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV25 
 WORD &AMP; IMAGE: TRUTH IN SURFING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 25, or thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's CENTERPIECE news service. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of CENTERPIECE _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.) 
 By MAX FRANKEL  
 c.2000 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I can foresee the e-junk-mail of the next Internet generation:
``Dear Joe: We know you like adult movies, but we also know you
have never seen sex like this. Keep this sample with our
compliments and sign up for a weekly treat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Mary: We heard your chat room complaint about the apple
cake crust. Next time try our pie plate and special mix. Just click
here and be the star of your next church bazaar!''
</P>
<P>
   Because they can't find the word ``privacy'' in the
Constitution, our courts, from the Supremes on down, are refusing
to help consumers fend off horrendous intrusions into personal
life. And so the Internet is fast becoming a giant spy network that
gathers and peddles a record of what we read, write, watch, think
and buy to make us ever more precise targets of unsolicited ads,
mail and marketing ploys.
</P>
<P>
   The technology of intrusion now infests virtually every Web
page, browser, e-mail message and chat room, and it relentlessly
tracks our individual movements, interests, moods and even
keystrokes. As a result there is a multivolume cyberarchive
matching up tens of millions of names, addresses, ages and personal
characteristics with the books and underwear we bought, the stocks
we sold, the music we downloaded and the cancer facts we once
pursued.
</P>
<P>
   Huge sums are being spent to harvest these nuggets of
information and to bundle them for delivery to both online and
off-line advertisers and merchants. The Big Brother industry, like
most Web enterprises, is not yet earning big bucks, but it is
betting that customized and fancy new Internet imagery will invade
our minds to much greater effect than the catalogs and junk mail
that have long filled our mailboxes.
</P>
<P>
   In time, the courts may wise up, but by then we may all be not
only cataloged but also palm-printed and even facially digitized.
Too many judges are failing to recognize the urgent need to balance
the First and Fourth Amendments, the rights of corporate free
speech against the right of people to ``be secure in their persons,
houses, papers and effects.''
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, the Supreme Court refused even to hear an
appeal from the 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which struck
down a ruling of the Federal Communications Commission to limit US
West's use of information about its customers.
</P>
<P>
   The commission wanted the phone company to ask all customers to
consent to the release and ulterior use of personal information.
But the court stood by the company's weak offer to make people opt
out by withdrawing permission _ if they could find and decipher the
obscure instructions for doing so.
</P>
<P>
   As you can discover on the vast majority of Web sites, that
prepositional distinction between opting ``in'' and ``out'' marks
the difference between meaningful and disingenuous respect for
privacy. Web merchants have made a show of ``self-regulation'' by
posting lengthy and complicated statements of ``privacy policies,''
many of which permit diligent readers to withdraw from some lists
and warn them of intrusions by third parties.
</P>
<P>
   But in only a minority of cases _ like The New York Times Web
site _ is the language of these cautions unambiguous. And even when
clear, the warnings and instructions are not standardized; they
must be hunted down and mastered on every Web page you ever visit.
</P>
<P>
   Also like The Times' site, some major sites promise to use their
customer data only in an anonymous aggregate, to help advertisers
focus their messages and assess the results. But most ``policy''
statements are contradictory, hard to locate, subject to change and
lacking any mechanism for enforcement or redress.
</P>
<P>
   If the courts persist in thus favoring property over privacy,
the only real remedy is to write laws that will treat privacy as
valuable property. That is hardly a radical proposition.
</P>
<P>
   All of us regularly and knowingly trade our privacy for
commercial benefit. We accept phone calls at awkward moments for
the convenience of being connected. We volunteer our Visa card
numbers and leave a trail of our purchases for the comfort of
shopping from home. We leave a bar-coded menu of our favorite foods
for a quick supermarket checkout.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us have learned that the personal information we yield
has commercial value. It is property that the receivers routinely
sell to other merchants so that they can bombard us with
solicitations tailored to our surmised lifestyles. But atomized
consumers lack the power to command a decent price for this
informational property.
</P>
<P>
   When a pollster calls me to sample my political views or tastes
in food, I can refuse to answer unless he shares some of his fee.
But I cannot strike a deal with the anonymous spies that pursue me
online. If America's marketers really believed in a free market,
they would fully expose themselves and their data traffic and let
me decide whether the price is right.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of baiting me with offers of a ``free'' search engine,
e-mail and current stock quotes, Yahoo should be required when I
enter its site to define those services as payment for its right to
resell my identity and online habits to other merchants.
</P>
<P>
   The Times' Web site should explain up front that it is not
giving its news away without charge; it is bartering the news and
other services to learn about reader interests for the commercial
benefit of advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Upon entering an iWon.com lottery for millions of dollars, I
ought to be told which ``sponsors or business partners'' it says in
fine print will share in the registration information I supply. And
even if I keep watch, as instructed, for iWon policy changes, who
will police its partners?
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, we need laws, like those for truth in lending, to
regulate truth in surfing. Web sites should be required to adopt
standardized technologies to expose the full extent of their use of
personal information and to seek their customers' ``opt in''
consent. The same should be required of third parties who then buy
or share that information.
</P>
<P>
   And any change in the deal should require a new agreement. I may
welcome countless future offers that play to my interests, but I
want something of value in exchange for exposing myself to
strangers, for the burden on my computer and for the time I spend
sorting through the flood of e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   If what I tell you about myself has an ulterior market value
beyond our immediate Web transaction, I deserve to be told your
intentions, asked to approve and be acceptably paid.
</P>
<P>
   (Max Frankel is the former Washington Bureau chief, editorial
page editor and executive editor of The New York Times. He won a
Pulitzer Prize in 1973 and has been a correspondent in Eastern
Europe, Moscow and the Caribbean. Frankel now writes this ``Word &AMP;
Image'' column for The New York Times Magazine.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
