<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2637 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     06-23 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRAYER DECISION LEAVES QUESTIONS, NOT INDIGNATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Supreme Court decision handed down earlier this week
limiting prayer in the nation's public schools would have left me
deflated as recently as a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   But today, thanks to my own struggles _ personal and spiritual _
I don't feel that way. My mind is filled with the words of this
passage from the eighth chapter of Romans:
</P>
<P>
   ``And we know that all things work together for good to them
that love God, to them who are the called according to his
purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   And so I'm simply reminded that God is in control.
</P>
<P>
   Even six months ago I might have cursed the justices' decision,
would've joined the chorus of voices lamenting the moral state of
our society and the need for more prayer, particularly in our
schools. Instead, I hold fast to the fact that nothing in the
universe happens, has ever happened, except when God allows it.
</P>
<P>
   That might be a difficult truth to accept if you're of the mind
that what just occurred was tragic, that being good and perfect,
God could not possibly allow such a decision when we're clearly
admonished to acknowledge him ``in all our ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends of mine who could not care less about prayer or praying
have noted that God could not care less about the outcome of a
sporting event.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe my friends are right. Maybe what God really cares about is
not the score but how we win; not how high we climb the corporate
ladder but how we treat the people we meet on our way up; whether
we took the time to acknowledge him in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   I'm reminded of the message of the Roman centurion in the book
of Luke, the subject of my Sunday school lesson on Father's Day.
</P>
<P>
   As the story goes, the centurion was a man of authority, the
commander of a hundred soldiers. If he told one of them to go, they
went. If he told one to come, he came. And if he told another to
``do this,'' he did it.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, the story said, when he wanted Jesus to heal his
servant, he didn't let his status keep him from admitting he needed
Jesus' help.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's all prayer is, admitting we need God to
accomplish life's goals, no matter how big or small we are or how
big or small the problem is.
</P>
<P>
   What I know from personal experience is that when I pray and
truly turn my fears and problems over to God, he answers. Sometimes
the answer is immediate and definitive, and other times I've had to
teeter between uncertainty and impatiently waiting.
</P>
<P>
   But over and over again, God has proved his faithfulness and is
still working things to my good. That's hard to see when you're
hurting, when you feel like the world is against you. And depending
on your vantage point, it can be difficult to see God's hand in
last Monday's Supreme Court ruling regarding school-sanctioned
prayer.
</P>
<P>
   I can't explain it. God's thoughts are higher than mine. He
tells us clearly, for instance, in Deuteronomy 29:29 that, ``The
secret things belong unto the Lord our God.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people, particularly Christians, see the Supreme Court's
ruling as nothing more than hostility toward religion. I see it as
another way for him to get our attention, to make good on his
promises.
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, the court's ruling isn't a curse at all. It's a
blessing.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7791, or e-mail:
gstaples(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
