<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2643 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GUNS-INTERNET-0625-CO     06-23 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-INTERNET-0625-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   GROUPS FEAR INTERNET BECOMING ``VIRTUAL GUN SHOW''
</P>
<P>
   For Use Sun. June 25 And Thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   By EUNICE MOSCOSO
</P>
<P>
   C.2000 COX NEWS SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Internet is quickly becoming a gun-owner's
dream market. Hundreds of sites offer everything from custom
holsters to Colt revolvers _ many at discount prices.
</P>
<P>
   No driving to a store. No trade show fee. Unbelievable
selection.
</P>
<P>
   While gun collectors and dealers hail this new branch of
E-commerce, it's making gun control groups increasingly nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, the Internet is becoming a virtual gun show,'' said
Kristen Rand, director of federal policy for the Violence Policy
Center, a group that supports gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Rand said the Web is creating a national market that facilitates
interstate gun sales. This defies ``the bedrock of gun regulation
in America'' which is to keep sales within each state in an effort
to control distribution and access, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, gun control advocates say regulations on Internet
sales are not carefully monitored and that many sites, which merely
hook up buyers and sellers, have no obligation to abide by the
rules that regulate gun dealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone can set up an Internet site that sells guns,'' Rand
said. ``They can sell a million guns over a site and the owner of
the site would be under no duty to get a federal firearms
license.''
</P>
<P>
   Some big online auction houses, including eBay, have decided to
refuse gun trade, but there are still an estimated 80 auction sites
devoted to firearms and about 4,000 sites that have gun sales.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon has added another dimension to what are called
``secondary markets'' for guns, which previously included gun shows
and private sales, often through classified ads. These secondary
markets _ which account for an estimated 40 percent of sales _ have
long been the target of gun control proponents.
</P>
<P>
   But comparing online sales to gun shows and private sales isn't
fair, says Dale Blankenship, who owns and operates dalesguns.com _
an Internet site that he started about two years ago, to supplement
his home-based business in Powhatan, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand how they come up with that,'' he said. ``I
think Internet is the safest.''
</P>
<P>
   Blankenship, who has worked in gun repair and sales for 17
years, said that the problem at gun shows has to do with unlicensed
dealers. On the Internet, regulations call for any firearm
transaction to take place through a dealer with a federal license,
which requires a background check.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people get real confused... they think I can just
sell to anybody,'' he said. ``I can't deliver (a firearm) to
anybody except another dealer.''
</P>
<P>
   If a private individual wants to buy a gun on the Internet, they
must do it through a dealer, who charges the buyer a small fee.
Sellers require the buyer to send a photocopy of the federal
license bearing a fresh signature.
</P>
<P>
   But sellers are not required to call the Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms to verify that a name or address on a license
is valid, although the regulation says dealers may investigate
further if they wish.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control proponents say these regulations are loosely
enforced and easy to circumvent.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, two high school students in Montclaire, N.J.,
figured it out.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the 17-year-olds passed themselves off as dealers,
after persuading a Florida gun dealer to give them his license
number on an online chat room.
</P>
<P>
   They used the number to forge a license and used it to purchase
at least four handguns through an Atlanta, Ga.-based site,
GunBroker.com. Federal licenses are about the size of a car title
and don't carry a photograph.
</P>
<P>
   Blankenship said he didn't know if he could spot a fake license
but added, ``I think I would be able to tell. I hope I would.''
</P>
<P>
   Gun control advocates say another flaw in the Internet gun trade
is that the dealer can't see the customer face to face.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a customer comes in person, a dealer might be able to
look at someone and ask: Does this person look underage? Does this
person look like he is clearly intoxicated or mentally deranged?
Over the Internet, you can't tell. You can't see at all,'' said
David Bernstein, spokesperson for Handgun Control, Inc., a
Washington-based lobby group.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Blankenship said that when someone walks into his
business to buy a gun, he can't deny them a sale because of their
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I legally can't say: 'Hey you don't look right,''' he said,
adding that he won't sell anyone a gun until they pass a background
check required by law.
</P>
<P>
   The growing trend of Internet gun sales has caught the attention
of state and federal law enforcement agencies. The push for
regulations will likely increase as more buyers turn to the Web.
Some sites are already making millions in sales. The Atlanta-based
GunBroker.com is projecting $12 million in sales by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the booming E-commerce, the ATF is considering
starting a unit to investigate firearms and explosives sales on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In Illinois, Attorney General Jim Ryan has launched a new
initiative to target illegal gun sales online and at gun shows.
House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., is backing a request from
Ryan for an $ 850,000 federal grant to create a special unit to
investigate and prosecute such cases.
</P>
<P>
   In the U.S. Senate, an amendment that would have prohibited
unlicensed dealers from selling guns over the Internet was defeated
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., who introduced the measure, said
he is revising pending gun control legislation to require online
verification of licensees. But such a provision has little hope of
passage this year as several gun control measures have been stuck
in Congress for months.
</P>
<P>
   Rand said that delays in further regulation of Internet gun
sales could have tragic results.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a matter of time before something truly horrible
happens where someone got their weaponry over the Internet...It's
entirely predictable.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.vpc.org, www.handguncontrol.org,
</P>
<P>
   Eunice Moscoso can be reached by e-mail at
eunicem(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
