u s BC-GLF-LPGA-BOS &LR;      06-23 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KERRIGAN LEARNS FROM HER MISTAKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. _ Though the leaderboard would indicate
otherwise, the clock was not rolled back at the McDonald's LPGA
Championship. Instead, a veteran's favorite recipe _ tough
conditions and major championship nerves _ was rolled forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``When 1 under is on the board, or 2 under is on the board, it
just seems easier to look at,'' said Jane Geddes, who aced the
par-3 17th, shot 5-under-par 66, and assumed a one-shot lead after
the first round in this major championship at DuPont Country Club.
``You feel you can rise to the occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   Though she has been a stranger to leaderboards for several
years, the 40-year-old Geddes is familiar with the names behind
her.
</P>
<P>
   Like 49-year-old Pat Bradley, the pride of Westford, Mass., and
Betsy King, 44, who shot 68 to share second place with Tracy Hanson
and Gloria Park.
</P>
<P>
   Or 43-year-old Patty Sheehan, locked in a four-member group at
69.
</P>
<P>
   Or Jan Stephenson, 48, whose round of 70 put her even with
Annika Sorenstam, Laura Davies, and seven others.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was 43-year-old Beth Daniel in a 20-player logjam at
72 that featured Karrie Webb. Even the legendary JoAnne Carner,
still in love with golf at age 61, shot 73.
</P>
<P>
   Geddes, Bradley, King, Sheehan, Stephenson, Daniel, Carner.
Combined they have won 20 major championships, but in this yearlong
celebration of the LPGA Tour's 50th anniversary, the group
represents yesterday's glory (only King has posted a win in the
last three years) more than tomorrow's greatness. But that isn't to
say they can't enjoy today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of my best rounds in a long while, which is why I'm
so excited,'' said Bradley, who took a glance at the leaderboard
before her afternoon tee time and saw what Geddes had _ decent
scores, but not deep red ones. ``Over the years, my success has
been in tournaments like the majors (she's won six), where it's not
a putting contest, where players are 8 or 9 under after the first
round. When I saw that it was hovering around 1 or 2 or 3 under, I
said, `This is exactly what I need.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, like Geddes, is not filled with false hopes. She will
be the American Solheim Cup captain in October, so she's on Tour
this season as much to keep an eye on her potential team members as
to put up great scores. But don't think that a little pride isn't
burning inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get frustrated at myself because one minute I can play a
hole brilliantly, then the next minute make just a really stupid
mental mistake,'' said Bradley, who made very few miscues over a
DuPont CC course that played soft thanks to a torrential downpour
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The rain, said Bradley, was a blessing because the course had
played fast and hard during practice rounds and balls were
constantly rolling through pinched fairways and into thick rough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice, because people could be aggressive,'' said
Bradley, who went out on the back side and posted birdie-birdie,
then got to 3 under with a birdie at the 17th. A birdie at the
par-3 third got her to 4 under, but Bradley gave that stroke back
on the next hole before coming in with five straight pars and a
wide smile.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley hasn't tasted major victory since 1986 and Geddes has to
go back to 1987 for the second of her two major conquests, in this
event though not at this venue. Back then, said Geddes, ``I took it
for granted. I thought I was going to do it forever.''
</P>
<P>
   But forever ended in the late '80s for Geddes, who won five
times in 1987 then not again for four years. She has not won since
1994 and her blossoming Internet company has fueled thoughts of
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been putting a lot of pressure on myself, but I came here
with the goal in mind to have fun and enjoy this week,'' she said.
``It's a major, on a golf course I like, and whatever happens,
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   After a bogey on her fourth hole, the 13th, Geddes pouted and
was reminded of her pre-tournament philosophy by her caddie. It
must have worked because she went birdie-par-birdie-ace to get to 3
under.
</P>
<P>
   Shades of 1986 when she won the US Open? In a way, yes, because
``I like when pars are good scores. I generally play well when
courses are tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so tough that she couldn't finish with a 20-foot birdie putt
at the eighth hole (her 17th), then close with a sand wedge to 6
feet at the par-5 ninth that set up her fifth birdie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a ball today,'' said Geddes, whose best finish in 12
starts this year is a tie for 17th. ``It's been a long time since
I've had fun on the golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of her colleagues, those blasts from the past, were saying
the same thing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 1318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2669 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS     06-23 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPETITION SHOULDN'T STRIKE FEAR IN HEARTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They are relatives, baseball cousins who share a
similar view of history. They both watch their teams play in
ancient ballparks; both can interview parents, and in some cases
grandparents, who have never witnessed a World Series title; and if
you look into their eyes, you can sense that there is October
sadness tattooed on their souls.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the comparisons end between fans of the Red Sox and
Cubs. They are cousins, not siblings. No one in North America can
panic like a Sox fan. Rod Beck has pitched for both teams and has
noticed the major differences. In Chicago, he was a 9-to-5er
playing before afternoon crowds where fans ``enjoy the game, but
are very laid-back. If you actually win, it's considered a bonus.''
In Boston, the reliever has seen how winning is demanded, so much
so that there is audience uneasiness about a team in first place.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox defeated the Yankees Thursday night at Fenway Park,
4-2. Before the win, which resulted in a split of the four-game
series, the Sox were 11-18 in their previous 29 games. Because of
that Tigeresque streak (the pathetic baseball team, not the
precocious golfer), mournful wails can be heard throughout New
England. The chorus varies slightly: Get another starter. Get
another bat. Get Sammy. Get Juan. Get Moises. Get Bagwell.
</P>
<P>
   Get a grip.
</P>
<P>
   When the Sox go into their front yard and look at the homes of
their American League neighbors, they return to their living rooms
mumbling to themselves, ``You expect us to be worried about that?
Please.''
</P>
<P>
   They're right. It's one thing to have weaknesses, which the Sox
have. It's quite another to face someone who can exploit your
weaknesses and bring you to your knees. There is no such team in
the AL. But it's hard to think about that when it seems that your
team is flammable, one strong wind away from being singed for the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the team struggles, the fans' minds go back to history,''
Red Sox coach Tommy Harper said. He laughed and added, ``History
belongs to fans; games belong to the players. You know, I know
there are some fans who say, `Well, they win every time I go to the
game.' Or, `They win when I wear my green hat.' '' Harper pointed
to Nomar Garciaparra's locker and said, ``I think we win when he
wears a certain hat.''
</P>
<P>
   The hat Garciaparra wore Thursday was the hat he's been wearing
all season. It's a hitting hat. His average is now a
you've-got-to-be-making-this-up .396. Yankees manager Joe Torre
said pitching to the shortstop is like playing chess _ short of
relying on computerized chessmaster Deep Blue, there aren't a lot
of answers for Garciaparra, who is Bobby Fischer with a bat.
</P>
<P>
   Those who are skeptical of the Sox should go house hunting in
the AL neighborhood. Below are the seven-best dream homes in the
league:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO (46-26)
</P>
<P>
   Record vs. Sox: 1-2
</P>
<P>
   Conversation piece: Their best pitcher is a man named James
Baldwin, whose namesake was the most provocative American essayist
of the 20th century. The pitcher doesn't dazzle like the writer,
but he has the second-best ERA (3.56 to Pedro Martinez's 1.18) in
the AL. He also has 10 wins.
</P>
<P>
   Change-the-subject material: While Chicago has received
excellent pitching so far (second to the Red Sox), their top three
starters after Baldwin are Cal Eldred, Jim Parque, and Mike
Sirotka.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND (42-29)
</P>
<P>
   Record vs. Sox: 2-2
</P>
<P>
   Conversation piece: Their top three starters _ Kevin Appier, Gil
Heredia, and Tim Hudson _ have a combined won/lost record of 24-9.
One of Hudson's losses was an aberrational 14-2 bombing against the
Red Sox April 15. So in the last two months, he has only one loss.
Opponents hit only .222 against him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Change-the-subject material: At times, it seems as if Rob Deer
is their patron saint. They have struck out a staggering 529 times
this season, tops in the league.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE (40-30)
</P>
<P>
   Record vs. Sox: 2-1
</P>
<P>
   Conversation piece: This is the Mariners' first full season in
their new home. They reinvented themselves when they moved. They
and the Red Sox have given up the fewest home runs in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Conversation piece II: Edgar Martinez. He could play until he's
50 and still hit .325.
</P>
<P>
   Change-the-subject material: Top three starters are soft-servers
Aaron Sele, Jamie Moyer, and John Halama.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (37-32)
</P>
<P>
   Record vs. Sox: 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Conversation piece: When healthy, they have an awesome
Rotisserie lineup that includes Roberto Alomar, Manny Ramirez, and
Jim Thome.
</P>
<P>
   Change-the-subject material: The Indians have seven pitchers on
the disabled list. They also strike out nearly as much as the A's.
They also have an incurable Pedro Complex. In the mind of every
Indian there is an image of Martinez as king. He simply has the
team and the city spooked.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (36-31)
</P>
<P>
   Record vs. Sox: 4-5
</P>
<P>
   Conversation piece: The buzz is that Juan Gonzalez will be
joining Bernie Williams and Derek Jeter in New York. If Gonzalez
does land in New York, he will join a good team that has such a
sense of entitlement that it believes it is a great team.
</P>
<P>
   Change-the-subject material: Despite their $90 million-plus
payroll, the Yankees know they will go nowhere if they don't get
another pitcher. Orlando Hernandez has a sore elbow. Roger Clemens
is on the DL. David Cone has one win.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO (39-34)
</P>
<P>
   Record vs. Sox: 4-4
</P>
<P>
   Conversation piece: The Blue Jays have the highest fielding
percentage in the league. Carlos Delgado is the best home run
hitter in the league, and David Wells has 12 wins.
</P>
<P>
   Change-the-subject material: They are neighborhood outsiders.
While the other contending teams occupy the top seven ERA spots
(led by the Red Sox), the Jays are at 5.47, high above the league
average of 4.96. They won't be in the playoffs with pitching like
that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM (36-35)
</P>
<P>
   Record vs. Sox: 2-1
</P>
<P>
   Conversation piece: Darin Erstad. Simple as that.
</P>
<P>
   Change-the-subject material: They have four starters on the
disabled list. Two of their best hitters (Mo Vaughn and Troy Glaus)
are among the league's top four strikeout victims.
</P>
<P>
   End of tour. It's enough to make you appreciate your own house
and its red, squatty ``B'' logo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Holley is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail
at holley(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
