<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2671 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-ORIGINAL-BOS &LR;      06-23 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ORIGINAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TALE OF A RACY LIFE ORBITING THE STARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
ORIGINAL STORY BY 
A Memoir of Broadway and Hollywood 
By Arthur Laurents 
Knopf, 436 pp., illustrated, $30 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sex _ his preferences and others', and denials of same _ is a
leitmotif of Arthur Laurents's memoir, and it's understandable. Sex
and sexual politics permeate the show business milieu that he
inhabited for so long, as a director and a writer of plays and
movies. You live and breathe it, and big decisions are based on it
_ probably more than those who are not in the business realize.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as befits a successful dramatic writer, Laurents is too
good a storyteller to get sidetracked from his story line, the
``arc'' of which chronicles his odyssey from a boyhood in Flatbush
to coming of age in college and the Army to his varied experiences
writing for radio, theater, and the movies. His experiences brought
him into contact with an assortment of legends. He seems to have a
telling anecdote about everyone from Alfred Hitchcock and Katharine
Hepburn to David Lean and Barbra Streisand. A fair number of these
legends turn out to be wily, treacherous, insecure, disagreeable,
and _ worst of all _ less talented than legend has it.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Laurents also settles scores with what he calls
``unrepentant homophobes'' and anti-Semites. Gloria Jones, widow of
novelist James Jones, was one of the former, he says, who
congratulated him for his writing of women. (Laurents's reaction:
``Wasted point: It's men that homosexual men can have trouble
writing.'') An anti-Semite was a professor of playwriting at
Cornell who would start sentences with ``you Jews'' _ there were
two others besides Laurents in the class. The professor's first
instruction to the class was a ukase: Never begin a play with a
telephone ringing. Laurents immediately wrote a one-act play that
began with a telephone ringing.
</P>
<P>
   A particular object of Laurents's disaffection is choreographer
Jerome Robbins, a ``monster'' with whom he collaborated on the
musicals ``West Side Story'' and ``Gypsy.'' Another figure is movie
director Sidney Pollack, with whom Laurents worked as screenwriter
of the movie ``The Way We Were.'' Laurents writes that Pollack
sacrificed a good movie to keep Robert Redford happy.
</P>
<P>
   There are enough gibes and lines to keep the devotee of
behind-the-scenes stories interested. Producer Ray Stark ``worked
overtime at the job he wanted: casting young actresses.'' A rival
for Laurents's affections is described as an ``assisted blonde.''
On playwright William Inge: ``His work made him seem a very
sensitive man; which he was _ to himself. He didn't understand what
it was to be a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   There are three wonderfully bitchy descriptions on one page
alone. Stripper Gypsy Rose Lee ``hadn't a good body but she was
smart enough not to expose it.'' Robbins ``was the rock and the
hard place.'' An actress playing Gypsy ``looked virginal even
though she was going through the orchestra like a dose of salts.''
Fortunately, Laurents's best lines are usually dryer than that one.
Consider an observation that recurred in Sardi's restaurant
whenever Moss Hart, not known for his interest in marriage, would
appear with a woman: ``Ah, here comes Moss Hart with the future
Miss Edith Atwater.''
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of inside looks. One of Leonard Bernstein's
problems: he ``wasn't housebroken.'' Here's Gypsy's mother's
trenchant advice to her daughter who's facing her first audience of
men: ``Make 'em beg for more and then don't give it to them!'' The
difference between a superstar and a mere star: Superstars, like
Redford and Streisand, don't play their characters, they play
themselves playing their characters. A play's ``dialogue, like a
good wig, deceived too well. It made the play seem better than it
was.''
</P>
<P>
   Laurents is at his best when he lets his feelings show through
his caustic veneer. Arguably the most poignant scene in the book
has Laurents acting on an instinct he couldn't control. The feared
theater critic Walter Kerr and his wife, Jean, at the end of
Gypsy's striptease, which brings down the house, dash up the aisle
on their way out even though the show isn't over. Laurents is
livid. He blocks the couple at the head of the aisle. ``Go back to
your seats,'' he orders. ``It isn't over.'' Startled, they
dutifully turn around and return to their seats. Composer Jule
Styne is devastated, sure Laurents has blown the review then and
there. Later at Sardi's, Laurents is handed Kerr's review, an
unalloyed rave, especially for Laurents's book.
</P>
<P>
   And some of Laurents's gems sound like hard-earned wisdom.
``People, particularly writers, often hear what isn't said because
it's what they want to be said.'' ``She mistook his not being sure
what he wanted to be for not knowing who he was. I always knew what
I wanted to be; I had to discover who I was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
