<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLER, FOUTS NEW FACES IN `MONDAY NIGHT FOOTBALL' BOOTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABC Sports ended its three-month search to rekindle the glory
days of ``Monday Night Football'' by hiring Dan Fouts and comedian
Dennis Miller and firing sideline reporter Lesley Visser, creating
a show that producer Don Ohlmeyer described as ``relevant,
accessible, and unpredictable.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Famer Eric Dickerson and ESPN's Melissa Stark will
replace Visser.
</P>
<P>
   Ohlmeyer and ABC Sports president Howard Katz explained that the
changes were necessary to stop the drop in ratings the last several
years and create not only a football telecast, but must-see
television.
</P>
<P>
   In the last three years, ABC fired Lynn Swann and Dan Dierdorf
in an attempt to right the ship _ all to no avail. Boomer Esiason
was fired after last season. ABC also fired its longtime director
(Craig Janoff) and producer (Ken Wolfe) to make way for a new
production team, assembled by Ohlmeyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't derive as much pleasure as I felt I should have,''
said Ohlmeyer, who produced ``Monday Night Football'' in the 1970s
during the heydays of Howard Cosell, Don Meredith, and Frank
Gifford.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation was rampant. Most of the usual suspects were either
working at another network or not interested. Former Miami Dolphins
coach Jimmy Johnson was too happy on his boat in Key West, Fla.
Mike Ditka took a job with a Chicago station. Bill Parcells said in
the Jets' front office. Dan Marino signed with HBO.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate slap came from Sterling Sharpe, who refused to
return telephone calls to ABC.
</P>
<P>
   The new team will need every bit of distinction it can muster.
Ratings last season dropped to to their lowest in the 30-year
history of the show. In 1970, the show earned a 18.5 rating. By
1977, the show had climbed to 21.5, and peaked in 1981 at 21.7.
It's been downhill since, bottoming out in '99 (13.8). That number
is still good for a Monday night program, but it can't compare with
the ``Monday Night Football'' of the glory years.
</P>
<P>
   Television has changed. More channels have meant more choices.
One of the great features of ``Monday Night Football'' were the
halftime highlights. These days, most fans have already seen more
and better highlights by the time Monday night rolls around.
Exclusivity is a mere memory.
</P>
<P>
   More troublesome to ABC Sports is ESPN. ESPN's Sunday night NFL
game is better produced, and while Michaels is still one of the
best play-by-play guys in the business, ESPN's Mike Patrick, Joe
Theismann, and Paul Maguire are no slouches. Throw in sideline
reporter Solomon Wilcots and ESPN's crew was arguably better than
ABC's.
</P>
<P>
   ABC auditioned about 20 people, including Rush Limbaugh.
Ohlmeyer said the conservative radio broadcaster was a very strong
candidiate, but was unable to convince ABC that he would he able to
juggle his radio job during the football season. Limbaugh might
still make a few special appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Both Ohlmeyer and Michaels said they were ``blown away'' by
Miller. During the workout session, Michaels said he was impressed
with Miller's general knowledge of the game, players, and team
histories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't look at Miller as comedian,'' Ohlmeyer said. ``His role
is to provide an interesting point of view about a sport that
people enjoy on television. Any other would be erroneous.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohlmeyer told reporters he had expected Miller to be
entertaining during the workout session in which he sat with
Michaels and called the Houston-Buffalo AFC Championship game.
``But I was knocked out by some of the observations he made that a
lot of professional anaylsts who looked at the same tape didn't
make,'' Ohlmeyer said. ``Miller brings a fresh way of looking at
things, which is the challenge of all broadcasters _ to observe the
obvious and present with a sense of discovery,'' Ohlmeyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Michaels said he is excited about his 16th year on the show and
is looking forward to working with Fouts, whom he described as a
great communicator, and Miller ``the ultimate wild card.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, as irreverent as ever during a teleconference with
reporters, said he plans to stay in the background when it comes to
commentary on the heart and fortitude of players, but will be
free-wheeling when it comes to ``matters of the mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller conceded that he was a ``quirky hire'' and said that he
was ``reasonably stunned'' by the decision. ``I hope I can prove
them right.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohlmeyer said it's unclear how much time ABC will give the new
crew. ``Chemistry takes time, but we should be hitting our stride
by October,'' he said. ``It will be a work in progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Quite naturally, Ohlmeyer said he has assembled the best team
and praised both Dickerson and Stark as well. ``Each member of our
team has distinctive voices, distinctive personalities, and
distinctive points of view,'' Ohlmeyer said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   World title fight on tap
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fox Sports airs the World Bowl game between the Rhine Fire and
Scottish Claymores at 1 p.m. Saturday. The halftime show includes a
chat about the upcoming NFL season with James Brown, Howie Long,
Cris Collinsworth and Terry Bradshaw . . . Fox Sports also unveils
two miniature cameras slated to be used on a referee and the helmet
of Rhine quarterback Danny Wuerffel, the former Heisman trophy
winner . . . ABC Sports, ESPN Inc. and Little League Baseball have
reached agreement on a six-year contract extension to televise the
Little League Baseball World Series.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
