<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REALITY OF BEING AN OLDER MOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN VENNOCHI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Massachusetts has become the first state where more babies are
born to women over the age of 30 than under it, according to
statistics just released by the state Department of Public Health.
For those of us who are finally ahead of a trend, rather than
behind one, this is a rare opportunity to deliver expert commentary
based entirely on personal experience.
</P>
<P>
   In a word: Ouch!
</P>
<P>
   That is the sound of my knees cracking as I rollerblade after my
almost 7-year-old daughter. It is also the sound of my ego bruising
when my 11-year-old son talks about the ``olden days'' _ as in the
'70s _ and begs me to stop playing vintage Carly Simon albums.
</P>
<P>
   The official Bay State phenomenon of older moms is explained by
the large number of educated women in the state and their tendency
to delay having children. Someday, I expect my daughter will be one
of those educated females. So, what would I tell her about the
pluses and minuses of putting off children for career or other
reasons?
</P>
<P>
   The first point is a cliche, but a necessary one for any parent
to convey: a child is a huge blessing and an equally huge
responsibility, no matter what the mother's age.
</P>
<P>
   There is no greater joy than the one that comes from a child's
sweet good night kiss. And there is no greater irritation than what
springs from a child's refusal to go to sleep when you have company
or simply no desire to lie down next to her in a bunk bed.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, the older you are, the harder it is to climb down
from the bunk bed. But in other ways, being an older mother has its
pluses.
</P>
<P>
   When your children study local and American history, you can
help with first-hand recollections of key moments. For example, I
can relate what I was doing during the Blizzard of '78 and where I
was when President Kennedy was shot.
</P>
<P>
   Children absolutely keep you young. You may be old enough to
remember singing ``She wore an itsy-bitsy, teeny-weeny, yellow
polka-dot bikini'' in the back seat of the family Rambler. But you
can't be totally over the hill if you can also trill along to
Britney Spears (``Oops, I did it again'') while navigating the
family minivan.
</P>
<P>
   The childless are starting to gripe that working parents shirk
their duties so that they can get home for soccer games. But young
children keep older parents more productive at work, in my opinion.
Who wants to be downsized when college tuition looms as a reality
until 2014?
</P>
<P>
   As for minuses, they mostly relate to feeling and looker older
than you want to admit. Once on Newbury Street, a sadistic parking
lot attendant looked, first, at me, then at the child-safety seat
in my car, and asked the age of my grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   There are constant cultural tradeoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Every time you try to listen to news, classical music, or
oldies, your children will switch the car radio to KISS 108. That
requires you to field questions from fifth-grade boys about what
Christina Aguilera means when she sings: ``I'm a genie in a bottle
/ You gotta rub me the right way.'' Who can remember?
</P>
<P>
   You watch ``Hey, Arnold!'' and ``Rugrats'' instead of
``Washington Week in Review. '' You play Candy Land and Junior
Scrabble when you would like to read a good book. When everyone is
talking about the latest movie, all you can do is hum the theme
song to ``Beauty and the Beast.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the solitude you seek as you get older is also more
difficult to achieve. When you take a bubble bath, your daughter
jumps in with you and her Barbies. When you long to linger over the
Sunday Times, your son drags you out for a game of one-on-one hoop.
At the beach, your children beg you to go in the water, when it
would be oh, so nice to fall asleep on the warm, dry sand.
</P>
<P>
   And what about the underlying professional rationale for putting
off motherhood _ that it is better to advance at work when you are
young, take a motherhood break, and then catch up? From a career
perspective, there is really no good time to have children.
Whenever you give birth, parenthood alters your perspective and
changes your priorities forever.
</P>
<P>
   You know what? The best time to have children is when you really
want them _ and when you are prepared to love them more than anyone
or anything else in the world.
</P>
<P>
   That is a trend worth contemplating.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joan Vennochi is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
