<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV25-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VINEGAR SHOULD LOOSEN PLASTIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June   25, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Some clear plastic was left on an outside aluminum storm
door. I failed to remove it with a hair dryer. How can I remove it?
</P>
<P>
   MARY ELLEN NAJARIAN, Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The longer the plastic film is left on an aluminum door (or
acrylic or Plexiglas), the harder it is to remove. Heat should
help, but what often happens is that you pull off a bit of plastic
and it divides itself into a long narrow strip. Not much
accomplished. It is like pulling off that plastic wrapping tape
that makes a real ripping sound when you pull it. When it comes off
in long strips, making me have to start all over, I quit.
</P>
<P>
   But mayonnaise or vinegar should work. Use vinegar; the
mayonnaise is too icky.
</P>
<P>
   How to use the vinegar: Because the plastic is impervious to
liquids, you have to pull off a bit of the plastic film and work
the vinegar between film and door. Let the vinegar seep down, then
try pulling off a bit more plastic. It is tedious, but I know of no
other way. I am surprised the heat didn't work, but it might have
set the plastic even more.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My front yard slopes toward the driveway, and when the
driveway gets wet it is slippery and also ices over in winter. How
can I keep water off the driveway?
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE GATZIOGIANNIS, Hopkinton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If you cannot regrade the yard to divert the water elsewhere,
you have to accommodate it. Try this: Dig a trench parallel to the
driveway, just a foot or two from the driveway itself. Make it 12
inches wide and 12 or more inches deep, and fill it with crushed
stone. Try to aim the trench to the street. Some towns do not allow
you do guide water to the street, but the water is better on the
street than on your driveway. You could put a steel grille over the
trench for good looks.
</P>
<P>
   If push comes to shove and the town objects, then ask the town
for a better idea. Unless the water table is very, very low, I do
not think turning that trench into a dry wall to allow the water to
drain downward will work.
</P>
<P>
   I do not think the town has storm sewers that you could hook
into on the street.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My new roof has moss on one of the slopes. I was advised to
install zinc strips. Will they work to keep away moss, algae, and
mold?
</P>
<P>
   J.J., Medfield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The zinc strips were developed, I believe, in the South,
where algae, moss, and mold are rampant. This phenomenon has become
common in the North, as well. The strips are placed under the
second-highest row of shingles near the ridge, with about two
inches of zinc exposed. Rain runs over the strips, bringing a bit
of zinc down the roof. It is toxic to moss, algae, and mold, and I
have not heard that the strips don't work. Remember, however, that
this technique will not necessarily kill the growths, but is a
deterrent, a preventative to keep the growths from recurring. So,
you have to scrape up the moss and treat the area with one part
bleach and three parts water. If the growths are green algae (no
depth) and black mold, they too have to be killed with the bleach
solution before the zinc strips can do their work. As ever, I have
to say, wear skin and eye protection when working with bleach.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. You wrote recently about a caller referring to white pine
shingles, and you asked, why not white cedar? My contractor says
you can't find white cedar shingles anymore. What can I do now?
</P>
<P>
   CONFUSED
</P>
<P>
   A. Huh? Wha? You can find another contractor, who will find
white cedar shingles at any lumber store. Even the handyman found
some last summer, and also noticed some at Home Depot the other
day. Your contractor just can't be bothered, so that is why I
suggest getting another.
</P>
<P>
   It's ironic. The white cedar referred to is probably another
species altogether, juniper, the tree that produces the little gray
berries. But it is called white cedar in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   If you opt for white cedar shingles, specify Extras. They are
the top quality, have no knots, and perform the best. Expose them 5
inches for best performance. They are green (full of water) when
sold, and will dry out after they are installed, turning a nice
silver color. But in drying out, they shrink.
</P>
<P>
   Now you can get kiln-dried white cedar shingles, excellent for
good service and weathering, but they cost $2 a square foot, twice
as much as green shingles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My tiler said he would put thin plywood over old linoleum and
put ceramic tile on the plywood. Is that OK?
</P>
<P>
   SALLY BURKE, Duxbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Sure. It is one of several techniques, and done right, the
tile will last for generations. Just make sure the plywood is
secured properly by screwing it down, because if it fails under the
new tile, you will have a whole new floor to redo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail
hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
