<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2678 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     06-23 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS E-COMMERCE WARS RAGE, SEND.COM FOCUSES ON PROFIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Lannon has run Send.com for three years now. But as
Lannon has come to realize, dot-com years are like dog years: An
awful lot happens in a short space of time.
</P>
<P>
   Over those three years, the Waltham, Mass. company _ best known
for its ads featuring ``The Giver'' _ has gone from a business that
sold wine over the phone, to one that sold wine over the Internet,
to one that sells wine, gifts, and gift services over the Internet.
Over those same three years, e-commerce firms have gone from
unknown to incredibly hot to incredibly cold.
</P>
<P>
   We sat down with Lannon recently to find out what the experience
has been like.
</P>
<P>
   Q. The change in the e-commerce world between last year and this
year is enormous, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   A.Last year, it felt like we were always running down a ski
slope. You needed all your energy not to fall and hurt yourself.
This year, we are going slower, but things feel more comfortable
and under control.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What does that mean in terms of managing your company?
</P>
<P>
   A.Last year, the focus was strictly on growing the top line.
This year, the market is demanding that we focus on getting
profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Q. So how have you done that?
</P>
<P>
   A.I'll give you one example. We use photography on our Web site.
Last year, we hired professional photographers to do that. This
year, we bought $25,000 worth of photography equipment and took the
pictures ourselves. We will save $100,000 in fees in just this one
area, and there are dozens of other examples just like that. We are
running things like a business now.
</P>
<P>
   Q. And you will be profitable by?
</P>
<P>
   A.The fourth quarter of 2001 _ six quarters from now.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You are still a private company. Will you be able to raise
the money you need to get from here to there?
</P>
<P>
   A.We have some strong venture investors. We will be able to
raise money from those investors and maybe from some new ones, as
well. If the stock market changes and an IPO makes sense, we will
be in a position to do that. The market will determine that.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How come you didn't join the herd that went public last fall,
when dot-coms were still in favor?
</P>
<P>
   A.The truth is we weren't ready to go public. We had a choice.
We could either prepare for Christmas or go public. We couldn't do
both. It turned out to be a blessing in disguise. If you have a
public stock that is in the tank, you get punished for it. Like it
or not, the stock price is a scorecard. We don't have that
distraction. As a private company we get to build the future
without the glare of the public spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Even without a stock in the tank, you must have had some
nervous employees this spring when the Nasdaq crashed.
</P>
<P>
   A.Morale definitely dipped for a while. We had to hunker down
and weather the storm. In the absence of communication from the
company, all anyone heard or read was negative. I met with every
employee and told them what was going on. We did a lot of
hand-holding, and we were able to make our retention package more
attractive. Fortunately we've had very little attrition.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You guys spent money last year to get your name known by the
public. Your ads were great, but do you regret spending the money?
</P>
<P>
   A.Not at all. We made an investment that will pay off over a
period of years, not immediately. The ad campaign made sense for us
because we have a different kind of transaction from most
companies. You don't buy anything from me directly. (Send.com's
gifts and services are provided by other retailers.) We need you to
trust us and find us credible. We need to shake your hand through
our Web site and our advertising. That may sound like a
rationalization, but it isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Q. And business is still growing, even though you have cut back
on your advertising?
</P>
<P>
   A.Traffic is growing. February was bigger than December, May was
bigger than February, and June will be bigger than May.
</P>
<P>
   Q. So reports of e-commerce's death have been exaggerated?
</P>
<P>
   A.I don't think anyone doubts that Internet commerce will
continue to grow. This current ugly environment will sort out the
good companies from the bad ones. It is going to force companies to
run smarter and reward those that do. I am extraordinarily
optimistic abut my industry. I am pessimistic about a lot of the
companies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
