<SLUG> BC-SOX-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAOS IS PART OF THE DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four to three is a rare score line in major soccer tournaments,
and when it occurs, the match has a good chance of being considered
a classic.
</P>
<P>
   Spain edged Yugoslavia, 4-3, with two injury-time goals in the
European Championships Wednesday in a game of high drama. But the
game in Brugge, Belgium, will not likely have the lasting effect of
the Italy-Germany World Cup semifinal that finished with the same
score after overtime in Estadio Azteca in Mexico City. There was so
much drama and unpredictability in the final stages of that match,
which took place 30 years ago, the score itself became the title of
a play and movie with a nostalgic '60s theme, the Italian version
of ``The Big Chill.''
</P>
<P>
   But such games symbolize the dynamic, and often chaotic, nature
of soccer. Yugoslavia appeared to have the match clinched with a
3-2 lead in the 49th minute. The Yugoslavs likely suffered a
letdown, since they had been assured of advancing to the
quarterfinals because Norway and Slovenia had tied, 0-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish, though, needed to win to qualify because they had
lost to Norway, and the first tiebreaker is head-to-head
competition. So, Gaizca Mendietta's tying penalty kick signified
little. But French referee Gilles Veissiere allowed another minute
of injury time, increasing the total time played to 99 minutes, and
Alfonso Perez hit the winning goal in the final seconds. That
vaulted Spain to first place and set up a date with France Sunday.
And it knocked Norway out of the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game shows the line which separates success from failure
that can be overcome in a minute,'' Spain's Josep Guardiola said.
``In one minute we reversed the situation, but if the referee would
not have whistled the penalty or if he had conceded less injury
time we would already be on the way home. But this is football.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never said we should be among the favorites. Others said
it, but not us. With this victory we have accomplished something,
but in reality we are where Spain always has been. The true measure
of quality is what we will do now. And we will be able to do it
only if we show we have the talent, the willingness to sacrifice,
and the right refereeing.''
</P>
<P>
   Euro 2000 has already produced some highlight comebacks.
Portugal rallied from a two-goal deficit to defeat England, 3-2.
Yugoslavia battled from a three-goal deficit to tie Slovenia, 3-3.
And Romania eliminated England after trailing, 2-1, with an
89th-minute goal.
</P>
<P>
   Euro 2000 has almost become a Club Med outing. Only the
Netherlands remains of the Northern European nations. Saturday's
quarterfinals include Portugal-Turkey in Amsterdam and
Italy-Romania in Brussels. Sunday's games are
Netherlands-Yugoslavia in Rotterdam and Spain-France in Brugge.
</P>
<P>
   The event is also a showcase for talent. Alfonso, who converted
the deciding goal for Spain, will likely attempt to leave Real
Betis, which has been relegated to the Second Division. But the
Seville club said Alfonso has a $43.6 million buyout clause in his
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the most in demand are Real Madrid's Raul, who has a
$165 million buyout clause, and Barcelona's Portuguese midfielder
Figo ($125 million). The buyout clauses likely could be challenged
in court, but the process would be too time-consuming to be
worthwhile for prospective purchasers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Juniors achievement
</P>
<P>
   The Copa Libertadores final in Sao Paulo also produced an
exciting conclusion, as Boca Juniors won the title for the third
time and the first time since 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiras was heavily favored in the final after playing to a
2-2 tie in Buenos Aires. Estadio Morumbi was filled with 75,000
fans _ 3,000 from Boca Juniors _ but the match finished, 0-0. And
Boca Juniors won, 4-2, on penalty kicks, thanks to the goalkeeping
of Colombian Oscar Cordoba.
</P>
<P>
   Cordoba stopped Faustino Asprilla and Roque Junior, silencing
the crowd, except for the Argentine minority, which included Diego
Armando Maradona in the broadcast booth. It was a particularly
bittersweet night for Roque Junior, the huge central defender who
keyed coach Luis Felipe Scolari's defense, since his next game will
be for AC Milan, which purchased him for $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still on top
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution also completed an improbable comeback Wednesday
night, leaving them with a 4-point lead in the Eastern Division
going into Saturday's visit to Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   Leonel Alvarez and Ivan McKinley will reinforce the Revolution,
which rallied for a 2-2 tie at San Jose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
