<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2680 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-GENOMICS-ART-BOS     06-23 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-GENOMICS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 GENOMICS DRAWING PLAYERS TO BOSTON AREA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Six years after Hans Nilsson set out to develop a
research and development center in Greater Boston for Astra AB, the
Swedish pharmaceutical company is now aiming to become a major
player in drug discovery.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Astra will open a 170,000-square-foot campus on a
64-acre site near the Cambridge Reservoir. Inside a trio of
barn-shaped limestone and glass buildings, Astra's scientists will
try to find new drugs to treat cancer and infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
   In planting roots here, Astra joins a growing list of major US
and European pharmaceutical and biotechnology firms expanding in
the Boston-to-Worcester corridor to take advantage of the area's
strength in genomics _ the mapping of the human genetic code. As
that process nears an important milestone, the race is already on
to create and market the next generation of medical therapies
expected to arise from the charting of human genes.
</P>
<P>
   The companies are all seeking to tap into the deep talent pool
at the area's universities, hospitals and high-tech companies,
which can help them further their research.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw from the start the superb science in the Boston area
and, after a quick look at Seattle, concluded we had to be here,''
Nilsson said.
</P>
<P>
   His company, now called AstraZeneca PLC, is only the latest
arrival. The region is home to pioneering genomic firms such as
Millennium Pharmaceuticals Inc. and top biotechnology firms such as
Vertex Pharmaceuticals Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer Inc. has a research presence in Cambridge, and Amgen
Inc., the nation's largest biotechnology company, is building a
research site there. Merck &AMP; Co. is developing a research tower in
Boston, while American Home Products is building a research site in
Cambridge and a manufacturing plant in Andover.
</P>
<P>
   (The world's single largest pharmaceutical research center is in
Groton, Conn., where Pfizer on Monday will formally open a
585,000-square-foot center with 120 laboratories and 800
researchers.)
</P>
<P>
   For AstraZeneca, a leader in gastrointestinal prescription drugs
to treat ulcers, the new research and development site here will
use the continuing stream of genomic information to create drugs
that can battle bacteria and fungi and cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Nilsson said AstraZeneca, which last year derived about
two-thirds of $18.4 billion in revenues from gastrointestinal and
cardiovascular drugs, is seeking to develop 15 drugs by 2003 for
regulatory approval. He said the company's goal is to reduce the
time to develop and bring new drugs to market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking data from the Human Genome Project off the
Internet every night and looking to where it can fit with our work
in infectious diseases,'' said Kenneth Fasman, vice president and
gloal head of informatics for AstraZeneca's Enabling Science and
Technology center.
</P>
<P>
   AstraZeneca's research center here is aimed at drug discovery.
It plans to hand off other functions, such as animal and human
testing, development and manufacturing, to other parts of the
global company. Its strategy is similar to Pfizer, which uses its
Cambridge site to evaluate emerging technologies, particularly in
genomics, that are then used at company drug research and
development centers in Groton.
</P>
<P>
   The reserach center here was designed before the completion of
the Astra and Zeneca merger in April 1999. Since, the company has
eliminated 1,000 research jobs worldwide, including 100 in
Worcester. Some of those laid off were offered positions in
Waltham.
</P>
<P>
   Nilsson, touring the Swedish-designed facility here, said it was
designed so that the chemistry and biology laboratories could be
quickly altered to accommodate corporate needs. To encourage
researchers from different parts of the company to meet and talk,
there are free coffee stations along with chairs and tables in a
center atrium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too often research buildings have bright atriums in the center
with dark areas for the scientists _ something we did not want to
do,'' he said, pointing to the windowed office cubiles and
brightly-lit laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether AstraZeneca's work environment
here will help attract scientists and computer engineers more
familiar with Cambridge's cluster of young companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
