<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONADVERTISING-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARNOLD TO FIRE UP NEXT PHASE OF TEEN ANTISMOKING ADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With a teen rally set for Seattle this weekend and ads that urge
young people to rip tobacco ads out of the magazines they buy,
Boston ad agency Arnold Communications is kicking off the next
phase of a $185 million marketing campaign that seeks to discourage
teenagers from smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Released earlier this year, the first ads in this campaign were
edgy and controversial. In one TV spot that made some networks
nervous, teens piled body bags outside a tobacco company building
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   New ads seem to retain that same in-your-face tone; they
continue to portray the tobacco industry as a seemingly greedy and
manipulative Mephistopheles out to take control of teenagers' lives
by addicting them to a product that kills one-third of its users.
</P>
<P>
   A new magazine ad shows an image of a hand with bandaged
fingers. The text urges the magazine's readers to ``Rip out the
next cigarette ad you see because tobacco killed about 430,000
people last year and paper cuts didn't kill anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The client for the campaign is the American Legacy Foundation, a
group established by the 1998 master settlement agreement between
the tobacco industry and 46 states.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement, the tobacco companies agreed to pay out
over time more than $200 billion. Part of the Legacy Foundation's
job is to use some of that money to finance an ad campaign that has
the goal of reducing smoking among teens.
</P>
<P>
   Many ad agencies vied for that lucrative assignment.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the foundation announced a winner _ an alliance of
ad agencies and public relations firms led by Arnold, New England's
largest ad agency.
</P>
<P>
   After extensive research with teens, the alliance earlier this
year unveiled a campaign it called ``truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Using ads and a Web site at www.thetruth.com, the campaign urges
teens to take control of their lives by rejecting the influence of
tobacco marketing, said Lisa Unsworth, an Arnold executive vice
president. Truth provides facts about tobacco and the tobacco
industry and enables teens to make informed decisions about
smoking, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to achieve this goal, one recent TV ad for black teens
says, ``Every year menthol cigarettes leave more than 33,000 minty
fresh African-American corpses.''
</P>
<P>
   In the latest phase of the campaign, plans call for about a
thousand handpicked teens to gather this weekend in Seattle for a
crash course in grass-roots, antitobacco advocacy.
</P>
<P>
   After the summit, plans call for ``truth'' buses to tour major
cities. At each stop, some summit-trained teens will preach the
truth gospel. One scheduled stop is outside Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   What has made the truth campaign potentially controversial is a
provision in the master settlement.
</P>
<P>
   In return for agreeing to pay out billions of dollars and to
scale back their own advertising, the tobacco companies insisted on
language in the settlement that asks the foundation to refrain from
running ads that ``vilify'' tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   When the initial truth ads aired, there was a debate over the
meaning of ``vilify.'' Some observers might assert that ads hinting
that tobacco executives are liars who traffic in a killer drug
might qualify as vilification.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold's Unsworth argues otherwise. Ads have been thoroughly
lawyered to avoid violating the ``vilify'' provision, she said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the tobacco industry has declined to publicly weigh in
with its own definition of vilify.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no problem with much of what the foundation is
doing,'' said Philip Morris USA media relations manager Brendan
McCormick. ``But we're disappointed with some of the ads and the
tone of the Web site. We don't think they're an accurate depiction
of our company, our employees, and the way we do business.''
</P>
<P>
   Some might argue ads that focus on the consequences of smoking
might be as effective as ads that seemingly target tobacco
companies.
</P>
<P>
   That may be the case for ads aimed at adults, Unsworth said, but
research shows that teens are most likely to respond to antismoking
ads that highlight the manipulative marketing strategies of tobacco
companies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Chris Reidy covers the retail and advertising businesses for The
Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 1330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2684 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-EUROPE-REFUGEES-$ADV2     06-23 1424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-REFUGEES-$ADV25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EUROPEANS, DESPITE WORKFORCE NEEDS, STRUGGLE WITH INFLUX OF
IMMIGRANTS
 &HT;    (1000&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    For Use Sun., June 25 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Last Sunday night, British customs officers at the port
city of Dover became suspicious about a produce truck that had just
arrived by ferry from Holland.
</P>
<P>
   They opened the back of the truck to find crates of tomatoes.
Still suspicious, the officers used a forklift to unload a few
crates to see what lay behind.
</P>
<P>
   One officer shimmied over the remaining stacks of tomatoes. To
his horror, the hot, darkened compartment contained the bodies of
58 Chinese immigrants. Two others were still alive.
</P>
<P>
   The 56 men and four women had paid up to US$30,000 each to be
smuggled into Britain, probably in search of jobs where they could
make more in a month than they could in a year in China.
</P>
<P>
   However, the truck's ventilation system had been was switched
off Sunday afternoon, a rare day when temperatures soared above 90
degrees. The air-tight produce compartment became a hot, airless
death chamber.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the truck's Dutch driver was charged with 58 counts
of manslaughter, and police were questioning other suspects in what
authorities believe is one of many well-organized cells of refugee
smugglers known as ``snakeheads.''
</P>
<P>
   The deaths come at a time when Europeans are struggling to come
to grips with the growing influx of immigrants from Asia and
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The Geneva-based International Organization for Migration
estimates that as many as 400,000 illegal immigrants enter Europe
each year _ about 100,000 more than the United States.
</P>
<P>
   From Africa they come across the broad expanse of southern
Spain, which is known as the ``southern gate,'' Europe's version of
the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   From Asia, they travel the arduous route through Russia and
eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Once in the European Union, they can move between countries
without documents as most border passport stops have been removed.
Britain is one of the few EU members that still checks passports at
the border, forcing immigrants without documents to find other
means of entry.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the United States, which was built by immigrants seeking
opportunity, European countries are still struggling with the
demands of becoming multicultural.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, public opinion in Europe has shifted against
immigrants, who are regarded by many as poor foreigners trying to
sponge off richer countries.
</P>
<P>
   Europe, again, unlike America, has little infrastructure for
assimilating people with different languages and religions. Polls
show many Europeans are convinced that illegal immigration is out
of control, and is likely to become worse.
</P>
<P>
   Voters respond favorably these days to the inflammatory
anti-immigration rhetoric of Austria's Jorge Haider, Denmark's Pia
Kjaersgaard and France's Jean Marie Le Pen.
</P>
<P>
   Even moderate politicians have responded to the concerns and
have pushed for tougher immigration rules and enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   However, advocates for refugees believe these new restrictions
only make it more likely that immigrants will go underground.
Consequently, they say that blame for the dreadful episode in Dover
must be shared not only by the gangs that traffic in human cargo
but also by European politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Khalid Koser of London University's Migration Research Center
believes the trend of anti-immigration policies have boosted a
market for refugee smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main reason illegal immigration appears to be growing is
that restrictive immigration policies have increased, making it
difficult for people to arrive in Europe legally,'' Koser said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that these criminal gangs are now going out
and marketing themselves, telling people they will be able to get
them into Europe,'' Koser said, ``and because it is more difficult
to get visas they are able to charge higher fees.''
</P>
<P>
   The push to stem the flow of immigrants has curtailed one
traditional avenue, claiming political asylum. Across Europe, about
350,000 people applied for asylum in 1999 _ a 20 percent jump over
1998. But fewer requests are being approved, and governments are
trying to end the practice of using applications to enter a country
legally and never leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Britain denied most of the 75,000 applications it received last
year, but two-thirds of the applicants had in the meantime
disappeared into their ethnic communities.
</P>
<P>
   After being criticized by Conservative Party opponents, British
Prime Minister Tony Blair's government recently vowed to deport
many asylum seekers and jail others while their requests are
processed.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative leaders believe their attack on asylum applicants
has found a receptive audience among voters in Britain worried
about what party leader William Hague described as a ``flood of
bogus asylum seekers.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the political climate, European governments are more
interested in stopping new migrants than catching the masterminds
behind the illegal trade, Koser said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``the big danger if they crack down on illegal
immigrants is that they will also close down the routes used by
genuine refugees to flee from persecution.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, almost all unskilled people now are excluded from
entry to the United Kingdom, despite the country's deeply valued
position as a harbor for persecuted people, said Nick Hardwick of
Britain's Refugee Council. ``It is virtually impossible for people
fleeing persecution to enter Britain legally,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, they are forced to resort to desperate measures.
</P>
<P>
   The migrants found in Dover came from Fujian province, a
southern coastal province with a rich history of its people
migrating abroad. In some villages, 10 percent of the population
has left, according to the International Organization for
Migration.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 50 international crime groups are involved in
organized refugee trafficking, officials say. The term for them _
``snakeheads'' _ comes from a gang based in Fujian province.
</P>
<P>
   Migrant smuggling has become big business. ``The profit these
criminals can make by smuggling humans in, rather than drugs, is
now very, very substantial,'' Jack Straw, the British Home
Secretary, told Parliament last Monday.
</P>
<P>
   To repay smuggling fees of US$20,000 to US$60,000, many
immigrants work in the service and garment industries. They find
housing with established family members.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 800,000 ethnic Chinese live in Europe, with most
making their homes in Britain _ about 250,000 _ and France _ about
200,000.
</P>
<P>
   Although the United States has been the favored destination for
smuggled ethnic Chinese, there are indications that Europe is
becoming a more attractive destination, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, European officials are trying to slow immigration
at a time when the continent is in need of fresh blood.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a low birth rate, the European Union's population
growth is the lowest since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, many European countries face the prospect of
developing a population imbalance with a surplus of older people
and a shortage of younger people do to the work.
</P>
<P>
   In 50 years Germany, which is becoming more and more dependent
on foreigners for its labor force, is expected to have more
retirees than workers.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations in late March estimated that Europe may need
as many as 150 million new immigrants by 2025 to maintain the
present levels of working and tax-paying communities.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Hall, the research director at the Centre for European
Reforms, believes that in time, the EU may need to attract
immigrants, setting annual quotas for newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Europe's population is falling,'' Hall said. ``If you take
Italy as an example, the Italian population is estimated to fall by
28 percent by the middle of this century.''
</P>
<P>
   While many political leaders are trying to clamp down on
immigration, others warn about the long-term consequences.
</P>
<P>
   In a February speech, former Italian Minister Massimo D'Alema
urged his countrymen to end their fear of immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we close the door to immigration,'' D'Alema said, ``we
would make our country poorer.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s e-mail address is BertR(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.iom.ch
</P>
<P>
   www.unhcr.ch
</P>
<P>
   www.igc.ch
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
