<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2686 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-BLACK-PHILANTHROPY-BO     06-23 1487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-PHILANTHROPY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSTITUTIONS VYING FOR BLACK PHILANTHROPY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the New Economy creates unprecedented wealth, African
Americans are earning more than ever before. Now philanthropic
organizations serving the black community are lining up for a
portion of the profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, (African Americans) are in the position to
pool their resources so as to bring about social change,'' said Ron
Ancrum, a senior consultant at Third Sector New England, a Boston
consultancy that serves nonprofits.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, African Americans have made the bulk of their
charitable donations through church organizations, giving $4.8
billion to churches last year, up from $4.3 billion in 1998. But
the big nonprofits serving black communities have been slow to
catch up to the new class of black professionals that has emerged
as a result of the longest economic expansion in US history.
</P>
<P>
   Now the push is on to tap that growing roster of African
Americans who have moved into the executive ranks. The reason: a
record increase in black buying power over the past decade. As a
result, nonprofits that serve poor black areas are looking more
closely at how to compete more effectively for the wallets of the
emerging class of black wealth.
</P>
<P>
   And that class continues to grow. College attendance rates among
African Americans hit a record 40 percent in 1997, up from 32
percent in 1991, according to a report released this year by the
American Council on Education in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nation's 34.5 million African Americans, 5.6 percent now
earn $50,000 or more, according to the US Census Bureau. Among
workers in the top fifth income percentile, African Americans now
earn an average annual salary of $94,000, up more than 60 percent
over the last two decades. White Americans in the same income
bracket earn approximately $134,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of factors leading to increased interest in
black philanthropy,'' noted Emmett D. Carson, president and chief
executive of the Minneapolis Foundation. ``For mainstream white
institutions there is the promise of a new donor base. . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Secondly, there are now African Americans who recognize that
for 200 years most black giving was crisis driven,'' he added.
``Now, however, there is a critical mass of doctors, lawyers,
financial executives, people who understand that you can give
strategically, that you can figure out the most pressing problems
facing African Americans and give through structured endowments,
wills, or bequests.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, total earnings of US black households rose to $490
billion, up from $441 billion in 1998, according to market
researcher Target Market News of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, black household income rose 40.2 percent during the
1980s, the fastest of any urban black population in the country,
according to labor economist Barry Bluestone, author of ``The
Boston Renaissance: Race, Space, and Economic Change in an American
Metropolis.'' That income jump is reflected in the suburban
communities within Route 128, which saw a 63.5 percent rise in
their black populations between 1980 and 1990.
</P>
<P>
   When Target Market examined charitable giving, it found
donations to nonprofits, political organizations, and educational
groups dropped to $7.3 billion in 1999 from $8.4 billion in 1998,
based on US Department of Commerce surveys of 3,000 black
households. At the same time, contributions to black churches
increased by $500 million. An additional half-billion dollars went
to emergency giving to family or friends.
</P>
<P>
   But turning more black earners into sophisticated givers is an
educational process, said Ancrum of Third Sector New England. ``Our
next step in Boston will be to hold smaller seminars focused
specifically on wills, estate planning, and teaching people that in
addition to leaving a legacy for your children, you can leave
something behind to a cause you believe in.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in the philanthropy field are also recognizing that a new
group of donors has emerged. Younger, perhaps even savvier, they
are not interested in simply writing a check.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who want to see, and perhaps even influence,
how their money is being used,'' said Carson, who calls such donors
``strategic givers.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Winters certainly fits that profile. A senior manager at
Boston-based AEW Capital Management, with $10 billion in public and
private assets, Winters, 40, earns a top salary and lives in
Newton.
</P>
<P>
   Winters made an annual contribution of $5,000 to Dimock
Community Health Center, but he wasn't satisfied with simply
writing a check. So he joined the board. ``I joined because I
wanted to make a contribution that went beyond dollars,'' he said.
``I wanted to provide a certain perspective as well as expertise.''
</P>
<P>
   Michele Courton Brown, 38, of Boston, supports the private
school her children attend and gives to the United Negro College
Fund and Fisk University. She also served on a committee that
raised $4 million to restore part of the Museum of African American
History.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who serves on eight boards, says white organizations ask
her for higher donations than black groups. ``Majority
organizations will say, gee, can you make an investment of
$10,000,'' said Brown, president of FleetBoston Financial
Foundation. ``African American organizations, by contrast, seem to
be apologetic. They may ask for $1,000. So the expectations for
giving appear to be higher at white organizations than at
African-American organizations, which rely more on sweat equity
from board members than on big donations.''
</P>
<P>
   When Mary Frances Winters, president of the Winters Group Inc.,
a research consulting firm in Rochester, N.Y., interviewed
middle-class donors around the country for a 1999 report on black
philanthropy, she found they all consistently gave to their
churches. ``When I looked at other areas of giving,'' she said, ``I
found that they tended to give haphazardly and not in a planned
way. These were people who do not trust white institutions and
areless likely to invest their money or give to organizations
outside the church.''
</P>
<P>
   Winters also found that white universities are often more adept
at getting support from alumni than black ones, partly because they
have more resources. ``Vanderbilt University is the same size as
Howard University in terms of student body, but Vanderbilt had 40
development officers and Howard had five.''
</P>
<P>
   Carson says his alma maters are a perfect example. Princeton
University, from which he received a master's and doctorate, has
stayed connected to him, keeping current on his address changes and
diligently seeking contributions from his six-figure income.
Meanwhile, Morehouse College in Georgia, the historically black
college from which he received his bachelor's degree in 1981, has
been much less aggressive in tapping his support.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I moved to Washington, D.C., Princeton found me,'' Carson
told a group of black philanthropic professionals who met in Boston
a few weeks ago. ``I moved to Maryland and guess who sent a note
thanking me for a modest contribution? Princeton. When I moved to
Minneapolis, Princeton knew it. Somehow Princeton knows where I am
before I get there. Morehouse still thinks I live in Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Morehouse says it has stepped up efforts to reach
alumni and is now embarking on a major development campaign. But it
has some catching up to do.
</P>
<P>
   Spelman College in Georgia and Hampton University in Virginia,
both historically black colleges, have launched major campaigns
aimed at their graduates and others who might be willing to endow
scholarships or create academic chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the push has paid off.
</P>
<P>
   In May, members of the class of 1990 donated $66,000 to Spelman,
whose endowment now stands at $216.7 million, up from just $156
million in 1997. Trisa Long Paschal of Spelman attributed a good
portion of that growth to wise stock market investments, but said
the school is also receiving more from alumni. Spelman has
completed a major campaign that raised $113 million and ``was the
first effort in which a historically black college had solicited
alumni for gifts of $10,000 or more.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, meanwhile, is in the midst of a $200 million campaign
to provide endowed technology scholarships and professorships that
so far has raised $160 million. ``In the past we did not have the
technology to keep in touch with'' the school's 20,000 alumni, said
Iris Wilson, an assistant business professor and associate director
of the Campaign for Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that a lot of the historically black colleges do
not have the technical expertise to do that,'' she said. ``The Ivy
League colleges and the major white institutions know when someone
moves across the street.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 1333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2687 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-GROOVE-BOS &LR;      06-23 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GROOVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GROOVE' LIVES UP TO ITS NAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
GROOVE 
Written and directed by: Greg Harrison 
Starring: Lola Glaudini, Hamish Linklater, Danny Kirkwood,
Mackenzie Firgens, Vince Riverside, Rachel True, Steve Van Wormer,
Nick Offerman, Elizabeth Sun, Angelo Spizziri, Jeff Witzke,
Dimitri, Ari Gold 
Running time: 83 minutes 
Rated: R (drug use, language and brief sexuality) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Groove,'' bless its little technopop heart, is the best movie
combining music and romance since ``High Fidelity.'' Greg
Harrison's loving and lovable celebration of San Francisco's
underground rave scene is never too dazed and confused to generate
a sweet communal vibe as it puts its own disarming spin on the
let's-party imperative. Its ravers juggle a search for love and a
need to appear cool, even when drugged, under the big glitter dome
that stands as a metaphor for the film itself. One of the feats it
pulls off is the fiction that raves are still underground
phenomena. These Bay Area ravesters know that you don't consult
newspapers or flyers on record store bulletin boards to find out
where the rave has floated to. You rely on word of mouth via phone,
pagers or the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the mystique is not knowing where any given weekend's
rave is. ``Groove'' gets off to a nice start by goofing on action
movies when a warehouse door rolls up to reveal the rave organizer
and true believer named Ernie (Steve Van Wormer) and his posse,
backlit in full Delta Force mode. Scarcely have they swung into
action, appropriating the place for one fugitive night, plugging
into the power line, than the kids start flocking to it, first
electronically, then by car, foot, and BART. The Bay Area Rapid
Transit system plays a supporting role in one of the year's
funniest vignettes, a blissed-out rave crew member riding the
subway deadpan with a huge mirrored glitter ball in his lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Groove'' alternates in its pacing between convulsive lurches
and hazy floating episodes, mimicking the drugs, mostly Ecstasy,
that are a part of the festivities. The film gives equal time, or
nearly so, to Elizabeth Sun's disco goddess, Maggie, representing
the dancers, who are there for the music and the cool mode it
allows them to slip into, and those who are looking for something
more. Most prominent among the latter are Lola Glaudini's Leyla, a
jaded and slightly defensive veteran of Manhattan's disco wars, who
thinks she may have struck emotional paydirt with Hamish
Linklater's David, a bright nerd from East Lansing, Mich., laboring
to hide his shame over the fact that this is his first rave.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Groove'' falls back on teen movie formulas like the Night
of Fateful Encounters, it handles them lightly, smartly, and in
some cases even endearingly. It's hip enough to be unafraid of
feelings, but it's too hip to ever slobber, even when the
mood-altering evening throws a cloud over Dave's brother (Denny
Kirkwood) and his girlfriend (Mackenzie Firgens). DJ John Digweed
opens the door to a jumping soundtrack, and Harrison the writer has
given Harrison the director lots of wryly funny lines, spacy little
explosions of wit from the mouths of half a dozen characters. Yet
what makes ``Groove'' so likable is its basic sweetness and
brightness. It likes its characters. It gives raves the benefit of
any doubt by insisting that they foster a sense of community. It
even allows cops to seem cool. ``Groove'' is a stoner's holiday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 1334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2689 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-CHICKEN-BOS &LR;      06-23 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-CHICKEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANIMATED `CHICKEN RUN' IS SHEER POULTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
CHICKEN RUN 
Directed by: Peter Lord, Nick Park 
Screenplay by: Karey Kirkpatrick 
With the voices of: Mel Gibson, Julia Sawakha, Miranda Richardson,
Jane Horrocks, Lynn Ferguson, Imelda Staunton, Benjamin Whitrow,
Tony Haygarth, Timothy Spall, Phil Daniels 
Running time: 82 minutes 
Rated: G 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The animation sweepstakes are ramping up, what with
``Dinosaur,'' ``Fantasia,'' and ``Titan A.E.'' Now room must be
made for ``Chicken Run.'' The question here is whether the Aardman
gang headed by Peter Lord and Nick Park could sustain the
claymation wave they launched with Wallace and Gromit and their
other shorts. The answer is yes. It's amazing how much life they
can breathe into a load of clay. ``Chicken Run'' is essentially a
savvy remake of a World War II prison camp escape drama, although,
strictly speaking, its English farm setting could more accurately
be described as an Auschwitz for chickens, complete with oven.
</P>
<P>
   The film opens on a starry sky beneath whose infinite vistas
sits an oppressively confining chicken farm, ringed with barbed
wire, sporting a sentry tower, and patrolled by vicious dogs. It's
bad enough that the chickens are butchered when they stop laying
eggs. It gets worse when the farmer and his witchy wife decide they
can make more money by installing a huge, clanking Rube Goldberg
gizmo that would allow them to feed chickens in one end and remove
packaged chicken pot pies at the other. As the virago voiced by
Miranda Richardson puts it, chickens in, pies out.
</P>
<P>
   Folded into the very basic gotta-be-free story line is more than
a bit of subtle humor needling such British folkways as the
tendency to carry on uncomplainingly. As one chicken says when
confronted with their fowl lives, ``It's a living.'' But that's not
good enough for the pluckiest of the lot, Ginger, voiced by Julia
Sawalha. She's determined to escape, and keeps breaking out, only
to be caught and tossed in the coal shed before being thrown back
behind the barbed wire with the rest of the chickens. Only her
egg-laying keeps the ax off her neck, a thing we realize at about
the same time we recognize the homage to ``The Great Escape'' when
we see Ginger killing time by bouncing a ball off the wall of her
sooty cell, a la Steve McQueen.
</P>
<P>
   Into the picture drops a cocky rooster named Rocky, a Yank who
doesn't disabuse them of their belief that he can fly, and can
teach the bottom-heavy hens how to fly, too, although he's a
refugee from his own brand of indentured servitude as a live circus
prop, shot from a cannon. Mel Gibson's voice supplies Rocky with
all the wiseguy lingo he needs until the jig is up and he has to
rebuild his credibility fast after an old RAF rooster named Fowler
(voice: David Whitrow) invokes the World War II Brit resentment
against pushy Yanks who were rather more forward with the local
women than the lads deemed sporting.
</P>
<P>
   The RAF rooster, the World War II elements, and the mood of
foreboding expressed in dark visuals mark ``Chicken Run'' as retro,
taking place, one would guess, in the '50s. Still, its pro-freedom
imperative keeps it from turning into a downer and its expressive
faces keep you watching. Before turning into a celebration of
traditional British pluck, borne on the flapping wings of a
ramshackle aircraft, it carries forward the hint of threatening
forces that so often imparts to the Aardman animations an extra
edge. In short, there's plenty to cluck about. The birds never make
it look easy, but ``Chicken Run'' is a case of up, up, and away.
There's nothing paltry about its poultry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
