<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-ME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARREY, FARRELLY MAKE A FARCE WITH A SPLIT PERSONALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
ME, MYSELF &AMP; IRENE 
Directed by: Peter and Bobby Farrelly 
Screenplay by: Peter and Bobby Farrelly, Mike Cerrone 
Starring: Jim Carrey, Renee Zellweger, Robert Forster, Chris
Cooper, Richard Jenkins, Daniel Greene, Anthony Anderson, Mongo
Brownlee, Jerod Mixon, Mixchael Bowman, Traylor Howard, Tony Cox 
Running time: 116 minutes 
Rated: R (sexual content, crude humor, strong language and some
violence) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene,'' the Farrelly brothers' new farce about a
Rhode Island state trooper with a split personality, will satisfy
Jim Carrey fans eager for a return to the contortionist slapstick
that made him a star. Still, not even Carrey's spectacular comic
elasticity can conceal the fact that the film is hit and miss. It
has a few laughs, but it also has a lot of dead air, and barely any
plot at all. In sporting terms, it's no home run. It's more like a
bloop double, with Carrey barely beating the throw to the bag.
Luckily, it also has something entirely unexpected going for it in
a big way.
</P>
<P>
   But first let's talk about Carrey. He plays a sweet doormat
named Charlie, who's so resolutely sunny, like Truman in ``The
Truman Show,'' that he doesn't realize he's suppressing a lot of
anger. It has to go somewhere, and it goes into an aggressive alter
ego, Hank. Charlie and Hank go everywhere together. When Charlie is
assigned to look after Renee Zellweger's cutie on the lam, and he
leaves his medication behind while fleeing some bad guys, the
comedy kicks into a higher gear.
</P>
<P>
   There's a certain satisfaction in watching bad Hank settle some
scores with locals who have been stepping all over Charlie,
including a bratty little girl and a lunk in a barber shop. You
wouldn't want to see anyone but Carrey jackknife his way through
this stuff. But it all seems a bit mechanical and even old this
time out, right down to the showdown in Providence's train station.
Carrey did this warring-self stuff more hilariously in ``Liar,
Liar.'' One problem is that while Hank walks the walk and talks
some foul-mouthed talk to Zellweger (who turns in a surprisingly
blah performance), he's never convincingly, ragingly wild.
</P>
<P>
   He's just Charlie in overdrive, delivering what by now has
become the obligatory crude humor of the Farrelly brothers. This
time the jokes involve a dildo and a chicken, among other things,
but even here, Carrey and the Farrellys largely seem to be going
through the motions. There's rudeness in their antics, but never
anything as liberatingly outrageous as in ``There's Something About
Mary.'' It's excess by the numbers, and a little of it goes a long
way in this script, which has been kicking around for a decade and
plays like it.
</P>
<P>
   People expect political incorrectness from the Farrellys, and
they dutifully try to provide it. Some have attacked the film for
making light of mental disabilities and confusing schizophrenia and
multiple personality disorder. But the same freedom of expression
that can make the film irritating also opens the door to an
exhilarating take on race. One of the plot elements involves
Charlie's newlywed wife running off with a diminutive black
chauffeur and subsequently giving birth to triplets. In the film,
Charlie is the one who raises them after she takes off.
</P>
<P>
   Played by Anthony Anderson, Mongo Brownlee, and Jerod Mixon, the
sons have grown into three enormous teens with genius IQs who talk
like street rappers but are sweet, loving, obedient, and even
protective of their father. They reassure Charlie as he hops on his
chopper that they'll do their homework and promise they'll have
``no bitches in the house after 11.'' In discussions of mature,
responsible filmmaking, the Farrelly brothers' names never come up.
But here they are, talking about race in America with more daring
and bite than any other movie has this season.
</P>
<P>
   What we've got here _ apart from funny, endearing characters
embodied by Anderson, Brownlee, and Mixon, who'll surely be
reunited in their own movie _ is trenchant, hilarious, almost
Swiftian commentary about white America's inability to see blacks
except as stereotypes. Although we're told the triplets' father is
a Mensa chapter chairman, we can only handle him if he's being
presented in the subservient role of a chauffeur. And we can only
accommodate the idea of young black geniuses in triplicate if
they're served up in boom-box mode.
</P>
<P>
   Who'd have thought it would be the Farrelly brothers who'd be
making such a frank statement about the limits of whites'
capacities to perceive blacks? And what does this say about
America's so-called race problem? Unexpectedly, Hollywood's
gross-out kings have served up a lukewarm comedy with a right-on
wakeup call about race. You may go into ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene'' to
laugh at Carrey shuttling between Hank and Charlie. But you'll come
out loving the three endearing heavies I can't help thinking of as
the new Charlie's Angels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 1337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
