<P>
   GORE-PROBE (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno refuses to
say whether she will appoint a special counsel to investigate Vice
President Al Gore's political fund-raising activities during the
1996 presidential campaign. Asked in a news briefing about reports
that the head of her department's campaign finance unit had
recommended such an appointment, Reno said only that any probe
should be done ``carefully.'' By MARK HELM. (Story will be filed
also in the POLITICAL NEWS, or ``p,'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TAIWAN (Washington) _ China is in the midst of a sweeping
military buildup but is unlikely to attack Taiwan for fear of
undermining Beijing's top priority of continuing its economic
growth and gaining world prestige, a new Pentagon report concludes.
By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-ECONOMY (Havana, Cuba) _ Cuba, playing up its tropical good
times and rogue reputation, hopes to reap a tourist bonanza. Fidel
Castro expects a boost in tourist dollars to help the island nation
dig out of its economic hole created by the U.S. trade embargo and
the loss of Eastern Bloc subsidies. The House is expected to vote
next week to partially lift the embargo by ending sanctions on U.S.
sales of food, medicine and medical supplies to Cuba. By DAN
FREEDMAN. (Filed Thursday.)
</P>
