<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2735 &Cx1f; ttj-z
t a BC-FACTORY-MURDERS-HNS &LR;      06-23 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FACTORY-MURDERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FAMILIES AND FRIENDS RECALL THREE MURDERED MEAT INSPECTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By KATHERINE SELIGMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN LEANDRO, Calif. _ Jean Hillery was a grandmother of four and
master swimmer who volunteered to teach young kids at a local pool
near her Alameda, Calif., home.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Quadros of Hayward, Calif., was an avid Red Sox fan and
golfer who helped build a skateboard park last year.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Shaline, a father of three from Sacramento, Calif., loved
his job of more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The three investigators, together having more than 60 years of
experience working to ensure meat safety, were gunned down
Wednesday at a San Leandro, Calif., sausage factory. All worked in
jobs little glimpsed by the public, government positions that took
them to the unglamorous sites of slaughterhouses, meat packing
plants, grocery store back rooms and garages stacked with animal
carcasses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to tease her about how she could go to the
slaughterhouses,'' said Joan Thompson, a longtime friend of
Hillery. ``She liked the investigative part of it. She felt she was
contributing, which is something she always did. She was a
contributor, not a taker.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvin Riley, a lab support worker at the U.S. Department of
Agriculture's Food Safety and Inspection Service in Alameda,
described Hillery as ``very positive and very outgoing.'' But she
was also known as a stickler.
</P>
<P>
   ``She believed in sticking to the rules,'' Riley said. ``She
didn't believe in shortcuts. You come in and put in your hours. You
didn't leave five minutes early.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley said he couldn't believe the news of her death.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was shock _ that's the first word that came out of my
mouth,'' he said. ``It was something that was needless _ needless
tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   In her spare time outside of work, Hillery, 56, was treasurer of
the Alameda Swimming Pool Association, a private nonprofit
organization that ran a pool where young kids flocked for swimming
lessons. On Tuesday, the day before the shooting rampage that ended
her life, she showed up to teach young kids water skills.
</P>
<P>
   Hillery had earned her undergraduate degree from the University
of Phoenix late in life, after raising her three daughters,
according to Dave Warner, the father of one of Hillery's
sons-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was real proud of that,'' said Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Born and raised in Alameda, Hillery at one time worked for the
Navy in a civilian job, then later went to work for the U.S.
Department of Agriculture. Several years ago she was promoted to
the job of compliance officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked her if she were ever nervous and she said no, it
didn't frighten her,'' said Thompson. ``She talked about going into
peoples' garages and into grocery stores that packed their own
meat. She never seemed to be wary of anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Quadros, 52, her colleague, had worked for the department
for 27 years, according to his son Chris. Unlike Hillery, Quadros
had expressed his concerns to his son and a longtime friend in
Michigan, who says Quadros thought compliance officers should be
allowed to carry arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he needed protection,'' said Dan Masta, who has known
Quadros more than 30 years, since the two worked at a Michigan bar
together.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Department of Agriculture special agent-in-charge David
Dickson said Hillery and Quadros, as compliance officers, were
charged with making random, unscheduled visits to food preparation
facilities, including the Santos Linguisa Factory, where the
shootings took place. Compliance officers often focus on sites that
have a history of problems or compliance issues. They also pursue
tips from the general public or employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``They often go in unannounced. They sometimes set up an
appointment to talk about problems that they may have had in the
past,'' Dickson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compliance officers work on a roving basis. They travel
throughout the area and make visits.''
</P>
<P>
   Masta recalled Quadros' love of baseball _ expressed in his work
as a coach, a fervent collector of baseball cards and fan of the
Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Quadros said his father's house was decorated with
memorabilia from the Red Sox, the team he began following during
his childhood in Dedham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   He said his father was promoted from inspector to compliance
officer three years ago and loved his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was widely accepted as the best at what he did,'' said
Chris Quadros. ``He had supervisors from Washington calling him for
advice. He loved being able to make a difference in helping people,
in knowing that because of what he was doing people might not get
sick and die.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year Thomas Quadros volunteered his time to help build a
skateboard park in Alameda so kids there would have a safe place to
ride their boards. He was close to his 22-year-old son, who had
been living with him.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his death, Quadros was house-sitting for his
brother and sister-in-law, who were in Europe. He called his son
Wednesday morning and left a message that he was visiting the
Santos Linguisa Factory. That was the last time Chris ever heard
his father's voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw the news, I immediately thought, `Oh no,'''said
Chris Quadros. ``I called my uncle's house and he just didn't
answer. I drove over there and there was a card from the FBI. I
knew that my dad was gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Deven Shaline also lost his father Wednesday. Bill Shaline, 57,
was remembered by California Department of Food and Agriculture
Secretary William Lyons Jr. as ``one of our lesser-known heroes,''
a senior special investigator called in from his department's
Sacramento office to help in the ongoing investigation at the
Santos factory.
</P>
<P>
   ``His compassion and commitment to a very important job were
keys to his outstanding performance over the many years he worked
to ensure a safe food supply for Californians,'' said Lyons.
</P>
<P>
   Said Deven Shaline, one of Bill Shaline's three kids, ``My dad
was a great man. He loved his job.''
</P>
<P>
   (Pia Sarkar and Jim Herron Zamora of The Examiner staff
contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
