<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2737 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-CUBA-ECONOMY-$ADV25-H     06-23 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ECONOMY-$ADV25-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CUBA BETS ITS ECONOMY ON TOURISM
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, June 25)  
 &HT;     (Eds: Repeating story filed Thursday in the ``w'' category.) &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA, Cuba _ This island nation, playing up its tropical good
times and rogue reputation, is in the midst of a tourist bonanza
and wants to lure even more visitors this year.
</P>
<P>
   Fidel Castro expects a boost in tourism dollars to help Cuba's
11.1 million people climb out of the economic hole created by the
40-year-old U.S. trade embargo and the loss of Soviet bloc
subsidies early in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   The new optimism comes at a time when the House is expected to
vote on easing the embargo banning U.S.-Cuba trade by permitting
sales of American food, medicine and medical supplies to Havana.
The Senate has passed a similar bill.
</P>
<P>
   If approved this week, the House measure would have little
immediate impact on Cuba's balance sheet, experts say. While
allowing the limited sales by U.S. companies, the bill would still
forbid Cuba to sell its goods to the United States and would not
allow Havana to buy on credit.
</P>
<P>
   But Cuba, which buys rice and other commodities from Asia, might
save some money on transportation costs since U.S. suppliers are
much closer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the current embargo, $3 billion in direct foreign
investment has flowed into Cuba in the past 18 months, according to
the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. Last year, 1.6 million tourists _
60,000 of them Americans _ infused a record $1.9 billion into
Cuba's dollar-starved economy _ more than double the 1992 level.
Cuban officials hope the number of visitors will top 2 million this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would then be in the big leagues,'' said Tourism Ministry
adviser Miguel Alejandro Figueras, adding that only 40 nations in
the world receive more than 2 million visitors annually.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism has surfaced as an antidote to the economic double
whammy that followed Castro's seizure of power in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. embargo set Cuba adrift from its major trading partner.
And the downfall of the Soviet bloc between 1989 and 1991 meant the
loss of massive subsidies and trade worth more than $2 billion
annually.
</P>
<P>
   Those were dark times, literally. Cubans suffered through
frequent blackouts because of the government's cost-cutting actions
restricting the use of electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Food was scarce. Tourist guide Carlos Aguiar recalls losing 40
pounds and looking emaciated. ``And I wasn't on a diet or
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Cuba has reinvented itself as a dollar-based
economy, open to foreign trade, tourism and investment even while
it remains a centrally planned communist state.
</P>
<P>
   This city's skyline is dotted with new and renovated hotels,
some run by foreign firms under management contracts and others
under construction as Cuban joint ventures with European and
Canadian hotel chains. An Italian company has also overhauled the
island's telephone system.
</P>
<P>
   While Cuba is nowhere near China in opening up its economy to
free enterprise, it has transferred most of its state-owned farm
land to semi-autonomous farmer cooperatives and individual owners.
Cubans can run restaurants out of their homes and charge fees for
giving private lessons in foreign languages.
</P>
<P>
   Economically, Cuba is still in a slump. It exports about $1.4
billion in sugar, nickel, cigars and other products. It imports $3
billion, much of it food, oil and other necessities on credit.
Tourism surpassed sugar in the 1990s as Cuba's main source of
revenue, providing funds that are crucial to the island's efforts
to join the world dollar economy.
</P>
<P>
   In a nominally egalitarian society, the new economy has created
a curious class division based not on education or party membership
but on access to dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Cubans who work in hotels, restaurants and other places
frequented by tourists get dollars in tips and can buy hundreds of
consumer items that most Cubans cannot afford.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the physician or lawyer or engineer who wants to be at
the hotel's front door getting the bags of tourists,'' says
Figueras. ``There are a lot of jokes about that.''
</P>
<P>
   At hotels some Cubans strike up conversations with tourists and
then offer them boxes of cigars at cut-rate prices provided the
buyers pay in dollars.
</P>
<P>
   In a 98-year-old tobacco factory here workers hold up individual
cigars to visitors and mutter, ``One dollar, one dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   Without dollars, life can be bleak. Reynaldo Jimenez, a social
sciences professor, and his wife, Mercedes, a dermatologist, have a
combined income in pesos equal to about $18.50 a month. Medical
care and education are free, and with rationing cards, food costs
little.
</P>
<P>
   The Jimenezes live in a small apartment at the top of three
flights of unlit stairs. Asked to recommend a nearby restaurant for
an evening meal, Reynaldo cannot say because he and Mercedes never
go out to eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that a family is better off if its income is
in dollars,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Those with relatives in the United States can receive up to
$1,200 a year in cash, a fortune for the average Cuban. In all,
Cubans receive about $900 million from their relatives annually.
</P>
<P>
   Economic improvement is difficult to measure. In Havana,
tourists are shocked by the tattered condition of streets, houses
and windowless, one-room apartments.
</P>
<P>
   But Cubans like to boast that everything is becoming up-to-date
on their island. They note with pride that five years ago the
government, desperate for revenue, started taxing private income _
just like other nations.
</P>
<P>
   To build up tourism, Cuba has invested $400 million in airports
in the past 10 years to make all parts of the island accessible.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Figueras laments that much more must be done to develop
restaurants, nightclubs, sports facilities and other tourist
attractions. ``We have no theme parks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Cuban-American opponents of Castro are
fighting hard to prevent Congress from easing the embargo. Noting
that Cuba is often slow to pay for the items it has bought from
other countries, they call it a deadbeat nation.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Sorzano, a leading anti-Castro spokesman and a former
national security official in the Ronald Reagan administration,
warns that if the United States eases the embargo, ``the American
taxpayer will be asked to foot the bill'' sometime in the future
when Castro cannot pay.
</P>
<P>
   But many American entrepreneurs see Cuba as a risk worth taking.
</P>
<P>
   ``People all around world are selling products to Cuba and
getting paid,'' said L. Craig Johnstone, a former State Department
official in the Reagan and Clinton administrations and now a vice
president at the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. ``Would you as a
business person have to keep an eye on your business? Yes. It's an
impoverished nation, but clearly there are a number of
possibilities there.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
