   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS (Jerusalem) _ A campaign of leaks is
underway to pre-expose Israel's bargaining positions in the peace
negotiations in order to pressure Prime Minister Ehud Barak against
making significant concessions to the Palestinians. The latest leak
came today, when an Israeli newspaper printed the contents of what
it called an American ``non-paper'' that it said could provide the
basis for a three-way, retreat style summit in the Washington area.
Israeli officials dismissed the document as speculative and
Americans officials said it was unofficial, of unknown origin and
inaccurate. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE-ELECTIONS (Dateline to kum) _ Looking ahead to crucial
parliamentary elections this weekend. As Zimbabwe's population
becomes more urbanized and a new generation matures, the
authoritarian governing party is increasingly out of step with the
country it has led since liberation from white rule. By Rachel
Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-U.S. (Seoul) _ In an effort to dampen speculation that the
prospects of reconciliation on the Korean peninsula will lead to a
diminished American military presence in South Korea, Secretary of
State Madeleine K. Albright stressed on Friday that United States
troops would not be withdrawn any time soon. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TAIWAN (Washington) _ A long-delayed Pentagon report
concludes that China's military has built up its forces and
positioned them against Taiwan, but concludes that China is
unlikely to have the ability to invade Taiwan in the next decade.
The Report also deals with its nuclear forces. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-MEDIA (Moscow) _ President Vladimir Putin says that a
free press is the foundation of democracy. Media magnate Vladimir
Gusinksy, out of jail pending a trial on embezzlement charges, is
taken to a police station for interrogation and refuses to talk. By
Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Mexico City) _ Several new polls show Mexico's
two leading presidential candidates in a dead heat about 10 days
before the balloting, with as many as a quarter of the voters still
undecided. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ELECTION (Miyakonojo, Japan) _ With a Parliamentary
election on Sunday, one race in southern Japan shows the contrast
between the old guard and the insurgents demanding change. By
Howard W. French.
