<HEADER>
A2746 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-FIGHTER-JETS-HNS &LR;      06-23 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIGHTER-JETS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JETS IN KOREAN WAR CHANGED THE WAY WARS ARE FOUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Air Force Capt. Ralph Parr, flying high over MiG
Alley, should have been fazed by the odds. It was he and one other
F-86 pilot, after all, against 16 MiG-15s.
</P>
<P>
   And it became 16-to-1 on July 7, 1953, when he pushed forward on
his stick and dived from 43,000 feet to near ground level, losing
his wingman somewhere on the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The end of the war was upon us, you know, and this might be my
only opportunity,'' said Parr, now 75, of New Braunfels, Texas.
``It was sort of, in for a penny, in for a pound.''
</P>
<P>
   That day, he shot down two MiGs, damaged another and chased off
the rest.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Korean War was over, Parr had carved a niche in
American fighter-ace history by shooting down 10 enemy aircraft in
30 missions. A double ace might rack up those numbers over 150
missions or so, perhaps more.
</P>
<P>
   But this was a new war _ the war of jets.
</P>
<P>
   With the advent of the turbojet engine, aerial combat never
would be the same.
</P>
<P>
   The two jets most often associated with Korea are the F-86 and
the MiG-15 _ and the fast and agile Sabrejet in time ruled the sky,
earning an 8-to-1 kill ratio, said the Air Force's Pentagon
historian, Dick Hallion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys knew it,'' said retired Brig. Gen. Frank Gailer, 76,
of San Antonio, a World War II ace with 5 1/2 kills. ``They all
knew the Russians and Chinese were flying. That was no real
secret.''
</P>
<P>
   One Russian, Maj. Gen. Sergei M. Kramarenko, was an ace when he
came to Korea in April 1951, having shot down 13 planes in World
War II. Before he left the peninsula, Kramarenko would claim 13
more, nine of them F-86s, before being downed himself.
</P>
<P>
   Two of his victories came Dec. 1, 1951, when Kramarenko was
among 16 Russian pilots who shot down 20 Royal Australian Air Force
F-8 Gloster Meteor jets.
</P>
<P>
   The slower Meteor, a first-generation jet developed years
before, was no match for a MiG. Parr likened the duel to a Corvette
racing a Ford Model A. Making matters worse, the Meteors were
oblivious to the danger as they opened a ground support mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't see us and they began to attack the town,''
Kramarenko, 77, said during visit to San Antonio earlier this year.
``I was behind them, so we started shooting and shot two of them.''
</P>
<P>
   It was one of the worst days of the war for allied fliers, but
there was plenty of misery to go around.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the conflict Parr, a forward air controller, went into
hiding when his position west of the Chosin Reservoir was overrun.
From the top of a hill, he watched Chinese troops capture two
fellow controllers, then force them to their knees. The enemy
troops shot the airmen in the back of their heads and rolled the
corpses into a ditch.
</P>
<P>
   American pilots faced the problem of trying to stop North Korean
troops from advancing in the midst of refugees. In August 1950, the
soldiers donned long robes worn by Koreans for centuries, and mixed
with refugees massing on the Naktong River near an American base in
Taegu.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Lt. Col. Duane E. ``Bud'' Biteman described his anguish
in ``Hot Shots,'' an oral history of the Korean air war. Nothing in
his military experience had prepared him for the prospect of
killing civilians. He flew his P-51 Mustang low and fired warning
shots.
</P>
<P>
   For soldiers on the ground, support from P-51s often meant the
difference between life and death, especially after the Chinese
entered the war.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the war ended, American pilots logged 900 confirmed
air-to-air kills over 710,886 sorties and dropped 772 million
pounds of bombs.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. air power was credited by those on both sides with staving
off the initial North Korean offensive and later keeping hundreds
of thousands of Chinese from running the allies off the peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sig Christenson can be reached via e-mail:
sigc(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
