<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-PARADE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     S.F. PLANS WORLD'S LARGEST GAY PARDE ON SUNDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CAROL NESS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ This year's San Francisco Gay Pride Parade puts
its future right up front _ after the dykes on bikes, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Queer youth, the young men and women who weren't even born for
the 1969 Stonewall rebellion honored by gay freedom day
celebrations around the country, will set the tone for San
Francisco Pride 2000, which culminates with Sunday's mondo parade.
</P>
<P>
   If size matters, San Francisco's 30th annual demonstration of
gay liberation is the biggest in the world, with 220 contingents
and half a million to three-quarters of a million people taking
part or watching.
</P>
<P>
   Once again this year, it promises to induce gasps, laughter,
tears and some yawns with its four hours of political courage and
sheer outrageousness.
</P>
<P>
   The Women's Motorcycle Contingent kick-starts things at 10:30
a.m., heading west up Market Street from the Bay to the Civic
Center, where festivities last all afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   This year's emphasis on youth is intentional, going with the
theme ``It's About Freedom,'' according to parade organizer Teddy
Witherington, who was brought in three years ago to give the
world's most famous gay pride celebration a professional feel.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the changes on his watch have raised protests that the
freewheeling liberationist roots of San Francisco's parade are
being poisoned by overcommercialization.
</P>
<P>
   The budget has risen to about $850,000, with only a small
percentage returned to community groups. Post-parade festivities at
the Civic Center are being fenced off for the second year, with $3
donations requested.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there's only one dot-com contingent.
</P>
<P>
   The number of stages at the Civic Center is up to 10, including
new youth/techno, Asian Pacific Islander and swing dance stages.
Performers include Olive (``I'm Not in Love'') and Ann Nesby
(``Love is What We Need''), both currently on Billboard's Top 10
dance chart.
</P>
<P>
   The parade is the centerpiece of a month of gay, lesbian,
bisexual and transgender celebration in San Francisco, including
the annual film festival, parties, art exhibits and a beauty
pageant. Saturday, a rally against hate and a mass commitment
ceremony will take place in the Civic Center.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night's Dyke March, in its eighth year, has expanded
into an afternoon of entertainment and a rally at Dolores Park.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the weekend, PFLAG (Parents, Families and Friends of
Lesbians and Gays) will be co-sponsoring a domestic partners
registration booth at the Civic Center. It aims to sign up enough
couples to make a point to legislators considering gay-rights laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
