 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of SATURDAY, June
24.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (``e'' code)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IDEAS PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   REAL-ANIMAL-ART (Undated) _ The trend in contemporary art toward
using real animals. By Sarah Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-ADDICTION (Undated) _ The debate about whether drug
addiction is a disease: Dr. Alan I. Leshner, the director of the
National Institute on Drug Abuse, says that the brain of an addict
is fundamentally different from that of a nonaddict. Initially,
when a person uses hard drugs like heroin or cocaine, the chemistry
of the brain is not much affected, and the decision to take the
drugs remains voluntary. But at a certain point, he says, a
``metaphorical switch in the brain'' gets thrown, and the
individual moves into a state of addiction characterized by
compulsive drug use. These brain changes, Leshner says, persist
long after addicts stop using drugs, which is why, he continues,
relapse is so common. Addiction, Leshner declares, should be
approached more like other chronic illnesses, such as diabetes and
hypertension. Going further, he says that drugs so alter the brain
that addiction can be compared to mental disorders like Alzheimer's
disease and schizophrenia. It is, he says, a ``brain disease.'' By
Michael Massing.
</P>
<P>
   GEERTZ-ESSAYS (Undated) _ Review of an essay collection, ``The
Interpretation of Cultures,'' by the anthropologist Clifford
Geertz. By Edwin Rothstein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER CULTURE AND ENTERTAINMENT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NOVEL (Beijing) _ A Chinese publisher has canceled plans
to translate and publish the celebrated novel ``Waiting,'' by
Chinese-born Ha Jin, after the book was harshly attacked in a
literary review here as a deliberate attempt by the transplanted Ha
to portray China as backward and repressive. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   CHILDRENS-BEST-SELLERS (New York) _ Starting July 23 the New
York Times Sunday Book Review will publish a children's book best
seller list in addition to its regular adult lists. This is partly
in response to the imminent publication of the fourth book in the
Harry Potter children's book series, which has a virtually
unprecedented print run of 3.8 million in the United States alone.
By Dinitia Smith.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS &LR;  (``e'' code)
