<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2807 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-MARC-ANTHONY-HNS &LR;      06-23 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARC-ANTHONY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ENGLISH LANGUAGE CD A NATURAL FOR SALSA SINGER MARC ANTHONY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RAMIRO BURR  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ While the Latino music explosion has been much
talked about, salsa/pop singer Marc Anthony says that his
English-language, self-titled pop CD was not a radical step for
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That album just represents another side of me; it's another
way of expressing myself,'' he said. ``It is different than my last
three albums (salsa) in that, except for the last song, `Da La
Vuelta,' it is not a Latin music album _ it is a pop album.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up listening to Gloria Gaynor, Air Supply and Barry
Manilow as much as I listened to Hector Lavoe, Tito Puente, et
cetera. Some of the songs were inspired by personal experiences;
others came out of my imagination. This album made me realize that
I could write songs again as I hadn't written in almost 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony is on his North American tour that will see 19 more
dates, including a Sunday show in San Antonio, before wrapping up
July 28 in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   He said his album, which has landed the singles ``I Need to
Know'' and ``You Sang to Me'' on the pop charts, was a challenge
but not new territory. ``Muy Dentro De Mi,'' a Spanish version of
``You Sang To Me,'' was released later as a single and landed on
the Latino charts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everything that's out there is unique. I didn't set
out to do anything different or unique or that appealed to
people,'' he said. ``I just set out to put out the best possible
album I could make, something I could be proud of.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I took a risk, it was in writing my own material, because
when I started making the album I felt, `There are people out there
that write much better than I could.' But I took a stab at it and
after writing my first two songs (the two singles), it gave me the
confidence I needed to keep at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony is the only Latino singer who has sold out Madison
Square Garden twice, starred in a Broadway musical (Paul Simon's
``The Capeman'') and appeared in several movies, including Martin
Scorsese's ``Bringing Out the Dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Spanish Harlem, Anthony was given the name Marco Antonio
Muniz, by his father, Felipe, a musician who greatly admired the
famous Mexican singer. But Anthony changed his name to avoid
confusion with the older man.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony started out singing house music in New York City dance
clubs and later joined up with the Latin Rascals, who worked with
producer Little Louie Vega.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Anthony scored with the single ``Rebel.'' The following
year, Vega and Anthony opened for Puente in Madison Square Garden;
later that year, Anthony recorded his breakthrough single, ``Hasta
que Te Conoci,'' the old classic by Juan Gabriel. Suddenly, the
snowball started rolling fast.
</P>
<P>
   His musical influences are varied.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a child, I was influenced by everything from my father's
boleros and ballads that he would sing with his friends at our
home, salsa music my mother listened to, the disco music of Donna
Summer and Gloria Gaynor my siblings listened to, as well as the
Eagles, Air Supply, Steve Perry, you name it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started singing dance/free-style music. It was Tito Puente
and his belief in me that inspired me to sing salsa and it
completely changed my life.''
</P>
<P>
   His family was also ambivalent about his career choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family always knew I was capable and always believed in me,
but at 19 my mom told me to join the Air Force because music wasn't
paying the bills. I actually went through all the motions, got my
physical, enlisted, etc. and two weeks before I was to leave for
the Air Force I got my recording contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``So luck has a lot to do with it. But had I gone to the Air
Force I might have been a general or something by now. I would have
still put everything into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Was there a moment in his life when he felt singing would be his
career?
</P>
<P>
   ``I still haven't made that decision. Come to think of it, I
never decided I was going to sing; I just always did. I don't
remember a day when music wasn't a part of my life. I always knew
it would be my life whether behind the scenes or as an artist.''
</P>
<P>
   By the way, he hates classifications.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even begin to describe myself. I really don't like all
of the classifications. I am a pop singer and a salsa singer. My
salsa albums belong in the salsa section. My pop albums in the pop
section of the record store.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you come to one of my concerts you get both sides of me,
the pop and the salsa, and I play with two bands because they are
entirely different genres that tap into completely different
sensitivities.''
</P>
<P>
   And what does music do for him?
</P>
<P>
   ``The ultimate purpose of music, of what I do, is to tell a
story, to make people feel something, to interpret. I do something
you cannot see. I move airwaves, so that people can feel,
understand a story. My father taught me when I was a child that
that's what singing is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Ramiro Burr by e-mail at rburr(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
