<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2815 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-FORD-TRUCK-HNS &LR;      06-23 1245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-FORD-TRUCK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE FORD SVT LIGHTNING IS A HOT TRUCK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ After a few minutes _ no, actually, just a few
seconds _ behind the wheel of the Ford F-150 SVT Lightning pickup,
this week's test drive, I was glad of two things.
</P>
<P>
   One: That it is not often that I get vehicles like this to test
drive, otherwise I would get into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   And two: That there was no traffic cop riding behind me when I
goosed the gas the first time and this vehicle scratched off like,
well, greased lightning.
</P>
<P>
   This is, without a doubt, one of the two hottest trucks I've
ever driven; the other was the 1991GMC Sonoma Syclone.
</P>
<P>
   Ford says the Lightning will go from zero to 60 mph in just 5.4
seconds, and I believe it. I also believe that it probably would
take less than 10 seconds to go from zero to impound, especially if
that traffic cop really is behind the Lightning.
</P>
<P>
   In more than 15 years of testing cars and writing about them,
this is one of the most fun vehicles I've had the pleasure of
driving.
</P>
<P>
   The Lightning probably is the fastest production-model truck in
the world, and I know it is one of the fastest street-legal
vehicles I've ever driven.
</P>
<P>
   If I had kept it much longer than the week I had it, I probably
would have gotten some kind of ticket, as careful as I was. This
truck likes to run, and it really is hard to rein in. With just
light pressure on the accelerator, this baby jumps out and starts
moving like quail coming out of a bush. And without even knowing
it, you're way beyond the speed limit.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure how practical all of that power is in this country,
where the highest legal speed limit is 75 mph (and just 70 here in
Texas). This truck really needs a place to run, and public highways
just aren't appropriate. I would probably want to make arrangements
with General Manager Eddie Gossage at the Texas Motor Speedway in
Fort Worth to let me take this baby around the track occasionally,
just to blow the carbon out of the cylinders.
</P>
<P>
   As far as that goes, perhaps anyone considering purchasing the
Lightning should arrange for some regular track time at a nearby
speedway, or at least put a good traffic lawyer on retainer.
</P>
<P>
   SVT stands for ``special vehicle team,'' which is a group of
Ford Motor Co. car nuts who have been given free rein to take
ordinary, everyday vehicles and make them special, both in
appearance and performance _ but with the emphasis clearly on
performance.
</P>
<P>
   This team has reinvented the Mustang Cobra, the compact Contour
sedan and a handful of other Ford vehicles. But I don't think any
of those compares to the good looks and extraordinary performance
of the Lightning, the true truck lover's truck.
</P>
<P>
   Ford says it doesn't really make money on these
limited-production vehicles, because development costs far outstrip
what the company charges the consumer for the privilege of owning
one. The value to the company, officials say, is the
public-relations boost that these special vehicles give to Ford.
</P>
<P>
   And you will pay dearly for the right to own a Lightning. List
price for our test vehicle was $31,400, including $690
transportation. In comparison, you could buy a base model F-150
with a V-6 engine for not much more than half of that.
</P>
<P>
   But, hey, this is a special vehicle, make no mistake about it.
That base model F-150 will look like a pup if it challenges you to
a (legal) duel.
</P>
<P>
   One look under the hood of the Lightning, and you'll understand
why. It has a supercharged version of Ford's 5.4-liter Triton V-8
engine, rated at a whopping 360 horsepower and 440 foot-pounds of
torque. That's 100 horsepower more than in the regularly aspirated
5.4-liter engine, and way more than the 205 horsepower of the V-6
engine.
</P>
<P>
   The SVT engineers added a forged-steel crankshaft, forged-alloy
connecting rods and forged pistons, and lowered the compression
ratio to 8.4:1 to allow addition of the Roots-type supercharger,
which sits on top of the intake system. That's as technical as I'm
going to get.
</P>
<P>
   This engine is connected to a heavy-duty four-speed automatic
transmission from the Super Duty F-series; no ordinary transmission
would do. There is no manual gearbox offered, though; that would
push performance even higher.
</P>
<P>
   There are some sports cars that can match or slightly exceed the
Lightning's performance, but not any pickups except perhaps that
1991 GMC Syclone, which came with a 4.3-liter turbocharged V-6, and
was just about as quick.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the most practical truck, either, particularly if you
have a family to haul around. To ensure the best handling to go
along with the Lightning's speediness, the SVT engineers decided to
use a regular cab, short-bed, flare-side version of the F-150. You
can get three people in the front seat if you need to, but there is
no extended-cab version to allow you to take the kids along in the
rear seat.
</P>
<P>
   Round driving lights and a special front fascia design are
exclusive to the Lightning, which has the special ``Lightning''
badging on both front fenders in front of the doors.
</P>
<P>
   The interior is rather luxurious for a truck. The seats are
leather-covered, the door panels are leather, and there is a
leather-wrapped steering wheel. The driver's side has electric seat
controls.
</P>
<P>
   Other standard equipment included dual air bags with a
passenger-side cut-off switch; a premium AM/FM stereo with
single-disc in-dash CD player; dual electric remote-control outside
mirrors, four-wheel disc brakes with three-channel anti-lock
system; power windows and door locks; manual air-conditioning,
overhead console with electronic compass and exterior temperature
gauge; cruise control; remote keyless entry; and floor mats.
</P>
<P>
   Standard are eight-inch, five-spoke, cast-aluminum wheels and
special Goodyear Eagle tires _ Z-rated for high-speed operation.
There is a solid rear axle and a 3.55:1 limited-slip rear end; the
rear suspension has five-leaf springs, and there are gas-tuned
shock absorbers all around.
</P>
<P>
   Up front, there are coil springs and a solid stabilizer bar.
Steering is power-assisted recirculating ball type. The only
options offered are a soft cargo-bed cover ($150), towing package
($245) and an AM/FM/cassette stereo with six-disc remote CD changer
that fits behind the passenger seat ($210). Our test vehicle did
not have any of the options, however.
</P>
<P>
   To help ensure that no one steals the vehicle, the Lightning has
Ford's passive anti-theft system, which uses a tiny transponder
built into the ignition key, set to a special security code. It
must correspond to the code stored in the truck's engine computer;
if not, the vehicle won't run.
</P>
<P>
   Braking is awesome, which is a good thing for a vehicle that can
go 140 mph (I didn't try this; I'll take Ford's word for it). Ford
says the Lightning stops from 60 mph in just 137 feet, which is 10
feet more than it takes to stop the much-lighter SVT Mustang Cobra.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel-economy ratings are 13 miles per gallon in the city and
17 mpg on the highway. That's better than I thought they would be,
but they are calculated on driving this truck at posted speed
limits and with easy acceleration. Fat chance that's going to
happen.
</P>
<P>
   The tank holds 24.5 gallons of gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III can be contacted via e-mail:
chambers(at)express-news.net.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
