<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2824 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-BUSH-EXECUTIONS-1STLD     06-23 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-EXECUTIONS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POLITICAL ANALYSTS SAY BUSH ISN'T HURT BY SUPPORTING DEATH
PENALTY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: SUBS to correct byline)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PEGGY FIKAC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Knocked by death penalty protesters while on the
presidential campaign trail, Texas Gov. George W. Bush isn't likely
to lose votes because of his support of the death penalty,
political analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a burning issue. It's momentarily an issue because
the media doesn't have anything else to talk about,'' said Mark
Petracca, chairman of the political science department at the
University of California at Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from a state where Bush is fighting hard against
Democratic Vice President Al Gore, Petracca predicted the Gary
Graham story would disappear from newspapers' front pages with
``the first airplane tragedy of the summer or boating tragedy or
celebrity killed or celebrity divorced.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush has got the standard right line here, which is, `I'm
following the law,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Graham was executed in Hunstville, Texas, Thursday night amid a
clamor of protests that he was innocent of the 1981 murder he was
convicted of committing in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Political experts predicted little or no backlash for Bush as
long as he appears to be handling the issue consistently and
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically, it's a wash,'' said Bruce Buchanan, a political
scientist at the University of Texas at Austin. ``I don't see it
doing him any great harm or any particular good, although it could
reinforce his image for decisively standing firm under pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush will face 14 more executions in the state before Election
Day.
</P>
<P>
   The death penalty won't be a factor with ``the overwhelming
majority of Americans who are in favor of capital punishment,''
said Matthew Felling of the Washington-based Center for Media and
Public Affairs, which does content analyses of news and
entertainment media.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also is a death-penalty supporter, Felling noted.
</P>
<P>
   The worst damage done to Bush over the death penalty came after
he was reported to have spoken in a mocking way about murderer and
born-again Christian Karla Faye Tucker's plea to live, Felling and
others said.
</P>
<P>
   A Bush spokeswoman has said Bush's demeanor was misinterpreted
and that he took the Tucker case seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he really understands now he cannot appear to be
taking that issue lightly,'' said Allan Saxe, a political scientist
at the University of Texas at Arlington. ``The issue of leadership
and seriousness is very important.''
</P>
<P>
   Questions have been raised nationally about the general quality
of legal representation at trial for Texans given the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Texas officials, including Attorney General John
Cornyn, have defended the state's process as fair.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the state's Democratic U.S. representatives have urged
Bush to place a moratorium on executions until a study can be done
of capital punishment here.
</P>
<P>
   The governor of Illinois has done so in his state.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's office said he doesn't have the authority to
independently change death sentences or stop executions.
</P>
<P>
   He only can grant a one-time, 30-day reprieve unless his
appointed Board of Pardons and Paroles recommends otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Bush recently did this for the first time in a case involving
DNA testing.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest case to draw high-profile attention, that of
Graham, who was defended by such well-known figures as the Rev.
Jesse Jackson, officials said Bush couldn't even grant a reprieve
without board action.
</P>
<P>
   That's because former Gov. Ann Richards previously had granted
Graham an independent reprieve.
</P>
<P>
   ``This does highlight the weakness of the gubernatorial office
in Texas,'' said Dennis Goldford, chairman of the department of
politics and international relations at Drake University in Des
Moines.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all that Bush talks about leadership, the governor's
office in Texas, relative to that in other states, is fairly
weak,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Goldford said at worst the Texas death penalty issue at this
point is only ``slightly negative'' for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts him on the defensive a little bit,'' he said. ``Bush
has been setting the agenda of the campaign so far, and Gore has
been responding to Bush. This doesn't knock Bush off stride. It
slows down his offense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 1532EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2825 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-CHICKEN-H     06-23 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-CHICKEN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AARDMAN LAYS A GOLDEN EGG WITH `CHICKEN RUN' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Speaking frankly, here, the chickens in ``Chicken Run'' don't
look all that chickeny. Their beaks are rubbery. Their cans are
bell-shaped. They have teeth. And they're accessorized _ scarves,
pearls, Coke-bottle glasses, cute little beanies. One of them wears
powder-blue bangs and knits.
</P>
<P>
   At night, while the nefarious chicken farmer and his
even-more-nefarious chicken-farming wife are otherwise engaged,
hens as intrepid as the POWs in ``Stalag 17'' hatch not babies but
elaborately mapped-out escape plans involving underground tunnels
and egg beaters. Ginger, the plucky (plucked?) heroine of the
farmyard, constantly runs afoul (afowl?) of her owners and has to
cool her wide bum in solitary, otherwise known as the coal bin. In
moments of panic the girls throw their wings over their heads and
scream, in distinctly unavian tones, ``AHHHHHHHHHHH!''
</P>
<P>
   No one who has seen the clay-animated Wallace and Gromit shorts
would be surprised to learn that the architect of all this
noodle-headed brilliance is Nick Park, he who cast a criminal
penguin in ``The Wrong Trousers'' and cooked up a demonic
sheep-shearing machine for ``A Close Shave'' (whose luddite
sentiments prefigure ``Chicken Run's''). Park's short films are a
joy to watch, for grown-ups and kids alike.
</P>
<P>
   So it is with ``Chicken Run'', Aardman Animations' first feature
film, an utterly charming, utterly good-natured spoof of
prison-breakout movies that mixes fine-feathered swashbuckling with
sweetly dippy humor. Nick Park fans should enjoy themselves. So
should everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   The film's putative star is Mel Gibson, who lends his voice to a
swaggering (cocky?) rooster-character who wows the ladies midway
through. He is, more accurately, the lone American accent in a cast
of quirked-out U.K. voices that includes Jane Horrocks (as Babs, an
especially flaky hen), Timothy Spall (as Mr. Tweedy, the farmer),
Miranda Richardson (as Mrs. Tweedy) and Benjamin Whitrow (as a
snuffling old rooster who flew with the RAF). Some of the humor is
inevitably British and may flap over the heads of wee Americans. It
doesn't matter: What matters is the chance to watch broilers and
fryers boogying under a disco ball. Goofiness is universal.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Aardman shorts, ``Chicken Run'' draws comic derring-do
against a stark backdrop of good vs. evil. The poor, imprisoned
hens, living in barracks, forced to lay eggs or die, line up for
farmyard ``roll calls'' in which despotic Mrs. Tweedy inspects the
lines in tall black boots and a dress that fans in the back like a
stiff Nazi overcoat. The hen that lays the fewest eggs gets the
axe. Grim days, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Ginger has a hard time getting her fellow chickies
motivated for yet another escape attempt. ``So, layin' eggs all yer
life, then gettin' plucked, stuffed and roasted is good enough for
you, is it?'' she implores in her pipsqueak English accent
(actually Julia Sawalha's). Peeps a compatriot: ``It's a livin'!''
</P>
<P>
   Into this hardscrabble existence drops Rocky ``The Flying
Rooster'' (Gibson), an AWOL circus performer _ a Rhode Island Red,
so he's a Yank _ whom everyone assumes can fly. The girls agree to
hide Rocky for a while in exchange for flying lessons. This he
does, leading them in farmyard calisthenics and devising
suspender-driven catapults that yield disastrous results. Their
efforts turn desperate when thundering trucks arrive from the
ominous Poultry Products Inc. (``Turn your chicken farm into a GOLD
MINE,'' the catalog boasts), the ramifications of which make Oven
Stuffer Roasters look like sunny optimists by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   And so on and so forth, to delightfully muddled effect. Suffice
it to say that the hens' lives are placed in mortal peril, which
drew terrified squirms from my two children but never became too
intense to watch. The kids loved ``Chicken Run'': high on giggles,
low on confusion, rich with characters they could recognize and
care about.
</P>
<P>
   What violence there is amounts to chicken wrangling
(poultry-on-poultry; poultry-on-human) and a brief fisticuffs
sequence that morphs into a mudfight. There's nothing that tests
the ``G'' rating. And there's nothing that tests the patience of
adults, who should walk away from ``Chicken Run'' with a squawk of
approval and a lopsided grin on their beaks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
