<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2826 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-DRESSING-ROOMS-ART-$A     06-23 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRESSING-ROOMS-ART-$ADV25-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF THESE WALLS COULD TALK, EARS WOULD BURN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT3 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(For release Sunday, June 25) 
 By GUY TREBAY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You are standing with your pants around your ankles
when a stranger pulls back a curtain and says, ``Peekaboo!'' You
have been locked out in a public place wearing a single black sock
and a cocktail dress with a price tag hanging off the side. You are
standing in your underwear when the woman your ex dumped you for
strides imperiously into the room.
</P>
<P>
   Pop quiz: Are you 1) trapped in a Freudian nightmare, 2) a
candidate for a case study in ``The Diagnostic and Statistical
Manual of Mental Disorders'' or 3) out shopping.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, obviously, is 3. And the source of your deep-rooted
anxiety is that perennial bane of the shopper, the dressing room.
Strange real estate, and even weirder psychic landscape, the
dressing room is part dream chamber, part orgone box and a retail
no man's land. Often cramped, creepy and hard to locate, it is
sometimes locked tighter than an ICBM installation and sometimes so
public it could be the stage set for an ``Oh! Calcutta!'' revival.
</P>
<P>
   There are certain enduring mysteries that attach to the dressing
room, like why there is always a fossilized Cheez Doodle in a
corner, why there are never enough places to hang your clothes,
what the mystery stain is on the seat of the solitary chair
(assuming there is a chair) and how come the lighting seems
designed for the application of F/X makeup. Let's leave the fun
house mirrors aside.
</P>
<P>
   The dressing room is a site of particular interest just now, a
time of year that may look and feel like summer but that in fact is
an entirely different point in the retail calendar. For serious
shoppers, late June is not the season of fireflies and view tables
at Della Femina in East Hampton. By the time of the summer
solstice, anyone of serious shopping purpose has posted his jitney
ticket on eBay and pitched a tent in Barneys. Markdowns are in full
force, spring and summer apparel being treated by retailers with
all the affectionate hindsight of a drunken one-night stand.
(Thirty percent off at Prada, 50 at Ermenegildo Zegna, 70 percent
at Amy Chan.) The alluring first fall shipments have begun to
arrive. Veterans know that all the great back-to-school clothes
will be sold out long before the first maple reddens. Summer is the
new winter, as they say.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why you might think retailers would recognize the
importance of dressing rooms. ``Dressing rooms are where the rubber
meets the road,'' Paco Underhill, a marketing consultant, said.
``The dressing room is critical to the conversion rate. A lot of
decisions are made there.'' ``Conversion rate'' is marketing jargon
for that alchemical moment when a shopper becomes a buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers agree that the transformation takes place inside a
dressing room. What's odd, though, is that this consensus is rarely
reflected in the rooms themselves, which in Manhattan represent a
true rarity _ real estate nobody seems to want. ``The dressing room
is a very important part of forming the customer connection,'' said
Underhill, the author of ``Why We Buy: The Science of Shopping''
(Simon &AMP; Schuster). ``It reflects the store's ethos. Yet, they're
inconveniently located, no one wants to clean them, the lights are
god awful. It's almost as if the space belonged to no one.''
</P>
<P>
   A meandering tour, ranging from the scruffy chic of NoLIta's
hole-in-the-wall fashion outposts, to the sanitarium hush of upper
Madison Avenue boutiques, revealed that Underhill's diagnosis was
apposite. At Mayle, a Mulberry Street favorite of fashionistas,
customers dress in a tiny closet behind a scrap of fabric. At the
Union Square discounter Bradlees _ whose sprayed concrete ceilings
and sepulchral dim evoke the Soviet-era department store GUM _ the
dressing rooms resemble shower stalls and can be entered only after
garment pockets are checked for ``like, stolen bobby pins or other
small stuff,'' a saleswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Banana Republic in SoHo, the pleasure of capacious, well
appointed dressing rooms is offset somewhat by self-locking doors
that overplay corporate paranoia about theft. (Salesman to
customer: ``You all right in there?'' Customer to salesman: ``Oh,
just fine. Be out as soon as I finish concealing these khakis in a
body cavity.'')
</P>
<P>
   At Loehmann's on lower Seventh Avenue, customers continue to
dress in an infamous communal space. It's the way they prefer it,
Fred Forcellati, a vice president, said. ``If someone's got a dress
you want, you can say, `Oh, that doesn't look great on you,' and
then the minute they put it down, you grab,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   And at Jeffrey, the relentlessly fashion-forward store in the
meat-packing district, where shoes are displayed with the devotion
of reliquary fragments, customers change in an area whose general
lack of amenity and privacy bring to mind a visit to the school
nurse.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a perfect world scenario,'' said Jeffrey Kalinsky, the
store's owner, ``a dressing room would have a mirror, some place to
sit down _ and a carpet,'' because sweaty bare feet track dirt. It
would also have ample hanging bars, even bathrobes and individual
makeup masks, which are provided at the original Jeffrey in
Atlanta. The reality is slightly less heady. ``Who wants to try on
a $3,000 dress behind a shower curtain?'' Barbara Heizer, a
customer, said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The same people, presumably, who skulk behind the drapery at APC
in SoHo, slithering into $300 cigarette jeans in a semipublic area
where there is no place to set the clothes you just shed. Or the
ones trying on $1,800 Hedi Slimane suits at Yves St. Laurent Hommes
on Greene Street, where customers dress in a velvet-curtained
cubicle with the feel of a coffin that won't stay shut. (It was
there that a ``Peekaboo!'' interloper recently surprised me with my
Nicole Farhi trousers puddled at my feet.)
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days, fitting rooms were big and lush,'' said Betty
Halbreich, author of ``Confessions of a Retail Therapist''
(HarperCollins) and a personal shopper at Bergdorf Goodman for 23
years. ``They had bud vases and flowers. Now, they don't even
bother cleaning them. There's no privacy. There are pins on the
floor. There are cameras, which I suppose you have to have, because
there's so much thievery.''
</P>
<P>
   The ideal dressing room, Halbreich said, would be the size of
Staten Island and furnished with two slipper chairs, a small table,
numerous clothes hooks and bars, and a three-way mirror of high
quality glass. Halbreich, a realist, said she would ``settle for
enough bars in the room to hang the clothes I'm showing, and enough
light to see if what you're buying is black or brown or navy or
mouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Illumination is the most often cited of the many problems
related to fitting-room design. ``The basic issues are as simple as
enough hooks, a good mirror and good lighting, which means
incandescent and fluorescent, but masked,'' said David New, vice
president for creative services at Barneys New York. Underhill
considered that three light settings (day, office, evening) are a
fitting-room necessity. But a dressing room should provide more
than that. It should ``surprise you and make you smile,'' said New,
whose designs include dressing areas with walls of vintage
postcards and Tic Tac packages on Barneys' Co-op floor.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that the Swedish retailer H&AMP;M was making a
Scandinavian light bulb joke when it designed the dressing rooms of
its hugely successful new Fifth Avenue store _ where each cubicle
has a toggle switch and a sign that reads: ``Would you like to
change the light? If you press the button, the light will change to
a colder daylight, which shows the colors of the garments in a more
natural way.'' When a visitor hit the button the room went abruptly
dark. Color him black.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are three places I like to look in a store,'' Underhill
said. ``The ladies' bathroom, the employee locker room and the
ladies' dressing room. They're all spaces that are an important
part of forming the customer connection, and that give you a sense
of the corporate ethos.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Lauren Polo stores, Underhill said, display a rare
conceptual follow-through, carrying brand identity from the selling
floor into the dressing room. And it's true that those areas at the
Ralph Lauren flagship on Madison Avenue practically clobber the
customer with the aura of a private men's club: Spy prints and
sepia pictures of vintage sports cars, Chippendale-style chairs
with hairy knees. What matter if it's all a fantasy? Does the
average shopper care that most private men's clubs are likelier to
have snapshots of ancient tennis champions falling out of their
frames, and flaking club chairs with springs that come at you like
rectal thermometers? ``Probably not,'' Underhill said.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be Thorstein Veblen to recognize that
manufactured illusion is central to consumption. Why, then, has the
intoxication been allowed to leach from so many aspects of
shopping, one of the the core experiences of Western life?
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize it to be an issue,'' said Christina Johnson, chief
executive of Saks Fifth Avenue, which is undergoing a five-year,
$100 million renovation of its 650,000-square-foot Fifth Avenue
store. ``Appropriate environment and appointments are essential to
engaging with the customer. We fall short at times of the standard
that we set for ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Halbreich of Bergdorf's agreed that the shopping environment
counts for everything. ``Management talks about service, but rarely
does anything about it,'' she said. ``In the end, what is the
difference between all these stores? A little knowledge, maybe? A
little taste? Service is all you really have, and it's not service
putting people in cells. The dressing room is more than just a
place to change your clothes. The sale is made in that room.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
