</HEADLINE>
  
 A NIGHTOUT WITH ERIC McCORMACK: DIVA FOR A DAY  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or By DENNY LEE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Eric McCormack's wife didn't stand a chance Wednesday
night at the Amfar benefit at Ellis Island. Though she looked
pretty in her polka dot dress and a peony corsage, Janet McCormack
was outnumbered competing for her husband's attention. It was,
after all, an AIDS benefit, and McCormack, the evening's MC, had to
keep 700 mostly gay men feeling generous during a four-hour
program.
</P>
<P>
   A straight Canadian-born actor may seem an unlikely draw for an
AIDS fund-raiser, whose headliners are typically gay icons like
Liza Minnelli and Elton John. But McCormack is the star of NBC's
``Will &AMP; Grace,'' the sitcom in which he plays a gay Manhattan
lawyer whose best friend is a straight woman.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, he was having a hard time stepping out of
character. Primped up in a black suit by Banana Republic, paired
with a parrot green shirt and matching silk tie, the handsome and
affable McCormack camped it up, showing off vintage postcards of
Elizabeth Taylor he had bought while window shopping earlier that
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fabulous,'' one man said. ``He's perfect boyfriend material,''
another whispered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was called a fag since I was 2,'' McCormack said, explaining
that growing up he was shy and didn't play sports. ``When I started
this show, my biggest fear was that the community wouldn't accept
me.''
</P>
<P>
   By 7:15, the crowd was lining up for cocktails in the baggage
room of the registry building as McCormack greeted Mario M. Cuomo
and others near the paparazzi pen. ``I had to miss an event for
Harry Belafonte,'' said the former governor, who was there to
deliver a keynote speech on AIDS activism.
</P>
<P>
   At 8, a medley of salmon, chicken and filet mignon was served
upstairs under a vaulted ceiling decorated with the AIDS Memorial
Quilt. ``I keep seeing guards walking around,'' said Larry Kramer,
the playwright and founder of Act Up, pointing to the prisonlike
catwalk that circles the room. He was among the nine who were
honored by Amfar that night.
</P>
<P>
   McCormack took the stage to deliver introductory remarks. ``As a
straight man playing a gay role,'' he began, but the audio system
could not compete with the din of forks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's great,'' said James Dale, the telegenic Boy Scout
whose gay rights case is expected to be decided before the Supreme
Court any day, ``but we also need openly gay people on
television.''
</P>
<P>
   By dessert, a flock of admirers were surrounding McCormack.
``I'm a better leading actor as a gay man than I've ever been in a
straight role,'' he said. ``I'm just being me.''
</P>
<P>
   McCormack's limelight suffered a temporary blackout with the
arrival of the supernova of the AIDS charity circuit: Elizabeth
Taylor. Dr. Mathilde Krim, Amfar's chairwoman, took over host
duties to introduce ``the only person in the world who doesn't need
an introduction.''
</P>
<P>
   A gasp could be heard as Taylor, escorted by a phalanx of
security guards, swept onto the stage, wearing a pink organza gown.
You could have heard an AIDS ribbon pin drop as she spoke for six
minutes about ``strength, courage and fortitude,'' before she was
whisked away. ``It was like the coming of the president of the
United States,'' said Matt Coles, the director of the American
Civil Liberties Union's AIDS Project.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half a million dollars had been netted in ticket sales
that evening, in addition to $60,000 that McCormack raised by
auctioning walk-on parts for his show. ``You really do get to kiss
me,'' he said after announcing a winning bid.
</P>
<P>
   As the event wound down at 11, McCormack got a final laugh when
he bid adieu to the partygoers and said, ``There's a couple of big
fairies waiting for you outside.''
</P>
</TEXT>
