<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM HARD DRIVES LOST TO HATE CRIMES LAWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   News snippets worth noting:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ALAMOS: Thank heavens for that office copier maintenance
contract, or those hard drives would still be missing! The most
troubling aspect of the wayward computer components isn't that they
were out of the chain of custody for up to six months. No, it's the
thought that if the Energy Department will publicly cop to this
kind of incompetence, what's going on that we don't know about?
</P>
<P>
   Banish the thought. Better yet, banish Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson. Time for him to, as they say, to crowd the plate and
take one for the team.
</P>
<P>
   JANE FONDA: The actress formerly known as Hanoi Jane finally
said she will ``go to my grave regretting the photograph of me,''
referring to the much publicized and highly criticized 1972 picture
of her behind the sights of a North Vietnamese anti-aircraft gun.
According to the July-August issue of O, the Oprah Winfrey
magazine, Fonda admits the hurt she caused American soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   I take that as an apology. Time to write finis to that ugly
chapter of American history.
</P>
<P>
   HATE CRIME LEGISLATION: The U.S. Senate passed legislation this
week that would add offenses motivated by sexual orientation,
gender or disability to the list of hate crimes covered under a
1968 federal law.
</P>
<P>
   The sliding scale of justice continues. This needless piece of
law will make it possible for judges to issue stiffer punishments
for ``hate crimes,'' which are somehow worse than run-of-the-mill
murders. My puzzlement remains: Aren't all deliberate, intentional
crimes acts of hatred? No, say the senators _ motivation is more of
a determining factor than the final outcome.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that this bill has a cloudy future in the
Senate, seeing as how it was attached as an amendment to a massive
defense bill (makes perfect sense to me). And the House has
previously rejected almost identical legislation.
</P>
<P>
   DEATH PENALTY: One of my colleagues wrote a column Wednesday
that primarily consisted of the names of the 221 people executed by
the state of Texas since 1982 _ ``when the state resumed killing
people,'' as he so bluntly put it. His point was something about
the number of potential innocents that the state has executed, as
many of these people went to their graves claiming innocence.
</P>
<P>
   If only I could get the newsprint it would take to list the
names of all the victims of those convicted of murder since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   For the sake of balance, let's put capital punishment into
perspective. Since 1977 _ when executions resumed after the Supreme
Court, a year earlier, refused to ban capital punishment _ about
400,000 people have been convicted of murder in the United States.
Less than 1 percent of that number received the death penalty. Only
a fraction of those have actually been carried out.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, many of the executed claimed actual innocence up to the
end. But reviews of capital cases show that most Death Row
prisoners never make factual innocence claims in the appeals
process because _ hello _ they aren't.
</P>
<P>
   ``In only a handful of death row appeals are there claims of
actual innocence that are not patently absurd,'' wrote Robert V.
Pambianco, chief policy counsel to the Washington Legal Foundation,
for The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   Much is being made about the 87 Death Row prisoners who were
saved from execution by DNA tests and new evidence. That's just
proof that the system is not capricious and arbitrary, but rather
goes to the ``nth'' degree to make sure that only the guilty die
for their crimes.
</P>
<P>
   As Pambianco wrote, death penalty opponents aren't arguing about
the morality of capital punishment or that specific prisoners
shouldn't be executed. Rather, he said, they contend that the
system is hopelessly flawed and likely to lead to the execution of
many innocent people. And the mainstream media have swallowed the
perception that innocent people have already been put to death.
</P>
<P>
   The dent in the armor: There is no evidence, anywhere, of a case
in which an innocent person has been executed since 1900.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7599. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
