r k BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX     06-23 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PEOPLE CAN'T AFFORD THAT' _ BUT DO WE CARE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Washington today, I find a pervading forgetfulness of the
fellow it's all supposed to be about _ the guy we used to call
``the common man.'' (Let's add ``and woman.'')
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan seems to make the big
economic decisions unilaterally. He has raised interest rates
again, four consecutive times, and we hear not a peep.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the cumulative effect of these recent increases will cost a
young family purchasing a $200,000 home a couple of thousand bucks
a year more in carrying costs.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's concern _ ironic to those of us who remember the
suffering of past recessions _ is that the economy is ``too
exuberant,'' investors have ``unrealistic expectations,'' and
unemployment is too low. This is the first time in my memory that
any responsible party has publicly intimated that we'd be better
off with more people unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   The object of my concern is not Greenspan but an official _ and,
to me, heretical _ mind-set that has come to dominate important
policy decisions.
</P>
<P>
   It's a kind of elitist economic attitude in which ordinary
people and what affects them are not really important and therefore
surely not necessary considerations.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan worries about inflation. That's commendable _ part of
his official duty. But there'd been no sign of inflation. Prices
have been remarkably stable for a longer period than anyone can
remember. So why increase interest rates?
</P>
<P>
   During the Korean War, President Harry Truman countermanded a
Federal Reserve decision that would have raised the prime rate to 6
percent from 5.5 percent. ``People can't afford that,'' Truman
said. That memory comforts me.
</P>
<P>
   This one haunts me: In 1980, the Fed raised interest rates,
making inflation palpably worse (it reached 18 percent) at a time
of severe energy shortages. The Fed actually created recession!
Jimmy Carter's presidency was doomed.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to thinking of the national good, planners no
longer seem to consider what's best for those striving to rise from
the bottom of the heap, or how to ensure that prosperity filters
down to them.
</P>
<P>
   Former Labor Secretary Robert Reich reveals that the most
affluent one-fifth of the world's citizens already own 74 times the
wealth of those in the bottom one-fifth. That gap is growing,
having doubled in the past 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   This alarming trend did not result simply from interest rates.
It is the cumulative effect of both deliberate policies and acts of
official neglect by the world's governments. It's an expression of
a new outlook, detached from any sense of economic justice.
</P>
<P>
   One symptom of what's happening was the recent House vote for
repeal of the inheritance tax. About 98 percent of America's
families were already lawfully exempted. A couple today can inherit
up to $1.3 million without paying any tax. The bulk of the revenue
comes from windfall inheritances of $5 million and more.
</P>
<P>
   Yet knowing that we need our hard-won budget surplus to help
keep Social Security solvent, House Republicans voted unanimously
for this give-away that would benefit only the top 2 percent while
costing the Treasury _ and that's all of us _ an estimated $104
billion in lost revenue over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Now we learn that, because of the most recent congressional
welfare overhaul, close to a million low-income parents have lost
Medicaid coverage altogether. In Texas, 51 percent of adult
citizens have no health insurance at all.
</P>
<P>
   How shall we label the emerging philosophy? Is this, possibly,
what Gov. George W. Bush means by ``compassionate conservatism''?
Sen. Pat Moynihan once referred to an unofficial attitude of the
Nixon administration as ``benign neglect.''
</P>
<P>
   It all seems to mean that governments may sympathize with
distress but not alleviate it, endorse equal opportunity but not
enforce it, verbally encourage just results but not pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it is, it's a far cry from Harry Truman.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright(at)tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
