<HEADER>
A2845 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-BOOKS-INTERVIEW-$     06-23 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOKS-INTERVIEW-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PRAISE OF THE FREEDOM TO TAKE CHANCES
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BIZ-BOOKS ) 
 (For release Sun., June 25)  
 By FRED ANDREWS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeffrey Pfeffer, co-author of ``The Knowing-Doing Gap,'' teaches
organizational behavior at Stanford University, in the heart of
Silicon Valley. In an interview, he described how Internet
companies in particular could learn to put their best ideas into
practice. Following are excerpts from the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How does the knowing-doing gap apply to e-commerce? Those
companies seem hell-bent on action. Do they really need prodding? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I would quote David Kelley from IDEO Product Development, who
said, ``Enlightened trial and error outperforms the planning of
flawless intellects.'' What is often lost is the word
``enlightened.'' The knowing-doing gap is not just about taking
action _ it's about turning knowledge into action. E-commerce is
obviously about taking action and being fast, but it's also about
being knowledgeable and enlightened. Action without knowledge
doesn't get you very far.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do e-commerce companies already embody what you teach? Many
go to great lengths to foster cooperation and open communication.
</P>
<P>
   A. Some e-commerce companies have done a very good job of doing
what we talk about. Some have not. There's a lot of fear at some of
them, a lot of distrust. At some of them, there's a lot of internal
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Q. But some of them do things right?
</P>
<P>
   A. Actually I think Amazon is pretty good on most of these
dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   They have created a climate in which people feel secure enough
to speak their mind and tell the truth.
</P>
<P>
   I think the paradox you uncover quickly in life is that many
organizations say they want people to learn but they also don't
want them to make any mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Q. To whom is your book directed? The boss? The board? Just
anybody?
</P>
<P>
   A. It is certainly directed at managers at any level who have
the opportunity to create environments. And I don't really believe
that an environment is created only by the CEO. You know, division
managers, department managers, group managers, they have the
opportunity in their local domain, however big or small, to create
an environment that reduces internal competition, reduces fear,
tries to encourage people not to get stuck in the past but to build
a better future for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How does change get going? If bad practices are deeply
embedded, how do you get the ball rolling?
</P>
<P>
   A. I think philosophy comes first. If you're committed to
building a culture in which people really do feel free to take
chances, it truly begins with philosophy and mind-set. Then you
just try stuff and see what works, and you keep innovating.
</P>
<P>
   Q. But does uprooting the old way require breaking some bones,
inflicting some pain?
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't know that it requires inflicting pain or breaking
bones. Look at Continental Airlines. When Gordon Bethune and Greg
Brenneman took it over and decided they were going to run
Continental in a different way.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Continental Airlines was in pretty desperate straits, right?
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, pretty desperate. They got rid of the senior management
who had operated under what I would call a fear-based and
anti-employee regime. There does come a point at which you have to
say, ``This is the way we're going to operate, and people who
aren't comfortable with this culture need to find another home.''
But I'm not sure I'd go so far as calling that breaking bones.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
