<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIVE-QUESTIONS-OPEC-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWARD OIL PRICE STABILITY, STEP BY STEP 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 25) 
 By NEELA BANERJEE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ Dressed modestly in his native collarless
garb, occasionally fingering a strand of prayer beads, Bijan Namdar
Zanganeh, Iran's petroleum minister, led a contingent of similarly
reserved, gray-bearded men who together played the role of wild
card last week during the meeting of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries here.
</P>
<P>
   When high oil prices drove OPEC to raise output in March, the
Iranians, led by Zanganeh, publicly rebelled, complaining of one
too many late-night phone calls to negotiators from Bill
Richardson, the American energy secretary. Ultimately, however,
they increased their country's exports. Last week, with crude oil
once above $30 a barrel and OPEC again under pressure to raise
production, Zanganeh quickly went along with the majority.
</P>
<P>
   After weathering the manic dips and rises of oil prices over the
last 18 months, Zanganeh, like other OPEC representatives, craves
stability, which he believes the plan to raise output by 708,000
barrels a day should afford. It also helped, Zanganeh said, that
there were no more trans-Atlantic phone calls interrupting the
talks.
</P>
<P>
   Zanganeh, born in 1952, is a civil engineer by training. He
became petroleum minister in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   First at a press briefing and then in his hotel suite, Zanganeh
discussed the rationale behind OPEC's latest decisions and their
impact on the global oil market. Following are excerpts from the
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Have you had discussions with U.S. companies about developing
new oil and gas fields?
</P>
<P>
   A. We have had many discussions with U.S. companies. But they
have unacceptable limitations on their activity in Iran placed on
them by the administration. I don't think it's good for open and
free trade. It's a decision that goes against both sides. It
deprives U.S. companies from participating in our projects. We have
money to develop our fields, but we would prefer to have the
participation of first-class foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How did the atmosphere of this OPEC session vary from that of
the last one, which seemed full of tension?
</P>
<P>
   A. We had a very good atmosphere this time. In our last meeting,
all the members complained of U.S. intervention. We didn't feel
external political pressure this time.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How did OPEC arrive at the figure of 708,000 barrels a day?
</P>
<P>
   A. It was a compromise, and we will support it and respect it.
We ourselves will be producing 104,000 barrels a day more. The
decision was not hard, because we had decided before that if the
price got up to $30 a barrel, we would increase production by
500,000 barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   And it's all very close: a matter of oil being $2 more a barrel
than $30 and producing 200,000 barrels more than 500,000 barrels.
That is all much the same.
</P>
<P>
   We only validated our previous decision.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How would you respond to criticism from the United States and
other nations? that this agreement does not go far enough to dampen
high oil prices?
</P>
<P>
   A. We felt we must be very careful in this situation to test the
market. If the market needs more oil, we will produce it. We have
an automatic mechanism for it. And there are only three months
before our next meeting, which will give us time to see the effect
of this decision. Step by step, we will test how much the market
needs.
</P>
<P>
   We are looking for a stable price, not necessarily high or low.
</P>
<P>
   Now we are planning for oil to play a smaller role in our
budget. We would like to use the revenues from oil to create funds
that would support our private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is the automatic mechanism you have now within OPEC to
increase production if your latest decision does not bring down oil
prices? And why is there so much secrecy around it?
</P>
<P>
   A. This is what you call a gentlemen's agreement. Let's just say
that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
