<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2856 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-TAIWAN-PRESIDENT-HNS &LR;      06-23 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-PRESIDENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TAIWAN APPEARS TO BE IN GOOD HANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HENRY E. CATTO Jr.  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ I sat and watched the man at the podium,
acutely aware that he could involve his country _ and ours _ in a
nasty, perhaps nuclear, Asian war. Was he an Indian? A Pakistani? A
Chinese Communist? No, he was Chen Shui-bian. Still don't know him
? Well, he is the new and freely elected president of the Republic
of China, also known as Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion was Chen's inaugural address. I was there as
chairman of a delegation of U.S. think tank officials who wanted to
meet with the new administration and see that most exciting of
political events, the first turnover of power from one party to
another in a new democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The reason that Americans should care what Chen would say and
what reaction the People's Republic of China reaction would have is
that we are closely bound to both these mortal enemies. We are
bound to Taiwan by treaty, trade and democratic affinity, and to
the mainland by respect for its potential as a world power and our
huge trade with the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   The turnover of power brings the new situation to a head. Taiwan
is now a full-fledged democracy, a developed nation, and no small
beer. With 23 million people, its two-way trade with the United
States has burgeoned to $218 billion, mostly in computer and
electronics products. Once an aid recipient, it is now a grantor of
foreign assistance. Its economy has changed from overwhelmingly
agricultural to industrial, and its purchasing power per capita was
$12,009 in 1998. The mainland's was $3,600. It is our third largest
trading partner and the 14th largest trading nation in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's trade with the mainland has grown tremendously. There
are 35,000 Taiwanese businesses in China, though heavy industry
development is not permitted by Taipei, lest the island become too
dependent on its rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Indirect trade has grown to $22.5 billion. Ten million Taiwanese
have traveled to China since the unofficial detente between the
two. This travel has proved a mixed blessing for China. While it
has opened the country for investment from Taiwan, many Taiwanese
have returned home disillusioned by China's poverty and its brutal
regime.
</P>
<P>
   The triangular relationship among the United States, Taiwan, and
mainland China is rife with ``cognitive dissonance,'' a term used
by psychiatrists to describe holding two diametrically opposed view
at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   For the United States, we highly value Taiwan's emergence as a
democracy, its vibrant economy, rich with potential sales for
American companies, and its boost for the idea of democratic
solutions to development. At the same time, while we loathe China's
human rights violations and bellicose foreign policy, we like to
take the long view that the ``capitalist road'' will inevitably
lead to more freedom for the Chinese people and trading profits for
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   For Taiwan, the sweet smell of freedom and wealth makes the idea
of being subsumed into poor, chaotic China most unattractive. The
lure of independence is great. Indeed, President Chen's party has
(or had) an independent Taiwan as one of its goals. And it feels it
can count on U.S. support in time of trouble, a confidence not
absolutely justified by the facts, given American fears of a third
war in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   As for China, there is a genuine belief that Taiwan is a
province of China and that it must be returned to the mainland. The
timing is open to negotiation. The communists have even been
rumored to be open to a change of name, perhaps adopting Taiwan's
name of the Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
   They feel the United States is interfering in a strictly
domestic matter. On the other hand, if they lose patience or are
swept away by nationalistic fervor and invade Taiwan, they will, at
a minimum, lose the respect and investment of the United States and
other democracies, and in the worst case, they might feel the sting
of America's military might.
</P>
<P>
   For all three, it is a diplomatic nightmare. For the United
States, there are choices, all unsatisfactory. We can (1) stay out,
regardless; (2) attempt to mediate; (3) pressure Taipei to come to
terms; (4) guarantee Taiwan protection; or (5) take a posture of
Oriental ambiguity and let both sides guess how we will react,
while striving mightily for time via negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   We would hope that China's extraordinary economic progress will
eventually bring moderation in its approach to the issues (though
it is far from certain that a democratic mainland would be
accommodating on the matter).
</P>
<P>
   Thus it is that we would all do well to keep an eye on the
handsome, smiling, bespectacled new president in Taiwan. We will
have a Chen Shui-bian in our future for sure. Fortunately, there is
good reason to think that his thriving country is in good hands.
</P>
<P>
   --------------------------------------------------------------------
------
</P>
<P>
   (Henry Catto Jr. is chairman of the Atlantic Council of the
United States
</P>
<P>
   and is a former ambassador and assistant secretary of defense.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
