u k BC-EDITORIAL-FEDBUDGET06     06-23 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-FEDBUDGET0624-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDITORIAL: Light years from true surplus, Washington must
maintain focus
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our leaders are a lot like the football player who celebrates
too early before crossing the goal line. Then he gets the ball
stripped. Then he gets booed off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is trumpeting a surplus. Pay dirt. Actually, all
Washington has done is move the chains. That's something. Ten whole
yards, much dust. But first down is no touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   After many years going into a gale, Washington has found the
wind at its back. A booming economy, plus austerity measures, plus
presidential vetoes that blunted too-generous tax-cuts, will yield
a true annual surplus at the end of this fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's ``surplus'' wasn't even that, if the general fund is
what one has in mind. That surplus relied on excess cash in the
Social Security trust fund. Without that, America would have been
in the red again.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in addition to projecting a true surplus this year _
meaning no padding needed from Social Security _ the Clinton
administration is projecting a $1.9 trillion surplus by the year
2010.
</P>
<P>
   That would be stunning, but not worth celebrating, since we'd
still be trillions of dollars short of paying off the national
debt.
</P>
<P>
   Right now that debt is $5.7 trillion _ $2.2 trillion of which
the government owes to its own trust funds, including Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's budget envisions eliminating the national
debt entirely by 2013. That sounds futuristic. In the
present-tense, leaders and candidates are far more interested in
cutting taxes or spending than in curbing that debt.
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential hopeful George W. Bush wants a $1
trillion tax cut over 10 years. His rival, Vice President Al Gore,
wants to use annual surpluses to pay down debt and pay some of the
IOUs held by Social Security. However, Gore also talks of a
``Social Security-plus'' 401(k)-style retirement option, government
matching contributions by as much as $3 for every $1, that could
cost $200 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's proposal for taking a 2 percent slice from Social
Security taxes to allow recipients to invest in the stock market
relies on economic prosperity and, if not, unknown cuts in benefits
to make everything add up.
</P>
<P>
   It is unwise, indeed silly to proceed with the notion that the
current economic boom will last another 13 years. That's unlikely,
maybe impossible. Washington must be more cautious with its
promises.
</P>
<P>
   What a grand day it would be if in 2013 we could retire the debt
and dance in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   But we aren't even to midfield yet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
