<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAMPTONS-WEEKEND-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVIVING THE HAMPTONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 25)  
 By BOB MORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An island village. The end of the weekend. An oversubscribed
jitney back to civilization. An angry mob encircles and entraps it
until the police come. This is not an episode of ``Survivor,'' the
CBS reality television series that pits 16 castaways against one
another as they vote each other off their island, one per week.
Rather, it's another true tale of survival in the Hamptons, where
people drive tanklike cars to battle for parking spaces, litigate
like tribal warriors and endure monsoons of bad press, and even
jail.
</P>
<P>
   Last Labor Day, a weekender too embarrassed to give her name was
leaving Jimmy Buffett's party in Sag Harbor when she was arrested
for drunken driving, then locked up in Riverhead. ``They wouldn't
even let me get my pashmina shawl out of my car,'' she said. ``So I
spent the night in nothing but a little lime green vintage cocktail
dress.''
</P>
<P>
   A true survivor, she was back this Memorial Day weekend to dine
out on her tale.
</P>
<P>
   Sarongs. Desperation. Control freaks. Tiki torches. Competition
between South and East. Hipsters in status sneakers. Back-stabbing.
Eating obsessions. The occasional black person. The Hamptons and
``Survivor'' have so much in common that it's hard to tell the two
contests of wits and wills apart.
</P>
<P>
   One island has punitive ``island council'' meetings. The other
has a local judge administering a verbal spanking and a $2,000 fine
to Puffy Combs for giving loud parties. One has exhausting relay
races with people competing for buried treasure. The other has
back-to-back parties competing for guests and charity dollars. One
has immunity idols. The other has matinee idols. Both are crawling
with sand crabs, stylists and cameras, one for network television,
the other for a ``Real World''-type Internet series on
HamptonsTV.com about a summer share _ recently cited by the town of
Southampton. Both have islanders with coveted building skills
(contractors are gods in the Hamptons) and clever map readers like
Jodi Della Femina, author of ``Jodi's Shortcuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, both have high-strung people in a beautiful setting
watching each other's every ugly move.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Donna Karan, Alec Baldwin and Martha Stewart (who
braved a recent fire in her Lily Pond Lane home), the photographer
Patrick Demarchelier is a survivor who knows how to avoid trouble.
He keeps three boats in Three Mile Harbor in East Hampton and
rarely goes ashore. ``People like to go to parties, and it is so
boring,'' said Demarchelier, who is French. ``City people don't
like the country, but in life, you have to love nature. If you
don't understand the tree and the ocean, you are in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   You also have to understand migratory traffic patterns. ``I
think the answer is to get out there early and then not leave your
house all weekend,'' said Rona Jaffe, whose latest novel, ``The
Road Taken,'' is being published this month and whose iHamptons.com
column takes on issues like firewood-stealing neighbors. Her social
endurance is often tested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't stand being in a home that makes me feel like I'm in a
museum,'' she said. ``I went to Jay Chiat's house for a Planned
Parenthood benefit, and he had a red rope in front of the bedroom.
Did he think I was going to jump up and down on his bed?'' Well, at
least Chiat's guests could use the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in the wake of vociferous carping over his proposed
new pier and house renovation, Tommy Mottola fled the Hamptons.
This year, Billy Joel sold Jerry Seinfeld his house and retreated
to Nassau County. The Baroness Milly de Cabrol won't be back,
either. ``We rented a house last July and there was a construction
pit next door so that the noise was worse than Manhattan,'' she
said. ``This year I'm going to Tangier, which won't be nearly as
dusty.''
</P>
<P>
   Paolo Zampolli, the president of ID Model Management, meanwhile,
is giving up the Hamptons on the Fourth of July for Brazil. ``It's
easier to go to Brazil,'' said Zampolli, who got on and off the
island last summer by helicopter, ``and it's cheaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Hamlisch is gone. Lee Radziwill is, too, at least for the
season. Then there's Michael M. Thomas, the Old Hamptons novelist
who rages against the New Hamptons in his New York Observer column.
He sold his Sag Harbor home and has moved to Dumbo, the area in
Brooklyn under the Manhattan Bridge. ``I think life in the Hamptons
is poison to writers,'' he said. ``Brooklyn feels more like Sag
Harbor than Sag Harbor as it is now.''
</P>
<P>
   Other casualties? The party-giving Wilzig brothers are selling
their Water Mill castle. The 516 area code is gone for good.
Maya's, the St. Bart's restaurant that arrived triumphally in
Wainscott last season, was not a survivor, even with children of
the rich and famous waiting tables. ``It had high prices, valet
parking and too much attitude,'' one wag sniped.
</P>
<P>
   Week by week, summer by summer, season by season, we watch with
cannibalistic glee as alliances are made and broken by tan people
circling each other and driven by fierce inner fires of
opportunism.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Courtney Sale Ross has replaced Ira Rennert, builder
of a massive and massively reviled Sagaponack house, as the newest
problem member of the Hamptons mogul tribe. ``She wants to build a
big institute in the woods,'' said Steven Gaines, the ``Philistines
at the Hedgerow'' author and the founder of iHamptons.com. ``We
would love to vote her off the island.''
</P>
<P>
   Extinguish your torch, Ross. It may be time for you to go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 1624EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
