<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2859 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-IRENE-HNS     06-23 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-IRENE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A LITTLE SOMETHING FOR EVERYBODY IN NEW CARREY FLICK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KRIS WORRELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's get right to the disclaimer. The following people may be
offended by ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene'': African-Americans, lesbians,
animal lovers, the disabled, midgets, parents, albinos, Germans,
members of Mensa and anyone with good taste.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, there's something for everybody in the new
comedy from brothers Peter and Bobby Farrelly (``Kingpin,''
``There's Something About Mary''), who have built a career on
grossing out audiences. ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene'' reunites the
filmmakers with Jim Carrey, who also starred in their 1994 debut,
``Dumb and Dumber.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie follows a similar format to ``Mary,'' their hilarious
1998 hit, with a hapless dork at the center of a love triangle.
Charlie Baileygates (Carrey) is a 17-year veteran of the Rhode
Island police force whose wife has left him and their three sons.
Charlie is an affable doormat, the kind of guy who just smiles when
a neighbor steals his newspaper and lets his dog poop in Charlie's
yard.
</P>
<P>
   But one day Charlie snaps and out comes Hank, Charlie's rude,
mean, violent alter-ego. Hank exacts revenge _ and then some _ on
almost everyone who has abused Charlie over the years. Let's just
say you wouldn't want to be Hank's neighbor (who receives one of
Hank's more graphic paybacks).
</P>
<P>
   Charlie is diagnosed with split-personality disorder, a premise
that gives Carrey ample opportunity to deliver his usual goofy,
gangly-limbed, rubber-faced, hyperkinetic performance. A scene in
which his two personalities engage in a raucous fistfight with each
other is classic Carrey.
</P>
<P>
   Having Carrey play a character with two personalities is hardly
a stretch. In fact, it could almost be a metaphor for Carrey's
career, one that finds the talented actor mesmerizing audiences
with dramas like ``The Truman Show'' one minute and mucking around
in low-brow comedies like ``Ace Ventura'' the next.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie is dispatched to drive Irene (Renee Zellweger), a
suspect in a hit-and-run case, from Rhode Island to upstate New
York. On the way, they are intercepted by a gratuitous subplot
involving crooked cops, the EPA and a golf course.
</P>
<P>
   Gags land in front of the pair, literally, for no particular
reason and with such frequency that the movie sometimes seems more
like a series of skits than a feature film _ perhaps because the
script, written initially in 1990 by the Farrellys, was unearthed
after the success of ``Mary'' and rewritten by the brothers and a
childhood friend. Like some second-rate prom date, ``Irene'' lacks
the cleverness and witty twists of ``Mary.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrey pulls out all the stops here, but one of the film's
weaknesses is that it relies too heavily on the actor's charisma
and physical comedy to carry it. And while he delivers plenty of
charm and chuckles, Carrey can only make so many sex-toy jokes,
contort his face and flail his arms before the whole idea of two
Jim Carreys begins to wear thin.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that, unlike in ``Mary,'' in which Ben Stiller
played off the solid performances of Cameron Diaz and Matt Dillon
as well as a cast of zany supporting characters, Carrey is pretty
much on his own here. Zellweger plays Irene, the love interest,
with the same sweet softness she brought to her role in ``Jerry
Maguire,'' but it doesn't work as well here _ she simply doesn't
have Diaz's sunny goofiness or comedic timing.
</P>
<P>
   And the supporting characters aren't much help, either. You
won't find anyone in this film as creepy and hilarious as Chris
Elliot's zit-faced stalker, or even the crotch-crunching pooch in
``Mary.'' Charlie's three high-school-age sons are funny at first,
until the one-joke premise on which they're based runs out of
steam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene'' might as well be called ``The Carrey
Show.'' You'll laugh, you'll cringe, but there's still something
about ``Mary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 1626EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
