<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2862 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-GRANDAM-REVIEW0624-CO     06-23 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRANDAM-REVIEW0624-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pontiac Grand Am appealing
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Although its styling runs ahead of its performance,
the Pontiac Grand Am still offers a balance of features that makes
it the division's best-selling car.
</P>
<P>
   Cat-eye headlamps, twin front grilles and round fog lamps give
the Grand Am instant recognition as a Pontiac, while the interior
appointments and layout show the General Motors corporate stamp
with rounded and recessed dials, too-small stereo radio controls
and working drink holders.
</P>
<P>
   Pricing and availability of models are definite pluses, with
Grand Ams starting at $16,455 for a base coupe and going through
SE1 and SE2 versions before topping out at $21,885 for a GT1 sedan.
The standard engine is a 150-horsepower four-cylinder, with a
170-/175-hp V-6 available. The stronger engine will enable the
Grand Am to deliver some of the performance promised by its sporty
look.
</P>
<P>
   In sedan form, as the test SE1 tagged at $20,005 showed, the
Grand Am is a useful car that can serve a family of four well.
Leave the coupe to singles and couples with no kids, because of the
expected difficulty of rear entry. Cargo room is good with a
14.6-cubic-feet trunk, but the opening is on the smallish side,
making it awkward to load packages and objects, for which the trunk
has plenty of space.
</P>
<P>
   Traction control and anti-lock brakes are standard on all Grand
Ams, and there's even a five-speed Getrag transmission offered on
some models _ not, however, with the V-6, which comes only with an
automatic. The four-speed is smooth enough, but the test Grand Am's
console-mounted shifter did spend a lot of time in the ``3''
position in order to have decent acceleration, particularly in
speed-up, slow-down expressway traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The four-cylinder engine, which generates peak horsepower at a
decidedly noisy 5,600 rpm, does make all 155 pounds-feet of its
torque at a more utilitarian 4,400 rpm. This, however, is not an
engine so quiet that anyone is likely to attempt to start it only
to find it running.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Am's ride is on the firm side, but not uncomfortably
so. The power steering and brakes have a fair degree of feel, but
the Grand Am is not a great-handling car. It can be pushy and slow
to come around in turns and on entry/exit ramps.
</P>
<P>
   But, as indicated by its sales-leading status, the Grand Am has
the features and utility to give it the appeal vital to success in
the compact class.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
