<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2864 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-WONG-COLUMN-!STLD-WRI     06-23 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WONG-COLUMN-!STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MALE BONDING: GOOD, BAD, SOMETIMES UGLY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: FIXES 8th graf, removing extra word ``announcement)  
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WILLIAM WONG  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PIEDMONT, Calif. _ It may not be obvious, but football star
Steve Young's retirement announcement and the New York Central Park
assaults have something
</P>
<P>
   in common _ male bonding.
</P>
<P>
   The Young event showed male bonding at its sweetest and
gentlest. The New York incident was male bonding at its most vile.
Nonetheless, both high-profile occurrences reminded the world that
men commune with one another in ways that subordinate women.
</P>
<P>
   This affirmation of maleness comes at a wholly ambivalent period
in contemporary male-female relations in the Western world.
Feminist struggles have yielded remarkable gains for women. They
have become well-integrated in the corporate world, as well as in
the public sector.
</P>
<P>
   A few women are chief executives of major companies. Two women
from the San Francisco Bay Area are U.S. senators representing
California. The secretary of State is a woman. First lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton is running for U.S. senator from New York. Several
women are prominent national TV sportscasters, long a men-only job.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, feminist victories have engendered a fierce
male backlash, aided in some cases by compliant women. While the
wage gap has narrowed, men still generally out-earn women for doing
the same kind of work.
</P>
<P>
   Culturally, we are in a Playboy retro period in which feminine
pulchritude is highly valued by the mostly male policy makers in
the entertainment world _ and by countless panting young men.
</P>
<P>
   Sexy lingerie purveyors flaunt their stuff all over commercial
TV, popular periodicals and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Young's long-awaited announcement of his retirement from
the San Francisco 49ers was an unfiltered exhibition of male
bonding. When, in his rambling remarks, he thanked all his coaches
and many teammates and even the team's support staff and sports
journalists, one could almost feel the camaraderie Young had
nurtured throughout his prodigious athletic career.
</P>
<P>
   For mere mortals, there might have been a trace of envy. Here
was a handsome man _ gifted in athletic and intellectual ways _ who
had become a heroic figure, now facing perhaps an even brighter
future _ newly married with a baby on the way and numerous options
in the corporate, legal and sports broadcasting world and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Going through the football wars, as Young has, is one
manifestation of male bonding. Another is going through real wars.
</P>
<P>
   The transition from one millennium to the next has brought us
many retrospectives on the great wars of the 20th century, and we
have seen countless tributes to veterans of those wars. What comes
across strongly is the bonding among the men who survived.
</P>
<P>
   War is the nastiest of collective human endeavors, yet men who
miraculously manage to escape alive retain indelible feelings about
the shared experience. Those who didn't go through the experience
wouldn't understand.
</P>
<P>
   The Central Park assaults are a form of male bonding gone
haywire. A bunch of guys, fueled by beer and other alcoholic and
perhaps narcotic stimulants, express their base animal instincts
when women approach. It's not just a herd of New York schmoes who
behave like wild dogs in heat.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the Tailhook incident of the early 1990s when a
convention of Navy aviators, all liquored up, assaulted women in a
Las Vegas hotel? We also see the potential for this kind of extreme
male bonding at professional sporting events like 49er and Raider
football games. Juiced from too much booze and the excitement of
watching their gridiron heroes smashing into one another, men in
the stands scream their heads off and threaten all sorts of mayhem
on fans wearing the jerseys of the opposing team.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, the players themselves _ whether on the football
field, baseball diamond, hockey rink, or basketball court _ are
transformed into mobs.
</P>
<P>
   Boys just being boys.
</P>
<P>
   (William Wong is an independent journalist and Examiner
columnist whose book, ``Yellow Journalist,'' will be published by
Temple University in February 2001.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
