<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2867 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BRYAN-CHAFIN0624-COX     06-23 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRYAN-CHAFIN0624-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wimberley's resident movie star
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ His mouth stretches wide, the lips contorting
slightly sideways, tiny teeth exposed. His small hand _ the one
with the big Band-Aid on its thumb _ moves to cover the hole, but
the gesture is in vain. Bryan Chafin, Hollywood actor, Nintendo fan
and French fries lover, is yawning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry, I'm not a morning person,'' he says, the gaping mouth
shrinking into a little boy's smile.
</P>
<P>
   It's 10:30 in the morning, but Bryan's mom, Juli, woke him up at
8 so they could be out of their Wimberley home by 9 and be here, in
Austin, on time for an interview with a journalist. I commiserate
with the boy by yawning, and our fraternity of fatigue is sealed.
</P>
<P>
   The kid's a movie star. Bryan, an 11-year-old Texas native,
co-stars in Mel Gibson's new film ``The Patriot,'' which opens
nationwide Wednesday. Directed by ``Independence Day'' and
``Godzilla'' helmer Roland Emmerich and written by ``Saving Private
Ryan's'' Robert Rodat, the nearly three-hour movie is a surefire
summer smash, spilling with pulse-quickening battle scenes, moist
family melodrama and oodles of patriotic hokum.
</P>
<P>
   Set during the American Revolution in 1776, it tells the story
of devout family man and war hero Benjamin Martin, played by
Gibson, who takes up arms against the English when his family's
safety is threatened. Bryan, bedecked in a ponytail and
button-laden Colonial attire, plays one of Gibson's four sons,
Samuel Martin. Bryan gets 19th billing in a credited cast of 61.
His character is listed before Gen. George Washington.
</P>
<P>
   This is Bryan's first major film after a passel of commercials
and independent movies made in Central Texas. He doesn't look like
a movie star. He looks like a good kid _ elfin face, freckly nose,
sandy hair and a precocious grin _ who might ruffle his parents on
occasion but gets stellar grades and loves sports.
</P>
<P>
   Child stars can be a pain. Just ask W.C. Fields. Or me. The
hellion who played the young Darth Vader in ``The Phantom Menace,''
for example, cut a swath of bratty petulance through the nation's
press corps. Few reported his inflated sense of entitlement, saucy
attitude and smarty-pants answers. We know now why the Dark Side
embraced this chosen boy.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Bryan, a child actor so far immune to Hollywood's
character-ravaging afflictions. He is nothing if not humble and
polite. He is self-conscious, self-effacing. He apologizes when he
yawns. He signs an autograph with ``Best wishes. Stay cool.'' You
just want to tousle his hair.
</P>
<P>
   If he's capable of giving the kind of kid answers journalists
dread (Why are you drawn to acting? ``It's just what I like to
do.'' Yes, but . . . ), Bryan is bitten by the kind of enthusiasm
that helps us tell our stories.
</P>
<P>
   Watch, and follow if you can, as he animatedly relates how he
wrote and directed a scene from a Harry Potter book for school, for
which he got an A+ and extra credit, or how he signed an autograph
at Burger King and . . . well, I couldn't follow that story.
</P>
<P>
   So back to the ``why acting'' question, which requires we first
investigate the Band-Aid on his thumb. Bryan sliced the digit with
a knife when he was whittling. His brother Blake, 16, is an
apprentice wood carver. ``I kind of like to copy my brother a
lot,'' says Bryan.
</P>
<P>
   Blake also acts in community theater. ``That's kind of how I got
into acting,'' says Bryan. ``I tagged along with him. He's more of
a theater actor than a film actor, but he's pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Bryan is in a Mel Gibson movie and Blake is carving lumber.
``What he thinks of my movie is kind of bittersweet, because like
he's proud of me but he got me into acting and he's kind of like,
'Man, that should be me.' But he's not mad,'' Bryan says.
</P>
<P>
   It's odd because Bryan hasn't seen ``The Patriot'' and I have.
They will see it Tuesday at the Hollywood premiere. He and mom want
to know how much screen time he has and if his 11 lines made the
cut. I tell him about a decapitation by cannonball in a battle
scene and he squeals, ``Oh, cool! Cool!''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan's character doesn't do much, but he does kill a man. One
shot from a musket and down goes the Redcoat. He went through a
week of musket training for that scene. ``First you put the musket
on half-cock so it can't go off, then you open the wick-pan, then
tear open the powder packet and pour it in,'' he recites. ``I got
to where I could fire three shots in a minute.''
</P>
<P>
   How did mom react to her 11-year-old killing? ``He was shooting
at nobody,'' she responds. This cool equipoise earned Juli respect
on the set in South Carolina. ``I was voted `most not like a stage
mom' by the hair dressers,'' she laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan also cries in the film. His trick: He thinks about his pet
cat Kato, who was run over by a car.
</P>
<P>
   On the first day of shooting, last fall, Bryan was ``a little
shaky.'' But the crushing tedium of movie-making soon numbed the
nerves. ``It's pretty much hurry up and wait the whole time,'' he
says, using an old Hollywood axiom. He played a lot of Nintendo in
his trailer with co-star Heath Ledger, who plays Gibson's eldest
son.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson, he says, ``was nice.'' Mom elaborates that Gibson
indulged in his well-noted set shenanigans and that Bryan gave the
Three Stooges fanatic a couple of Stooges toys to the actor's
delight.
</P>
<P>
   When the family is in Los Angeles over the next few days, Bryan
will meet with film people about prospective projects. Recently he
was one of three children considered for the big-budget action
movie ``Pearl Harbor'' as well as the upcoming Bruce Willis
project. He didn't get the roles.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bryan received his first fan letter, which mom has
put in a photo album. It's from a young Canadian girl, who wrote,
``You're a very sympathetic and talented young actor. . . . You're
so natural and you always bring something so positive and so
refreshing in all you do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes me feel good,'' says Bryan, ``because if I can get
one I'm sure there's going to be more coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
