<P>
   ZIMBABWE-ELECTIONS (Harare, Zimbabwe) _ The old heroes sing
liberation songs and predict an overwhelming victory for President
Robert Mugabe and his ruling party. But 200 miles south of the
capital here, in the poor, rural villages near Chivi, the ruling
party's local youth leader, Ocean Mudzivi, smells change in the
air. This weekend, Zimbabweans will vote in parliamentary elections
that will challenge the overwhelming dominance of Mugabe's ruling
party for the first time in this nation's 20 years of independence.
And as Mugabe campaigned across the country Friday, he urged people
to remember the past and to stay true to the party that liberated
them from white rule. But the old message is landing in the ears of
a changing nation. By Rachel Swarns.
</P>
