<P>
   GORE-FUNDRAISING (Washington) _ Vice President Al Gore said he
will make public the full transcript of his ``cooperative and
professional'' interview with a prosecutor who has called for a
special inquiry into Gore's veracity about his 1996 fund raising.
``I think the truth is my friend in this,'' Gore told reporters
Friday on his presidential campaign plane. The vice president said
he would release the 150-page interview because ``I want people to
judge for themselves'' and ``I want the truth to be known about
this.'' The supervising attorney for the Justice Department's
campaign finance task force, Robert Conrad, has suggested that a
special counsel should be appointed to investigate Gore's
statements in the interview. The recommendation for Attorney
General Janet Reno was made weeks ago, after the prosecutor
questioned Gore on April 18 about a Buddhist temple fund-raising
event Gore attended, as well as other topics. (Summary from wires)
By David Johnston and Don VanNatta.
