<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REDFISH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DISCOVERING A HAVEN FOR GULF COAST REDFISH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RON STRAIT  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARANSAS PASS, Texas _ Rats to bulls, there's nothing like
redfish fishing on the flats in the summertime.
</P>
<P>
   The bronzed and brawny heavyweights spend the first years of
life cruising the shallow bay waters, rooting crabs from the sea
grass, smacking gold spoons, popping leaders, breaking hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Early in life, redfish are called rats, or rat-reds. The name is
not derogatory. Rather, it denotes fish under the 20-inch minimum
legal possession length set by the state. Any redfish too small to
be kept legally is a rat.
</P>
<P>
   Rats are the spookiest members of the redfish clan. They travel
in large schools and are the first to move up on the flats with a
rising tide. Even though they are small in size, they still put up
a good fight.
</P>
<P>
   Wade fishermen who encounter a school of rat reds should watch
the movement of the school and cast so the fish move to the bait.
Casting directly to a fish within the school can spook the entire
school.
</P>
<P>
   When a rat is hooked, try to guide it away from the school for
the fight, and, if possible, keep it from splashing and thrashing.
It is possible to catch more than one red from the school if care
is taken, and learning the skills to work a school of small redfish
is a measure of the accomplished angler.
</P>
<P>
   When the targets get larger and more solitary in nature, the
positioning of a lure and the ability to control part of the battle
to hand enhance the quality of the fishing experience.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the fish ruler are large reds, 36 inches and
longer. They are known as bulls. The term ``bull red'' is not
gender-specific. Both male and female reds can be called ``bulls''
if they are big.
</P>
<P>
   Bull reds are uncommon in bays, but they are there. Big redfish
are creatures of the open Gulf waters and come close to shore only
during the spawning period from October into January.
</P>
<P>
   Between the rats and the bulls in size are the fish most sport
anglers bring to the dock in the summer. Generically, they are
called keepers. In Texas, the daily bag limit is three redfish
between 20 and 28 inches long. Most of those fish weigh from 4 to 7
pounds and are less than 4 years old.
</P>
<P>
   A redfish longer than 28 inches can be kept if the angler tags
it with the bonus tag that comes with a fishing license.
</P>
<P>
   In the last week of July and well into August, tides drop to the
lowest levels of the summer, and the redfish are pushed off the
flats into the deeper pockets, or holes, in the bay systems. The
phenomenon of thousands of redfish of all sizes ganged up in bay
pockets is called a ``rodeo.''
</P>
<P>
   When a redfish rodeo is on, it is not uncommon to see dozens of
boats anchored up in large circles around the holes with hundreds
of lines cast toward the middle. The fishing is fast and furious
and the catching can be non-stop.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing a redfish rodeo is a low-tech event. Fresh-cut mullet,
piggy perch or shrimp are good baits. Get a medium-heavy rod, some
17-pound test line and a reel with a good drag.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, a chunk of bait on a 3/0 hook is enough weight for
casting into the school. A half-ounce barrel sinker above a swivel
tied onto an 18-inch leader should be adequate to cast a bait into
the wind.
</P>
<P>
   A rodeo is not the place for a light-tackle fish fight. The idea
is to get the fish to the boat and into the ice chest while causing
as few tangles as possible with other lines.
</P>
<P>
   On an August low tide, plan to be at or near such places as
California Hole in the Estes Flats area.
</P>
<P>
   Look for boats positioned in a large circle, and move into place
very quietly. Even rodeo reds can be spooked out of a hole, and if
it's your fault for spooking them, you won't be a popular cowboy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 1655EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
