<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2870 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-CARLYLE-HOTEL-ART-     06-23 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CARLYLE-HOTEL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPENDING SALE OF LEGENDARY HOTEL CREATES CONCERN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT22, 23 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By GLENN COLLINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is intense concern in certain lofty altitudes
of Manhattan's Upper East Side. The Carlyle Hotel is for sale, and
the seriously soigne are worried that this oasis of sophistication
_ the preserve of presidents, prime ministers and popular legends _
will fall into, well, the wrong hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many guests come up to me and say, `I hope they don't
change things,''' said Ronald Hector, standing behind the reception
desk in his role as executive assistant manager. ``They all know
about the sale, and they are all worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Annexation by a boorish newcomer ``would be such a shame,'' said
Brooke Astor, the 98-year-old society cynosure who celebrated her
95th birthday at the Carlyle. ``I would feel so sad if it were no
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, it would be ``terrible'' if the Carlyle were sold ``to
anyone who didn't respect its inherent characteristics,'' said
Woody Allen, the filmmaker and sometime Carlyle guest who plays
jazz clarinet in the Cafe Carlyle nearly every Monday night.
``There are certain things that are just better left alone, and the
Carlyle is one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The 70-year-old hotel has long been a palace of secrets, well
before it became the New York White House for President Kennedy,
who made it a fulcrum of world _ and possibly other _ affairs. It
is the grand residence where Diana, princess of Wales, discreetly
stayed whenever she visited New York, and it is where John F.
Kennedy Jr. last ate breakfast before his plane crashed.
</P>
<P>
   In true Carlylish tradition, the parties to the sale have been
exquisitely private about hawking the property, and few reliable
details have leaked about the complex negotiations that have now
dragged on for more than a year. In an interview, Norman L. Peck,
the managing partner of the Carlyle, who heads its ownership group,
said he would not think of permitting an unqualified suitor to buy
``this very high-bred animal.''
</P>
<P>
   The sale comes as the occupancy rate in the city's 60,000 hotel
rooms is the highest in 20 years: 89.1 percent in April, according
to estimates by PricewaterhouseCoopers, the accounting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Average room rates citywide are $245.27, 11.7 percent higher
than a year before, but hardly in a league with the Carlyle. Its
cushy, antique-rich rooms go for $425 to $695 per night for a
single; suites range from $650 to $3,250.
</P>
<P>
   The opulent Carlyle is perhaps best known for the presence of
Bobby Short, the high-end saloon singer who has served up Cole
Porter and George Gershwin at the Cafe Carlyle since 1968.
</P>
<P>
   But habitues say they adore the state-of-the-art cosseting by
the work force of 437. Above and beyond the staff's paparazzi
protection, ``there seems to be a cone of privacy around
celebrities at the hotel,'' said Charles Dean, a restaurant captain
and the assistant maitre d'hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Discretion is so cherished that soon after the breakup of the
Beatles, two of them were guests in the hotel in different suites
at the same time but did not realize it until after they had left,
according to employees who were there. Even now, they will not say
which Beatles they were.
</P>
<P>
   The Carlyle prospectus was sent to a select group of several
dozen potential buyers ``because we didn't want to see a hotel like
this involved in a marketing process like a common commercial
property,'' said the Carlyle's broker, Benjamin V. Lambert of
Eastdil Realty in Manhattan. But word spread, and soon more than 50
bidders were clamoring to kick the tires.
</P>
<P>
   The intense secrecy imposed by the Carlyle has forced the
customarily gab-happy real estate clan to clutch at gossipy straws;
parties to the negotiations have refused to name names. In
December, a tabloid newspaper reported that the Carlyle was to be
bought by the sultan of Brunei for $150 million, but several
parties close to the deal, including Peck, emphatically deny it.
</P>
<P>
   It is likely that the Carlyle will be sold as a trophy property
to ``a strong foreign hotel company that is looking to enhance its
visibility throughout the world,'' said Sean Hennessey, director of
the hotel-consulting business of PricewaterhouseCoopers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
