<HEADER>
A2874 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-EUROPE     06-23 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-EUROPE-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READY FOR FENCES TO FALL IN EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 25)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It sounds a little weird, but the Old World is a work in
progress.
</P>
<P>
   Europe is in the throes of change, and investors there are only
beginning to benefit from the Eurocentric capital markets system
that is being built.
</P>
<P>
   Later this summer, for example, the European Commission is
likely to give pension funds in member countries the green light to
make cross-border investments. Collectively, those funds have $2
trillion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is old news to American money managers, who have
spent the last couple of years anticipating what these changes will
mean and how to profit from them.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Levy, head of international equities at Deutsche Asset
Management and manager of the Deutsche European Equity fund, took
some time last week to talk about those and other issues. Following
are excerpts from the conversation: &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q. Changes related to pension funds will increase the amount of
cross-border investing in Europe. How are you positioning your fund
to benefit from that? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A. We looked at the way these markets appeared from the point of
view of the managers in each country, and asked what their asset
allocation was. The answer was that it was incredibly distorted.
Spanish fund managers, for example, were pretty much captive to
Spanish stocks, which are dominated by utilities and banks.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have been freed from those constraints have been
moving into large companies outside their home country, names like
LVMH, Total Fina Elf, Mannesmann and Nokia. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q. Aren't many European funds underweighted in stocks? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A. By our standards, the exposure to equities is low.
</P>
<P>
   As pension funds become funded, instead of pay-as-you-go, we are
going to see an increasing shift from bonds to equities. That is
going to happen over the next 5 to 10 years, and is going to
generate tremendous demand for stock in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   I have seen conservative estimates that project institutional
demand for European equities to be $11 trillion between now and
2010. That is a big number, and it doesn't make any wild
assumptions about equities. The demand will outstrip supply, and
there will be more supply. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q. So do you expect to see a lot more companies go public? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A. For the first time, a lot of companies are going to start coming
to market. Companies will have the chance to raise capital in many
more markets, and investors will have the choice of which ones they
want to invest in.
</P>
<P>
   Before now, pension funds and companies were basically captive.
Except for the best-rated companies, who could float debt in the
Eurobond market, there has not been a capital market in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds rated ``A'' or below account for about 93 percent of the
American corporate bond market. In Europe, it is almost the
reverse. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q. Has your fund invested in any newly created companies?  &QL; 
 &QL; 
A. Early in the year, we positioned ourselves to invest in a number
of spinoffs, including two from Siemens, Infineon and Epcos.
</P>
<P>
   And we have invested in companies like Reckitt Benckiser, a
British company that has been taken over by Benckiser, a very
successful Dutch family-owned concern.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q. What are some of your other holdings? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A. Vodafone AirTouch is a large position, even though we are
underweight the United Kingdom. At the start of the year, we held a
number of blue chips like Philips, Siemens, Telefonica and Nokia.
We own companies like Intershop, a German software company, and
Total Fina Elf has been very exciting, and is one of our largest
positions. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q. Does the move to create one European market with a common
currency mean the Continent is less vulnerable to swings in the
American business cycle? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A. There is no way Europe or anywhere else would not be impacted by
a recession here. However, the euro zone does about 90 percent of
its trading within the European Union itself. So they are about as
closed a market as the U.S. is.
</P>
<P>
   A recession would create some spillover, but not as great as in
the past. And if the U.S. is able to pull off a soft landing, there
would be practically no effect. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q. Do European markets represent a good opportunity for American
investors? &QL; 
A. Some of the markets are doing better than others. France and
Sweden are doing all right. The United Kingdom has had a hard time,
because sterling was too strong.
</P>
<P>
   That said, there is no question this is a great time to get in.
Whether or not the euro has another bout of weakness, it is an
oversold, undervalued currency.
</P>
<P>
   The weaker euro gives dollar investors a nice window and
provides a nice tailwind for European economies and countries to
restructure.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 1701EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
