<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2875 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MEDIA-STUDY-0626-COX     06-23 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-STUDY-0626-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PARENTS AREN'T MONITORING KIDS MULTI-MEDIA USE, STUDIES SHOW
 &HT;    For Use Mon. June 26 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving in (w) Washington and (l) Lifestyle
categories
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Growing up in America is rapidly becoming a wired
experience but parents aren't plugged in to their kids' multi-media
habits, according to a trio of scholarly reports to be released on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The three studies by Annenberg Public Policy Center of the
University of Pennsylvania found that almost half of all families
with children aged 2 to 17 have a television, a VCR, a computer and
a video game player. More of these families subscribe to an
Internet access service than to a daily newspaper. They average
nearly three TV sets per household.
</P>
<P>
   The typical adolescent's bedroom is equipped with almost enough
gadgetry to stock an electronics store. Most children aged 8 to 16
have a television in their bedrooms. Three out of four have a
stereo or CD player; 39 percent can play video games there; 32
percent have a bedroom phone and 20 percent have a bedroom
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Parents estimate that their children spend four and a half hours
per day staring at some sort of video screen, according to the
surveys. However, parents are more concerned about what the kids
are seeing than about how much time is being spent with electronic
media.
</P>
<P>
   While 85 percent of parents worry about what their children
watch on TV, only 40 percent have sets equipped with V-Chips or
other blocking technology. And only about half of those with these
devices actually use them to regulate family viewing. The
percentage of parents who are familiar with the rating guidelines
for TV shows has declined from 70 percent in 1997 to 50 percent in
2000, the surveys found.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have these difficulties helping parents guide their
children's television use, imagine the problems we will have with
new media technologies entering the home,'' warned Emory Woodard, a
researcher for the Annenberg Public Policy Center, an academic
group that studies the role of communications in public policy
issues.
</P>
<P>
   The three studies _ ``Media in the Home 2000,'' ``Is the
Three-Hour Rule Living Up to Its Potential?'' and ``Public Policy,
Family Rules and Children's Media Use in the Home'' _ examine how
families use and regard media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Media in the Home 2000'' is based on telephone interviews with
1,235 randomly selected parents of children between the ages of 2
and 17 and 416 children between the ages of 8 and 16. The margin of
error in the parental survey was plus or minus 2.9 percent and was
plus or minus 5 percent for the interviews with children.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Three Hour Rule'' report analyzes educational programming
on 10 commercial TV stations in Philadelphia during the 1999/2000
season. The ``Family Rules'' report is based on 24 focus group
discussions with 87 children and 62 mothers of children in grades
3, 6 and 9.
</P>
<P>
   The studies found a remarkable media presence into American
homes.
</P>
<P>
   For families with children aged 2 to 17, 97 percent have a VCR
in their home, 70 percent have a computer, 68 percent have video
game players, 52 percent have online access and 42 percent have a
newspaper subscription. In four years, the number of these
households with Internet access has more than tripled from 15
percent in 1996 to 52 percent in 2000. These families with children
have an average of 2.8 TV sets per household and 78 percent
subscribe to at least basic cable.
</P>
<P>
   Low-income families (less than $30,000 annual income) are less
likely to have computers, Internet access or newspaper
subscriptions. However, they are equally likely to have a video
game player and their children are more likely to have TV sets in
their bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Family income is an inverse indicator of media use _ children
from high-income families spend the least amount of time with media
and children from low-income families spend the most time with
media.
</P>
<P>
   Of the media surveyed, children spent the most time watching TV
(147 minutes per day) and the least on the Internet (14 minutes per
day).
</P>
<P>
   Most parents (88 percent) told the survey that they regularly
supervise their children's TV viewing. About half said they do so
with their kids' use of the Internet or video games.
</P>
<P>
   The studies indicated that most parents aren't using the systems
set up to help them guide their children's TV habits.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Since 1997, local broadcast stations have aired a minimum of
three hours per week of educational programming in order to qualify
for expedited renewal of licenses granted by the Federal
Communications Commission (FCC). These programs must be labeled as
educational and informative _ E/I. But most parents were unable to
identify the E/I programs watched by their children. Indeed, 70
percent of the parents incorrectly picked ``The Oprah Winfrey
Show'' and ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'' as labeled E/I for
children.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Telecommunications Act of 1996, new televisions are
required to contain a computer chip _ V-chip _ that allows parents
to block out programs with certain ratings. Most networks are
voluntarily rating their programs _ TV-Y as suitable for all
children, for example.
</P>
<P>
   However, the studies showed that the system is not yet widely
used. Only about one in five families uses a blocking device
although twice that many have the technology to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``The V-chip ratings and the Three-Hour rule are not living up
to their potential,'' said Amy Jordan, a senior researcher for the
Annenberg Public Policy Center. ``Most TV programs now have ratings
and many families have blocking technology. There is also more
educational programming out there for families. But parents are not
using these tools to guide their children's television use.''
</P>
<P>
   The reports and their implications will be discussed Monday at
the Annenberg Center's 5th Annual Conference on Children and the
Media to be held in Washington, D.C. The Center was established by
publisher and philanthropist Walter Annenberg in 1994 to create a
community of scholars within the University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   For online information: www.appcpenn.org
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 1701EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2876 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-MEDIA-STUDY-0626-COX     06-23 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-STUDY-0626-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PARENTS AREN'T MONITORING KIDS MULTI-MEDIA USE, STUDIES SHOW
 &HT;    For Use Mon. June 26 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving in (w) Washington and (l) Lifestyle
categories
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Growing up in America is rapidly becoming a wired
experience but parents aren't plugged in to their kids' multi-media
habits, according to a trio of scholarly reports to be released on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The three studies by Annenberg Public Policy Center of the
University of Pennsylvania found that almost half of all families
with children aged 2 to 17 have a television, a VCR, a computer and
a video game player. More of these families subscribe to an
Internet access service than to a daily newspaper. They average
nearly three TV sets per household.
</P>
<P>
   The typical adolescent's bedroom is equipped with almost enough
gadgetry to stock an electronics store. Most children aged 8 to 16
have a television in their bedrooms. Three out of four have a
stereo or CD player; 39 percent can play video games there; 32
percent have a bedroom phone and 20 percent have a bedroom
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Parents estimate that their children spend four and a half hours
per day staring at some sort of video screen, according to the
surveys. However, parents are more concerned about what the kids
are seeing than about how much time is being spent with electronic
media.
</P>
<P>
   While 85 percent of parents worry about what their children
watch on TV, only 40 percent have sets equipped with V-Chips or
other blocking technology. And only about half of those with these
devices actually use them to regulate family viewing. The
percentage of parents who are familiar with the rating guidelines
for TV shows has declined from 70 percent in 1997 to 50 percent in
2000, the surveys found.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have these difficulties helping parents guide their
children's television use, imagine the problems we will have with
new media technologies entering the home,'' warned Emory Woodard, a
researcher for the Annenberg Public Policy Center, an academic
group that studies the role of communications in public policy
issues.
</P>
<P>
   The three studies _ ``Media in the Home 2000,'' ``Is the
Three-Hour Rule Living Up to Its Potential?'' and ``Public Policy,
Family Rules and Children's Media Use in the Home'' _ examine how
families use and regard media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Media in the Home 2000'' is based on telephone interviews with
1,235 randomly selected parents of children between the ages of 2
and 17 and 416 children between the ages of 8 and 16. The margin of
error in the parental survey was plus or minus 2.9 percent and was
plus or minus 5 percent for the interviews with children.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Three Hour Rule'' report analyzes educational programming
on 10 commercial TV stations in Philadelphia during the 1999/2000
season. The ``Family Rules'' report is based on 24 focus group
discussions with 87 children and 62 mothers of children in grades
3, 6 and 9.
</P>
<P>
   The studies found a remarkable media presence into American
homes.
</P>
<P>
   For families with children aged 2 to 17, 97 percent have a VCR
in their home, 70 percent have a computer, 68 percent have video
game players, 52 percent have online access and 42 percent have a
newspaper subscription. In four years, the number of these
households with Internet access has more than tripled from 15
percent in 1996 to 52 percent in 2000. These families with children
have an average of 2.8 TV sets per household and 78 percent
subscribe to at least basic cable.
</P>
<P>
   Low-income families (less than $30,000 annual income) are less
likely to have computers, Internet access or newspaper
subscriptions. However, they are equally likely to have a video
game player and their children are more likely to have TV sets in
their bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Family income is an inverse indicator of media use _ children
from high-income families spend the least amount of time with media
and children from low-income families spend the most time with
media.
</P>
<P>
   Of the media surveyed, children spent the most time watching TV
(147 minutes per day) and the least on the Internet (14 minutes per
day).
</P>
<P>
   Most parents (88 percent) told the survey that they regularly
supervise their children's TV viewing. About half said they do so
with their kids' use of the Internet or video games.
</P>
<P>
   The studies indicated that most parents aren't using the systems
set up to help them guide their children's TV habits.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Since 1997, local broadcast stations have aired a minimum of
three hours per week of educational programming in order to qualify
for expedited renewal of licenses granted by the Federal
Communications Commission (FCC). These programs must be labeled as
educational and informative _ E/I. But most parents were unable to
identify the E/I programs watched by their children. Indeed, 70
percent of the parents incorrectly picked ``The Oprah Winfrey
Show'' and ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'' as labeled E/I for
children.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Telecommunications Act of 1996, new televisions are
required to contain a computer chip _ V-chip _ that allows parents
to block out programs with certain ratings. Most networks are
voluntarily rating their programs _ TV-Y as suitable for all
children, for example.
</P>
<P>
   However, the studies showed that the system is not yet widely
used. Only about one in five families uses a blocking device
although twice that many have the technology to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``The V-chip ratings and the Three-Hour rule are not living up
to their potential,'' said Amy Jordan, a senior researcher for the
Annenberg Public Policy Center. ``Most TV programs now have ratings
and many families have blocking technology. There is also more
educational programming out there for families. But parents are not
using these tools to guide their children's television use.''
</P>
<P>
   The reports and their implications will be discussed Monday at
the Annenberg Center's 5th Annual Conference on Children and the
Media to be held in Washington, D.C. The Center was established by
publisher and philanthropist Walter Annenberg in 1994 to create a
community of scholars within the University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   For online information: www.appcpenn.org
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
