<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: ENTERTAINMENT MARKETERS FORM NEW ALLIANCES 
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Big changes are coming to the small but intensely
competitive world of agencies that specialize in creating
theatrical advertising.
</P>
<P>
   G-Whiz Entertainment in New York, a unit of Grey Global Group,
is getting out of the business of producing campaigns for Broadway
and off-Broadway shows to concentrate on larger assignments in
entertainment marketing. And Wilner Advertising in New York, a
Broadway show specialist, is closing.
</P>
<P>
   The changes come as efforts to sell tickets to live theater grow
in complexity and scope, while it becomes increasingly challenging
to gain the attention of consumers in an environment saturated with
entertainment options that range from new reality series on
television to a glitzed-up revival of professional wrestling to
so-called extreme sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theater business itself has never been better, but it's
very labor-intensive,'' said Nancy Coyne, chairwoman at Serino
Coyne Inc. in New York, which handles shows like ``Aida,'' ``Beauty
and the Beast,'' ``Cats,'' ``Footloose,'' ``Kiss Me, Kate'' and
``The Lion King.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to make a go of it unless you have a lot of
clients,'' she added. ``With one or two, it's hard to do.''
</P>
<P>
   G-Whiz Entertainment is forming an alliance with Eliran Murphy
Group in New York, which specializes in theatrical advertising, to
serve the needs of producers of plays and musicals whose accounts
had been handled by G-Whiz Entertainment. Those billings were
estimated at $3.5 million out of a total of $110 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The formation of G-Whiz Entertainment resulted in a change in
our mission,'' said Barbara Martino, president and chief executive.
Her reference was to a move made in February by Grey Global,
formerly Grey Advertising, to merge two specialty units.
</P>
<P>
   That merger brought together G-Whiz, founded in July 1999, which
focused on marketing to children and teen-agers, with Grey
Entertainment, founded in 1974, which focused on traditional
entertainment campaigns like the promotion of shows on and
off-Broadway as well as films. Martino had been president at G-Whiz
before the merger that produced G-Whiz Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entertainment slant is becoming more of a youth-marketing
slant,'' Martino said. ``The Broadway effort pretty much did not
fit under where we were headed.''
</P>
<P>
   The shift in emphasis, she added, would benefit the
youth-focused clients of G-Whiz Entertainment like Aeropostale, a
retailer of apparel aimed at teen-agers; Delsner/Slater, concert
promoters; SFX Entertainment; the Warner Bros. unit of Time Warner;
and Youtopia.com, a Web site focused on teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Eliran Murphy, an agency with 27 employees handling accounts
with billings estimated at $25 million, will assume the theatrical
accounts now handled by G-Whiz Entertainment, assuming of course
that clients agree to the switch. The shows affected include the
current production of the long-running revue ``Forbidden
Broadway,'' called ``Forbidden Broadway Cleans Up Its Act''; ``Late
Night Catechism''; the coming production of ``Little Women''; and
``Tony 'n Tina's Wedding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hopeful they're interested in working with us,'' said
Barbara Eliran, chief executive at Eliran Murphy. Ann Murphy,
president and creative director, described the alliance as ``a
referral'' of the clients to Eliran Murphy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The 10 employees at G-Whiz Entertainment who work on theatrical
advertising, out of a total of about 110, are to be interviewed for
positions at Eliran Murphy, which now works for productions like
``A Moon for the Misbegotten,'' ``Cabaret,'' ``Dame Edna,''
``Dinner with Friends'' and ``I Love You, You're Perfect, Now
Change,'' as well as the Brooklyn Museum of Art, the Manhattan
Theater Club, the New Jersey Performing Arts Center, the New York
City Opera and the Roundabout Theater Company.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to Wilner, its closing was described Thursday in
interviews with several top executives at other theatrical
agencies. Telephone calls to Jon Wilner, the president, were not
returned.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Wilner said he was owed over $500,000 by Livent Inc.,
the producer of the musical ``Ragtime,'' which his agency handled
until Livent filed for bankruptcy protection.
</P>
<P>
   The sole Broadway production now handled by Wilner is the
musical ``Saturday Night Fever.'' That show is shifting its account
to Serino Coyne, said Bill Evans, a spokesman, after receiving ``a
memo from Jon Wilner resigning the account.''
</P>
</TEXT>
