A2881 &Cx1f; taf-z
r a BC-FLAPPING-ROTOR-COPTER     06-23 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAPPING-ROTOR-COPTERS-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A FLAP  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF JUNE 26, 2000)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By PAUL MARKS  
 Copyright 2000 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Traditional helicopters have a vertical tail rotor to stop the
main rotor from spinning the craft endlessly round and round. But
running that second rotor wastes around 8 percent of the chopper's
fuel, says Vladimir Savov, an expert in aerodynamics at the
Bulgarian Air Force Academy in Sofia. So to save that fuel, Savov
has invented the ``rotopter,'' a helicopter that flaps its rotors.
</P>
<P>
   Helicopters can already fly without tail rotors _ using
counter-rotating main rotors or elaborate fans on the tail boom _
but Savov has taken a different tack that he says will be far
cheaper. To fight the tendency of a helicopter to turn in the
opposite direction to its spinning rotor system, Savov has removed
the engine that spins the main rotors. Instead, flapping the rotors
up and down makes them spin of their own accord.
</P>
<P>
   Savov's design involves an engine driving a crank that creates
an up-and-down reciprocating motion that in turn drives two
separate rotor arms. By flapping the rotors up and down, and
carefully choosing the angle each rotor's aerofoil presents to the
air during its cycle, the rotors begins to rotate on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no rotating moment transmitted to the rotopter rotor
blades, so there is no torque reaction _ and so no need for a tail
rotor,'' Savov said in a telephone interview from his home in
Pleven. ``The efficiency of the system could be comparable to that
of a standard helicopter,'' he claims.
</P>
<P>
   The downside of the idea is the distinctly odd _ and slightly
alarming _ vibrating motion of the rotors, which would probably
make for a very uncomfortable ride in a full-sized machine (see
video at www.geocities.com/CapeCanaveral/Runway/7551).
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be a big problem-I just don't know yet,'' says
Savov, who plans to undertake vibration isolation tests.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Westland Helicopters in Yeovil, Somerset, says:
``Savov's video shows it works, but it will take a lot more
modeling to prove it can actually move forwards and remain
stable.'' &QL; 
 &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science and
technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
