<HEADLINE>
GETTING PAST AN AFFAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERICKA MELLON  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NOTE: PLEASE CORRECT BYLINE
</P>
<P>
   A love affair can be either a death knell or a wake-up call for
couples, Janis Abrahms Spring contends.
</P>
<P>
   Spring is an expert on infidelity. The Westport, Conn.,
psychologist wrote After the Affair: Healing the Pain and
Rebuilding Trust When a Partner Has Been Unfaithful (HarperCollins
1997) and gives lectures to her peers nationwide. She spoke
Thursday to counselors and psychologists in Lenexa and is appearing
today in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   In her book Spring emphasizes that ``after'' does not
necessarily mean the end. She tells couples dealing with an affair
``to step into the center of the ring, remove your boxing gloves
and join hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Many couples have this match to fight. Spring says one in every
2.7 couples in the United States is affected by an affair. And with
the increased popularity of the Internet, she says, virtual affairs
have become more common.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The Star, she shares some of her insight.
</P>
<P>
   How do you define an affair?
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally an affair refers to the violation of sexual
exclusivity in a marriage. ... But this is a very narrow definition
because it refers only to sexual intercourse, only to married
couples, only to heterosexual couples. And affairs go way beyond
those dimensions. So I say that an affair is not necessarily about
sex but about secrets and a violation of trust.
</P>
<P>
   You write that it is possible for a relationship to survive an
affair. Does this belief surprise many people?
</P>
<P>
   Many people believe once the trust is broken, the relationship
is broken. But the truth is, we don't really know how we'd react to
something until it happens. Affairs happen to good people in good
relationships, too. The process of making sense of what went wrong
can be a growth process.
</P>
<P>
   How is it possible to survive?
</P>
<P>
   I have found that there are three essential ingredients to
healing.
</P>
<P>
   (First), unfaithful partners have to be willing to apologize
generously and often, to understand the harm they've caused. The
second essential ingredient is unfaithful partners have to be
willing to look deeply within themselves and understand why they
strayed so it never happens again. Third, unfaithful partners have
to be willing to earn back trust.
</P>
<P>
   Trust is not a cheap gift. It's something the unfaithful person
earns. And how do they earn it? By doing little things everyday
that make the hurt partner feel loved and safe.
</P>
<P>
   How have the Internet and chat rooms complicated the picture?
</P>
<P>
   Because the Internet is so accessible, anonymous and cheap,
people use it easily, secretly and they don't tend to see it as a
violation of the relationship. In reality, people are spending
hours talking graphically and pornographically to people they'll
not only never touch, but also never see.
</P>
<P>
   But when their partner finds out, they experience a very
profound shattering and violation because affairs are about
secrets. Plus, all the energy is going into these cybersex
relationships. The life of the marital relationship is drained.
</P>
<P>
   What advice can you give couples so that one partner doesn't
stray?
</P>
<P>
   The greatest antidote is when partners take responsibility for
their personal issues.
</P>
<P>
   If in your early years you were abandoned or abused, you may
grow up not feeling safe in relationships. You cannot trust people
fully and cannot love fully, and you go in search of one partner
after another. Or it could be you weren't valued as a child. These
vulnerabilities often are underlying the attraction to another
person.
</P>
<P>
   The second piece of advice is never take your partner for
granted and understand how relationships need to be nourished
everyday.
</P>
<P>
   When is it not right to stay together after an affair?
</P>
<P>
   When people ask me, ``What's my success rate,'' I say I don't
base my success on whether partners stay together but whether they
make a thoughtful decision about that.
</P>
<P>
   For some people it's better to get out. For other people, they
need help staying in and not leaving the relationship. I'm not for
preserving the relationship at any cost.  &LR; tag1:To reach Ericka
Mellon, features reporter for The Star, call (816) 234-4392 or send
e-mail to emellon &LR; kcstar.com
</P>
</TEXT>
