<HEADER>
A2886 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-RUN-OLYMPICS-HNS &LR;      06-23 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-OLYMPICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     OLYMPIC TRACK EVENTS HEAT UP 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUGENE, Ore. _ With the temperature of the track season about to
go from lukewarm to lava-hot, it says here that:
</P>
<P>
   Marion Jones will not win five gold medals at the Sydney
Olympics. In fact, she won't even win four.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Johnson will smoke Maurice Greene when _ or rather, if _
the two finally meet at 200 meters in the Olympic trials next month
in Sacramento. And he'll do the same two months later in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, Johnson and Greene are three points of a triangulated
star system in U.S. track and field. For that, the country should
be thankful.
</P>
<P>
   It's an isosceles triangle, though, with Jones at the pinnacle
based on her talent, looks, personality and stated goal of winning
five gold medals at the Olympic Games. That plays well in sound
bites on TV but, as she'll learn, it's reality that bites.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is a lock for gold medals in the 100, 200 and 4x100 relay,
but the 4x400 relay is no sure thing and in the long jump, she's a
glamorous hack desperately trying to fake it. It won't work. The
way she's jumping, Mrs. Jones won't come close to earning a long
jump medal _ if she even makes the U.S. team in the event.
</P>
<P>
   At the base of the triangle, Johnson and Greene are holding up
two equal and opposite legs. Johnson is the world record-holder in
the 200 and 400 meters trying to duplicate his awesome performance
from Atlanta four years ago. Greene is the world record-holder in
the 100 with the temerity to invade Johnson's territory in the 200.
Something's got to give.
</P>
<P>
   All three athletes will compete in the Prefontaine Classic on
Saturday at Hayward Field in Eugene, along with a who's who of U.S.
and international athletes in serious preparation for the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   For American athletes, it's the start of a defining month of
competition that continues Sunday in Portland with the Oregon Track
Classic and July 1 at Stanford, Calif., with the GMC Envoy Open,
followed by the Olympic trials July 14-23 at Hornet Stadium on the
Sacramento State campus in California.
</P>
<P>
   With the Olympic trials three weeks away, it's time for
America's best athletes to show their fitness in the three meets
leading up to Sacramento _ Pre, Portland and Stanford. The GMC meet
at Stanford represents the last opportunity for elite competition
prior to the trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``That'll be just right for me in terms of preparation,'' said
Regina Jacobs of Oakland, Calif., who will run the 800 at Pre and
the 3,000 at Portland. ``What motivates me? A lot of unfinished
goals. There are so many things I want to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, 36, a former Stanford runner, won the silver medal at
1,500 meters at last year's World Championships. As a
middle-distance specialist, she'll run the 800 at Pre for speed and
the 3,000 at Portland for endurance, then come back to the middle
for a mile at the GMC meet at Stanford's Cobb Track &AMP; Angell Field
a week from Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   That should put her in good stead for the trials, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The adrenaline that pumps into your body when you compete at
the Olympic trials, with all that energy, it's electric,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pre meet pumps a fair amount of adrenaline, too. On
Saturday, Jones will run the 100 and attempt to find some semblance
of form in the long jump. Johnson will run his first 400 of the
season. Greene will try the 200, which leaves the 100 to such
sprinters as Jon Drummond, Obadele Thompson of the Bahamas, NCAA
champion Bernard Williams of Florida, runner-up Coby Miller of
Auburn and Ja'Warren Hooker of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   As for Jacobs, who just gets better with age, she's in deep in
the Pre 800 against Maria Mutola, the No. 1-ranked half-miler in
the world. Mutola has a best of 1:55.43. Jacobs' fastest is
1:58.55.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for a really awesome race,'' Jacobs said. ``I know
it's going to be very, very fast. It's going to be a dynamic race.
Maria always races under 2 minutes. Weather permitting, it will be
a fast race.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, Johnson and Greene will hope for the same thing on a
weekend when track gets serious.
</P>
</TEXT>
