<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2890 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0624-COX     06-23 1862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0624-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Parrying that sword hanging over his head
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore said today he's asked his attorney to make public the
entire 150-page transcript of a ``cooperative and professional''
interview with a federal prosecutor about his 1996 fund-raising
activities. ``I think the truth is my friend in this,'' Gore said.
He said he was making the entire interview public because ``I want
people to judge for themselves.'' The supervising attorney for the
Justice Department's campaign finance task force has recommended
appointment of a special counsel to investigate the truthfulness of
Gore's statements about his 1996 fund-raising at a Buddhist temple.
Attorney General Janet Reno so far hasn't indicated how she'll act
on the recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   `LIFELONG LEARNING 'PROPOSALS
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore was unveiling a $2.3 billion ``lifelong learning''
package today featuring tax breaks and community grants aimed at
expanding working training programs. The proposals, being offered
during a symbolic swing through Silicon Valley, are part of a much
larger $40 billion education package. The $2.3 billion price tag
would be over 10 years, and targeted specifically at training
programs in new high-tech fields. Gore is in the second week of his
``prosperity and progress tour'' where he's seeking credit for the
nation's robust economy.
</P>
<P>
   WATCH GORE TELL YOU MAYBE HE'S JUST TOO BRAINY
</P>
<P>
   In an interview airing on ABC's ``20/20'' tonight, Al Gore says
thinking too hard is one of his weaknesses, and wife Tipper jokes
about having had a ``full-time career working psychologically with
this guy.'' Gore also admits what many believe to be true: ``I'm
not a natural, back-slapping politician.'' His greatest weakness?
Gore said it's that he's too cerebral. ``I think sometimes I turn
too much to my head ... in the sense of trying to think through
problems. And Tipper's taught me over the years to feel the
emotional dimension of the challenges that we face.''
</P>
<P>
   ALL PART OF THE BIGGER PICTURE
</P>
<P>
   Delegates to the Green Party National Convention are meeting
this weekend to nominate Ralph Nader as their candidate for
president, hoping he can provide the party with the higher profile
it needs to make significant inroads in states where their issues
play well. Nader, a lifelong consumer advocate, concedes he has no
chance for the White House, but is looking for a bigger prize. He
hopes to use his increasing clout to push favored issues, such as
election reform, health care and fighting what he says is the
concentration of power in corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   A KEYHOLE INTO CHARACTER
</P>
<P>
   Gary Graham may be dead, but debate over capital punishment will
shadow George W. Bush's White House bid because his state is
scheduled to execute an average of one man a week through Election
Day. Bush's handling of the furor over how the death penalty is
meted out in Texas might be a window into his personality, giving
voters a preview of how he might deal with the nation's weightiest
public policy decisions. ``Someday, he might have to push a button
that doesn't just fry an individual but says, `We are at war,' ''
said Marc Landy, chairman of Boston College's political science
department. ``The issue with Bush is not does he have the guts to
do it, but is he a judicious, thoughtful, mature leader?''
</P>
<P>
   THE NADER FACTOR
</P>
<P>
   Months after they dismissed Ralph Nader as a fringe third-party
candidate who would fade quickly, Democratic and Republican
strategists now say that the consumer advocate has emerged as more
politically potent than Pat Buchanan and could deeply complicate Al
Gore's candidacy. Nader, who is expected to capture the Green
Party's nomination in Denver this weekend, already is forcing Gore
to compete more vigorously for the enthusiastic support of labor
and other groups that are reliably Democratic. And in a tight
general election race with George W. Bush, a few points could make
a difference _ and force Gore to reconsider his strategy in
important states.
</P>
<P>
   COELHO'S PROBLEM A BRAIN CYST
</P>
<P>
   Tony Coelho, the recently exited campaign chairman for Al Gore,
has a brain cyst that doesn't appear to be life-threatening.
Campaign manager Donna Brazile, who has kept in close touch with
Coelho since he stepped down a week ago citing an inflamed colon,
said earlier this week that his health problems turned out to be
worse than first thought: a cyst was discovered at the base of his
brain. Elaborating, Brazile said Coelho, 58, suffered from other
non-life-threatening ailments, including an irregular heartbeat. He
was replaced by Commerce Secretary William Daley.
</P>
<P>
   HE HAD THE WINDFALL AT HIS BACK
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission said it will investigate
Rick Lazio's parlaying $2,300 into $16,000 in one day in stock
option trading. Lazio, running against Hillary Clinton for the
Senate in New York, denied any wrongdoing and said he'll cooperate.
But while Lazio talked cooperation, campaign manager Bill Dal Col
went on the attack: ``The Clinton administration has a long history
of abusing federal authority and using government bureaucracies to
attack their political opponents. Today, they reached a new low.''
No immediate comment from the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   OIL MONEY GREASES THE CAMPAIGN
</P>
<P>
   Oil and gas money has been the essential lubricant of George W.
Bush's political career. It financed his unsuccessful run for
Congress in 1978, helped him win the governor's office in 1994, and
is fueling his run for president now. Bush's biggest lifetime
patrons are employees of the Enron Corp. and at least 25 of his top
fund-raisers, the ``Pioneers,'' are connected to the oil business.
The second-largest source of contributions for his presidential
campaign is the Houston law firm Vinson &AMP; Elkins, which prides
itself on the size and reach of its oil and gas practice.
</P>
<P>
   LET'S SEE THOSE FACES
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia City Council, in an effort to prevent violence
at the Republican convention, adopted an anti-mask ordinance
modeled on a Georgia law aimed at combating the Ku Klux Klan. The
council voted 11-5 to make it illegal for anyone to wear a mask
with the intent of threatening or intimidating another person. The
new ordinance, which still must be signed by Mayor John Street, was
crafted with help from the Anti-Defamation League.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN KEEPS SCORING IN NEW HAMPSHIRE
</P>
<P>
   Nearly five months after John McCain trounced George W. Bush in
New Hampshire's presidential primary, his campaign has beat the
Bush organization again. The state's 17 delegates to the Republican
convention elected a national committeeman and committeewoman from
McCain's campaign: Michael Dennehy and Nancy Merrill. McCain, the
48-30 percent primary winner, won 10 of the delegates. Bush won
five and publisher Steve Forbes won two.
</P>
<P>
   CAUSE SHE'S JUST A WORKING MOTHER HERSELF
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton raised $200,000 for his wife's New York Senate
campaign at a private reception for wealthy donors at a Georgetown
mansion. Clinton told two dozen people, who paid $10,000 or more
each to attend _ that Hillary Clinton would make a good senator
because she understands the problems faced by working parents.
</P>
<P>
   BUT THE LAKERS ALREADY WON THE TITLE
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Los Angeles for the 1984 Summer Olympics found a
city transformed: murals depicting the saga of man adorned
freeways, newly planted trees lined roads and the entire city was
swaddled in reds, yellows and blues. But when William Daley, Al
Gore's new campaign chairman, arrived today, he and his staff found
a laid-back city with little being done to prepare for the Aug.
14-17 convention. The major decorating project is a series of small
banners featuring photos of people taken by schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   REPUTATIONS ARE HARD TO OVERCOME
</P>
<P>
   New Al Gore campaign chief William Daley acknowledges that one
of the biggest challenges facing his man is that George W. Bush is
getting credit for the economy, the issue on which Gore had been
basing his hopes. But, Daley said, that's a ``knee jerk'' reaction
and he hopes to counter it by recruiting supporters from big
business and labor to go to Nashville, where Gore's campaign is
based.
</P>
<P>
   Daley: ``I don't know if it's just kind of a gut thing, but
Republicans have always historically got more credit for running
the economy, and being good for the economy, even at the height of
the deficit. So I think we've got a challenge to remind people what
things were like in 1992.''
</P>
<P>
   `SHADOW CONVENTION' SIDESHOW
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan coalition of advocacy groups and celebrities is
planning an alternative to the two conventions. The ``shadow
conventions'' are to highlight three issues: the gap between rich
and poor, campaign finance reform, and the failed war on drugs.
Among those sponsoring the event: Common Cause, Public Campaign and
syndicated columnist Arianna Huffington. Among the celebrities:
Sen. John McCain, actors Warren Beatty and Ron Silver,
``Politically Incorrect'' host Bill Maher and comedian Al Franken.
The proceedings are to be Webcast on www.shadowconventions.com.
</P>
<P>
   AUTOWORKERS RUN OVER OLD ALLY
</P>
<P>
   The United Automobile Workers has retaliated against a longtime
friend who defied the union and supported the China trade bill. Not
only has the UAW decided against endorsing Rep. Sander Levin
(D-Mich.), but it's thrown its support behind his Republican
opponent, Bart Baron. The UAW and the International Brotherhood of
Teamsters persuaded the Michigan AFL-CIO to remain neutral, instead
of supporting Levin. Some labor leaders are criticizing the union,
arguing that if a Republican is elected in the district, it will be
harder for Democrats to regain control of the House.
</P>
<P>
   HE HAS TO LEARN TO EAT THE GRITS
</P>
<P>
   When William Daley made his first trip as campaign chief to Al
Gore headquarters in Nashville to rally the troops the other day,
he passed up the biscuits and grits at breakfast in favor of a
fruit plate. But attendees said he won points anyway by listening
to their suggestions and complaints. Daley's five-minute rallying
speech was closed to the press, but applause and some cheers could
be heard coming from the room.
</P>
<P>
   ESTRANGED BEDFELLOWS
</P>
<P>
   It's Hinson vs. Hinson in divorce court _ and on the campaign
trail. State Rep. Shirley Hinson faces her estranged husband,
Jimmy, on Tuesday in a Republican primary runoff election for her
seat. The couple's high-profile domestic discord _ which includes
alleged death threats, infidelity rumors, jail time and a
restraining order _ has pushed aside most other issues. ``Without
question, unequivocally, it's about revenge,'' says Shirley Hinson,
50, who has been married for 32 years and got into politics at her
husband's urging.
</P>
<P>
   _Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
