<HEADER>
A2895 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-CUCCIA-NYT &LR;      06-23 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CUCCIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENRICO CUCCIA, 92, ITALIAN BANKER 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Enrico Cuccia, a famously reclusive Italian banker who
was at the center of Italian finance for half a century, died
Friday in Milan. He was 92.
</P>
<P>
   Cuccia, who at his death still kept an office at his bank,
Mediobanca SpA, and held the title of honorary chairman, controlled
important parts of the Italian economy for decades, using his bank
to broker mergers and buy shares in a vast web of industrial groups
known as the ``Mediobanca galaxy'' and including Fiat, Pirelli and
Olivetti.
</P>
<P>
   Cuccia was mostly known as a promoter of ``family capitalism,''
using Mediobanca, which for most of its history was controlled by
state banks, to aid Italy's most powerful industrial families like
the Agnellis. Leopoldo Pirelli, the former chairman of Pirelli SpA,
once joked, ``What Cuccia wants, God wants, too.''
</P>
<P>
   When the news of his death broke around noon, the Italian
Banking Association interrupted a meeting for a minute of silence.
In a different kind of homage, on the stock exchange in Milan,
Mediobanca shares went up 6.2 percent as investors gambled that
Cuccia's demise would lead to a reorganization of the Mediobanca
empire, and even a takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few years, Mediobanca lost some of its influence
to foreign competition and a changing Italian economy. But Cuccia
played an important role in the battle last year for Telecom
Italia, the Italian telephone and communications company; he
advised Olivetti as it beat a rival offer from Deutsche Telekom in
the takeover of Telecom Italia.
</P>
<P>
   Cuccia, a short, stooped man who favored gray suits, never gave
interviews; news photographers stalked him on his way to work. But
his reticence had limits. His most recent entry in Who's Who in
Italy described him as having played ``a major role in all of the
major financial operations in Italy.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Rome to a Sicilian family, Cuccia began his career at
Italy's central bank and in 1934 moved to the Istituto per la
Ricostuzione Industriale, or IRI, a state holding company that had
been set up in 1932 by the fascist government to manage state
property. The IRI founder and chairman, Alberto Beneduce, became
his father-in-law in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   In 1938, Cuccia began working at the state-controlled Banca
Commerciale Italiana. His father-in-law tapped him in 1946 to start
Mediobanca, which was created by two IRI-controlled banks and the
Banco di Roma to act as a medium-term lender for big industry, an
activity then forbidden to Italian commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
   Under his leadership, Mediobanca bought minority shares in
important companies and became their banker, arranging major
mergers. Cuccia arranged the 1966 merger of Montecatini and Edison,
which became Italy's chemical giant, Montedison.
</P>
<P>
   He worked closely with the Fiat chairman Gianni Agnelli. In
1986, Cuccia helped the wealthy Agnelli family get rid of the
Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi as a shareholder in Fiat by buying
back shares of the automotive empire worth $3.1 billion. Cuccia
made the Agnellis even richer, but the complicated financial
arrangement he devised cost an international group of banks $600
million in losses.
</P>
<P>
   Cuccia's cachet remained intact, but his absolute power seemed
to wane in the early 1990s, when several deals he sought to broker
fell through. However, it was mostly the changes in the Italian
economy that loosened Cuccia's grip on major transactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Italian economic world was made of state holdings and
family-owned fortunes,'' said Fabio Tamburini, author of ``A
Sicilian in Milan,'' an unauthorized biography of Cuccia.
``Mediobanca, which was controlled by IRI and has as its board
members the most powerful families, was the clearinghouse for these
two worlds, which today no longer exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Giuliano Amato, a former head of Italy's
antitrust authority, was one of many who on Friday paid tribute to
Cuccia's prominent role in recent Italian history, but he also made
clear that he disapproved of Cuccia's web of cross-shareholdings,
which critics viewed as stifling competition.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the coincidence that Cuccia died a few days before IRI,
the symbol of state ownership, was due to be closed after the sale
of most of its assets, Amato said, ``He represented the best of
Italian capitalism, which is now undergoing profound
transformation.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuccia's wife, whose unusual first name, Idea Nuova Socialista
(New Socialist Idea), reflected the ideological fashions of an
earlier era, died in 1996. Cuccia is survived by two daughters and
a son.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
