<HEADER>
A2896 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-LEWINSKY-$ADV25-N     06-23 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-LEWINSKY-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MONICA'S STORY, A CHAPTER ON ENTREPRENEURSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   By ABBY ELLIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Monica Lewinsky breezed into her mother and
stepfather's penthouse apartment in Manhattan and sighed. After
apologizing for being late _ she couldn't find a cab, traffic was
awful _ she kissed her stepfather goodbye as he was leaving and
plopped down in a chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so lucky,'' she murmured. It's not the sort of assessment
that one might expect from Lewinsky, but she seemed to mean it.
</P>
<P>
   At 26, she is still young, but she seemed poised, no longer the
wide-eyed White House intern. And she appeared excited about her
role at the helm of her new handbag-design company, The Real Monica
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Her handbags, made of cloth in a ``hippie chic'' style, are sold
at Henri Bendel in Manhattan, at Fred Segal Melrose in West
Hollywood, Calif., and on her Web site, therealmonicainc.com. ``I
originally wanted to use Monicainc.com, but that was taken,'' she
said. ``A friend said, `What about The Real Monica Inc.?' and I
thought, `OK.'''
</P>
<P>
   By now the story of how she started her business is almost as
well-known as the person. Two years ago, while the White House
scandal was playing out, Lewinsky had some time on her hands. She
put it to use knitting, but found that she couldn't afford the bag
she wanted for carrying the yarn. Having some experience in sewing
_ she designed costumes for high school plays _ she decided to make
her own handbags.
</P>
<P>
   Friends loved them _ and suggested that she place them in
stores. She did some research and, with help from a few friends,
wrote a loosely detailed mission statement, which provided general
information about the product line and guidelines for how the
company would be run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided that the Web would really be the best place to
start,'' she said. ``We have a 24-hour store, in every city, in
every state, in every country in the world. And we've had sales all
over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The site has had more than 5 million hits since its debut last
September. On March 22, when the bags were first sold at Bendel's,
she received 400 e-mail messages. She does not respond to such
notes personally, but a small customer service department does, and
she says she takes suggestions seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get tons of e-mails from young people starting out and they
want advice,'' she said. ``It's a difficult situation: I don't know
that I feel comfortable giving anybody advice.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky is not in charge of company finances, having delegated
the job to one of her four partners. ``I'm involved in the sense
that I know what's going on, but not in the day to day,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But she designs all the bags, which are sewn by hand at an
apparel manufacturer in Louisiana, where about 12 people are
working for her.
</P>
<P>
   She buys the fabric herself from showrooms in Dallas and in the
garment district of Manhattan. ``They all know me by name,'' she
said, then stopped and laughed: ``Well, everyone knows me by my
name, but they think of me as a different Monica, not that one.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, she said, no one seems fazed by her notoriety. ``The
people with whom I've been working have been wonderful,'' she said.
``At first there was probably a slight hesitation to take what I
was doing seriously, but after they spent about five minutes with
me they began to treat me like they would any customer.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many other young Internet entrepreneurs, she readily
acknowledged that she knew nothing about business before starting
her company. ``If you'd said, B-to-B? B-to-C? Venture capital? I'd
have thought it was a ride at Disney,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But she is learning quickly. She's had to.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, people were not exactly begging to be involved in
a Monica Lewinsky project. And contrary to popular perception, she
said, she is not a millionaire _ and is instead working to get out
of debt. Although she declined to be specific, published reports
have put her legal fees at $1.5 million. (She reportedly earned
$500,000 for her book, ``Monica's Story,'' and had a $300,000
endorsement deal with Jenny Craig, the diet company.)
</P>
<P>
   ``People have such a misconception about my financial
situation,'' she said. ``My parents aren't helping me out; I paid
them back for the money they put out.'
</P>
<P>
   Her finances were so precarious that at first she bought fabric
at retail _ partly, she said, because she wanted to keep the
business a secret until it was ready, partly because she didn't
think she would get credit as a young entrepreneur. ``I used to
make fun of myself for that, but I recently heard from several
people that a lot of people start out buying materials retail,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Now she does have credit, and a viable product. She and her four
partners, who prefer to remain anonymous _ all are friends, with
either business, Web or design experience _ are negotiating for
venture capital. She did not disclose specifics, but as for sales,
she said, ``Our first quarter in 2000 is two times that of our
first quarter in 1999, and we're expecting similar growth for the
second quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Is she exploiting herself to make a buck? After all, on the Web
site are the handwritten words ``Made especially for you by
Monica,'' surrounded by roses. There is also a list of questions,
like ``Where can I acquire autographed books and pictures?'' (The
answer: For now, you can't.) and ``What is the lipstick that Monica
wore on the Barbara Walters special?'' (Club Monaco Glaze).
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, the name is what attracts people to the
product, but what's going to satisfy the customer is that it's a
great product,'' Lewinsky said. ``I don't want people to think I'm
taking advantage of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Burstell, the general manager at Bendel's, agreed. ``We
bought 200 bags and did a blind test last Christmas, with no hype
at all,'' he recalled. ``They evaporated in two weeks. They really
fit in fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   In March, 250 bags were sold at Bendel's the day that Lewinsky
appeared in the store. Burstell estimated that nearly 500 people
showed up to see her bags _ or, perhaps, to see her.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky said of that day, ``To see all of the bags there,
displayed so beautifully and to be in such a prominent place, I
just started crying.''
</P>
<P>
   Burstell first heard about the bags from a friend who had seen
them in California and told him to call Lewinsky. He did. They met,
and he was impressed. ``I was amazed at how funny she is,'' he
said, ``and she comes unattended'' _ without an entourage _ ``which
I found refreshing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bendel's just received its summer order: 400 new purses and
totes, priced from $80 to $170. ``They'll go soon,'' Burstell said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky has just finished designing a fall-winter-holiday line
that will hit the shelves at the end of summer. Other pieces _ a
makeup case, messenger bag, and a ``Mommy tote'' for things like
diapers _ are in the works.
</P>
<P>
   She is also considering taking classes, most likely in
e-commerce, to prepare for the future.
</P>
<P>
   And is she proud of herself?
</P>
<P>
   She smiled. ``When something goes from conception to opening on
the Web, to selling out at Christmas and being in stores like
Bendel's and Fred Segal, to then looking into getting venture
capital _ all within the year _ that is something to smile about,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially if you compare it to the year before.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
