u i BC-RUSSIA-MEDIA-580&AMP;ADD-     06-23 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-MEDIA-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN MEDIA MAGNATE REFUSES TO ANSWER PROSECUTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Vladimir Gusinsky, the Russian media tycoon whose
arrest last week raised fears here of a crackdown on the press,
refused to answer questions Friday from state prosecutors who say
he helped defraud the government. He called the charges nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   President Vladimir Putin gathered his security advisers in the
Kremlin on Friday to draft a new national ``information doctrine''
_ one that Putin said would be rooted in total press freedom and
the absence of state censorship.
</P>
<P>
   The two counterpoints only underscored the breadth of the gulf
separating the Kremlin and Gusinsky, a frequent critic whose
businesses have come under growing government pressure this year.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky is apparently accused _ the prosecutors' inquiry
remains secret _ of swindling the state out of $10 million during
his purchase of a St. Petersburg television station in 1997. He has
said that his holding company, Media-Most, actually poured nearly
$5 million into what was then a penniless business.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the head of Putin's security council suggested
that the Kremlin's view of a free press might not square with that
of Gusinsky or other liberals.
</P>
<P>
   Putin was quoted as telling the security council that ``without
a free media, there is no free society.'' But the security council
head, Sergei Ivanov, said later that the council did not exclude
creating an ``appropriate state mechanism'' to ensure public
support for the government.
</P>
<P>
   That hinted at a new state information agency or ministry, a
prospect certain to alarm those who remember the Soviet Union's
overpowering propaganda machine.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky on Friday accused the government of trying to shoehorn
the independent press into that role, saying that his prosecution
was designed to install a new head of Media-Most who would ``force
journalists to tell stories about the grandness of our president.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody even seems to be trying to hide that it is absurd,'' he
said. ``I am not going to take part in this nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky's empire, which includes the nation's only independent
television network, leading newspapers and a weekly newsmagazine,
has been a frequent problem for the Kremlin and a sharp critic of
Putin's policy on the war in Chechnya. Gusinsky has also been close
to political rivals of the Kremlin, like Moscow's mayor, Yuri
Luzhkov.
</P>
<P>
   As if to cap a week of maneuvering by the two enemies, the
prosecutors said Friday that Gusinsky would not be allowed the
leave the country this weekend to visit his family, who live in
Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has stayed above any bad blood between the Kremlin and
Media-Most, even saying that he was not told in advance of
Gusinsky's arrest last week. But his government has been pressing
the company on many fronts this year, from private warnings to tone
down its television news coverage to public threats by a major
creditor, the state-controlled Gazprom natural-gas monopoly, to
call in its loans.
</P>
<P>
   Gazprom, which says it owns 14 percent of Media-Most outright
and holds another 40 percent as loan collateral, ratcheted up the
pressure again this week, naming a former Kremlin official to
oversee its media holdings and negotiate with Gusinsky for
repayment of the loans.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has been variously assailed by Moscow's liberals and
intellectuals as a tool of warring tycoons and a threat to
democracy for the government's actions against Gusinsky and
Media-Most. But outside Moscow the case has raised barely a ripple.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Nor does it seem to have affected his political clout. On Friday
the lower house of Parliament voted overwhelmingly to approve
Putin's plan to reshape Parliament's upper house, the Federation
Council, by ousting all of Russia's governors and their appointees
from the body.
</P>
<P>
   The change is universally seen as strengthening Putin's grip on
Russia's wayward provinces _ and weakening the governors,
potentially some of his most powerful opponents.
</P>
<P>
   But despite this week's talk of a crackdown on the press and a
move toward authoritarian rule, the lower house voted 302-86 for
the measure. Putin needed 300 votes to override any veto by the
Federation Council, and political analysts said Friday that he
could get even more if the upper house decides to fight the
overhaul.
</P>
</TEXT>
