<HEADER>
A2905 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV25-B     06-23 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV25-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOILING IT DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June   25)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To begin with, there's too much news.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the day shift got to work Friday at the Globe's
foreign desk, there were already 755 stories in the foreign news
computer queue. And that doesn't take into account what our own
people were writing from their outposts, what the various news
services would continue to pour forth during Friday's news cycle,
and whatever accident, flood, famine, terrorist act, or film star
scandal erupted while I was getting coffee.
</P>
<P>
   What we do is try to sort it out for you, what happened in the
rest of the world. It's like bolting a water bubbler onto the end
of a gushing firehose. You have to slow it down and squirt it in
one direction in order to drink it.
</P>
<P>
   If you think of news as casualties on the battlefield of life,
the term is ``triage,'' sorting out which cases are urgent, which
can wait temporarily, and which can afford a good leaving alone for
a while.
</P>
<P>
   If your metaphor of choice is the supermarket, we try to stock
the shelves with a reasonably balanced selection of meat, potatoes,
green vegetables, canned soups, soda pop, and cookies (that would
be the comics). Foreign news, study after study tell us as the
circulation folk peer over the reader surveys, is in the category
of broccoli, kale, Chinese cabbage, and rutabaga.
</P>
<P>
   Readers know it's supposed to be good for them; they just have
to force themselves to choke it down. Friday's queue contained
hundreds of more-or-less routine items, including one slugged
``French-dogpoop'' that would have informed you that it costs
Parisian taxpayers 10 francs per kilo for what city employees scoop
up on their ``poobikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether you get to read a story or not always comes down to some
editor's decision. Orders. Whim. Hunch. Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   So in the never-ending battle of scheming how to get the
customers to eat their spinach, editors have some rules of thumb.
Terrorism goes first, plane crashes (often the same category) go
second, floods or hurricanes next, and earthquakes, depending upon
the number of dead and the amount of dramatic video tape readily at
hand.
</P>
<P>
   Then we move over into the slow lane: Chiefs of state nattering,
foreign ministers convening, do-gooders conclaving,
non-governmental-organizations decrying. And then there's the UN.
The United Nations, so elegant in concept, so expensive in budget,
so ineffective in practice, so infuriating in bureaucratic
tendentiousness. The UN. So easy to get mad at.
</P>
<P>
   What will happen this week in Geneva is yet another attempt by
the UN to address the bedeviling challenges of globalization, this
time in Geneva, at a five-year-after-the-fact follow-up to see how
things have changed since the Copenhagen meeting of 1995 that tried
to set things right.
</P>
<P>
   Rare will be the newspaper that will devote much if any space to
the deliberations in Geneva of the Special Session of the General
Assembly on Social Development. At issue is globalization _ how do
the poor fare while the rich are going gangbusters?
</P>
<P>
   There is fierce debate underway among the experts, economists,
bureaucrats, bankers, politicians, NGO-ers, and assorted kibbitzers
about how best to bring the really-poor up into the working-stiff
category.
</P>
<P>
   Sample debate: Is Nike a filthy-rich corporate exploiter of poor
peasant labor in Vietnam stitching together sneakers for
overprivileged American kids? Or is Nike a genuine force for good
in a Third World backwater where it provides jobs for 50,000
peasants who'd otherwise be pulling rice plants out of the mud for
pennies a day?
</P>
<P>
   When you get to the level of the United Nations, or the World
Bank, or the International Monetary Fund, these debates become
terribly complex. Which is why you can understand the editorial
temptation to run the ``French-dogpoop'' story ahead of the dreary
analysis from Geneva about how there was this terrifically
complicated debate about how to deal with globalization.
</P>
<P>
   As an expert on neither subject, I can approach this challenge
in the true spirit of journalism: starting from ignorance. I am
with Sir Francs Bacon: start in certainty, end in doubt; start in
doubt, end in certainty. Maybe. Since no one can figure out yet if
Sir Frank was the real Shakespeare or not, I figure he must have
started out in certainty on that one.
</P>
<P>
   But back to Geneva: On one side are those who think development
has to come first, and social progress and poverty-fighting later.
On another side, there are those who advocate helping the poor
first, and not being so immediately concerned with unleashing
market forces. It's a gross oversimplification, no doubt, but then
so is much of journalism.
</P>
<P>
   I only have about 15 lines left here. I'll make this simple:
About one out of five people on this planet live on less than a
dollar a day. That's the bottom line. When the World Bank expert
hired to write this year's World Development Report, Ravi Kanbur,
quit in protest over the way things were going, a lot of academics,
outsiders, and NGO types expressed alarm.
</P>
<P>
   Writing Wednesday in the Financial Times, Martin Wolf put it
this way: ``The World Bank is not Oxfam . . . this dispute
demonstrates that the Bank cannot run with both the pro-growth,
pro-market hares and the anti-growth, anti-market hounds. It has to
choose between them.''
</P>
<P>
   We'll see another version of this conflict between pro- and
anti-market forces played out in the streets outside the American
political conventions this summer, just as we saw the street
theater in Seattle over the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The person America elects as president this November will have
more influence over the outcome of this argument, as over so many
others, than any one else among the 6 million-plus roaming the
planet.
</P>
<P>
   David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 1738EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
