r s BC-FBN-MNF-HNS &LR;      06-23 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MNF-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ABC TAKES A GAMBLE ON ITS FRONT-LINE `MFN' TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PETE DOUGHERTY   
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forty-five minutes into a conference call that was convened
Thursday to allow 125 reporters to speak with the new ``Monday
Night Football'' principles, Dan Fouts' voice was heard for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame quarterback definitely wasn't the newsmaker.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to spice what the network perceived as a
``sameness'' to its NFL telecasts, ABC hired comedian Dennis Miller
_ and Fouts _ to fill the booth alongside Al Michaels.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who tried (some would say unsuccessfully) to follow
Chevy Chase on ``Saturday Night Live,'' now is left with trying to
bring back the prime-time magic missing from ``Monday Night
Football'' since the departure of the late Howard Cosell in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't Chevy,'' Miller said. ``I'm not going to be Howard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Howard is gone. Don (Meredith) is counting his money in Santa
Fe,'' producer Don Ohlmeyer said. ``The world is a different place
than it was in the mid-'70s. Howard, who was outrageous at that
time, I'm not sure would be that outrageous today. We're not trying
to recreate the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Then just why is ABC venturing into the new millennium with a
comedian in the booth?
</P>
<P>
   Some critics accused Ohlmeyer, who returns to the MNF role he
held in the 1970s, of trying to stir publicity. If that was
Ohlmeyer's motive, it worked. Names from Rush Limbaugh to Bill
Parcells to Sterling Sharpe were thrown about in the 3 1/2 months
since Boomer Esiason was fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``People aren't going to tune in week after week to watch a
buzz,'' Ohlmeyer said. ``Like at Indianapolis, at a certain point
the green flag drops. Everybody involved in the telecast either
performs or they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   All parties made it clear that Miller wasn't hired to launch a
nightclub act in the booth, although his persistent attempts to
inject humor into the conference call Thursday were grating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know football like a nerd,'' Miller said. ``I've watched it
my whole life. I'm going to try to stay in the background and ask
questions a fan might ask. I'm not going to pontificate about what
I think a guy should be or shouldn't be doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohlmeyer and Michaels spent Thursday trying to convince the
skeptics that Miller, unlike his ``Saturday Night Live''
predecessors, is a ready-for-prime-time player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Al and I were just knocked out by some of the
observations Dennis made,'' Ohlmeyer said of an in-studio audition
Miller did with Michaels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked out of there thinking Dennis knew as much about the
National Football League as anybody we brought in and anybody I had
talked to over the last several years,'' Michaels said. ``He was
completely up to speed on everything.''
</P>
<P>
   If Miller isn't up to speed, the sophisticated Monday night
audience will know it. From that standpoint, this is a bigger
gamble than when ABC brought Esiason in to replace Frank Gifford.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 1739EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
