<P>
   A FORMER MIGRANT WORKER REMEMBERS DRIVE-IN MOVIES. Columnist
Bill Maxwell laments the closing of St. Petersburg's remaining
outdoor movie theater _ the 28th Street Drive-In. Maxwell, who came
from a family of migrant workers, recalls his childhood love affair
with drive-in movie theaters. He writes: ``No matter where we
traveled, a drive-in was within driving distance. As black migrant
farm workers, we were always strangers ... Rarely were we welcomed
in indoor theaters. But drive-ins were different ... In a strange
way, the drive-in experience gave us dignity.'' (slugged:
BC-DRIVE-IN-MOVIE-THEATRES-NEW-AMERICA-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   FEWER BLACK YOUTHS PURSUE BASEBALL CAREERS. ``These days, fewer
black kids are picking up bats and balls, and among those who do,
few are holding on to them into high school, college and the
pros,'' writes Kevin Blackistone, a columnist for Emerge magazine.
Why? There are more partial scholarships and fewer free rides
available on the baseball diamond. Kids and parents who are looking
to sports to finance a college education are more likely to pursue
football and basketball, where the chance of winning a full
scholarship is much greater. (slugged:
BC-FEW-BLACKS-IN-BASEBALL-NEW-AMERICA-NYTSF)
</P>
