<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2911 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-MNF-MILLER-HNS &LR;      06-23 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MNF-MILLER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MILLER WILL ADD VERVE TO SOMBER `MNF' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't want to go off on a rant here, but this is insane. It
might be insanely brilliant, or criminally insane, or just the
guy-in-the-park-who talks-to- the-squirrels insane, but it is
without a doubt nuts.
</P>
<P>
   I love it.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Miller: Yuppie satirist, award-winning talk show host,
king of the run-on sentence peppered with cultural references,
political asides and f-bombs _ and the new co-host of ABC's
``Monday Night Football.''
</P>
<P>
   In the booth, 46-year-old Miller joins play-by-play man Al
Michaels and another newcomer, former San Diego Charger great Dan
Fouts.
</P>
<P>
   ABC calls the Miller move a risk. I call it potentially great
theater. People will tune in just to see if this stand-in fan
immolates himself on live national television.
</P>
<P>
   Fouts, a Hall of Famer and ABC college football commentator who
previously did NFL games for CBS, was a safe pick. Call it a
running play up the middle on third-and-one.
</P>
<P>
   But Miller? Miller? That's a double-reverse, halfback option
pass from your own 1-yard line. You just don't do it. You'll be
crucified when it blows upon you.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, if it works ...
</P>
<P>
   And it very well might. Sports fans are muttering astonished
four-syllable ``Whaaaaaats?'', while many sportswriters and
commentators are already waxing indignant. Let 'em. Me? After the
initial shock, I smiled, then giggled.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah it's sports, but sports today is show business. Get over
it.
</P>
<P>
   If it's a tight game, football fans are going to watch even if
Pauly Shore is doing the commentary. But to combat a ratings slide
propelled in part by the popularity of Monday night wrestling on
cable _ as well as keep viewers during dog games _ ABC had to
gamble.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe a glib, unconventional talk-show host like Miller _ whose
appointment is already creating a buzz beyond the sports pages _
could make it a show again, provided he proves he knows a tight end
from the end zone. Remember, ``MNF'' was famous for the
entertainment value it got from the late Howard ``I Never Played
the Game'' Cosell, who came to announcing after a career as a
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Consider what Miller, a former ``Saturday Night Live'' cast
member, said on his HBO show ``Dennis Miller Live'' back in 1996:
</P>
<P>
   ``If I see one more athlete make a routine play and do a wild
banshee itchy dance, I'm going to slap the man senseless with my
remote, strap him in the Tony Burgess chair, toothpick his eyes
open, and make him watch a little bit of the old Nike
ultracommercialism till he pukes.''
</P>
<P>
   When was the last time you heard a former player drop a
``Clockwork Orange'' reference into a telecast?
</P>
<P>
   Or:
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, if I have to see Neon Deion
Prime-Time-Do-Rag-Video-Game-Rap-Album-
Krugerrand-Necklace-Wearing-Pizza-Hut-Two-Sport Sanders
high-stepping in the end zone like some kind of Bob Fosse-trained
Nazi one more time, I think I'm going to do the Icky Shuffle right
off a (expletive) cliff.''
</P>
<P>
   Admit it: That is a whole lot better than ``What a great play,
Al!''
</P>
<P>
   Michaels calls a very good game, and does his homework. Fouts
will supply the Xs and Os, breaking down the zone blitz and hitch
patterns and trap blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Miller? Let him rag on the fat drunk guy in the stands wearing
face paint and no shirt.
</P>
<P>
   It's insane. It's going to be a disaster. Then again, maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a running back can throw a decent pass from his own
goal line.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Miller says: That's just my opinion. I could be wrong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
