<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEW-BLACKS-IN-BASEBALL-NEW-AMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEWER BLACK YOUTHS PURSUE BASEBALL CAREERS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By KEVIN BLACKISTONE  
 &HT;    Erick Strickland was a throwback athlete during his high school
days in Bellevue, Neb. Unlike most kids, he didn't just concentrate
on one sport. Unlike most black kids, he included baseball in his
repertoire.
 &HT;    Strickland became a first team All-Nebraska performer in
basketball, football and baseball. He was recruited in each sport
by the most famous college sports programs in the country. The New
York Yankees even offered to make the 6-foot-3-inch, 220-pound
outfielder a first-round draft pick right out of high school if he
would forget about his other athletic interests and focus on
baseball. Strickland decided otherwise.
 &HT;    He accepted a basketball scholarship to Nebraska, where he led
the Cornhuskers to the National Invitation Tournament title in
1996, was named that tournament's MVP and earned a degree in
sociology.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, he was drafted by the Florida Marlins' baseball
organization and spent his summers playing in the Marlins'
minor-league system. Some of his minor-league teammates, such as
Edgar Renteria and Luis Castillo, graduated to the Marlins'
major-league club that won the World Series in 1997.
 &HT;    By then, however, Strickland was playing only basketball.
Despite not being drafted by an NBA team, he made the Dallas
Mavericks' roster. He signed a six-year contract with the team in
August 1997 and hasn't thought about baseball since.
 &HT;    ``My heart wasn't in it,'' Strickland admits.
 &HT;    These days, fewer black kids are picking up bats and balls, and
among those who do, few are holding on to them into high school,
college and the pros.
 &HT;    Last year, the Northeastern University Center for the Study of
Sport in Society reported that the 3 percent participation rate of
black players in major-league baseball was at a 10-year low. The
center also reports that the participation rate of black players in
Division I college baseball is 3 percent, based on 1996-97 figures.
 &HT;    Major-league baseball, which just three years ago patted itself
on the back for having allowed Jackie Robinson to break its color
barrier in 194, is on the verge of becoming a predominately Latino
sport.
 &HT;    Strickland, 26, says he was lucky to have played baseball at
all. As an Air Force brat who moved around the country, he was
afforded the opportunity that other black kids in urban areas were
not.
 &HT;    ``In the inner city, it's harder to play baseball because you
don't have fields; you don't have places to play,'' Strickland
says. ``Growing up in small towns, growing up in the communities I
did, we had fields and opportunities to play baseball. In the inner
city, kids have basketball courts. It depends on where you live.''
 &HT;    Strickland also admits that he was always more attracted to
sports other than baseball. ``I think in baseball, it doesn't seem
like there's a sense of being involved throughout the whole game,''
he says. ``It seems kind of boring.''
 &HT;    Dennis Poppe, who oversees the college baseball championship
tournament at the NCAA, says the popularity and publicity of
basketball and football has hurt baseball's appeal.
 &HT;    ``I've heard the statement that the slam dunk is more popular,''
Poppe says. ``It could be that.''
 &HT;    Basketball and football certainly are more popular in the
media's eye. On any fall or winter evening, for example, a college
basketball game can be found on television. On any fall or winter
weekend, a college football game can be seen on TV.
 &HT;    The NCAA has a tough time selling baseball to broadcasters,
though, because the games can take three or four hours, and the
threat of cancellation because of weather is always looming, Poppe
says.
 &HT;    Another reason kids of all colors may lean toward football and
basketball is a very practical one: scholarships.
 &HT;    ``We're limited in the numbers of grants-in-aid we give in
baseball compared to other sports,'' Poppe explains.
 &HT;    There are more partial scholarships and fewer free rides
available on the baseball diamond. Kids and parents looking to
sports to finance a college education are more likely to pursue
football and basketball, where the chance of winning a full
scholarship is much greater.
 &HT;    The NCAA is not sitting idly as fewer black kids pursue
baseball. During the College World Series, it holds free clinics,
though not race specific, in the hopes of luring young people to
the diamond.
 &HT;    For several years now, major-league baseball has operated urban
programs specifically to ignite the passion that black kids once
had for the game, as well as to attract new customers for the 21st
century. All in all, though, they are pitches that aren't finding
the mark with black kids.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Kevin Blackistone is a columnist for Emerge magazine.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Hispanic Business magazine 
<TEXT>
