A2946 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-NYT &LR;      06-23 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT CLEARS WAY FOR ELIAN TO RETURN TO CUBA 
</HEADLINE>
   By JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal appeals court Friday rejected a request by Elian
Gonzalez's Miami relatives to reconsider a three judge panel's
refusal to grant the Cuban boy an asylum hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The decision clears a path for Elian to return home with his
father by next Wednesday, seven months after the boy was rescued
floating on an inner tube off the coast of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel Gonzalez, the boy's father, is under a court order
not to remove his son from the United States. But unless the
Supreme Court issues an emergency stay, the appeals court said
Friday that it will issue a mandate at 4 p.m. Wednesday lifting the
court order barring Gonzalez from taking his son back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's Miami relatives, who took care of the boy after his
rescue, filed a petition seeking the rehearing on June 16. But even
then lawyers for the relatives expressed little hope the appellate
court would side with them. Instead they have said that they will
appeal the case to the U.S. Supreme Court and a seek an emergency
order to prevent Gonzalez from taking Elian to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But such stays by the high court are extremely rare, because
justices must only issue them if they believe there is a
substantial likelihood of overturning a lower court decision.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's Miami relatives filed a legal motion on July 16 asking
the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta to rehear the
request for an asylum hearing for the 6-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service has repeatedly
said that only Juan Miguel Gonzalez has the right to request an
asylum hearing for his son. Since Elian was rescued, Gonzalez has
said that he wants to bring his son home to Cuba, and he has fought
attempts by Elian's great-uncle to win an asylum hearing for the
boy.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was one of only three survivors after the boat that he,
his mother and 13 others were in capsized. Elian's mother,
Elisabet, was trying to immigrate with her son to the United
States. She did not tell the boy's father, from whom she was
divorced, that she was taking him from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   For Cubans on both sides of the Straits of Florida, Elian has
become a kind of political totem. In Cuba, Fidel Castro's Communist
government has organized demonstrations demanding Elian's
repatriation. In Miami, Cuban immigrants have held up the boy as a
symbol of freedom, and demanded that the U.S. government not allow
him to be returned to a totalitarian society.
</P>
<P>
   After his rescue, temporary custody of Elian was given to his
great-uncle Lazaro Gonzalez, a Cuban immigrant who lives in Miami.
But Justice Department officials ordered Lazaro Gonzalez to give up
custody after Juan Miguel Gonzalez arrived in Washington, D.C. from
Cuba and agreed to stay until the legal battle over the boy was
resolved. When Lazaro Gonzalez balked at giving up the boy, armed
federal agents raided the Miami home on April 22, seized the boy
and returned him to his father.
</P>
<P>
   Since the raid, Elian has been in the Washington area, first at
a Maryland retreat and later at a home inside the city.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's Miami relatives have contended that the appellate panel
erred when it based its June 1 decision on a 1984 Supreme Court
decision that executive branch agencies, like the INS, are entitled
to wide discretion to interpret their own regulations. The Miami
relatives' lawyers said the court should instead look to a high
court decision from May 1 that said courts need not defer to
executive agencies' decisions that are not based on rules made in
formal procedures.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, the court rejected a Labor Department ruling that
said states could not require public employees to take compensatory
time off at specific times. Lawyers for Elian's Miami relatives
argued that case gave courts the power to overrule the INS.
</P>
<P>
   But the Justice Department has argued that the Miami relatives
are misinterpreting that court ruling, and that even if judges are
not obliged to defer to government agencies, they must not
substitute their interpretations of the law for an agency's.
</P>
<P>
   In a written opinion issued Friday, the appellate court said the
Supreme Court ruling did not apply, and even if it did the court
said that administrative decisions by the executive branch are
still due some deference.
</P>
<P>
   The appellate court decision can be found on the Internet at:
</P>
<P>
   ftp://ftp.ca11.uscourts.gov/usca11/gonzalez2.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
