<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2950 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-RECORD-COLUMN-TEX     06-23 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECORD-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISIT TO NOTRE DAME WOKE UP ECHOES FOR ME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PHIL RECORD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was filled with emotions and memories as I stepped off a bus
one afternoon earlier this month and looked up at that golden dome,
considered by many to be the most famous of college landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   It was appropriate that I was accompanied by my dear friend, Don
Hellinghausen of Midland. Don, then of Breckenridge, and I first
met more than 54 years ago as we ventured forth to attend the
University of Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   Together we had stepped out of a cab at the end of Notre Dame
Avenue and looked up at that golden dome. My emotions were far
different that September day in 1946 than they were this month.
</P>
<P>
   I was awe-struck as I looked at the campus for the first time. I
also was a little bit frightened _ but not homesick _ at the
challenges I would have to face without having a parent to turn to
for the first time in my life.
</P>
<P>
   I had dreamed of attending Notre Dame since I was 10. I had an
uncle and cousin who had attended the northern Indiana school and
was attracted by their stories of life at Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   Ours was not what one would consider a normal freshmen class. I
guess we numbered more than 1,500. Most of these freshmen were
World War II veterans. I was among the handful of non-veterans,
and, at 17, was among the youngest in the class.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the universities and colleges of the 1940s were quite
paternalistic. But the Holy Cross priests, who ran Notre Dame,
carried it to the extreme.
</P>
<P>
   Most students lived in dormitories. Freshmen had to be in their
dorm by 10 p.m. They were permitted to stay out until midnight one
night a week. Sophomores could stay out until midnight twice a
week, juniors three times a week and seniors every night of the
week.
</P>
<P>
   But anyone coming in after midnight paid a big price. I know of
at least one football star who was summarily tossed out of school
for trying to sneak through a dorm window at 1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   It was in our freshman year in 1946 that the good fathers
decided to raise standards dramatically so that the university's
academic standings would more closely match those of the football
team.
</P>
<P>
   On top of all of this, those of us who lived on campus were not
permitted to have a car. You could be kicked out of school if you
were under 21 and caught partaking of any alcoholic beverage _ even
on St. Patrick's Day.
</P>
<P>
   We non-veterans took the tough discipline pretty much in stride.
But there was considerable _ and understandable _ grumbling in the
ranks of the veterans, many of whom had survived the horrors of
war.
</P>
<P>
   And it certainly would be difficult to enforce such edicts in
today's world. But our class survived them. In fact, they were
probably the right thing for our generation.
</P>
<P>
   The camaraderie was unbelievable. The fact that we were all
males who lived in dorms probably contributed to this. (Women were
not to be admitted for two more decades.)
</P>
<P>
   The athletes were granted no privilege other than the training
table during the season of their sports. They had to live among us.
They were treated as just one of the boys by the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   Well almost.
</P>
<P>
   I had a special respect for Leon Hart, the first lineman (he was
an end) to win the Heisman trophy. He weighed more than 250 pounds
and was considered a giant of a player in those days.
</P>
<P>
   During the off-season, Leon had to take physical education, and
I had the misfortune of being on Leon's team. I also had the
misfortune of being a terrible basketball player.
</P>
<P>
   When Leon would get frustrated with my ineptness, he would pick
me up by the nape of my T-shirt (I weighed no more than 140) so he
could chastise me on an eye-to-eye basis.
</P>
<P>
   That first winter at Notre Dame was a killer for a boy from
Texas. Snow quickly lost the glamour of being a fun thing.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the rigid discipline, the frigid winters and the
challenging curriculum, I quickly began a four-year love affair
with a special place called Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   (Retired ombudsman Phil Record is consultant to the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram and is the newspaper's professional in residence at
Texas Christian University's Department of Journalism. He can be
contacted a precord(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
