u f BC-JAPAN-TELECOMS-NYT &LR;      06-23 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-TELECOMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN'S DOCOMO CONSIDERS ENTERING BRITAIN'S WIRELESS MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ NTT DoCoMo Inc., Japan's leading wireless communications
company, dropped hints Friday that it may soon establish a presence
in Britain, a lucrative mobile phone market that would
significantly add to DoCoMo's increasingly fast-paced international
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to press reports that DoCoMo was on the verge of
acquiring a stake in Telesystem International Wireless Inc., a
Canadian company that is heavily invested in the British market, a
senior DoCoMo executive acknowledged that a link with Telesystem
was an attractive option.
</P>
<P>
   The executive, Kiyoyuki Tsujimura, head of DoCoMo's global
business development division, also said a link with Orange, a big
British mobile phone company, was another attractive option.
</P>
<P>
   Tsujimura spoke after the Financial Times, Britain's leading
business daily, and Jiji Press, a Japanese wire service, both
reported that DoCoMo was about to spend 200 billion yen, or about
$1.8 billion, to buy a 15 percent stake in Telesystem.
</P>
<P>
   DoCoMo officials declined to confirm those reports, and the
Japanese company's stock fell 1 percent Friday to 3.01 million yen.
</P>
<P>
   DoCoMo owns 19 percent of Hutchinson Telecom, an affiliate of
the Hong Kong conglomerate Hutchinson Whampoa, which already has a
joint venture with Telesystem to develop a network to provide
mobile services in Britain. Telesystem recently spent $6.4 billion
for one of five new licenses to offer those services and now must
seek partners to help it make the capital investments needed to
exploit the license.
</P>
<P>
   A Telesystem investment would fit in with DoCoMo's strategy of
buying small stakes in foreign mobile phone operators to spread its
``i-mode'' service, the largest mobile Internet access service in
the world with 7 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   The company recently bought a 15 percent stake in KPN
Communications, a Dutch wireless operator, and is rumored to be in
negotiations with VoiceStream Wireless, a U.S. mobile phone
company, and SK Telecom, a Korean mobile phone company.
</P>
<P>
   Tsujimura also said DoCoMo could lease a network to avoid the
acquisition of expensive infrastructure at a time when providing
content and the technology to bring it to tiny phone screens is
looking like a more lucrative business.
</P>
<P>
   DoCoMo is suddenly moving fast to establish a beachhead in
Europe, home of the biggest immediate opportunities in the global
mobile market, because its i-mode technology will be matched by a
technology known as ``wireless application protocol'' or WAP,
within the next year or so.
</P>
<P>
   So far, i-mode enjoys an advantage over WAP, which uses a
different communication format than the Internet and thus requires
Web sites to write completely new programs to deliver their
contents over WAP-enabled mobile phones.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, i-mode uses the same communication format as the
Internet, making it relatively easy for Web sites to connect to
DoCoMo subscribers. But it was only available in Japan until last
month, when Hutchinson Telecom subscribers began to have access to
online racing car games from one of DoCoMo's Japanese content
providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``By sometime next year, the specifications for a new generation
of WAP fully compatible with the Internet will be out,'' Tsujimura
said. ``Then there will be no distinction between WAP and i-mode.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
