A2957 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-CHICKEN-MOVIE-AZR &LR;      06-23 0463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICKEN-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOCK FLEES DINNER-PLATE FATE IN DELIGHTFUL `CHICKEN RUN' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - One can only imagine the pitch meeting for ``Chicken
Run'':
</P>
<P>
   `Hey, let's remake ``The Great Escape,'' only with chickens.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny thing is, it works.
</P>
<P>
   The creators of BBC animation favorites Wallace &AMP; Gromit offer
up a delightful tale about a group of chickens trying to escape
from a bleak egg farm before their evil human owners turn them into
potpies.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's stop-motion animation is top-drawer. Done in
Plasticine (a cousin of Claymation), the chickens have wonderfully
expressive faces that run the gamut of emotions, from stark terror
to anger to elation. They cry when they're sad and sweat when
they're nervous, a la the sinister penguin from W&AMP;G's ``The Wrong
Trousers.''
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, the dialogue is so snappy and the pacing so
smooth that you really find yourself caring about what happens to
your new feathered friends, even if you've been known to frequent
KFC.
</P>
<P>
   The first part of the film is filled with references to ``The
Great'' ``Escape,'' the classic Steve McQueen movie about Allied
POWs in a German prison camp. The chickens dig tunnels, get thrown
into the cooler and even line up for their `commandant.''
</P>
<P>
   They also behave like chickens, panicking at a moment's notice
or attacking their chicken-feed trough with ravenous abandon.
</P>
<P>
   The story focuses on Ginger (voiced by Julia Sawalha), who is
smarter than your average chicken and convinces her cohorts that
there's more to life than laying eggs and ultimately ending up as a
Sunday dinner. She's joined by Rocky the Rooster (Mel Gibson), a
circus performer on the lam who agrees to help.
</P>
<P>
   Though Ginger routinely fails in her escape attempts, she
redoubles her efforts when she spies the delivery of a giant potpie
machine: a multigeared, clanking piece of hardware that oozes
foreboding.
</P>
<P>
   The farm is run by the fiendish Mrs. Tweedy (splendidly voiced
by Miranda Richardson), who browbeats Mr. Tweedy and tells him that
he's imagining things when he says the chickens are organizing a
breakout. There are some engaging secondary characters, including
two profiteering rats and an air-headed knitting chicken named Babs
(Jane Horrocks).
</P>
<P>
   The film retains the English wit found in Wallace &AMP; Gromit and
includes other trademarks from the popular animated shorts. There's
a well-synchronized dance number and several seamless action
sequences, including an uproarious scene in which the oversize
chickens try to learn to fly.
</P>
<P>
   The final sequence is imaginative and eye-catching. By then, as
funny as it sounds, you're really rooting for the chickens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 1800EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2958 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MEXICO-CITIBANK-NYT &LR;      06-23 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CITIBANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIBANK SEEKS MEXICAN COURT RULING ON PREPAID BAILOUT LOAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAN FINEREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The Mexican government is once again embroiled in
a borrowing problem with Citibank, resurrecting memories of the
Latin debt crisis two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   But this time Mexico is not late in its payments. Rather, the
bank says, Mexico has paid too early.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem odd that a bank would get upset if a borrower with a
legacy of financial instability wanted to pay off a debt early,
known in banking as a prepayment. But for Citibank, Mexico's
prepayment of a $2.5 billion loan means the bank loses hundreds of
millions of dollars in interest income it had assumed would flow in
during the next six years.
</P>
<P>
   For Mexico, the prepayment helps minimize the taxpayer cost of
salvaging the country's banking system, which is still burdened
with insolvencies.
</P>
<P>
   The government has been under intense fire from opposition
parties to curb the mushrooming cost of the bank bailout. And as
the Citibank debt was among the most costly on the books of the
government's bank bailout agency, the government said it decided to
repay now and save taxpayers at least $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   Citibank has insisted the prepayment is illegal and has gone to
a Mexican court to press its case, essentially arguing that Mexico
is not permitted to pay off the debt yet. The timing of the
dispute, coming just days before Mexico's presidential elections,
has made it a political issue.
</P>
<P>
   The government does not want to alienate foreign banks and other
overseas investors whose money is critical to Mexico's economic
stability. At the same time, no Mexican politician wants to be seen
as fearful of a big financial power like Citibank, which to many
Mexicans symbolizes the hold that the United States has
historically exerted over Mexico and other Latin American nations.
</P>
<P>
   It was Citibank, after all, that was among the most aggressive
American lenders to countries like Mexico and Brazil, which
struggled to renegotiate billions of dollars of delinquent debts in
the 1980s. The chief negotiator for American banks during that
crisis, William Rhodes, is a vice chairman at Citigroup, Citibank's
parent company.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's current dispute with Citibank revolves around
Citibank's May 1998 agreement with the government's bank bailout
agency, the Bank Savings Protection Institute, to buy Banca Confia,
a 230-branch commercial bank that had a history of bad management,
money laundering and corruption scandals.
</P>
<P>
   Citibank purchased Confia for $185 million on the understanding
that the government would assume $2.5 billion in Confia debt and
repay it to Citibank over eight years. This would provide Citibank
with about $120 million a year for the restoration of what Julio de
Quesada, the chief executive of Citibank's Mexico subsidiary,
called ``a broken bank.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, De Quesada called the debt a subsidy, ``an
integral part of the deal to compensate the bank for fixing
Confia.'' If the government had not assumed the debt, he said,
Citibank would not have bought Confia.
</P>
<P>
   The bank bailout agency, for its part, maintains that the Confia
agreement allows the agency to pay Citibank back at any time.
Vicente Corta, a lawyer who is executive secretary of the agency,
said it would never have made the prepayment without legal grounds
to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Some banking analysts agree. Lawrence Madsen, who follows the
banking industry for the investment firm UBS Warburg in Mexico
City, said that if the bank bailout agency had not researched the
legality of a prepayment, ``I really would be very surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   A Mexico City judge will hold a June 30 hearing on Citibank's
request for an injunction to stop the prepayment. It is unclear
what the next step in the legal process would be.
</P>
<P>
   But both Citibank and the bank bailout agency have pledged to
use all the legal tools at their disposal to defend their
positions.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers who have been following the case say the argument is
likely to center on whether the Confia sale documents specify that
Mexico's bank bailout agency can pay back the debt in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Citibank argues that the documents only allow the prepayment of
the total equity value of Confia, now worth about $137 million.
Corta of the bank bailout agency says there is no prohibition
against further payments. Citibank also argues that the bailout
agency violated the Mexican Constitution by assuming it is
empowered to act at all, because the Confia deal was signed by
another Mexican regulatory agency that no longer exists.
</P>
<P>
   Fauzi Hamdan, an opposition party legislator who presides over a
congressional committee overseeing Mexicos bank bailout, said the
bailout agency was acting within its legal rights.
</P>
<P>
   Citibank has also expressed anger over how the prepayment was
made, suggesting it was done deliberately to catch the bank off
guard.
</P>
<P>
   The bank bailout agency announced on the afternoon of May 4 that
the prepayment would be made at noon the following Monday. Because
May 5 was a public holiday, Citibank was not given the opportunity
to protest the payment.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Citibank's legal representatives hand delivered letters
to the houses of the bailout agency directors over the weekend,
explaining that it would be difficult to accept such a huge amount
of money at such short notice. The government responded by
splitting the payment in two _ nearly $1.1 billion on Monday, May
8, and the rest two days later.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers following the case said Citibank was unlikely to drop it
without a promise that Mexico will pay the lost interest. Corta
seems happy to leave it to the judge to decide.
</P>
<P>
   ``If at the end of the day they are in the right, we will pay
all that corresponds to them,'' Corta said. ``But if we are in the
right, then all we ask is that they accept the court's decision and
that they publicly declare that we always acted in accordance with
the law.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 1802EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2961 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-ME-MOVIE-AZR &LR;      06-23 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ME-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST CARREY FLICK IS SICK AND IT'S A SNOOZER, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Near the end of ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene,'' Jim Carrey
beats himself up.
</P>
<P>
   Heaven knows he deserves it. It's fair punishment for starring
in this moronic farce, which lurches from tragically unfunny to
pointlessly raunchy with the grace of a drunken wildebeest.
</P>
<P>
   You have to give the movie some credit, though. It does manage
to offend almost every group, from ethnic minorities to women to
the mentally ill. It also throws in animal cruelty and child abuse,
just for a few more yuks.
</P>
<P>
   When I say this film is offensive, I don't mean it will make
your Aunt Tilly blush. This stuff would have Chris Rock shaking his
head and saying, ``Guys, I just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, this is a Farrelly brothers movie, and they are gross-out
kings. But in their other films (`There's Something About Mary,`
`Kingpin,` `Dumb and Dumber`), some of the raunchy sight gags were
funny. In this one, they're just cruel, gratuitous and sad.
</P>
<P>
   Carrey plays a Rhode Island state trooper named Charlie whose
wife gives birth to three African-American children after having an
affair with a limo driver (who, for no reason at all, is played by
a midget). After she leaves the kids with Charlie, he snaps and
develops an alter ego named Hank.
</P>
<P>
   Hank is a hilarious prankster, dunking children in water
fountains, relieving himself on his neighbor's lawn and assaulting
women on park benches. If none of this sounds funny, it's because
it's not.
</P>
<P>
   The movie just keeps giving you reasons to hate it. If it's not
the insipid ``Dukes of Hazzard'' narration, it's the syrupy score,
which is selection A7 on the Jukebox from Hell. Either that, or The
Captain and Tennille are getting work again.
</P>
<P>
   As for Charlie's grown kids, their chief job seems to be
repeating the same profane phrase over and over again. It's almost
like they're having a contest.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the inane plot, which has Charlie hooking up with
Irene (Renee Zellweger) and chasing around after crooked cops. We
never find out why, but that's OK, because explaining it would make
this movie longer, and nothing is worth that.
</P>
<P>
   Just when you think the movie is only out to offend, it proves
it can be boring, too. If the Farrellys had one shred of human
decency, they would have issued suicide capsules.
</P>
<P>
   But no, we must press on, as the movie turns into a lovey-dovey
road picture with all the charm of a rabid pit bull. There's no
chemistry at all between Carrey and Zellweger, who plays the part
as if she's been hit on the head with a large object.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his rubber-faced gifts, Carrey isn't very creative in
distinguishing his alter egos. He just gives Hank a gravelly voice
and a potty mouth.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, when both personalities inhabit Carrey's body, he
throws himself out of a moving car.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's entertainment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
