   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN _ ATLANTA _ The 12-member 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals refused Friday to take another look at the custody battle
over Elian Gonzalez. The Court denied a request for a rehearing
from the Cuban boy's Miami relatives, who are seeking to keep him
in the United States. A three-judge panel of the Atlanta-based
court had ruled against the Miami relatives earlier this month.
(Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   PLANECRASH _ BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Two aircraft collided west of
this city Friday, sending one crashing into a housing complex,
officials said. The fate of the second aircraft wasn't immediately
known. Three people were killed in the incident, according to early
reports. (Palm Beach Post). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   DAVIDIAN-TRIAL24 _ WACO, Texas _ First week of Davidians civil
lawsuit trial ends with testimony Friday. (Witherspoon, Waco
Tribune-Herald). 30.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH _ AUSTIN, Texas _ When Texas Gov. George W. Bush stepped up
to a bank of microphones to let the world know that Gary Graham's
fate was sealed, his voice and manner were somber and serious _ a
stark contrast to the smirky, frat boy image he has been battling
throughout his campaign. How did Bush handle himself Thursday? We
explore and assess. (Heath, Austin American-Statesman). 20-22.
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   AIRPORT-HUBS _ WASHINGTON _ With the proposed merger of United
Airlines and U.S. Airways, United plans to expand Charlotte as a
hub airport and compete with Atlanta and Delta on routes in the
Southeast, officials of the two companies told a congressional
hearing Friday. (O'Dell, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving on NYT in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CONGESTION-CHARLESTON _ CHARLESTON, S.C. - As he fights traffic
in this historic - and increasingly congested - city where he has
been mayor for a quarter century, Joseph Riley defends what he
calls Charleston's ``strategic'' economic development. But each big
project, such as the $69 million state aquarium that opened last
month, brings more tourists. And some in Charleston complain that
the city risks losing the charm that, year after year, places it on
the list of most hospitable U.S. cities. ``What a great aquarium is
a science museum,'' Riley counters, ``and great cities have art
galleries and museums and zoos so that its citizens can be inspired
and learn from true important civic institutions in their midst.''
(Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADES _ WASHINGTON - Federal and state officials reached an
agreement late Thursday that will assure adequate water to the
Everglades while protecting current users rights for the future.
The agreement sets the stage for a Senate panel to approve the
Everglades restoration project next week. (Lipman, Cox News
Service). 15.
</P>
