<P>
   NBA DRAFT
</P>
<P>
   BKN-DRAFT-MIHM _ AUSTIN _ Orlando Magic General Manager John
Gabriel has two words for those who would dismiss Chris Mihm
offhand as unfit to play center effectively in the NBA. Brad
Daugherty. Gabriel considers Daugherty a cautionary tale for those
taking measure of NBA draft prospects. Daugherty, a college star at
North Carolina in the mid-1980s, was widely considered to lack the
toughness necessary to work near the basket as a pro. As NBA scouts
took measure of him, Daugherty was tattooed with the ``S'' word _
too soft. Based on that reputation, Philadelphia, which had the No.
1 pick in the 1986 draft, traded it to Cleveland. As it turned out,
Daugherty became one of the better centers in the NBA. Using skill
and athleticism more than muscle and intimidation, Daugherty became
a five-time all-star, averaging 19 points a game before his career
was cut short after eight seasons because of a back injury.
Gabriel, voted the NBA's top executive this season, says, ``I think
you have to be careful when you label people soft. I was part of
that staff in Philadelphia. We could have drafted Daugherty, but
there were concerns that he was too soft.''Chris Mihm is an NBA
player. (Rosner, Austin American-Statesman). 49. WITH FILE PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-DRAFT-SPURS _ AUSTIN _ The San Antonio Spurs do not have a
first-round draft pick, a condition they are considering changing.
The Spurs would have selected 24th in the draft Wednesday if they
had not traded their pick to Chicago for guard Steve Kerr in
January, 1998. Hoping to move back into the first round, the Spurs
will offer the two second-round picks they hold, Nos. 41 and 54
overall. The 41st pick was acquired in a trade with Dallas last
year. No. 54 is the Spurs' own second-round slot.The Spurs, who do
not have a first-rounder, may try to trade two seconds for a first.
(Rosner, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   BKN-DRAFT-ROCKETS _ AUSTIN _ Carroll Dawson, the Houston Rockets
executive vice president of basketball, figures the law of averages
will prevent him from making a blockbuster deal during this year's
NBA draft. After all, the Rockets stunned the league last year,
acquiring point guard Steve Francis, the second pick in the draft,
in a trade with Vancouver.The Houston Rockets have a first round
pick and are looking for a player to match with Steve Francis.
(Rosner, Austin American-Statesman).16.
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPICS
</P>
<P>
   RUN-MARIONJONES _ Advance two big track meets _ Prefontaine meet
at Eugene, Ore. and Adidas meet at Portland, Ore. Marion Jones has
brashly staked her claim on 5 gold medals in Sydney, but she'll
need a lot of luck not to slip up in the long jump. The field event
gives her fits, and she'll try to master it and the 100 meters at
the Prefontaine Classic. (Fish, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
