<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2973 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-AUSTIN0624-COX     06-23 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-AUSTIN0624-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush unscathed by execution according to analystBy Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The controversy that swirled around convicted
murderer Gary Graham's execution should not damage Gov. George W.
Bush's White House bid even as potent questions about the way Texas
metes out justice persist, political observers said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Graham proclaimed his innocence until his death by lethal
injection at 8:39 p.m. Thursday, two hours after he was scheduled
to die because appeals by his lawyers delayed the execution.
Shortly before the execution, Bush told reporters, ``I am confident
that justice is being done. May God bless the victims, the families
of the victims and may God bless Mr. Graham.''
</P>
<P>
   That somber tone, coupled with polls showing that two-thirds of
Americans continue to support the death penalty, has insulated Bush
from fallout over the execution of a ninth-grade dropout convicted
on the testimony of a single eyewitness, said Larry Sabato, a
political scholar at the University of Virginia. Ironically, he
said the whole controversy could wind up damaging Vice President Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush's position has helped him,'' Sabato said. ``He appeared
compassionate and serious throughout the episode. He did not appear
blood thirsty, which would have hurt him. By inference, Gore was
portrayed as anti death-penalty, which he's not. His allies, like
Jesse Jackson, were the people out front calling for an abolition
of the death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore remained largely silent throughout the debate, saying only
that states with high rates of criminal justice errors, such as
Illinois, should consider suspending executions. Republican
Illinois Gov. George Ryan's decision to take that step earlier this
year helped set off questions about the death penalty. Ryan did so
after 13 men on death row in his state were exonerated.
</P>
<P>
   Sabato said Gore's silence has been a tactical mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the average person not paying close attention to politics,
the assumption is that if Bush is for the death penalty, that Gore
must be against it,'' he said. ``Gore reinforced that by not
commenting. He didn't want to get into it. And what he did say was
equivocal.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Jano Cabrera called Sabato's take, ``entirely
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore was on the front page of the New York Times
unequivocally stating his support for the death penalty....,''
Cabrera said. ``Every time he's been asked about it, he's made his
position clear, that he supports the death penalty for heinous
crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   University of Texas political scientist Bruce Buchanan said
there is no good political reason for Bush to soften his death
penalty stance even with 15 executions lined up before the November
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing that I can see suggests that the public is going to
revise its view of either the death penalty or of Governor Bush,''
Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   But given questions raised about the quality of legal
representation for Texas death row inmates, Bush should consider
softening his language when he asserts that he is certain that all
135 people executed on his watch have been guilty, Sabato
cautioned.
</P>
<P>
   A recent investigation by the Chicago Tribune raised questions
about shoddy legal representation and the use of jailhouse
witnesses in capital cases in Texas. Nationally, a Columbia
University study found that two-thirds of death sentences in the
past 23 years have been overturned and DNA testing has led to the
release of innocent men on death row.
</P>
<P>
   Sabato said it would strengthen the, ``compassionate part of his
compassionate conservatism,'' for Bush to ask Attorney General John
Cornyn to conduct a study over the next few months of how the death
penalty is applied in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should the governor be given pardon power?'' Sabato said.
``That's seems like a perfectly reasonable question to ask.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Texas law, a governor may not override the 18-member Board
of Pardons and Paroles, all gubernatorial appointees, if it votes
to move forward with an execution. A governor can grant a single,
unilateral 30-day reprieve, a choice Bush said he did not have this
time because former Gov. Ann Richards had already given Graham such
a delay.
</P>
<P>
   David R. Dow, a law professor at the University of Houston, said
the argument that Bush was powerless to delay Graham's execution
is, `` a myth that's been created by the governor's office.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think about that provision, the obvious logic is to
prevent a single governor from thwarting a jury verdict by issuing
stay after stay after stay,'' he said. ``It suggests that what it
really means is that a single governor can only grant a single
stay. So, I think he had the power under that law to grant a
single, 30-day reprieve.''
</P>
<P>
   Dow said it would take a court challenge to clarify the statute,
unlikely given the politics surrounding Graham's case. Cornyn's
office also read the law to mean that Bush could not grant a 30-day
reprieve.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're allies and that's the interpretation that best
protected Governor Bush,'' Dow said.
</P>
<P>
   After Graham had exhausted his appeals Thursday, the state could
legally have moved ahead with the execution even though his
lawyers, taking their last shot, filed a civil suit against the
pardons board. Ironically, presidential politics probably gave
Graham more time, Dow said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at that point, if it were not Gary Graham, if it were
not for all this national media attention, I wouldn't have been
surprised if the state had gone ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
