<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2980 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-CAR-ROAD-COURSE-NYTR &LR;      06-23 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-ROAD-COURSE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROAD COURSES PROVIDE A DIFFERENT SET OF CHALLENGES 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICH RUPPRECHT   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.  
 
 2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SONOMA, Calif. _ Sure, Jeff Gordon is going to have to worry
about Mark Martin and Rusty Wallace on Sunday and Dale Earnhardt
will be wary of the Burton brothers and Ricky Rudd, but the real
battle figures to be each NASCAR driver against the Sears Point
course.
</P>
<P>
   Road races on the Winston Cup Series are polar opposites from
the usual oval track racing. There's plenty more to do than just
turn left. The cars must be set up differently, with weight needed
on both sides. The cars are even different. They aren't the cars
driven last week in Pocono. These are road race cars, NASCAR style.
Each team has one for Sears Point and Watkins Glen, the only two
road race courses on the Winston Cup circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Most NASCAR drivers won't say they hate the road race courses,
just that they offer different challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's kind of in the same boat,'' said Tony Stewart, who
has won two Winston Cup races this year and was running third at
Sears Point last year when a flat tire caused him to drop back in
the pack. ``We all only run two road course races a year.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, though, is that road cars are not the top
priority for NASCAR teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not something that we focus really hard on because
we do only have two races on the schedule that are road courses,''
Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon has won the last five road races _ two at Sears
Point and three at Watkins Glen _ which makes him the favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Racers who have watched Gordon at Sears Point describe him as
someone who doesn't always attack the course, but studies it early
on in the race. He seems to feel out the course, waits to make
moves and takes advantage of others' mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly much different than racing on the ovals,''
Gordon said. ``When you're on an oval track, you're in the corner
much longer, you've got to be thinking a lot more about what the
car is doing. You have to be thinking about the shocks and springs
and, `What can I do as a driver and how can I tell the team what
the car is doing?'
</P>
<P>
   ``On a road course, a lot of it is, you win a certain corner,
drive the car in pretty deep, and think, `I probably could have
gone in deeper, maybe I could have picked up on the throttle a
little later.'''
</P>
<P>
   Before Gordon came along, it was Rudd, Rusty Wallace and Terry
Labonte who built reputations as the top road course drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart is only a second-year NASCAR driver, but he showed
proficiency at Sears Point last year. Following Monday's race at
Pocono, Stewart headed to a road course in Virginia to prepare for
Sears Point.
</P>
<P>
   The keys to any road race course are knowing how to get into and
out of turns, when to shift gears _ most cars have four speeds, and
turns can be taken in either first or second gear _ and how to be
light on the brakes so the wheels don't lock up.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all the drivers have had road race schooling. Dale
Earnhardt Jr., a rookie on the circuit this season, visited Sears
Point in April along with a handful of NASCAR drivers and joined
drivers from the track's Russell Driving School.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, road course racing is more of a mental thing,'' said
Kyle Petty, who has a win at the other road course in Watkins Glen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to show these road courses some affection,'' Petty
said. ``You can't walk in there telling the place how much you hate
it and how much you wish you had a bulldozer to dig it up and how
that fifth-mile at Yancey Hollar Speedway in Wherever, Mississippi,
is a heck of a lot better deal than this. You have to get your mind
right and you have to have some fun with it.''
</P>
<P>
   John Andretti, who will race the STP No. 43 car for Richard
Petty, said road racing experience can be slightly overrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually we go to Sears Point or Watkins Glen and people start
looking for an Indy car background to decide who is a good road
course racer and who isn't,'' he said. ``If I was a car owner
running just one race, I'd go find me a good stock car driver
first, especially one who is pretty good on the short tracks, and
worry about his road course racing second.''
</P>
<P>
   Andretti concedes that experience on road courses is an
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you can take a good stock car driver and teach him to be a
pretty good road course racer,'' he said. ``You can't always take a
good road course racer and make him a good stock car driver.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 1812EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2984 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-R-CAR-NASCAR-IRVAN-NY     06-23 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CAR-NASCAR-IRVAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERNIE IRVAN IN THE SLOW LANE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating)  
 (ATTN: N.C., S.C., Fla., Calif., Mich.)   By HOWARD SENZELL   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SONOMA, Calif. _ Last year Ernie Irvan was one of 43 drivers in
the Save Mart/Kragen 350 at Sears Point. On Sunday he will be the
grand marshal for the parade lap, a spectator, a former Winston Cup
driver.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992 and '94 he took the checkered flag here. Irvan, Jeff
Gordon and Rusty Wallace are the only drivers to win Sears Point
twice. This year while Gordon and Wallace are racing, Irvan will be
in the pace car, a guest of Sears Point management.
</P>
<P>
   At 41, Irvan would seem to have good racing years left. But two
crashes, including one in which he was given a 10 percent chance to
survive, persuaded him to retire.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after his second accident, doctors told Irvan one more
head trauma would be fatal. The next day, Sept. 3, 1999, Irvan
announced his retirement at a tearful press conference in
Darlington, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I miss it?'' Irvan replied to the obvious question. ``You
bet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would I ever consider a comeback? No.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvan is at peace with his retirement and his choice to spend
time with his son, Jared, and daughter, Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a doctor tells you another blow to the head will be
fatal, it puts things in perspective,'' he said. ``I retired
because I knew it was time, not because I was forced out.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvan retired with 15 Winston Cup victories and earnings of more
than $11 million. Casual fans may know him best for the horrific
accident that nearly took his life on Aug. 20, 1994. In a practice
run for the GM Goodwrench Dealer 400 at Michigan Speedway, Irvan's
right front tire deflated, sending the car into the Turn 2 wall at
more than 170 mph.
</P>
<P>
   After emergency workers extricated him from the car, he was
diagnosed with critical brain and lung injuries. Doctors grimly
announced he had a 1-in-10 chance of surviving that first night.
</P>
<P>
   By early September, though, he was well enough to be removed
from ventilator support. A few months after that he walked on stage
at the NASCAR Awards Banquet in New York to receive the True Value
Hard Charger Award.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 16, 1995, NASCAR cleared Irvan for competition and two
weeks later he qualified on the outside pole for a race at North
Wilkesboro, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, in retrospect, that was the highlight of my career,''
Irvan said. ``After everything I went through, and because most
people said I couldn't come back, it felt great to be racing
again.''
</P>
<P>
   He wrote a storybook chapter to his career in 1997 when he
returned to Michigan International Raceway and won the Miller 400
after starting in 20th position. His driving career, however, ended
exactly five years later at the same raceway.
</P>
<P>
   As before, he crashed in a practice session and was airlifted
from the track. This time it was a milder head injury and bruised
lung, but the doctors said next time Irvan would not be so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   So, these days Irvan lives a more typical life. He drives his
daughter to school, picks up the dry cleaning and runs other
errands for his wife, Kim.
</P>
<P>
   Retirement, however, has not been smooth. The injuries have
taken a toll and then in March, fire destroyed Irvan's
10,000-square-foot home on his 160-acre farm in Mooresville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fire was a very traumatic thing and my family and I still
aren't over it,'' Irvan said. ``Our goal is to rebuild the house
like it was. We're trying to get back what we had.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvan says he's just ``80 percent'' of what he was before the
crashes. He can't focus like he could before the first crash and
his instincts aren't as sharp. He says he becomes flustered in
heavy traffic.
</P>
<P>
   His publicist, Roxanne Pauline, said Irvan's fan club has grown
to more than 3,000 since his retirement and his clothing line
continues to sell well. He has been hired to make appearances at
tracks such as Daytona, Charlotte, Pocono and now Sears Point. He
has taped a fishing show for Fox Sports Net and has been featured
in segments for ESPN 2's Outdoor Life show.
</P>
<P>
   Irvan set aside time this week to thank a special group of
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I owe my life to the doctors at the University of San
Francisco,'' Irvan said. ``This year, now that I'm retired, I'll
have a chance to spend time with them.''
</P>
<P>
   While recovering from his first accident, a brain aneurism was
detected. He was referred to surgeons in San Francisco. The
delicate surgery was a success, enabling Irvan to continue his
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at peace with what my life is now,'' Irvan said. ``I have
a lot to be thankful for and I lead a fairly normal life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
