<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2992 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-JAPAN-ELECTION-BOS &LR;      06-23 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ELECTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTERS IN JAPAN SEEM SATISFIED WITH THE STATUS QUO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHARON MOSHAVI GLOBE CORRESPONENT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHIBUKAWA, Japan _ Japan's economy is in a stupor, the prime
minister in the political dog house, and the young generation in a
hurry for change.
</P>
<P>
   In that kind of a climate, voters in most democratic countries
would ``throw the bums out'' to send a clear message to the ruling
party. But not, it seems, in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all polls leading up to Sunday's parliamentary
elections predict that the Liberal Democratic Party, which has
ruled Japan for 43 of the past 45 years, will hold on to power,
possibly even bolstering its majority in the Diet.
</P>
<P>
   It's baffling to many, but there does appear to be an answer:
political inertia.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling party ``has been occupying its position for so long,
they should just continue,'' says barber Hiroaki Suda, 50, echoing
the sentiment of many in this town, known as the ``bellybutton of
Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   Business may be lousy, his shop musty from disuse, but Suda is
in no hurry to elect new faces. ``No politicians can improve the
economy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Home to three prime ministers, including the late Keizo Obuchi,
Shibukawa and its environs are the country's political heartland.
Rural areas like this have for years provided the the ruling
party's core support, in return for the party's largesse and
subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Though Japan's poor economy has diluted the loyalty of voters
here and many are critical of the massive public spending that is
propping up the economy, most don't want change.
</P>
<P>
   In part, that's because economic conditions are much less
precarious than a few years ago. ``People don't want to lose their
jobs. They want stability, and stability means continuity,'' said
political analyst Shigenori Okazaki in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The lackluster opposition is also keeping many voters from
upsetting the status quo, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The half-dozen or so opposition parties, particularly Minshuto,
the Democratic Party of Japan, have a muddled message and provide
voters with an unappealing alternative, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Some parts of Minshuto's message are difficult for voters to
swallow. The party platform calls for a tax increase in an attempt
to reign in Japan's mounting debt, the highest of any
industrialized nation.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent campaign rally in Tokyo's Ginza district, Yukio
Hatoyama, the party leader, rattled off a list of campaign
proposals, pleading with voters to cast their ballots for any
opposition party at all. ``Don't give your vote to the party that
destroys democracy and freedom,'' Hatoyama urged.
</P>
<P>
   Toshiki Igihashi, a voter, was not impressed. He does not
support the ruling party, but he doesn't trust anyone else either.
``There's no other real party that has enough power to rule,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's newly installed prime minister, Yoshihiro Mori, has been
called a national embarrassment. He's made several verbal blunders
since he replaced Obuchi, who suffered a stroke in April and died a
month later. Most notably, he created a furor when he conjured up
images of the imperialistic past by calling Japan a ``divine nation
with the emperor as its core.''
</P>
<P>
   Just this week, he made another public gaffe when he said he
hoped undecided voters will stay away from the polls. ``It would be
great if they stay uninterested and stay asleep,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mori's approval ratings are hovering around 18 percent, a record
low. Yet the revolving door that is the prime minister's office _
seven have held the post while Bill Clinton was president _
suggests that what matters to people is the system, more than any
single politician.
</P>
<P>
   Family ties matter, too. A full one-third of the candidates for
parliament are relatives of former politicians. Many virtually
inherit their political organizations and their seats, usually from
their fathers.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point is Yuko Obuchi, a 26-year-old former TV producer
who is contesting the seat held by her late father, who, in turn,
at age of 26, inherited the seat from his father.
</P>
<P>
   At Yuko Obuchi's campaign office in Shibukawa, the first thing
that greets visitors is a picture of her father. The campaign is
being run mostly by older men _ politicians who were close to the
late prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   They say it makes sense to have the daughter take her father's
place, that it reassures the voters.
</P>
<P>
   Her qualifications? ``She's young and fresh and pure,'' said
Eiichi Nakamura, a local assembly member and one of Obuchi's
campaign managers. She'll grow into the job, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi has been spending the last few weeks campaigning through
the district. No one expects her to lose, but ``it would be really
rude to only depend on her name and not do anything,'' said another
campaign manager, Yoshihiro Okada.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's political dynasties don't rely on a cult of personality,
like the Gandhis in India or the Kennedys in the U.S. In Japanese
politics, family members are simply, by virtue of their name, in
the best position to take advantage of their relative's political
network, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   The LDP's strong showing in the polls astounds many veteran
political observers. ``It is an extraordinary situation that a
government that has done very poorly for a decade is able to
perhaps get a fresh mandate,'' said Roger Buckley, a professor of
history at the International Christian University in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, most Japanese, in the cities and the countryside, seem
to be so apathetic that few care who wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever wins, nothing will change,'' said Takiko Hagiwara, 81,
as she bought sweets from a Shibukawa shop.
</P>
<P>
   Shopkeeper Teruko Tosaka agreed. ``The whole system is corrupt,
she lamented, the whole campaign meaningless. What's important,''
she said, pointing at a basket of sweet bean cakes, ``is that
people used to buy 10 at a time. Because of the economy, most only
buy five.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she can't figure out why so many of her friends and
neighbors are willing to re-elect the government over and over.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mystery,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 1821EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
