<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0272 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3002 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-DRAFT-MIHM0624-CO     06-23 1749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-MIHM0624-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Frustrated Mihm feels the sting of pre-draft scrutiny
 &HT;    By Mark Rosner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Orlando Magic General Manager John Gabriel has
two words for those who would offhandedly dismiss Chris Mihm as
unfit to play center effectively in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Daugherty.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel considers Daugherty a cautionary tale for those taking
measure of NBA draft prospects. Daugherty, a college star at North
Carolina in the mid-1980s, was considered by some to lack the
toughness necessary to work near the basket as a pro. As NBA scouts
took measure of him, Daugherty was tattooed with the ``S'' word _
too soft. Based on that reputation, Philadelphia, which had the No.
1 pick in the 1986 draft, traded it to Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Daugherty became one of the better centers in
the NBA. He was a five-time all-star who averaged 19 points per
game before his career was cut short after eight seasons because of
a back injury.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel, voted the NBA's top executive this season, says, ``I
think you have to be careful when you label people soft. I was part
of that staff in Philadelphia. We could have drafted Daugherty, but
there were concerns that he was too soft.''
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Mihm, the former Texas Longhorn, for inspection,
trying to detatch the same tag Daugherty had.
</P>
<P>
   When NBA scouts and executives look at Mihm, they see the rare
7-foot center who can shoot, pass and block shots; a young man _ he
turns 21 in July _ who has developed deft post moves.
</P>
<P>
   But some scouts also see a lack of passion. Can he develop the
moxie necessary to survive against Shaquille O'Neal, Alzonzo
Mourning, David Robinson and Tim Duncan? If not, is Mihm talented
enough to succeed anyway?
</P>
<P>
   Mihm's agent, Jeff Austin, considers himself well-versed on the
subject, having represented Daugherty and Robinson, who couldn't
shed the soft label until the Spurs won the NBA championship last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard that for years about David,'' Austin said. ``It is
interesting, though, that you don't hear that about Tim Duncan, who
is placid and expressionless. I think Chris is very much like Tim
in demeanor.''
</P>
<P>
   THE COMPETITION
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the 2000 NBA draft is a referendum on Mihm. Three
teams with top-five picks in the draft are fairly desperate for a
center: No. 1 New Jersey, No. 4 Chicago and No. 5 Orlando.
Vancouver, which has the No. 2 pick and a center with a large
contract _ Bryant ``Big Country'' Reeves, is considering Mihm as a
power forward. How much these teams value Mihm will be revealed by
their selections Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Mihm, who left Texas after his junior season, is competing for
draft position with three power forwards: Kenyon Martin of
Cincinnati, Marcus Fizer of Iowa State and Stromile Swift of
Louisiana State, all viewed as aggressive players. Darius Miles, a
recent high school graduate who plays small forward, also is
considered a possible top-five pick. Nets President Rod Thorn said
Wednesday that he is considering all five players with the No. 1
pick. But according to most media speculation, New Jersey will
either choose Martin or trade the pick, and Mihm will be selected
by either Chicago or Orlando. Teams are also considering Joel
Przybilla, a center from Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Mihm auditioned for Chicago in early June. Afterward, one
Internet sports site, citing an unnamed witness to the private
workouts, said Mihm was badly outplayed by Jamal Magliore, a former
Kentucky center. But someone else who attended the workouts
disputed that report, saying Magliore repeatedly hacked Mihm
whenever he tried to shoot, much like opponents maul the Lakers'
O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Mihm appeared upset by the report during a press conference in
Chicago while attending the NBA pre-draft camp earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole idea is laughable. I couldn't have put up the
numbers I put up in college, averaging 18 points a game, if I was
soft,'' Mihm said. ``Teams came out to stop me night after night
with collapsing zone defenses and double- and triple-teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, Mihm was still defending himself when he was in
Orlando for a workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one person's opinion, and it just got blown up,'' Mihm
said Tuesday. ``Half the people who say these things have never
seen me play.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Austin, ``What was reported is preposterous. Fortunately,
the people making decisions don't listen to Internet
rumormongers.''
</P>
<P>
   The intense scrutiny seems to have become a burden.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough,'' Mihm said. ``I want to do well. . . . There is a
lot of pressure to perform.''
</P>
<P>
   QUALIFIED PRAISE
</P>
<P>
   The NBA men who evaluate talent are known for deception around
draft time. Many readily admit to that. But for what it's worth,
several have openly praised Mihm, albeit some temper their
enthusiasm with questions or instructions about his desire.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando reportedly would take Mihm if he is available at pick
No. 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a great body, he knows how to play, and he's
well-coached,'' said Magic director of player personnel Gary Brokaw
after Mihm worked out in Orlando Tuesday. ``It's rare to see a big
guy who shoots it as well as he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Mel Daniels, Indiana's director of player personnel who twice
was MVP of the old American Basketball Association while playing
center for the Pacers, is impressed by Mihm.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has all the tools. He's a 7-footer who is strong, can block
shots, can score, can run,'' Daniels said. ``He's a great athlete
with a major upside if he comes in willing to do the things he has
to do to become a great basketball player.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Dawson, Houston's executive vice president for
basketball, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come into the league, these guys will kick your
tail,'' Dawson said. ``Then we see how you adapt. Chris is blessed
_ wonderfully talented. He's got the ability to do everything. The
question is whether he wants it badly enough. He seems to want to
play in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte Hornets scout Kip Bass believes Mihm can develop the
necessary edge. But Bass said you can never be sure about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been kind of a docile guy in college, and the hardest
thing to do is to figure out how big a guy's heart is,'' Bass said.
``You can't do that for a few years. If you could answer that
question `yes' right now, if you knew that he'd have that spirit
and heart, he'd definitely be the No. 1 pick. Either way, I think
Mihm's going to be a good player. He's got too much talent and
brains. He's going to get a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   R.C. Buford, San Antonio's vice president and assistant general
manager, said it should not take long to determine how tough Mihm
is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a good chance we'll know a lot more about it
six months into the (first) season,'' Buford said.
</P>
<P>
   Buford cites Philadelphia center Matt Geiger as someone who
plays more aggressively than anticipated. Geiger, who arrived in
the NBA as a second-round pick without Mihm's skill, has developed
aggressiveness he didn't have in college.A LARGE VOID
</P>
<P>
   Generally, though, NBA scouts and executives have difficulty
comparing Mihm to anyone in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a believer in comparison evaluation, but I can't think of
one for Mihm,'' Gabriel said. ``I love him. But the best in our
business struggle to compare centers because there are none. Chris'
game is sort of unique. I like the fact that he comes into the
league at a time when centers need to step away (from the basket)
and shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   Perimeter shooting has become a handy skill for centers because
new NBA rules allow teams to play zone defenses on the side of the
court where the ball is located. Before the rules changed this
season, defenders could not double-team player until he received
the ball. Only O'Neal, an anomoly who is strong, quick and nimble
at 7-1, 345 pounds, regulary scores inside with two or three
defenders guarding him.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel is right about the lack of viable centers in the league.
Sacramento's Vlade Divac, rated the fifth-best center in the league
by Sports Illustrated before the 1999-2000 season, has averaged a
modest 12.4 points and 8.7 rebounds during his career.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1990, only 13 have been selected among the top 10 players
in the draft. Just four of those have been successful: O'Neal,
Mourning, Duncan (a part-time center) and Dikembe Mutombo. All were
among the top four players selected the year they were drafted, but
that designation does not ensure success. Shawn Bradley, the No. 2
pick in 1993, has been an albatross for three teams, most recently
Dallas. Michael Olowokandi, the No. 1 pick in 1998, has yet to show
the Clippers they made the right choice.
</P>
<P>
   The success rate among players drafted since 1990 as centers
with the sixth through 10th picks has been frighteningly poor. All
seven _ Erick Dampier, Adonal Foyle, Reeves, Eric Montross, Luc
Longley, Felton Spencer and Sharone Wright _ have struggled or
failed to establish careers.
</P>
<P>
   HELP WANTED
</P>
<P>
   At worst, Mihm should never have to worry about having to find
work. If the success rate at center is low, employment opportunity
is abundant. Every team needs players who can at least try to guard
the elite centers and grab a few rebounds. The NBA employs at least
a dozen players who have lasted more than 10 years as journeyman
centers, usually as reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Herb Williams retired from the New York Knicks this season after
18 years in the league, the last seven doing virtually nothing.
Charles Jones, formerly of Houston Rockets and four other teams,
lasted 15 seasons despite averaging 2.3 points and 4.5 rebounds.
Joe Kleine is still around, with Portland, after 15 seasons and
fewer than five points per game. When Will Perdue left the Spurs
this season, Spencer stepped in, albeit much less effectively.
</P>
<P>
   The job might be demeaning, but the pay is great. Even the least
effective backup centers make $1 million a year or more. Ten years
of NBA experience guarantees $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte's Bass doesn't think Mihm will have to live as a
journeyman.
</P>
<P>
   But Bass does suggest those judging the draft will need more
patience for Mihm than for Martin or Fizer, if for no other reason
than the position he plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be hard for Mihm at first,'' Bass said. ``One night he
will be playing against Shaq, one night against Robinson and
Duncan, one night Mourning. It's hard for a young guy to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
