u s BC-BKN-DRAFT-ROCKETS0624     06-23 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-ROCKETS0624-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Houston wants power forward but may have to trade up to get one
 &HT;    By Mark Rosner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Carroll Dawson, the Houston Rockets executive
vice president of basketball, figures the law of averages will
prevent him from making a blockbuster deal during this year's NBA
draft.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the Rockets stunned the league last year, acquiring
point guard Steve Francis, the second pick in the draft, in a trade
with Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   ``You only move up once every six or seven years,'' said Dawson,
whose team has the ninth pick this year. ``We moved up last year.''
</P>
<P>
   That will not stop the Rockets from trying. The Rockets, fairly
set in the backcourt with Francis, Cuttino Mobley and Shandon
Anderson, want to draft a power forward with some size. Last year
they drafted Kenny Thomas, a promising player but undersized at 6
feet 7 inches.
</P>
<P>
   To get what they want, the Rockets will have to make another big
trade and move up. The three most coveted power forwards _ Kenyon
Martin of Cincinnati, Marcus Fizer of Iowa State and Stromile Swift
of Louisiana State _ are expected to be taken within the first four
picks, perhaps the top three.
</P>
<P>
   Dawson said the Rockets are interested in Texas center Chris
Mihm, but that also would require moving up in the draft. Rockets
center Hakeem Olajuwon will retire when his contract expires after
next season. Kelvin Cato, who last season signed a six-year, $42
million contract to become Olajuwon's successor, has yet to
establish himself as a viable NBA center. Some with the Rockets
believe Cato could play power forward if the team had another
center.
</P>
<P>
   Pundits who prepare mock drafts have worked under the logical
assumption that the Rockets will not move up. They predict the
Rockets will take small forward Mike Miller of Florida or shooting
guard DerMarr Johnson of Cincinnati. Dawson said he understands the
rationale in those mock drafts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't find what you need, you go for the best player
available, which is probably a two (shooting guard) or three (small
forward),'' Dawson said.
</P>
<P>
   Drafting a small forward/big guard type like DerMarr Johnson
would provide the Rockets with insurance should they lose Mobley,
their second-leading scorer last season, to free agency.
</P>
<P>
   Under the NBA's labor agreement, the Rockets can retain Mobley
by matching offers from other teams for up to $3.8 million next
season. Only three teams _ Chicago, Orlando and the L.A. Clippers _
have room under the salary cap to pay him that much.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets are concerned that one of those teams might make
Mobley a substantial offer if they can not attract higher-level
players who are available: Tim Duncan, Grant Hill, Tracy McGrady,
Eddie Jones and Jalen Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Should the Rockets decide to take a second-tier power forward,
they can probably choose from UCLA's Jerome Moiso, Syracuse's Etan
Thomas or Olumide Oyedeji, a 19-year-old Nigerian who played
professionally in Germany last season.
</P>
<P>
   Moiso is a rare player who is taller than listed. UCLA lists him
at 6-10, but he measured 7 feet during the NBA pre-draft camp in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
