<SLUG> BC-MA-IPOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO IPOS GO SMOOTHLY: THEY'RE PROFITABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANTHONY FLINT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Two Massachusetts companies with qualities once rare in
IPOs _ products and profits _ made modest debuts in their first day
of trading Friday, helping breath new life into the flagging market
for new stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Charles River Laboratories of Wilmington and Manufacturers'
Services Ltd. of Concord both closed more than 30 percent over
their offering prices of $16 a share in their debut on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the successful IPOs are typical for the current,
more cautious environment. After several companies trading on
Nasdaq bombed recently with their IPOs, a proven track record and
solid financials have become critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors have definitely become more selective about the
companies they are picking, and main criteria is profitability and
positive cash flow,'' said Omar Sacirbey, senior editor at IPO
Reporter, a Thomson Financial publication.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure I would say it's a return to fundamentals but
there is some nostalgia for a return to the old days,'' said
Randall Roth, research analyst at Renaissance Capital in Greenwich,
Conn., which does research on IPOs and runs an IPO fund.
</P>
<P>
   Charles River Laboratories, formerly a unit of Bausch &AMP; Lomb,
produces labatory animals that are carefully bred with diseases for
research use by pharmaceutical and biotech companies. Its shares
closed at $22, a 37 percent jump.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which operates 53 facilities in more than 50
countries, has been profitable since 1997. For the first three
months of this fiscal year, it reported $76.7 million in revenue
for net income of $4.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the company said no executives would be
commenting on the IPO Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers' Services Ltd., meanwhile, provides manufacturing
on a contractual basis for companies including Palm Pilot, IBM and
Hewlett-Packard, having bought up factories worldwide. Its shares
closed at $21.25, a 30 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very happy we were able to go public today and it
appears to be well received,'' said John MacInnes, vice president
and treasurer for Manufacturers' Services.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers' Services Ltd. has also been profitable, reporting
$207 million in revenue in the first quarter of last year for net
income of $103,000, although for the first quarter of this year the
company finished in the red $12.9 million on revenue of $332
million.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best features of the company's business is a two-year
contract to produce Palm Pilot hand-held computer devices. The
company started out with a solid business model of offering a kind
of ``rent-a-factory'' service, which is attractive for businesses
that prefer to contract out the actual production of goods rather
than operate manufacturing facilities themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The lead underwriter for both deals was Donaldson Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette Inc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
