<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spurs may trade into first round
 &HT;    By Mark Rosner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The San Antonio Spurs do not have a first-round
draft pick, a condition they might try to remedy.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs would have selected 24th in the draft Wednesday if
they had not traded their pick to Chicago for guard Steve Kerr in
January 1998.
</P>
<P>
   If they try to move back into the first round, perhaps with a
pick in the early 20s, the Spurs can offer the two second-round
picks they hold, Nos. 41 and 54 overall. The 41st pick was acquired
in a trade with Dallas last year. No. 54 is the Spurs' own
second-round slot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've thought about trying to move up,'' said Sam Schuler, the
Spurs' vice president for basketball operations. ``It's not a great
draft at the top, but with all the foreign players and
underclassmen, it's a deep draft.''
</P>
<P>
   Why would a team trade out of the first round? Primarily for
salary-cap reasons. NBA teams are required to give three-year
guaranteed contracts to their first-round picks, regardless of
whether the players earn a spot on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs need look no further than their own draft history to
find an example of such trades. In 1999, holding the last pick in
the first round _ No. 29 _ the Spurs set up a trade with Dallas.
San Antonio picked Leon Smith, the troubled high school player from
Chicago, and sent him to Dallas for two second-round picks. By
trading their first-rounder, the Spurs avoided increased salary-cap
problems _ they are already over the cap _ that would have been
induced by drafting a player they did not think could even earn a
spot on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   This year is different, though. With seven players on the team
who become free agents on July 1, the Spurs could use some help,
either perimeter players or a backup center.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a couple of teams we've talked to who might be
willing to make the trade,'' Schuleer said. ``But it's probably a
draft-day decision when we see who's still available. You arrange
it and then see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
