<P>
   LEVI-STRAUSS (San Francisco) _ With sales falling and profits
scarce, Robert Haas, the beleaguered chairman of Levi Strauss &AMP;
Co., struggles to preserve Levi Strauss as a clothing maker with a
conscience. Levi's announced results last week suggest only that
the company has slowed its decline. It therefore remains unclear
whether the company can endure with its legacy of social
responsibility intact. By Karl Schoenberger.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-MUSIC (Undated) _ Why do business giants and would be giants
like Vivendi and AOL want to be in a business _ music _ that seems
to be imploding under the threat of new technology? Because it
isn't imploding; in fact, it's having its best sales year ever. And
besides, it's these companies, and not the mp3.com's of the world,
that have the power to manufacture popular culture. By Alex
Berenson and Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-WATCH (Undated) _ Weekly Wall Street commentary. By
Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INVESTING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-HEDGE-FUNDS (Undated) _ You might think that hedge funds,
those unregulated investment pools that are reserved for the rich
and powerful, had fallen out of favor after two of the most famous
managers, George Soros of the Quantum Fund and Julian Robertson of
Tiger Management, threw in their monogrammed towels. If so, you may
not be cut out to be a ``hedgie.'' By Patrick MacGregor.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-INSURERS (Undated) _ While technology stocks have been
careening wildly, some ugly ducklings seem to be in the process of
transforming themselves into market darlings: The companies that
sell insurance on cars, houses and businesses. Suddenly, Property
and Casualty insurers look like bargains. By Joseph B. Treaster.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-SOFTWARE (Undated) _ The over-the-counter bulletin board
is a hazardous place for investors, where blasts of hot air about
obscure stocks and their supposedly dazzling prospects propel
shares into the stratosphere. Alas, these fliers usually fizzle
out. One of the latest balloonists is Save the World Air, a company
based in Australia that says it has the ``world rights to market
and manufacture the zero pollution-fuel saving device.'' By
Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds, budgeted earlier as INVEST-WILD-IDEAS.)
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-INSIGHT-EUROPE (Undated) _ It sounds a little weird, but
the Old World is a work in progress. Europe is in the throes of
change, and investors there are only beginning to benefit from the
Eurocentric capital markets system that is being built. Michael
Levy, head of international equities at Deutsche Asset Management
and manager of the Deutsche European Equity fund, talks about
Europe's economic future. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INSIDE FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-FUTURE (Redmond, Wash.) _ ``We are on the brink of a
new computing revolution.'' ``As big a transition as from DOS to
Windows.'' ``Microsoft's Net Bet is Boldest Yet.''Lest anyone
possibly miss the point at the Microsoft Corp.'s big media event
last week, the captions in the slide show and demonstrations were
all designed to convey the notion that the company's strategy for
the future would be, in the words of another Internet company's
ubiquitous ads, ``big _ really big.'' By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   RETIRE-PROPOSALS (Undated) _ Few issues point up the ideological
gulf between the likely major-party presidential candidates more
clearly than their very different approaches to inducing Americans
to save more money for retirement. Vice President Gore proposes
that the government provide a subsidy of as much as $3 for every $1
that you kick in to your retirement kitty, a new entitlement
program designed to favor the relative have-nots. George W. Bush
will probably endorse a plan under which the kitty will be fattened
with taxes that currently helps finance Social Security. What is
remarkable, however, is what the two sides now have in common: a
recognition that the electorate wants the long-term adequacy of
Social Security to be debated instead of avoided. By Robert D.
Hershey.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   PROFILE-JACOBS-CONSECO (Minneapolis) _ What does Irwin Jacobs,
corporate raider turned impresario of competitive bass fishing, see
in Conseco? By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   TIFFANY-RING (Undated) _ Profile of Linda Hanson, who came up
with the idea for the new Tiffany engagement ring. By Kruti
Trivedi.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-LEWINSKY (Undated) _ Monica, the business person, is selling
a new line of handbags at places like Bendel and asking to be seen
in a new light. By Abby Ellin.
</P>
<P>
   FIVE-QUESTIONS (Vienna) _ (Undated) _ Dressed modestly in his
native collarless garb, occasionally fingering a strand of prayer
beads, Bijan Namdar Zanganeh, Iran's petroleum minister, led a
contingent of similarly reserved, gray-bearded men who together
played the role of wild card last week during the meeting of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries here. By Neela
Banerjee.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-BOOKS (Undated) _ Why can't companies get off the dime?
Jeffrey Pfeffer and Robert Sutton have studied the ways of business
for decades, and they come away puzzled as to why so many companies
fail to act on what they know. In their pragmatic book, ``The
Knowing-Doing Gap'' (Harvard Business School Press, 2000) Pfeffer
and Sutton offer the voice of experience about companies that know
what to do but just can't. By Fred Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   With:
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-BOOKS-INTERVIEW (Undated) _ Jeffrey Pfeffer, co-author of
``The Knowing-Doing Gap,'' teaches at Stanford University, in the
heart of Silicon Valley. In an interview, he described how Internet
companies in particular could learn to put their best ideas into
practice. By Fred Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-ENTERPRISE (San Francisco) _ Enterprise Application
Integration software firms are the opposite of the Blue Chip
Technology companies that investors have been buying since the
spring selloff. They are extraordinarily volatile, have scant track
records and no earnings. But companies like Vignette, Vitria,
Webmethods, Tibco and Crossworlds also have the high octane growth
that can justify their valuations. And they are selling for less
than half their highs. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   ONTHEJOB-MESSAGES (Undated) _ On the Job: Misdirected messages.
By Lawrence Van Gelder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ECON-COLUMN (Undated) _ The United States seems to have tired of
using the fruits of American labor as a weapon in global politics.
In the span of a month, Congress eliminated China's annual trade
review and President Clinton eased economic sanctions against North
Korea. The State Department even dropped the term ``rogue state''
from its diplomatic lexicon: Libya, Iraq and Syria are now simply
``states of concern.'' Could the 38-year embargo on trade with Cuba
be next? By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   MIDSTREAM-COLUMN (Undated) _ As baby boomers, we are getting a
reputation. We take heat for our questionable cell-phone habits,
the big trucks we drive and our overall obsession with money. Now
investment advisers are shaking their heads over how we invest. We
are, they say, incredibly risk-prone and oblivious to the lessons
of history. We know that, of course, and it seems that many of us
don't care. But not all of us. By James Schembari.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AUTOS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT-CARS-SPYDER (Undated) _ Reviewing the Toyota MR2 Spyder.
By Dan Neil.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-SMART-TALKING (Milford, Mich.) _ Sometimes, cars say the
darndest things. Humorous look at one driver's bad experience with
a talking GM concept car. By Cheryl Jensen.
</P>
