A3015 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-PLANE-CRASH0624-COX     06-23 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANE-CRASH0624-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No survivors in airplane collision
 &HT;    By Marc Caputo
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla._ A stunt airplane and a Lear jet collided in
mid-air Friday, killing all four people aboard as burning wreckage
crashed into a gated golf-course community.
</P>
<P>
   No one on the ground was injured when the debris rained down on
a one-square-mile area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw two balls of fire coming down,'' said Ivory McCall, a
43-year-old construction worker who watched the Lear take off and
explode moments later.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I could see was fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Lear jet pilot Richard Smith, co-pilot Kevin Reyer and observer
Brad Moncrief left Boca Raton Executive Airport about 11:40 am.
They headed west and planned to bank north in order to go to St.
Lucie County International Airport, where the new model Lear 55 was
to be repainted.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes before their takeoff, stunt pilot John Lillberg
apparently departed from Pompano Beach in a one-seat Extra 300
stunt plane.
</P>
<P>
   About 11:44, the two planes collided over the 17th hole of the
Boca Grove Plantation golf course. Pieces of the Lear rained down
near the 17th tee, not far from a startled foursome finishing their
round.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 40, of Boca Raton, was a father of three boys ages 3, 6
and 8. His family had been planning a move to another house in a
new neighborhood and their old house was full of boxes, ready for
the movers. Moncrief, 29, and Reyer, 35, were single and lived in
Fort Lauderdale.
</P>
<P>
   Lillberg, 57, was a father of two girls, an adult and an
11-year-old. He gave flying lessons in Pompano and commuted to his
suburban Boynton Beach home by plane, friends said.
</P>
<P>
   The mangled body of one of the pilots _ officials suspected
Lillberg _ was found wrapped in what looked like a red-and-white
parachute.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a pretty sight,'' said 18-year-old Anthony
Mannarino, whose house the body landed near. Mannarino said he
wasn't awakened by the loud collision, but by the screams of his
house keeper as the debris fell down.
</P>
<P>
   James Kazek won't ever forget the sound and site of the crash,
which happened just above him as he drove down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw two huge red balls of flame floating down to earth,''
Kazek, 56, said. ``It was an unbelievable site to see.''
</P>
<P>
   An engine from the Lear jet landed within 25 feet of a
three-story condominium and at least one building was damaged by
the ensuing fire. Smaller debris pelted roofs and yards.
</P>
<P>
   Rod Sirmeyer, a pool cleaner who was in the complex, said he
heard the Lear crash. He ran to the plane's cockpit and tried to
put out the fire with water from a garden hose while some
condominium maintenance workers sprayed it with a fire
extinguisher. Small explosions continued for several minutes, he
said. It was obvious, he said, that everyone aboard had perished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt really sad for the people's families,'' Sirmeyer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
