<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3057 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-BARAK-BOS &LR;      06-23 0367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-BARAK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK TAKES A LESSER EVIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak's last-minute, coalition-saving
agreement Thursday with the Sephardic religious party Shas reflects
his determination to keep as the primary aim of his government the
pursuit of peace.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Barak's capitulation to the parochial demands of
Shas was hardly propitious. The deal means that Barak was forced to
side with sectarians against secularists in a fundamental dispute
that divides Israeli society.
</P>
<P>
   Barak gave in to Shas for the sake of the peace process. He kept
Shas in the government for a price that includes $6 million in
fresh funds for the party's indebted schools. Shas was also able to
escape oversight of the way it spends money on its school network.
Until Thursday's deal, that oversight had been exercised by a
secular minister of education, Meretz leader Yossi Sarid, who was
one of three ministers from his party to resign from the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   The enmity between Sarid and leaders of Shas had become personal
as well as political. The secular, progressive Sarid had been
successfully distributing government funds to public schools in a
manner that made those schools more attractive to Israeli parents
who had enrolled their children in heretofore cheaper Shas schools.
Consequently, there had recently been a significant shift of
students from Shas schools to secular public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Shas leaders now may crow that they were able to get rid of an
implacable foe. The dovish Meretz Party could not stay in the
government after such a blatant surrender to Shas on the very
principle that defines Meretz's reason for being. Meretz leaders
saved face by saying they bowed out of government to preserve the
possibility of making peace.
</P>
<P>
   The political logic that led Barak to this choosing of a lesser
evil was that Meretz, even though outside the Cabinet, will still
support a reasonable peace accord with the Palestinians. So, in
theory at least, Barak should still be able to call on a large
coalition for peace. In reality, he has learned that Shas is hardly
a partner he can count on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
