<P>
   GUNS-INTERNET _ WASHINGTON _ Gun control advocates, long
concerned about a ``gun show loophole'' they say makes obtaining
weapons too easy, have a new worry. The ``Internet loophole,'' they
say, lets anyone with a credit card buy guns without a background
check. (Moscoso, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving Friday on the NYT wire in (w) Washington category
</P>
<P>
   HONDATOWN _ Lincoln, Ala. _ More than a year ago, Lincoln Cafe
owner Sharon Denson posted a message of hospitality on her marquee
outside. She proudly welcomed Honda to the city of 3,500, where the
car manufacturer plans to make the hot-selling Odyssey minivan in
2003. Today, however, there's mixed emotions about Honda. A
two-lane country road must be widened to five lanes to accommodate
traffic to the plant. Businesses are being bought out for cheap.
Dump trucks roar on the road. (Manuel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 45. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-DIVERSITY-0625 _ Has been RESKEDDED to Sunday, July 16.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-POLL _ Most Texas voters think Gov. George W. Bush has
done a good job in office. They're just not sure why. Despite
overwhelming approval ratings, sixty-three percent of registered
voters in the state _ including 56 percent who support Bush's
campaign for president _ can't name a reform the governor has made,
according to The Scripps Howard Texas Poll released today. (Austin
American-Statesman). 20.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 9
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-REFUGEES _ LONDON _ The fact has been known for some
time, but this week's tragic incident involving the 58 Chinese
refugees whose bodies were found in a truck at the English port of
Dover highlights a growing problem for Europe: illegal immigrants
risking their lives to come to wealthier western nations for a
better life. This increasing number of refugees from Asia and
Africa is starting to get a cold reception from many here, as they
raise concerns about demands and changes to European society.
Developing. (Roughton,. Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Fri., June 23, on NYT Wire.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-ANNIVERSARY _ SEOUL, South Korea _ Fifty years after North
Korea invaded the South, triggering a war that left nearly 37,000
American soldiers dead, the border dividing the Korean Penninsula
into Communist North and Capitalist South remains the world's last
Cold War fault line, a place where U.S., South Korean and North
Korean troops face off across the most heavily militarized border
anywhere in the world. For protecting South Korea for the past five
decades, the United States has secured a strategic toehold in
Northeast Asia, at the doorstep of China and Russia, and has built
an enduring alliance with South Korea, host of the 1988 Summer
Olympic Games and home to one of the world's strongest economies.
Now, North and South Korea stand at the brink of a historic detente
that could usher in the reunification of the divided Penninsula,
shifting, yet again, the geostrategic stakes for the United States.
The costs and the benefits of half a century of U.S. involvement in
Korea, pegged to 50th Anniversary, on June 25, of the outbreak of
the Korean War. (Chao/Deans, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet Focus page for the week.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thursday, June 22, on NYT Wire.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PRISONERS _ MITROVICA, Kosovo _ There are reportedly more
than 1,500 Kosovar Albanians still held in Serb prisons without
being charged. Many of them were rounded up by Serb paramilitaries
during last spring's ethnic cleansing campaign. Serbs call them
prisoners of war, but their wives and mothers call them hostages.
The United Nations can do little to secure their release ? another
criticism people have about the U.N. It's a very politically touchy
subject. The cease-fire accords left out any mention of prisoner
releases, for a number of reasons. But now, families are left with
no recourse except to pay bribes and ransoms to get their relatives
out of jail, paying anywhere from $4,000 to $10,000. We tag along
and bear witness to one of these exchanges at the Kosovo-Serbia
border to tell the story of these families being reunited. (Coker,
Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thursday, June 22, on the NYT Wire.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-FOX _ MEXICO CITY _ Spot coverage of the major closing
campaign rally here for opposition candidate, and top challenger in
the Mexican presidential election Vicente Fox. Developing.
(Ferriss, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-PRI _ MEXICO CITY _ The presidential election on July 2
has political observers and experts asking a rather unusual
question: What if the Instituational Revolutionary Party, the PRI,
doesn't retain presidential power after 71 years? If opposition
candidate Vicente Fox is able to topple PRI candidate Francisco
Labastida Ochoa, what happens to seven-decades of social
infrastructure? Is there a worst-case scenario? Mexico's
government-controlled unions used to bring out massive numbers of
voters for the PRI. They've declined in strength as Mexico has
become less centralized and authoritarian, so can they still churn
out enough voters to help the PRI's candidate win? This population
is a critical part of the PRI political machine. (Ferriss, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   US-MEXICO _ WASHINGTON _ What's the U.S. view of the Mexican
election, and is there a lot at stake? Would a Fox win change trade
relations at all? What about the war on drugs? The likely answer is
very little change at all. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
