<HEADER>
A3080 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-NETSALES-BO     06-23 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-NETSALES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAX UPHEAVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, June 26, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The debate over whether to charge a sales tax on e-commerce
purchases has brought into high relief the essential unfairness of
the sales tax _ a patchwork of confusing and regressive levies that
vary from state to state. Some states exempt food or clothing from
the sales tax, while others do not, and still others try to make a
distinction between necessities and luxury items. In New York State
until very recently, marshmallow bits were not taxed because they
were considered a cooking item, but full-size marshmallows were
taxed because they were categorized as candy.
</P>
<P>
   The e-commerce debate, which has many governors who depend on
sales taxes from old-fashioned purchases in a dither because of the
potential lost revenue, has provoked second thoughts over the
wisdom of any sales taxes at the state level. While major changes
in state tax structures are hard to achieve, the question raises
important issues.
</P>
<P>
   Murray Weidenbaum, briefly Ronald Reagan's chairman of the
Council of Economic Advisers and long a fixture among academic
economists, has expanded the debate significantly with his
recommendation that both federal and state taxes be revamped by
exempting any investment from current taxation while making up the
lost revenue in higher income taxes. In a paper published by the
Center for the Study of American Business this month, he argues
that such a system would in effect be a tax on consumption without
the flaws of the sales tax. The advantage, he contends, is that it
would encourage savings and investment, which lag dangerously in
America.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts is fortunate among states for having a fairly
progressive sales tax structure _ exempting food, most clothing,
and other necessities. It is, as a consequence, less burdensome on
people with lower incomes and raises only about a fifth of total
state revenue. Instead, the state depends more heavily on the
income tax, usually a more equitable device.
</P>
<P>
   Other states on average get about a third of total revenue by
taxing a wider range of goods at heavier rates. Many of them apply
the tax to food and all clothing, which makes the tax highly
regressive _ weighing proportionally more heavily on low-income
households.
</P>
<P>
   This disparity among states' application of the tax, plus the
different tax rates from state to state, have also advanced the
argument against taxing e-commerce sales, since it would require
extensive cataloguing of each state's practices for applying the
tax and might generate a constitutional argument about whether
companies operating in non-sales tax states like New Hampshire
could be required to collect the tax.
</P>
<P>
   Weidenbaum's proposal would do away with all those issues, an
attractive feature. But his proposal is flawed by visiting its
benefit, deductibility of investments, primarily on higher-income
taxpayers since they do the bulk of investing. And it would replace
one complex set of rules, those governing the sales tax, with
another that would distinguish genuine investment from the
pass-through of funds through checking accounts or similar
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The sad political fact is that many Americans appear to prefer
sales taxes to income taxes, misperceiving them as the lesser of
two evils. The likelihood of getting 50 legislatures to embrace
such a change, plus Congress, is of a very low order. Weidenbaum
nevertheless has performed a useful political service by pointing
out the flaws of the sales tax _ flaws that electronic commerce can
only enlarge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
