(888) 346-9867; e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in the ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BANGLADESH-ACID (Gosarigaon, Bangladesh) _ More than 100
Bangladeshi women a year are victims of attacks by men, usually
spurned suitors, who throw acid in their faces. No one is sure why
this crime occurs here at such a high pace, for this nation on the
Indian subcontinent is not so different from many others in its
poverty or its culture or its treatment of women. And in a
male-dominated society, the victims rarely find justice. By Barry
Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT17,18,19, sent 6/21; and a map.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Mexico City) _ Several new polls show Mexico's
two leading presidential candidates in a dead heat about 10 days
before the balloting, with as many as a quarter of the voters still
undecided. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-MEDIA (Moscow) _ Vladimir Gusinsky, the media tycoon
whose arrest last week raised fears of a press crackdown, refused
to answer prosecutors' questions on Friday. The prosecutors say
Gusinsky helped defraud the government. He called the charges
nonsense. As he did so, President Vladimir Putin gathered his
security advisers in the Kremlin to draft a national ``information
doctrine,'' one that Putin said would be rooted in total press
freedom and the absence of state censorship. By Michael Wines. (725
words)
</P>
<P>
   (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in the ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLEAN-AIR-RULES (Washington) _ A federal appeals court in
Washington upholds anti-pollution rules covering 19 Midwestern and
Eastern states, lifting a stay on enforcement of standards set down
by the Environmental Protection Agency in 1998. This means the
states must see to it that coal-fired power plants run cleaner or
face sanctions. An appeal to the Supreme Court likely, but
environmentalists are elated. By David Stout. (800 words)
</P>
</TEXT>
