</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOING-TO-THE-DOGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAKFAST AT THE REGENCY? ARF COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - Toto II, a white Bichon poodle wearing dark
sunglasses, sat nestled in her owner's lap while a waiter in white
gloves and tuxedo served her a bowl of scrambled eggs, rice, and
grated cheese _ The Great Dane Special, the menu called it _ with
Evian water and a biscuit on the side.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is her first breakfast at the Regency,'' the dog's owner,
Donna McDonald, said, explaining the shades. ``I wanted her to look
like a celebrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday was Take Your Dog to Work Day _ and the first day of a
new policy by the Loews hotel chain that not merely allows but
encourages its guests to bring their pets along, supplying dog
beds, bones, toys, dog-walking and -sitting services, and a doggie
room-service menu.
</P>
<P>
   The Regency Hotel is Loews' Manhattan flagship and it celebrated
the occasion by holding a swank breakfast for all dogs whose
masters were willing to pay $30 a pop (proceeds of which went to
animal charities).
</P>
<P>
   ``The Regency is the home of the Power Breakfast,'' Jonathan
Tisch, the president of Loews, proclaimed. ``This is the Power
Breakfast for dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   From 7 to 10 am, 65 dogs and their owners rambled through its
Park Avenue portals. There was Edie Falco of ``The Sopranos,'' with
her mixed yellow lab-white shepherd, Marley; Ishbel MacIntosh of
the Discovery Channel's ``Epicurious'' with her shorthair,
Velvetine; Joseph Montebello, creative director of Harper Collins
publishers, with his two West Highland terriers, Porsche and Emma.
</P>
<P>
   All around, there were golden retrievers, miniature schnauzers,
Wheaton terriers, Brittanys, Keeshond Eskimos, Shi-Tzus, Canaans _
a very Upper East Side crowd _ rolling, noshing, slurping, and
sniffing as if they owned the place.
</P>
<P>
   Similar events took place in other cities. Take Your Dog to Work
Day is an attempt at a national holiday, the brainchild of
Pets.com, a pet supply web site. ``Bark breakfasts'' were held in
all 15 of the Loews hotels around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the affair in New York had its own distinct air, as does
this city's canine culture generally.
</P>
<P>
   Three things contribute to a strange environment for dogs, at
least in the borough of Manhattan: (1) the presence of many rich
and busy people most of whom (2) live in relatively cramped
apartments and (3) have _ except for those who live near Central
Park, where dogs can frolic off-leash before 9 a.m. and after
sundown _ no place to walk their dogs but concrete sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   As if to compensate for these burdens, New Yorkers tend to
splurge on their canines where they can.
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan Yellow Pages lists 23 day-care camps for dogs,
some of them as posh in their own ways as camps for human kids. The
Sutton Dog Parlour, just a few blocks east of the Regency, offers
outdoor sandboxes, playhouses, swimming pools, even a little park
with a (much-used) fire hydrant, as well as indoor games when the
weather gets bad, all for $20 to $25 a day, depending on the dog's
size.
</P>
<P>
   For about the same price, Paws Inn, in Chelsea, also has a
fenced-in roof and rooms full of couches where dogs can sit around
a television that plays ``Lassie'' tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Other such places include Canine Country, Run Spot Inc.,
Doggie-Do, and Yuppie Puppy. At each, between 20 and 40 dogs are
dropped off nearly every weekday morning, and picked up every
night.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Cerbi, owner of Camp Canine, on the Upper West Side, said
most of his customers are single or childless couples. ``It's a
godsend for these people,'' he said. ``Otherwise, their dogs would
sit home, chewing on the furniture and going nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Department of Health counts 107,753 registered dogs
in the city _ 25,714 in Manhattan alone, or about one dog for every
30 households. But officials privately estimate the unlicensed dogs
would double or triple that number.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Kaplan, author of ``The New York Dog Owners' Guide,''
figures the number is growing. ``There's an increase of
dog-ownership with an increase of affluence,'' she said. ``I see a
lot more dogs than I did five years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   In a crowded city where dogs and people constantly rub up
against one another, Kaplan theorizes that the city's dogs fill a
unique social function. ``The reason to have a dog in New York City
_ assuming you like dogs _ is they are an absolutely fantastic way
to socialize,'' she said. ``When you first move to New York, it can
be a lonely place. Walking a dog in the park or down the street,
you end up talking with other dogowners, you get to know when
they're out walking their dogs. It makes New York more like a
little village, it brings the city down to a human scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Pets.com has tried to sell corporations on Take Your Dog to Work
Day with precisely this argument _ that what's good for Fido is
good for business. Its brochures cite a study by the American Pet
Products Manufacturers Association, concluding that dogs in the
office reduce employees' stress level, blood pressure, absentee
rate _ and increase the amount of work that gets done.
</P>
<P>
   The sell seems to be working. ``We received 3,000 e-mails from
companies interested in officially recognizing the day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
