<HEADER>
A3100 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-WEB-TUNES-LADN &LR;      06-23 1628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-TUNES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELF-MADE RECORD MOGULS ON THE WEB
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's an old story: boy meets record label; boy signs deal with
record label; boy's albums, on first or second or 28th try, don't
sell as well as record label likes; boy loses deal, record label
and any residual goodwill toward music business in one conjoined
swoop.
</P>
<P>
   This story (substitute ``boy'' freely with ``sensitive girl
singer/songwriter,'' ``eardrum-busting metal band,'' ``gangsta rap
collective,'' etc.) is repeated so often in the music business that
it's a wonder anyone is left in the music business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The record industry traditionally is not geared toward legacy
artists, people who get older but still have an audience,'' said
Todd Rundgren, a long-time musician and producer. ``Every artist in
my situation ends up this way after 25 years: a household name who
just barely gets a deal on (eclectic independent label) Rykodisc.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Rundgren can take credit for five Top 40 hits and many
music-technology firsts, he released his newest album this month
without a major-label deal he could stomach. And he's hardly alone,
said Ric Dube, an analyst for Webnoize, a Cambridge, Mass.,-based
consultant on music and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rundgren's situation is a good (example); there are a lot of
artists of his sort, who have a few hundred fans in every city,''
said Dube.
</P>
<P>
   That sort of fan base won't keep a big record label happy, and
in fact, the Big Four have jettisoned huge numbers of such artists
from their rosters in recent years as the industry has
consolidated.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to the Web, those veterans are finding they can make
a decent to good living without relying on often-indifferent big
record labels and mainstream radio stations, both of which are
focused on a relative handful of big-selling hitmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Rundgren, in his typical DIY fashion, created a whole new way
for his fans to support his work with Patronet, a Web service where
fans pay $40 a year to help support his work.
</P>
<P>
   In return, they get ``MIDI files (a standard file format for
electronic music), chat forums, Video On Demand, things I write and
screen, regular mailings, events that only subscribers participate
in,'' Rundgren said. ``They get a whole variety of things to
experience and download.''
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, said Patronet President Stuart Shapiro, fans become
``mini-Medicis,'' sponsoring their favorite artist's ongoing work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our service is for the devoted fans in our fan base,'' Shapiro
said. ``It's a private club.''
</P>
<P>
   Rundgren just sold Patronet to Artistent so he could concentrate
on making music, while allowing the company to work with other
veteran artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a hundred artists that this applies to right now,''
Shapiro said. ``They have a devoted fan base, probably don't have a
contract, sell 25,000 to 100,000 albums, but they have no value to
the conglomerates. They still tour, they still write music, they
still have fans. What do they do?''
</P>
<P>
   For country music veteran Charlie Daniels, using the Web wasn't
a choice three years ago. Frustrated with label executives who
didn't know his band's work, he went his own way, setting up
www.charliedaniels.com and Blue Hat Records.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Hat just released his latest, ``Road Dogs,'' a throwback to
his 1970s music created without the big-label meddling that drove
him nuts the last few years there.
</P>
<P>
   And on Daniels' Web site, fans can buy his Blue Hat records and
merchandise like hats and T-shirts, check tour information, hear
bits of his music and read a weekly column by Daniels that covers
everything from politics to ``what a beautiful spring day it is.''
</P>
<P>
   In effect, what Rundgren, Daniels and others are doing is using
the Web to create supercharged versions of the old fan club, though
the Web allows far more to be done, far more personally and far
more cheaply, said Rich Holtzman, vice president of marketing for
the Web-oriented label Atomic Pop (at www.atomicpop.com).
</P>
<P>
   ``If the artist is comfortable with opening up others to their
creative process, you can create a wonderful place for fan to come
visit,'' said Holtzman. ``It's really an advantage for the artist
because now they can be closer and more personal with their fans
than ever before but with less investment of time. You can go
directly to those consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Atomic Pop's best known artist is Chuck D, the fiery rap
producer and leader of Public Enemy, whose most recent album has
sold more than 100,000 copies. Unlike a bigger record company,
Holtzman said, Atomic Pop is still pushing the record a year after
it was released, something his company can easily and cheaply do
through the Web.
</P>
<P>
   And Chuck D has used Atomic Pop's resources in novel ways to
connect with his fans, recently setting up a weekly Internet show
called ``Bring the Noise'' (at www.btn.com) that features his and
other people's music, guest interviews and more.
</P>
<P>
   It's not always easy selling records on the Web, because big
labels and big radio stations still command the kind of marketing
muscle and audience reach that translates into big sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest thing is getting your music to people through
radio because (the stations) are so strictly formatted and
consulted,'' said Daniels. ``The thing for people like Todd and us
and the Marshall Tucker Band, we're still playing dates to
thousands of people. But we can't get (our music) on radio. We have
to nip at their heels a bit and go through the backdoor'' of the
Net.
</P>
<P>
   But actually, Daniels and Dube said, artists can make more money
on their recordings, despite selling fewer records, because they
can keep so much more of the money from each record sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this sort of model, if you can make it work, the artist
instead of selling 100,000 records, can sell 5,000 and make
money,'' Dube said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason why that's possible is that technology has
allowed artists to shortcut many of album-making's traditional
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computers are recording studios, and pressing plants, and
warehouses now,'' Dube said. ``There are no production costs. In
the old world, if you wanted to put out a record, the first thing
you needed to know was how many records you were going to sell, so
you'd know how many to press. Which seems insane.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web works best for established artists who already have a
well of fans to dip into, but you don't need a huge name to have
some nice success.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way that the Internet has changed the dialogue has had a
good effect on music,'' Rundgren said. ``The blind assumption was
that no one would succeed without a record company behind them.
That changed when Korn got signed. They had already built up a
devoted audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Bands like Creed and Korn used the Net to build a base of fans
and keep them connected to the band's doings. Other artists have
used the Web simply to keep in touch.
</P>
<P>
   English singer/songwriter David Gray recorded three albums in
the mid-1990s before undergoing the standard breakup story with his
North American labels, then had to shelve one album and go without
North American distribution for another, 1998's ``White Ladder,''
even though the album went platinum eight times over in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   To stay in contact with his fans, particularly those who didn't
have access to his newer work, Gray set up www.davidgray.com, with
discussion areas, e-mail and tour information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was staggered by what happened,' Gray said. ``When the site
was set up, people from all over the world got on to it. We had a
real world community. It worked really well.''
</P>
<P>
   Though album sales weren't the site's main reason to exist, he
sold ``White Ladder'' through the site, one of the very few places
where the record was available to State-side fans.
</P>
<P>
   And once stations such as Los Angeles' KCRW-FM and
Philadelphia's WXPN-FM began playing some of its most striking
songs, sales took off, so substantially that he began selling
through Amazon.com as well.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, he became the first act signed by the new label
co-founded by American musician Dave Matthews, a fan of his music.
And perhaps the best song on his album, ``Please Forgive Me,'' was
featured on a recent episode of the Fox TV show ``Time of Your
Life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web sales helped make it all possible, though Gray said he
wouldn't have relied on the proceeds for his living.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more like a litmus test,'' Gray said. ``You get the
feeling there's something out there. There's no huge money to be
made. I don't think there are that many records being sold. But it
was so exciting to see there was an appetite out there for my
music. Critical acclaim is one thing, but when people go mad for
something and start raving about it, that's a brilliant thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles songwriter Phil Roy, who recently opened for Gray in
a Philadelphia concert, can claim something of the same story. He
spent 18 years writing songs for everyone from Jennifer Love Hewitt
to L.A. Guns to Ray Charles, before releasing ``grouchyfriendly''
in January.
</P>
<P>
   He set up a graphically distinctive Web site at www.philroy.com
where fans could buy the album, talk with each other and get tour
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can buy it through Amazon.com or go to my site,'' Roy
said. ``And they send me all these lovely messages with each of
these $15 checks. The only ones that are unresponsive are the
record companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, sympathetic DJs on KCRW and WXPN helped push his music,
which has made a difference for his success.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a break,'' Roy admits, but adds, ``The Net
leveled the playing field. I could never do this even two years
ago. Now the door's open.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
