A3102 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-RESURRECTION-REVIEW-L     06-23 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESURRECTION-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIEWERS DESERVE BETTER THAN THIS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below; `tonight' in story refers to Mon., June 26.) 
Our rating: 2 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
 
``Resurrection Blvd.,'' debuting tonight on Showtime, is the only
English-language TV series in America _ and let's guess that, with
the networks and cable, there presently are roughly 200 ongoing
fiction shows _ that prominently features Latino actors and/or
examines Latino themes. While you're pondering that staggering
inequity, take a moment likewise to lament that it's too bad this
one's not any better.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Riddled with cliche and melodrama, ``Resurrection Blvd.''
follows the saga of the Santiago family of East L.A. Patriarch
Roberto (Tony Plana), a former boxer whose brother was seriously
injured while boxing, drives his son Carlos (Michael DeLorenzo) to
become a champion. Roberto's oldest son Miguel (Mauricio Mendoza)
helps his pop with Carlos. Youngest son Alex (Nicholas Gonzalez)
attends med school and has an eye for a cute blonde there. Daughter
Yolanda (Ruth Livier) not only works long hours at a Beverly Hills
law firm but also, understandably resentfully, helps take care of
the family, while Victoria (Marisol Nichols) is a high school
student not particularly adept at picking friends. Bibi (Elizabeth
Pena), the tempestuous sister of Roberto's recently deceased wife,
conveniently lives next door (shades of ``Everybody Loves
Raymond'') and visits Roberto's home frequently to provide a lot of
expository clarification.
</P>
<P>
   It's Victoria who sets the drama into motion here, by getting
flirtatious with Jaime (Jose Solano, Jr.), a local thug. She cuts
school to attend a party where she finds him with another woman,
and even though all she's done is express mild interest in him,
she's furious; before long, she's nursing a shiner courtesy of said
bad guy (this guy's just plain evil). Well, of course Carlos has to
settle the score just a couple of days before the big fight that
will decide whether he has a shot at a serious career in boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Resurrection Blvd.'' prides itself on placing Latinos not only
before but behind the camera; one wishes the producers had put some
in the writing room who had a cogent understanding of character and
plot development. For example, Carlos' longtime girlfriend simply
disappears after he's shot; when she briefly shows up again, she
simply explains she had ``stuff'' she had to do. When Alex's blond
med student asks why he dropped out, he too simply chalks it up to
``stuff.'' His inability to communicate doesn't prevent them from
arranging a date, shot in montage so there's no need to write
anything depicting their chemistry or lack of it; simply cut to the
end of the evening where she says she had a nice time and they
smooch.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the cast deserves better material. Plana, an
undervalued veteran actor, finds a resonant emotional core in
scenes where the writers neglected to place any. Pena could do more
than what she's given to do here, as well. DeLorenzo exudes an
appealing soulfulness, while Gonzalez could emerge as the breakout
star here, and not just because he's the only actor who doesn't
have an accent. Livier does laudable work in a thankless,
underwritten role, and Nichols exudes such freshly scrubbed appeal,
it's tough to think of her as someone who'd have trouble finding
appropriate friends. Cheech Marin and Paul Rodriguez turn up in
small roles in tonight's 90-minute pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Another quibble: ``Resurrection Blvd.'' is yet another one of
those shows in which the Latino characters speak in Spanish only
when it's a word the gringos know (``Que?'' ``Vamanos!''
``Comprendo todo'') or can figure out from the context.
</P>
<P>
   Why not just give the audience credit _ if it's a scene in which
the characters might reasonably converse solely in Spanish, let
them; a subtitle here and there isn't going to kill anyone and it
might seem more realistic to the series' target audience. Which
deserves better _ and, definitely, more _ than ``Resurrection
Blvd.'' &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The show: ``Resurrection Blvd.'' &QL; 
What: Drama focusing on the lives of an East L.A. Latino family. &QL; 
The stars: Michael DeLorenzo, Elizabeth Pena, Tony Plana, Nicholas
Gonzalez, Ruth Livier, Mauricio Mendoza, Marisol Nichols, Daniel
Zacapa. &QL; 
Where: Showtime. &QL; 
When: 10 p.m. Mondays. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
