<HEADER>
A3124 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-INTERNET-SITE-LADN &LR;      06-23 0275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-SITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE: SITE OF THE WEEK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ---What: (registered trademark sign with the r in a circle) (tm
superscript sign for trademark)ARK: Master culture jammers mimic
the structures of American capitalism to funnel money from donors
to media satirists who pull a variety of high-profile pranks. They
more modestly call it ``corporate consulting for the 21st
Century.'' &QL; 
---Where: www.rtmark.com (pronounce it ``artmark'') &QL; 
What's cool: This site with a name even more impenetrable than
Prince, the Artist Formerly Known as a Typographic Error, is the
pivot point and paymaster for post-modern pranksters who've done
such things as create Web sites mimicking George W. Bush and the
World Trade Organization; swapping voice boxes in Barbie and G.I.
Joe dolls; and a series of compact discs that stretch our
increasingly litigation-cramped notions of what constitutes free
speech, criticism and the ``fair use'' doctrine. &QL; 
---Features: Want to help finance someone's great cultural
revolution? Or at least minor cultural skirmish? They've got their
own ``mutual fund model'' to cobble together funds from a variety
of sources. They finance projects that ``meet our bottom-line
criterion: `attack without physical injury' ... to humans, that
is.'' Coming up is their third annual Corporate Poetry Contest. And
of course, you can link to past tricks and see what they've
wrought. &QL; 
---You'll like this if: You think globalized corporate culture may
not be an untouchable good. Or you just like a good political
practical joke. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
