<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3130 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV25-B     06-23 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV25-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBER PEARL HARBOR? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 25, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three interesting things happened last week in the Microsoft
case. Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson gave the government permission
to ask the Supreme Court to take up the matter in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   He delayed his various conduct orders to the company for a year,
instead of three months, giving the high court plenty of time to
act, preserving an aura of fairness.
</P>
<P>
   And in Redmond, Wash., Microsoft rolled out the next stage of
its Internet strategy, an ambitious and many-pronged project which
it dubbed Microsoft.NET. The idea is to slowly turn its traditional
shrink-wrapped software business into an Internet-based
subscription computing service.
</P>
<P>
   The blueprint is for a system so extensive that, curiously
enough, were it successful over the course of the next decade it
could take over the operation of the entire World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad time, therefore, to remember the day the company
rolled out its (itals)first(unitals) Internet offensive _ and got
itself in so much trouble.
</P>
<P>
   That was December 7, 1995. Microsoft called 200 reporters and
analysts to Redmond to announce that it was going to stop running
away from the Web and, instead, tackle it. ``You will see this
company transformed,'' said president Steve Ballmer. ``This is our
jihad!'' (For a lively account, see ``How The Web Was Won'' by
Seattle Times reporter Paul Andrews.)
</P>
<P>
   Strange as it sounds, Microsoft in those days was on the ropes.
Depite the hoopla surrounding the rollout of its Windows 95
operating system _ remember the $200 million ad campaign, featuring
the Rolling Stones ``Start Me Up''? _ the perception was growing
that it had somehow missed the boat.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle's Larry Ellison in September had proclaimed that the
personal compter was a passing fad. Network computers soon would
replace it, he predicted, inexpensive devices capable of plugging
in to the Internet (or a corporate intranet) and drawing on
whatever programs were desired _ for a fee. Bill Gates'
newly-published book, ``The Road Ahead,'' was a laughingstock among
the cognoscenti; it barely mentioned the Web. In November, analyst
Rick Sherlund of Goldman Sachs removed Microsoft from his
recommended list.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, start-up Netscape Communications Corp. stock was
soaring. Its initial public offering in August had been priced at
$28, but its shares soared to nearly $75 the first day, before
closing at $59. Magazines trumpeted inventor Marc Andreesen as the
next Bill Gates. Pundits declared that technnology once again was
about to accomplish the creative destruction of a monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   And indeed, Netscape's browser did threaten Microsoft's
monopoly. Like's Sun's Java computer language, it was a crucial
piece of middleware, a program that worked across many operating
systems and so had the potential to promote real competition.
</P>
<P>
   So Microsoft called in the press to announce the deep changes
that it quietly had been preparing. Internet Day, they called it.
Gates began his remarks with a thorough analysis of the Japanese
bombing that had brought the United States into World War II. The
shrewdest reading of it came from the Japanese admiral who led it.
Isoroku Yamamoto wrote in his diary, ``I fear we have awakened a
sleeping giant.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was Microsoft that was launching the surprise attack
that December day. Gates was displaying his usual tin ear for
symbolism. (``Perhaps someone forgot that the (itals)bad(unitals)
guys had attacked then, in most American minds,'' wrote Robert H.
Reid in his account of the meeting in ``Architects of the Web.'')
In Gates' eyes, however, Microsoft had been the Navy slumbering at
Pearl.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft chieftain then introduced his own Web browser, the
Internet Explorer, which was tied inextricably to its Windows
operating system, which commanded more than 90 percent of the
market. A team of 2,300 programmers had worked day and night for
six months to make it ready.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy worked, brilliantly. Netscape shares fell nearly
$29 the next day, and in the next few years, the company was
virually rolled up, at least as a direct threat to Microsoft. AOL
purchased it in November 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble was, the US Justice Department was watching.
Previously it had accepted Microsoft's promise not to muscle its
competitors _ Novell, Lotus, Borland, Sun _ again. This time the
company's conduct of the browser war with Netscape became the focus
of the government case. An avalanche of e-mail, meeting notes, and
memoranda introduced into evidence during the trial persuaded Judge
Jackson the company was guilty of antitrust violations in many
instances. Netscape was just the most flagrant.
</P>
<P>
   First Microsoft tried to persuade Netscape to simply carve up
the browser market, he found, with Microsoft intending to take the
lion's share. When Netscape refused to abandon its efforts to
compete, Microsoft set to work put them out of business, by fair
means and foul.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Jackson ordered that the company be broken in two,
in such a way that the PC company would have to compete for new
business among the middleware companies and with the Internet half
of Microsoft. The company has appealed his rulings.
</P>
<P>
   At its product announcement last week in Redmond, the company
once again had bent to the task it set five years ago _ trying to
extend its dominion to the Web, this time more gingerly, more
subtly than before. The government and even the judge have accused
it of being up to its usual tricks.
</P>
<P>
   They fear Microsoft is again illegally attempting to leverage
its monopoly of personal computers in order to extend its control
to servers (the large computers that are the workhorses of the
Internet) and to various small Internet appliances (such as Palm
Pilots) whose popularity is growing rapidly. The trick, of course,
is to control the degree of ease and completeness with which
rivals' devices may be interconnected.
</P>
<P>
   The company clearly has learned something from its travails. The
new computing platform is designed to work with non-Windows
platforms, at least up to a point. But executives admitted last
week that key features were designed to work (itals)better(unitals)
with other Microsoft gear _ raising the possibility that the
extraordinary bundle of software services contemplated by
Microsoft.NET could someday take over the entire Internet, on
exactly the same logic that Windows rode to desktop hegemony.
</P>
<P>
   The moral of the story of Pearl Harbor Day in Redmond in 1995 is
that the lock on the personal computer desktop that Microsoft
possesses is far more powerful than it looks _ especially when
wielded with a determination to have it all. Technology is a
powerful solvent, it is true. But for situations like this, we need
the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
