<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ELECTION-ART-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN JAPAN, LONGTIME LEGISLATOR FACES STRONGER OPPOSITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIYAKONOJO, Japan _ For a powerful politician seeking
re-election to parliament for the fifth time, Kazumi Mochinaga is a
man of few words.
</P>
<P>
   With his campaign in full swing for the national election on
Sunday, Mochinaga declines to give interviews, makes few public
appearances and hardly ever gives political speeches in his
conservative rice-growing district near the southern tip of the
island of Kyushu.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, using a time-honored formula of his long-governing
Liberal Democratic Party, Mochinaga, 76, a former Welfare Ministry
official, long ago locked up the support of just about every major
business and professional association in the region and is
perfectly happy to let them campaign on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign headquarters, occupying a sprawling parking lot
here, seems intended to create a crushing sense of the inevitable,
filled as it is with the banners of the many influential
townspeople who have endorsed him and poster-sized testimonials
from party bigwigs in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps his glossy campaign poster best crystallizes the message
to the voters, with its images of a bullet train, immaculate
highways and a huge amusement center that will be host to some of
the events of this summer's meeting of the world's leading
industrial nations. With all of Kyushu's Liberal Democratic Party
legislators arrayed around Mochinaga, the poster succeeds in
announcing ``look what all of our years of government have brought
you,'' without using any words.
</P>
<P>
   But this kind of campaign, along with the kind of politics that
have produced it, are under attack across Japan as never before by
opposition candidates who argue that an era of mammoth politically
driven public works spending has come close to ruining Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Many voters have also begun to say that however nice the
old-guard politicians' promises may sound, Japan, with its
seemingly intractable crisis of debt and stagnation, must finally
learn to say no.
</P>
<P>
   Although most opinion polls suggest another victory by the
Liberal Democrats, the conservatives who have run Japan for all but
two years since 1955, skepticism toward the government and its
policies has rarely been so great.
</P>
<P>
   The Cabinet of Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori has a popularity
rating scarcely reaching the double digits, and many political
analysts here say that the party's hold on the people is crumbling.
</P>
<P>
   A glimpse of the future is already on display in quiet,
mountain-ringed towns like this one, where an insurgent campaign by
a young independent candidate is giving Mochinaga the run of his
life.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate, Yoshihisa Furukawa, is no policy radical. What
the eager 34-year-old does promise, however, is a shakeup of the
shadowy collusion between business and government that has been the
Liberal Democratic Party's hallmark. Counting on his own seemingly
boundless energy, he offers a new relationship between voters and
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   While Mochinaga seems almost to sleepwalk through his campaign,
Furukawa, limited only by the hoarseness creeping into his voice,
wants to meet every voter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets close enough to the electorate to feel their spittle
on his face,'' one aide said.
</P>
<P>
   As Furukawa's campaign van goes from neighborhood to
neighborhood, campaign workers intone an almost hypnotic message
through the loudspeakers emphasizing his young age, his Internet
address (www.393939.com) and a determination to ``fight to the end
to resurrect Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   As they shout, Furukawa often leans clear across the vehicle,
nearly climbing out of the driver's window to thank the women who
come out of their houses to greet him, and constantly waves his
sunburned left arm to the farmers who look up from rice fields
momentarily, smile and bow.
</P>
<P>
   This energetic approach earned the challenger, then unknown, a
respectable score when he took on Mochinaga in the last election,
four years ago. Now the incumbent, by his own aides' admission, is
running scared.
</P>
<P>
   `` Mr. Furukawa is running as an independent, and that is a
minus,'' said Kenichi Sugimura, an official in the Mochinaga
campaign who bemoaned the passage of a simpler era when the
instructions of an employer or a husband sufficed to make a whole
family vote a certain way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our opponent has been campaigning ever since the last
election, and such a grass-roots effort is a bit frightening,''
Sugimura said. ``It is impossible to know how much support he
has.''
</P>
<P>
   But as frightening as Furukawa's method is for the incumbent, it
is the message of candidacies like these, with their promise to
break the bonds between business and government, that most
threatens the Liberal Democratic Party
</P>
<P>
   ``Mochinaga and so many other Diet members are like tribesmen,
each representing their own favorite interest groups,'' said
Furukawa, who works as an adviser to his parents' liquor business.
``They think their job is to suck money out of the government and
spend it here. I believe we have to examine our fiscal problems
honestly, and level with the people for once.''
</P>
<P>
   The straight talk is clearly working with a lot of voters here,
especially, it seems, younger voters and women.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, Mochinaga was always very confident, but this
race is too close to call,'' said Watanabe Makiko, 47, a homemaker.
``There are many things I'd like to see changed in this country,
and Furukawa's campaign gives people hope.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But if the opposition campaign has inspired hope in some
quarters of the electorate, the incumbent retains some powerful
assets.
</P>
<P>
   Foremost among them, perhaps, is apathy. Asked about the nearly
50 percent of the electorate that has expressed no preference in
opinion polls, Mori, whose brief tenure in office has been marked
by provocative comments, said he hoped they would ``just sleep'' on
Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   Even more powerful in small towns like this, however, is simple
fear.
</P>
<P>
   At a campaign event for Mochinaga, public child- and
nursing-care employees were virtually ordered by their superiors to
turn out for the incumbent, whose four-minute speech was one of the
longest of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Construction companies and other businesses have been made to
understand that if they do not support Mochinaga, contracts will
dry up and bidding opportunities will disappear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until three months ago, business people used to invite
Furukawa to their parties and weddings, but suddenly that all
stopped,'' said Shinobu Fujita, a construction company executive
who supports Furukawa. ``But then the word was passed around that
if you were his supporter, you would be made to feel the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very hard to mobilize people under those circumstances.
In Japan, we call that giving people something to think about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
