<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3137 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-635&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      06-23 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-635&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CHANGES SUBJECT FROM EXECUTION TO ENERGY PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUSCALOOSA, Ala. _ On the morning after a highly publicized,
bitterly controversial execution in Texas, Gov. George W. Bush
quickly tried to change the subject Friday, challenging Vice
President Al Gore's record and positions on several fronts, from
Social Security to the longstanding investigations into the
fund-raising practices of Democrats in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush was most eager Friday to cast Gore as someone who was
partly responsible for _ and a proponent of _ high gasoline prices.
</P>
<P>
   Carrying with him a copy of Gore's 1992 book on the environment,
``Earth in the Balance,'' Bush twice read aloud a passage
describing ``higher taxes on fossil fuels'' as ``one of the logical
first steps in changing our policies in a manner consistent with a
more responsible approach to the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Want to talk about energy?'' Bush said Friday morning to the
reporters on his campaign plane, who had spent the last several
days grilling him about capital punishment. Then, opening the book,
he said, ``Page 173.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was on his way to Alabama from Texas, and his attention to
the book suggested that he wanted to move on from the subject that
had dominated news coverage of his campaign, the execution Thursday
night of a convicted killer named Gary Graham.
</P>
<P>
   Though many legal experts said Graham had received a deeply
flawed trial, and five of 17 members of a state parole board voted
Thursday afternoon to commute Graham's sentence to life in prison,
he was put to death by lethal injection at the state prison in
Huntsville at 8:49 p.m. Central Daylight Time. A half-hour before
that, Bush read a statement to reporters expressing confidence that
``justice is being done.''
</P>
<P>
   Over 19 years, dozens of courts and dozens of judges had heard
and rejected appeals by Graham's lawyers. But Graham steadfastly
proclaimed his innocence of the 1981 murder for which he was given
a death sentence and, in a statement just before his execution,
said, ``The truth will come out.'' It took a full minute for prison
officials to strap a struggling Graham to the gurney.
</P>
<P>
   In response to questions from reporters on his campaign plane,
Bush said he was aware of the details of Graham's final minutes.
When the governor was asked if he understood how other people,
looking at the facts in Graham's case, could come to a different
conclusion from him, Bush said: ``Yes, I do. Good people can
disagree.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to all the prominent people, like the actor Danny
Glover and the Rev. Jesse Jackson, who rallied to Graham's cause,
Bush said: ``I don't resent it in the least. I think it's part of
the American process.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's assertion Friday that Gore supported higher gas prices
came as he and Gore jockeyed for position on a campaign issue that
is suddenly looming large.
</P>
<P>
   And it deflected attention from reports of the enormous sums of
campaign money that Bush has received over the years from the gas
and oil industry. Gore has suggested that Bush's coziness with the
energy industry would make him reluctant to intervene on behalf of
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seems to be an effort out of Washington to blame me for
rising energy prices,'' Bush said at a news conference around
midday. ``The American people aren't going to buy that. The
Clinton-Gore administration has been there for seven years and
we're more dependent now than ever before on foreign oil sources.
And I'm amazed that they're trying to shift the blame.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Hattaway, a spokesman for the Gore campaign, said the
Clinton administration had consistently explored ways to reduce
dependency on foreign oil. He also questioned Bush's ties to the
oil industry, noting that Bush wants to give companies access to
oil reserves in pristine patches of Alaskan wilderness that Gore
wants to protect.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And Hattaway said that what Gore was proposing in ``Earth in the
Balance'' was not higher prices at the gasoline pump but steeper
taxes on companies that harvested and produced the kinds of fuels
that were most damaging to the environment. Hattaway said that
Gore's plan included details that would protect consumers from
higher gasoline prices, but he was unable to explain how.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Bush was clearly feeling ``the heat over gas prices
and his failure to take on his friends in the oil and gas
industry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
