<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, June 24, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Very warm and humid conditions will cover most areas from the
central and southern Plains to the Atlantic Seaboard this weekend.
A series of disturbances near the northern edge of the sultry air
mass will produce clusters of heavy showers and thunderstorms from
the northern Rockies to the Great Lakes states.
</P>
<P>
   Humidity will increase in the Northeast Saturday as breezes from
the southwest develop. Sunshine will be ample, however, and clouds
will begin to increase later Saturday, especially west of the
Appalachians. Farther west, broken bands of strong thunderstorms
will erupt during the heat of the afternoon from the southern Great
Lakes states to the central Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure will suppress clouds over most of the Southeast,
although a few thunderstorms will form near the coast. Meanwhile,
moist air lingering from the southern Sierra to the central Rockies
will promote afternoon thunderstorms over many peaks.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: RECURRENT RAIN
</P>
<P>
   The first six months of 2000 have been the wettest on record in
Binghamton, N.Y. Since Jan. 1, 27.26 inches of rain have been
measured, eclipsing the previous record of 26.63 inches in 1998.
Normal rainfall from January through June in Binghamton is about 18
inches. In 1998, the wet first half of the year was followed by the
driest second half on record, when only 12.62 inches of rain fell.
This year there is no sign of much drier weather returning to the
Northeast.
</P>
</TEXT>
