<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, June 25, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   ANTI-INTELLECTUALISM-REVIEW (Washington) _ These days, it seems,
a candidate's brainpower could be as much a political liability as
an asset. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-PRIVACY-REVIEW (Undated) _ As reports of electronic
security breaches and privacy lapses roll in with increasing
frequency, it has become almost an article of faith among computer
security experts that the radical, global effort that could make
the Internet more secure will not happen until a major catastrophe
strikes. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   CELEBS-INTERVIEW-REVIEW (Undated) _ Earlier this month, a Swiss
journalist was fired by a major German newspaper when it was
revealed that his intimate interviews with Hollywood celebrities
like Sharon Stone and Brad Pitt were fabricated. A look at the
world of celebrity interviews. By John B. Kenney.
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-CLAIMS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Written off as powerless and
invisible 50 years ago, American Indians have been winning back
small but significant chunks of land during a time of general
renaissance for many of the tribes. For the last 30 years, a new
generation of tribal lawyers has blown the dust off ancient
treaties to find that the deeds signed by kings and presidents
still have remarkable power in American courts. By Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSE-LAWYERS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Incompetent defense
attorneys; details later.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-INTERNET-REVIEW (Undated) _ Wine lovers have been surfing
the web, finding wines that interest them, and then ordering them
via credit card. There is also a thriving direct shipment business,
with wines ordered by phone or e-mail and shipped in small case
lots, bypassing both wholesalers and retailers. And, of course,
state tax collectors, as well. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-SCHOOLS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Last week, the Supreme Court
held that student-led prayers at high school football games are
unconstitutional. Largely overshadowed by the headline-making
decision was another important case concerning separation of church
and state in an educational setting. By a 6-3 vote, the high court
let stand a lower court ruling in Tangipahoa Parish Board of
Education vs. Freiler, which barred a Louisiana school board from
requiring that the Darwinian theory of evolution only be taught
with a disclaimer mentioning the Biblical story of creation. By
Thomas Vinciguerra.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-WAR-REVIEW (Geneva) _ Those who advocate for the world's
poor are mounting a powerful moral and political campaign to make
advanced medicines, developed through billions of dollars of
research costs, available to those who cannot pay. By Donald G.
McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   POVERTY-REVIEW (Washington) _ These days, only orange-haired
college drop-outs and Third World dictators believe capitalism is
not the high road to a better world. But at the World Bank, the
high church of development economics, a widening schism about how
to fight poverty is sending ripples around the world. By Joseph
Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-REVIEW (Washington) _ Iranian politics aren't quite so
simple as a zero-sum game between dueling clerics. Rather, they
involve a collection of overlapping power centers operating with
varying degrees of authority, independence and success. By Elaine
Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   ROGUE-STATES-REVIEW (Pyongyang, North Korea) _ ``Rogue states''
is not the first diplomatic appellation to fall out of use, of
course. The end of the cold war spelled doom for a raft of
nasty-sounding labels. like Iron Curtain, Evil Empire and Red
China. But Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's move appeared to
be the first deliberate effort to change the diplomatic lexicon in
pursuit of foreign policy goals. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   GREECE-REVIEW (Undated) _ Greece is not quite on the verge of a
nervous breakdown, but it is a society where national identity is
being tugged in opposite directions. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
