<HEADER>
A3168 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-LACMA-PREVIEW-LADN &LR;      06-23 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LACMA-PREVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
  
LACMA exhibit shows contemporary ceramics as colorful expressions 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes a vase isn't just a vase, or a teapot just a teapot.
</P>
<P>
   In the protean world of contemporary ceramics, these vessels
might be devotional objects, ingenious architectural experiments,
or pointed social commentaries wrapped inside complicated visual
puns. Perhaps all three.
</P>
<P>
   Whether miniature or monumental, classical or aggressively
post-millennial, ceramics after World War II have been as much
about what they express as what they contain.
</P>
<P>
   That historic transition _ from ceramics as functional objects
to ceramics as the tangible embodiment of abstract ideas _ is the
subject of the Los Angeles County Museum of Art's just-opened
exhibition ``Color and Fire: Defining Moments in Studio Ceramics,
1950-2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Assembled from LACMA's large permanent collection of
contemporary ceramics, ``Color and Fire'' marks the first time the
museum has organized this type of comprehensive survey.
</P>
<P>
   In her catalog essay, Jo Lauria, LACMA assistant curator of
decorative arts, dates the birth of the modern ceramics movement to
around 1925. That year marked the end of the Arts and Crafts era,
during which most pottery was created by ``teams of skilled
artisans'' who divided themselves into specialized tasks of
``shaping, decorating, glazing, and firing.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, today's studio ceramicist is a kind of auteur,
responsible for every step of object-making, from planning to
production. Partly liberated from the market necessities of
mass-production, ceramicists began to play with possibilities.
Ultimately rejecting the Bauhaus adage that form must follow
function, they looked at new ways of how a container encapsulates
space, ropes it off, makes it its own.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout centuries of Western art, lowly clay hadn't been
taken seriously as a sculptural medium, compared with prestige
materials like marble and bronze. But as technological
breakthroughs in the form of new glazes and tougher substances
proliferated, so did the variety of ceramics and what they had to
say.
</P>
<P>
   Southern California is a worthy venue for this exhibition, home
to such renowned practitioners of the art as Peter Voulkos and the
late Beatrice Wood of Ojai, the ``mama of Dadaism.''
</P>
<P>
   With 200 ceramic objects offering up their glimmering surfaces,
``Color and Fire'' gives us much to reflect on. &QL; 
---What: ``Color and Fire: Defining Moments in Studio Ceramics,
1950-2000.'' &QL; 
Where: Los Angeles County Museum of Art, 5905 Wilshire Blvd. &QL; 
When: Noon-8 p.m. Mondays, Tuesdays and Thursdays; noon-9 p.m.
Fridays; 11 a.m. to 8 p.m. Saturdays and Sundays; through Sept.
17. &QL; 
Admission: Adults $7; students and seniors $5; children/younger
students $1; children five and under free. The second Tuesday of
every month is free to all. Call (323) 857-6000 or visit the Web
site at www.lacma.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 1946EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
