A3184 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ASIAN-ECONOMY-BOS &LR;      06-23 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIAN-ECONOMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC LEADERS SEE NEED FOR REFORMS IN ASIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHATHAM, Mass. _ Three years after currency crises ripped from
one Asian economy to the next, world financial leaders meeting here
Friday concluded that it would be extremely difficult to enact
effective reforms to prevent a similar economic collapse from
occurring in the future.
</P>
<P>
   With Pleasant Bay sparkling in the background, the officials
debated the reforms undertaken in Asian financial and economic
systems _ reforms that some said may not go far enough.
</P>
<P>
   The international audience of economists, central bankers,
securities, regulators, and academics who gathered here explored
the causes of the financial crises in Latin America and Asia in the
1990s, as well as the solutions attempted.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Sheng, chairman of the Hong Kong Securities and Exchange
Commission, told an international audience of economists, central
bankers, securities regulators, and academics that in his 30-year
career as a financial official, he has witnessed three major crises
in Asian banking systems.
</P>
<P>
   Without significant reforms, he added, ``You can bet your bottom
dollar there will be another financial crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   After Thailand's currency, the baht, plunged in 1997 and other
Asian currencies followed, a chain reaction swept through the
once-booming region and then spread rapidly to Russia and Latin
America as each country lost liquidity and investors fled. The
overseas shakeup even rocked the US financial system. Intervention
by the US Federal Reserve System injected some liquidity into a
shaky world system, but the developing economies that were hit
continue to struggle with recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Officials all seemed to agree that some US-style standards of
disclosure and accounting _ to properly measure financial assets or
other economic data _ are needed. The political difficulties of
such reforms were acknowledged but were beyond the scope of those
attending. They also agreed that a better set of world economic
data is needed to help researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Goldstein, managing director of the World Bank, said
that although Asian financial systems have undergone reform, the
``easier and quicker reforms'' have mostly been implemented.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Fischer, first deputy managing director of the
International Monetary Fund, a global lending agency that has been
under harsh attack for its handling of the financial meltdown, said
that disclosure by government institutions in the securities
markets can prevent bad decisions that precipitate crises.
</P>
<P>
   For example, once the baht began plunging investors learned that
Bank of Thailand had overextended itself by taking huge positions
in futures markets. The pending financial commitments would further
drain crumbling currency stockpiles and worsen the country's
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer said it was also instructive that countries with
flexible exchange rate systems in place, such as South Korea,
seemed to benefit in the midst of crisis by holding large foreign
currency reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Korea had about $35 billion in currency reserves in place, which
virtually disappeared within weeks as money flowed out of its
currency during the crisis. With restructuring well underway in
Korea, it has restored $80 billion in reserves and plans to add to
that, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was no coincidence Korea experienced what was viewed as a
speedy recovery in a region where some countries are still
grappling with the aftermath of the crisis, Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
   A stockpile of currency reserves ``seems to matter,'' he said.
Fischer added that ``providing lines of credit by IMF and by
institutions could help countries very much.'' The IMF has set up
credit lines, he said, but technical difficulties to date have
prevented their use.
</P>
<P>
   Sheng, of Hong Kong's SEC, delivered the most blunt assessment
of a lesson of Asia's crisis that he believes was missed by many
experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Development economics over the past 50 years has been all
about (pursuing) growth, and we do not realize we cannot achieve
growth without huge risks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to manage national risks (within countries), because
national risks add up to global risks,'' he said. ``The strength of
the network is dependent on its weakest link.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
