<HEADER>
A3186 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CHILDREN'S-BEST-SELLE     06-23 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDREN'S-BEST-SELLERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW YORK TIMES BOOK REVIEW PLANS CHILDREN'S BEST-SELLER LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Times Book Review will print a separate
best-seller list for children's books starting July 23.
</P>
<P>
   The change is largely in response to the expected demand for the
fourth in the Harry Potter series of children's books, editors at
the Book Review said.
</P>
<P>
   The new Harry Potter book, the title and plot of which are being
kept secret by the publisher, Levine/Scholastic, is scheduled for
release July 8. With an initial print run of 3.8 million in the
United States, it is widely expected to reach the top of the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time has come when we need to clear some room'' on the
list, said Charles McGrath, the editor of the Book Review, which
appears weekly in the paper's Sunday editions.
</P>
<P>
   Editors said that the idea of adding a children's list, in
addition to the three hardcover lists for fiction, nonfiction, and
``advice, how-to and miscellaneous'' and separate lists for
paperbacks in those categories, had been under consideration for
some time. The new list will mix all categories of children's
books, fiction and nonfiction, but in the beginning will show only
hardcover sales. Like the adult list, the children's list will have
15 slots.
</P>
<P>
   Some publishers have been advocating such a move for months,
complaining that a cluster of popular children's books can keep
deserving adult books off the lists. On Feb. 27, for instance, a
third of the places on the hardcover fiction list had children's
books: three Harry Potter books, ``The Legend of Luke'' by Brian
Jacques, and ``Bud, Not Buddy'' by Christopher Paul Curtis.
</P>
<P>
   The Harry Potter books, a series by the British author J.K.
Rowling about a young magician in training at the Hogwarts School
of Witchcraft and Wizardry, will have been on the list for 79 weeks
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the Harry Potter books on the adult list also has its
advocates, said Deborah Hofmann, the editor of the best-seller
list. ``There are those who would argue that these books have a
strong following among adult readers.''
</P>
<P>
   But editors said that the change was supported by booksellers.
``Booksellers who report their weekly sales figures to us have
responded enthusiastically,'' Hofmann said, ``because more room is
now available.''
</P>
<P>
   The new list will include both picture and chapter books, unlike
the Publishers Weekly children's best-seller list, which divides
books into categories, including picture, chapter and paperback
books. The children's list will be derived from the same sources as
the adult list. The Times does not disclose those sources, but they
include about 4,000 bookstores and scores of wholesalers that sell
to 50,000 different outlets, including gift shops and department
stores. Sales from children's bookstores are expected to be added
to the rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Some books, like the Harry Potter series and the novels of John
Grisham, can make their debut at the top of the list, although it
usually takes two weeks or so after the publication date for
information about sales to be collected and printed.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, books that are published close together and are
part of the same series are listed simply by the series title.
</P>
<P>
   Hofmann said that the Book Review would ``for the most part be
guided by the publisher's own sense of whether the book is adult-
or youth-oriented. But, for instance, if it has been reviewed as an
adult book and retailers tell us it's getting most of its sales
from the youth market, we would be open to further discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   McGrath noted that ``if another `Harry Potter' came along, even
if it were only on the children's list, if it were a true crossover
book, it would be noticed'' by the public. ``Being on the kids'
best-seller list wouldn't ghettoize it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate the new children's list, the two pages of the
Book Review on which the adult hardcover and paperback best-seller
lists appear have been redesigned. The ``Advice and How To''
hardcover list, at the bottom of the hardcover list, is moving to
the paperback best-seller page, and the new children's book list
will replace it..
</P>
<P>
   Still, McGrath said, ``I don't want to rule out the possibility
we will adjust this. This is a work in progress.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
