<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3203 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TIMEWARNER0624-COX     06-23 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMEWARNER0624-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AOL, Time Warner gain shareholder approval of merger
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax and Matt Kempner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Shareholders of Time Warner and America Online didn't
get much time to celebrate Friday morning's overwhelming _ and
widely expected _ vote in favor of merging the biggest media and
online companies.
</P>
<P>
   Both stocks fell throughout the day, and after the market
closed, the Federal Communications Commission asked the companies
how America Online's AOLTV will affect competitors. The commission
also had questions about service the company provides over
high-speed digital lines used by phone companies. Approvals from
the FCC, the Federal Trade Commission and the European Union are
needed to complete the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The merger votes themselves proved cakewalks, with 99 percent of
the Time Warner shares and 97 percent of the America Online shares
favoring the deal. The Time Warner vote came in New York;
shareholders of America Online cast ballots in a hotel in Vienna,
Va., not far from the company's Dulles, Va., headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Now the companies have to convince regulators in the United
States and in Europe that they should be allowed to merge. If those
approvals are won, then the companies will have to integrate their
businesses and prove to investors that the deal makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm quite confident that in Europe and around the world, there
will be support for the merger,'' America Online Chairman and Chief
Executive Steve Case said Friday. He predicted the deal would be
completed by fall.
</P>
<P>
   Besides winning over regulators, the companies will have to show
Wall Street they can deliver on expectations. For example, the
companies have predicted that cash flow _ a commonly used measure
of media company performance _ will grow significantly faster
because of the combination.
</P>
<P>
   But Barry Hyman, an analyst with Ehrenkrantz King Nussbaum, has
his doubts.
</P>
<P>
   He said the companies have predicted cash flow would grow 30
percent to 50 percent faster. ``I'm having difficulty accepting
that. I think that's one reason you have AOL trading at these
levels. Can they generate that substantial of an increase?''
</P>
<P>
   Similar doubts showed up among some America Online shareholders,
who have seen their stock drop from $73.75 just before the merger
was announced, to $53.38 on Friday, when it lost $2.88.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Halpern, from Washington D.C., rose twice at the America
Online meeting to ask when investors like herself would see their
stock appreciate again. She described America Online as ``the best
investment I ever made,'' but said she worries about the future.
</P>
<P>
   Case said he was certain the shares would rise sharply after the
companies combined to become the key player in ``the Internet
century.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the merged company would act like a ``growth'' stock,
continually reinvesting profits into new businesses. As a result,
it will not pay dividends, as Time Warner has.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about stocks prices were not limited to America Online
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Schein, a Miami resident visiting New York, said she has
part of her retirement in Time Warner stock, which fell $4.06
Friday to close at $77.56. But that's still well above the $64.75
close just before the merger deal was announced.
</P>
<P>
   Schein wanted a little investment advice from Time Warner
Chairman Gerald Levin. Saying she wants to retire in five years,
Schein asked what would the combined company's stock do over that
period. As a Time Warner shareholder, she would get 1.5 shares of
stock in the new company for each share of Time Warner stock she
owns. America Online shareholders would get one share in the new
company for each share of America Online they own.
</P>
<P>
   Levin declined to make a specific prediction, but said,
``Obviously, I appreciate the question because you and I are in the
same boat. I have my entire net worth in Time Warner stock.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I am optimistic about the future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner's biggest shareholder, Ted Turner, was not at the
meeting. Levin said Turner met with Time Warner executives earlier
in the week in New York. ``I suspect that today Ted has gone to
Montana.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been published reports that Turner has expressed
unhappiness with his role in the new company, where he would be one
of two vice chairmen but would no longer have direct control over
CNN and other Turner Broadcasting System units.
</P>
<P>
   Levin, responding to a shareholder, repeated his past insistence
that Turner will remain a strong leader in the new company. In
addition to Turner's stock holdings _ about 9 percent of Time
Warner's shares _ ``he has moral authority in our company,'' Levin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
