   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   DEATH-PENALTY-FEDERAL (Washington) _ Looking at the federal
death penalty system. With the nation's attention drawn to recent
executions, the focus has been largely on the states, primarily
Illinois, whose governor has declared a moratorium, and Texas,
which puts more men and women to death than most countries and
whose governor, of course, is running for president. By Raymond
Bonner. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-ARMY (Jerusalem) _ Near the ancient caves of Bet Guvrin
in Israel, there is a secret Palestinian village on a hill. It
consists of about 15 houses and a mosque and is for Israelis only.
The village is a simulation, a three-dimensional stage set that the
Israeli army uses to train its troops in occupation techniques,
riot control and all-out battle. It is populated by soldiers
playing the roles of what an army official called ``the enemy'':
Palestinian stone throwers and police officers, even journalists
and housewives. For the Israeli soldiers trained there, the
experience can be dizzying. By Deborah Sontag. (The story has moved
in ``i'' news file.) 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   BANGLADESH-ACID (Gosarigaon, Bangladesh) _ More than 100
Bangladeshi women a year are victims of attacks by men, usually
spurned suitors, who throw acid in their faces. No one is sure why
this crime occurs here at such a high pace, for this nation on the
Indian subcontinent is not so different from many others in its
poverty or its culture or its treatment of women. And in a
male-dominated society, the victims rarely find justice. By Barry
Bearak. (Scheduled to move by 8:45 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT17,18,19, sent 6/21; and a map.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-PRICES (Undated) _ AT&AMP;T submits a new proposal that would
give telephone users more flexibility in seeking to save money on
some long-distance calls but that appears to fall short of stemming
the outcry from consumer groups and federal regulators over its
plans to raise certain costs for tens of millions of customers. By
Simon Romero. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
