<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3210 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-TOBACCO-570&AMP;     06-23 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-TOBACCO-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE APPROVES SPENDING ON ANTI-TOBACCO SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the second time in a week, the House has voted
to permit the Justice Department to use money from other federal
agencies in its lawsuit against tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 215-183, the House approved an amendment by Rep.
Henry Waxman, D-Calif., that allows the Justice Department to
receive $12 million from the departments of Veterans Affairs and
Health and Human Services to help support the lawsuit. The measure
had been strongly supported by the Clinton administration and
vigorously opposed by the House Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the efforts of the House leadership, 55 Republicans
backed Waxman's amendment, more than offsetting the 35 Democrats
who voted against it.
</P>
<P>
   Approval of the measure marks the second time this week that the
House has defied the Republican leadership and approved a transfer
to the Justice Department to help finance the lawsuit. On Monday
the House voted to block the Department of Veterans Affairs from
transferring $4 million to the Justice Department. The following
day the House reversed itself and permitted Veterans Affairs to
send the funds to Justice.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Waxman's amendment to a bill to finance the
operations of the Commerce, Justice and State departments removed a
provision that would have banned the Justice Department from
receiving money from any agency to help in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this settles the issue,'' Waxman said after the vote.
``I can't see how any other effort in any other legislation will
succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say, however, that they fully expect additional
efforts to limit the funds available to the Justice Department for
its litigation related to tobacco. Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, has
inserted language in the Senate version of the spending bill for
the Justice Department that prevents the transfer of funds for the
suit.
</P>
<P>
   Republican efforts to restrict or eliminate financing for the
lawsuit are one of several issues that have prompted Clinton to
threaten to veto the spending bill for the Commerce, Justice and
State departments. Clinton has also objected to the amounts
contained in the bill for such programs as hiring more police,
setting aside more land for national monuments and making
contributions to U.N. peace-keeping efforts.
</P>
<P>
   With such threats hanging over this spending measure and others,
most lawmakers expect tough negotiations with the president as the
fiscal year winds down in September. So far, the House has passed
nine of the 13 spending bills that must be enacted for the
government to continue to function. The Senate has approved three.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's action was the latest in a long line of skirmishes over
the lawsuit filed by the Justice Department that seeks to recover
from tobacco companies the money spent on health care by the
departments of Veterans Affairs, Health and Human Services, and
Defense.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the subcommittee that oversees the Justice Department
refused to grant the department's request for a $20 million
transfer from those three agencies to help pay for the litigation.
At the time, Rep. Harold Rogers of Kentucky, chairman of the
subcommittee, told Justice Department officials that they should
pay for the lawsuit out of their own operating funds.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno has said repeatedly that without
being able to use funds from other agencies the Justice Department
might not be able to advance the lawsuit.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After being rebuffed by the subcommittee, the Justice Department
unilaterally requested $8 million from the three agencies without
informing the subcommittee, according to Rogers' office. Justice
Department officials justified their action by citing a 1995 law
that allowed it to request funds from the Pentagon to help defend
the Navy in a suit brought by contractors for a jet fighter.
</P>
<P>
   As the subcommittee drafted spending bills to fund the Justice
Department during the upcoming fiscal year that begins on Oct. 1,
Rogers included a provision that prevented the Justice Department
from once again asking the three agencies for financial help in
pressing the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1995 law was passed, the Justice Department has made
21 requests for a total of $324 million from other agencies to help
in lawsuits. In 17 of those cases, the Justice Department was
defending agencies that were being sued. The tobacco case is only
the fourth _ and by far the largest _ of the cases in which the
Justice Department requested funds in a case where the federal
government is the plaintiff.
</P>
<P>
   On the House floor on Friday, few Republicans spoke in defense
of tobacco companies. Instead, those who opposed Waxman's amendment
said they believed the 1995 law merely permitted the Justice
Department to use funds from other departments to defend that
department, not to file suits itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statute is for defensive purposes,'' said Rogers. ``The
government is not to sue willy-nilly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
