<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3218 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BELLSOUTH-SPRINT0624-     06-23 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-SPRINT0624-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth watches for opening
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As WorldCom and Sprint battle to save their $120
billion merger, BellSouth is pondering its options, wondering if a
blockbuster move would add needed muscle both in the United States
and overseas.
</P>
<P>
   As the industry consensus has it, the telecom future belongs to
a handful of large, global companies with a full range of services
_ especially data and wireless. And while Atlanta-based BellSouth
is nowhere near dropping an offer on the table, it is eyeing at
least two options for bulking up _ one dependent on a partial
collapse of WorldCom's deal to buy Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom's purchase of Sprint is in trouble with U.S. and
European regulators, who are worried that the two companies
together would control too much of long-distance markets and the
transmission of Internet data. Together, Sprint and WorldCom would
handle nearly half the world's Internet data traffic and about
one-quarter of the U.S. long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   But wireless _ the unit that WorldCom covets most intensely _
competes in a crowded market and would trigger little concern about
potential monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth's $100 billion bid for Sprint in October was trumped
by WorldCom. But if WorldCom is willing _ and permitted by U.S. and
European regulators _ to buy just Sprint's wireless business,
BellSouth could scoop up Sprint's long-distance, local and Internet
lines unit for probably half the price it was ready to pay for the
whole company.
</P>
<P>
   That is no slam-dunk: first, BellSouth would probably have to
outbid at least a few European suitors. Then, it would face the
current ban on entering the long-distance market, either delaying
the deal until it wins approval for long-distance or concocting
some kind of regulatory end-around.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also a second scenario, apparently under review
before WorldCom ran into regulatory whitewater: BellSouth would
combine with Denver-based Qwest Communications and U S West _ two
companies about to merge _ as well as Dutch-based KPN Telecom and
KPN Qwest, a European joint venture.
</P>
<P>
   From that deal would emerge a $50 billion-a-year company with
local service in 23 states and a pumped-up Euro presence in data
and wireless.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth already has an investment in Qwest and a partnership
with KPN, but a ``menage-a-cinq'' would be a bold step for a
company that has always shied from any investment that
substantially diluted earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Yet BellSouth has already made a series of big-ticket moves this
year that signal an increased willingness to take chances _ and to
spend money.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic shift in BellSouth's image came in October
with its $100 billion bid to buy Sprint _ half of it in cash. While
eventually falling short, that offer did force WorldCom to dig
deeper into its own pockets to make the purchase.
</P>
<P>
   And since then, BellSouth has:
</P>
<P>
   partnered with Dutch-based KPN Telecom.
</P>
<P>
   forged a deal to spin off its U.S. wireless unit in a national
venture with SBC Communications.
</P>
<P>
   announced plans to use a satellite to deliver television
throughout the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   announced plans to create a tracking stock for its Latin
American investments.
</P>
<P>
   And BellSouth, which for years has courted and eventually
rejected suitors, is ever more open to marriage.
</P>
<P>
   The mood swing comes partly because telecom continues to
consolidate. But that attitude is also shaped by knowledge that a
small group of European companies are aching to enter the U.S.
market and are looking at acquisitions, perhaps of companies like
BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   Among them, the most often mentioned are France Telecom, NTT of
Japan and German-based Deutsche Telekom. All hunger for a U.S.
presence like the 15 million customers held by Sprint
long-distance. Looking to extend its reach, Deutsche Telekom
recently won shareholder approval to spend nearly $100 billion for
such acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth's stock was worth about $85 billion at the close of
business Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation has raged about the WorldCom-Sprint deal in the
weeks since Legg Mason analyst Scott Cleland called it ``a dead man
walking.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department staff has recommended against the merger,
and the department itself seems emboldened by its success in
fighting Microsoft. Meanwhile, competition experts from the 15
European Union states reportedly supported EU Competition
Commissioner Mario Monti's draft decision to block the merger,
according to Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   A final decision in Europe is due on July 5.
</P>
<P>
   But with European regulators in Washington this week, some kind
of compromise could be hammered out. And the companies were
reportedly negotiating feverishly with regulators Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If no agreement is reached, the companies will abandon the deal,
Reuters reported
</P>
<P>
   Monti has suggested that he will take a tough line, perhaps
because of residual resentment of WorldCom for the way it handled
its merger with MCI. As part of that deal, MCI's Internet
``backbone'' was sold to British-based Cable &AMP; Wireless _ which
later charged WorldCom with bargaining in bad faith.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
