<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3220 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-GORE-PROBE-HNS &LR;      06-23 1485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-PROBE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GORE RELEASES TRANSCRIPT OF FBI INTERVIEW ON FUND-RAISER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore, whose presidential campaign
has been rocked by calls for a new probe of his 1996 fund-raising
activities, on Friday released a 150-page transcript of his
interview with a federal prosecutor two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   It showed Gore heatedly denying under oath any wrongdoing about
his role in a controversial 1996 luncheon at a Buddhist temple near
Los Angeles. He has consistently said he did not know the event was
a fundraiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure as hell don't recall having _ I sure as hell did not
have any conversations with anyone saying this is a fund-raising
</P>
<P>
   event,'' Gore testified. ``As to whether or not I had any
follow-up conversations that said, were we able to set up this
event or not, I don't think I did. But I may have ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Gore told reporters Friday on his campaign plane that he was
releasing the entire April 18 transcript because ``I think the
truth is my friend in this. I have full confidence in the judgment
of the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, who was on his way to a fund-raiser in
California, added that he wanted ``people to judge for
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., who has been holding
hearing into campaign finance abuses, announced that the head of
the Justice Department's campaign finance unit had recommended to
Attorney General Janet Reno that a special counsel be appointed to
investigate the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   According to Specter, Robert J. Conrad Jr. told Reno that during
the interview that he and two FBI agents conducted with Gore,
questions arose about the vice president's truthfulness about the
luncheon he attended at the Hsi Lai Buddhist Temple in Hacienda
Heights, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The transcript shows that although Conrad questioned Gore on
several topics, he returned repeatedly to the temple fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were aware in late February (of 1996), were you not, that
there was a goal of raising $108 million by the DNC (Democratic
National Committee)?'' Gore was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' the vice president replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then a couple of months later there is a DNC-sponsored event
at the temple and it didn't raise any fund-raising issues in your
mind?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not know this was a fund-raiser,'' Gore answered.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Reno refused to say Friday whether she will
appoint a special counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at her weekly news conference, she said only that any
investigation into the matter should be done ``carefully and
without commenting on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno also vowed that she would not bend to public or media
pressure in the case. ``If we let some in the media push
inappropriately without knowing the facts, if we let people think
that because they leak something they can pressure us into
decisions, that just won't work,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   According to congressional sources, Reno was angry about the
leak to Specter and has launched an internal investigation into how
it occurred.
</P>
<P>
   During the news conference, Reno also was asked about the timing
of the leak and whether it would affect the presidential race
between Gore and Republican candidate George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make sure the investigation is done the right way,
that it is done to seek justice so it is done fairly so it does not
interfere with the democratic process,'' the attorney general said.
``I am going to do everything in my power to see that any decision
that I make is made without political influence from anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   This latest call for a new probe could spell serious trouble for
Gore, the presumptive Democratic presidential nominee, by raising
more questions about his veracity in the midst of the 2000
campaign. The appointment of a special counsel in itself would
provide new fodder for Republicans, and any such inquiry could
easily continue through the November election.
</P>
<P>
   After announcing the White House release of the transcript, Gore
raised questions about the timing of the recommendation and its
public disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the timing is a comment in and of itself,'' he said.
``Here we are four months before a national election ''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was suggesting political motives within the Justice
Department, he said, ``I'm not going to go beyond what I've said. I
think the timing speaks for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also rejected suggestions that his April 18 interview with
the prosecutors had been confrontational. ``I have told the truth.
I have cooperated fully,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he did not think people would ``find anger reflected''
in his answers and that during the interview he ``concentrated on
being cooperative.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have admitted that I made mistakes in fund-raising but I
have always told the truth about this matter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During his campaign stop in Northern California, Gore attended a
luncheon to raise $500,000 for the Democratic National Committee.
At a dinner in San Francisco Friday night he was expected to raise
another $1 million for the DNC.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, on his way to a campaign stop in Alabama Friday, said the
questions about Gore's fund raising are ``indicative of what has
gone on'' in the Clinton administration. ``I reiterate my call for
a new tone in Washington, which is going to require a new
administration,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad's recommendation puts new pressure on Reno, who rejected
an earlier recommendation from one of Conrad's predecessors,
Charles G. LaBella, as well as from FBI Director Louis Freeh, to
ask for an independent counsel to investigate Gore. She also
declined to do so after two preliminary investigations of Gore's
role in Democratic fund-raising telephone calls from his White
House office.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general has been strongly criticized by Republican
lawmakers and officials for past refusals to seek an independent
investigation of the Democrats' fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Justice officials insist that the department's campaign finance
unit, set up shortly after the 1996 presidential election, has
``vigorously'' pursued all leads and has succeeded in winning 17
convictions. Conrad was appointed by Reno six months ago to head
the unit.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Reno declined to appoint an independent counsel to
investigate whether a former White House aide, Harold M. Ickes,
lied to a Senate committee about his activities on behalf of the
Teamsters union. In December 1998, she found no reasonable grounds
to seek the appointment of an independent counsel to investigate
President Clinton's role in the 1996 Democratic fund-raising
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who was previously questioned four times by campaign
finance investigators, was interrogated for four hours by Conrad
and the FBI agents on April 18.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has said that he was unaware that the luncheon, attended by
saffron-robed nuns and monks, was a fund-raiser, although he has
acknowledged that he knew it was finance-related.
</P>
<P>
   The event, which lacked the conventional trappings of a
fund-raiser such as expressions of thanks for contributions,
nonetheless raised $140,000 for the Democratic National Committee.
Much of the money was later returned when questions arose about the
donors. Longtime Gore fund-raiser Maria Hsia was convicted this
year of campaign finance violations, which included disguising the
true source of donations given by the temple's nuns and monks.
</P>
<P>
   Under rules that took effect last July after the independent
counsel law lapsed, the attorney general must appoint a special
counsel from outside the Justice Department when a criminal
investigation ``would present a conflict of interest for the
department.''
</P>
<P>
   An attorney named to the special counsel's post does not have
the same degree of autonomy as an independent counsel had under the
lapsed law. While a special counsel would be free to structure any
probe as he or she sees fit and to exercise independent judgment
about whether to bring criminal charges, the regulations make it
clear that the ultimate responsibility for the handling of the
matter remains with the attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   The only special counsel named under the new regulations is
former senator John C. Danforth (R-Mo.), who is looking into
whether the FBI contributed to the deaths of 74 people at the
Branch Davidian compound near Waco, Tex., and then engaged in a
cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Reno defended her decisions in 1997 and 1998 not to
appoint an independent counsel, saying she still believes she made
the right decision based on the information available for review at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to look at specific evidence,'' she said. ``If you look
at that and all that has come out based on the information we had
at the time the decision was correct.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 2010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0338 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3222 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AIRBUS-SUPERJUMBO-NYT     06-23 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRBUS-SUPERJUMBO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPE'S AIRBUS ANNOUNCES 555-PASSENGER JUMBO JET CHALLENGE TO
BOEING 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ In a huge gamble to displace the mighty but
aging Boeing 747 jumbo jet, Airbus Industrie announced Friday that
it plans to build a gigantic rival with enough room for 555
passengers and amenities like a restaurant and bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Though the decision had been expected for months, it set the
stage for one of the most dramatic wagers yet in the aerospace
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The family of aircraft, designated A3XX, will cost $12 billion
to develop. The A3XX will be two stories high, have a range of
8,150 miles and probably carry a price of about $230 million.
</P>
<P>
   If the A3XX succeeds, it would end Boeing 747's three-decade
monopoly in jumbo jets. The loss of that monopoly, with its
relatively fat profit margins, could in turn deprive Boeing of its
ability to finance growth in more competitive markets for smaller
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   But the risks to Airbus are extraordinary. Boeing executives
have argued for years that there is only a tiny market for
super-jumbo jets, because passengers are increasingly avoiding huge
central ``hubs'' of air transport in favor of direct flights to
smaller cities and smaller planes.
</P>
<P>
   However, Boeing is also preparing for the possibility of
building a stretched-out version of the 747, which it says would
cost only $3 billion to $4 billion to develop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is either going to be huge, or it is going to be real, real
bad,'' said Todd Ernst, an aerospace analyst at Prudential
Securities, referring to the A3XX. ``There isn's much room for a
middle ground here.''
</P>
<P>
   Airbus executives also announced a long-awaited restructuring of
the company from an unwieldy consortium of four companies _
Aerospatiale Matra of France; DaimlerChrysler's aerospace unit in
Germany; BAE Systems PLC of Britain, formerly known as British
Aerospace; and Construcciones Aeronauticas SA of Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus will be a single corporation 80 percent controlled by the
European Aeronautics Defense &AMP; Space Co. EADS, as that company is
known, in a merger of all the Airbus partners except BAE Systems.
</P>
<P>
   After months of negotiating, BAE Systems agreed to accept a 20
percent stake in Airbus and let EADS retain the rest. EADS is now
launching an initial public stock offering, to be completed July
10, which is expected to raise about $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at EADS say the conversion of Airbus into a
conventional corporation will save money, eliminate inefficiency
and streamline the clumsy decision-making that had plagued the old
consortium.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a tremendous competition, a fair-play match
between Boeing and Airbus,'' said Jean-Luc Lagardere, Airbus'
co-chief executive, at a news conference Friday in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   It may well become a political battle as well. European
governments are expected to lend Airbus much of the up-front
development money. Although that is allowed, it may provoke
protests from the U.S. Congress about improper subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   The A3XX hardly amounts to a revolution in air transportation,
but it would be different. Its initial version will have enough
room for more than 500 passengers, compared with 420 seats on the
747-400.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on what the airline itself wanted to do, Airbus
executives say the extra space could be used to offer a
round-the-clock cocktail lounge, a library, a playing area for
small children or a medical clinic.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the behemoth could also be configured as a
monstrous can of sardines. By cramming in as many seats as
possible, the airplane could hold more than 900 passengers on the
two decks.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus executives argue that advances in technology and
materials will make it possible to reduce the A3XX's operating
costs by as much as 25 percent in comparison to the Boeing 747-400.
</P>
<P>
   But that will not count for much if airlines conclude that they
cannot keep the huge airplanes loaded with passengers. If Boeing is
right and Airbus is wrong, the A3XX would quickly turn into a
lumbering and underused elephant on many routes.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus executives argue that the steady growth in air travel
requires bigger and more efficient aircraft. They predict that the
number of people flying will increase by at least 5 percent a year
for the foreseeable future, and that airports and airlines will be
overwhelmed unless there are much bigger aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airports that handle 30 million passengers a year right now
will have 60 million in 10 years from now,'' said Alain Dupiech, a
spokesman for Airbus. ``You have limits. Nobody wants to have to
take off or land at 2 o'clock in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing executives agree that long-distance air travel will
increase, but they say the nature of the travel is changing.
Instead of flying between major hubs like New York and Tokyo,
passengers will increasingly demand to bypass the hubs and fly
directly to smaller destinations.
</P>
<P>
   The result, in Boeing's view, is that total demand for
super-jumbo jets will be only 400 or 500 planes during the next 20
years. Airbus executives predict it will be about 1,200.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Airbus needs to sell at least 200 of the A3XXs to
break even on its investment, and at least 600 to reach Airbus' own
profit targets.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus executives say eight companies have expressed
``interest'' in buying a total of 52 A3XXs. Of those, five have
have identified themselves publicly: Air France, Singapore
Airlines, Virgin Atlantic, Emirates Airlines and International
Lease Finance Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Most other big airlines have refused to tip their hands yet.
Lufthansa of Germany has said it is not yet ready to place any
orders.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's announcement does not represent a point-of-no-return
for Airbus. Officially, the company merely announced its readiness
to start taking orders. If all goes as planned, development would
start at the end of this year and the first planes would be
delivered in 2005.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
