u f BC-CUBA-EMBARGO-BOS &LR;      06-23 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-EMBARGO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPORT IN HOUSE GROWS FOR EASING CUBA EMBARGO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After four decades of an economic embargo against
Cuba, a proposal to allow food and medicine sales to the communist
nation is experiencing a groundswell of support in the US House,
where it may be approved as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   But advocates of the measure, who for years have argued the Cuba
ban is outdated and futile, admit that some of the credit for the
growing number of endorsements belongs to someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Before the plight of the 6-year-old refugee focused national
attention on the communist island, they say, most constituents gave
little thought to whether the US policy made sense. Nor, they say,
was there much interest in bucking the powerful Cuban-American
community, which until recently operated largely outside the public
spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   And while a number of other factors have helped renew the Cuba
debate in Congress _ including a vote to expand trade relations
with another communist nation, China, and a new study showing that
American farmers could earn millions of dollars in sales to Cuba _
almost no one can explain the growing interest in Cuban trade
policy without eventually mentioning the little boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been worrying about this for six or seven years, but we
never thought it would come this quickly,'' said Representative J.
Joseph Moakley, Democrat of Massachusetts, a longtime supporter of
increased ties with Cuba. ``It's the Elian thing. Elian has done
his people some good.''
</P>
<P>
   The pending agreement, which would allow US companies to sell
food and medicine to Cuba but bar Cuban companies from exporting
goods to the United States, still faces stiff opposition from
Cuban-American leaders in Congress. But a similar measure has
passed in the Senate before, and would probably do so again this
year. Even though the Senate this week rejected a bill to study
changing overall US-Cuba policy, the Senate is generally more
favorable toward free trade than the House.
</P>
<P>
   More significantly, House Republican leaders have in recent
weeks indicated they no longer oppose relaxing sanctions outright.
Instead, they have agreed to try to work out a compromise that
would satisfy both sides.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations are delicate: Many Republicans do not want
Cuban leader Fidel Castro, or businesses within his reach, to have
any dealings with US banks. They are, therefore, demanding the
legislation specify that Cuba pay for all food and medicine
purchases with cash. Advocates of the bill say that requiring
cash-only deals would be almost the same as keeping the sanctions
in place.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, some opponents are outraged that the
legislation would also ease food and medicine sales to several
other countries, including Libya and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Still, House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, an Illinois Republican,
last week said an agreement was ``about there.'' And Representative
Robert Menendez, a New Jersey Democrat long opposed to lifting Cuba
sanctions, said the most remarkable development is that there have
been any negotiations at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we're giving (them) a major break, a major
concession, because we don't believe in sales to Cuba, period,''
said Menendez, one of several House members insisting on the
agreement mandating cash-only deals.
</P>
<P>
   Justifying the Cuba embargo has become increasingly difficult
for many in the House, especially those who voted last month to
normalize trade relations with China. During that debate, many
pro-business Republicans argued that engaging China economically
would encourage democratic change. That caused many legislators to
wonder: Wouldn't the same theory apply to Cuba?
</P>
<P>
   ``The China debate has led to a natural questioning of whether
our Cuba policy is appropriate,'' said Representative James P.
McGovern, a Massachusetts Democrat. ``On all fronts, there is much
more activity on Cuba than there has been at any time I can
remember.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the US agriculture industry has begun a
massive push to open trade relations with Cuba, arguing its
proximity and its fundamental need for food could be a gold mine
for American farmers.
</P>
<P>
   According to a study commissioned by the World Policy Institute,
a New York-based think tank, the partial relaxation of sanctions
being considered in the House could lead to $444 million a year in
food and medicine sales, as well as 6,000 related US jobs. If the
embargo were lifted entirely, the effects could mean $1.6 billion a
year in US sales, plus approximately 20,000 associated US jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even the economic analyst who conducted the study, Paula
Stern, former chairwoman of the US International Trade Commission,
said the chief reason for the sudden fascination with Cuba is
largely due to one boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all been interested in seeing how quickly public opinion
has moved with regards to Cuba,'' Stern said. ``Everyone is an
expert now on Cuba because of Elian. I believe the reason why the
legislation is moving has to do with the fact that the general
public is looking at Cuba.'' In the past, she said, Cuba was
watched by ``just a small and energized group who oppose trade.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some believe that group of powerful Cuban-Americans,
now represented to the world by the Miami relatives of Elian
Gonzalez, may be partly responsible for any momentum the embargo
bill has gained.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Fernandez, the press officer for the Cuban Interest Section
in Washington that represents that country, said the Miami
relatives _ who cloistered Elian in their home and were often
depicted by federal law enforcement officials as unreasonable _
drew attention to views that are out of step with the rest of the
country. ``The American people have had the chance to know exactly
what kind of people these right-wing Cuban-Americans are,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Menendez called that ``wishful thinking.'' And he said there was
still time for the embargo bill to backfire, inspiring the
Cuban-American community to redouble its attempts to defeat it.
``Whatever negativity might be perceived as a result of the Elian
issue will fuel their efforts,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 2011EDT &QL; 
