<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-AVENTIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLENNIUM, AVENTIS SET $450 MILLION DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Millennium Pharmaceuticals Inc., Massachusetts' largest
biotechnology company, announced a $450 million deal with Aventis
SA Friday to create, develop, and market a new line of
anti-inflammatory drug products.
</P>
<P>
   Millennium executives said the deal with Europe's fourth-largest
pharmaceutical company will help transform the Cambridge company
from a genomics firm to a full-fledged drug-development company.
</P>
<P>
   The five-year Aventis deal calls for both companies to share
their drug discovery technologies, co-develop, test, manufacture
and share equally in the profits of their jointly developed drugs
in the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   For products outside North America, Aventis wil pay Millennium
royalties based on sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time where a genomics drug discovery and a
pharmaceutical company combine their respective pipelines of
pre-clincial drugs in one field for an exclusive relationship for
five years and beyond,'' said Mark Levin, Millennium's founder and
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Aventis will pay as much as $40 million a
year for five years to access Millennium's proprietary drug
discovery technology with the goal of finding drug candidates to
treat such diseases as rheumatoid arthritis, asthma, and certain
allergies.
</P>
<P>
   The alliances enables ``scientists the opportunity to work
side-by-side in the joint discovery of new technologies and new
anti-inflammatory drugs,'' Aventis executive vice president Frank
L. Douglas said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Aventis will also purchase $250 million of Millennium stock over
the next 17 months _ $150 million at the closing of the deal by
July 6 and $100 million in two purchases next year. Based on the
company's stock price of $120 a share, Aventis will own about about
2 percent of Millennium shares _ well below the stake of German
pharmaceutical firm Bayer A.G., which owns 10.84 percent of
company.
</P>
<P>
   Friday Millennium shares closed at $119.5625, down $4.9375.
</P>
<P>
   The Aventis partnership _ second in size to a $465 million
agreement with Bayer _ raises the total value of Millenniun's
pharmaceutical agreements to $1.8 billion. By contrast,
Millennium's first drug-discovery deal was a five-year, $70 million
agreement with Hoffmann La Roche. One of the compounds that
Millennium helped develop was an anti-obesity medication that
Hoffmann La Roche will begin testing later this year.
</P>
<P>
   During a press conference Friday morning, Aventis officials
explained they were looking to partner with an American
biotechnology company that had technology and promising new
products.
</P>
<P>
   ``We analyzed gaps in our R&AMP;D efforts and found them in genomics
and informatics,'' said Thomas Hofstaetter Aventis' head of
corporate development. ``Millennium can fill these gaps.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's agreement caps a series of converstations between the
two companies that began last summer, according to Alan Crane,
Millennium's vice president and head of business development.
Millennium, which employs more than 1,500 people will be adding
chemists, toxicologists, and pharmacologists to its staff as part
of Aventis agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be the biopharmaceutical company of the future, not
just a biotech or technology-oriented company but a fully
integrated firm,'' Crane said. ``This relationsip with Aventis
helps us get there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 2013EDT &QL; 
