<HEADER>
A3233 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ZIMBABWE-ELECTIONS-AR     06-23 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-ELECTIONS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ZIMBABWE, DISILLUSION WITH RULING PARTY IS RAMPANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe _ The old heroes sing liberation songs and
predict an overwhelming victory for President Robert Mugabe and his
ruling party. But the party's local youth leader smells trouble in
the air as he campaigns in poor rural villages.
</P>
<P>
   The youth leader, Ocean Mudzivo, has taken to searching funerals
and festivals for converts because young people no longer flock to
his political rallies. He talks of land and liberation, but the
young say he belongs to the party of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ask, `Why should we vote for you? We have no work, and
even you are doing nothing,''' said Mudzivo, 39, who was imprisoned
as a teen-ager for supporting Zimbabwe's struggle against white
minority rule. Today, he works odd jobs and grows vegetables to
survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no answer for them,'' he continued. ``I am a leader in
my party, and I cannot give up on it. But the party will have to
change.''
</P>
<P>
   This weekend Zimbabweans vote in parliamentary elections that
will challenge the overwhelming dominance of Mugabe's ruling party,
the Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic Front, for the first
time in the country's 20-year history. And as Mugabe campaigned
across the country Friday, he urged people to remember the past and
to stay true to the party that helped liberate them from white
rule.
</P>
<P>
   But the old message is being delivered to a changing nation.
</P>
<P>
   Today, about a third of the population consists of young people
who were either children in 1980, when majority rule was achieved,
or were born shortly after. And a significant percentage of the 5.8
million voters have registered since February, after the ruling
party suffered its first major political defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Even within the ruling party itself, the generation gap is
widening. For the first time, dozens of politicians have defected
from Mugabe to run as independent candidates, many of them men in
their 30s and 40s who see little future for themselves in a party
still dominated by aging freedom fighters.
</P>
<P>
   And as voters cast their ballots at 4,000 polling places, many
will ask themselves: Can the party of liberation transform itself
into a party that addresses unemployment and corruption along with
traditional issues of land redistribution and black empowerment? Or
can people trust a new, untested opposition party that has gained
popularity by promising honest government and an improving economy?
</P>
<P>
   There are still fears that the elections will be marred by
violence or fraud. Tensions are high, and about 300 foreign
observers and 30,000 local police officers are now stationed in 10
provinces, after a violent political campaign during which at least
26 people were killed and more than 1,000 white farms were invaded
by black squatters.
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt that Mugabe's government will cede some
power to the new opposition. His party currently controls all but
three seats in Parliament, and the opposition, the Movement for
Democratic Change, is contesting all 120 seats that are up for
election. Some government officials acknowledge that they will
likely lose their near-total grip on power, though they differ on
how many seats will be lost.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the result, prominent members of the party that
has always dominated politics here are already admitting that they
will have to change their message and perhaps reshuffle their ranks
to appeal to a younger and increasingly urban population.
</P>
<P>
   ``The generation gap is the problem,'' John Nkomo, the campaign
manager for Mugabe's party, said in an interview. ``The young
people, the so-called born frees, haven't got the feeling I have,
the humiliation I felt under white rule, the suffering I felt.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``These young people have been to school with the children of
the white farmers,'' said Nkomo, who is also the minister of local
government and national housing. ``They don't know these feelings.
Even within the party, some of our chaps say we are led by people
who are too old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of us feel it would not be the best thing to do to reduce
the number of senior people right now. But once we have resolved
this period of transition, you will see younger people in and older
people out.''
</P>
<P>
   The party has already begun to address issues important to the
disaffected. In recent months, the government began cracking down
on corruption and publicizing the victories of young, reform-minded
politicians in party primaries. Last week Mugabe, 76, acknowledged
at a rally here that the nation was suffering from soaring
inflation and joblessness, and he promised to re-introduce price
controls.
</P>
<P>
   But party members fear the new approach may have come too late
to blunt the challenge. And similar anxieties are rippling across
much of southern Africa, where parties associated with liberation
movements in South Africa, Namibia and Mozambique still dominate
national politics.
</P>
<P>
   In South Africa, where nearly 60 percent of people between the
ages of 18 and 20 did not register to vote in last year's
presidential election, the African National Congress is already
opening a campaign to woo young people. In Namibia, a new
opposition party drew much of its strength from young voters. And
even though the ruling party there gained strength in last year's
parliamentary elections, the worrying parallels between Zimbabwe
and Namibia have dominated newspapers and radio talk shows there.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It is not that the old ideals no longer resonate. People still
speak proudly about how Mugabe dramatically expanded access for the
entire population to schools and clinics during his first decade in
power. Many share his bitterness at the legacy of British
colonialism and white minority rule, which left the tiny white
minority in control of more than half of the country's fertile land
and most of the economy. And many express deep misgivings about the
opposition party's alliance with white farmers and business
executives, who have not rushed to help resolve the economic and
racial inequities in this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can never win election, not when they are a stooge of the
white man, not when they are there to defend the rights of the
whites, the white settlers in a situation of social and economic
balance,'' Mugabe told cheering supporters Friday as he attacked
the opposition party.
</P>
<P>
   But for growing numbers of people, the worries about land and
whites are overwhelmed by the frustration at the government's
inefficiency, mismanagement and corruption in the face of a
contracting economy.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, the percentage of people living in poverty
has surged to more than 60 percent, from 40 percent. Wages have
fallen to pre-independence levels. The government can no longer pay
creditors, buy enough fuel or supply medicines to hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   And one of the country's most most popular musicians, Thomas
Mapfumo, who once sang in praise of Mugabe's government, recently
shot to the top of the local charts with a song titled
``Disaster,'' which chronicles the country's recent decline.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Voter apathy has been one of the most vivid signs of public
disengagement and discontent with what has become virtually a
one-party state.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, when blacks finally won majority rule, 84 percent of
voters voted in national elections, according to the U.N.
Development Program. In the last parliamentary elections, in 1995,
that figure had fallen to 26 percent. And by last year, in local
elections, the turnout plunged to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zanu-PF pretends they're in touch with the people, but they're
blind,'' said Albert Meke, 43, a politician who defected from the
ruling party to run as an independent candidate in Chivi. ``Young
people _ some of them are for the new opposition because they are
unemployed and the MDC is promising to address those issues,'' said
Meke, who had been a member of the ruling party for decades and has
served in Parliament for nearly two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the government were making those efforts, young people
would feel more secure,'' he added. ``Some of the hardships we are
experiencing are of our own making.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
