<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3236 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-CALGARY0624-COX     06-23 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALGARY0624-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thrashers prepared for any offers at draft
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY _ As the Thrashers prepared for their second entry draft
today, the team's general manager said he realized predicting the
team's first selection would be futile. A year ago, a decision
wasn't made until a blur of trades was consummated 10 minutes
before Don Waddell walked up to the podium and announced Patrik
Stefan as the first pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know what's going to be presented to you, but
nothing has been presented so far,'' Waddell said Friday. ``If
anything does happen, it'll happen right before the draft again.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, wasn't stopping any media outlet and lobby
lizard from speculating on trade rumors and how today's annual
lottery will unfold. The Thrashers pick second after the New York
Islanders, who appear split on who they will take first. If they
don't trade the pick, the Islanders likely will select Slovakian
left winger Marian Gaborik or Wisconsin left winger Dany Heatley.
</P>
<P>
   Or Boston University goalie Rick DiPietro.
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers are interested in three players: Heatley, Czech
defenseman Rostislav Klesla and Gaborik _ probably in that order,
although Waddell was not tipping his hand Friday. ``We've gone back
and forth on this,'' he said. ``Who we take might be affected by
what else we can do in trades.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, Waddell maintained there was a ``75 percent chance''
the team would keep the selection. Any talented player at any
position would fill a need for the Thrashers, who are coming off a
season during which they lost 61 games, won 14 and were outscored
313-170 (all league worsts). Heatley is a power forward who can
score. Klesla is a physical defenseman who can move the puck and is
a strong leader. Gaborik, Waddell said, ``is the most skilled
player in the draft.'' But none likely will play in the NHL for at
least a year.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders, who won a draft lottery two weeks ago, are
central to most of the rumors. General manager Mike Milbury isn't
keeping quiet. Conversely, he's fueling every conceivable rumor.
Even Heatley noticed as much. When asked Friday whether Milbury
indicated the Islanders would select him first, Heatley said, ``He
indicated he likes a lot of guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston and Ottawa are among the teams that have had talks with
the Islanders about moving up, ostensibly to take DiPietro. Milbury
also reportedly is considering taking DiPietro if he trades young
backup Roberto Luongo, with Colorado among the possible
destinations. Waddell, also looking for a backup goalie, said
Luongo has not been offered to him.
</P>
<P>
   Ottawa has no shot at DiPietro or Heatley _ whom they
interviewed for two hours last week. In Waddell's words, ``I'll go
out on a limb and say Heatley is not going to last until the 21st
pick.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senators reportedly were dangling holdout Alexei Yashin for
a package including the Islanders' top pick. But Ottawa general
manager Marshall Johnston doused some of the trade speculation
Friday when he said a decision on whether to deal Yashin won't be
made until after an arbitrator rules on whether the talented
Russian forward is a restricted free agent.
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers are not in the Yashin derby. But Waddell does want
to stockpile the minor-league system with 12 picks in nine rounds,
including three in the sixth and ninth Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't draft too many players at this point,'' he said.
``We're not like Detroit, where we can say, `We don't need centers
or left wingers.' We need everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
