<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3240 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-COKE-SUIT-LAWYER-1170     06-23 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-SUIT-LAWYER-1170(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER HAS SPLIT EMPLOYEES IN BIAS SUIT AGAINST COKE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To his old friend the Rev. Jesse Jackson, Willie E. Gary is ``a
bigger-than-life character.'' Indeed, whether the topic is
compensation for a client in one of the hundreds of personal-injury
cases he has taken on, or the fine points of his private jet, a
Gulfstream II soon to be replaced by a Boeing 737, Gary is a man
who thinks in outsized proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Gary, 52, has been practicing law for the last 25 years and
presides over his own firm, housed in a baronial waterfront office
in Stuart, Fla., north of Palm Beach. Among his courtroom triumphs
was a $500 million award in 1995 for a Mississippi funeral-home
owner who sued Loewen Group. It was then the biggest verdict in
Mississippi history, and was eventually reduced to $175 million,
still a tidy sum.
</P>
<P>
   Gary is well aware of his power, stemming from dozens of similar
successes. So his sudden decision this spring to take up the cause
of black Coca-Cola employees in their racial-discrimination claims
against the company has created no small commotion, dividing the
plaintiffs by promising to win them enormous sums of money and
threatening the tentative settlement in the federal lawsuit that
was announced last week.
</P>
<P>
   For the Coke employees, some of whom had lost faith in the
original legal team, Gary's leap into the case changes the
equation. Now that a settlement is close, they must decide, once
details are made available this fall, whether to stay that course
or switch to Gary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're between a rock and a hard place,'' said Kenneth
Phillips, who was laid off in February as a computer engineer in
Coke's Atlanta headquarters. He is not a plaintiff but would be
covered by the settlement, which includes current and former
employees from 1995 to now. ``They are playing games with people's
lives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gary promises more cash for his clients than he says the lead
lawyer, Cyrus Mehri, has asked Coke for. Mehri says he has never
discussed specifics with Gary, whose pledge helped him attract four
of the eight named plaintiffs, along with some of the 2,000 current
and former Coke employees who would be included under the
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Gary has launched a fresh offensive against
Coke. Teaming up with Johnnie Cochran, the lawyer who defended O.J.
Simpson, Gary filed a $1.5 billion lawsuit in Georgia state court
contending that a group of black women who worked at Coke were
subjected to a hostile work environment, racial harassment and
other unfair treatment.
</P>
<P>
   One woman, the complaint alleged, was told to clear away lunch
plates and ``made to feel more like a maid than a
paraprofessional.'' Another was supposedly paid $15,000 to $20,000
less than white colleagues in similar jobs.
</P>
<P>
   A Coke executive, Carl Ware, has called the Gary-Cochran lawsuit
``an 11th-hour act of blatant and disruptive legal maneuvering''
designed to derail the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gary is no stranger to the company, and his complicated
relationship with Coke is seen by many as a major factor in the
legal role he is now playing.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson introduced him to the company's former chairman and
chief executive, M. Douglas Ivester, in January _ thinking, he
recalled, that Gary could give Coke some advice on how to handle
the lawsuit. In March, Coke's marketing department completed a
major advertising deal with Gary's recently formed cable TV
channel, MBC Network.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Gary was contacted by one of the plaintiffs who was
looking for a new lawyer; Jackson had provided Gary's name.
</P>
<P>
   Gary's bid to join the federal lawsuit, on the plaintiffs' side,
was rejected by the judge. But his dealings with Coke have provoked
questions about his ability to represent Coke employees properly.
He says he will file his own lawsuits and not worry about any
class-action aspects, where the potential conflicts of interest are
particularly potent. The separate settlement from Coke, he says,
actually makes his job easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, they will have admitted their wrongdoing,'' he said
in an interview at his office in Stuart, ``and that's a hurdle I
won't have to cross.''
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, his only experience in a class-action
discrimination lawsuit has been defending a Florida sugar company
sued by West Indian cane cutters in a case that he won and that is
being appealed. In 1998 he was fined by the court for being abusive
to lawyers on the other side, trial documents show. A spokeswoman
for Gary said the order was later dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Gary traces his interest in the Coke case to his father, who
spent much of his life being underpaid as he picked string beans,
cabbage and other crops in sweltering fields across the Southeast.
Dividing the Coke plaintiffs was not his preference, he said. ``We
wanted unity in this case,'' he said. ``But sometimes, it's just
not feasible to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had explained the details of the advertising deal
between his television channel and Coke to the four plaintiffs who
hired him. In March, the company agreed to pay several million
dollars over five years to show commercials on the MBC Network, a
family-entertainment channel targeted toward blacks in several
metropolitan areas.
</P>
<P>
   Gary recalls that he began seeking a role on the plaintiffs'
side in the Coke lawsuit in April. Then on May 9, MBC announced the
advertising deal. Newspaper reports about it came as a surprise to
most of the black employees who had met with Gary individually and
in group meetings in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But Gary was ready with damage control. ``When he flew his staff
of attorneys in and they broke it down, then we understood,'' said
a Coke employee involved in the case. ``He is not someone that Coke
wants to see.'' Those lawyers pointed to a $5 million settlement
that he got from a Coke bottler for a toddler injured by one of its
delivery vans.
</P>
<P>
   A Coke spokesman said the company sought the advertising deal
because it wanted to reach the channel's target audience. The
channel specializes in religious, sports and entertainment
programming for black families; Gary stars on ``Spiritual Impact,''
his own talk show. ``There was no awareness on the part of the
lawyers at Coke that we were having negotiations for a media buy
with MBC,'' said the spokesman, Rob Baskin.
</P>
<P>
   Gary sees no conflict. ``If my standing up for my principles and
what I believe in is going to make them cancel the contract,'' he
said, ``then the hell with the contract.''
</P>
<P>
   He has no trouble, he said, distinguishing between Coke his
opponent in the lawsuit and Coke his business partner. ``They
allowed this to happen,'' he said, his voice rising. ``They knew it
was happening, and they didn't do anything about it. It would be a
sad day in America if they got away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, say that Gary should avoid even the appearance
of conflict. ``It's not a matter of which he cares about more,''
said John Coffee, a professor at Columbia University Law School who
has kept a close eye on the Coke lawsuit. ``It's that the interests
overlap.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Mehri, the plaintiff's lawyer who represented black workers at
Texaco in a racial-discrimination case that was settled for $140
million in cash in 1996, said he was put off by Gary's whirlwind
attempt to become co-lead counsel on the federal class-action
lawsuit. ``We could not rule out the possibility of a conflict of
interest, even though we did not know the full extent of his
relationship with the company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's relationship with Coke is also complex. The company
supports his social-action organization, Operation Rainbow/PUSH,
and the organization owns a small stake in the company. For the
last two years, Coke has been a major sponsor of the group's annual
convention, held in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Coke is also a sponsor of the Wall Street Project, a program led
by Jackson that seeks to improve investment opportunities,
including access to capital, for minorities.
</P>
<P>
   At the Coca-Cola annual meeting this year in Delaware, Jackson
delivered an impassioned oration on the lack of diversity at Coke.
But he did not endorse the boycott of Coke products called for by
the previous speaker, Larry Jones, a former employee who took a
busload of black employees from Atlanta to Wilmington.
</P>
<P>
   Jones and several others took the boycott to New York this week,
holding up placards that read ``Coke Discriminates'' as traffic
streamed past them in Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   Gary's connection to Jackson, and both men's ties to Coke, are
sources of concern to some. ``Now Willie Gary comes in, and he has
a strong tie with Jesse Jackson, yet Jesse Jackson has a strong tie
with Coke,'' Phillips said. ``It's very chaotic.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Jackson said he originally thought Gary could
serve as Coke's peacemaker. ``I thought Willie could help them
resolve the crisis,'' he said. ``They could have no doubt used his
services. He could have at least laid out for them what the options
were.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary has great rapport with juries, evoking his country roots to
stupendous effect. And he works hard at his craft. His personal
office, complete with carved stone fireplace and full bar, adjoins
a paneled miniature courtroom, in which witnesses and lawyers
rehearse their lines.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he was prepared to handle the Coke lawsuit, Gary
said he had handled all kinds of corporate litigation, including
breach of contract and discrimination. According to some Coke
employees, Gary has made convincing arguments that he can get them
a bigger award than Mehri's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones who are knowledgeable about this will opt out and go
to Willie Gary,'' said one employee. ``Willie Gary has profoundly
stated that we are aiming for the sky. If it starts at $1 billion,
we'll walk away with $1 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehri said he has never discussed the size of the projected
settlement with Gary. ``It is not our practice to discuss
settlement strategy with any attorney who comes barreling in off
the street,'' he said. ``We never did, and we never would.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehri has some detractors as well. Concern about his
effectiveness escalated in early April after one of the plaintiffs
listened in on a conference call between several lawyers on Mehri's
team, Phillips said, and concluded that Mehri was not working in
everyone's best interests. The concerns included the amount of cash
the plaintiffs were likely to receive. Mehri's team dropped three
of the plaintiffs after deciding that they were not acting in the
best interests of the whole class.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Coke employees worry that the tentative settlement will
fall short of what they think they deserve. ``I don't want them to
go for a small amount of money for all the discrimination that has
occurred,'' said Angela Graham, one of the plaintiffs in the
lawsuit Gary filed.
</P>
<P>
   While some talk of rejecting the settlement, they also express
concern that Coke may see the split between the lawyers as a
strategic advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Gary said that would be a mistake. ``The longer they drag out
this case, the worse it's going to get,'' he said. ``It's cheaper
to do the right thing than to have to deal with a guy like Willie
Gary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 2017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
