<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0349 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3244 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AOL-TIMEWARNER-745&AMP;AD     06-23 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-TIMEWARNER-745&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAREHOLDERS APPROVE MERGER OF AOL AND TIME WARNER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The word AT in parentheses has been used instead of the
symbol, which is nontransmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The shareholders of both America Online and Time Warner on
Friday approved the merger of those two companies into the world's
largest media conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   The companies nonetheless do not expect to complete their merger
until late fall, because they must still gain the approval of a
bevy of regulators, including the Federal Trade Commission, the
Federal Communications Commission, the European Union, and
municipal authorities in many cities where Time Warner owns cable
television systems.
</P>
<P>
   Both regulators and analysts say that there is little chance the
deal will not be allowed, but officials are in no hurry to approve
what would be the largest merger in corporate history, valued at
$165 billion. Indeed, the FCC is expected to hold a hearing on the
deal in late July.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is simply a process of checking off a series of boxes
between now and the fall,'' said Henry Blodget, an analyst with
Merrill Lynch. ``The shareholder vote was the biggest hurdle.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest regulatory issue relates to whether the combined
company will allow more than one high-speed Internet service to use
its cable television systems.
</P>
<P>
   Until the merger, Time Warner had planned to offer only its Road
Runner service. But the companies now pledge to allow competing
services, like the Excite(AT)Home service controlled by AT&AMP;T. The
regulators may nonetheless impose some sort of requirement for open
Internet access into their approval of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Time Warner is negotiating with providers of
high-speed Internet access to offer their services on its cable
systems. It hopes to have a few such deals completed in the next
month or two in order to show the regulators that it is acting in
good faith.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter last week, the FCC asked AOL and Time Warner about
America Online's instant messaging service and that company's
ownership of a stake in Hughes Communications, the provider of the
DirecTV satellite service, which competes with Time Warner's cable
systems.
</P>
<P>
   And in another letter released Friday, the agency asked for
documents related to business alliances by both companies,
including Time Warner's stake in Road Runner and AOL's investment
in the TiVo television recording system. Regulators and analysts
said that none of these issues is likely to ultimately present much
of a sticking point for the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union has said it would take four months to look at
the deal, but it is expected to defer to regulators in the United
States. The EU, however, may take a tougher look at Time Warner's
unrelated proposal to combine its music operation with that of EMI
Group.
</P>
<P>
   In the shareholder vote, about 99 percent of Time Warner
shareholders, meeting in New York, and 97 percent of America Online
holders, in Tyson's Corner, Va., approved the deal.
</P>
<P>
   America Online, whose stock had been soaring in the weeks before
the merger agreement was announced on Jan. 10, agreed to exchange
1.5 of its shares for each share of Time Warner. For Time Warner
shareholders that meant receiving stock in America Online worth
$110.63, 71 percent more than it was trading the day before the
deal was announced.
</P>
<P>
   Since that time, with Internet stocks of all sorts crashing,
America Online shares have fallen to $53.25, 27 percent below their
pre-deal price. Time Warner shares are at $77.56, still above their
price before the merger agreement, although the premium has fallen
to 20 percent. On Friday, Time Warner shares fell by $4 and America
Online shares dropped by $3, amid a general selloff of Internet
shares.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Case, America Online's chairman, was asked about the
decline of the company's stock in a hotel ballroom packed with more
than 500 shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening really has less to do with AOL and less to do
with the merger and more to do with what's happening in the
sector,'' he said. ``Almost every company that we compete with,
ranging from Yahoo to Amazon to Microsoft to AT&AMP;T are down
substantially more than we are in that period.''
</P>
<P>
   As the deal works its way through Washington and Brussels,
Belgium, the managements of America Online and Time Warner are
working to create organizational and operating plans so that they
can move quickly as soon as the deal is completed. The companies
have promised Wall Street that they will cut $1 billion a year in
costs and increase their revenue by 30 percent annually, an
aggressive target for many of Time Warner's more mature businesses.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Top executives from Time Warner, including its chairman, Gerald
Levin, and vice chairman, Ted Turner, now regularly attend the
weekly management meeting held by Case. And the company has planned
a three-day management retreat in July timed to coincide with the
baseball All Star game in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Among the business issues discussed most heavily is how to
increase advertising sales at the combined company and how to sell
subscriptions to Time Warner magazines, like Time and Fortune, to
America Online users and the AOL service to Time Warner magazine
subscribers. There is continuing discussion, as at all record
labels, about how to make sense of the rise of free music on the
Internet resulting from technologies such as MP3 and Napster.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, lower-level executives at both companies have been
told not to wait until the merger is complete to find ways to work
with each other. Thus news from Time Warner's CNN now is featured
in America Online's Netcenter Web site and so on.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more difficult issues that executives at the two
companies have to discuss is the executive compensation system.
Like most technology companies, America Online has paid relatively
low cash salaries and given its executives substantial stock
options. Like most established companies, Time Warner has offered
generous salaries and more modest stock grants.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of both companies say they are working to come up
with a new system that is somewhat in the middle and that has a
measure of consistency, without requiring Time Warner executives to
all take huge cuts in salary.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of the new company will not be told about their
compensation packages until the deal is completed, executives said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, few senior executives of either company have resigned.
But Timothy Boggs, 50, Time Warner's senior vice president for
global policy, said Friday that he would resign at the beginning of
next year. In the combined company, Boggs was to have reported to
George Vradenburg III, his equivalent at America Online.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 2018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
