<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3247 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ECON-COLUMN-ART-$ADV2     06-23 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-ART-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: POLITICAL REALITIES SAY AN EMBARGO WILL LINGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 25) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States seems to have tired of using the
fruits of American labor as a weapon in global politics. In the
span of a month, Congress eliminated China's annual trade review
and President Clinton eased economic sanctions against North Korea.
The State Department even dropped the term ``rogue state'' from its
diplomatic lexicon: Libya, Iraq and Syria are now simply ``states
of concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Could the 38-year embargo on trade with Cuba be next? There's
some real momentum building, but don't bet on a big breakthrough,
at least while Fidel Castro is still alive.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of people, including some powerful business lobbying
groups, are determined to see the embargo relaxed or eliminated
outright. But even the most modest easing, to permit sales of food
and medicine to Cuba, faces uncertain prospects in the
Republican-controlled House.
</P>
<P>
   Passage is closer than ever, if only because the bill's
Republican sponsor, George ethercutt, faces a tough re-election
fight in Washington State's farm country. But the Cuban-American
lobby is pushing for a compromise that would allow sales only for
cash on delivery _ no credit allowed. Trade rarely flourishes under
such a restriction, which is the point.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban-Americans, many of them passionately anti-Castro, make up
less than one-half of 1 percent of the population, but they are a
political law unto themselves. Cubans are concentrated in Florida,
a swing state in presidential elections, and they turn out heavily
for candidates who pledge not to compromise with Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Witness the way both Al Gore and George W. Bush opposed the
Clinton administration's decision to send Elian Gonzalez back to
Cuba with his father, defying opinion polls in the thick of the
primary campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cubans punch way above their weight in presidential politics,
and that's not changing,'' said Max Castro, a senior researcher at
the North-South Center of the University of Miami. ``The day will
come that we don't have an embargo, but I think it will have to be
chipped away bit by bit.''
</P>
<P>
   A flurry of what Charles Shapiro, head of the State Department's
Cuban Affairs Office, calls ``changes at the margins'' are already
underway. More American are visiting Cuba. Some 135,000 Americans
received official permission last year, up 10 percent from the year
before. Some, including the Yale Glee Club and the Baltimore
Orioles, flew on new direct air service to Havana from New York or
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The tourist flow is still small, but not irrelevant for the
United States hotel industry, which remembers Cuba as the leading
Caribbean destination before the Castro era. Competitors from Spain
and Canada, which do not restrict trade with Cuba, are leading a
rush to invest there while American chains must watch from 90 miles
away. Hotel groups are among a swelling anti-embargo lobby
gathering steam in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Other pro-trade groups are trying to make the case that Cuba's
11 million people are hungry for American goods. Paula Stern, the
former chairwoman of the U.S. International Trade Commission who
now heads her own trade consulting group, calculates that without
the embargo the United States could sell $444 million worth of food
and medicine a year in Cuba, generating 6,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a growing sense in the business community that if
we're going to trade with North Korea, Vietnam, Russia and some
countries in the Middle East, why aren't we trading with Cuba?''
said Thomas Donohue, who heads the United States Chamber of
Commerce. ``People are asking fundamental questions about a policy
that's clearly illogical.''
</P>
<P>
   But Congress is listening with just one ear, at least so far.
The Senate seems not to want to even study the matter: last week it
voted 59 to 41 against creating a special commission to research
the effectiveness of the Cuba embargo.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that Cuba upends the usual political
order in Washington. Democrats, usually skeptical of free trade,
generally want to lift the embargo, while ordinarily trade-friendly
Republicans tend to want to retain it.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Birns, a Cuba expert at the Council on Hemispheric Affairs
in Washington, said that when the embargo finally goes, 2000 will
be seen as the watershed. The Gonzalez case exposed the anti-Castro
lobby as fanatical, a label that will be hard to shake, Birns said.
</P>
<P>
   But he thinks the political calculus still does not favor
dramatic action on the embargo, and certainly not in an election
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can accuse people of hypocrisy and double standards all
you want,'' he said. ``But they're not going to do anything about
it until they see a political advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
