<HEADER>
A3250 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CLINTON-OLYMPICS-NYT &LR;      06-23 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-OLYMPICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON GETS TIPS ON POLE VAULTING, RACE WALKING FROM U.S.
OLYMPIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHULA VISTA, Calif. _ President Clinton saluted American
athletes at an Olympic training center here Friday and received
some expert instruction in pole vaulting, race walking and archery.
</P>
<P>
   Under a hot California sun, Chad Smith, who hopes to represent
the United States in the decathlon at the Olympic Games this fall,
showed Clinton how he hoisted himself up in the pole vault. Andrew
Hermann, a champion race walker, taught the leader of the free
world how to gyrate his hips and swing his arms while gliding along
the track. Two archers, Vic Wonderly and Rod White, demonstrated
how to shoot Olympic bull's-eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The president, who gave up jogging after he injured a knee,
watched carefully, questioned the athletes intently, but, much to
the relief of his aides, declined to put his newly found knowledge
to use.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did, however, salute the athletes preparing for the
Games this fall in Sydney, Australia, and announced initiatives he
said he hoped would encourage more Americans to break into a sweat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people like the Olympics, in large measure, because
the Olympics work pretty much the way we think life ought to
work,'' the president said. ``Everybody gets an opportunity to play
_ and regardless of race or station in life _ and increasingly,
thank goodness, regardless of gender.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he has directed the departments of Education and
Health and Human Services to formulate measures to encourage more
children to become more physically fit. From 1991 to 1999, the
percentage of high school students in daily gym classes declined
from 42 percent to 29 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   During Clinton's tour of the 150-acre training center here, one
of three such facilities in the United States, the president saw
athletes honing their skills for the upcoming Games, and others
still competing for membership on the U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to win all the medals you can,'' Clinton told
several hundred athletes who took a break from their routines to
hear him. ``But I want you to realize that by what you have
accomplished already, and by the way you have done it, you have
already made your country very proud.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said he was particularly impressed with the
marathon runner Christine Clark, who is 37 and began running only
five years ago but who has been selected for the Olympic squad.
</P>
<P>
   He also singled out Deena Drossin, who is competing for a place
on the track and field team. During a championship race in
Portugal, she was stung by a bee in her throat. She blacked out in
the middle of the race but managed to get up and continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``She gave new meaning to the term `making a beeline,''' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   The president said that he would not attend the Games this fall
and that Hillary Rodham Clinton would be occupied with ``a
competition of her own.'' But Clinton said his daughter, Chelsea,
was planning to attend to cheer for America's athletes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
