<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3254 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-MUSIC-ART-2TAKES-     06-23 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-MUSIC-ART-2TAKES-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC INDUSTRY HEARTBREAKERS, DREAM MAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 25) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ALEX BERENSON with MATT RICHTEL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom says the music industry is under siege,
threatened by Napster and MP3 and digital piracy.
</P>
<P>
   In the none-too-distant future, techno-visionaries declare,
musicians will not need record labels. Instead, they will market
and sell recordings directly to fans over the Internet. Even the
labels that manage to hang on to their artists will find their
sales eviscerated by piracy. With free music available on the Web
via Napster and other song-trading services, only fools will pay
for songs.
</P>
<P>
   That's the conventional wisdom. Why, then, did the French
conglomerate Vivendi agree last week to pay $34 billion in stock
for Seagram, whose Universal Music division is the world leader?
And why did Jean-Marie Messier, Vivendi's chairman, describe music
as the most important element of the deal? Or, as one music
industry executive put it in language too colorful to quote
directly: If things are so bad, how come we're selling so many
records?
</P>
<P>
   Good questions all. In their rush to mock the Vivendi-Universal
deal _ and to write off Bertelsmann, Sony, Time Warner and EMI,
which with Universal dominate the $40 billion music industry
worldwide _ fans of Napster, MP3 and other upstart technologies are
ignoring the fact that the music industry is booming, perhaps a
more powerful force in pop culture than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, sales of albums, as the industry
anachronistically calls full-length CD's and cassettes, are up
about 8 percent, to 312 million through mid-June, according to
Soundscan, which tracks such things. Albums released this year by
Eminem, Britney Spears and 'N Sync had the three fastest-selling
debuts in the history of the music industry. Eminem records for
Interscope, which is owned by Universal, while Britney Spears and
'N Sync are on Jive Records, which is partially owned and
distributed by BMG.
</P>
<P>
   Shipments of CD's are almost certain to top one billion this
year for the first time, up from 940 million last year, according
to the Recording Industry Association of America, a trade group.
Over all, the industry is on track to ship more than $15 billion in
CD's, DVD's, and even vinyl albums this year _ double the level of
a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   That strength comes in the face of the explosive growth of
Napster, a free service that allows anyone connected to the
Internet to trade songs with anyone else registered with the
service. In the 18 months since it was created by Shawn Fanning,
then 19 and a Northeastern University student looking for a way to
share music files, Napster has registered more than 13 million
users _ without any paid advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, it has become a cultural phenomenon, the subject
of magazine cover articles and ominous news reports. ``Like
techno-termites, computer users who swap free recordings are
gnawing at the foundations of the music industry,'' The Wall Street
Journal intoned on Tuesday, laying the blame for ``a piracy
plague'' squarely on Napster.
</P>
<P>
   The recording industry is indeed concerned about Napster. Its
new mechanism for distributing songs _ both convenient and free _
has proved its attractiveness, especially for the young people who
are the most avid music consumers.
</P>
<P>
   In a lawsuit scheduled to be heard next month, the industry
contends that the service contributes to copyright infringement.
Napster disputes the accusation that its technology hurts record
companies, arguing that it gives consumers a way to sample songs
before buying albums.
</P>
<P>
   Recent rulings in other cases have gone the industry's way, and
the music companies say they can create an equally convenient
digital system that protects their property rights, though so far
they have not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Napster's growth indicates demand for music digitally, not
demand for Napster,'' said Dave Goldberg, chairman of Launch Media,
a company that has partnered with traditional labels to offer songs
and music videos over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The focus on Napster and its Internet ilk ignores the
established music industry's real strengths _ and the reasons that
companies like Vivendi and America Online are buying into the
business, Goldberg and others say.
</P>
<P>
   The companies are not paying billions for the opportunity to
truck CD's to retailers. Rather, like movie studios _ to which most
of the big record companies are attached _ they are first and
foremost in the promotion and marketing business.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States alone, there are hundreds of thousands of
bands with enough original material for full-length CD's. MP3.com,
which operates an Internet site where bands can post music free,
had 74,000 artists and 469,000 songs available for download at the
end of May.
</P>
<P>
   Yet at any given moment, only a few dozen musicians occupy the
public's attention, generating the kind of radio play, record sales
and adulation that generations of garage bands have dreamed about.
The others are just background noise.
</P>
<P>
   And it is the background noise _ or at least the kind of music
little heard outside college quads _ in which the upstarts
specialize. From December to March, the number of bands on the
MP3.com site rose to 63,000 from 45,000. But the number of CD's
sold on the site during that time was stuck, at about 26,000 a
month. (MP3.com stopped reporting its CD sales after March.) Put
another way, consumers bought more copies of the new Britney Spears
album on the day it was released than they have ever bought at
MP3.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``The record industry so far has a lock on almost all the
marketable talent out there,'' said Ron Rodrigues, editor in chief
of Radio &AMP; Records, a Los Angeles newspaper that covers the music
industry. ``There hasn't been an entrepreneur as of yet who's been
able to skirt the recording industry as we know it and make money
outside the system. The whole front end of the process by which the
record gets marketed and played hasn't changed yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it likely to anytime soon. The keys, now more than ever,
are money and size.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   After a decade of consolidation, the radio industry has two
giant gatekeepers, Clear Channel Communications and Viacom's
Infinity Broadcasting, which each control hundreds of stations
across the country. Viacom also owns MTV _ if anything even more
important than radio to the success of a new album. Both companies
carefully build their stations' playlists _ making it difficult for
an unknown band or song to become a hit in one market and spread to
others.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the heightened power of the record labels, which
themselves have consolidated into a few giant corporate hydras. The
labels' clout is crucial to getting new bands broadcast exposure,
the fuel that drives sales. Labels trade promotional appearances by
successful, established bands for air time for new bands. They pay
to sponsor concerts with local radio stations, a practice that some
critics say skirts close to payola, the illegal act of paying to
have a song played. They advertise everywhere from Rolling Stone
magazine to posters on construction sites.
</P>
<P>
   Without all that, it is nearly impossible for a band to break
through the clutter, said Michael Nathanson, who follows the music
industry for Sanford C. Bernstein, the securities firm. Nathanson
said that even Warner Music and EMI had struggled recently to get
some new artists' songs on the air because BMG and Universal have
been so dominant for the last year _ though Nathanson does not
expect that situation to last.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to promotion and marketing, labels put up the cash
advances that artists use to record their albums, and they offer
creative advice, for better or worse. Sometimes the labels go a
step further, actually creating bands with a sound and look they
think will resonate.
</P>
<P>
   Critics who say Napster and MP3.com will destroy the labels
``have misunderstood the business of music,'' said Paul Vidich,
executive vice president of Warner Music.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of performers, like Courtney Love, have protested the
labels' dominance, but record executives say the current system
works for most musicians, who lack the time or money to promote and
market an album.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think artists are in the position of being risk-takers
like that,'' Vidich said. ``They would rather get a big advance.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, upstarts like MP3.com, which boldly declared last year
that it would take power from established labels by offering bands
higher royalty payments and direct access to consumers, seem to be
recognizing that their role may simply be to push the industry to
embrace new means of distribution and promotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no desire to put the labels out of business,'' said
Hank Barry, Napster chief executive. ``We believe that this advance
in technology will increase interest in music.''
</P>
<P>
   The labels, after years of dragging their heels on digital
distribution, seem finally to agree. Before the year is out,
Universal plans to sell digital music over the Internet;
eventually, Messier hopes to link the service to his budding
cell-phone empire. Similarly, AOL is likely to explore way to
electronically distribute music _ including Warner's _ to its
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhere along the line, we thought the album was created by
God and forgot it is not the only way that music is packaged and
sold,'' said Jay A. Samit, EMI Music's senior vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Still, exactly how music will be sold in the future remains an
open question. Goldberg favors subscription services that will
allow users to hear as much music as they want, commercial free,
for a fee of $15 or so a month. If the record industry could
convince the 100 million Americans considered to be active music
consumers to sign up for a subscription service, it would have
annual revenue of $18 billion, slightly more than current annual
record sales, he said. He also expects advertising-supported
Internet radio services to become more popular.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Vidich said he thinks subscription services
are unlikely to catch on as long as free, ad-supported radio is
available. He says digital downloads of individual albums will more
likely be popular _ as will traditional CD's.
</P>
<P>
   ``People do like CD's'' he said. ``They continue to buy about
900 million CD's every year in this country. I don't think people
are going to change their behavior dramatically. They're going to
continue to do what they've done, and they're going to do new
things.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 2021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
