<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0355 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3258 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-DISCOVERY-COVE250-COX     06-23 1404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISCOVERY-COVE250-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    You'll be flip for the ride, courtesy of a bottlenose dolphin,
and the mammal-to-mammal bonding at Orlando's new Discovery Cove
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 25.
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO _ My dolphin has gone limp.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was for me to grab her dorsal fin with both hands and
hitch a ride as she swam directly to trainer Carrie Nelson,
stationed on a rock outcropping about 25 feet to the left. But
halfway there, Natalie _ a 5-year-old, 340-pound Atlantic
bottlenose _ has veered off course and glided to a halt. For a few
seconds she is inert in the saltwater lagoon, droopy at both ends _
a slick, slack arc of indecision.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe she caught sight of another trainer, looking on from the
far edge of the palm-ringed pool, and got confused. Maybe she was
distracted by the other dolphins. Far more likely though, at least
to my mind, is that she's annoyed by the flailing, hapless human
she's dragging behind her, who can't seem to get a proper grip on
her fin to save his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's try again!'' bellows Paul Komkanski, treading water next
to me. Komkanski and Nelson are two of four wildly enthusiastic
trainers guiding me and several others through a preview of the
dolphin-swim experience at Discovery Cove. Just across the way from
sister attraction Sea World Orlando, the 30-acre, interactive
marine park is Central Florida's latest bid for your tourist
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Guests of Discovery Cove, which opens Saturday, can snorkel
among stingrays and puffer fish in a coral reef (where you can also
spy sharks behind glass); float under waterfalls and through an
aviary on a 3,300-foot ``lazy river''; or they can just bask in the
baking Florida sun on the man-made beach.
</P>
<P>
   But the 800-pound gorilla, as it were, is the dolphin swim. The
90-minute session, including a 45-minute pre-swim presentation on
dolphin anatomy and habits, isn't the only attraction of its kind.
There are similar programs at the Seaquarium in Miami, in the
Florida Keys and at various oceanside resorts in the Caribbean. But
it's a convenient destination for landlocked Atlantans longing for
a more tactile encounter with marine life than they can get at the
local tropical fish store.
</P>
<P>
   It's a pricey ride: $179 plus tax, $89 if you opt out of the
dolphin swim, though that's akin to visiting Zoo Atlanta and not
seeing the pandas. You also get a buffet-style meal _ including,
oddly, some seafood entrees _ and passes to Sea World Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   The wallet-hoovering admission doesn't seem to be deterring
visitors; July and August are virtual advance sell-out-- . (The
reservations-only park limits attendance to slightly less than
1,000 guests per day.)
</P>
<P>
   Those willing to pay the top ticket price are in for an
intensely hands-on _ and occasionally lips-on _ experience.
</P>
<P>
   My swim begins with a kiss from Griffith, one of 28 dolphins
that Discovery Cove, er, employs. Another female Atlantic
bottlenose, Griffith poses for photo ops with guests when they
first enter the pool. Heeding the trainers' warning to approach her
straight on and not from above _ lest she jerk her head up while
we're engaged _ I gingerly buss her nose, or rostrum. It's wet and
rubbery, like smooching the toe of a rain boot. But it's not the
worst kiss I've ever had.
</P>
<P>
   Next I meet C.J., a 7-year-old Atlantic bottlenose/common
dolphin mix, and I stroke his soft white belly, which I'm told he
likes. Forty minutes later, I'll end the swim with a quick,
whooshing ride on Capricorn, Natalie's 35-year-old, 700-pound papa.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, though, Natalie and I dance our skittish pas de
deux.
</P>
<P>
   According to the trainers, we're meant to establish
``relationships'' with the dolphins. ``Training is basically
building trust,'' Komkanski coaches. And like most first dates,
it's taking a while for Natalie and I to get comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   She circles the pool and comes back for another pass at the
tandem swim. Komkanski beckons me into position and I grasp her fin
again. ``She's just learning to do this, so you're actually helping
us train her,'' he continues in his rah-rah, howdy-campers tone.
``And remember, we don't make the dolphins do anything they don't
want to, so if she's here with you, it means she wants to be.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm skeptical: If I were a dolphin, would I rather be toting
around a pasty guy in a too-tight wet suit vest, or hanging with
the other dolphins, munching on herring?
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Komkanski's pep talk gives me a little more
confidence as I take hold. This trip goes better _ Natalie makes a
beeline for Nelson and I manage to hang on for nearly two-thirds of
the way.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson throws her a few finger-size fish and she wiggles away.
Our brief encounter at an end, I paddle over to attempt to build a
relationship with Capricorn, a veteran of countless Sea World
shows.
</P>
<P>
   He waits with the imperturbability of an old war horse as I grab
his tattered dorsal fin and pectoral flipper. A few quick pumps of
his massive tail and we're at the shore. Exhilarated, I disengage
and he swims off to claim his herring bounty. Godspeed, soldier.
</P>
<P>
   As I slosh onto the shore, still giddy from my aquatic
communion, a question lingers. How do the dolphins feel? Is this
just a one-sided romance?
</P>
<P>
   That's open to debate. Many animal rights advocates maintain
that dolphins suffer in such programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're opposed to dolphin captivity in general,'' says Lisa
Lange, a spokeswoman for the People for the Ethical Treatment of
Animals. ``And swim-with programs are the worst, because not only
are these intelligent, sensitive animals confined to what to them
is the equivalent of a bathtub, but they have to lug lazy tourists
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Discovery Cove officials assert that the animals benefit from
the stimulation of human contact. And besides, counters former
trainer Julie Scardina, ``there's no dolphin environment today
that's not affected by man. There's habitat destruction, pollution,
hunting, overfishing of their resources, all kinds of dangers. I'd
rather take care of the animals and know that they have a great,
safe place to live.'' (Scardina, who acts as ``animal ambassador''
for Sea World and Discovery Cove, takes critters on public
appearances, including occasional spots on ``The Tonight Show With
Jay Leno.'')
</P>
<P>
   As for this lazy tourist, I believe that no dolphins were harmed
during the researching of this story. And I'm grateful for their
time and patience. I can now say that I've connected, lips to
rostrum, hand to fin, with some of the Earth's most accommodating
creatures.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and a special thanks to Natalie, who really knows how to
give a guy a lift.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Nonstop Orlando flights are $81 each way on
AirTran or Delta with a 14-day advance purchase.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Discovery Cove information: Opens Saturday. Hours are 9 a.m.
to 5 p.m. daily, year-round. Admission of $179 includes dolphin
swim; access to all swim and snorkeling areas; a buffet-style meal
(snacks and beverages are also for sale); use of mask, snorkel,
swim vest, towel and locker; parking; and passes to Sea World
Orlando, to be used within one week. $89 includes everything but
dolphin swim. Participants in the dolphin swim must be at least 6
and may not wear jewelry. Reservations required. Call
1-877-434-7268 or visit www.discoverycove.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What to bring: Guests should supply their own swimsuits, pool
shoes and hats. Only the park's animal-safe sunscreen may be used;
free samples are provided upon arrival, additional quantities are
on sale at the gift shop. No outside food, beverages or coolers are
permitted.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Accommodations: Orlando has hundreds of hotels ranging from
budget motor lodges to world-class resorts. For information on
where to stay, call the Orlando Vistors Center at 407-363-5872 or
visit www.Go2Orlando.com.
</P>
<P>
   The Renaissance Orlando Resort at Sea World is offering a
Discovery Cove Adventure Travel package, which includes two nights
of accommodations, one dolphin-swim pass and one non-dolphin-swim
pass to Discovery Cove and two passes to Sea World. The package is
$555 per person, based on double occupancy, and is good from June
through December. 1-877-846-3555 or www.renaissancehotels.com.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
