<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3259 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-DEATH-PENALTY-FEDERAL     06-23 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-PENALTY-FEDERAL-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS MURDER CASE MAY PUT DEATH PENALTY SPOTLIGHT ON CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Texas, Iowa, S.C., Md., Pa., Ala., Mo., Va., Okla.,
Ind., Calif., Wis.)   By RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the nation's attention drawn to recent
executions, the focus has been largely on the states, primarily
Illinois, whose governor has declared a moratorium, and Texas,
which puts more men and women to death than most countries and
whose governor, of course, is running for president.
</P>
<P>
   This has allowed the Clinton administration to remain largely
above the fray because there has not been a federal execution in
nearly 40 years. Although Vice President Al Gore favors the death
penalty, he has not faced the tough questioning that Gov. George W.
Bush has, and Gore has said little other than that he does not see
the need for a federal moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   But the case of a condemned migrant worker may soon call
attention to the federal capital punishment system.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Raul Garza, a migrant farm worker and high school dropout
who was convicted seven years ago of marijuana smuggling and three
drug-related murders in Brownsville, Texas, is scheduled to be
executed on Aug. 5. It would be the first federal execution since
John F. Kennedy was president, when a man was put to death by
hanging in Iowa, for kidnapping and murder.
</P>
<P>
   The Garza case raises broad, and for many, troubling issues
about the application of the federal death penalty, most
specifically, whether race and geography determine who is sentenced
to die at the hands of the U.S. government. Seventeen of the 21
federal death row inmates are minorities, and federal prosecutors
in a dozen Southern states account for more than half of the
federal cases in which the death penalty is sought.
</P>
<P>
   Garza's lawyers have exhausted legal appeals, and are turning to
the court of public opinion and politics. They have enlisted the
American Bar Association, which in a highly unusual move last
month, called on President Clinton to declare a moratorium on
federal executions.
</P>
<P>
   Garza wants to ask the president for clemency. But his lawyers
said they are facing some formidable handicaps.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, there are no guidelines for filing a clemency
petition in a federal capital case.
</P>
<P>
   The president's power to grant clemency, be it reprieve,
commutation or pardon, is found in Article II of the Constitution.
It cannot be limited by Congress or the courts, which means the
president can grant clemency whenever he thinks the sentence is
unjust, mercy dictates or in the name of the public tranquility.
</P>
<P>
   The first step in the process is for the prisoner to file a
request with the pardon attorney of the Justice Department, who
then makes a recommendation to the president. That office has
adopted regulations and forms for inmates to use, but these apply
to noncapital cases.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said in February that the department was drafting
regulations for capital cases; a department official said Friday
that they were not yet finished. Garza's lawyers are waiting for
these in order to avoid filing a petition that is thrown out for
failing to follow procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really between a rock and a hard place,'' said Gregory
Wiercioch, a lawyer with the Texas Defender Service, who has been
representing Garza in his appeals. ``A lot of the information we
want to put in the petition, we don't have. It's in the hands of
the government.''
</P>
<P>
   This includes a study on whether race is a factor in applying
the death penalty in federal cases. The Justice Department has
turned down Garza's request for the study or the raw data that the
department has gathered. A department spokesman said the study has
not been completed and the data would not be made public.
</P>
<P>
   Garza's lawyers have also requested information on how the the
Justice Department has handled other capital cases. There are a
dozen cases like Garza's _ multiple drug-related murders _ in which
federal prosecutors did not seek the death penalty, including six
in New York, Wiercioch said. He wants to know why the death penalty
was sought in Garza's case and believes that race was a factor. Of
the 27 defendants against whom the Bush administration sought the
death penalty for drug-related killings, including Garza, 23 were
African-American or Hispanic, Wiercioch said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, when Congress was considering sweeping death penalty
legislation, Attorney General Janet Reno said in a letter to a
congressman who opposed the death penalty that the department was
developing procedures that would allow for the disclosure of its
capital prosecution decisions ``so that the public can review and
understand the basis for such decisions.'' A Justice Department
official said this week that the procedures have not yet been
adopted.
</P>
<P>
   After the Supreme Court declared in 1972 that the death penalty,
as it was then being applied, was unconstitutional, states quickly
adopted laws that the court upheld. But Congress spent the next 16
years struggling to find a way around the court's concerns. In
1988, Congress adopted what has become known as the ``drug kingpin
statute,'' which allows for the death penalty against an individual
who commits murder as part of a larger drug enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, in 1994, Congress enacted the Federal Death
Penalty Act, which expanded the crimes for which a defendant could
be executed. They include the assassination of the president,
large-scale drug trafficking even when no one is killed, drive-by
killings, sexual abuse resulting in death and destruction of a
plane, train or motor vehicle resulting in death.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law requires the appointment of two lawyers for an
indigent defendant facing the death penalty, at least one of whom
must be experienced in capital cases. As a result, claims of
ineffective assistance of counsel do not mark the federal system,
as they do many states, such as Texas, where defendants have been
represented by lawyers who have slept through trials, or have
otherwise displayed gross incompetence.
</P>
<P>
   The principal concerns about the federal death penalty are
whether it is being applied fairly and uniformly.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Since 1988, the Justice Department has allowed the death penalty
to be sought against 199 defendants, according to the Federal Death
Penalty Resource Counsel in Columbia, S.C. Seventy-six percent of
those defendants are minorities, and 52 percent are
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 21 federal inmates currently on death row _ including
Timothy McVeigh, who was convicted in the Oklahoma City bombings _
about 62 percent, or 13 are African-Americans. This is a greater
percentage of blacks on death row than in all but four states:
Maryland, Louisiana, Illinois and Pennsylvania. In Texas, by
contrast, 41 percent of the death row population is black, and in
Alabama, 46 percent, according to the Death Penalty Information
Center, a private organization in Washington that opposes the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``If some back county in the South had the same kind of numbers,
the Department of Justice would be down here investigating, handing
out indictments,'' Wiercioch said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
