<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN0624-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Odds for Elian to stay slim
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The likelihood of Elian Gonzalez' return to his Cuban
homeland increased substantially Friday when the federal appeals
court in Atlanta declined to reconsider the international custody
battle.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-year-old boy's Miami relatives said they will appeal to
the U.S. Supreme Court, but the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
ruling gives them a tight deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court, in a five-page ruling issued Friday, said all
legal restraints keeping Juan Miguel Gonzalez from taking his son
back to Cuba will be lifted at 4 p.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court said it will not _ with ``NOT'' written in
large, boldfaced letters _ extend the Wednesday deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, a three-judge 11th Circuit panel ruled that
the Immigration and Naturalization Service was within its right to
deny an asylum hearing for the young shipwreck survivor.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's Miami relatives, who want the boy to become a U.S.
citizen, asked the full court to reconsider the panel's decision.
For that to happen, seven of the court's 12 judges must agree.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel is ``grateful'' for the court's ruling and eager to
take his son home, said his Washington lawyer, Gregory Craig.
</P>
<P>
   But Armando Gutierrez, a spokesman for the Miami family, said
they believe ``this historic case'' deserves consideration by the
Supreme Court, and will file an appeal Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're still fighting for what his mother wanted and lost her
life for,'' he said. ``They're not going to give up hope. They hope
he will still be here for the 4th of July celebration.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian's mother and 10 others drowned when their boat sank
fleeing communist Cuba to the United States. Elian was rescued off
the Florida coast Thanksgiving Day.
</P>
<P>
   The odds of the Supreme Court taking Elian's appeal appear slim.
More than 8,000 petitions a year are filed before the court; last
year, it accepted fewer than 100.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the court's nine justices would have to agree to hear
the case. Justice Anthony Kennedy, the member of the Supreme Court
assigned to the 11th Circuit, probably will make the initial
decision on whether the injunction keeping Elian in the United
States should remain in effect.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration lawyers who have followed Elian's case predict such
a ruling is unlikely. ``I'd say the odds of the Supreme Court
taking this case are very low,'' Atlanta lawyer Dale Schwartz said.
``It appears very likely that Juan Miguel will soon be able to take
his son back home.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Atlanta attorney Socheat Chea: ``I think the decision by
the panel pretty much sealed the fate of Elian's return to Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian has been staying with his father, stepmother and his
half-brother in the Washington area since April, awaiting the
resolution of the legal maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
