A3261 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-NAMIBIA25-COX     06-23 0391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAMIBIA25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Footprints in the sand: Uncovering the mystery of Namibia
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 25.
 &HT;    By Keith Hadley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Namibia is a vast country of bounteous beauty and abundant
sunshine on the southwest coast of Africa. It takes its name from
the Namib Desert, a place of haunting landscapes that runs the
entire length of Namibia's South Atlantic coast. Here, the
apricot-colored dunes are said to be among the largest on earth.
</P>
<P>
   The Namib is where ``the desert kisses the sea,'' says Atlanta
Journal-Constitution photographer Keith Hadley, 43, who recently
visited and profusely photographed Namibia.
</P>
<P>
   With his wife, Charmaine (making tracks in the sand in his photo
at right), Hadley toured with a group of 14 other African-Americans
who live all over the country, from Alabama to California. None had
ever visited Namibia.
</P>
<P>
   Hadley did advance research, but because Namibia is just
developing as a tourist destination, he felt he would be
``discovering a mysterious, uncharted territory.''
</P>
<P>
   With his camera, he did.
</P>
<P>
   Namibia was annexed by Germany in 1885 and administered by South
Africa until gaining its independence in 1990. It's one of the
larger countries in Africa, yet with a population density among the
world's lowest (1.6 million people occupying 318,216 square miles).
The openness, accentuated by wide horizons and clear skies, made
for some wonderful photo opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Hadley describes his trip as ``a humbling experience'' that had
him thinking of forebears who were forced from Africa as slaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many African-Americans want to go back to the motherland as a
`Roots' thing,'' says Hadley, who visited Africa for the first time
three years ago, satisfying a longtime ``burning desire,'' and has
returned every year since. ``They left in shackles, and here we
were coming back as editors and doctors and lawyers. We felt
fortunate, because when you go back, there are millions of people
who have struggled because of what colonialism has done to the
continent.''
</P>
<P>
   As for photographing in Namibia, Hadley says, ``The only real
challenge I experienced was keeping sand out of my camera.''
</P>
<P>
   Keith Hadley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 2022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
