<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3265 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-GEHRY-MUSICPROJECT25-     06-23 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEHRY-MUSICPROJECT25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Part theme park, part museum, hip architect Frank Gehry's paean
to rock 'n' roll erupts in funky, colorful chaos
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 25
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Architecture is ordinarily a noun. Applied to Frank
Gehry's mind-bending design for the Experience Music Project, it is
definitely a verb. The exterior of the interactive rock 'n' roll
museum, which opened this weekend, bulges, arches, flares, ripples,
crumples, careens and caroms.
</P>
<P>
   The 140,000-square-foot metal-skinned building appears to be in
a state of becoming. It has no definite front, back or sides, no
distinction between wall and roof. Its six interlocking, amoeboid
forms reveal no straight lines, and there are no words with which
to name its shapes.
</P>
<P>
   No shrinking violet, the EMP actually blazes with color _
fire-engine red, baby blue, purple haze, chrome and bronze.
</P>
<P>
   This architecture is imaginative. Dynamic. Forceful. But not
beautiful. While they have their lyrical moments, the individual
shapes are more often ungainly. The baby blue hits the wrong note.
The strips of blue and green glass that snake along the roof are
gratuitous. The 206-feet-long behemoth is, well, weird.
</P>
<P>
   Its site _ at the edge of the Seattle Center, the grounds of the
1962 World's Fair _ doesn't help. The EMP is parked at the foot of
the Jetson-esque Space Needle, across the street from the squat
Polly Esther nightclub and in front of the Fun Forest, the kiddie
amusement park whose garish colors and swooping forms might have
been an inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   So, you were expecting another Bilbao? Gehry's transcendently
elegant Guggenheim Museum, which hugs the Nervion River in the
Basque region of Spain, is, you will recall, widely considered one
of the most original buildings of the 20th century. It catapulted
the California architect to the top of his profession.
</P>
<P>
   But then, this istemplation. The Experience Music Project is a
valentine to musical creativity that delights in overstimulation.
With the city's monorail zipping between two of the forms and a
motion-simulated ride one of the exhibits inside, it's closer to a
theme park than a museum.
</P>
<P>
   For this project, Gehry, seems to favor exuberance over
aesthetic finesse, a strategy that works to a point. Brash and
confrontational, the $100 million structure captures the spirit of
its subject. Seattle critic John Pastier aptly describes it as ``an
improvisatory riff frozen in midnote.''
</P>
<P>
   Gehry, 71, is a classical music fan. Patrons Paul G. Allen,
Microsoft mogul and Jimi Hendrix fan, and his sister, Jody Allen
Patton, chose him to design their museum because his relationship
to his own profession mirrors that of rock innovators. Today's
``it'' arcaces, his presence is there. The exterior colors and
materials and jutting shapes find their way inside, even into the
exhibit design, revving up an already high-key experience even
more.
</P>
<P>
   Like it or hate it, one thing is undeniable. The Experience
Music Project is always the Experience Architecture Project as
well.
</P>
<P>
   The Experience Music Project
</P>
<P>
   9 a.m.-11 p.m. daily. Seattle Center, Fifth Avenue North and
Broad Street, Seattle. $14.95-$19.95. Tickets available through
Ticketmaster. 206-770-2700.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Not famed architect Frank Gehry's most successful
effort but an imaginative homage to the rambunctious spirit of rock
'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : A virtual visit of the museum :
www.emplive.com
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Fox writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
