<SLUG> BC-SELF-TANNER25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Made in the shade: Get golden with self-tanners
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 25
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you want to practice ``safe sun,'' make certain your tan
comes out of a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the telltale orangy streaks of self-tanners in the past,
today's sunless products are effective, fast and a smart way to
achieve a natural-looking faux glow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We highly recommend self-tanners to our patients, since they
do not pose any risk to the skin,'' says Dr. Jean Kois, a
dermatologist in the office of Georgia Dermatology Specialists.
</P>
<P>
   Self-tanners, she adds, ``are not absorbed into the skin. The
active ingredient is the chemical DHA (dihydroxyacaetone). It only
binds with the top, dead layers of the skin, causing it to stain
the skin a brownish color.'' The intensity of color depends on the
amount of DHA, usually from 3.5 to about 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, Kois cautions that although self-tanners provide you
with a tan, they do not protect you from the sun. ``You still need
to wear a sunscreen with an SPF of 30,'' she says. Sunless products
are available in sprays and gels, lotions and creams and come in a
wide range of prices. Examples: Avon Sunless Tanning Cream SPF 8
($9.50); Clarins Self Tanning Milk SPF 6 ($23.50); Clinique Face
Quick Bronze Tinted Self-Tanner ($14.50); Estee Lauder's Go Bronze
Tinted Self-Tanner for Body ($25); Hawaiian Tropic Self-Tanning
Foam ($7.99); L'Oreal Suncare Ombrelle Sunless Spray SPF 12
($8.99); Merle Norman's Sun Free Self Tanning Creme ($12.50);
Neutrogena Instant Bronze Tinted Sunless Tanner for the face
($8.45); and Neutrogena Sunless Tanning Foam ($8.45).
</P>
<P>
   Some tanners do contain sunscreens and moisturizers, so read
labels carefully. ``Also, look for tanners that contain alpha
hydroxy acids,'' says Daniel Maes, vice president of research and
development at Estee Lauder. ``Acids like citric acid decrease
skin's pH, so color develops into a very natural-looking brown.''
</P>
<P>
   If you want a faux tan but don't want to bother with the mess,
let a professional do it. Day spas offer this service. Prices are
in the $75 to $85 range. Usually included in the price is an
exfoliation treatment as well as application.
</P>
<P>
   For glowing results with self-tanners at home, follow these
suggestions: Choose a shade based on your own skin tone; always
apply tanners to clean skin; rub in the product thoroughly; before
applying a tanner to your face, wash and dry your skin thoroughly;
be patient.
</P>
<P>
   Choose a shade based on your own skin tone. If you have fair
skin, go for a light shade. (You can always reapply for a richer
``tan.'') Medium and dark shades are good for darker complexions
and olive-toned skin.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Always apply tanners to clean skin. Shave your legs and
exfoliate your body with a mild scrub in the shower or tub. Dry off
completely. Most cosmetic companies advise applying a moisturizer
only to joints _ knuckles, ankles, elbows and knees. However, if
you find applying a moisturizer is helpful before putting on a
self-tanner, be sure the moisturizer is well soaked into your skin.
If not, the self-tanner might streak.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rub in the product thoroughly. Use vertical strokes followed
by horizontal ones. This ensures even color and no missed spots.
Work quickly from feet (don't forget between your toes), to legs,
to torso. By doing this, the self-tanner won't collect in creases
across your waist and behind your knees when you bend over, causing
darker stripes. Do joints last. Ask a friend or spouse to do your
back. Apply self-tanner to back of hands, then immediately wash
palms with soap and water.
</P>
<P>
   Let your body dry for 20-30 minutes. Hint: Wear dark underwear
and loose clothing for several hours after application. And, if you
apply at night, be sure and sleep on old sheets. Some color will
come off.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Before applying a tanner to your face, wash and dry your skin
thoroughly, then mist on a toner. Coat your eyebrows with petroleum
jelly and spread a small amount around your hairline to prevent
discoloration. Then put on a shower cap. Use a tanner sparingly
around the lip and chin area, since it tends to ``grab'' these
areas. Note: Many companies have self-tanners specifically for the
face.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Be patient. Tans start to develop in one to two hours and
usually are fully developed by four hours but each person's body
chemistry is different.
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johnson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
