A3267 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-STYLE-HANKIES25-COX     06-23 0231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-HANKIES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Handkerchief print fashionable again
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Alma E. Hill
</P>
<P>
   c. 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Handkerchiefs are fashionable again, but these days stylish
women are wearing them on their back, not tucking them into their
sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   That's because hanky-inspired prints and designs are cropping up
everywhere, in halter tops, pants, blouses and dresses. The
V-shaped handkerchief hemline is even making a comeback for flirt
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of the new trend of feminine dressing. Designers
have replaced grunge and androgyny with soft, flowing fabrics,
body-flattering styles and dainty print designs that say, ``I am
woman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Women want to look like women, feminine, pretty and sexy,''
says LeeAnne Swor, owner of L'Asia a women's boutique in Buckhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're buying prints and anything bright-colored. The
handkerchief print is just fun. It's kind of an alternative to
paisley.''
</P>
<P>
   Handkerchief designs are nothing to thumb your nose at. The
print is versatile enough for work or play, subtle enough for curvy
or svelte figures and popular enough to find in a wide range of
stores and prices.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, a lady should always own at least one hanky.
</P>
<P>
   Alma E. Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
