<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0363 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3271 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-HOWARD-FINSTER25-COX     06-23 2655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOWARD-FINSTER25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Howard Finster: Ready for heaven
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday June 25.
 &HT;    By Howard Pousner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUMMERVILLE, Ga. _ Word was out that the Rev. Howard Finster,
the godfather of saving souls, the hardest-working man in the folk
art business, had been seriously sick.
</P>
<P>
   So the faithful flocked to Paradise Garden, his wild 3-acre folk
version of the Garden of Eden, during last month's Howard Finster
Fest, a show and sale that offered a thoroughly mixed bag of 60
artists but only one Howard. With the ailing 83-year-old creator
recovering from double pneumonia and congestive heart failure and
battling diabetes, many visitors worried it might be the last
chance to see Finster, get his autograph, hear one of his classic
sermonettes. And, some feared, it might be the final opportunity to
visit Paradise.
</P>
<P>
   Finster, appearing frail, a tad hunched over and shrinking in a
too-big suit, makes no bones that he's ``fixing to leave this here
world.'' But if he's heaven-bound soon, he's also interested in
taking along some lost sheep.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I'll tell you, find out some of the real facts
before you meet God,'' the pontiff of Paradise preached into a
video camera while sitting on an elevated porch in the back of the
garden in northwest Georgia. Blissfully oblivious to the nearly 100
pilgrims waiting in line at his feet, many holding his posters and
T-shirts and the album covers he designed for R.E.M. and Talking
Heads, Finster was just starting to build up a head of steam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesus told me. ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Before he lifted off on flames of fire and brimstone, however,
granddaughter Heather Brown tried to yank him back to earth,
imploring, ``Paw-Paw, the people are wrapped around this building
waiting for you!''
</P>
<P>
   Atlantan Mike Hunter decided to forgo the line and instead poke
around Finster's art environment, which he had not visited since
the early '90s. He had no idea of the disappointment in store.
</P>
<P>
   Many consider Paradise Garden Finster's defining achievement, a
Noah's Ark of stuff that the preacher and repair-shop tinkerer
spent decades assembling on reclaimed swampland, showcasing the
inventions of mankind. Creating Paradise was major in his
progression into a full-time sacred artist, with more potential
converts showing up to tour it than he ever saw on a Sunday at any
of the small-town churches where he led prayer.
</P>
<P>
   But today, it's Paradise, a shadow of its former glory, that
needs saving.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the tower of bicycle parts, the pump house of Coke
bottles, the broken-down white Caddy that Finster turned into a
canvas of famous faces, the tomb of an unknown citizen and
countless more oddities are still here. But hundreds of items the
quarreling Finster family sold off in the mid-'90s, and which now
are included in the High Museum of Art and private collections, are
long gone _ including the stretch of sidewalk where Finster
embedded his bicycle and lawn mower repair tools when he turned
totally to art making, as well as entire structures such as the
Bible House. And most of what remains is fading fast or rusting
away.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter was struck by the garden's relative sparseness _ which
seemed dead wrong for a place once renowned for its utter
filled-beyond-the-brim-ness. ``I have great memories of visiting
when I was younger,'' the 37-year-old graphic designer says. ``It
was all overgrown, had kudzu trails you would kind of follow and
come out upon the bicycle-part monolith or other surprising things.
It's nothing like it used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet perhaps the biggest surprise in the garden is in the retail
shop at its entrance. Here, where the toll-free line, 1-800-FINSTER
(346-7837), rings and rings, prices for Finster's work have doubled
or more. And ``re-creations'' of his popular small painted wooden
cutout figures by daughter Beverly _ including historical and pop
figures like Cleopatra and Elvis and a menagerie of animals _ have
begun to line the shelves.
</P>
<P>
   The inflated prices and imitations (family members have long cut
out Finster's forms and painted in a background color or two, but
never been allowed to do full-fledged copies) are the result of his
diminished output since he was laid low following a March speaking
engagement at New York's Museum of American Folk Art. Known for
cranking out some 30 works per week, and 46,000-plus since 1976,
Finster wasn't able to turn out anything for more than a month.
Recently, the self-proclaimed Man of Visions has managed an average
of half a dozen a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel worthy to be doing God's work,'' Beverly Finster,
44, a schoolteacher turned businesswoman who has managed her
father's art since 1994, says of the re-creations, which both she
and Finster sign. ``But what can I do? We want his work to go on.
We want his message to go on. I feel it's part of my calling.''
</P>
<P>
   At one time or another, at least three other Finster kin, Howard
Finster's son Roy Finster and grandsons Michael Finster and Allen
Wilson, felt that calling. But none has been actively involved in
the garden in years, not after Beverly borrowed $125,000 and bought
out her four siblings. That was, she says, after someone threatened
to burn the place down if her dad deeded it to her.
</P>
<P>
   `I thought it'd go on forever'
</P>
<P>
   For a poor soul who thought he was ``ready to go to the heavenly
land'' but a few weeks before, Howard Finster manages to look
rather sporty one sun-dappled afternoon a few days before Finster
Fest. Greeting visitors in the studio wing of his rambling white
brick house on a leafy downtown Summerville avenue, he's decked out
in royal blue slacks, a madras shirt and a gold sport coat.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Finster, a curious mix of Billy Graham and P.T.
Barnum, has always loved playing to a camera. He's wise enough to
know that there's no such thing as bad ink or video footage when
you're spreading God's glory.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at his work table _ which is crowded with a Coca-Cola
bottle cutout he's beginning to paint, brushes soaking in mineral
spirits, open paint cans caked with thick skins of enamel, and gobs
of glitter _ he's not shy about telling a photographer what to
shoot. And when the camera's going, count on him clutching one of
his creations to make sure it's in the frame. ``Get a picture of
that,'' he says, pointing a liver-spotted hand at a lithograph of
his rendition of the Last Supper, ``and you might be able to sell
it for $10,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for a frequent cough and the presence of the cane he
holds close, it's easy to forget that Finster has been in the
hospital three times in recent weeks. ``The doctor said it'd take a
long time to get it all coughed out. The flame comes out like
glue,'' he says, mispronouncing ``phlegm.''
</P>
<P>
   Physical ailments seem a mere inconvenience, keeping him from
doing his _ make that the Lord's _ folk art. ``I can't keep my art
around,'' he laments. ``They need two truckloads (at Paradise
Garden's shop) right now for people to pick through. I've got so
many things I could do if I was back to my regular strength.''
</P>
<P>
   During all the years he built up Paradise Garden, Finster
expected it to survive him. But now he's not sure it will. It's
been at least a decade since he was strong enough to tend the
garden and add to its inventory of discarded treasures. Since he
and Pauline, his wife of 67 years, moved from the garden to the
``executive branch'' side of town, seeking peace from family
discord and the steady stream of visitors, Finster has for the most
part limited his appearances to Sunday afternoon cameos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like for Paradise Garden to live on so that people can
enjoy it,'' he says. ``But visitors have sorrow in the heart when
they see it going down. It's a hard thing to bear. Never did I
think that I'd need more money (to maintain it). I thought it'd go
on forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The subject of money is a sore one. He says that in an effort to
keep his children from doing each other or the garden harm over its
ownership, he gave them their inheritance in cash in advance _ a
total of $150,000, he thinks, though his math and memory are
equally fuzzy. ``And they spent that on cars and stuff that ain't
no good _ nothing that makes money. They just throwed it away.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Beverly, who quit her job as a middle school art teacher in
1996 to try to salvage what remained of Paradise, is not exempt.
``I think sometimes she's not cut out for business,'' he says.
``She's a teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Finster asserts she's spent untold thousands on the
garden _ among the big-ticket items, a perimeter fence (vandalism
had long been a problem) and roof repairs to the World's Folk Art
Church, a high-rising, wedding cake-shaped chapel that remains
locked due to structural damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took my daddy 35 years to build this place, and it might
take me 35 years to restore it,'' says Beverly, who runs the
gallery as a for-profit business but incorporated the garden as a
nonprofit, charging an admission earmarked for upkeep.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Finster says he approves of her re-creations of his
paintings (``as long as she continues to copy the Bible verses''),
but he's got his doubts about whether she truly feels his fervor.
``She goes to church, but I can't say she's ready to go to
heaven,'' he says. ``She needs to work on getting closer to God.''
</P>
<P>
   The artist probably never expressed his misgivings about his
heirs more succinctly than in a 1985 painting titled ``The Super
Powers,'' a Cold War allegory in which rows of people must pass
between two threatening black beasts to enter heaven. Lettered
under cottony clouds with smiling faces, a frequent motif for the
glorious afterlife of saved souls, are ``Finsterisms'' including:
``No drunkards to worry about,'' ``Jesus has it all up here'' and
the stinger, ``No more stupid children to fret over.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some family members are really lucky to have family,''
observes Finster friend Larry Schlachter, a Lookout Mountain art
collector and dealer, ``because no one else would put up with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Selling pieces of Paradise
</P>
<P>
   James Allen, an Atlanta picker _ someone who combs the
countryside for art and other treasures to resell _ received a call
in early 1994 that sent a shiver. The collector on the other end
``told me that he didn't know what was going on but that early
works from Paradise Garden were suddenly showing up in Atlanta for
sale,'' he recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, who had approached Howard Finster many times over the
years only to be rebuffed, sped to Summerville the next day. He was
greeted by Finster's son Roy, who announced that his father was
liquidating some things and the picker could ``go see what I
wanted'' and they could work a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like saying, `The Vatican is open, take what you
want,''' Allen says.
</P>
<P>
   The picker scoured the garden and came up with a list. He made
out a check to Roy and had his van filled when Howard Finster's
grandson Allen Wilson appeared and argued that Roy didn't have the
authority to sell anything.
</P>
<P>
   Not sure who to believe, James Allen drove directly to Howard
Finster's house. ```I told that boy (Roy Finster) not to sell
anything,''' Allen recalls Finster booming. But when the picker
offered to put everything back, Finster insisted that he take it.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next six weeks, Allen returned for larger and larger
items, ultimately requiring a crew and heavy moving equipment. But
then all the dealings were directly with the artist. ``He knew that
things were disappearing. He could sell them or someone else
could,'' recalls Allen, who comforted Finster by telling him he
thought it all would wind up in worthy public and private
collections, preserved for future generations.
</P>
<P>
   And that's what happened: The High Museum of Art secured the
lion's share, including a series of monumental concrete sculptures,
lengths of Finster-poured mosaic sidewalk and small items like
hanging sun catchers that reflected light into some of the garden's
dark corners. Allen kept one work: a simple metal cutout of a star
on a tall pole.
</P>
<P>
   The picker says he didn't feel ambivalent ``for one second''
about his role in partially dismantling Paradise. ``The garden was
so pathetic then. The buildings were starting to rot, and it was
grown over and returning to a swamp. To think of all the money
that's gone to the family, and none of it's been put back in.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he knew Finster felt all right about the arrangement the
day he invited the artist to come watch the crew remove the
concrete sculpture ``The Calves and the Young Lion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When the front end loader was lifting it from where it had
been (since 1967), pulling it away from the weeds and the muck and
the clutter, Howard just let out a squeal and yelled, `Look at how
beautiful that is!'''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Calves and the Young Lion'' is a highlight of the High's
special Finster gallery, shown with some 35 other objects amid the
museum's permanent collection. It's an unusual space _ a sprawling
chunk of northwest Georgia wooliness plopped among pristine pieces
such as a Henry Moore sculpture. Behind ``The Calves and the Young
Lion'' and two other potent large-scale concrete creations hang
billboard-size black-and-white enlargements showing the works as
they appeared in Paradise Garden _ in better days. But there are
also classic Finster peculiarities such as a small display pairing
sci-fi-looking dental molds and, inexplicably, some Mount St.
Helens volcano dust.
</P>
<P>
   The High claims the installation is the first attempt anywhere
to conserve and display a large-scale outdoor folk environment in a
museum setting.
</P>
<P>
   James Allen estimates that at least $200,000 worth of
collectible pieces remain in Paradise Garden, should Beverly
Finster change her mind and decide to sell any. But while High folk
art curator Lynne Spriggs says she'd like to add more paintings
from Finster's brilliantly inventive early years, she is not eyeing
anything in the garden, which she visited a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned about Finster's condition, she returned with an even
fuller respect for his passion, industry and fortitude. ``When he
started creating sacred art, he went at it with such a sense of
zeal,'' she says. ``He's lived a lot of life hard and fast. He's
put a remarkable amount of energy out in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   On his `last bit of suffering'
</P>
<P>
   On the day his visitors arrive with camera and notebook in hand,
Finster clearly isn't feeling the spark. After recording the Coke
bottle cutout as his 46,397th work in a spiral notebook _
containing page after page of nothing but creakily scrawled numbers
_ he suggests adjourning to the back yard.
</P>
<P>
   He steps unsteadily with his cane back to the plastic lawn
chairs under a couple of maple trees, the uncompleted Coke cutout
dangling from his hand _ just in case there's a photo op.
</P>
<P>
   The swimming pool in the far back, where young Finsters once
cavorted, has been filled up and appears forlorn. Finster says he
closed it to keep youngsters from drowning. Lord knows his kids
have produced a passel: 15 grandchildren, 20 great-grandchildren
and two great-great-grand-
</P>
<P>
   children.
</P>
<P>
   The hush of the late afternoon hardly suits him, though, so he
quickly gets to talking about what will happen when he departs this
mortal coil. ``If I fall dead today with a stroke, I won't know
anything about it,'' he says, resolute as ever. ``When the Lord
takes his people, they don't feel suffering. The last breath you
take is your last bit of suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, he's interrupted by a church bell in the distance, tolling
its 4 o'clock call.
</P>
<P>
   ``That church bell brings me comfort,'' Finster allows, before
adding what may be the greatest understatement in the twisty
history of folk art: ``You know, I used to be a preacher.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Pousner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
