<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3272 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-GLOBE-FREELANCERS-BOS     06-23 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBE-FREELANCERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE TO RULE SOON ON CHALLENGE TO GLOBE'S TERMS FOR FREELANCERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After hearing the opening skirmish in the battle
between The Boston Globe and its freelance contributors Friday,
Suffolk County Superior Court Judge Carol S. Ball said she would
rule by Monday on whether to prevent the paper from enforcing a
July 1 deadline for a new ``license agreement'' with freelancers.
</P>
<P>
   That agreement allows freelancers to retain their copyrights but
gives the Globe the right to reproduce their past and future work
in other forms, including online, without additional compensation.
On June 12, a group of freelancers filed a lawsuit, claiming those
terms constitute ``unfair and deceptive trade practices.''
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 750 Globe freelancers face a July 1 deadline to either
sign the deal or stop working for the paper. (Globe spokesman
Richard Gulla said almost 340 contributers have signed to date.)
Friday's hearing was on the plaintiffs' request for an injunction
to set aside that deadline and to prohibit the paper from enforcing
the agreement with those who have signed.
</P>
<P>
   Calling that proposal ``unfair and unconscionable,'' plaintiffs'
attorney Indira Talwani argued that the Globe ``can't say to our
folks, `if you don't sign this unfair contract, we won't even look
at your work.'. . . The threat is that if you do not sign what is
an unfair agreement, we will cease doing business with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Globe attorney William Berkowitz countered that the paper ``is
free to set the terms under which it will do business.'' And while
he characterized the Globe proposal as ``actually more favorable
than those used'' by many other papers, he said the ``mere offer of
a contract that they think is unreasonable'' does not violate the
law.
</P>
<P>
   When Talwani stated that the Globe had issued a ``sign it by
July 1 or you're out'' ultimatum to freelancers, Berkowitz said
contributors who sign later could reestablish a relationship with
the paper.
</P>
<P>
   Ball at one point told Talwaini that ``in fairness, you've got a
tough row to hoe on this one.'' In an interview after the hearing,
Talwani said she was not concerned by the judge's statement,
adding, ``I think she will find it's a novel case, but it's based
on traditional concepts (of) unfairness.''
</P>
<P>
   While declining to read anything into Ball's caution to the
plaintiffs, Berkowitz said the Globe has the ``unfettered right to
say `these are the terms under which we will do business with you.'
''
</P>
<P>
   In one ironic touch, Judge Paul A. Chernoff, who was slated to
hear Friday's arguments, reportedly recused himself because he had
written a piece for the Globe, becoming, as Ball joked, ``a
potential member of the plaintiffs' class.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 2025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
