<HEADER>
A3274 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-NATIELLO-FASHIONS-ART     06-23 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIELLO-FASHIONS-ART-$ADV25-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RETURN OF THE WALKER AND THE LADYLIKE LOOK OF NATIELLO 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 25) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By RUTH LA FERLA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last week at Saks Fifth Avenue, Craig Natiello, who
designs for the Halston label, was showing his fall collection to a
circle of his faithful _ young society figures, including Tara
Rockefeller and Somers White. He paused to note that most truly
chic women know how to dramatize their assets. To reinforce the
point, he pulled back his hair, tilted his chin skyward and pursed
his lips in a dowager pout, the image of Diana Vreeland.
</P>
<P>
   Natiello's talent for impersonation has served him well. For a
decade, he worked for Bill Blass, rising to the position of senior
designer. He cultivated Blass' deft way with a pair of shears, his
polished manner and, not least, his personal touch with well-bred
clients.
</P>
<P>
   Bent on entertaining young plutocrats like Nathalie
Gerschel-Kaplan, Marina Rust, Jennifer Creel and Brooke de Ocampo
in what he considered the Blass tradition, Natiello draped them,
regaled them with gossip and squired them to as many dinners and
galas as his calendar would hold.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, he parlayed his creative talent and position as
smooth-talking escort to the young East Side crowd into a coveted
appointment as chief designer for Halston, a post some people think
will seal his status as designer of the hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of good buzz about him _ he's the next big
thing,'' said Cristina Greeven, the publisher and editor of
Manhattan File, a magazine that chronicles the doings of young
celebrities and socialites. Comparing him to competitors like
Michael Kors, another designer with an upper-crust following, she
added, ``Craig is in that phase of carving out a niche in which
social connections are superimportant.''
</P>
<P>
   Natiello has invoked a tradition that dates to the days of
Mainbocher, couturier to the Duchess of Windsor, and recalls
legendary fashion partnerships like those of Jacqueline Kennedy and
Oleg Cassini, Audrey Hepburn and Hubert de Givenchy, Blass and Babe
Paley. It is a specialty role in the world of fashion, to be sure.
Most successful designers _ Tom Ford of Gucci, Ralph Lauren, Tommy
Hilfiger _ did not get that way by cultivating a social elite
little known to the world. They did it by marketing. When they do
forge a bond with a customer, it is likely to be a rock star or
Oscar nominee, who will parade their wares before the world.
</P>
<P>
   But Natiello arrives at a time when Park Avenue chic is stronger
than it has been in a generation _ when ``ladylike'' dressing has
been decreed the freshest thing and women under 35 are reviving
society weddings, balls and other rituals long thought irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you could say we grew up together,'' Natiello said of
his friendships with de Ocampo, Rust, Kim Hersov and Lillian Wang
von Stauffenberg, all of whom he met while he worked for Blass and
they toiled as junior editors at Elle and Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   His bonds with junior society, in fact, are what gave him the
edge over other candidates when the owners of Halston parted with
the label's previous designer, Kevan Hall, and looked for a
replacement. ``We hired Craig not only because of his talent but
because of his knowledge of the couture customer,'' said Nicholas
J. DeMarco, Halston's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Natiello's connections are an asset for a company intent on
resurrecting Halston as a luxury brand and purveyor of simple but
glamorous evening wear and, beginning next spring, of high-end
daytime clothes, men's clothing and accessories.
</P>
<P>
   At a dinner Natiello gave last week at Swifty's, the gathering
place of the former Mortimer's crowd, Laura Henson, the label's
public relations director, was quick to take up the company line.
Looking around the table crowded with his friends like Andrew and
Jill Roosevelt and James and Whitney Fairchild, she mused: ``What
did they say about Halston? He traveled in the circles of the women
he dressed. Craig is like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Natiello would certainly like you to think so, although he
perhaps overstates his entree into this world. During the American
Fashion Awards this month, he was hardly besieged by air-kissing
society princesses. He and Henson circulated largely alone. Some of
the prominent young women he claims as friends seem to know him
only superficially.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of his Seventh Avenue apprenticeship, the
designer, 38, reinvented himself, in the great American tradition.
The only son of a teacher and a school administrator, he rehearsed
for his chosen part growing up in Hartsdale, N.Y. While majoring in
English at Manhattanville College, he adopted the uniform he wears
to this day _ a slate-colored turtleneck and matching cardigan
coiled around his throat. In his college days, the costume raised
eyebrows. ``I would walk across the quad, and people stared,'' he
recalled. ``Finally, my friend Barbara remarked, `It's a little too
Halston, don't you think?'''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But then, that was the point. With his shoulder-length
hair and butter-cream complexion, Natiello also bears more than a
passing resemblance to some of New York's better-known socialites.
``He worships Jamie Gregory and Joanne de Guardiola,'' said Steven
Stolman, a fashion designer with stores in Easthampton and Palm
Beach, Fla., who travels in the same circles. ``It's gotten to the
point where he even looks like them.''
</P>
<P>
   Stolman added: ``It's all very theatrical, the blond hair
flying, the cashmere sweaters flapping, very dramatic when you see
it coming toward you on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Natiello seems to regard himself as a modern composite of
American tastemakers like Blass, Geoffrey Beene and Halston, of
course. He has the manner down: the jaded air and languid posture,
the insouciant, designer drawl. One difference is that he lacks the
well-known self-irony of his idols. On the sales floor at Saks, he
gestured casually toward a black-beaded, sable-trimmed evening
dress. ``It has a sense of body, of confidence, of youthfulness _
it's all in the cut of the jib, you know,'' he said, reproducing
Blass' inflections with an eerie Tom Ripley fidelity.
</P>
<P>
   If his visitors found the performance affected, they gave no
clue, laughing in response.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, it seems, Natiello can count on their
indulgence. They can count on him to cater to their desire for
self-invention. When many better-established designers have
abandoned private fittings, leaving the pinning and tucking to
assistants, Natiello remains a hands-on designer. Fussing over his
charges like Cedric Hampton, Nancy Mitford's hyper-refined aesthete
in ``Love in a Cold Climate,'' he brings out their inner goddess,
and they respond with gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I walked down the aisle at my wedding, Craig actually
fluffed me,'' trilled Roosevelt, whose wedding dress Natiello
designed last year.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part a group of traditional young women whose
collective motto might be ``Don't make waves,'' Natiello's clients
rely on him to make them look provocative and just this side of
tarty. ``He knows how to push someone's style, maybe make it a
little more sexy,'' said Marin Hopper, Elle's fashion director, who
has watched Natiello do fittings. ``He knows how to show off her
body in the best way.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
