<SLUG> BC-SALVATION-OVERVIEW24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Army's aim: 'Soup, soap, salvation'
 &HT;    By Derrick Henry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Most people know the Salvation Army is in the business
of saving souls. From its earliest days in the late 1800s,
Salvation Army officers have sought out sinners in slums, saloons,
streets and brothels.
</P>
<P>
   But the church's efforts do not stop with salvation. The
organization wages war against hunger, poverty, illness and
homelessness, offering a helping hand to the needy of any race,
religion, creed or circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will help anyone,'' says Cate Cummins, public relations
officer for the Salvation Army's Metro Atlanta Command. ``That's
part of our mission statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Founder William Booth was fond of saying: ``Soup, soap and
salvation _ and never reverse the order.''
</P>
<P>
   The Salvation Army now ranks among the world's largest social
service providers. Last year, it offered services to more than
250,000 people in metro Atlanta and more than 33 million worldwide.
Since 1991, it has ranked as America's most popular charity by far
in terms of private donations, according to the Chronicle of
Philanthropy, a national biweekly newspaper of the nonprofit world.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, private donations amounted to $1.2 billion, more than
twice that received by the second-place charity, the YMCA. The
Metro Atlanta Command runs on an annual budget of $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   It does a lot with the money. Within the 14-county metro Atlanta
region, the Salvation Army operates nine community centers
(including ones focusing on Atlanta's growing Asian and Latino
populations), seven thrift stores, five Boys &AMP; Girls Clubs,
low-income housing for senior citizens and disabled adults, and
transitional housing for single men and women as well as families.
</P>
<P>
   To keep pace with the need, the Metro Atlanta Command is in the
midst of a $36 million capital campaign to renovate and expand 12
existing facilities and build four new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Year-round programs include disaster relief, drug and alcohol
rehabilitation for adults, job training, and tutoring for children
and adults. Its Fresh Start Initiative supplies ``Begin Again
Bags'' with housecleaning supplies and toiletries to disaster
victims or formerly homeless families moving into their own
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous special projects are held throughout the year in metro
Atlanta. In January, the Salvation Army collects and distributes
warm coats and blankets through its Project Overcoat.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer, it runs camps for kids and senior citizens. A
Can-a-Thon food collection drive is held in November. During the
Christmas season, it provides 30,000 children and senior citizens
with gifts through its Angel Tree program. And on Thanksgiving and
Christmas, the Salvation Army serves a community feast to the
hungry and homeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have survived because we are adaptable to the needs of the
times and communities we serve,'' says Wes McKinney, director of
donor services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We adapt to anything.''
</P>
<P>
   AT A GLANCE
</P>
<P>
   Volunteer opportunities: The Salvation Army seeks volunteers in
the areas of disaster relief, tutoring children, and serving the
homeless, senior citizens and disabled. There are opportunities to
teach English as a Second Language, provide computer training for
adults, and offer after-school care at the community centers and
Boys &AMP; Girls Clubs. Throughout the year, help is needed with
special programs such as food and clothing collections. During the
Christmas season, the Salvation Army needs volunteer bell ringers
and people to distribute gifts to children and senior citizens and
to serve holiday meals on Thanksgiving and Christmas. Volunteers of
all ages are welcome; volunteers under 16 must be accompanied by an
adult. For more information, call 404-873-3101.
</P>
<P>
   To donate goods: Call 404-522-9783 to arrange for a pickup of
large bundles of clothing, furniture or heavy appliances. The
Salvation Army also accepts motor vehicles. To drop off donated
goods, check the phone book or Georgia Web site for the thrift
store nearest you.
</P>
<P>
   To donate money: Make out a check to Salvation Army, specify the
county or program you wish to support, if desired, and mail to
Salvation Army, PO Box 8237, Atlanta, GA 31106. To make a credit
card donation, call 404-873-3101.
</P>
<P>
   Web sites: International: www.salvationarmy.org. Georgia:
www.salvationarmy-georgia.org. Derrick Henry writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
