<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-ELECTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIMBABWE OPPOSITION SOLIDLY IN PLACE, OBSERVERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe _ Throughout the campaign for this weekend's
parliamentary elections in Zimbabwe, President Robert Mugabe
repeatedly vowed not only to crush the opposition, but remove it
permanently from the political landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Part bravado, part intimidation _ Mugabe's supporters have
threatened reprisals against villages that vote against the ruling
party _ the boast reflects historical confidence. In the past
decade, as African countries have faced pressure from Western
donors to allow freely contested elections, fledgling opposition
parties have had little success gaining power or surviving defeat
at the ballot box.
</P>
<P>
   But Zimbabwe appears set to break the mold. The Movement for
Democratic Change, which poses the first serious challenge to
Mugabe's party in 20 years, is only nine months old. But unlike
political organizations formed hastily around one person ahead of
elections in countries such as Kenya, Zimbabwe's opposition grew
out of a long consultations among diverse groups tapping broad
popular discontent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the outcome this weekend, political scientists here say,
democratic ideals are flowering and the days of one-party rule in
Zimbabwe are drawing to a close.
</P>
<P>
   ``This party was not formed by a group of people, but was born
out of the trade unions, women's organizations, and other parts of
civil society,'' said Welshman Ncube, an academic recruited by the
opposition. ``The party is not opportunistic, dashing for power. As
long as those organizations survive, the party will survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past four months, Mugabe's techniques to fend off the
electoral challenge has drawn criticism from the likes of South
Africa's Archbishop Desmond Tutu, who called the Zimbabwean
president ``a caricature of an African dictator.'' Mugabe has
encouraged a campaign of violence against his opponents; blamed the
white minority and the former colonial power, Britain, for
sabotaging Zimbabwe's economy; manipulated voting districts and
voters' rolls; and barred some international observer missions;
manipulating the state-run media and harassing the independent
press.
</P>
<P>
   On the final day of campaigning Friday, 14 opposition party
election officials were abducted by pro-government thugs and held
for several hours. Most were released unharmed, but one candidate,
Zachariah Rioga, was still in a coma Friday night being badly
beaten.
</P>
<P>
   Without such violence, violence, said John Makumbe, head of the
political science department at the University of Zimbabwe, ``the
opposition was looking at sweeping the deck.'' Amid soaring
joblessness and rampant corruption, he said, the people's
discontent has never run deeper.
</P>
<P>
   Ncube said the opposition will claim victory if it wins at least
51 seats, the minimum needed to block a two-third majority in the
150-seat parliament. Mugabe's party held all but three seats in the
previous legislature. The opposition's threshold is within reach,
Makumbe said. The party is likely to sweep the urban vote, and even
with the violence, will probably at least dip into Mugabe's
traditional rural base.
</P>
<P>
   The electoral schedule also favors the opposition. Mugabe's
current term ends in 2002, meaning his foes can start building
immediately on whatever momentum they collect this weekend. Ncube
said his party has already started planning for the presidential
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The simplest assurance, however, that Zimbabwe is poised to
break the grip of one-party rule lies in the sheer number of
first-time voters who have risked the violence to help the
opposition build a grass-roots base.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Mugabe's supporters belong to the generation that fought
the bush war to end colonialism. Twenty years on, they still equate
freedom with Mugabe's rule. ``So many people died for Zimbabwe to
be free,'' said Dikwi Cosmas, a veteran of the liberation struggle.
``What did this new party do so the country could be free?''
</P>
<P>
   Emmanuel Chamunorwa, in his 20s, who has volunteered with the
opposition in the townships around Kadoma in central Zimbabwe, has
a ready answer for Cosmas. Independence, he said, wasn't supposed
to replace one form of oppression with another.
</P>
<P>
   ``This government has been around 20 years,'' Chamunorwa said.
``We are working for the black man, but still he's blaming the
white man. Mugabe is cheating black people. The fear is broken.
People are tired.''
</P>
</TEXT>
