<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: KIDNAP VICTIMS FREED
</P>
<P>
   The victims of a pair of politically emblematic kidnappings that
deeply offended the Colombian public were both released. A
right-wing paramilitary group freed Guillermo Valencia, a member of
Congress who is the brother of one of the government's chief
negotiators in peace talks with leftist guerrillas. He was seized
Monday in an effort to torpedo the talks, while a 5-year-old girl
whose parents said she was being held by the country's main
left-wing guerrilla group was released after 70 days in captivity,
but only after a ransom was paid.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA: VOTE SET
</P>
<P>
   The presidential election scheduled for May 28 but postponed
when the National Electoral Council acknowledged that its
vote-counting system was hopelessly flawed has been rescheduled for
July 30. Governors, members of Congress and mayors are to be
elected the same day, but voting for regional and local councils
has been pushed back to Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: PRESIDENT OVERRULED
</P>
<P>
   A labor court ruled to overturn a recent act of President
Fernando de la Rua to cut public service salaries by 12 percent to
15 percent to reduce the deficit and cut interest rates. The ruling
came after recent labor strikes but is expected to be overturned by
higher courts.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND: MAD COW FRAUD
</P>
<P>
   An Irish farmer was sentenced to five years in prison after
pleading guilty to importing a cow with mad cow disease into his
herd in 1996. James Sutton, 49, faced debts of $833,000 and stood
to gain $89,000 from a government compensation program when his
entire herd was destroyed to prevent the spread of the disease.
Later investigations revealed a smuggling operation that brought in
infected cattle from Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: KOHL STILL UNDER FIRE
</P>
<P>
   The governing Social Democrats urged former Chancellor Helmut
Kohl to resign from Parliament a day after he made comments
comparing their recent treatment of him over illegal campaign funds
with Nazi persecution of the Jews. A leading Social Democrat,
Wilhelm Schmidt, said Kohl had become an ``unacceptable liability
for the entire German people.'' Kohl rejected the demand, saying he
``requires no history lessons'' from his political foes.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: TRAVEL BAN
</P>
<P>
   President Abdurrahman Wahid banned travel to the Spice Islands,
where Muslim fighters have been arriving to stoke violence that has
taken thousands of lives. Eighteen more people were reported
killed.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHANISTAN: AID PLEA
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. refugee agency called for more aid for Afghanistan,
warning that drought may force Afghans to flee to Pakistan and
Iran. Afghanistan has been hit by its worst drought in 30 years,
raising the specter of mass starvation, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
   SRI LANKA: TAMIL PLAN
</P>
<P>
   President Chandrika Kumaratunga and the main opposition United
National Party have agreed to form an interim council to administer
Sri Lanka's northeast in an attempt to end Tamil separatist
violence. Tamil Tiger rebels will not be a part of the council
unless they renounce violence, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN WALKOUT
</P>
<P>
   Russia's ambassador, Sergey Lavrov, walked out of the Security
Council after members voted not to allow Yugoslavia's delegate to
speak in a session on the European Union's peace efforts in the
Balkans. Richard Holbrooke, the American delegate, said the vote
was based on President Slobodan Milosevic's refusal to change
Yugoslavia's nomenclature and flag, saying it was unacceptable that
the ``flag of Tito'' still flies on First Avenue.
</P>
</TEXT>
