<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3293 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-NATIELLO-FASHIONS-ART     06-23 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIELLO-FASHIONS-ART-$ADV25-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: best way.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Much as he was doing at Saks the other day. Coaxing White, an
event planner at the Horticultural Society of New York, who was
dressed in a T-shirt, tan trousers and Hermes belt, into a racy
black leather jacket, he said, ``It's a little James Bondish, a
little pickup thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The look is sexy, but never vulgar, that's what I like,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Hopper recalled that Natiello's first job at Blass was in
publicity. ``He was very good at introducing the collection to lots
of young people,'' she said. ``It was very smart. The house needed
a younger spokesperson for the world of American glamour.''
</P>
<P>
   After he began designing, Hopper said, it became clear that he
had ``incorporated a younger look into a classic style.'' The
reaction of fashion editors at the time, she said, was, ``Wow,
Bill's never looked so young.''
</P>
<P>
   The designer's loyalists embrace him as one of their own. ``One
thing that makes him mix and match so easily is that he speaks a
kind of shorthand that everybody gets,'' said Helen Schifter, a
former fashion writer for Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   Last March at the Oscars party at Morton's in Los Angeles,
Schifter watched Natiello scrunch up his face and roll his eyes at
the passing parade of luminaries. She interpreted his gestures as
``a slightly wicked running commentary on everyone else in the
room,'' she said, adding, ``For me, it was the funniest 20 minutes
of the whole evening.''
</P>
<P>
   Natiello doesn't confine his comments to strangers. At Swifty's,
he greeted Mai Harrison, who had wed Ridgely Harrison, the model in
the Jenkins gin advertisements, two weeks earlier at a society
ball.
</P>
<P>
   The designer eyed the nickel-size diamond on her hand.
``Tomorrow she'll fry her coffee on that ring,'' he said, cackling.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, he peered at Fairchild, the daughter-in-law of
John Fairchild, the former Women's Wear Daily publisher. She was
wearing gilded Chanel ear tassels and a feathered muffler, which
tended to obscure her chin.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has oodles of style _ and she's not hesitant about showing
it,'' Natiello said with a mix of tact and cattiness. ``She can
take forever deciding what to wear. Sometimes I think she's all
about getting dressed and getting undressed, and why even go to the
party?''
</P>
<P>
   In Natiello's circle, such barbs might pass for wit. ``When you
go out with Craig, you know you're going to have his lens on
everything,'' Schifter said. ``It's sort of like being with Henry
James. A lot of people are very talented but have no people skills.
I love Marc Jacobs, but Craig is more upbeat in some ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Natiello seems to relish his role as society escort. ``He would
be in the category of a walker,'' Greeven of Manhattan File said.
She put a positive spin on a term for the sometimes foppish men who
accompany wealthy women to parties when their husbands are busy or
bored. ``I wish there were more of his kind,'' Greeven said,
sighing. ``People aren't doing that so much anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   If most young married women who relentlessly go out choose to
arrive with a sister these days or in a group of other women or
simply by themselves, there is also a contingent of under-35s who
are happily updating the walker tradition popularized in the 1980s
by the Nancy Reagan set.
</P>
<P>
   Going out with Natiello is like ``being in junior high school
again,'' said Schifter, whose husband, Timothy Schifter, is
president of LeSportsac, the handbag company. ``You get to gossip
in a friendly way. Which husbands in general are not interested in
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   A wave of younger men recognize that the role of escort _ with
no expectations beyond making smart conversation and being well
groomed _ has its advantages. Being seen at the right party with
the right sort of woman is a professional asset, said Todd Romano,
a New York decorator. It reinforces the perception, he said, that
``this fellow is a player, he's part of the scene.''
</P>
<P>
   It also makes for a very good time. ``I don't look at
socializing with my customer as work _ it's a pleasure,'' said
Stolman, who has dressed and hobnobbed with clients like Betsy
Kaiser, C.Z. Guest and her daughter Cornelia. ``Fashion is one of
the few trades in which you're invited to the dinner table, rather
than kept below the stairs. I think that's why a lot of people
choose to become a fashion designer.''
</P>
<P>
   Like designers of old, Natiello is imperious. He issues edicts.
Lose the bracelet, he once told Roosevelt. ``And I did,'' she
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one under 25 should wear my clothing,'' he says haughtily.
``You can't wear these things until you're 30. You don't have a
sense of yourself until you're 30.''
</P>
<P>
   Natiello's new employers are hoping that the authoritative air,
along with a commercial sense he gained at Blass, will finally
bring profitability to Halston, a famous name that has been in
chaos under four owners in the last six years.
</P>
<P>
   The latest proprietor of the label founded by Roy Halston
Frowick is Neema Clothing Ltd., primarily a maker of men's wear.
</P>
<P>
   As Natiello tells it, some months before Blass announced his
retirement last year, he took his assistant aside and told him
Halston was searching for a new designer. Blass wrote a letter
recommending Natiello to Halston's chief executive, DeMarco, who
confirmed this account.
</P>
<P>
   Why would Natiello jump to an extremely shaky label when he
might have expected to inherit the top job at Blass? ``It was the
moment to come out from under the mantle,'' Natiello explained.
``When I was ready to leave, it was Bill who told me, `Put your own
stamp on it.' And at Halston I can. This is my own gig.''
</P>
<P>
   He dreams of rebuilding Halston into the luxury brand it was but
has not been for years. ``This is the only fashion house in America
that can actually be Gucci-ized,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He fantasizes about dressing even more of the understated
fashion icons of his day. At his showroom on Seventh Avenue last
week, Natiello said: ``You know who's so good at that throwaway
thing is Nina Griscom. She has that Babe Paley thing. She always
looks like she just came out of the pool, put on that great dress
and looks fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   Is Griscom a client? Natiello flipped back his hair. ``No,'' he
replied with a level stare. ``Not yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
