<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT CLEARS WAY FOR ELIAN TO RETURN TO CUBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Reorganizes and rewrites completely. Note new byline.)  
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A federal appeals court in Atlanta has refused to
reconsider the case of Elian Gonzalez, leaving the U.S. Supreme
Court as a last hope for the Miami relatives who want to prevent
his return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the nation's highest court intervenes, a step considered
unlikely, the 6-year-old and his father, who have been living in
Maryland and later in Washington while the legal appeals play out,
would be free to leave the United States and return to Cuba after 4
p.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The 12 members of the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals not
only denied the Miami relatives' request for a re-hearing Friday,
but they did not even call for a vote on the question.
</P>
<P>
   The relatives' lawyers, Judge J.L. Edmondson wrote in the
unanimous opinion, should direct any requests for a further stay of
the deadline to the Supreme Court, and wrote that the appeals court
would not grant any future motions for a stay. He wrote the ``NOT''
in bold, oversized letters.
</P>
<P>
   Approval from seven of the 12 members of that court was needed
for a re-hearing of the case, in which a three-judge panel had
ruled June 1 in favor of the government and, indirectly, Elian's
father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the nine Supreme Court justices must agree to hear an
appeal, but a single justice can grant a stay, or refer the
question about a stay to the full court.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy is the Supreme Court member assigned
to hear emergency cases like this one. If he does not act on a
stay, the father could legally put his son a plane for Cuba as
early as 4:01 p.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for the Miami relatives, Spencer Eig, said the
relatives here will appeal, and seek a stay of that deadline. ``We
feel the future of a small boy is important enough to take to the
highest court,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But legal experts say that a stay seems unlikely, and that a
friendly ruling for the Miami relatives is, if the case is heard,
even more unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pack-your-bags decision,'' said Pamela Falk, a
professor of international law at the City University of New York
who has argued similar cases before. ``The legal issues are over.
The family has exhausted every remedy. They had their day in court.
They had many days.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, where Elian has been living with his father,
step-mother, half-brother and a delegation of friends and teachers
from Cuba, a lawyer for Juan Miguel Gonzalez said the family has
not decided when they would leave the country if the stay actually
does expire.
</P>
<P>
   The Gonzalez family, said Gregory B. Craig, their lawyer,
``looks forward to resuming a normal life.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno, who has been criticized for her
handling of the case, said she was ``pleased that the 11th Circuit
Court of Appeals has acted unanimously in denying the motion for
re-hearing. Now that the court has conclusively upheld our
decision, I am hopeful that this father and son will soon be able
to move on with their lives together.''
</P>
<P>
   In their appeal, lawyers for Lazaro Gonzalez, the boy's Miami
great uncle, had argued that the three-judge panel was wrong to
uphold an Immigration and Naturalization Service decision to return
Elian to his father in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge panel had found that, while the court might
disagree with sending the boy back to a Communist government with a
long, dismal history on human rights, the law gave wide discretion
to the immigration agency in such cases and that the powers of the
executive branch of government should be respected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since this case does not present a complicated legal issue,
there is no reason to expect the Supreme Court to take interest in
this appeal,'' said David Abraham, a professor of immigration law
at the University of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, where Lazaro Gonzalez kept the boy in his home after
he was rescued at sea in November and until the armed federal raid
reunited him with his father in April, people were disappointed,
but there were no demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the house where Elian had lived, which has become a
shrine of sorts in the exile community, only a few people showed up
to voice their displeasure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel it's a case that is appropriate for the Supreme
Court,'' said Eig, the lawyer for the Miami relatives. He said the
relatives' lawyers will argue that Elian has constitution rights to
apply for asylum.
</P>
<P>
   But the Supreme Court is more likely to affirm Juan Miguel
Gonzalez's rights in the case, said Falk. ``It is so highly
unlikely that the Supreme Court will grant even an emergency
injunction.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian has been at the middle of an international custody battle
since he was found floating on an inner tube off the coast of
Florida on Thanksgiving Day. He was one of three survivors of a
failed crossing from Cuba that drowned his mother and 10 others.
</P>
</TEXT>
