<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CHATRIER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILIPPE CHATRIER, 72, A FORCE ON INTERNATIONAL TENNIS SCENE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN B. ADAMS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time in the 1970s and the '80s, when Philippe
Chatrier wore dual chapeaux as president of the International
Tennis Federation and president of the French Tennis Federation,
that all roads in tennis led through Gaul. That era officially
ended Thursday when Chatrier, the man responsible for the return of
tennis to the Olympics and the renaissance of his home Grand Slam
tournament, the French Open, as one of the game's four most
prestigious championships, died at age 72.
</P>
<P>
   Chatrier had suffered from Alzheimer's disease for several years
and died in the Brittany town of Dinard, the French Tennis
Federation announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
   As a player, journalist and administrator, Chatrier parlayed a
deep passion for tennis with an instinct for making deals that
showcased the game. France's junior champion at 17 in 1945, a
member of its Davis Cup team from 1948 to 1950 and its captain from
1969 to 1972, Chatrier gave up playing internationally in 1953 to
launch Tennis de France, the nation's first tennis magazine.
</P>
<P>
   But it was in the twin roles as head of the French federation
(1973-93) and the international federation (1977-91) that he
reached his zenith as a power broker in international athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a great influence in world sports and weighed heavily
on the evolution of tennis,'' Christian Bimes, the current French
federation president, told The Associated Press Friday. ``Under his
impetus, tennis, a sport that was living in the past, became a
major sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Bimes said the rebirth of the French Open, the return of tennis
to the Olympics and France's Davis Cup victory in 1991 were
Chatrier's most memorable accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   Said Francesco Ricci Bitti of Italy, the international
federation's current president, ``I'll always regard him as the
father of international tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   Urbane, charming and indefatigable, Chatrier understood both the
velvet glove and the iron fist of international sports politics. He
worked tirelessly toward the creation of open tennis, in which
professionals and amateurs play together, which began in 1968. As
the International Tennis Federation president, which entitled him
to a seat on the International Olympic Committee, he was the
indomitable force in returning tennis to the Olympics, first as a
demonstration sport in 1984 and then as a medal sport in 1988 after
an official absence of 64 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``An extremely shrewd judge of character,'' Bitti said, ``he was
one of the greatest talent scouts that I have ever met.''
</P>
<P>
   On the recommendation of Arthur Ashe in 1971, Chatrier enrolled
Yannick Noah, an 11-year-old from Cameroon, in the French
development program. Twelve years later Noah won the 1983 French
Open, becoming the first Frenchman to win since 1947. It was only
Chatrier's most visible step in revitalizing tennis in France. In
his tenure as the French federation president, the number of
registered players rose from 224,000 to 1,350,000. Chatrier was
also devoted to tennis' traditions and did not hesitate to punish
or criticize what he considered transgressions to its heritage.
When Jimmy Connors chose to play World Team Tennis in 1974,
Chatrier called the renegade league a ``circus'' and banned Connors
from the French Open that year, perhaps costing the world's No.
1-ranked player a Grand Slam of the game's four major tournaments;
Connors won the other three _ the Australian Open, Wimbledon and
the U.S. Open. In 1990, Chatrier chastised Andre Agassi when he
showed up at Roland Garros stadium in a typically unorthodox _
black and pink _ outfit; Agassi returned serve by calling Chatrier
a ``bozo.''
</P>
<P>
   Chatrier was married twice, first in 1953 to Suzanne Partridge
of England and then to the former French golf champion Claudine
Cros in 1993. He is survived by a son, Jean-Philippe. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
