<HEADLINE>
SAFE HARBOR
</HEADLINE>
  Preventing pool injuries never an accident 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Goes with sidebar) 
By ANGELA LEMIRE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Statistics tell us drownings _ the leading cause of death in Los
Angeles County of children 5 and under _ occur most often during
the summer months in backyard swimming pools.
</P>
<P>
   Hindsight teaches us these tragedies and most water-related
injuries are preventable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You turn your back on a child for one second and that child
could end up at the bottom of a pool,'' said Ray Rodriguez, a
community outreach officer for the Los Angeles County Fire
Department. ``We stress all the time not to take your eyes off the
kids while they're in the pool or even near a pool.''
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 40 young children drown in Los Angeles County every
summer, which accounts for half of all accidents annually involving
children 5 and under.
</P>
<P>
   Every summer, professionals like Rodriguez try to hammer home
the message of water safety, hoping to reach parents, party hosts
and guests who might attend everything from simple poolside
get-togethers to graduation, birthday or holiday parties _ where
food, drink, games and other children too easily can distract
watchful eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 70 percent of drownings in Los Angeles County have
occurred in swimming pools, while 30 percent have taken place in
bathtubs, hot tubs, toilets _ even buckets and puddles. Of
incidents involving swimming pools, 65 percent took place at the
home of the child's immediate family, 33 percent occurred at the
homes of friends and relatives, and two percent occurred elsewhere,
such as public pools, according to county figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The drowning cases are often cases where everyone at the party
thought that somebody else was watching their kids at all times,''
said Holly Craig, a pediatric nurse in Northridge, who promotes
child safety inside and outside the home through ``Child and Parent
Resources,'' a nonprofit group. ``You have to, have to, keep an eye
on children in water at all times.''
</P>
<P>
   Most drowning victims had been out of sight for less than five
minutes _ about the time to answer the phone, use the bathroom or
grab a glass of water, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent common mishaps, Child and Parent Resources suggests
parents and party hosts set strict rules at their discretion. For
example, forbid diving during large gatherings, limit the number of
children in the pool at one time, limit diving or jumping to one
person at a time, have everyone exit the pool area when food is
served, or mark the pool deck in chalk to indicate where diving in
shallow areas is forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez recommends that parents, siblings, friends and family
members take scheduled turns supervising pools _ even for using the
bathroom or grabbing an iced tea.
</P>
<P>
   For parents or party hosts who can afford it, Craig recommends
hiring a professional lifeguard for large gatherings. Area
community centers and pools can refer lifeguards.
</P>
<P>
   Experts also encourage parents to teach children how to get an
adult's attention and help immediately if another child is in
trouble and _ for more serious medical emergencies _ make sure
children know how to call 911.
</P>
<P>
   Homeowners should make sure their pools have basic rescue
equipment handy, such as a ring buoy on a rope, that can be thrown,
can keep the child afloat and pull him or her to safety. Other
poolside items should include a CPR instruction poster, phone to
call 911, waterproof first-aid kit, approved life preserver vests
(in child and adult sizes) and approved flotation devices for
children.
</P>
<P>
   And any rescue professional would tell pool owners that it's a
good idea to know CPR (cardio pulmonary resuscitation), which
requires an annual certification renewal and four-hour classes.
</P>
<P>
   Near-drownings can have devastating consequences, noted Dr. Alan
Kuban, Emergency Department director for West Hills Hospital and
Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Brain damage grows worse the longer a person goes without
oxygen, he said, adding that lasting effects can range from motor
skill and thought- process problems to vegetative, coma-like
states.
</P>
<P>
   Though less frequent, diving accidents sometimes result in
serious spinal cord injuries such as paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   But the most common injuries suffered in and around pool areas
are less severe.
</P>
<P>
   Broken bones, sprains, bad cuts and even concussions often
result from falls on slippery decks or from diving boards, said Dr.
Marc Kerner, a trauma surgeon at Northridge Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making sure there's no glass around the pool area is an
obvious way to prevent injury, but you'd be surprised by how many
badly cut feet we see,'' said Kerner. &QL; 
---A step further &QL; 
Many specialty swimming pool retailers carry products that do
everything from securing hot tubs and preventing falls on slippery
decks, to fencing off pool areas and setting off child safety
alarms.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, homeowners can place safety signs in pool areas.
</P>
<P>
   Signs reading ``no running,'' ``no diving,'' ``no glass near
pool,'' ``pool capacity'' and ``caution: wet deck'' sell for about
$5 each, said James Thomas, manager of Our Pool Store in Woodland
Hills and Glendale.
</P>
<P>
   Other inexpensive products include tread kits, which provide
some traction on slippery decks, stairs and ladders; floating
``stringers'' that rope off shallow swim areas from the deep end,
and collapsible canvas barriers, which prevent entry to the pool
area when not in use.
</P>
<P>
   Jacuzzi owners too can equip ``hot tubs'' with locking covers
and safety grates. The grate (about $14), placed over the main
suction drain, keeps small children from getting pulled and tangled
in the drains of older model hot tubs.
</P>
<P>
   For homeowners with larger budgets, Our Pool Store owner Ron
Susca recommends the Kiddie Catch, a $1,200 netting kit that
stretches across the pool when not in use, to catch fallen
children; a see-through screen mesh fence (at $20 per foot) that
stands four feet high and completely surrounds the pool; and
mechanical vinyl pool covers, which run about $6,000.
</P>
<P>
   Pool alarms sound alerts inside the home when someone has
entered or fallen into a swimming pool. Starting at around $150,
some models detect motion in the water, while others are tripped
when a laser beam field over the pool is broken. Wrist-worn alarms
sound when a child's wrist is submerged in water.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter what gadgets and safeguards are in place, experts
emphasize there are no substitutes for child supervision and taking
the time to educate children on water safety and hazards.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can child-proof your pools, but children by nature are not
pool- safe,'' said Kuban. ``They need supervision at all times.'' &QL; 
---What to do if a child is in trouble in a pool:
</P>
<P>
   1. Yell for help.
</P>
<P>
   2. Get the child out of water.
</P>
<P>
   3. Call 911 immediately for emergency medical assistance.
</P>
<P>
   4. Begin CPR if trained. If not trained in CPR, follow telephone
instructions from fire department until medics arrive, or consult
emergency instructions in local telephone book.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Los Angeles County Fire Department &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
