<HEADER>
A3306 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l BC-POOL-SAFETY-LADN &LR;      06-23 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POOL-SAFETY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE PRECAUTIONS FOR A SAFE SUMMER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Goes with main pool-safety story) 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Los Angeles County Fire Department; National Safety Council;
Underwriters Laboratories Inc.; Child &AMP; Parent Resources
Northridge; Dr. Marc Kerner, Northridge Hospital; Dr. Alan Kuban,
West Hills Hospital and Medical Center. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
By far the most important rule for preventing pool drownings is to
use constant supervision. Children in or around pools should be
watched by an adult at all times. But here are some additional ways
to safeguard your kids:
</P>
<P>
   1. Erect a 4- to 5-foot fence completely surrounding pools and
spas. Fences should provide clear views of pools and have no
vertical openings wider than four inches. Do not install fences
that children can climb.
</P>
<P>
   2. Install self-closing gates at entrances to pools and spas,
with safety latches that children cannot reach.
</P>
<P>
   3. Lock all doors in the home that lead to pool area at all
times. (Also note that small children can exit through ``doggie
doors.'') Motion sensors can also be installed at doors leading to
pools that sound an alarm when tripped.
</P>
<P>
   4. When pool is in use, remove pool covers completely and stow
neatly.
</P>
<P>
   5. Secure, lock or remove steps and ladders leading to
above-ground pools when not in use.
</P>
<P>
   6. Keep in-ground pools lit at night.
</P>
<P>
   7. Keep all pets, toys and child amusements out of pool area
when not in use. Do not let children play in the vicinity of a pool
or leave a child alone by a pool.
</P>
<P>
   8. Children who cannot swim well should swim with an adult in
water, or wear personal flotation devices (PFDs) approved by the
United States Coast Guard (USCG) or Underwriters Laboratories (UL).
Note that some flotation devices, such as inflatable ``arm
floaties'' and waist rings, may make it easier for children to
swim, but are not approved life-savers. Toddlers, even infants,
should receive swim lessons, as well.
</P>
<P>
   9. Do not allow glass in pool areas. Have children wear
protective footwear when they are not swimming. Reduce slippery
surfaces by installing tread kits. And do not allow children to run
on pool decks.
</P>
<P>
   10. Keep basic rescue equipment such as roped buoy rings,
first-aid kits and CPR emergency instructions poolside at all
times. Make sure every household member knows how to respond to
drownings, near-drownings and other accidents. Also make sure they
know how to call 911 for emergency medical assistance.
</P>
<P>
   For additional information on pool safety or the county program,
WATCH (Water Awareness Training for Children in the Home), call the
Los Angeles County Fire Department Community Relations Office at
(213) 881-2411. To reach Child and Parent Resources, call (818)
995-4277.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
