s f BC-PROFILE-JACOBS-CONSEC     06-23 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-JACOBS-CONSECO-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISHING FOR BASS, AND BIG PROFITS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., Minn., Ky., Ala.)   By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The phone rings and Irwin L. Jacobs, the fabled
corporate raider of the 1980s, cannot hide his emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my God,'' he says, holding the telephone to his ear. ``Get
out of here!'' A long pause. ``Goodness. Yes. Do it.''
</P>
<P>
   He turns to his visitor. ``I apologize,'' he says. ``There's
something important going on.''
</P>
<P>
   That something is a sharp rise in shares of Conseco, the big but
beleaguered insurer, on a news report that Gary C. Wendt, a former
General Electric executive, is a leading candidate to head the
company. Jacobs keeps reaching for his hot line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again? How many shares have traded?'' He paces. ``Wow! OK
Bye.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs scheduled this meeting at his 25th floor office in
downtown Minneapolis two weeks earlier to talk about his latest
passion: a national bass fishing tournament. But he keeps getting
interrupted. He confesses that the talk about him having designs on
Conseco might be true. ``There's no question we've had discussions
with people,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs grew enormously wealthy two decades ago by acquiring
large stakes in troubled companies like Kaiser Steel and Walt
Disney and then selling them for big profits. But on this day, he
does not tip his hand as to whether he is just interested in seeing
his Conseco investment climb in value _ he has been buying shares
over the last few months _ or whether he is plotting a full-fledged
takeover of the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing definite,'' he says. ``But we are looking at
all our options.''
</P>
<P>
   He bought a few hundred thousand shares several years ago, when
Conseco and its acquisition-minded founder, Stephen C. Hilbert,
were the hot growth story in the insurance business. Conseco stock
started collapsing last year, partly because of sharp declines at
the finance unit that was formed by the acquisition of the Green
Tree Financial Corp. More recently, as the market judged that
Hilbert had paid too much for Green Tree, a mobile home lender,
Jacobs did what he has been doing for decades: buying shares in
what he considered a temporarily out-of-favor stock.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen million shares, in fact. ``I noticed the shorts were
selling,'' Jacobs, 58, recalls. ``They were selling to me. I
concluded this thing was a license to steal at $5 a share.''
</P>
<P>
   The shares fell to as low as $4.50 in mid-May, but soon
rebounded to $7 on speculation about Wendt. They have since
retreated to $5.75.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics, however, say Jacobs has a penchant for hinting at
takeover bids to drive up a stock and then failing to follow
through. A few years ago, he moved to get control of MEI
Diversified, which owns hair salons and a variety of other
businesses _ and then dropped out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I told you what I thought about Irwin Jacobs, he'd sue me
within 24 hours,'' said Marc Kozberg, president of Dougherty Value
Advisors here and a former shareholder of MEI Diversified. ``The
first question I would ask is whether he has the wherewithal to buy
Conseco.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to respond, Jacobs, with more than $50 million by his own
account invested in Conseco, hints that he has assembled a ``team''
to arrange a possible takeover. He will not say more.
</P>
<P>
   He stops talking about Conseco and returns to his other
preoccupation: Operation Bass. This meeting, after all, was about
bass fishing, not corporate raiding.
</P>
<P>
   With Genmar Holdings, his boat manufacturing business, in a
slump in the early 1990s, Jacobs commissioned a study and found
that ``our fishing customer was there all the time, even in a down
market.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Why aren't we catering to their passion?'''
</P>
<P>
   That is when Jacobs bought Operation Bass, a 40-employee company
based in Gilbertsville, Ky., that is a leader in bass tournament
promotions. The deal, if one of his smallest, has been one of his
most satisfying in years.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Jacobs _ worth an estimated $400 million _ wanted to
find a way to publicize Genmar's fishing boats, including the
Ranger and Wellcraft brands. But then he recognized an audience
bigger than potential boat owners: the 55 million Americans who go
fishing each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the largest group of untapped consumers,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs says people who love fishing tend to be loyal _ and buy
billions of dollars' worth of consumer goods. His vision: Why not
splash corporate logos on fishing boats, the way Nascar paints its
race cars? ``The Nascar demographics are identical,'' he says.
``And no one has marketed to them.''
</P>
<P>
   He put up some prize money and convinced Wal-Mart Stores to
become the lead sponsor of the annual Operation Bass fishing
tournament, which was held this weekend in Florence, Ala., and is
one of the largest in the world. He corralled Kellogg's, Coca-Cola
and Visa as backers, too.
</P>
<P>
   He also got busy generating publicity. There is a Wheaties box
with Denny Brauer, the champion of the 1998 tournament, feted as
``Angler of the Year.'' ABC News did a report on the fishing
tournament; ESPN, its sister network, now broadcasts it every year.
Did he mention the research report showing that fishing is more
popular than tennis and golf combined?
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Genmar _ a private company that he acquired in
the 1970s and transformed into the world's second-largest boat
maker _ was on the verge of bankruptcy. Now, says Jacobs, who
remains Genmar's chairman, it is growing at a 30 percent clip, with
sales approaching $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   He has fish on his mind, almost all the time. Off to lunch in a
nearby restaurant with Genmar's chief executive and chief financial
officer, Jacobs says he has come up with a recipe that ``fishing
people'' might love _ a fish batter that he says Kellogg has
expressed interest in marketing. ``This is pretty good,'' he says,
tasting some trout he has arranged to have prepared in the batter.
``What do you guys think?''
</P>
<P>
   The more provocative question, of course, is this: What's next
for this deal maker turned bass-fishing promoter?
</P>
<P>
   Unpredictability, he says. That is the course he has always
taken. ``If you look back at every deal I've done, I haven't tried
to be unpredictable; it's just the circumstances that make me do
what I do,'' he says. ``I'm just flexible.''
</P>
<P>
   So if shares of Conseco, based in Carmel, Ind., an Indianapolis
suburb, do not begin to climb soon, keep an eye on Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't expect me to move to Indianapolis,'' he says. ``But I've
made serious investments, and I've made one in Conseco. So I would
seriously consider doing something about that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
