u w BC-STATES-VOTE-PA     06-23 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-VOTE-PA </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  ATTENTION EDITORS: THIS IS THE REAL VOTE CHART! WASHINGTON
WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this transmission should be
directed to 202-628-3100, Ext. 218. WASHINGTON, June 23 -- The
following chart shows how senators and representatives voted on key
bills and amendments within the last week. A ``Y'' means the member
voted for the measure; an ``N'' means the member voted against the
measure; a ``?'' means the member did not vote; and a ``P'' means
the member voted ``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: Federal
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Tuesday approved, 57-42, an amendment by Sen.
Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., to enhance federal enforcement of hate
crimes. Part of the Defense Appropriations bill, the provision
would allow the prosecution of violent crimes based on a victim's
sexual orientation, gender or disability. Supporters contented it
would punish hate crimes. Opponents assert it would infringe on
state and local law enforcement. A ``yes'' vote supports federal
hate crime legislation.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: State
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Tuesday passed, 50-49, a measure by Sen. Orrin
Hatch, R-Utah, to study and support hate crime investigations by
state and local law enforcement agencies. The measure is part of
the Defense Appropriations bill. Supporters argued that the measure
would create a strong and workable assistance program for state and
local law enforcement. Opponents contended that the provision would
not protect all Americans from hate crimes. A ``yes'' vote
supported state and local funding to prevent and prosecute hate
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: Helicopter
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Wednesday rejected, 47-51, an amendment to provide
at least $110 million for helicopters to stem the cultivation of
drugs in Colombia as part of a Foreign Operations Appropriations
bill. Proponents said it would have allowed the military to use
Black Hawks, which can fly higher and farther than other
helicopters. Opponents complained that Black Hawks were expensive
to operate and maintain. A ``yes'' vote supports funds for
helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   4) BILL NUMBER: Medicare
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Thursday rejected, 44-53, a provision to contain
the cost of Medicare prescription drugs and encourage competition
among private providers. The amendment would have been part of an
appropriations bill for the Departments of Labor, Health and Human
Services, and Education. Supporters said it would help the aged.
Opponents wanted insurance companies not Medicare to provide drug
benefits. A ``no'' vote limits Medicare benefits and services.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3 4
</P>
<P>
   --- --- --- ---
</P>
<P>
   SANTORUM (R-PA) N Y Y N
</P>
<P>
   SPECTER (R-PA) Y N Y N
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: Tobacco
</P>
<P>
   The House on Monday rejected, 197-207, an amendment to transfer
medical care funding to the Justice Department for lawsuits against
tobacco companies. The measure would have been part of the
Departments of Veterans Affairs and Housing and Urban Development
Appropriations bill. Supporters hoped to continue federal lawsuits
against tobacco companies. Opponents said that the amendment would
take needed funding from veterans' medical treatment. A ``no'' vote
stops funds for the Clinton administration to sue the tobacco
industry.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: EPA
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday approved, 226-199, a provision to
prohibit the Environmental Protection Agency from identifying areas
with high levels of ozone. The amendment is part of the Departments
of Veterans Affairs and Housing and Urban Development
Appropriations bill. Supporters said the measure would protect
communities from the stigma of having a poor air rating. Opponents
argued it would weaken the agency. A ``yes'' vote restricts EPA
programs.
</P>
