<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3318 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-TIFFANY-RING-ART-$ADV     06-23 0346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIFFANY-RING-ART-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAKING THE MOLD AT TIFFANY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 25) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By KRUTI TRIVEDI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As senior vice president of merchandising at Tiffany
&AMP; Co., Linda Hanson had to be careful when talking about creating a
new design for the Tiffany engagement ring.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the company had been making its trademark ring, with
its famous ``Tiffany setting,'' for 114 years. But Hanson pressed
for a new product, and Tiffany introduced Lucida, billed as ``the
new Tiffany engagement ring,'' last fall. With a square-cut diamond
and sleek setting, it is a far cry from the traditional Tiffany
setting, with a round diamond. The new ring starts at $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Hanson, who was a math and economics major at Smith College,
worked in the 1980s for Smith Barney, where she eventually became a
vice president in corporate finance. But she was always fascinated
by gems and first became interested in design during her art
history classes at Smith.
</P>
<P>
   After seven years at Smith Barney, she wanted a career change.
She studied at the Gemological Institute of America and joined
Tiffany in 1990, becoming a vice president in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The new ring, several years in the making, is intended to
attract a more adventurous buyer. ``We knew that we needed to
create a new icon in the engagement world,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But making an icon isn't easy. Hanson directed a team of
gemologists, designers and marketers that produced the ring. The
gemologists worked on different ways to cut the stone while
designers worked on creating the band. Then the team made sure that
the cut matched the design of the setting.
</P>
<P>
   The group practiced on real diamonds. As for the scores of
stones that just didn't work, Hanson said many were simply
discarded. ``It sounds kind of weird, because you use actual
diamonds, but that's just a part of research and development,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
