<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3320 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-AMAZON-STOCK0624-COX     06-23 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMAZON-STOCK0624-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fear fuels Amazon plunge
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If Wall Street analysts don't think Amazon.com _ with
one of the strongest brands on the Internet _ can make money, it
doesn't bode well for the rest of the e-commerce landscape.
</P>
<P>
   That bleak scenario sent investors scurrying Friday, when it
seemed nobody on Wall Street had anything good to say about the
Seattle-based retailer, which sells everything from books to
toothpaste and Palm Pilots to 20 million Web shoppers around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com shares dropped nearly 20 percent of their value in
heavy trading Friday, reaching a 52-week low. Shares have tumbled
from a high of $113 six months ago to $33.88 Friday, wiping out $28
billion in value. The stock plummeted on analysts' concerns that
Amazon _ which has yet to turn a profit _ might be facing a bleak
Christmas season and could perhaps run out of cash.
</P>
<P>
   The comments sent up yet another red flag to investors already
skittish about dot-com holdings. Amazon, Yahoo!, America Online and
eBay are considered the ``big four'' companies of the New Economy.
If it appears that one of the biggest and best known online brands
can't make money, then who can?
</P>
<P>
   Mary Meeker, a Morgan Stanley Dean Witter analyst known as the
grand dame of Internet stocks, helped trigger the downturn by
saying on CNBC that she sees potential for ``no upside'' and
``modest downside'' for Amazon until the Christmas season, which
will be ``make or break'' time.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts from Lehman Brothers expressed similar concerns about
Amazon's cash flow and its ability to generate profits during the
second and third quarters. Lehman analysts were concerned that,
despite its 20 million customers and $1.6 billion in revenue for
1999, Amazon had burned through $1.2 billion in cash over the last
five quarters, and still shows no profit. The analysts were worried
the company might run out of operating money and labeled it ``high
risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazon's director of public relations Bill Curry dismissed the
Lehman reports entirely. ``It's pure hogwash. We are asolutely
nowhere near _ put that in boldface letters _ running out of cash.
Anybody who does understand the cash flow dynamics of our business
understands that we are nowhere near running out of cash. ``
</P>
<P>
   Curry said the company ended the first quarter with nearly $1
billion in cash and expects to generate a positive cash flow from
its operations over the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about Amazon's financial health surfaced early this
year, when the company posted record sales for 1999 of $1.6
billion, but spent $720 million more than it took in.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Russell Grandinetti, Amazon's director of investor
relations, told the Journal-Constitution that the company's losses
were due to the cost of growing the company, including $300 million
on the company's state-of-the-art distribution centers, one of
which is in Henry County south of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Curry's strongly worded comments Friday were directed at a
report issued by Lehman Brothers analysts Ravi Suria and Stan Oh,
which said: ``Going into what is arguably its most challenging
holiday season, we believe that the combination of negative cash
flow, poor working capital management, and high debt load in a
hyper competitive environment will put the company under extremely
high risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Their words of warning are based on concerns that while Amazon
is one of the world's best known brands in online or offline
retailing, it has been unable to leverage the value of its brand
and stop the ever-increasing flow of red ink.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon has $1.08 billion in cash and is using $115.7 million a
month beyond its revenues, according to data compiled by Bloomberg
News. That means the company could run out of cash in nine months
if it continues spending at the same rate.
</P>
<P>
   However, not all analysts are concerned that Amazon is going to
close its virtual doors.
</P>
<P>
   Miles Russ, senior analyst with Robinson Humphrey in Atlanta
said the stock plunge was an overreaction. ``The dot-coms are so
much out of favor right now that everybody gets twice as nervous
when someone is out there saying something bearish about the big
four. It's dot-com paranoia magnified.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was unconcerned about sluggish second and third
quarters for the online retailer. ``It's a seasonal business after
all,'' Russ said.
</P>
<P>
   The analyst also dismissed rumors that Amazon.com founder Jeff
Bezos might consider selling or merging his company with a
traditional ``brick and mortar'' retailer such as Federated
Department Stores, owners of Bloomingdale's, Macy's, Burdine's and
Rich's stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Bezos would be interested in merging with a
bricks and mortar company,'' Russ said. ``Although I do believe
that lots of brick and mortar companies would like to get in with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the pure Internet retailers, Amazon has the best
following and has the highest likelihood of being classified with
brick and mortar retailers,'' said David Herskovits, a partner with
Deloitte and Touche consulting firm. ``But there's still a lot of
future for Amazon and there's still a story to be told.''
</P>
<P>
   Russ says Amazon's prospects are still good and the company
insists it will cut back on its spending, although details of its
planned fiscal prudence are sketchy. ``The company is going to
survive,'' Russ said.
</P>
<P>
   Russ contends Amazon's distribution centers could turn out to be
a very valuable asset. ``People have to recognize that (Amazon) has
hard assets, including distribution centers with huge capacity and
that's worth something. They could use it as collateral for any
kind of financing. Amazon.com is not just some little dot.com with
just a Web site.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
