<P>
   BIZ-BOOKS (Undated) _ Why can't companies get off the dime?
Jeffrey Pfeffer and Robert Sutton have studied the ways of business
for decades, and they come away puzzled as to why so many companies
fail to act on what they know. In their pragmatic book, ``The
Knowing-Doing Gap'' (Harvard Business School Press, 2000), Pfeffer
and Sutton offer the voice of experience about companies that know
what to do but just can't. By Fred Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   With:
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-BOOKS-INTERVIEW (Undated) _ Jeffrey Pfeffer, co-author of
``The Knowing-Doing Gap,'' teaches at Stanford University, in the
heart of Silicon Valley. In an interview, he described how Internet
companies in particular could learn to put their best ideas into
practice. By Fred Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-ENTERPRISE (San Francisco) _ Enterprise Application
Integration software firms are the opposite of the Blue Chip
Technology companies that investors have been buying since the
spring selloff. They are extraordinarily volatile, have scant track
records and no earnings. But companies like Vignette, Vitria,
Webmethods, Tibco and Crossworlds also have the high octane growth
that can justify their valuations. And they are selling for less
than half their highs. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   ONTHEJOB-MESSAGES (Undated) _ On the Job: Misdirected messages.
By Lawrence Van Gelder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ECON-COLUMN (Undated) _ The United States seems to have tired of
using the fruits of American labor as a weapon in global politics.
In the span of a month, Congress eliminated China's annual trade
review and President Clinton eased economic sanctions against North
Korea. The State Department even dropped the term ``rogue state''
from its diplomatic lexicon: Libya, Iraq and Syria are now simply
``states of concern.'' Could the 38-year embargo on trade with Cuba
be next? By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   MIDSTREAM-COLUMN (Undated) _ As baby boomers, we are getting a
reputation. We take heat for our questionable cell-phone habits,
the big trucks we drive and our overall obsession with money. Now
investment advisers are shaking their heads over how we invest. We
are, they say, incredibly risk-prone and oblivious to the lessons
of history. We know that, of course, and it seems that many of us
don't care. But not all of us. By James Schembari.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AUTOS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT-CARS-SPYDER (Undated) _ Reviewing the Toyota MR2 Spyder.
By Dan Neil.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-SMART-TALKING (Milford, Mich.) _ Sometimes, cars say the
darndest things. Humorous look at one driver's bad experience with
a talking GM concept car. By Cheryl Jensen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STYLE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Coded `l'
</P>
<P>
   DRESSING-ROOMS (Undated) _ You are standing with your pants
around your ankles when a stranger pulls back a curtain and says,
``Peekaboo!'' You have been locked out in a public place wearing a
single black sock and a cocktail dress with a price tag hanging off
the side. You are standing in your underwear when the woman your ex
dumped you for strides imperiously into the room. Pop quiz: Are you
1) trapped in a Freudian nightmare, 2) a candidate for a case study
in ``The Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders'' or
3) out shopping. The answer, obviously, is 3. And the source of
your deep-rooted anxiety is that perennial bane of the shopper, the
dressing room. By Guy Trebay.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BOOMER-DEATH (Undated) _ In a few years, the baby boomers are
going to be entering the prime perishing years, and we all know
what that means. They're going to turn dying into a form of
self-expression. Each and every last boomer is going to strive to
make his or her death a unique and fulfilling ritual. By David
Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   HAMPTONS-WEEKEND (Undated) _ An island village. The end of last
weekend. An oversubscribed Jitney back to civilization. An angry
mob encircles and entraps it until the police come. This is not an
episode of ``Survivor,'' the reality TV series which pits 16
castaways against one another as they vote each other off their
island. Rather, it's another tale of survival in the Hamptons,
where people drive tank-like cars to battle for parking spaces,
litigate like tribal warriors, endure monsoons of bad press, and
even jail. By Bob Morris.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ In the third century B.C.,
Theophrastus wrote that the Greeks planted broad beans to improve
the soil. So I'm in good company. By Anne Raver.
</P>
<P>
   NATIELLO-FASHIONS (New York) _ Last week at Saks Fifth Avenue,
Craig Natiello, who designs for the Halston label, was showing his
fall collection to a circle of his faithful _ young society figures
including Tara Rockefeller and Somers White. He paused to note that
most truly chic women know how to dramatize their assets. Vamping
to reinforce the point, he pulled back his honey-streaked hair,
tilted his chin skyward and pursed his lips in a dowager pout, the
image of Diana Vreeland. Natiello's talent for impersonation has
served him well. By Ruth La Ferla.
</P>
<P>
   With Photo.
</P>
<P>
   NITEOUT-MCCORMACK (New York) _ Night Out with Eric McCormack,
the star of NBC's ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' the sitcom in which he plays a
gay Manhattan lawyer whose best friend is a straight woman. By
Denny Lee.
</P>
<P>
   With Photo.
