<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0386 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3328 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SALVATION-ARMY24-COX     06-23 1611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALVATION-ARMY24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In Atlanta and around the world, the Salvation Army marches
forth to do good deeds and save souls
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With a background in law enforcement, Ted Owenby is used to
wearing uniforms. In a few days, he will be wearing a new one _
that of an officer in the Salvation Army.
</P>
<P>
   Owenby and his wife, Susan, enlisted as ``soldiers'' in the Army
in 1993 after an applicant for a driver's license at the Ocala,
Fla., licensing bureau where Owenby worked invited them to a
Salvationist service.
</P>
<P>
   Like many people, ``I didn't even know the Salvation Army was a
church,'' Owenby said. ``I knew it as a social service
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, at 50, the Owenbys are the oldest members of a class
graduating June 29 from the College for Officers' Training, the
Salvation Army's seminary in south Atlanta for the Southern states.
They will go on to be pastors in a local Salvation Army church,
called a corps. As they cross the stage at their graduation
ceremony, or commissioning service, they will learn along with the
audience where they will be sent.
</P>
<P>
   Swapping a cop's uniform for that of a Salvationist feels
different, Owenby said. ``This one causes you to feel humble. The
other one didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Owenbys and other Salvationists stand out among casually
clothed crowds _ sometimes being mistaken for hotel bell captains
or airline pilots _ they will blend in next week.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty thousand of their brothers and sisters in uniform from
around the world will gather in Atlanta Wednesday through July 2
for the Army's International Millennial Congress. The meeting, to
be held in the Georgia World Congress Center and Philips Arena, is
only the eighth in the 135-year history of the Army and the first
to be held outside Salvation Army headquarters in London. It is
expected to be the largest Army event ever.
</P>
<P>
   In a visit to Atlanta last year, the supreme commanding officer
of the 1 million-member Army worldwide, Gen. John Gowans, said,
``After all these years, it's time it left London, don't you
think?''
</P>
<P>
   As home to the 1996 Olympic Games, ``I think Atlanta's the right
place for Salvationists to get together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is already a major center for the Salvation Army in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being the site for the seminary, the city is
headquarters for 15 states in an arc from Maryland to Texas, one of
four territorial centers in the United States. The Army has nine
``corps community centers'' or churches in metro Atlanta, with a
total of 1,312 members. The temple, at North Druid Hills Road and
I-85, is the site of many officers' weddings and funerals.
</P>
<P>
   But even in Atlanta, many people are ignorant about the Army
beyond its brass bands, disaster relief efforts and Christmas bell
ringers.
</P>
<P>
   Society's unwanted
</P>
<P>
   The Salvation Army is a Christian denomination with mainline
Protestant worship and Wesleyan theology that says eternal life
through Jesus Christ is available to everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Founder William Booth, a Methodist minister, and a group of his
associates founded the Army out of a mission agency in England in
the 1860s. Its primary focus was to reach the unchurched and
unwanted, such as prostitutes, beggars and drunks. Realizing it was
hard to interest people in religion when they were cold, hungry and
thirsty, Booth offered ``soup, soap and salvation.''
</P>
<P>
   From its beginning the Army was distinctive.
</P>
<P>
   Booth, described as a rather self-righteous man with a passion
for order, saw the military structure as a way to continue his own
control of his followers while deploying them wherever they were
needed. Even today, the international Army is very local in its
efforts to meet the specific needs of a unique community, said
spokesman Lt. Col. Tom Jones of U.S. headquarters in Alexandria,
Va.
</P>
<P>
   Booth found the imagery of the war of good vs. evil easily
understandable to the uneducated classes he was trying to reach.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the military identity evolved:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Even ``soldiers'' in the Army, or regular church members, may
wear uniforms. Officers are clergy who are identifiable by their
red trim, and they move up through the ranks by seniority or
appointment beginning with lieutenant.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  To join the Army is to sign the ``Articles of War,'' which
outline the denomination's doctrine and include a promise to
refrain from alcohol, tobacco, gambling, pornography and the
occult.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Local congregational leaders, comparable to a vestry, session
or board of deacons in other denominations, are called ``local
officers.'' Their chairman is the ``corps sergeant major.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Army's newspaper is called The War Cry.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  To give a tithe or offering in a Salvationist meeting is to
``fire a cartridge.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Brass bands accompany singing at worship.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Army has its own salute _ the index finger of the right
hand pointed toward heaven.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Salvationists who die are ``promoted to Glory,'' in Army
language.
</P>
<P>
   The military terminology is based on the teachings of St. Paul,
author of many of the Epistles in the New Testament, who wrote
about Christians as good soldiers and urged early followers to
``put on the breastplate of faith and love, and for a helmet the
hope of salvation.''
</P>
<P>
   Women preachers
</P>
<P>
   Women, beginning with Booth's wife, Catherine, were always
permitted to preach and hold leadership positions. Two women have
led the Army _ Booth's daughter Evangeline and, most recently, Gen.
Eva Burrows, who served in the 1980s and early 1990s and is
expected to attend the congress in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Booth helped to convince her reluctant husband that
women should be equal in the church, according to Roy Hattersley, a
British politician and writer who wrote ``Blood and Fire, William
and Catherine Booth and Their Salvation Army'' (Doubleday, 1999,
$26.95).
</P>
<P>
   Catherine, as described by Hattersley, was both an effective
preacher and a more astute student of theology than her husband,
who operated more by instinct than scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   In the Army, husband and wife are always the same rank, although
they may have different jobs. They are paid one stipend to share,
and are furnished housing by the Army. They move only their
families, clothes and personal goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Salvation Army is what it is today because of
Catherine Booth, William's wife,'' said Jessica Swyers. ``And I
don't say that just because I'm a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Swyers, 24, and her husband, David, 26, will be graduating with
the Owenbys from officer training next week. David Swyers said he
finds the role of women in the Army to be ``special'' and ``very
biblical.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All through the New Testament, you find women who held
churches in their homes,'' he said. ``I think of Jessica as my
equal and my partner. What better person to have as your equal and
partner than your best friend and your wife?''
</P>
<P>
   Family roots
</P>
<P>
   Both David and Jessica can trace their family lines back six
generations in the Army; both are the offspring of Army officers.
</P>
<P>
   But they were reluctant to tell each other when they felt called
by God to the full-time ministry. Both had decided as teenagers
that being Army officers was the last thing they wanted to do.
</P>
<P>
   David was teaching and Jessica was considering a career in the
funeral industry when both felt the need to enter the ministry. But
they were seriously dating and neither wanted to make a choice
between their relationship and the ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I could truly be happy if I had just forgotten
my calling and married somebody who didn't want to be an officer,''
Jessica Swyers said. ``I don't think I would have fulfilled what
God wanted me to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Their goals as Army officers are the Army's goals, said David
Swyers. ``We want to make a difference. We want to leave the world
better than we found it. And we want to lead as many people to
Christ as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Expanding roles
</P>
<P>
   As the Swyers enter their Army career, Majs. Dalton and Casey
Cunningham will be taking a new step in theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Dalton Cunningham, 48, has been named commissioner of the Army
in Georgia after heading the army in metro Atlanta since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In almost three decades as officers, the Cunninghams have
ministered around the South, from opening a community center in
Charlotte, to persuading a Ku Klux Klansman in Alabama to burn his
sheet, to managing youth ministry in Baltimore and Texas, to
coordinating a major building campaign in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   They were 19 _ she a Salvationist from birth, he a former
Baptist _ when they felt the call to sell their home and furniture,
quit their jobs and enter seminary in August 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Army doctrine is ``very plain'' about how Salvationists should
live out the practice of their faith, said Dalton Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   A sacrificial life
</P>
<P>
   He cites one difference between the Army and the Methodism from
which it sprang. The Army does not offer sacraments such as baptism
or Communion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Salvation is simply by grace,'' he said. ``There's no other
requirement.''
</P>
<P>
   And the bread and wine of the Last Supper, offered as a
sacrament in most Christian churches, is not regarded as necessary.
But the Salvationist is expected to live a sacrificial life,
Cunningham said.
</P>
<P>
   He quotes a Salvationist hymn: ``My life must be Christ's broken
bread, My love his outpoured wine, A cup o'erfilled, a table spread
beneath his name and sign, That other souls, refreshed and fed, May
share his life through mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
