<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSURERS-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BATTERED INSURERS, A TIMELY TURNABOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 25)  
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While technology stocks have been careening wildly, some ugly
ducklings in the insurance industry appear to be transforming
themselves into market darlings.
</P>
<P>
   The companies that sell insurance on cars, houses and
businesses, a decidedly unglamorous business, had been sputtering
under the strain of poor earnings, in large part a result of
natural disasters like Hurricane Floyd, and of rising interest
rates since the middle of last year. Their stocks took a real
beating in the first two and a half months of 2000 as technology
stocks were rising sharply. But when technology shares began
selling off in mid-March, the insurers rebounded.
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt that the insurance stocks had been
oversold by many measures. Many still look relatively cheap when
compared with their peaks of a year or so ago. In addition, signs
of a slowing economy suggest that interest rates may begin to level
off, good news for the group because higher rates can translate
into smaller profits. Even more important, insurers are beginning
to nudge up prices, which also bodes well for profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The property-casualty insurers had been among the most
disfavored stocks on Wall Street,'' said Robert P. Hartwig, the
chief economist at the Insurance Information Institute, an industry
group in New York, adding that some had dropped below book value.
``But since the dot-com shipwreck, people have been looking to put
their money in companies that are actually making a profit. And the
insurance stocks have been among the greatest values on Wall
Street.''
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday, the technology-heavy Nasdaq index was down 5.5
percent for the year, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's property-casualty
stock index was basically flat. Since March 10, the insurance index
has gained 38.3 percent while the Nasdaq, despite its rally since
May 23, is off 23.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In general, rising interest rates dampen insurance stock prices
along with those of other financial services companies. So the
Federal Reserve's short-term interest rate increases, which began
in the middle of last year, have naturally been a drag on the
group's performance. But with insurance stocks well above their
March lows, investors seem to be saying that the economy is
beginning to slow down _ and that the Fed may be nearly done
raising rates.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks of many types have been picking up. But Alice
Schroeder, an analyst at PaineWebber, says property-casualty stocks
stand out because they are less sensitive to economic developments
_ many people have to buy insurance whether or not prices are
rising _ and ``the fundamentals of these companies are actually
improving.''
</P>
<P>
   Auto insurers are a case in point. Shares of the Progressive
Corp. closed on Friday at $77.875, up 58.1 percent from their 2000
lows on March 13, while those of the Hartford Financial Services
Group closed at $53.3125, up 81.5 percent from their low on the
same day.
</P>
<P>
   Ace, the international insurer based in Bermuda, has risen 83
percent from its March nadir, to $26.875. The St. Paul Companies, a
big commercial insurance group, is up 60.9 percent from its low on
March 8, to $35, and Allstate, a leader in auto and homeowner
coverage, is up 34.5 percent, to $23.875.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the run-up, the property-casualty stocks may have room
to move higher. At the beginning of last year, for example,
Progressive traded at more than twice its current price. Other
stocks are well below their 1999 highs too. ``It may not be the
first inning of this game,'' said Doug Cliggott, the United States
equities strategist for J.P. Morgan Securities. ``But I don't think
it's beyond the third inning. It's still a very attractive point to
get in.''
</P>
<P>
   Some fund managers agree. ``I think there's a long ways to go, a
lot of upside, plenty of potential in these stock prices,'' said
Jeff Morris, who manages the $1.3 billion Invesco Financial
Services fund. Noting that the stocks have moved away from their
recent highs, he added that he ``wouldn't read too much into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Others sounded more cautious. Schroeder says some prices of a
year or two ago were historical highs that may be difficult to
overtake anytime soon. Although many of the stocks may have topped
out, she said, there is still money to be made on Ace; XL Ltd.,
another big Bermuda insurer; two of her favorites, AIG and
Berkshire Hathaway; and the two biggest commercial brokers, Marsh &AMP;
McLennan and Aon.
</P>
<P>
   After declining for nearly a decade, prices for commercial
insurance, which offers protection to corporations for most
everything from shareholder suits to plant explosions, are starting
to show signs of increasing. Some of the biggest auto insurers,
including Progressive and Geico, the Berkshire Hathaway unit, have
also begun raising their prices after two years of declines across
the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can make a pretty good case that the insurance cycle is
turning in a more positive direction,'' Cliggott said.
</P>
<P>
   New markets are opening, too, Hartwig said, citing China and
India and a whole field of coverage devoted to cyberspace problems.
A handful of big insurers are entering that field with policies
covering loss of data and damage from viruses. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
