<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3332 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MICROSOFT-FUTURE-$ADV     06-23 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-FUTURE-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM THE BIGGEST (MICROSOFT), SOMETHING REALLY BIG (INTERACTIVE
SERVICES) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 25)  
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ ``We are on the brink of a new computing
revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As big a transition as from DOS to Windows.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft's Net bet is boldest yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Lest anyone possibly miss the point at the Microsoft Corp.'s big
media event last week, the captions in the slide show and
demonstrations were all intended to convey the notion that the
company's strategy for the future would be, in the words of another
Internet company's ubiquitous ads, ``big _ really big.''
</P>
<P>
   To add a little more emphasis, Bill Gates, Microsoft's chairman,
told the assembled analysts and reporters from around the globe,
``You could say it's a bet-the-company thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Under continuing assault in its antitrust battle with the
government, Microsoft held the event not only to offer a glimpse of
some new products _ including software for talking computers and
``interactive paper'' tablets _ but also to suggest that it had a
much broader vision of the future.
</P>
<P>
   The company, judged a predatory monopolist by a federal judge,
took pains to paint it as a friendly future in which it would work
with competitors and partners alike to make the Internet as easy to
use as a television or a telephone.
</P>
<P>
   In time, Microsoft said, it would essentially transform the
heart of its revenue base from packaged software to subscriber-paid
``interactive services.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether consumers, analysts and investors will wind up going
where the company wants them to go remains to be seen. There's
still the antitrust case, which the company's top officials tried
to acknowledge with a bit of roundabout humor.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's chief executive, Steven A. Ballmer, noted that the
event itself was delayed three weeks to avoid coinciding with Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson's ruling that he wanted to split the
company in two. ``For me, the last three weeks made me feel almost
like a caged animal,'' he told the crowd. ``I wanted to come out of
the closet and tell everyone what we've been up to! But, `back in
the closet,' the PR people said. You really don't want to do this
on that day.'''
</P>
<P>
   So, now that the day for ``this'' has arrived, what is
Microsoft's vision for its next generation of services, which the
company calls ``.NET'' (pronounced dot-net)?
</P>
<P>
   In essence, according to the demonstrations at the company's
conference center here on Thursday, Microsoft.NET is about making
what is often called a ``cloud'' of services on the Internet, to be
accessed by a range of personal devices, including hand-held
``tablets'' and organizers, cell phones, cameras and whatever else
inventors dream up.
</P>
<P>
   It promises a world of incredibly instant gratification. In one
video, called ``Family Vacation,'' the Microsoft presentation
depicted an entire trip being arranged in moments. Dinner
reservations at a fancy restaurant are made instantly via a two-way
camera link to the maitre d'. He greets the caller on screen and
beckons to the table where Mom and Dad might be seated with Mom's
parents, who are then messaged to make sure that the restaurant is
suitable. Of course, the smiling grandparents instantly message
back.
</P>
<P>
   During the vacation, the family makes an outing to the zoo. For
some reason, the grandparents don't go, but they can share in the
pleasure in real time: When the family comes up with an especially
nice picture on their digital camera, they send it, wirelessly, to
the grandparents, who are watching television at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, look at that!'' Grandmother beams, so taken with it that
she pushes a button and zaps it into a frame that sits on a table
by the sofa.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's world would also let people talk to their computers,
and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you want to do now?'' the female-voiced computer asks
a sales manager in another demonstration. He asks, ``How's the
market doing today?'' and she _ or it? _ after verifying if he
wants to know about the Dow or Nasdaq or both, returns in seconds
with the latest report. Then he asks to schedule a meeting with a
colleague later in the week. ``Let me see if you are both available
at that time,'' his computer tells him, then schedules the meeting
into their calendars.
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer said the company had dedicated more than half of its
roughly $4 billion budget for research and development to the new
strategy and would keep spending huge sums on it.
</P>
<P>
   For the strategy to really succeed, of course, hardware vendors
and software developers will have to follow Microsoft's lead. But
given the languid response to the company's push into consumer
electronics, such an entourage is by no means guaranteed. Many
other companies, from America Online to cellular providers, hope to
provide the ubiquitous Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   While some of the products Microsoft talked about this week will
be rolled out within months, others probably will not show up for
years or a decade, if ever. Still, many analysts credited the
company with laying out a strong vision.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy has already created some interesting
strange-bedfellow alliances.
</P>
<P>
   Loudcloud Inc., described by its founder as a ``software power
grid in the sky'' that can help businesses in all sorts of ways,
said last week that it would be Microsoft's software development
partner for a number of Internet services. The founder in question?
Marc Andreeson, whose Netscape famously did battle with Microsoft
in the ``browser war'' that is at the heart of the antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you asked me six months ago whether I'd be partnering with
Marc Andreeson,'' Ballmer allowed, ``I would have thought that was
pretty strange.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
