u i BC-CHINA-TAIWAN-NYT &LR;      06-23 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TAIWAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA PUSHING TO MODERNIZE ITS MILITARY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ China is modernizing its armed forces to counter
military threats from technologically superior enemies, but
``significant shortcomings'' in its weapons and training will leave
it unable to challenge the United States for ``an indefinite period
of time,'' according to a Pentagon study released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's report said China's military modernization
efforts are also increasing its ability to threaten Taiwan,
especially with long-range missiles. But the study concluded that
the People's Liberation Army, hobbled by limitations in fighter
aircraft and amphibious ships, would not fare well if ordered to
invade Taiwan in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the short term (2000-2005), the PLA will have only a
limited capability to conduct integrated operations against
Taiwan,'' the unclassified version of a longer classified study
said.
</P>
<P>
   The study, one of a series mandated by Congress, will almost
certainly fuel the debate over the future of China's military and
focus new attention on the diplomatically perilous issue of arms
sales to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Because the study analyzed both strengths and weaknesses in the
Chinese military, its findings amounted to a Rorschach test,
providing critics and supporters of the Clinton administration's
policies toward China evidence to support their views.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get whatever you want out of this report,'' one
Pentagon official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., one of Capitol Hill's most
ardent hawks on China, said the study highlighted President
Clinton's failed efforts to engage China and the need ``to view the
People's Republic of China as a strategic competitor, rather than a
strategic ally.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the analysis concluded that China's
leadership, headed by President Jiang Zemin, remained ``largely
preoccupied by domestic concerns,'' more than military and national
security issues.
</P>
<P>
   It said that in the aftermath of NATO's air war against
Yugoslavia and the bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, some
Chinese officials ``seriously considered'' giving defense a higher
priority, but that the leadership ``reaffirmed its priority
emphasis'' on economic growth during its annual retreat last
August.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, a potential conflict with Taiwan involving the United
States has become ``the dominant scenario'' guiding the Chinese
military's planning and weapons development, it said. The military,
while lagging technologically, has been pouring resources into
devising strategies and weapons to exploit U.S. weaknesses, the
study found.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese have also devoted enormous efforts to developing
means of ``electromagnetic warfare,'' and attacks on computer and
communications networks. And they have an ``aggressive program'' to
buy weapons from Russia, including missiles, attack submarines and,
most recently, two destroyers.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which relied on intelligence findings as well as
writings of China's military strategists, said the Chinese had
carefully studied the 1991 Persian Gulf War and NATO's air war
against Yugoslavia, where U.S.-led forces used overwhelming force
and technological superiority to crush the enemy. The analysis
found that much of China's research and training now centers on
countering just such an attack, by developing or buying missiles
and other weapons that could threaten advanced aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Still, while China is restructuring its armed forces, its air
force and navy remain too antiquated and ill-equipped to launch a
serious invasion of Taiwan or other countries in the region. The
navy's amphibious transport ships could carry only one infantry
division across the Taiwan Strait, leaving other troops dependent
on trawlers and fishing boats.
</P>
<P>
   The report's findings are likely to intensify pressure on the
United States to sell more and more advanced weapons to Taiwan to
counter the Chinese buildup. China has strongly opposed sales to
Taiwan, which it considers a renegade province. In April, the
administration approved a sale of upgraded missiles and a
long-range radar system, but refused Taiwan's request for four of
the most advanced U.S. destroyers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite lingering tensions, the report plays down the likelihood
of open conflict between China and Taiwan, arguing that Beijing
would avoid anything that risked its economic growth and access to
foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``In initiating a military conflict with Taiwan, Beijing would
run the risk of jeopardizing both its continued economic
development and its political standing,'' the report concluded.
``China's resolve to employ military force, however, should not be
discounted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
