u a BC-EXP-DEATH-PENALTY-FED     06-23 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXP-DEATH-PENALTY-FEDERAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS MURDER CASE MAY PUT DEATH PENALTY SPOTLIGHT ON CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   By RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the nation's attention drawn to recent
executions, the focus has been largely on the states, primarily
Illinois, whose governor has declared a moratorium, and Texas,
which puts more men and women to death than most countries and
whose governor, of course, is running for president.
</P>
<P>
   Although Vice President Al Gore favors the death penalty, he has
not faced the tough questioning that Gov. George W. Bush has, and
Gore has said little other than that he does not see the need for a
federal moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   But the case of a condemned migrant worker may soon call
attention to the federal capital punishment system.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Raul Garza, a migrant farm worker and high school dropout
who was convicted seven years ago of marijuana smuggling and three
drug-related murders in Brownsville, Texas, is scheduled to be
executed on Aug. 5. It would be the first federal execution since
John F. Kennedy was president.
</P>
<P>
   The Garza case raises broad, and for many, troubling issues
about the application of the federal death penalty, most
specifically, whether race and geography determine who is sentenced
to die at the hands of the U.S. government. Seventeen of the 21
federal death row inmates are minorities, and federal prosecutors
in a dozen Southern states account for more than half of the
federal cases in which the death penalty is sought.
</P>
<P>
   Garza's lawyers have exhausted legal appeals, and are turning to
the court of public opinion and politics.
</P>
<P>
   Garza wants to ask the president for clemency. But his lawyers
said they are facing some formidable handicaps.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, there are no guidelines for filing a clemency
petition in a federal capital case.
</P>
<P>
   The president's power to grant clemency, be it reprieve,
commutation or pardon, is found in Article II of the Constitution.
It cannot be limited by Congress or the courts, which means the
president can grant clemency whenever he thinks the sentence is
unjust, mercy dictates or in the name of the public tranquility.
</P>
<P>
   The first step in the process is for the prisoner to file a
request with the pardon attorney of the Justice Department, who
then makes a recommendation to the president. That office has
adopted regulations and forms for inmates to use, but these apply
to noncapital cases.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said in February that the department was drafting
regulations for capital cases; a department official said Friday
that they were not yet finished. Garza's lawyers are waiting for
these in order to avoid filing a petition that is thrown out for
failing to follow procedures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
