u i BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-N     06-23 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARANSKY CAMPAIGNS AGAINST ISRAELI CONCESSIONS TO THE PALESTINIANS
 
</HEADLINE>
   By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ A campaign of leaks is under way to pre-expose
Israel's bargaining positions in its peace negotiations so as to
put pressure on Prime Minister Ehud Barak against making
significant concessions to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The latest leak came Friday when an Israeli newspaper printed
the contents of what it called a U.S. ``nonpaper'' that it said
could provide the basis for a three-way, retreat-style summit
meeting in the Washington area.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials dismissed the document as speculative, and
U.S. officials said it was unofficial, of unknown origin and
inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the document, as summed up by the newspaper Yediot
Ahronot, does contain the plausible outline of an eventual
agreement. The newspaper said Interior Minister Natan Sharansky and
Ariel Sharon, leader of the rightist Likud Party, had obtained the
document. The office of Sharanksy said he had provided it to the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The document said Israel would be able to consolidate and annex
settlement blocs with Palestinian assent, if it gave up equivalent
territory elsewhere. It says some 40,000 settlers would have to be
evacuated or, if the Palestinians eventually agreed, remain under
Palestinian rule.
</P>
<P>
   It said that if the Palestinians agreed, the Jordan Valley would
be transferred to full Palestinian control, but leased back to
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   It said that the principle of the right of return of Palestinian
refugees would be granted, but that very few refugees would
actually be allowed to come back. An ``opaque formula'' would
expand a family reunification plan that already exists, under a
different name.
</P>
<P>
   It said Barak is contemplating conceding Arab neighborhoods in
Jerusalem to Palestinian control in exchange for a Palestinian
declaration that the conflict is over.
</P>
<P>
   And it said the United States and other Western nations would
pledge an aid package of more than $100 billion that would be
distributed over 20 years. Most of the money would constitute a
compensation package for Palestinian refugees and their host
countries.
</P>
<P>
   A Western diplomat who saw the document said it was hand-written
and seemed to contain notes from a briefing by a Jewish-American
official. The notes refer to ``our land'' and ``our settlements.''
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks ago, Sharansky released what he said was his
understanding of Barak's intended concessions in an anguished
letter to the prime minister that he made public. Friday, the
essence of Sharansky's letter was reprinted in full-page
advertisements here, under the headline: ``Dear Prime Minister
Barak: We are seriously concerned.'' It is signed by members and
leaders of several American Jewish organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday, Sharanksy, whose Russian immigrant party remains
part of Barak's fragile coalition, sent the prime minister a letter
accusing him of keeping the coalition partners in the dark about
the substance of the negotiations. He said Barak planned to co-op
critics in his Cabinet by taking them with him to Washington, but
that it would not work: ``We will be left with only one choice _ to
agree to an accord to which we are opposed, or to reject it and
return home. This may sound simple in theory, but I know and you
know that the option to reject an agreement is unrealistic and
would lead to the disgrace of Israel before the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharanksy urged Barak to stop his ``race toward a summit'' and
to work more closely with his coalition partners to forge a
consensus agreement. Sharanksy said he would ``end the partnership
between us'' if Barak did not agree.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
