<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3356 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-BROTHER25-COX     06-23 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-BROTHER25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    African conflicts reveal something about continent, relief
efforts, ourselves
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 25.
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1998, Journal-Constitution photographer Rich Addicks and I
traveled to southern Sudan, where famine was decimating the
population. We saw people too weak to stand, and we saw mothers
bury their babies.
</P>
<P>
   I knew the famine was not the result of drought or
overpopulation. It was caused by callous warriors who cared nothing
for human life. Still, the question of what to do seemed simple
enough: When people are starving, they must be fed. Addicks'
powerful and humane photographs conveyed the same message.
</P>
<P>
   People gave money to relief agencies. Schools organized
fund-raising drives. Some parents wrote to tell me that their
12-year-old son had sent all his savings to feed the hungry.
</P>
<P>
   Caring about other people makes us human. But, as Scott
Peterson's savage and penetrating new book makes clear, Africa is
rarely as simple as it seems.
</P>
<P>
   The delivery of food to Sudan has saved thousands of lives, but
it has also fueled a 20-year civil war. Sudan's warlords not only
create starvation by turning people into refugees, they sometimes
herd the starving into particular places so humanitarian agencies
will deliver food where the armies need it.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, an American, covered Africa through much of the '90s
for the Daily Telegraph of London; in 1990 and '91 he also wrote
free-lance stories for the Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   He was sliced in the head with a machete in Somalia on a July
day in 1993 when a mob killed two of his colleagues. He was
hunkered in a foxhole in Sudan when a fellow correspondent was shot
through the leg. He walked through Rwanda when murderers roamed the
roads and bodies roiled the rivers.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike some reporters' memoirs, ``Me Against My Brother'' is
also a work of scholarship. It is extensively researched and
thoroughly documented. This is history at its most penetrating.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson chooses to write about Somalia, Sudan and Rwanda not
because they're the only places he knows _ he covered other
countries in Africa as well _ but because of what these horrific
experiences tell us about Africa, intervention and ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   The first half of the book is devoted to the U.S. and U.N.
experience in Somalia in the early '90s _ a mission bungled so
badly it led to international refusal to stop the genocide in
Rwanda in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The mission began when President Bush saw starving people on
television. Why not deliver food? he thought.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials like to describe what happened in Somalia as
``mission creep,'' but it was a 180-degree turn. Having missed an
opportunity to disarm the country's clans, Western officials
declared war on one Somali warlord, Gen. Mohamed Farah Aidid. The
U.N. devolved into just another warring clan; 90 percent of its
budget was being spent not on relief but on the military.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistani peacekeepers were killed raiding Aidid's radio
station. The U.N. escalated its war effort. On the day that
Peterson was set upon and his friends were killed, the mob was
reacting in rage to a missile attack by U.S. helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal-Constitution carried an Associated Press report that
said the missiles were fired at ``a renegade warlord's command
center,'' and 13 Somalis had died. Those were the official lies.
The missiles were fired at clan elders who had met to figure out
how to make peace with the U.N. And the Red Cross confirmed not 13
deaths, but 54.
</P>
<P>
   By the time it ended, this mission of mercy had resulted in the
deaths of dozens of peacekeepers and perhaps 2,000 Somalis. Then,
improbably, U.N. and U.S. officials rehabilitated Aidid and flew
him to peace talks in Addis Ababa, the capital of Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
   After all the blood, money and lies, what was accomplished?
``Nothing here,'' Peterson writes, ``had changed at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Little has changed in Sudan, either, as Peterson makes clear,
despite massive infusions of international food aid since the
1980s. The food feeds the armies, which then run roughshod over the
people, causing, in turn, more famine.
</P>
<P>
   To its credit, CARE, the Atlanta-based relief and development
organization, has realized that the cycle has no end. The
organization has abandoned its apolitical stance and begun lobbying
for a political end to the war. We can only hope that more
organizations come to realize that there's no such thing as
nonpolitical aid.
</P>
<P>
   Of Rwanda, what can be said? The worst stain on President
Clinton's record lies not on Monica Lewinsky's dress but in the
small country once known as the Switzerland of Africa. Some 800,000
people were murdered as the Clinton administration covered its eyes
and urged other nations not to act, either.
</P>
<P>
   Led by U.N. Ambassador Madeleine Albright, American officials
refused to use the word ``genocide'' because that word carries an
international legal responsibility to intervene. It was 1994 _ an
election year.
</P>
<P>
   All this while 45,000 people were being murdered every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine that every single word in this book is the name of a
victim,'' Peterson writes. ``This entire volume would then list
only 150,000 of the dead, not even one-fifth of the likely death
toll. More than five volumes of this book would be required to list
just the first names of every victim.''
</P>
<P>
   When Tutsi rebels took power, ending the genocide, the Hutus _
many of whose hands dripped with blood _ crossed into Zaire or
Tanzania, dropping their machetes in piles at the borders, and
walked into the open arms of relief organizations only too ready to
feed and rehabilitate them.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson writes with a searching anger that shows no mercy _ not
on the Africans who kill each other, nor on the humanitarians whose
bungling makes things worse, nor on the heart of a reader who
cares. He excoriates the international community but makes no
excuses for the killers.
</P>
<P>
   And on the continent where human life began, he finds some of
what it means to be human. Near the end of the book, he asks a
trauma psychologist this: Is there Rwanda within every one of us?
Comes the reply: ``Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   But Africa shows that within each of us live other qualities,
too. One of Addicks' photographs from Sudan won first place in the
World Press Photo competition. The winning picture did not show an
emaciated infant nor an adult too weak to stand. It showed a mother
tenderly kissing the cheek of her child.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson ends on the same note. One morning in Rwanda his
attention was drawn by the tchk, tchk, tchk of a razor. A mother
was cropping her daughter's hair. In the movement of the mother's
hands and in the stifled giggles of the girl, Peterson found ``a
spiritual moment of great and common tenderness.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the slaughter, one can find _ even on the killing fields
of Rwanda _ such sweet and utter love.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  NONFICTION
</P>
<P>
   Me Against My Brother: At War in Somalia, Sudan and Rwanda. By
Scott Peterson. Routledge. $26. 357
</P>
<P>
   pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: History at its most penetrating.
</P>
<P>
   Don Melvin is assistant international editor at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
