u f BC-AT&AMP;T-PRICES-755&AMP;ADD-N     06-23 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-PRICES-755&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T REFILES ITS PLAN ON RATES 
</HEADLINE>
   By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T submitted a new proposal Friday that would give telephone
users more flexibility in seeking to save money on some
long-distance calls but that appeared to fall short of stemming the
outcry from consumer groups and federal regulators over its plans
to raise certain costs for tens of millions of customers.
</P>
<P>
   Caught between the demands of Wall Street to generate higher
earnings and the expectations of customers who were promised
savings because of lower access charges, AT&AMP;T said it would
eliminate the $3 monthly minimum charge for low-volume callers and
would offer a wider variety of options to reduce charges for people
who make most calls on certain weekend days.
</P>
<P>
   Still, rates for many long-distance calls would go up under the
plan, with some customers potentially facing per-minute charges as
much as 56 percent higher.
</P>
<P>
   While William E. Kennard, the chairman of the Federal
Communications Commission, said he was encouraged by AT&AMP;T's move, a
fellow commissioner sharply criticized the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``With its latest tariff filing, AT&AMP;T failed to deliver the
consumer benefits it promised,'' Gloria Tristani, one of the five
FCC commissioners, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, which handles 60 percent of the United States' residential
long-distance calls, said it would give its 28 million customers
not on discount plans a choice of three options.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with the July telephone bills, one plan would allow
those customers to pay 16 cents a minute on all calls regardless of
time or day. Another plan would charge 10 cents a minute on one
weekend day chosen by the customer, but would impose higher charges
ranging from 18 cents to 29.5 cents a minute the rest of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Those who fail to select one of those plans would face rates
that would be raised several cents above AT&AMP;T's basic charges,
which are currently 11.5 cents on weekends, 26 cents on weekdays
and 16 cents on weekday evenings.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T said it consulted the FCC on the new rate plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe we've bent over backward to listen to people on
this,'' said James Cicconi, AT&AMP;T's general counsel. ``This reflects
extensive consultation with the FCC and with our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   The company said the new rate structure would cut its expected
profits for the year by a penny to 2 cents a share. Shares of AT&AMP;T
fell $1.6875, to $34.3125, on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also generally failed to impress consumer advocates,
who praised its increased flexibility but criticized it for not
passing on enough savings to customers from a recent FCC agreement
reducing the fees that long-distance companies pay to local phone
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``While they've responded to public criticism, AT&AMP;T has not gone
far enough,'' said Gene Kimmelman, the co-director of the
Washington office of Consumers Union, an advocacy group. ``But at
least this proposal is an improvement, because it provides people
with more choices than they previously had.''
</P>
<P>
   After the FCC lowered the fees paid by long-distance carriers to
local telephone companies, AT&AMP;T and other companies were expected
to pass on some of these savings to customers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet on the same day the agreement was announced, AT&AMP;T filed
documents with the commission that suggested that the company would
increase most of the per-minute charges for customers who make few
calls.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's filing, which was intended to mitigate the criticism
at the earlier proposal, AT&AMP;T eliminated its minimum monthly charge
of $3, a move that would benefit 15 million of the 28 million
customers that the company has under its basic plan. In addition,
AT&AMP;T eliminated a $1.51 carrier line charge.
</P>
<P>
   According to one of the plans put forward Friday, the company
would allow customers to make calls on one weekend day, either
Saturday or Sunday, for 10 cents a minute, a reduction from the
11.5 cents a minute that was available earlier. On the other
weekend day, though, charges would rise to 18 cents from 11.5
cents.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's proposal is cheaper when compared with the plan
submitted earlier this month that was discarded. Under that
proposal, customers were to be charged 29 cents a minute on all
days except Sunday, during which long-distance calls would cost 7
cents a minute.
</P>
<P>
   But for customers who do not choose any of AT&AMP;T's new plans, the
long-distance rates will go up, to 14.5 cents a minute from 11.5
cents on Saturday and Sunday, to 29.5 cents a minute from 26 cents
during peak hours on weekdays, and to 22.5 cents a minute from 19
cents on weeknights.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   WorldCom and Sprint, the second- and third-largest long-distance
companies, have not raised rates recently. Analysts suggested that
AT&AMP;T would probably not benefit from Friday's proposal, putting
additional pressure on the company's stock, which has declined
nearly 40 percent in the last three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guidance they're giving is that this should translate into
a net reduction in revenue,'' said Scott Cleland, a
telecommunications analyst at Legg Mason Precursor Group. ``This
isn't good for AT&AMP;T, given that they've been consistently losing
share to competitors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
