<HEADLINE>
NEW CAUCUS AIMS TO HELP NATION RIDE OUT THE STORM 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers) &HT;    
 By CARL HULSE  
NYT Regional Newspapers  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   WASHINGTON _ Natural disasters are
<TEXT>
hardly new. But to some members of Congress, the demands that
increasingly frequent hurricanes, floods, twisters and forest fires
place on federal relief efforts are nearing cataclysmic
proportions.
<P>
   Already this year, disasters have been declared in Alabama,
Kentucky, Tennessee, Texas and seven other states. Last year began
with tornadoes tearing through Arkansas, Louisiana and Georgia and
ended with Hurricane Floyd decimating parts of North Carolina and
the Eastern Seaboard, killing more than 50 people and doing an
estimated $6 billion in damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``No part of this country is immune to natural disasters,'' said
Sen. John Edwards, D-N.C.
</P>
<P>
   To better prepare the nation and Congress for future
catastrophes, Edwards and other lawmakers have formed the Natural
Hazards Caucus with the goals of making federal relief more
accessible and encouraging preventive action that can lower the
human and financial toll from any calamity.
</P>
<P>
   James Lee Witt, the head of the Federal Emergency Management
Agency, told the inaugural meeting of the caucus co-chaired by Sen.
Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, that the federal government spends only $25
million annually on disaster mitigation compared with billions
poured out for disaster aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mitigation and prevention saves lives, saves dollars and makes
good sense,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said the caucus hopes to propose ways to better
coordinate disaster response, streamline the process of applying
for aid, and encourage a public mind-set more geared toward
prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens said he would also like to advance legislation that
shifts more of the responsibility for insuring against major
disasters to the private sector, though he conceded such a proposal
has no chance in an election year.
</P>
<P>
   Caucuses are a common way for lawmakers to focus attention on
favorite causes. Their effectiveness is often related to the energy
put behind the organization. Some recent groups, such as the
moderate Blue Dog Coalition, have had significant impacts on
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Other Southern charter members of the Natural Hazard Caucus
include Democratic Sens. John Breaux of Louisiana, Max Cleland of
Georgia and Chuck Robb of Virginia and Republican Thad Cochran of
Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO VOTE
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco-state lawmakers from both parties want to extinguish
funding for the Clinton administration's lawsuit against the
tobacco industry to recoup federal health care spending on
smoking-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all Southern Republicans opposed spending $4 million
in Department of Veterans Affairs money to press the suit. And most
of the three dozen Democrats who voted with them also hailed from
the region, driven by sympathy for the growers they represent and a
fair amount of campaign money distributed by the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   The advocacy group Campaign for Tobacco Free Kids reported that
the 207 House members who voted to cut off funding for the suit
typically received five times the tobacco industry contributions of
those who backed the suit. Funding for the legal effort will be a
running feud as Congress sorts through the spending bills for the
agencies involved.
</P>
<P>
   WHOSE CHOICE?
</P>
<P>
   Congress might not be eager to fund school vouchers, but the
conservative Heritage Foundation found that lawmakers who oppose
them are not reluctant to send their own children to private
school.
</P>
<P>
   A poll of lawmakers done by the group determined that almost
half the senators and 40 percent of the House members who responded
had enrolled at least one child in a private school. The group said
that members of Congress who took advantage of private schools for
their own families helped defeat House and Senate measures that
would have given more Americans the same opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   But critics of school vouchers say their opposition doesn't stem
from anyone choosing private schools but instead is based on
resistance to using public dollars to support such institutions.
</P>
<P>
   MONUMENTAL PUSH
</P>
<P>
   While residents of the West are fighting Clinton administration
efforts to preserve land by granting it national monument status,
an Alabama group is pushing the White House to bestow the title on
two national forests in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Alabama National Monument Coalition met recently
with officials of the White House Council on Environmental Quality
to press for monument status for the Talladega and Bankhead
forests.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the group contend the forests are being exploited by
timber companies from outside the state, but they are certain to
run into opposition from groups concerned about any restrictions on
forest use.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington Bureau chief of the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
