<HEADLINE>
EPA PLAN TO STEM FLOW OF SMOG TO EAST COAST IS UPHELD BY COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal appeals court has upheld a new
air-pollution program meant to drastically reduce smog that flows
from the Midwest to the East.
</P>
<P>
   Although still subject to further appeals, the ruling on
Thursday by the District of Columbia U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
would affect 19 states. It upholds a decision by a three-judge
panel of the same tribunal, which held in March that rules set down
by the Environmental Protection Agency in 1998, but stayed by a
lawsuit, were proper.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision is a major environmental victory for everyone
living throughout the Eastern United States,'' Carol M. Browner,
the EPA administrator, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials have said the new rules could remove 1.1
million tons of nitrogen oxide _ equivalent to the pollution from
166 million cars _ from the air each year. They estimate that the
endeavor will cost $1.7 billion annually over 15 years but make up
for it in lower medical costs and better public health.
</P>
<P>
   Two environmental groups, the Natural Resources Defense Council
and the Clean Air Trust, expressed elation. ``This decision will
help clear up the smog that has been searing the lungs of people
across the Eastern United States,'' said David Hawkins, a lawyer
for the natural resources group.
</P>
<P>
   It was not certain how quickly the new rules, supposed to be in
place by 2003, would actually go into effect. Michigan and West
Virginia, whose officials contend that their states have been
treated unfairly, and other parties that have sued the EPA may seek
an appeal before the Supreme Court. Or lawmakers from those states
and others could fight the EPA in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Coal-burning power plants are the target of the regulatory
action because the smog-causing chemical the EPA is going after,
nitrogen oxide, is a byproduct of burning fossil fuels. Federal
officials say more than 100 million people live in regions where
the air would be improved, especially in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   New York, New Jersey and Connecticut and other states in the
East are also covered by the regulations, but the issue has
developed as one that pits those states and others against states
farther west. More than half the reductions in nitrogen oxide
emissions would come in six states: Illinois, Indiana, Michigan,
Ohio, Pennsylvania and West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Officials in New York state have viewed the new regulations
favorably, and EPA officials said Friday afternoon that the state
had already submitted plans for reducing its smog.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey has also moved to upgrade its coal plants, the EPA
said. Robert C. Schinn Jr., commissioner of New Jersey's Department
of Environmental Protection, called the appeals court action ``an
enormous boost'' for the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut officials, too, lauded the court decision. The
state's attorney general, Richard Blumenthal, said Friday that the
case was ``a poor candidate'' for Supreme Court review. ``There's
no conflict among the federal courts, it's plainly correct on the
merits and it requires no drastic change in national policy,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials estimate that the new rules would cost a
typical household $1 a month in extra electricity charges that the
utilities would pass on to their customers to cover costs of
upgrading equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The Midwest Ozone Group, a coalition of utilities and other
businesses that have contested the regulations, expressed
disappointment through its lawyer Kathy G. Beckett, who said group
members had been trying to cut down on pollution. She said the
coalition would consider an appeal to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental officials in Michigan and West Virginia said that
their states had been trying hard to cut down on their pollution,
and that they, too, would consider further appeals. They
questioned, too, whether their states really polluted New England
skies as much as some people suspected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do need to reduce our emissions, and I know we create some
problems for Pittsburgh,'' said Skipp Kropp, an environmental
official in West Virginia. ``But New Hampshire?''
</P>
<P>
   The 19 states have 128 days from the appeals court ruling, or
roughly to the end of October, to tell the EPA how they expect to
comply. Assuming the new rules go into effect, states that fall
short could face sanctions, including the loss of highway
construction money.
</P>
<P>
   Other states covered are Alabama, Delaware, Kentucky, Maryland,
Massachusetts, North Carolina, Rhode Island, South Carolina,
Tennessee and Virginia. Three others, Georgia, Missouri and
Wisconsin, were included in the EPA's original order, but the
appeals court removed them pending further review.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
