<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SKUBE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The closing riffs of a writer caught in a Catch-22
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 25.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Portrait of an Artist,
</P>
<P>
   as an Old Man. By Joseph Heller. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $23.
</P>
<P>
   With aging comes a good chance not just of atherosclerosis but
also a certain peace of mind, a disinclination to kickhorses you
once kicked dead or alive or to disturb the dog's slumber. It can
be a sad thing, not catastrophic like a coronary but sweet-sad in
the way a sunset can be when minute by minute the day is slipping
away. Like the fire whose heat is ebbing, a writer's creative
juices are an exhaustible resource, and no one knows it better than
the writer himself.
</P>
<P>
   So conscious of it are they that many writers are convinced
they're running on empty, with miles to go and a contract hanging
over their heads. Others, like the late Joseph Heller, live the
self-torture of trying to repeat what cannot be repeated.
</P>
<P>
   With his first book, Heller entered both a title and an idea
into the vernacular. Because of Heller, even people who don't read
know what a ``Catch-22'' is. Heller's satirical war novel,
published in 1961, crystallized a no-win situation with mordant
accuracy, even if critics were slow to recognize it.
</P>
<P>
   Heller captured the particular insanity of the military _ of any
bureaucracy _ only too well, and every novel he published
subsequently was widely reviewed but inevitably compared with the
one that was wittier, crisper in its dialogue, sharper in its
delineation of our social maladies and, inevitably, just a little
better. Many were best sellers, because he had made his name. But
book by book _ seven in all _ they were judged to have fallen
short, and by a little more each time.
</P>
<P>
   It makes little difference that Heller's 1974 novel ``Something
Happened,'' a satire of the corporation's crushing effects on
individuality, today seems as funny as and more contemporary than
``Catch-22.'' The common opinion was that Heller had already said
what he had to say.
</P>
<P>
   But he wanted to be celebrated one last time, like the drunk who
hears his bar stool buddies toasting him as he heads off into the
night. In ``Portrait of an Artist, as an Old Man,'' Heller's
autobiographical protagonist Eugene Pota tells his editor: ``I want
to cap my career with a masterpiece of some kind, a great, original
work, even a great very small one. I want to crown my end with
applause, to go out on a note of triumph. Like an athlete dying
young, but my race finally run.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be too easy, and unkind, to pull the leg back and lay
the boot into this expired thoroughbred. Better that we note, with
disappointment and regret, that this time he really did pull up
lame. ``Portrait of an Artist, as an Old Man'' is not a book that
needed to be published, and Simon &AMP; Schuster certainly knows it. It
is like a guitarist closing his show with a series of riffs, some
of them brilliant but none of them connected to anything whole.
</P>
<P>
   Heller the man died of a heart attack. Heller the artist died in
the paralysis of writer's block. The autopsy, if you have $23 to
spare, is here between covers. Heller wrote it himself:
</P>
<P>
   ``The artificer who lives long enough, particularly the writer
of fictions for page and stage, may come to a time in his life when
he feels he has nothing new to write about but wishes to continue
anyway. Musicians joke in belittlement about the last compositions
of Mozart, who died young, that he did not know when to quit.
Shakespeare did know when to quit: `Our revels now are ended,' he
wrote in `The Tempest,' and departed with his winnings for the role
of a country squire in Stratford.''
</P>
<P>
   Give a dead man the benefit of the doubt and assume the implied
comparisons were unintended. All that need be said is that Heller
had an aberrant, skewed sense of humor that _ in more books than
just his first _ nailed our obsessions and frailties. He was once
himself the fresh new voice, and at the end of his life he saw how
frantically we search for anything new and novel: ``After all, a
new talent can be discovered only once. And astonish hardly more
than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more darkly, ``Portrait of an Artist'' sees marital fault
lines with a spooky clarity: ``Talkative and good-natured, she
commonly had very much more she wished to say than he cared to
hear, and she often found herself in what she thought of as a
Catch-22: she must either refrain from talking to him about things
she wished to talk to somebody about, in effect surrender her right
to freedom of speech, or risk his irritated, sometimes furious
discontent by boring him loquaciously, and neither seemed fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Heller, as it happens, was caught in a Catch-22 of his own:
``Like others am
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
