<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-PARLAYMPICS0624-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big wheels training in Warm Springs
 &HT;    By Mike Tierney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARM SPRINGS, Ga. _ Franklin D. Roosevelt was a visionary.
Ranked second all-time on your presidential hit parade by a panel
of historians, he left a legacy ranging from his New Deal policies
to his recognition of the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the polio-stricken FDR in his wheelchair today, tooling
around his old stomping grounds, chatting up the distinguished
boarders at the Roosevelt Warm Springs Institute for
Rehabilitation. Not even he could have foreseen that the facility
someday would lure accomplished disabled athletes from across the
globe to train for events such as the upcoming Paralympics in
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   An inquisitive sort, FDR might have had some questions for what
surely would be his favorite competitors _ these big deals on
wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Are more racers disabled through congenital or childhood
diseases, or by accidents? About one in every four is a victim,
mostly of disease, at birth or at a young age, estimates Wendy
Gumbert, director of the Roosevelt Sports Training Center. Those
athletes enter the sport with a mental edge because they have long
been accustomed to coping with their infirmities.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't know what it's like to be able-bodied,'' Gumbert
said. ``(If it happens) at 18, you're going to go through a
depression phase. It's a total life change.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue-ribbon racer Saul Mendoza of Mexico was afflicted by polio
at age 1. The upstart Josh Brunies of Hammond, La., and the
established Louise Savage, an Australian who hauled away four gold
medals from the 1996 Paralympics, are spina bifida casualties from
an early age. Cheri Blauwet was a year old when her father
accidentally drove a tractor over her on their farm in Larchwood,
Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   The majority includes John MacLean, a 33-year-old Aussie who was
riding a bike in 1988 when he was hit by an 8-ton truck going
nearly 70 mph. The Canadian Andre Beaudoin was 20 when he crashed
on a motocross bike while zipping across a field. ``When you're
young,'' Beaudoin said, ``you do things you don't know are
dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ted Brides? Now, there's a story.
</P>
<P>
   LET'S HEAR IT
</P>
<P>
   A triple amputee from Miami, he was a platoon leader in Vietnam
in 1970. One morning, he left a foxhole to fill some canteens and
caught mortar fire on the way back. ``I felt like I was being
billowed up in a cloud,'' he recalled. He landed to see his fingers
at odd angles and his legs splayed. ``I remember feeling oddly calm
about it. There was relief that I was going home.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, 54, he didn't take up wheelchair racing until 10 years ago,
inspired by a man who eventually raced a 5-miler at age 83 a few
months before his death. In 1995, he told himself, ``I'm getting
too old for this.'' But he won two medals in Atlanta and is back
for more.
</P>
<P>
   How can a triple amputee race? Brides uses a wheelchair that
allows him to steer by placing the hook, which replaced his right
arm, into a ring. He ``pulls'' with his left arm.
</P>
<P>
   That's nothing. Quadruple amputee Tony Valenpost, a sprinter,
places his nubs on paint cans for traction and pushes off for fast
starts.
</P>
<P>
   How much strategy is involved in racing? A lot. Racers can draft
off each other, same as race-car drivers. Some pace themselves,
while others go all-out to seize the lead and dare competitors to
come get them. Racers have to find the proper path. Taking the
inside lane saves ground, but they can veer to the outside for an
unobstructed route.
</P>
<P>
   Listening to the racers is like eavesdropping on Dale Earnhardt
talking with his crew chief: drafting, pulling, boxing in, blocking
out, breaking the pace . . . .
</P>
<P>
   Even the tires involve some thought. Do you inflate them to high
pressure and maximize speed or cut off the pump and lower the risk
of a blowout?
</P>
<P>
   Are there collisions? Oh, yeah. Many racers observe a
gentleman's agreement and make way for charging competitors, but
it's not always the case, and crashes can occur. Josh Brunies,
sporting a nasty forearm bruise from a wreck the day before, said,
``Some people are out there for themselves. They don't care what
happens to everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   How important are the wheelchairs to the racers? To some, like a
member of the family. ``I used to beat my chair, but you gotta baby
your chair. I don't want nobody touching mine,'' said Brunies, who
refuses to check his as baggage on flights. Sauvage has a beloved
beat-up chair that is remindful of the old, rusting car you cannot
part with.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza damaged his cherished chair in a collision early in the
Atlanta Paralympics. ``I'm done,'' he said. ``I better go home.'' A
replacement arrived, and Mendoza spun the new wheels to a record.
</P>
<P>
   Racers can rig their chairs with tape to make them more
aerodymanic, but improved technology has made them fairly uniform
and equally fast.
</P>
<P>
   Is wheelchair racing a full-time job? For the upper crust, yes.
Mendoza, a Los Angeles Marathon winner four consecutive times,
trains mornings and afternoons, covering as much as 125 miles per
week on the roads of Pine Mountain. For him, the Institute is home
for about eight months of the year. Like others, he has easy access
to Hartsfield International for flying to competitions around the
world. He entered 30 races last year _ winning 28, worth as much as
$5,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   Sauvage, who generally does road work in the a.m. and gym work
after lunch, competes in well-paying marathons, such as Boston. She
collected $10,000 by winning there once. This year, she finished
second.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the elite have sponsorship deals. McClain has appeared
in a few shoe commercials overseas, one in which he starred as The
Mayor of Niketown.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's largely a hard labor of love. Mendoza, for all of
his success, makes a modest living. A college graduate, he retired
in 1988, unretired two weeks later. ``I couldn't handle it,'' he
said. ``I realized it was my passion.''
</P>
<P>
   For others, it's just one part of their lives. Blauwet, 19, is a
4.0 student at the University of Arizona in molecular biology and
music who plays clarinet and piano. Her boyfriend is an able-bodied
triathlete.
</P>
<P>
   So, these people are real athletes? You bet. MacLean's accident
occurred while he was training for a triathlon. Since, he has
competed in the Ironman in Hawaii and has swum the English Channel.
Brides played college football. Mendoza was named Mexico's athlete
of the year in 1996. Sauvage says, ``My life is sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Role models, too. Mendoza has lifted the spirits of disabled
Hispanic kids at Grady Memorial Hospital. MacLean aspires to teach
youngsters ``to be a player, not a spectator.'' Blauwet sees
herself operating sports camps for the disabled someday.
</P>
<P>
   What makes a good disabled athlete? A spirit of independence
helps. Blauwet's parents encouraged her to reach to the top shelf
for items rather than fetching them for her. Also, a high pain
threshhold. Sauvage hyperextended her elbow and, rather than taking
R&AMP;R, taped it up and kept training. She and Blauwet have rods
implanted in their backs.
</P>
<P>
   What do you think of the Roosevelt Warm Springs Institute as a
place to train? ``It's brilliant,'' MacLean said.
</P>
<P>
   So, you might say it's the New Deal. Is that why everyone seems
in such a good mood here? Well, if you listen closely, you will
hear complaints about the track surface that raises the risk of
accidents. But, overall, these are grateful men and women.
</P>
<P>
   Here is Wendy Gumbert's take on the smiles: ``They are totally
happy with their lives. Any barriers (about being disabled) were
broken a long time ago. Had they not broken them, they wouldn't be
competing for the Paralympics.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
