<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3413 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-JFKJR-CRASH-BOS &LR;      06-23 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JFKJR-CRASH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOURCES SAY NTSB, KENNEDYS CLASHED AFTER JFK JR. CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Amid reports that the National Transportation Safety
Board is expected to rule that pilot error by John F. Kennedy Jr.
caused the plane crash that killed him, his wife and her sister,
Washington sources claim the agency's handling of information
during the subsequent investigation caused friction between the
offices of Sen. Edward M. Kennedy and NTSB chairman James Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulties first surfaced in the hours after Kennedy's
plane crashed, and became so pronounced that the White House
enlisted Cabinet secretary Thurgood Marshall Jr. to help facilitate
communications.
</P>
<P>
   The raw feelings from last summer burst to the forefront again
Friday after ``NBC Nightly News'' on Thursday reported the NTSB's
expected findings: That on July 16 John Kennedy Jr. became
disoriented in the murky night sky and lost control of the plane
off the coast of Martha's Vineyard. The report is scheduled to be
released next month.
</P>
<P>
   Like many relatives of loved ones who die in airplane crashes,
those close to the Kennedys felt the NTSB did not keep them up to
date on the search and investigation, the sources said. While NTSB
staffers _ including then-managing director Peter Goelz _ met
frequently with Kennedy staffers, preliminary agreements frequently
bogged down.
</P>
<P>
   One source said Goelz and US Coast Guard Rear Admiral Richard
Larrabee would return from meetings with the Kennedys only to find
``fencing'' inside the agency about how to handle queries from the
senator's office.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the difficulties stemmed from the flow of
communications, a Washington source said, adding that news
reporters sometimes got information about the search and
disseminated it before Senator Kennedy's office knew about it.
</P>
<P>
   Reached Friday, Senator Kennedy's spokesman, Will Keyser, had no
comment about the NTSB report or relations between the senator's
office and the NTSB.
</P>
<P>
   For someone like Senator Kennedy, a senior legislator who is
accustomed to getting questions answered quickly, the experience
may have been particularly painful, said a transportation source.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB final report on the crash, prepared by regional
investigator Robert Pearce in Parsippany, N.J., was sent to NTSB
headquarters in Washington in the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said that the report has been reviewed by fewer than six
people, among them chairman Hall _ the only one of five
presidentially appointed board members to see it _ and Aviation
Safety Chief Bernard Loeb and counsel Daniel Campbell. The NTSB did
not tell Kennedy's office about the general thrust of the final
report before it was leaked to the media, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Goelz, who is no longer with the NTSB, also refused to comment
Friday. And NTSB spokesman Ted Lopatkiewicz also would not talk
about the matter, adding that Hall was out of the country and could
not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the sensitive nature of investigating a crash in which
John Kennedy Jr. _ the celebrity son of a beloved president and
nephew of a powerful senator _ was at the controls, several sources
insist the NTSB did not alter the report to eliminate the phrase
``pilot error.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the agency, which investigates all aviation accidents
and recommends safety improvements does not use the phrase ``pilot
error'' in its investigations, transportation officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Two sources familiar with the investigation said the Kennedy
crash is unlikely to lead the NTSB to include any new safety
recommendations in the report, such as requiring pilots who fly at
night to be certified in reading instruments.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, who had more than 300 hours of flying time, was working
toward a rating that would have allowed him to fly the
single-engine plane by looking only at instruments, including an
indicator with an artificial horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots use that instrument to prevent the effects of spatial
disorientation, a confusion resulting from an imbalance in the
inner ear. The condition leads pilots to believe they are flying
level when in fact the plane is out of control.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing mechanically wrong with Kennedy's plane, which
had an autopilot that would have helped him keep the wings level
and slowly descend as he approached Martha's Vineyard, where his
sister-in-law Lauren Bessette was to get off. John Kennedy and his
wife, Carolyn Bessette Kennedy, had planned to fly on to Hyannis
for the wedding of Kennedy's cousin, Rory.
</P>
<P>
   Two sources familiar with the investigation said it was unlikely
the report, which is still being reviewed, would fault Kennedy for
not using the autopilot.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how many times _ if at all _ Senator Kennedy and
Hall spoke directly to each other in the hours and days after the
accident. Some sources said a grief-stricken Kennedy was attending
to family matters and did not meet with NTSB or White House
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was not the NTSB board member on call at the time,
Hall traveled to the scene in Cape Cod anyway, and gained national
exposure from frequent news conferences _ raising speculation in
Washington about his motives.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to Hall, however, said he was not seeking
limelight; rather, he was nearby on Long Island for the anniversary
of the TWA Flight 800 disaster, and knew from the TWA investigation
that several different agencies would be involved in the Kennedy
crash investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Only the NTSB chairman or its managing director can immediately
ask other agencies for assistance, and Hall wanted to make sure the
crash team had every resource it needed. Still, there were concerns
over who would pay for the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the investigation said the Coast Guard ordered
the Navy salvage vessel USS Grasp to the search site, but the NTSB
hesitated at paying for it. The White House eventually determined
that each agency should carry its own costs, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Once the White House got involved, Marshall and Andrew Cuomo _
secretary of Housing and Urban Development and husband of Kerry
Kennedy Cuomo _ became pivotal players. Cuomo, who was in Hyannis
for the family wedding, quickly became a liaison, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the difficulties in communication, there were moments
when everything clicked, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   One transportation source said that on July 23, when a memorial
service was held in New York City for Kennedy, his wife and
sister-in-law, the USS Grasp had completed its salvage work. The
ship was initially scheduled to dock during the memorial service,
but NTSB and Navy officials agreed to keep it at sea during the
service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
