</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CONRAD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 CAMPAIGN-FINANCE INVESTIGATOR IS PRAISED FOR SKILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (With GORE-FUNDRAISING) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Attorney General Janet Reno appointed Robert
Conrad to direct the Justice Department's campaign finance task
force late last year, she praised his prosecutorial skills and said
she expected him to ``expand upon the successes'' of the campaign
finance inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Barely six months later, Conrad handed her a political hot
potato by recommending that she appoint an independent counsel to
investigate Vice President Al Gore's involvement in fund raising
for the 1996 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad, 42, earned a reputation as a skilled prosecutor and
trial attorney during more than 10 years in the U.S. attorney's
office in Charlotte, N.C., those who have worked with him say. From
1992 until last year, Conrad was chief of the office's criminal
division.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad's former boss in Charlotte, U.S. Attorney Mark Calloway,
called Conrad one of the most capable prosecutors he had ever
worked with. ``He is a relentless investigator and has a high sense
of duty and fairness,'' Calloway said when Conrad was appointed to
the Justice Department post in December.
</P>
<P>
   A former North Carolina attorney general, Lacy H. Thornburg,
praised Conrad's courtroom skills. ``Bob is a seasoned prosecutor
and skilled trial attorney,'' Thornburg said.
</P>
<P>
   But Democratic officials on Friday questioned Conrad's
impartiality, noting that he had contributed $250 in 1996 to the
re-election campaign of Sen. Jesse Helms of North Carolina, a
staunch conservative Republican and a consistent foe of the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   The donation to Helms is apparently the only political
contribution Conrad has ever made, according to federal election
records.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad went to work for the U.S. attorney's office in 1989. Tom
Ashcraft, then the U.S. attorney, had been a member of Helms'
Senate staff and served on the board of the Jesse Helms Center, a
foundation controlled by the senator. He was appointed to the U.S.
attorney's post by President Ronald Reagan in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad is a graduate of the University of Virginia Law School
and Clemson University, where he was a basketball star and an
academic all-American.
</P>
<P>
   Reno established the campaign finance task force in 1996 to
investigate accusations of illegality in the 1996 presidential
campaign. The task force has indicted 22 people over the last four
years for campaign finance abuses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 2132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0411 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3435 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-KOREA-U.S.-ALBRIGHT-N     06-23 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-U.S.-ALBRIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A U.S. PULLOUT ISN'T PLANNED IN SOUTH KOREA, ALBRIGHT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ Trying to dampen speculation that the
prospects of reconciliation on the Korean Peninsula would lead to a
smaller U.S. military presence in South Korea, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright stressed Friday that U.S. troops would not be
withdrawn any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   With Foreign Minister Lee Joung-binn of South Korea at her side,
Albright said that talk of reducing U.S. troops was ``not
appropriate'' and ``premature'' and that the troops would continue
to be a deterrent against North Korea and a stabilizing force in
the region.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said even if the two Koreas agreed to end the Korean War
with a peace treaty, U.S. troops would ``continue to play their
role as a guarantor of the balance of power.''
</P>
<P>
   The first senior administration official to visit South Korea
after the summit meeting last week between the North and South
Korean leaders, Albright arrived here to learn more about what
occurred and to establish Washington's interests as the
reconciliation unfolds. She met President Kim Dae-jung and then
Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's presence also put a spotlight on the 37,000 U.S.
troops here and what role they might have in the future. Protests
have been growing for several months at a U.S. Air Force bombing
range 50 miles southwest of the capital.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference with Albright, Lee said Kim had told his
North Korean counterpart, Kim Jong Il, at their meeting that he
wanted U.S. troops to stay in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that we have expanded the North Korean
understanding on this particular issue,'' Lee said. ``The American
forces will be needed here even after the establishment of a peace
regime on the Korean Peninsula.''
</P>
<P>
   The nature of the North Korean leader's reply has remained
somewhat unclear and was not clarified at the news conference. In
the last several days, however, administration officials said they
had been pleased that Kim Dae-jung had raised the question of U.S.
troops at the Pyongyang meeting and suggested that the North Korean
leader's response did not appear to be unsatisfactory.
</P>
<P>
   One administration official with knowledge of post-summit
briefings by senior South Korean officials said the North Korean
leader had indicated that he was not eager to have the U.S. troops
leave South Korea. It is possible, the official said, to draw a
very rough analogy from the fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989, when
the Soviet Union did not push for the pullout of U.S. troops from
West Germany.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea might be content to see a continued U.S. military
presence, the official said, albeit in a different mode, to ensure
that a vacuum was not created as changes occurred over what could a
drawn-out reunification.
</P>
<P>
   Another U.S. official said when the South Korean president told
Kim Jong Il that he wanted U.S. troops to remain as reunification
progressed, the North Korean indicated that he ``was not totally
opposed to this,'' the official said, recounting a briefing that
South Korean government had given him.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the Pyongyang summit meeting caught U.S. policy
makers off guard. In the days since then, they have confronted
unanticipated questions in public and private about the role of
U.S. troops. In Washington, questions abut the size and components
of the military presence are being raised.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, officials are stressing that the meeting, as
Albright said Friday, was promising, but had not resolved anything.
</P>
<P>
   In answer to a South Korean reporter's question, Albright said:
``We have alliance structures with Japan and South Korea. We don't
put a time limit on our responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. military role in the South has changed in the last
decade. The troops have moved from a leading to a supporting role
in defense. But the South Korean government has continued to argue
that its own forces could not deter an invasion from North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Albright also tried to emphasize that the United States had its
own channels to North Korea. She said that Washington would soon
reopen talks with North Korea aimed at curbing its missile
development and that it had just completed a round of talks in Rome
with North Korea on ensuring that its nuclear program is for
civilian use only.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
