<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3436 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TV-SPORTS-MILLER-BOS &LR;      06-23 1381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-MILLER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADDING COMEDIAN TO `MNF' A RATINGS HAIL MARY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (s and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dennis Miller on Monday Night Football?
</P>
<P>
   Don't laugh yet. It's been tried before.
</P>
<P>
   Dandy Don Meredith left ``Monday Night Football'' after the 1974
season, and producer Don Olhmeyer wanted to hire Bill Cosby to
replace him. Cosby had played football at Temple University and
Ohlymeyer said he believed Cosby would have been perfect. But the
deal never happened. Nor did a possible deal with Burt Reynolds.
Ohlmeyer ended up hiring ex-player Alex Karras.
</P>
<P>
   Before all the sports purists get further lathered up, ``Monday
Night Football'' has always been about entertainment. The naming of
Miller, the former member of ``Saturday Night Live'' and current
HBO host, is only the latest attempt to attract casual observers to
ABC.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, it was announced that Miller would join Al Michaels
and Dan Fouts in the broadcasting booth.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Gunther, co-author of ``Monday Night Mayhem,'' a 1988
account of the NFL's showcase game, said the hiring of Miller
symbolizes a return to the show's roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Roone Arledge created the show in 1970, the whole notion
was to create a program that appealed to the casual fan,'' Gunther
said. ``It's a smart thing to hire Miller. The show had lost track
of it's history of going for marquee names, the guys that were
bigger than sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the purists don't want to hear any of that
entertainment stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird,'' said Peter King, NFL analyst for CNN/SI. ``I
can't believe the NFL is very happy about Dennis Miller being on
it's showcase game. We're not taking about a football game anymore.
There are probably some (NFL team) owners like (Dallas's) Jerry
Jones or (New England's) Bob Kraft who are excited about the
possibility of earning huge ratings and more television money. Then
there are the other NFL owners who remain purists at heart who are
probably throwing up somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is not whether sports is entertainment, but whether
hiring Miller is enough to reverse the almost epidemic hemorrhaging
of viewers. For ``Monday Night Football,'' the loss is particularly
acute among males 18-34, many of whom are glued to professional
wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's desperation,'' said Robert Thompson, a Syracuse
University professor of television and film. ``It is a stunt to
attract viewers and rekindle the glory days of the 1970s when the
action in the booth was more exciting than on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Those days are long gone. With more channels, more sports, more
outrageousness, the hiring of a comedian barely makes a ripple,
especially considering that the smart-ass sports commentator is the
most duplicated schtick in America.
</P>
<P>
   NBC Sports chairman Dick Ebersol joked that he was glad the
search was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God the monumentally important hunt for `MNF' talent is
over and at last newspapers everywhere can get back to the vital
task of finding the Lindberg baby,'' said Ebersol, who himself is
looking to boost ratings next year by launching a new football
league with World Wrestling Federation president Vince McMahon.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was insouciant. Talk radio shows hummed with
outrage over Miller's hiring. Just as plentiful were tempered
comments of praise. Of the 14,000 respondents to a CNN/SI poll, 30
percent said hiring Miller was a terrible idea, 28 percent said
wait and see, 22 percent said it was a great idea, and 20 percent
said at least it is not Rush Limbaugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look back at what the sports media critics wrote
about Howard Cosell, it was horrible,'' said Bill Carter, a New
York Times television writer and co-author of ``Monday Night
Mayhem.'' ``But hiring a (non-football) person was an innovation of
the '70s that has been done and redone. The challenge for them is
to keep the diehards and the causal fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Straight football hasn't worked. Dan Dierdorf played football,
as did Boomer Esiason, but neither struck a chord with viewers.
Television ratings for ``Monday Night Football'' reached a peak in
1981 with a 21.8 average rating (or about 21 million households).
That number has steadily declined to a 13.7 rating last season.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with strong competition from professional wrestling on
cable and network shows such as Fox's ``Ally McBeal'' and CBS's
``Everybody Loves Raymond,'' ``Monday Night Football'' lost almost
20 percent of its male viewers last year between 18 and 34. CBS and
Fox have been able to stay even, or grow slightly, in that
important demographic. The statistics also show that the three
networks with football coverage are basically attracting the same
percentage of male and female viewers.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, no one is standing out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It remains to be seen whether the on-air talent can have an
impact on the ratings,'' said Neil Pilson, the former CBS Sports
president. ``Most people tune into a game because of a matchup. ABC
wasn't lucky last year. They are hoping that Miller appeals to the
younger, hipper viewers.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL, for one, is hoping that the entertainment strategy
works. NFL spokesman Greg Aiello said that a few months ago NFL
commissioner Paul Tagliabue told him ``Monday Night Football'' had
to be more entertaining because it was on in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He believes that `MNF' has to be more than just Xs and Os,
more than graphics and statistics and more entertaining,'' said
Aiello, who described the Miller hiring as ``inspiring.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox officials agreed hiring Miller was a great idea. The network
took a chance last year and hired Jimmy Kimmel, a regular on Comedy
Central and host of a Los Angeles radio show. When he first
appeared on Fox's Emmy Award-winning pregame show with James Brown,
Terry Bradshaw, Cris Collinsworth, and Howie Long, viewers sent
angry letters to the network asking why.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's entertainment,'' said Scott Ackerson, a Fox Sports
coordinating producer. ``We took a lot of heat on Kimmel but it
worked out fine. At the end of the year, people told us that they
thought he was funny. It really is about entertainment, pure and
simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the blowout games last year on ``Monday Night Football,''
including the San Francisco 49ers-Atlanta Falcons matchup when both
teams were out of playoff contention, entertainment might be the
show's saving grace.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you did television for the purists, you would get a 2
rating,'' Ackerson said. ``What you want to have is when the game
is a blowout, people still hang around. When the game is close,
anyone could call it. But they might hang on longer if it's
entertaining. Hey, my hat is off to ABC for stepping up and doing
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether ABC's gamble is successful remains to be seen. A lot
depends on the quality of the games. A lot also depends on Miller,
who arguably started the smart-ass style copied by ESPN anchors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if this is going to work,'' said Robertson. ``In
the '70s, there were only two other choices and `Monday Night
Football' was more of a variety show with football in the
background. Nowadays there are hundreds of other options for people
who don't watch sports. Maybe Miller can stem the flow. He is
enough of a loose-cannon and unpredictable character that viewers
might tune in just to see what he says. But I'm worried that the
television audience will continue to leave regardless of who is in
the booth. Hiring a comedian was a great stunt for the old
networks. It's not for the modern-day cable universe.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, 47, is undaunted. Known for his caustic wit on ``Dennis
Miller Live'' on HBO -- ``I don't want to get off on a rant'' or
``Of course, that's just my opinion, I could be wrong'' -- Miller
readily concedes that he was a ``quirky hire.'' He also explained
that he knows what it's like to follow in the footsteps of a
legend. Miller came after Chevy Chase as the weekend anchor on
``Saturday Night Live.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't Chevy Chase and I'm not going to be Howard Cosell,''
Miller said. ``I don't know football broadcasting, but I know how
to work in front of a camera and I will (work hard) coming up with
lots of information. I'll do the best I can, but I can only be me.
I can't change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 2135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
