<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3461 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-RUN-MARION-JONES0624-     06-23 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-MARION-JONES0624-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jones takes big leap in drive for 5
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUGENE, Ore. _ Aspiring to be an Olympic diva has some
non-negotiable requirements. You've got to package your celebrity
by publishing a book, be cast in a catchy ad campaign for Nike and,
most important, separate yourself from the pack.
</P>
<P>
   Have a dream, girl.
</P>
<P>
   Marion Jones has it all working. The star of Nike's ``Me &AMP; Mrs.
Jones'' commercials just released a book, ``See How She Runs,'' and
has an unprecedented Olympic appetite. She is staking out five gold
medals, which beats the heck out of what Michael Johnson brought to
the Atlanta Games and is something never before attempted
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   If everything goes according to script in Sydney, you can bet on
NBC selling the striking 24-year-old as the greatest female athlete
in the universe.
</P>
<P>
   That she can rush to gold in the 100 and 200 meters is a solid
possibility. It gets a little dicey in the 400 and 1,600-meter
relays, with the risk of a dropped baton and the reliance on
others. But her Sydney dream could hit the pits in the long jump,
where Mrs. Jones _ actually married to world champion shot-putter
C.J. Hunter _ is, at best, a work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   Jones takes another pre-Olympic Trials crack today at the long
jump in the Prefontaine Classic Grand Prix, where she also will
display her 100-meter speed.
</P>
<P>
   It is a hectic weekend for the sport, with top Americans and a
handful of elite foreigners competing at either the Nike-sponsored
Prefontaine or the rival Adidas Oregon Track Classic on Sunday in
Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt, the long jump is going to be the most
challenging,'' acknowledged Jones, expected to be the breakout star
of the Sydney Games. ``I never said going after the five events
would be an easy task. I've always proceeded along this whole road
knowing that it would be quite difficult, but I'm up for the
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   And the chore.
</P>
<P>
   When healthy, no one in the world can touch her in the sprints.
Jones has been ranked No. 1 in the world by Track &AMP; Field News in
both the 100 and 200 each of the last three years. She also opened
this season with a 49.59 seconds clocking in the 400,
fourth-fastest time by an American ever.
</P>
<P>
   Since the spring of 1997, Jones has run 57 finals in the 100 and
200-meter sprints and has won all but four. Only the late Florence
Griffith Joyner ever has run faster.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones has yet to beat anyone in an Olympic spotlight, and
two-time gold medalist Gail Devers and the talented Inger Miller
lurk in the 100.
</P>
<P>
   As a high school senior, Jones qualified as an alternate on the
400-meter relay team for the 1992 Barcelona Games, but she passed
to play basketball at North Carolina. In 1996, injuries kept her
away from the trials.
</P>
<P>
   At last summer's World Championships, billed as a dress
rehearsal for the Games, she promised to win four events. In the
end, she won only the 100. She placed third in the long jump and
headed home after pulling up lame with back spasms in the 200
semis.
</P>
<P>
   It has been suggested that the physical strain of the long jump
caught up with her, but Jones will hear nothing of it. ``The
problems had nothing to do with the long jump,''' she said. ``I
felt perfectly fine.''
</P>
<P>
   But the long jump is her weak event. Three-time Olympic champion
Jackie Joyner-Kersee, 38, is weighing whether to leap out of
retirement next month for the trials. Spaniard Niurka Montalvo and
Fiona May of Italy cast are considerd the top gold-medal contenders
in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Jones began the season suffering her worst performance of the
past three years in the Osaka Grand Prix, where she placed fourth
with a best of 20-7. Last weekend, she went a modest 21-6 and was
upset by training partner Chandra Sturrup in a meet in Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime I decide to jump, the pressure is going to be there,
simply because I've had some problems in the past,'' Jones said.
``We sat down long and hard after Osaka, and I wasn't very
comfortbale with the new style we were using. So we went back to
what worked in `98. Although people criticized in 98, it wasn't
nearly as much as people are criticizing now.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones scrapped plans to turn herself into a power jumper who
explodes into the air off the board. Instead, she is returning to
her basic form of sprinting off the takeover board in an almost
flat arc over the sand. Her technique isn't pretty, but it produced
a jump of nearly 24 feet two seasons ago.
</P>
<P>
   With her heavy workload, it figures to be important for Jones to
pop a good early jump in the trials and Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the goal, always,'' she said. ``Historically for me,
it has taken four, five, six jumps. So I'm quite used to that. I'm
a competitor, and if somebody like a Fiona May or Heike Drechsler
is behind me, I'm not going to pass knowing they have the
capability of jumping 23 feet at any moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 24 years old, if I can't take six jumps in a competition,
then what is going to happen when I'm 28 or 29? I might as well do
it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
