<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3465 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-DRAFT-DIPIETRO-BO     06-23 1437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DRAFT-DIPIETRO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISLANDERS SETTING SIGHTS ON DIPIETRO? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta _ When you think about teenagers lobbying
parents for something, it's usually for a later curfew, borrowing
the car on a Saturday night, or pushing for Internet time.
</P>
<P>
   The requests usually aren't to move more than 600 miles from
home after your sophomore year of high school or bidding farewell
to college after your freshman year.
</P>
<P>
   But Rick DiPietro campaigned for both of those things, convinced
his parents he was right, and Saturday at the Saddledome, he is in
a position to be the highest American-born goaltender selected in
the National Hockey League draft since Tom Barrasso in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Barrasso was picked fifth by Buffalo and went right to the the
Sabres' lineup out of Acton-Boxborough (Mass.) High School. Word
around the rink was that the New York Islanders, who have the No. 1
pick, were gearing up to not only select DiPietro, but to have a
contract in place before stepping to the podium.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders, who have been handcuffed by financial
restrictions the last few years, are expected to increase their
payroll significantly this season. The other part of the equation
revolving around DiPietro is whether the Islanders can reach a deal
for their current goalie of the future _ Roberto Luongo, whom the
Islanders took fourth overall in 1997. If they can get a
significant return for him, it's likely DiPietro would go first.
</P>
<P>
   DiPietro, whose family resides in Winthrop, Mass., is the
top-ranked North American goalie after a sensational showing at the
World Junior Tournament and an outstanding freshman season at
Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   The road here, though, was paved through Ann Arbor, Mich., first
and Boston's Commonwealth Avenue second _ the first destination
DiPietro had to fight for and the second he elected to walk away
from.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After a year at St. Sebastian's, where DiPietro and current
Boston College goalie Tim Kelleher sat on the bench watching Mike
Morrison (now at the University of Maine) stop pucks, DiPietro put
together a sales pitch and went about lobbying his parents to allow
him to go to Ann Arbor to play in the Team USA Development Program,
which, at the time, was headed by former Lake Superior State coach
Jeff Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   DiPietro's argument was the glut of goalies at St. Sebastian's
and the fact that his progress was being hindered. DiPietro yearned
for a more substantial opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hated it, he hated it,'' said DiPietro's father, Rick,
about his son's season at St. Sebastian's. ``He wanted to play.
When he was playing in the Metropolitan Boston League, the goal was
to get into an independent school like St. Sebastian's or Belmont
Hill and then become a starting goaltender. It was very frustrating
for him to have to sit on the bench. We had always wanted him to go
to an independent school and never board. We wanted him to be at
home right through high school. When he said he wanted to go to Ann
Arbor it was a tough decision for us, especially for his mother.''
</P>
<P>
   DiPietro, who is represented by Boston-based Woolf Associates,
flourished in the program and continued to excel at BU. In the
World Junior tournament in Sweden in December and January, DiPietro
became just the second American in the competition's 23-year
history to earn the Directorate Award as the tourney's outstanding
goalie. Last spring, he set an NCAA tournament record with 77 saves
in BU's 3-2 quadruple-overtime loss to St. Lawrence in the NCAA
quarterfinals, the longest game in tournament history.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the May 1 deadline for opting into the NHL draft loomed,
DiPietro sat his parents down again. His folks wanted him to stay
in school. The 18-year-old wanted out. This time, he was armed with
an even better salesman's pitch, a lawyerlike determination, and a
steely resolve. As Rick and Cheryl DiPietro had learned two years
before, saying no to this kid wasn't possible, especially when they
came to believe he was right.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the selling job he had to do, DiPietro laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's always the case with parents, I think,'' said DiPietro,
who seems poised beyond his years. ``You've got to try to sell them
on something that you want. Going to Ann Arbor and opting into the
draft were two things I really felt strongly about. They were
pretty good about realizing what I wanted. It took a little
convincing, but as soon as I did, they jumped on board and were
really supportive. I just sat down with them and told them how I
felt and brought up some points I felt were important when I was
making the decision and they began to see where I was coming from.
It took a while but they finally came around.''
</P>
<P>
   When the lobbying first began _ it coincided with the euphoria
over his World Junior performance _ DiPietro's father quickly
dismissed talk of the draft. There were college games to play,
classes to attend, and May 1 was a long way off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it was something he didn't need to think about until
May so the discussion only lasted for a few seconds,'' said the
elder DiPietro, who works in property management. ``It was a matter
of `Listen, you need to play well because if you don't play well,
opting in isn't even going to be a consideration. So just go focus
on playing college hockey.' For Rick, the discussion wasn't long
enough and the answer wasn't good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   When the end of April rolled around, the goalie put on his best
full-court press and his parents had no choice but to see things
his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the last three or two days, he convinced his mother
and myself that it was the right thing to do,'' said the elder
Rick. ``He probably, at the very end, wavered more than we did. We
were at a place where, `This is what he is going to do,' and we
were going to support him. If he decided not to go and stay in
college, that was terrific. If he was going to opt in, then we were
going to support him 100 percent of the way. He convinced us that
this was something that meant an awful lot to him, this was his
dream. His feeling was, `You've got to let me do it, I know I can
do it.' We believe in him and we believe in him enough through his
18 years that when he's committed to something and he does his best
at something, he's generally going to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   That isn't to say the young man doesn't listen to anything other
than his inner voice. Quite the contrary. He has a very cocky style
on the ice, but he's very articulate and thoughtful off the ice. He
said he solicited all kinds of opinions. He talked to Colorado
Avalanche forward and former Terrier Chris Drury, BU coach Jack
Parker, and myriad others. He said the best advice came from
Bruins' goaltender John Grahame, who spent three years at Lake
Superior State before turning pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said it was his dream (to make the NHL) and that college
was a steppingstone to the next level, and if the time felt right
then it was your opportunity to make that step, that you should try
to do it,'' said DiPietro. ``I thought that was great advice
because I came to college looking for it to be a steppingstone to
the NHL.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He has spent the last little while undergoing physical and
psychological testing and extensive interviews by prospective
suitors. It's been a grueling process but DiPietro, who is known
for his superior puck-handling skills, believes deep in his heart
that he can be a successful NHL goalie. It's what he's worked for,
what he's planned for, and definitely what he has lobbied his
parents for.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I commit myself to something, I work my hardest to
achieve it,'' he said. ``I feel like this being my dream and
everything and putting my full effort into to it, I'll keep
progressing to the point where I can be an impact player in the
NHL.''
</P>
<P>
   Until later Saturday, when the big announcement comes, it'll be
a waiting game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been kind of an anxious time, to tell you the truth,'' he
said. ``I'm just hoping this thing works its way out and everything
goes as planned. It seems like days are dragging on until
(Saturday) but it's been a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   One could argue that it's been even more stressful on mom and
dad. At least, though, the lobbying is over. Their son is about to
get what he wants _ again. Given his track record, no one doubts
it's just the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``As parents, we're sort of just along for the ride,'' said dad.
``Now we're all along for the ride.''
</P>
<P>
   And the next destination is in sight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 2145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0419 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3483 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-REAL-ANIMAL-ART-NYT &LR;      06-23 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-ANIMAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANIMALS HAVE TAKEN OVER ART,   AND ART WONDERS WHY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Germany)  (ART ADV: Photos, NYT 8 and NYT9, have been sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SARAH BOXER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why have real animals _ clothed, splattered, slaughtered and
hatching _ become players in the art world? These days it seems
that every contemporary art exhibition must have its animal, dead
or alive.
</P>
<P>
   At the Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art in North Adams,
the centerpiece of an exhibition called ``Unnatural Science'' is
``Misfit (St. Bernhard)'' by Thomas Gruenfeld. It is the head of a
sheep seamlessly attached to the body of a dog. Get it? Sheepdog.
</P>
<P>
   For the Whitney Biennial this year, Yukinori Yanagi, a
Japanese-born conceptual artist, created two pieces with the help
of some ants. For one, Yanagi assembled a replica of Jasper Johns'
``Three Flags'' by pouring red, white and blue sand into three
Plexiglass boxes. Then he poured in live ants, inviting them to
tunnel through the sand. As the ant farm got busy, the flag began
to collapse.
</P>
<P>
   In February at the Trapholt Art Museum in Denmark, Marco
Evaristti displayed 10 goldfish, each swimming in its own blender,
and viewers were allowed, if they wanted, to turn on a blender and
frappe a fish. ``Two fish were blended at the opening,'' The
Associated Press reported, ``and police ordered the blenders' plugs
pulled after a local group, the Union for the Protection of
Animals, complained.'' The museum's director, Peter Meyer, said
five more fish were blended on the weekend after the opening.
</P>
<P>
   Of course there is Animal himself, Damien Hirst. At the
``Sensation'' show in London and Brooklyn, Hirst presented numerous
animal corpses, including: a shark in formaldehyde (``The Physical
Impossibility of Death in the Mind of Someone Living,'' 1991); a
whole cow cross-sectioned and fitted into plexiglass cases (``Some
Comfort Gained From the Acceptance of the Inherent Lies in
Everything,'' 1996); a pig on a rail, sliced the long way so
viewers could see the insides from snout to tail (``This Little
Piggy Went to Market, This Little Piggy Stayed at Home,'' 1996).
</P>
<P>
   The use of live and dead animals in art has a history, and the
history begins in Surrealism. Go back to 1938, when Salvador Dali
made ``Rainy Taxi'' for the lobby of the International Exposition
of Surrealism at the Galerie Beaux-Arts. Inside the car were two
mannequins, one covered with live snails from Burgundy that fed on
nearby lettuce and vines watered by rain falling from the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years later, larger fauna came into the picture. There
was Robert Rauschenberg's angora goat encircled by a tire
(``Monogram,'' 1955-59). Hermann Nitsch disemboweled and tore apart
a dead lamb in Germany in 1962 (``The Orgies Mysteries Theater'').
</P>
<P>
   In Germany in 1965, Joseph Beuys lectured earnestly to a dead
hare (``How to Explain Pictures to a Dead Hare''). A decade later
he came to America and caged himself for a week with a live coyote
(``Coyote: I Like America and America Likes Me,'' 1974). In 1969,
Jannis Kounellis tethered 12 live horses to the wall of a gallery
in Rome (``Horses''). A few years later, Annette Messager was
outfitting dead sparrows with small wool sweaters _ pink, yellow
and blue _ that she had knitted herself (``Boarders at Rest,''
1972).
</P>
<P>
   What does it all mean?
</P>
<P>
   Well, there are some things you can say. Artists have favored
certain animals _ lambs, horses, dogs, bunnies, birds and insects.
They have tended to give their animal works fancy titles, with the
same themes cropping up again and again _ sacrifice, sex, death,
control, possession, abjection. Still, it is impossible to
generalize. The explanations that artists, critics and curators
provide are as numerous as the works of art.
</P>
<P>
   Start with Rauschenberg's goat in the tire. The critic Robert
Hughes, who nicknamed it ``The Satyr in the Sphincter,'' thought it
was an emblem of nature caught in culture's web and also an
insignia of homosexuality: the priapic animal, he observed, had
pushed its way into a giant orifice. The critic Arthur Danto saw
the goat as a sacrificial animal ``wreathed with laurel when led to
the altar.'' Leo Steinberg, in ``Encounters With Rauschenberg,''
called it Rauschenberg's act of possession: ``As the artist would
encircle a car key with paint, and a bicycle with neon tubing, so
here,'' Steinberg wrote, he circled the goat and ``made it
private.''
</P>
<P>
   Beuys and his dead bunnies and live coyote have also provoked
talk, particularly from Beuys himself. After he performed ``The
Chief,'' a work in which he rolled himself in a blanket that was
plugged up at each end with a dead hare, Beuys was asked whether he
considered himself ``the chief of the animals.'' He responded,
``Yes, I speak for the hares that cannot speak for themselves.''
Then he added, ``I would like to elevate the status of animals to
that of humans.''
</P>
<P>
   Nitsch said that his mutilation of a dead lamb was a way of
taking ``upon myself the apparently negative, unsavory, perverse,
obscene, the passion and the hysteria of the act of sacrifice so
that YOU ARE spared the sullying, shaming descent into the
extreme.''
</P>
<P>
   Less grandiosely, the philosopher Peter Singer said the presence
of animals in some art seemed intended to drive home an injustice:
``We know that animals are close to us, evolutionarily,
genetically. But we still haven't changed the way in which we use
them for food or research.'' Take the fish in blenders. ``When you
give people the option of turning the blender on,'' Singer said,
``you raise the question of the power we do have over animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Others see irony. Steve Baker, a lecturer in historical and
critical studies at the University of Central Lancashire in
England, argues that many of these artists seem bent on creating a
``postmodern animal,'' to show that animals are to some degree
human constructions.
</P>
<P>
   These new pastiche creatures ``may or may not incorporate living
animals,'' he writes in ``The Postmodern Animal.'' In any case, it
doesn't quite matter, because living animals these days ``are
arguably being `made' in the factory farm and in the scientists'
laboratory just as much as in the poststructuralist philosopher's
text or the postmodern artist's studio.''
</P>
<P>
   With Dolly, the cloned sheep, the time of the postmodern animal
may have arrived in science. If that is the case, artists are
prepared. Baker considers Rauschenberg's goat in a tire,
Gruenfeld's mismatched taxidermy and William Wegman's dog dressed
up as a bug-eyed, flippered frog (``Frog/Frog II,'' 1982) to be
``botched'' animals. Botching, he notes, is not all bad. It is a
creative procedure. It is ``reverse butchery.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the final word on animal art belongs to Robert
Storr, a senior curator at the Museum of Modern Art, who suggests
that the use of animals has followed a general ``shift to
literalism.''
</P>
<P>
   By the 1960s a painting was just paint and canvas. Sculpture
went the same way. A steel box was a steel box. A stone was a
stone. There was a leaning toward ``quiddity,'' he said, toward the
``itness'' of material. So what does that mean for animals in art?
An animal, Storr says, is ``not a style, a movement, a tendency.''
An animal is definitely not a new medium.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a museum, sometimes an animal is just an animal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 2157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
