<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0420 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3484 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-GEERTZ-ESSAYS-NYT &LR;      06-23 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEERTZ-ESSAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE THE COMPLEXITY OF CULTURES MEETS NATURE'S SIMPLICITY 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his most famous essay, written almost 30 years ago, the
anthropologist Clifford Geertz dissected the ritual of a Balinese
cockfight. In preparation for the fight, men would groom choice
roosters, nurture them and coddle them. A villager would
suggestively sit with a bird between his thighs, ``bouncing it
gently up and down to strengthen its legs.''
</P>
<P>
   When the time came, a master craftsman would fit the bird's legs
with razor-sharp spurs and send it into a 50-foot square ring, to
slash another similarly equipped cock, while village men bet on
which bird would slaughter the other. The owner of the winner would
eat the loser.
</P>
<P>
   The sexual symbolism is far from subtle _ the Balinese word for
cock means hero, warrior, lady killer, tough guy _ but there is
more going on here. Geertz meticulously described the frenzied
betting on the fight, how ``Balinese status hierarchy'' is
reproduced in the battle and the way in which the Balinese
revulsion at animal-like behavior (babies are not even permitted to
crawl) is countered by this animalistic extravaganza. In a
cockfight, he suggested, the Balinese display their culture.
</P>
<P>
   The only way for a foreigner to understand that culture is to
become immersed in its detail. This essay (in his classic
collection, ``The Interpretation of Cultures'') was a demonstration
of his anthropological philosophy: We come to understand another
social universe through ``thick description.''
</P>
<P>
   The point is not to discover unchanging universal principles but
to unmask the particular. The Western anthropologist is a peculiar
guest in an alien world, observing a performance while affecting
the world he observes.
</P>
<P>
   Geertz's most recent collection of papers and lectures, written
over the last two decades, makes the peculiarities of his
profession still more pronounced.
</P>
<P>
   What, he asks, is anthropology really about?
</P>
<P>
   What is to be made of Nayar matrilineal society, Aztec sacrifice
and Hopi forms of speech, let alone cockfights?
</P>
<P>
   Isn't the anthropologist doomed to misinterpret another culture?
Is any universal judgment possible?
</P>
<P>
   Anthropologists, Geertz writes, are ``merchants of
astonishment,'' who constantly undermine any generalizations.
</P>
<P>
   So the anthropologist stands at a troubled crossroads _ a place
where, it turns out, many contemporary political battles also play
themselves out. In one direction is the world of culture, diverse
and unimaginably complex. In the other is the world of nature,
immutable and universal. Though Geertz has now spent many years on
the faculty at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, his
career has been spent following one path while trying to hold the
other in view.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with his allegiance to the world of culture, where
absolutes do not apply, Geertz quotes Montaigne: ``Each man calls
barbarism whatever is not his practice.'' His idea of ``thick
description'' does not only describe anthropology's possibilities,
it also limits those possibilities. Anthropology is particular,
never more.
</P>
<P>
   The path he does not take leads to a very different world, where
universals are possible, where there is such a thing as human
nature and where there may even be moral standards that allow one
culture to judge another _ to condemn, say, human sacrifice or
ritual clitorodectomies.
</P>
<P>
   The central essays of this book attack such positions. Some
anthropologists, Geertz suggests, place ``morality beyond culture
and knowledge beyond both.'' But he argues that there is absolutely
no evidence supporting universalism. In one piece, ``The State of
the Art,'' Geertz declares: ``Any sentence that begins, `All
societies have,' is either baseless or banal.'' In another, ``Anti
Anti-Relativism,'' based on a 1985 lecture, Geertz turns sarcastic
and fiercely polemical, hinting that universalistic declarations
easily lead to absolutist condemnations like ``the poor are
worthless'' or ``blacks are subhuman.''
</P>
<P>
   But Geertz exaggerates the positions of his opponents to score
points. Just because bad judgments about morality are possible
doesn't mean judgments about morality are impossible. Sometimes he
seems to recognize this. He calls his lecture ``Anti
Anti-Relativism'' because while he tends to support relativism, he
is not fully comfortable with postmodern relativism, in which
almost no judgments are valid and even anthropology begins to seem
an impossible undertaking.
</P>
<P>
   Geertz's quasi-relativism, though, leads to other problems. He
describes a cultural dilemma: An American Indian is waiting for a
dialysis machine, but the white middle-class doctors don't want to
put him high on the list because he is an alcoholic. The Indian
asserts his people's troubled past and his right to drink; the
doctors assert their right to set social priorities. What is to be
done?
</P>
<P>
   The relativist would say there is no way to judge between the
two claims. But Geertz urges a kind of mutual understanding. ``If
we wish to be able capaciously to judge, as of course we must, we
need to make ourselves able capaciously to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet eventually the judgment must be made, and isn't that an
assertion of standards favoring one right over another? In fact, in
the midst of Geertz's thick descriptions, all sorts of assumptions
are made about the anthropologist's ability to render objective
judgments.
</P>
<P>
   One result is an uneasy ambivalence. Geertz wants to resist the
clutches of either party, but this doesn't necessarily make him
right, only representative of his profession. For the troubled
crossroads marks precisely the place where anthropology was born,
and where it still dwells.
</P>
<P>
   Anthropology is a distinctly Western enterprise. As far as I
know, no other culture has ever undertaken a systematic
understanding of the world's various societies. It was an
enterprise that arose partly out of a notion of universal law _
finding principles that would apply across all times and all
cultures.
</P>
<P>
   If all human life shares certain principles, then it becomes
difficult for any one society to assert claims of innate
superiority. Western universalism gives birth to Western
relativism. So anthropologists have ended up thrashing about
between the worlds of universalism and relativism. The rest of us
stand on the sidelines, frenziedly betting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
