<HEADER>
A3489 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      06-23 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEEP DISCOUNTS FAIL TO LIFT SALES OF AFFORDABLE VEHICLES
</P>
<P>
   Automakers say that despite recent deep discounts, auto sales
have not picked up in June from the relatively subdued pace of May,
providing evidence to the Federal Reserve Board that recent
interest-rate increases may be slowing the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   Auto executives and dealers say sales of luxury cars and sport
utility vehicles remain extremely strong. But the mass market for
more affordable cars, minivans, sport utility vehicles and pickup
trucks has softened as middle-class families have become leery of
borrowing money at ever steeper rates.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T SUBMITS A NEW RATE PROPOSAL
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T submitted a new proposal that would give consumers more
flexibility in seeking to save money on long-distance calls but
that appeared to fall short of stemming the outcry from consumer
groups and federal regulators over its plans to raise certain costs
for tens of millions of people. AT&AMP;T said it would eliminate the $3
monthly minimum charge for low-volume callers and offer a wider
variety of options to reduce charges for people who make most calls
on certain weekend days.
</P>
<P>
   S&AMP;P OFF SLIGHTLY IN MIXED TRADING
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index was down 10.70 points, to
1,441.48, in mixed trading. Blue-chip shares rose and technology
stocks came under selling pressure for the second consecutive day
as investors locked in profits after a weeks-long run-up. The Dow
Jones industrial average finished up 28.63 points, to 10,404.75,
while the Nasdaq composite index fell 91.50 points, or 2.3 percent,
to 3,845.34. The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond rose to 6.03
percent from 5.96 percent on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   DOCOMO MAY ESTABLISH BRITISH LINK
</P>
<P>
   Responding to press reports that NTT DoCoMo was on the verge of
acquiring a 15 percent stake in Telesystem International Wireless,
a Canadian company that is heavily invested in the British market,
a senior DoCoMo executive acknowledged that a link with Telesystem
was an attractive option. Officially, DoCoMo declined to confirm
the reports, but dropped hints that it might soon establish a
presence in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   CONAGRA TO BUY INTERNATIONAL HOME
</P>
<P>
   ConAgra said it had agreed to buy International Home Foods for
about $1.6 billion in cash and stock in a deal that would put Chef
Boyardee pasta, Gulden's mustard and PAM cooking spray into
ConAgra's corporate pantry. Shareholders of International Home will
receive $22 a share, half in cash and half in ConAgra stock.
ConAgra, with brands like Orville Redenbacher popcorn, Swiss Miss
hot chocolate and Healthy Choice prepared meals, will also assume
$1.3 billion in debt.
</P>
<P>
   AVENTIS IN ALLIANCE WITH A START-UP
</P>
<P>
   Millennium Pharmaceuticals will receive up to $450 million in
financing from Aventis Pharma, the big European drug company, as
part of a wide-ranging drug-development and technology alliance.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA TOUGHENS TALK ON WTO ENTRY
</P>
<P>
   A top Chinese trade negotiator warned that his country would not
make any more concessions to open up markets for goods and services
in its bid to join the World Trade Organization. The negotiator,
Long Yongtu, said some countries had made ``unreasonable
requests,'' apparently referring to an insistence by developing
countries that they receive the same trade privileges that China
had negotiated with the European Union and the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
