r f BC-NAPSTER--SUIT-SFCHRON     06-23 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAPSTER--SUIT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAPSTER TRYING TO RESOLVE LEGAL PROBLEMS WITH MUSIC INDUSTRY 
 &HT;     BY BENNY EVANGELISTA
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
In light of MP3.com Inc.'s recent multimillion-dollar settlements
with the recording industry, Napster Inc. executives could be
trying to avoid an even costlier fate by settling their own legal
squabble with the world's major record labels.
<P>
   Although industry sources said no formal settlement talks have
begun, Napster officials have reportedly had informal discussions
with the record companies to resolve the copyright infringement
suit against the San Mateo startup.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Recording Industry Association of America asked
for a preliminary injunction to stop Napster users from sharing
songs owned by the RIAA's members. That move was a way of ``setting
up the legal argument that the major labels have been financially
hurt by Napster in a significant way,'' said Malcolm Maclachlan,
media analyst for International Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legally speaking, that's using the left hook that sets up the
right cross for the knockout,'' Maclachlan said. ``Napster sees the
left hook coming and wants to call a truce.''
</P>
<P>
   The RIAA originally filed suit in U.S. District Court in San
Francisco in December claiming Napster's popular program allows
music fans to share illegal copies of songs with each other via the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Napster spokesman Dan Wool said he could not comment on
published reports that interim CEO Hank Barry, a partner with
Hummer Winblad Venture Partners, which has invested $15 million in
Napster, was talking to record industry executives about a
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   However, Wool said that while Napster remains confident it can
win the case, company officials have also made no secret of the
fact that ``they've been talking to everybody about everything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to work on (business) models that will be fair to
the artists and the industry,'' Wool said.
</P>
<P>
   Internet music portal MP3.com Inc. of San Diego recently settled
unrelated copyright infringement suits with two record labels.
MP3.com agreed to pay roughly $20 million apiece to the two record
companies and is negotiating similar deals with the other three. In
that case, the RIAA had already won a ruling finding MP3.com had
violated copyright laws with its virtual music storage service.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations against Napster are far more serious and
potentially costly if U.S. District Judge Marilyn Hall Patel should
rule that the Napster program allows its 10 million users to swap
pirated songs.
</P>
<P>
   And Hummer Winblad does not want to see its $15 million
investment go down the drain if Patel pulls the plug on Napster,
Maclachlan said.
</P>
<P>
   The RIAA is using internal Napster memos against the company. In
a brief filed in court, the RIAA quoted from a memo sent by
co-founder Sean Parker to co-founder John Fanning, the uncle of
Napster creator Sean Fanning, that addresses music piracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Users will understand that they are improving their experience
by providing information about their tastes without linking that
information to a name or address or other sensitive data that might
endanger them (especially since they are exchanging pirated
music),'' the RIAA quoted from Parker's memo.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Benny Evangelista at  &LR; bennye &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of NAPSTER2 (105434 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
