<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3499 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-WALMART--ANNIVERSARY-     06-23 1654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALMART--ANNIVERSARY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIGHTY WAL-MART RULES RETAIL WORLD WITH IRON FIST  &HT;     BY CAROL EMERT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Few retailers, if any, have weathered as many black eyes as
Wal-Mart Inc. The discount king, which turns 50 this year, has been
branded a killer of downtown communities, a union buster and an
exploiter of underage sweatshop workers.
<P>
   Twice in the past four years, immigrant seamstresses making
Wal-Mart's Kathie Lee Gifford clothing were found to be working in
sweatshop conditions in New York, with workweeks as long as 80
hours and little to no pay. Multiple investigations of overseas
contractor factories have found abuses such as seven-day workweeks,
forced overtime, the use of child labor and hazardous working
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart doesn't deny sewing shop problems and says it has taken
steps to improve conditions. But even as the retailer incurs the
enmity of everyone from human rights activists to historical
preservationists, Wal-Mart has achieved a level of dominance
without parallel in modern times.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1950 by Sam Walton, whose early stores were called
``Walton 5 &AMP; 10,'' Wal-Mart, of Bentonville, Ark., is now the
single biggest retailer on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Its sales are estimated to hit a stunning $195.7 billion this
year _ more than double those of the world's second-biggest
merchant, German grocer Metro AG.
</P>
<P>
   New Wal-Mart stores often face opposition, but the company
usually prevails. This year, Wal-Mart expects to open 235 stores on
top of its 3,030 in the United States and 1,019 in eight foreign
countries, from South Korea to Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area remains relatively under-Wal-Marted, with only 18
Wal-Mart discount stores and two Sam's Club warehouses throughout
Alameda, San Mateo, Santa Clara, Napa, Sonoma and Solano counties.
Contra Costa, San Francisco and Marin counties have no Wal-Marts or
Sam's Clubs at all.
</P>
<P>
   But that is changing. Wal-Mart has stated its intention to fill
in underserved West Coast markets. Additional locations are already
under way in Fremont and Napa.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the company will begin opening its mammoth
``supercenters'' here _ 200,000-square-foot formats featuring both
groceries and general merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   A survey by WSL Strategic Retail, a New York consulting firm,
illustrates just how deeply ingrained Wal-Mart has become in
American shopping habits.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 40 percent of people surveyed by WSL, all of whom were
women and the primary shoppers in their households, had shopped at
Wal-Mart in the previous week.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety percent of those polled had visited a mass merchant in
the past three months _ knocking supermarkets, at 83 percent, from
the top spot for The number of people shopping at drug stores,
department stores, malls and home improvement stores is also
falling as more people of all income levels fill their shopping
needs at discounters _ mostly Wal-Mart, said Wendy Liebmann,
president of WSL.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart's dominance occurs not by accident, but by a highly
strategic design. Wal-Mart watchers identify two traits that have
gotten the company where it is today: a single-minded, even
ruthless focus on growth, and the extraordinary business smarts and
discipline necessary to pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   Because it wields more clout than any other retailer, Wal-Mart
can _ and does _ squeeze its suppliers for rock-bottom wholesale
prices, allowing it to undercut competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, low prices are the main reason people shop at
Wal-Mart, although its broad selection, convenience and customer
service also get high marks.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Wal-Mart's largest vendors maintain staff in Bentonville
to keep their biggest client happy. And Wal-Mart isn't bashful
about asking for favors, including extremely cushy terms of credit.
Every penny saved gives Wal-Mart more of an edge over its rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Another key cost-saving measure for Wal-Mart _ and one that has
proven an enormous public-relations headache _ is selling apparel
made in low-paying sewing shops, mostly in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
   Activists such as the National Labor Committee, whose
congressional testimony sparked the Kathie Lee Gifford furor in
1996, have toured Wal-Mart's contractor factories and reported
serious abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Similar allegations have been made against many companies, from
Gap to Nordstrom to Tommy Hilfiger. But as retailing's 800-pound
gorilla, Wal-Mart attracts more flak than most.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart promised to institute independent factory monitoring
after the Gifford episode. ``We admitted publicly that we are
working to improve conditions around the world and we began
requiring suppliers to ensure that every factory conforms to local
workplace laws and that there was no illegal forced or child
labor,'' said Wal-Mart spokesman Tom Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart is doing its best when it comes to apparel sourcing,
Williams said. ``The key thing is that we're not perfect. We try to
be as open as we can, and we're going to continue ... to be as open
and caring as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Such assurances fail to placate Wal-Mart's foes. Charles
Kernaghan, executive director of the National Labor Committee,
continues to issue reports on factory conditions, although he
complains that his efforts don't get as much press as they used to.
</P>
<P>
   His organization, whose biggest source of funding is the
Unitarian Church, is considering suing Wal-Mart to disclose the
factories it uses. Wal-Mart has declined to furnish the
information, citing competitive concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Labor costs are also an issue in the United States, where
Wal-Mart's 885,000 employees make it the country's largest
private-sector employer. Williams called Wal-Mart's pay and
benefits ``very, very competitive,'' but he declined to comment on
reports that most sales associates earn well under $10 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to unionize Wal-Mart stores, which would give workers
more leverage over pay and hours, have been repeatedly thwarted.
</P>
<P>
   That situation seemed to be changing earlier this year, when
butchers in a Texas store voted to join a union _ the first
pro-union vote in a domestic Wal-Mart. But a few days later,
Wal-Mart said it would phase out butcher shops in that region, a
decision it attributed to store economics and not the union vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas case aside, many Wal-Mart employees are loyal to
Wal-Mart and not interested in unions. Wal-Mart cultivates a strong
corporate culture that sits well with many workers. Every store
holds a daily morning pep rally in which staffers shout ``the
Wal-Mart cheer'' (``Gimme a W!'' ``W!'' etc.)
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart also lets employees buy company shares at a discount, a
popular policy as long as Wal-Mart stock continues to climb.
(Shares closed at $53.75 yesterday, up $1.25. In the past year, the
stock is up 21 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart has even turned its annual shareholder meeting into a
massive perk for workers. In an Arkansas sporting arena, thousands
of associates gather annually to wave signs and cheer as executives
give folksy speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Other attractions have included morning exercise sessions with
Richard Simmons, appearances by country music artists and a
testimonial from Barbara Bush about how much George loves tomato
sauce from Sam's Club.
</P>
<P>
   While employees are important, the key to any retailer's success
is keeping its customers happy. ``Greeters'' at the entrance of
every Wal-Mart put a smiling local face on the company. But
Wal-Mart's back-end systems are the real key to customer
satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart's distribution and inventory-management systems are
considered the best in the industry. Its sophisticated computers
track which items are selling in each store and what needs to be
reordered. This helps ensure that its shelves are stocked and
shortages are rare.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart has been equally strategic in deciding what it will
carry, specifically in its decision to become a grocer. In 1988,
the company opened its first supercenter combo store, a move that
sent shivers through the grocery industry.
</P>
<P>
   That fear was well founded. Twelve years later, Wal-Mart is the
largest grocery seller in theUnited States with an estimated $51
billion in 1999 sales compared with $45 billion for runner-up
Kroger Inc.
</P>
<P>
   California supermarkets are already nervous about Wal-Mart
supercenters, although the format has not yet premiered on the West
Coast. Last year, grocers and labor unions backed a superstore ban
that was passed by the California Legislature, but then vetoed.
</P>
<P>
   Groceries not only give Wal-Mart an enormous source of sales,
they also provide a one-stop-shopping synergy that boosts sales of
general merchandise by 20 to 40 percent, said Sandy Skrovan, a
consultant with PricewaterhouseCoopers.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart has even begun opening small conventional grocery
stores called Neighborhood Markets for people who don't want to
hike around a supercenter. For fans of electronic shopping, the
company is beefing up its Internet presence.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart's opponents admit that their efforts have had little
impact on the retailing giant, whose earnings reports consistently
show both strong sales and robust profits.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart's investors, meanwhile, just keep getting wealthier.
Sam Walton's heirs are worth a combined $85 billion, the same as
Bill Gates, Forbes magazine estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-Wal-Mart forces face an uphill battle because the company's
formula is so irresistible. Wal-Mart's core customers ``need to
stretch a dollar for their families' sake,'' allowed Kernaghan.
``Where else are they going to shop, Brooks Bros.?''
</P>
<P>
   But for Kernaghan, the fight is nothing less than a moral
imperative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wal-Mart controls more of the market than any retailer ever
has,'' Kernaghan said. ``When you're talking about Wal-Mart, you're
fighting for what kind of a country this is going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carol Emert at  &LR; cemert &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
