<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERC--CONTRACT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCURY NEWS REACHES PACT WITH UNIONS 
 &HT;     BY CAROLYN SAID 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ The San Jose Mercury News reached a last-minute
agreement with its unions Friday for an eight-year contract,
averting a threatened strike.
<P>
   Representatives of five unions agreed to a new contract that
would grant annual raises of 4.15 percent for reporters and 4.63
percent for lower-pay classifications. Portions of those increases
would go to health and welfare programs and pension plans.
</P>
<P>
   The contract also includes a $1,000 signing bonus for full-time
employees and $300 for part-timers. It expands same-sex domestic
partner benefits to include leaves for bereavement, medical care
and maternity or paternity.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative contract is retroactive to Nov. 1, 1998, and runs
until June 30, 2006.
</P>
<P>
   The unions were bargaining on behalf of about 1,275 of the
paper's 1,500 employees. Union members will decide whether to
ratify the contract in early July.
</P>
<P>
   Employees who had been working without a contract _ or raise _
for the past 20 months were irate that the region's economic boom
was passing them by, while the cost of living soared. The current
top minimum wage for Mercury News reporters is $983.60 a week,
although newspapers in general often choose to pay more for certain
employees.
</P>
<P>
   According to an economic analysis by the San Jose Newspaper
Guild, the cost of a two-bedroom apartment in Santa Clara County
has risen from $885 a month in 1995, when the last contract was
signed, to more than $1,400 today.
</P>
<P>
   The unions had asked for a 10 percent raise in April, and
management offered 2 percent. The unions were prepared to strike at
noon Friday if no agreement had been reached. That deadline was
extended an hour and a half, after a marathon all-night negotiating
session.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's expensive to live down here,'' said Bill Wyland, an
organizer with the Newspaper Guild, based in Washington, D.C.
``It's a very profitable paper but they've had a 25 percent
turnover in the past five years. They needed to offer something
that would keep people at the paper or they'll have everyone
jumping to all the dot-coms.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Rasky, an acting associate professor in the journalism
department at the University of California at Berkeley, said,
``Speaking as someone who has only watched this from the outside
and doesn't know the internal issues, it would certainly seem that
the Merc is trying to retain experienced people and attract
smarter, younger people. They are under enormous pressure from
online companies who regard the Merc as the first place to raid.''
</P>
<P>
   Rasky said uncertainties in the Bay Area newspaper climate may
have hastened a settlement. A judge is now deciding whether to
allow Hearst Corp.'s planned purchase of The San Francisco
Chronicle to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is so up in the air that it's hard to say whether
they were responding to perceived competition from a one-newspaper
town in San Francisco with a deep-pocketed owner, or whether they
view this as potentially a great opportunity because their
competitor in San Francisco may not be as strong as they once
imagined.''
</P>
<P>
   Luther Jackson, executive officer of the San Jose Newspaper
Guild, said the wage increases are among the largest granted U.S.
newspaper employees in recent times.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues at the 300,000-circulation Mercury News jumped 6.5
percent last year, to $306.3 million, heavily fueled by classified
ads for high-tech jobs.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carolyn Said at  &LR; csaid &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
