   &UR; FOR WHOM THE ROADS TOLL: SHOULD CALIFORNIANS PAY AS THEY GO? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CALIF-TOLL-ROADS?-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ On June 22, the California Environmental
Dialogue, a new 32-member group including _ improbably _ General
Motors, Chevron, BP Amoco, the Sierra Club and Environmental
Defense, published a paper on the state's transport policy. In it,
they endorsed the principle that the ``user should pay'' for road
use and that ``tolls and congestion pricing should be utilized
whenever possible'' _ a first for the big oil and car firms.
Drivers' groups, however, are opposed to the idea. Kevin Murray, a
state senator from freeway-laced Los Angeles, calls road-pricing a
middle-class fantasy dreamed up by ``some dweeb in a dark room
doing quantitative analysis.'' &QL;
</P>
