<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SPORTING MUSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's laughing-out-loud edition of The Sporting Muse:
</P>
<P>
   Based on some of the caterwauling by armchair quarterbacks out
there, ABC Sports apparently hired Hitler and Hannibal Lechter as
Al Michaels' partners on Monday Night Football.
</P>
<P>
   There's no denying that the hiring of comedian Dennis Miller as
a member of the MNF cast -- shall we call him a comedic analyst or
a football pun-dit? -- was a stunner, and that it changes the
standards of what passes as a sportscaster.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't deserve all of the negative reaction its received
in some of the more conservative sports parlors. Three points come
to mind in assessing the decision:
</P>
<P>
   1. If the MNF gig was destined to go to a non-traditional type,
who better than the most well-read and sophisticated comic? This
isn't like hiring Henny Youngman. Miller doesn't play a role like
an actor, he doesn't have an agenda like Rush Limbaugh, and he
takes everything he does pretty seriously.
</P>
<P>
   2. Has anything you've heard from the mouth of Boomer Esiason,
Frank Gifford or Dan Dierdorf on MNF the last five years been
memorable? Esiason was a waste of time, Dierdorf was on autopilot
for three years, and I defy anyone to recall a cogent comment from
the Giffer dating back to the Cosell and Meredith era.
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, what exactly did Cosell or Meredith bring to
the MNF table beyond their notoriety? It's easy to romanticize that
period because of its impact, but the reality is that people tuned
in to hear Meredith poke holes in Cosell's ego. Cosell could no
more breakdown a pass prevent defense than Julia Child.
</P>
<P>
   Michaels and Dan Fouts will be there to talk as much strategy
and analysis as needed, and don't be surprised if Miller has as
much insight as Esiason.
</P>
<P>
   3. His hiring is perhaps the clearest sign yet that sports on
television is purely an entertainment vehicle. You and I might take
sports a bit more seriously, and consider it part of a city's
sociological make-up or hold it up to the same standards as an HMO
or City Hall. But for TV it's just well-dressed programming, and
it's time everyone in TV copped to that fact.
</P>
<P>
   4. Did you stop to consider the competition? That may be the big
story. ABC launched a search for the best football analysts in the
business and they came up empty.
</P>
<P>
   The top available candidates were Sterling Sharpe, Steve Young
and Dan Fouts, which is enough to make one cry. So forgive me if I
forgive ABC for hiring a comic. ...
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bird wasn't about to break any coaching records held by
Red Auerbach, Phil Jackson or even Pat Riley, but the cost of his
retiring as coach of the Pacers will be large.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a couple of playing time decisions related to Reggie
Miller, Bird used his personnel superbly, and he only went to the
Hack-a-Shaq strategy when it was a last resort. And he was as
bothered by it as anyone in Laker gold, too. ...
</P>
<P>
   Now that the NBA season is finally over, attention can be turned
to the Dodgers -- if their season isn't already over.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are within touch of the N.L. West lead, but all of
the problems that faced them at the beginning of the season are
still present -- an inconsistent bullpen and holes up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the pressing problems can be traced in part to G.M.
Kevin Malone, too. Tommy Lasorda goofed by not reading the fine
print when he traded for Jeff Shaw, but it was Malone who lavished
him with a three-year contract -- or a year-plus more than he had
ever proven himself as a major league closer. Now he's hurting, and
the team is on the hook for $6 million next year and $7 million in
2002 (with a $1.5 million buyout).
</P>
<P>
   The contract Malone gave Carlos Perez has hamstrung decisions
regarding the makeup of the pitching staff. Todd Hundley was
damaged goods when the Dodgers traded for him, and now he's
disabled. Likewise Devon White, who was age-wary when Malone signed
him as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' modest 17-17 home record doesn't instill a lot of
confidence in catching Arizona, either, and the Dodgers don't see
the D- Backs again until September. ...
</P>
<P>
   Deja vu: Now that the NBA season is finally over, attention can
be turned to the Angels -- if their season isn't already over.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels were in touch with the rest of the A.L. West before
the Oakland A's and Seattle Mariners just launched a sprint. The
fact the Angeles are over .500 despite a quilted pitching staff is
a salute to Mike Scioscia.
</P>
<P>
   But even should Tim Belcher and Ken Hill return healthy, they
still may not have enough pitching to hang with the A's and
Mariners. What's worse, both teams re-constructed their pitching
staffs at the same that the Angels clearly needed pitching
renovation.
</P>
<P>
   The ten games the Angels have against the A's and Mariners
beginning next week look pivotal. They don't need to catch either
team, but they do need to stay close. ...
</P>
<P>
   As much as I'd like to see Tim Salmon earn his first-ever
All-Star bid, Darin Erstad and Troy Glaus are both more deserving.
The Dodgers' Gary Sheffield will likely be their only all-star,
although a case could be made for Chan Ho Park. ...
</P>
<P>
   The idea of the Cubs trading Sammy Sosa is like trading the
family pet. Why would you? He's not the problem in Chicago. He
certainly doesn't cost them runs -- his 64 RBI through Thursday was
second in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Don Baylor wants Sosa to become a more complete player,
whatever that means. Does he want Sosa to shorten up and hit behind
the runner? Does he want him to steal 40 bases at a time when the
steal is passe, and despite plenty of statistical evidence that
stolen bases are minimally important in the long run?
</P>
<P>
   The fact Baylor spent the end of his career as a DH doesn't help
his cause in urging Sosa to become a ``complete'' player. ...
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox may be interested in trading for Sosa. But despite
all of the lore about the Green Monster and what it does for
right-handed power-hitters, Fenway actually favors left-handed
hitters. The Sox have three switch-hitters and two left-handed
hitters in their daily lineup. ...
</P>
<P>
   I love the man dearly, but I saw way too much of Magic Johnson
during the Lakers' celebration. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
