<P>
   &UR; MEXICO: IT'S TIME FOR AN HONEST HANDOVER OF POWER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEXICO-VOTES-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Change comes slowly to Mexico, the country with the world's
longest-serving ruling political party. Ever since the emergence in
the 1920s of the Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), power in
Mexico has changed hands through backroom deals in which the
incumbent president has chosen his successor _ whose subsequent
electoral victory was a formality, achieved when necessary by
fraud. No longer. That makes Mexico's presidential election on July
2 a historic _ and hopeful _ event. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors...TIMELY for JULY 2 election) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (900 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEWARE OF DANGEROUSLY DECEPTIVE DEMOCRACIES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PHONEY-DEMOCRACY-ECONOMIST-200&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, the past decade has been a splendid time for
democrats. All over the world, dictatorships, whether communist or
military, have been in retreat; demand for ballot boxes, election
monitors and people who know how to run parliaments has been as hot
as for Pokemon cards. Indeed, for the first time in history, the
proportion of the world's population that lives in countries that
can claim to be broadly democratic has climbed past 50 percent.
Closer scrutiny, however, finds several imposters in the crowd:
countries still ``in transition'' towards full democracy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 150-word optional trim; 1,025 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOR THE TIME BEING, PUTIN SHOULD REMAIN ON PROBATION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POKERFACE-PUTIN-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Three months after Vladimir Putin won Russia's presidency, some
ugly things have been happening in his benighted country. The new
man, a former KGB officer, has been cracking his whip. He has
sounded belligerent towards several of Russia's former vassal
states on its rim, and shows little sign of softening towards
Chechnya, the rebel republic devastated at his command. Things may
yet change but, for the time being at least, Putin remains on
probation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (825 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A DOSE OF HEALTHY LESSONS FROM HEALTH-CARE STUDY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMPARING-HEALTHCARE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Health-care spending is everywhere on the increase. In 1948, it
took 3 percent of gross world product; now, says a new report from
the World Health Organization, the figure is 7.9 percent and
rising. Governments and health-care providers have much to learn
from studying the structure and performance of other countries'
health systems. But what may matter more for public policy than the
rankings in the WHO report are four general conclusions about
health care. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (625 words) &QL;
</P>
