</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-GONZALEZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZALEZ HAS QUESTIONS. DO YANKS HAVE ANSWERS? 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ One of Juan Gonzalez's agents stressed Friday that his
client had not exercised his no-trade clause, and that he still had
an interest in playing for the New York Yankees. That kept alive
the possibility that Gonzalez could soon be acquired from the
Detroit Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got an open mind about going to the Yankees,'' Fernando
Cuzza, the agent, said. ``He's got an open mind about talking to
the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuzza and the Yankees had brief discussions Friday about what it
would take to persuade Gonzalez to join the two-time defending
world champions. The Yankees and the Tigers on Thursday agreed to a
deal in principle that would have sent outfielder Ricky Ledee, the
top prospect and third baseman Drew Henson and the Class AA
left-handed pitcher Randy Keisler to Detroit for Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Cuzza said the main reason he contacted a member of the Yankees'
hierarchy was to clarify Gonzalez's position and refute reports
that said Gonzalez had invoked his right to veto the trade. The
Yankees have a 72-hour window that ends at noon Sunday to try to
agree to terms with Gonzalez. Both sides could petition the
commissioner's office to extend the window, and the request would
almost certainly be granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that we wanted to get across to the Yankees
today was that those rumors reported about Juan vetoing the trade
were not true,'' Cuzza said.
</P>
<P>
   But there could still be a stumbling block, because Cuzza and
another friend of Gonzalez's said the slugging right fielder would
probably not be interested in signing a long-term deal. It seemed
doubtful the Yankees would give up three young players to rent
Gonzalez for the last three months of the season. Gonzalez agreed
to leave Texas and play this season for the Tigers, but he turned
down Detroit's long-term deal _ eight years and $140 million _
after he was obtained from the Rangers. The Yankees, whose
suggestion of a one-year extension to Gonzalez was not accepted,
would probably have to offer close to $140 million. Apparently,
Gonzalez would still be reluctant to sign such a lengthy extension
without having played a day as a Yankee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan is more likely to want to play the rest of the year out
and see how the chemistry is and how things are,'' Cuzza said. ``I
think once he goes there, he'll feel like he wants to stay and work
something out.''
</P>
<P>
   Another friend of Gonzalez's, who has spoken with him and who
insisted on anonymity, added, ``He'll waive his trade veto and he
won't ask for anything to waive it, but he doesn't want a contract
extension.''
</P>
<P>
   Do the Yankees want the 30-year-old Gonzalez desperately enough
to give up three players without guarantees that they will have him
beyond the 2000 season? It seems unlikely. But the Yankees could
try to include lesser prospects in the trade, they could hope
Gonzalez comes to the Bronx and falls in love with the team, or
they could decide that adding the two-time American League Most
Valuable Player to their needy offense is worth the current price,
even if it is only for the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make sense with him not wanting to leave Detroit,''
Paul O'Neill said. ``Does it? I don't see how that makes sense.''
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty about whether Gonzalez would be joining the
Yankees filled the visiting clubhouse before the Yankees played the
White Sox Friday night. Bernie Williams, who played in youth
baseball leagues with Gonzalez in Puerto Rico when they were 15
years old, said he would gladly call Gonzalez and talk to him about
the positive aspects of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the team wants me to talk to him, I'll be willing to do
it,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre refused to discuss the Gonzalez situation, other than
admitting that he met with Ledee and told him to ignore the trade
speculation, because the manager would be the first one to tell him
if he were traded. Other than a slump in the second half of the
1996 season and the drama of the postseason, Torre called the
spectacle created by the Gonzalez and Sammy Sosa rumors ``the
toughest distraction we've had to deal with.'' The Cubs have asked
the Yankees for at least five of their elite prospects for Sosa,
and those discussions have not advanced.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee has been distracted. Orlando Hernandez rushed up to Ledee
in an animated fashion and asked him why he was still with the
team. Ledee smiled, but he is so worried and had such a bad
headache that he took five pain relievers before the game. Still,
Ledee knows his future is probably tied to Gonzalez's decision, and
he is honest about what could happen by Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got money, he's got MVPs, he's got everything you could
want,'' Ledee said. ``He said he wants to win. Why wouldn't he come
here?''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said Gonzalez has often been booed as an opposing
player at Yankee Stadium. Williams added that Gonzalez was quiet,
emotional and private, and that did not always translate well in
New York, where the attention and the expectations are intense. But
Williams looked around the clubhouse at a core of players who have
won three of the last four World Series and wondered if Gonzalez
could see exactly what he saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't see him passing up this opportunity with where he
could be and where he's playing now,'' Williams said. ``Nothing
against Detroit, but he's got a chance to win if he comes here.
He's won all the individual awards. If he goes on and plays his
whole career and doesn't win, he'll think about this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
