<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3522 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-ASSESS-1STLD-WRI     06-23 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ASSESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE IS STILL RAISING FUNDS AS INQUIRY CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Inserts new graf that begins ``In the transcript ...'' Since
this graf now contains the first reference to Clinton, there is a
change in the following graf from ``Bill Clinton's'' to
``Clinton's.'') 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE with JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Within hours of ordering his lawyers to release the
transcript of his interview during the investigation into his 1996
fund-raising activities, Vice President Al Gore was back to
business as usual on Friday _ trolling for money.
</P>
<P>
   In an affluent Silicon Valley neighborhood, Gore raised $500,000
over lunch. In Denver on Thursday, Gore headlined two events that
raised a total of $1.1 million. On Friday, after the Silicon Valley
lunch, he attended a gala dinner on the San Francisco waterfront
where the singers David Crosby and Steven Stills serenaded several
hundred people.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a reception at a private home. The day's total take:
$2 million. On Saturday he was scheduled to attend a fund-raiser in
Miami that was expected to bring his three-day total to over $3.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raising events were broken up by the news on Thursday
that, based on an April 18 deposition of Gore, a Justice Department
official was asking Attorney General Janet Reno for an
investigation into the vice president's money-raising activities in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night Gore advisers read the transcripts of the
deposition and on Friday they released copies to news
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about Gore's overzealous money-raising, coming in the
midst of a fund-raising swing, put an especially fine point on what
Gore likes to call the ``irony'' of his situation.
</P>
<P>
   Here is how Gore _ who has tried to deflect criticism of his
links to the fund-raising problems by calling himself ``an
imperfect messenger'' for overhauling the campaign finance system _
dealt with this uncomfortable topic at lunch on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In a sun-splashed dining room, where paintings by Miro and
Chagall decorated the stucco walls, he talked confidently about the
nation's powerhouse economy, borrowing a line from Ronald Reagan:
Did Americans feel they were better off today than they were eight
years ago?
</P>
<P>
   There was a soft murmur of assent. And then, perhaps in a nod to
the issue that had dominated Friday's news reports, Gore briefly
made a pitch for tossing out the entire campaign finance system
that has caused him so much grief.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an irony to talk about this issue at a fund-raising
event, I realize,'' Gore told the dozen or so people who had paid
$25,000 each to lunch on grilled salmon and vegetables. ``But the
first bill I will present to Congress will be the McCain-Feingold
campaign finance bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has struggled mightily over the last two weeks to focus
attention on the upside of the Clinton administration _ the
unprecedented economic expansion and his ideas for using the
nation's growing budget surplus to improve education, health care
and the environment. This forms the basis of his ``prosperity and
progress tour'' and the underpinning of his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   But he is being pulled away from sketching out a rosy future to
explaining the past. And in doing so, he is being pulled inexorably
into the downside of the administration _ not just the questionable
fund raising of 1996 but the specter of the next president spending
his time being questioned under oath about whether he has told the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   In the transcript released Friday, Gore gives a startlingly
similar answer to the now-infamous answer given by President
Clinton as he quibbled over the meaning of the word ``is.'' When
Gore was asked what role the coffees would play in raising money,
he said: ``Let me define the term `raising.''' He added, ``If you
mean by it, would they be events at which money was raised, the
answer is no.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last year, Gore has been working furiously to separate
himself from an administration that has been accused repeatedly of
not telling the truth, even as his opponent, Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, has offered himself as an alternative. And Bush clearly
hoped that the call for an investigation into Gore's truthfulness
would signal to voters that a Gore administration would not be much
different from Clinton's.
</P>
<P>
   ``If America is tired of scandals and investigations, let's
elect somebody different, other than the people of the Clinton/Gore
administration,'' Bush said in Alabama on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the Gore campaign was employing a durable Clinton
tactic made familiar during the Monica Lewinsky investigation _
pre-emptively releasing hundreds of pages of documents in an effort
to defuse the controversy and dispatch it quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and his advisers moved in an uncharacteristically
aggressive fashion to dispel any suggestion of wrongdoing and,
using another Clinton tactic, implied that the re-emergence of the
issue was, if not a vast right-wing conspiracy, at least an
orchestrated smear by the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president hinted broadly that Thursday's leak of the
request for an investigation was politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the timing of this whole thing speaks for itself,''
Gore told reporters as he announced that his campaign was releasing
the transcripts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have told the truth,'' he added. ``I have cooperated fully.
And I don't want people to have the impression that I am trying to
hide something. I am not. I want you to see it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fabiani, a spokesman for Gore and a veteran of the Clinton
White House damage-control operation, said that the release of
documents was the best way for the Gore campaign to fight what he
described as ``Republican dirty tricks.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Fabiani said that the Republicans, through Sen. Arlen Specter,
R-Pa., had leaked the information because ``Bush was having a bad
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Fabiani noted that the governor had been presiding over an
execution and pointed to reports that Bush's financial ties to the
oil industry would render him useless in the battle against high
gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Republicans tried to do yesterday was to kick up dust
and say, `No one really knows what the issue is, but it's an issue,
it's significant and it comes out of this April 18 deposition,'''
Fabiani said. ``Those of us who read through the deposition last
night couldn't find a single such issue that was compelling, and
the quickest way to challenge that was to release it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Gorlin, a Democratic consultant, said the Gore campaign
was probably smart to release the transcripts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton lesson is to show that it's worth it to engage in
the discussion, partly because the public doesn't care that much
and partly because this gives Gore standing'' to make his case and
challenge the Republicans, Gorlin said. ``The thinking is, let's
take the hit now and move on, that they won't find anything they
can use in the fall, and by then it will be old news anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   She also said that the possible investigation illustrated the
age-old problem for vice presidents seeking to become president:
``Is this election about what's gone on during the previous
administration or is it about what he can do in the future?''
</P>
<P>
   Allies of Gore saw another possible advantage in releasing the
transcripts. Although Gore uses the word ``hell,'' apparently
reinforcing reports that he was angry and confrontational during
the deposition, Fabiani suggested that this showed passion, a
quality that he has been accused of lacking.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the Bush campaign and for Specter said that there
was no collusion between them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 2247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
