<HEADER>
A3523 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-FUNDRAISING-CIA-1000(     06-23 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNDRAISING-CIA-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW EVIDENCE IN A FUND-RAISING INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES RISEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A former official of the Central Intelligence
Agency has provided fresh evidence to support accusations that a
top Democratic Party official sought to enlist the agency to aid a
major donor to President Clinton's 1996 re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In a new unpublished manuscript, the former official _
identified during congressional investigations into Democratic
fund-raising abuses only as ``Bob from the CIA'' _ describes a
telephone conversation he said he had with Donald Fowler, then the
chairman of the Democratic National Committee. Fowler was seeking
the agency's help for Roger Tamraz, a Lebanese-American
entrepreneur who had contributed at least $300,000 to the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Accusations that Fowler sought to use the CIA on behalf of
Tamraz rocked the agency in early 1997 when they surfaced in the
midst of the confirmation hearings in the bid by the national
security adviser, Anthony Lake, to become director of central
intelligence. Lake withdrew his nomination as soon as the
accusations of Democratic efforts to politicize the agency emerged.
Later that year, Tamraz became a star witness in the congressional
investigation into Democratic campaign fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler also testified, telling a Senate committee investigating
the campaign finance scandal that he could not recall ever talking
to a CIA officer in order to help Tamraz.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Bob from the CIA'' never testified publicly about the
matter. At the time, he was still undercover as an officer in the
Directorate of Operations, the agency's clandestine espionage arm,
and even his last name remained classified. He gave a deposition to
Senate investigators and left the agency not long after the Tamraz
affair.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in his book-length manuscript, he writes that Fowler wanted
him to help Tamraz overcome resistance by White House staffers who
were trying to prevent Tamraz from meeting with President Clinton.
Tamraz wanted support from the Clinton administration for his plan
to build an oil pipeline in the Caspian Sea region.
</P>
<P>
   Tamraz had previously had a secret relationship with the agency,
and when he ran into resistance from officials at the National
Security Council at the White House, he told Fowler that the agency
might be able to pry open the White House doors so he could meet
with President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore. Tamraz gave
Fowler ``Bob's'' name, since he was then a senior manager in the
agency's Central Eurasian Division.
</P>
<P>
   But Fowler insisted in his congressional testimony that he could
not recall ever having called the agency on Tamraz's behalf. The
notes also made it clear that Fowler understood Bob's CIA
affiliation, according to the Senate campaign finance committee's
report on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very sensitive to the implications of perjury statutes,''
Fowler told the Senate campaign finance committee in 1997. ``But I
have in the middle of the night, at high noon, late in the
afternoon, early in the morning _ at every hour of the day for
months now searched my memory about conversations with the CIA, and
I have no memory _ no memory of any conversations with the CIA.''
</P>
<P>
   Fowler, who served as chairman of the Democratic National
Committee in 1995 and 1996, said again in an interview Friday that
he could not recall any conversations with an agency official on
Tamraz's behalf. ``I've been through that a hundred times, and I
just have no memory of any of that,'' said Fowler. ``I have made
multiple statements about that, and don't have anything else to say
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the new manuscript, Bob writes that on Oct. 18, 1995, Tamraz
called him at his office at the agency. ``A fellow named Don Fowler
is going to call you,'' he (Tamraz) said. ``Please talk to him.'''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Bob writes, he did not know who Don Fowler was.
So he took Fowler's number from Tamraz, and called him to see who
he was and what was going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fowler called back the next day _ October 19th, and identified
himself as the chairman of the Democratic National Committee,'' the
manuscript says. ``I never identified myself as a CIA employee, and
Fowler never referred to my CIA employment, but it was nevertheless
obvious that he knew exactly who I was. He told me he was trying to
help his good friend Roger Tamraz. He told me straight out that he
was upset with'' two National Security Council officials ``because
they were blocking Tamraz's access to the president, and they were
doing it for the benefit of major corporations like Amoco. He said
that Roger had been disinvited to a White House fund-raising event,
and so Roger had complained to Fowler. I guessed Roger had given
the DNC chairman my name as someone from CIA who could vouch for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   In its final report on its investigation into campaign fund
raising, the Senate committee said that ``it is likely'' that
Fowler's claims that he couldn't recall his contact with Bob were
false.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA has blocked publication of the manuscript, arguing that
it contains too much classified material about agency operations.
Since the author submitted the manuscript to be cleared in
December, the agency's Publications Review Board has repeatedly
demanded numerous changes, despite a requirement that the review
process be completed in 30 days. Current and former CIA officials
are required by law to seek agency clearance for books or articles
they publish to ensure that they don't divulge classified
information.
</P>
<P>
   Bob said he now believes that the agency's demands have been so
excessive that the book can't be published in its current form.
</P>
<P>
   The author and his Washington attorney, Victoria Toensing, have
appealed the decisions of the review board to the agency's
executive director. In the meantime, HarperCollins, the New York
publisher, has canceled its contract to publish the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were legal issues relating to the publication of the
book, and Harper Collins decided not to go forward,'' said Lisa
Herling, a spokeswoman for Harper Collins.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Disputes between the agency and Bob and his attorney over the
manuscript have intensified in recent days, after security
personnel demanded to retrieve copies of a letter Toensing had
written to the agency's executive director relating to the
manuscript. An agency spokesman said the incident was prompted by
the fact that the CIA believed the letter contained classified
information, and Toensing had sent the letter to the agency over an
unclassified fax machine. However, Toensing said in an interview
Friday that she had been using the same fax to communicate with the
agency on matters related to the book for months.
</P>
<P>
   A CIA security official called Toensing's office and talked to
her son, Brady Toensing, who is also a lawyer, since Victoria
Toensing was traveling at the time. The security officer said she
wanted to search the law office's files and computer hard drives
for classified information, according to Brady Toensing. He said he
denied the request. On June 15, two CIA security personnel arrived
at Victoria Toensing's law offices. Brady Toensing said he gave
them the letter, and assured them he had erased copies of the
letter from the office computers. The security personnel left
without renewing their request to search the office or his mother's
computers, Brady Toensing said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Harlow, a spokesman for the agency, denied that the
security personnel had ever asked to search the computer hard
drives in Victoria Toensing's offices.
</P>
<P>
   Another CIA spokesman, Mark Mansfield, insists that the agency's
objections to the manuscript are not politically motivated or a
result of the author's disclosures concerning Democratic fund
raising. Instead, the agency is only opposed to his use of
operational details. The agency said that Bob's case marks only the
fourth time in the last five years that a current or former agency
official has appealed decisions by the publications board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost invariably, the publications review board process is
collegial and involves negotiation,'' said Mansfield. The board
``works to ensure that classified information is not divulged,
while at the same time not interfering with an author's right to
tell his or her story. Our very legitimate concern is that the
written product not contain classified information.''
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Toensing responded by saying that the agency has sought
to prevent the book's publication by claiming that material like
the Tamraz affair, and another incident concerning a prostitute, is
classified. ``We have complied with the rules of the prepublication
process,'' she said in an interview. ``However, the CIA has made
false claims of classified information to thwart publication of
this book. We have told them time and again we don't want to
divulge information about clandestine operations. This is not what
we are arguing about.''
</P>
<P>
   After the author left the agency in late 1997, he was awarded a
Career Intelligence Medal for his actions during his clandestine
espionage career. He wrote his book without identifying his last
name at the request of the agency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
