<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PURITAN JUDGE'S ANTI-SLAVERY VOICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Judge Samuel Sewall, a prominent and pious Bostonian of
Puritan times, is remembered for much these days, it is for the
literary and historical value of the diaries he kept, and his
repentance for his role in the Salem witchcraft trials.
</P>
<P>
   Sewall served on a court appointed by the governor of
Massachusetts in 1692 to examine the witchcraft accusations in
Salem. Alone among the judges, he later apologized publicly, with a
statement read aloud in his church, the Old South Meeting House.
</P>
<P>
   But today, Sewall might better be remembered for another
declaration. June 24 happens to be the 300th anniversary of the
printing of a remarkable pamphlet he wrote, offering religious
arguments against slavery, which was then legal in Massachusetts.
It was one of the earliest anti-slavery declarations made on
American soil, arguing a cause that few people would join until
much later, on the eve of the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Sewall titled his pamphlet ``The Selling of Joseph: A
Memorial,'' a reference to the story in the 37th chapter of Genesis
in which Jacob's sons sell their brother Joseph into slavery in
Egypt. The document begins, ``Forasmuch as liberty is in real value
next unto life: none ought to part with it themselves, or deprive
others of it, but upon most mature consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   Sewall went on to say, ``It is most certain that all men, as
they are sons of Adam, are coheirs; and have equal right unto
liberty, and all other comforts of life.'' He also wrote that
slavery was not a natural condition for human beings.
</P>
<P>
   When he wrote the pamphlet, Sewall was almost 50 and was serving
on Massachusetts' highest court; he would become its chief justice
in 1718.
</P>
<P>
   (His pamphlet was not the first anti-slavery declaration in the
Colonies. Mennonites in Germantown, Pa., published a short but
strong anti-slavery statement in 1688.)
</P>
<P>
   The current pastor of Old South Church, which is now 333 years
old, is the Rev. James W. Crawford, who preached a sermon about
Sewall a few years ago titled ``The Last Puritan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was an amazing man,'' Crawford said in an interview. ``Not
only as a justice but as a great reader, a great writer. He was on
the board of overseers at Harvard College. He was quite an
intellectual.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford said he regarded Sewall, in his apology for serving on
the witchcraft court and in his anti-slavery pamphlet, as acting
very much in the tradition of Old South, where Benjamin Franklin
was baptized and the Revolutionary patriot Samuel Adams served as a
deacon.
</P>
<P>
   The church, he said, was founded as ``a progressive institution,
doing its best to disengage from the rigid Calvinist fundamentalism
of the first generation'' of Puritans. Old South, he said, ``always
has been in the forefront of recognizing social change and trying
to interpret the Gospel to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The church now is part of the United Church of Christ, a
Protestant denomination that traces its roots to the Puritans and
the Congregationalists who came after them.
</P>
<P>
   The denomination's president, the Rev. John Thomas, said
Sewall's pamphlet would be included in a seven-volume series of
theological documents related to the denomination's history, to be
published later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a lovely reminder of the historical roots that we
often ignore,'' Thomas said, ``that really nourish many of the
contemporary involvements of the United Church.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas also acknowledged that ``there were many New England
Congregationalists that participated in the slave trade in one way
or another, so our story is never a pure one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' Thomas said, ``Sewall in his own life embodied that
ambiguity _ as a participant in the Salem trial, in a sense
representing the worst of what we have been, and then writing this
tract, and representing the best of what we have been.''
</P>
<P>
   The diaries kept by Sewall, who died in 1730, have long been
public documents. His entry for June 19, 1700, contains the
notation that he had been ``much dissatisfied with the trade of
fetching Negros from Guinea,'' and had had ``a strong inclination
to write something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   After reading a contemporary commentary on the apostle Paul's
letter to the Ephesians, Sewall wrote that day, ``I began to be
uneasy that I had so long neglected doing anything.'' He concluded
by saying he hoped that he ``was call'd of God to write'' the
pamphlet and that a divine blessing would accompany it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
