<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT COULD BE A GOOD DRAFT FOR KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Kings' trade for Zigmund Palffy and Bryan
Smolinski certainly can't be, and shouldn't, be second guessed. The
two forwards helped Los Angeles crawl from the depths of the
Western Conference to fifth place and a rare spot in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit swept the Kings in the first round, but there is reason
to believe the prospects for the immediate future are bright.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy and Smolinski, however, didn't come cheaply. The Kings
sent three recent top draft choices (Olli Jokinen, Josh Green,
Mathieu Biron) to the New York Islanders and pretty much wiped out
any depth there might have been in the farm system.
</P>
<P>
   ``That trade pretty much cleaned out our young players, but
there aren't any regrets in the organization,'' said Al Murray,
Kings director of scouting. ``We made tremendous strides (last
season).''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Murray and the rest of Kings management know there is a
big job ahead, and that job begins today at the 2000 NHL Entry
Draft in Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of needs to address in this draft,'' said
Murray, who knows the Kings must address those needs thoughtfully
if they don't want a repeat of the playoff drought that followed
the departure of Wayne Gretzky and a host of other aging veterans
in the years following the Kings' run to the Stanley Cup finals in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are well stocked in goal. Los Angeles has Stephane
Fiset and Jaime Storr on the NHL level and has a number of quality
prospects in the minors. But the Kings are short on center and wing
prospects, especially since they were unable to sign 1998
second-round pick, center Justin Papineau who has re-entered the
draft.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles' three top minor league forwards are Pavel Rosa, who
has yet to prove he can play on the NHL level, the often injured
Eric Belanger, and Scott Barney, who recently had back surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings select 20th in the first round and have at least one
pick in seven of the nine rounds. Los Angeles currently has no
fourth or sixth-round picks, but it has three in the fifth and two
in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   However, draft picks don't automatically turn into prospects,
especially in NHL drafts, where GM's and scouts are trying predict
the potential of 17 and 18-year old youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I compare it to going into a high school classroom and picking
out who will be a doctor or a lawyer,'' said Murray. ``You don't
know who is going to be able to make the adjustment to the NHL.
Some kids figure out how to work hard and make it and some maybe
change because of the money.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's draft seems tailor made for the Kings' needs even
though it's not deep, and is lacking in quality prospects on
defense. The strength of the draft is at wing.
</P>
<P>
   Hotshots Danny Heatley and Marian Gaborik will be long gone by
the time Los Angeles picks, but the Kings still should have a
number of decent wingers to pick from.
</P>
<P>
   Russian wingers Alexander Frolov, Alexei Smirnov, Alexei Mikhnov
and Nikita Alexeev are among those could be available, along with
Canadian junior standout Justin Williams. Centers that might still
be up for grabs late in the first round include Jarret Stoll and
Marcel Hossa, brother of Ottawa standout Marian Hossa.
</P>
<P>
   If Los Angeles opts to look at defensive prospects, Swedish
defenseman Lars Jonsson, American Ron Hainsey and 209-pound Russian
Anton Volchenkov are possibilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 2310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
