<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGSIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS KNOW IMPORTANCE OF GOALIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Having two top-notch goaltenders isn't merely a
luxury the Los Angeles Kings desire. Management realizes it's a
necessity in today's NHL, especially when one looks at the recent
medical history of Stephane Fiset and Jaime Storr.
</P>
<P>
   Both goalies have suffered serious injuries in each of the past
two seasons, and twice they have been sidelined at the same time.
With that in mind, the Kings have opted to protect both Fiset and
Storr in today's NHL Expansion Draft in Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles officials were so intent on shielding their two top
goalies that general manager Dave Taylor traded a draft choice to
Chicago for Steve Passmore, a goalie who had played at least 10 NHL
games last season and could be made available to Minnesota and
Columbus. Taylor has even had talks with both the Wild and Blue
Jackets about one of them selecting Passmore so the Kings wouldn't
lose a defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Kings opted to protect two goalies, they could protect
only three defensemen. Rob Blake and Mattias Norstrom were
no-brainers, while the promising but inconsistent Aki Berg was the
other defenseman protected. First-year NHL pro Jere Karalahti did
not have to be protected.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves veteran Sean O'Donnell very much exposed, along with
free agent Garry Galley, Jaroslav Modry and Philippe Boucher.
Neither expansion team is likely to select a free agent, but they
very well could be interested in a strong stay-at-home defenseman
like O'Donnell. His loss would leave a big hole in a relatively
thin Los Angeles defense.
</P>
<P>
   Among the forwards not protected, winger Craig Johnson is the
most likely to be chosen. The speedy Johnson, who scored nine goals
and 23 points while playing a checking role last season, grew up in
Minnesota and played three years at the University of Minnesota.
The ties would seem to make him a perfect fit in the Wild's scheme
of things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I wasn't going to be protected,'' said Johnson, who was
acquired by the Kings in the 1996 trade that sent Wayne Gretzky to
St. Louis. ``I would like to stay with the Kings, but if I'm
(chosen by) the Wild, then it happens and I'll make the best of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran winger Nelson Emerson is also unprotected, but he is 32
years old and his $2 million salary isn't something either
Minnesota or Columbus would be that interested in picking up.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings protected seven forwards: Luc Robitaille, Zigmund
Palffy, Jozef Stumpel, Glen Murray, Bryan Smolinski, Ian Laperriere
and Kelly Buchberger.
</P>
<P>
   According to draft guidelines, all teams except Nashville and
Atlanta will lose two players, but no more than one goalie or
defenseman. A team that loses a goaltender can't lose a defenseman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 2310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0451 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3630 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-DUCKS2-LADN     06-23 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS2-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS FACING HARD FACTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As the Anaheim Mighty Ducks head into their eighth
NHL Entry Draft, the cold, hard facts are that Anaheim is 43 games
under .500 in its first seven years, and has qualified for the
playoffs just twice.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks defeated Phoenix in 1997, but have lost eight straight
playoff games to Detroit since beating the Coyotes in their
first-round series.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, across the country in Florida, the Panthers, who like
the Ducks joined the NHL in the 1993-94 season, are one game over
.500 and have advanced to playoffs three times, including a
stunning run to the 1996 Stanley Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
   So what have the Ducks done wrong?
</P>
<P>
   For the most part nothing. Anaheim management from the beginning
insisted it was going to build a solid foundation through the
draft. And for the most part the Ducks have done just that,
starting with the selection of Paul Kariya in the 1993 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Four of Anaheim's first-round draft choices are currently on the
roster Kariya, Oleg Tverdovsky, Ruslan Salei and Vitaly Vishnevski.
Another, Chad Kilger, was used as trade bait, along with
Tverdovsky, in the deal that brought Teemu Selanne to Southern
California. Ducks general manager Pierre Gauthier then used last
year's No. 1 pick to bring Tverdovsky back.
</P>
<P>
   Other current Ducks acquired in the draft include second-line
center Matt Cullen, regular defensemen Pavel Trnka and Niclas
Havelid, and forwards Mike Leclerc and Antti Aalto. Anaheim also
has high hopes for youngsters Maxim Balmochnykh, Mikael Holmqvist
and Jordan Leopold, even though they might not make their mark for
several years.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim's draft performance certainly hasn't been perfect
second- and third-round picks like Nikolai Tsulygin, Valeri Karpov
(1993); Johan Davidsson, Craig Reichert (1994); and Brian Wesenberg
(1995) didn't pan out.
</P>
<P>
   But the Ducks' draft record certainly compares favorably with
Florida's, especially when you consider they stole top-line center
Steve Rucchin in the 1994 Supplemental Draft.
</P>
<P>
   But that being said, the question remains, why is Florida 44
games up on the Ducks in the win-loss column?
</P>
<P>
   The simplistic and popular answer is that Disney has been
unwilling to spend money on the team; that it hasn't gone out and
signed any big-name free agents.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds logical to some, but upon closer inspection that's
just critics taking the easy way out. The Ducks spend over $15
million a year in the checks they hand out to Kariya, Selanne and
Guy Hebert, and Anaheim certainly isn't the only team not signing
aging players to what Gauthier calls ``retirement contracts.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Rangers spent millions on unrestricted free agents
last season and they didn't come close to making the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull is one of the only successful free agent signings in
recent seasons and he went to a Dallas team that was already in the
league's upper echelon, thanks to its shrewd drafts and trades.
</P>
<P>
   One vocal critic of the Ducks insists that they have already
done the hard part acquiring superstars Kariya and Selanne and that
they simply need to fill out the supporting cast.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds easy, but it's not. This isn't basketball where two
players can turn a team into champion like the Lakers. Hockey is a
true 20-man sport, and teams need time to acquire the depth
necessary for a run at the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Where the Ducks' development did bog down was after their 1997
playoff run, when former GM Jack Ferreira and former team president
Tony Tavares clashed with coach Ron Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson was let go and the Ducks floundered under the ill-suited
Pierre Page, who never had a chance thanks to Kariya's lengthy
holdout and season-ending concussion.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps that wasted year will turn out to be a blessing in
disguise. Ferreira was demoted and Tavares turned over control of
the hockey operations to Gauthier and gave up his title as
president.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks failed to make the playoffs last season, but the depth
is improving and there is reason for optimism. Given time, it's
hard to believe Gauthier won't turn them into a consistent winner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
