<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS GM HASN'T CHANGED PHILOSOPHY ON BUILDING TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Pierre Gauthier knows that failing to make the
playoffs is unacceptable, especially in a winner's market like
Southern California. But the Mighty Ducks' general manager insists
he hasn't changed his philosophy about building a team, even though
he traded Anaheim's first-round pick on draft day last year, and
recently dealt away his second-round selection in Saturday's NHL
Entry Draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we will be going to the podium (to announce a draft
choice),'' said Gauthier, realizing that deals like the one in
which he acquired Oleg Tverdosvky (from Phoenix in exchange for
Travis Green and the 15th overall pick) don't drop in a GM's lap
every draft day. Tverdosvky, after all, is a 23-year old all-star
caliber defenseman and figures to be a fixture at the Pond for
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should never say never based on last year,'' said
Gauthier, who would love to acquire a power forward with a scoring
touch. ``But I'd never trade for an older player for a short-term
fix. We can obtain players other ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier, who traded this year's second-round pick for promising
goalie Jean-Sebastian Giguere, is a firm believer in building
through the draft. As Quebec's chief scout and Ottawa's GM, he saw
first-hand how good drafts can turn around franchises. He also
points to Detroit and New Jersey as teams that built their
rock-solid foundations through the drafts.
</P>
<P>
   ``All good clubs are built through the draft,'' he said. ``It's
all about stockpiling assets.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks are scheduled to draft 12th in the first round. They
have one third-rounder, two fourths, three selections in the fifth
and one each in the sixth and seventh rounds.
</P>
<P>
   This year's draft is not considered particularly deep,
especially on defense, and Gauthier feels there are only one or two
players who might make an impact next season. The majority of those
drafted figure to be long-term projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these kids won't play (on the NHL level) for three of
four years,'' he said, knowing just how tough it is to project the
futures of 17- and 18-year-old youngsters. ``But if you don't draft
well, five years comes and goes very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier has had success drafting European players in the past,
and he feels this year's draft has a distinct European quality to
it.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the players that might be available when it's the Ducks'
turn to draft figure to be European, including Russian wingers
Alexei Smirnov, Alexander Frolov and Nikita Alexeev; speedy Swedish
forward Martin Sameulsson; two-way Czech center Vaclav Nedorost;
211-pound Russian defensemen Ilya Nikulin; and Lars Jonsson, a
offensively gifted Swedish defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Gauthier has improved the Ducks' depth on defense
and in goal, leading many to believe that Anaheim will stockpile
forwards, their greatest need at the moment. But Gauthier insists
he can't, and won't, draft for need.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows, we might draft seven defensemen...we are looking
for players,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And one never knows what round those players might be found on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people say it looks like a crap shoot, but some shoot
crap better than others,'' he said of finding quality players in
the later rounds of the draft.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
