<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLLS PUT LEADING CANDIDATES IN MEXICO IN DEAD HEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAM DILLON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Public opinion surveys show the two leading
presidential candidates in a virtual tie before the election on
July 2, with as many as one-fourth of the voters undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Three polls show Francisco Labastida Ochoa, the governing party
candidate, leading by a slender margin. A fourth survey showed
Vicente Fox Quesada, of the center-right National Action Party,
slightly ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The half dozen polls were released on Wednesday and Thursday
because publication of polling information is prohibited from
midnight Friday until 8 p.m. on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   The polls show that the race, in which Labastida enjoyed an
overwhelming advantage over Fox, has continued to narrow. And they
have intensified the extraordinary uncertainty and public tension
about the outcome of an election that has become a plebiscite on
whether the Institutional Revolutionary Party, known as the PRI,
should continue to govern Mexico after 71 years in power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either candidate, Labastida or Fox, could win this election,''
Alejandro Moreno, the chief pollster at the Mexico City newspaper
Reforma, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In the nationwide survey published Thursday in Reforma,
Labastida was favored by 34 percent of voters, Fox by 32 percent,
and Cuauhtemoc Cardenas Solorzano, a leftist candidate, by 13
percent. Three percent of those surveyed said they would vote for
minor candidates or for no candidate, and 19 percent of voters said
they were still undecided or refused to respond to pollsters'
questions. The margin of sampling error was plus or minus 3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Another nationwide poll, commissioned by Reuters and carried out
by Zogby International, a New York research firm, showed Labastida
to be supported by 31 percent of voters, Fox by 29 percent and
Cardenas by 10 percent. The margin of error was plus or minus 3
percent. About 3 percent of those surveyed said that they supported
minor candidates, and 27 percent said they were undecided or
declined to respond, said John Zogby, president of Zogby
International, in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   In a third survey, also announced on Thursday, conducted by
Grupo de Economistas Asociados, a private Mexico City research
firm, Fox was supported by 32 percent of those surveyed, Labastida
by 31 percent and Cardenas by 15 percent. Twenty percent were
undecided. Two percent supported minor candidates. The margin of
error was plus or minus 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a tie,'' Mauricio Gonzalez Gomez, the research
organization's director, said in a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The polling reports provoked an immediate debate about how to
interpret the high numbers of voters who refused to express a
commitment for any candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts argued that the undecided voters, whose numbers
ranged from 18 percent to 27 percent depending on the survey,
represented the percentages of eligible voters who are unlikely to
cast ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts say the high percentage of uncommitted voters
reflects the high level of political fear in the electorate after a
campaign that has been extraordinarily bitter. Complaints have been
heard across Mexico that officials of the government and the PRI
have threatened that voters would lose access to government welfare
and farm programs if Fox wins. As a result, some analysts have said
that many of the people expressing indecision in the surveys are
merely reluctant to acknowledge their intentions to vote for the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Most surveys taken before Mexico's last presidential elections,
in 1994, predicted that the PRI would earn 2 percent to 3 percent
more votes than the party eventually received at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the new surveys showed that when voters were asked to
leave aside their own preferences and to say whom they expected to
win the election, significantly more Mexicans believed that
Labastida would win.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1994 elections, the PRI won votes from many Mexicans by
portraying itself as the party that could offer stability in a
dangerous world. This year, as Fox has campaigned as the candidate
of change, Labastida has again been playing on voters' fears, and a
survey published on Wednesday by a private consulting group,
Consultores y Marketing Politico, suggested that the tactic could
be effective.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to choose between social peace and having a new party take
over power, nearly eight in 10 voters said that they preferred
stability.
</P>
</TEXT>
