u s BC-BKN-LAKERS-WEST-NYT &LR;      06-23 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-WEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE REBUILT THE LAKERS, BUT WEST MAY QUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For 12 years, Jerry West worked to rebuild the Los Angeles
Lakers into a championship team. He cleared enough space beneath
the salary cap to acquire the game's most dominant center, shrewdly
maneuvered a draft-day deal to sign a prodigy out of high school
and, to top it all off, helped woo the league's most successful
coach.
</P>
<P>
   But just four days after Shaquille O'Neal, Kobe Bryant and Phil
Jackson led the Lakers to their first NBA title since 1988, West
admitted Friday that he was uncertain of his future with the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   A league executive said Friday that West would soon resign as
the Lakers' executive vice president for basketball operations.
When reached in his Los Angeles office Friday, West did not refute
the notion that he would leave the Lakers during the off-season.
Although he said that his retirement was not imminent, the
62-year-old West also declined to say that he would be around to
watch the team he assembled defend its title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea what I'm going to do,'' West said. ``When
you've been in this business for a long time, I think we all get to
the point sometime where we think, `Why do I need this?' But I
certainly felt that way the last two years and I haven't done
anything, so I don't know what I'm going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   West, an executive in the Lakers' front office since 1982, has
entertained the idea of retiring before, most recently after the
1997-98 season. He now has a three-year, $10.5 million contract
extension that runs through the 2002-03 season, but he said that
that would not necessarily stop him from retiring this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told everyone, until our season's over, and our season's not
over, I've got work to do,'' West said. ``I'm supposed to be here
until September. Because I have a contract doesn't make any
difference. I don't have to hold them to that, and they don't have
to hold me to it, either.''
</P>
<P>
   A person close to West said he could envision West leaving the
Lakers in mid- to late July. ``Now that he's won, I think he
actually might do it,'' the person said. ``The problem is, he's
said it before. I won't believe it until it actually happens.''
</P>
<P>
   It would seem like a strange time for West to step away. After
12 years of trying to return Showtime to Los Angeles, he has done
so with a bang, building a team around O'Neal and Bryant that could
become a dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   But according to two league executives and another person with
knowledge of the Lakers' situation, West is bothered by his
decreased role since Jackson arrived. They said Jackson had usurped
much of West's decision-making power, angering West and prompting
him to consider resigning.
</P>
<P>
   West, however, denied having any problems with Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's absolutely ludicrous,'' West said. ``For me, he's been
like a breath of fresh air. He's been absolutely great to work
with.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been no secret, however, that West and Jackson have
clashed over the role of Glen Rice in the Lakers' game plan.
Believing that Rice's outside shooting ability would make him the
perfect complement to O'Neal and Bryant, West traded Elden Campbell
and the All-Star guard Eddie Jones for Rice and two others last
season. But Rice, with his limited defense and inability to create
his own shot, has not fit well into Jackson's triangle offense and
has butted heads with the coach. As a result, Rice almost certainly
will not be in a Lakers uniform next season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
