<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY--TRIALS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Slay goes to the mat for Texas
<TEXT>
<P>
   Olympic berth might boost state wrestling
</P>
<P>
   By DANNY ROBBINS
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS _ One way or another, Brandon Slay's life is about to
change.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on how things go today, he will be a member of the
U.S. Olympic wrestling team _ the first Texan in that position _ or
he finally will enter the work force with the rest of the
University of Pennsylvania's Wharton School of Business Class of
'98. Go to Sydney or go to the office. No pressure there.
</P>
<P>
   Slay's quest will be front and center among the do-or-die
stories when the U.S. team is determined today. Wrestlers who won
their weight classes at the national championships in April will be
paired against those who won their classes in the Olympic challenge
tournament, which was played out Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   As the freestyle national champion in the 167-pound class, Slay
was assured a spot in the finals, where the winner will be
determined through a best-of-three series of matches. Today, he
faces the task of beating Brian Dolph, a former NCAA champion at
Indiana who is now an assistant coach at Penn. Dolph upset ex-Iowa
wrestler Joe Williams in the challenge tournament final to earn a
shot against Slay.
</P>
<P>
   As badly as Slay wants a place on the Olympic team for the
obvious reasons, the Amarillo native knows what his spot on the
team would mean to those who care about wrestling in Texas. He
would be more than Texas' first Olympic wrestler. He would be the
state's first standard-bearer in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something that's driving me as well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wrestling is a hugely popular sport at the high school and
college levels in Iowa, Oklahoma and other states, but it is
basically an afterthought in Texas, relegated to the ``club sport''
level by the state's universities and colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Wrestling is an NCAA sport at only five schools in the Big 12
Conference _ Oklahoma, Oklahoma State, Iowa State, Nebraska and
Missouri _ and is not likely to surface anywhere else. When schools
deal with the gender equity concerns mandated by Title IX,
wrestling is often the first program to go.
</P>
<P>
   With Slay among the primary competitors and with the event being
staged at Reunion Arena in Dallas _ a city literally going to the
mat to hype its 2012 Olympic bid _ the trials have caused an
uncharacteristic buzz for wrestling in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Wrestling officials believe the trials can reinforce the
legitimacy the sport received when it was placed under the umbrella
of the University Interscholastic League two years ago. About
one-fifth of Texas' 1,232 public high schools had boys or girls
wrestling teams during the 1999-2000 school year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that basically there's no college wrestling in the
state, but that will hopefully come if you build a base, and the
base to me is starting to be a factor,'' said Dan Gable, the
legendary former Iowa wrestling coach and one of the freestyle
coaches for the U.S. Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   Among those attending Friday's freestyle session was Bryan High
School coach Mike Zito, four of his wrestlers in tow. Zito said
Slay's presence at the trials should significantly impact all high
school wrestlers in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``By him being here, it just gives these kids something to
attach themselves to,'' said Zito, a Texas A&AMP;M graduate who
wrestled in high school in Ohio. ``Our best guys might be
undefeated in Texas. Then we go up to Oklahoma (to compete) and
they get killed. In Brandon Slay, they can see that a little work
paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   Young wrestlers in Bryan-College Station have been exposed to
Greco-Roman heavyweight Matt Ghaffari, who won the Olympic silver
medal in 1996 and two years ago started a camp with Zito.
</P>
<P>
   Ghaffari finished second to Rulon Gardner at the 2000 nationals
but worked his way through the challenge tournament to earn another
shot at Gardner today. Win or lose, Ghaffari, 38, will be in Bryan
on Monday to begin a weeklong visit to the camp.
</P>
<P>
   Slay hopes his success will allow him to organize a major
wrestling club in Amarillo and spur at least one Texas college to
start an NCAA-level program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in equal rights,'' he said, referring to the Title
IX-related pressure on school administrators. ``But you see schools
starting women's crew with women who have never been in a boat. You
see them give $25,000 to those programs and cutting others. I don't
understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Slay, 24, lost only one match during his wrestling career at
Amarillo's Tascosa High School _ pre-UIL _ and also was an
all-district nose guard in football. His route to becoming one of
wrestling's elite meant leaving the state for the University of
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Recruited by some of the more traditional wrestling schools,
Slay chose Penn because of its academics. Facing the financial
consequences of attending an Ivy League school that does not offer
athletic scholarships, he said he has $25,000 in student loans to
repay.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father and I talked about that when I was being
recruited,'' he said. ``He said, `All these schools want to give
you a scholarship and you want to go to a place that costs $30,000
a year? Why?' I said, `Because 30 years from now, you'll be happy I
graduated from the Wharton School of Business.'''
</P>
<P>
   Slay earned his degree in 1998 and twice reached the finals of
the NCAA championships, losing as a senior in '98 to Iowa's
Williams. According to the Amarillo Globe-News, only one other
Texas wrestler _ Bobby Johnson, an Amarillo native who competed for
Oklahoma State in the 1950s _ has appeared in the finals at the
NCAAs.
</P>
<P>
   For the last two years, Slay has lived and trained at the U.S.
Olympic Training Center in Colorado Springs. Working with freestyle
coach Kevin Jackson, a 1992 Olympic gold medalist, he has improved
significantly, reaching the point where he was able to beat
Williams at the nationals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has raised the bar,'' said Greg Strobel, who will be one of
the U.S. Olympic freestyle wrestling coaches. ``I saw Joe Williams
at the world championships and didn't think anybody would challenge
him this year. I was a little surprised when Brandon beat him at
nationals, but Brandon is in the driver's seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Slay's pairing with Dolph, an assistant at Penn since 1993,
offers the added subplot of student vs. mentor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't teach him all my tricks,'' Dolph, 33, said. ``but I
showed him a lot. It's kind of weird. But, at the same time, you
always have a couple tricks up your sleeve.''
</P>
<P>
   Slay will be joined today at Reunion by a large contingent of
family, friends and current and former coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Section 104,'' he said, pointing to a section in the lower
portion of the arena and indicating his group might fill it.
</P>
<P>
   For those seeking to climb aboard the bandwagon, the Texas
chapter of USA Wrestling has been selling ``Slay 'Em Brandon''
T-shirts ($10 apiece) outside the arena since Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, the possibility Brandon will be the slayed.
It is a possibility he doesn't want to think about, but one he
seems capable of handling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see myself sticking around and training for 2004,'' he
said. ``If I win, great. If something freak happens and I lose,
I'll deal with it. There are other things I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
