<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-CONVENTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES OKS $4 MILLION TO BAIL OUT DEMOCRATIC NATIONAL
CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ By a one-vote majority, the Los Angeles City
Council Friday approved $4 million to bail out the host committee
for the Democratic National Convention here, assuring enough cash
to begin building the stage at the Staples Center next month and
avoiding a political embarrassment for Mayor Richard Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   But Riordan's victory came at a personal price: $1 million, to
be exact.
</P>
<P>
   That is because the Council required that several $1
million-dollar letters of credit held by the Democratic National
Committee from a group of wealthy civic leaders backing the
convention must be cashed before any of the new city money is
spent. One of those letters has Riordan's signature.
</P>
<P>
   In an even more bitter twist, the bailout could not muster a
majority from the 15-member Council's 12 Democrats, and Riordan, a
Republican who helped to lure the convention in the first place,
had to rely on a liberal Democrat, Jackie Goldberg, a frequent
antagonist in a Council full of them, to pass it.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg, who represents Hollywood, called the vote the hardest
of her career and agreed to support the grant only after the
Council accepted her amendments on the letters of credit, as well
as a requirement that Pershing Square in the heart of downtown Los
Angeles be available for public protests.
</P>
<P>
   Civil liberties groups have criticized a plan to limit protests
to a fenced-off area set aside near the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg's amendments also required the police Department to
meet with an ad hoc Council committee before and during the
convention to avoid any police overreaction to protests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jackie made it really clear she would vote no,'' said her
chief of staff, Sharon Delugach, who expressed surprise that the
council member's conditions had been met, especially those
involving the police and protesters. From the beginning, the
convention has been dogged by fund-raising difficulties, chiefly
because the organizers agreed to finance the $35 million cost
almost entirely from private funds, as did organizers of the 1984
Olympics here.
</P>
<P>
   The city originally agreed to provide transportation and
security services amounting to about $7 million, but estimates of
those costs have risen and earlier this week the Council approved
$2 million more.
</P>
<P>
   But it balked at a request for an additional $4 million to
jump-start construction work, with members insisting that would
violate their original promise to taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   However, the measure passed on Friday 8-5, the bare majority
needed in the 15-member body. Two members were absent.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Austin, a spokesman for the host committee, said the group
was ``thankful that the Council expanded its partnership,'' and
said the investment would help reap $135 million in economic
activity for the city.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the troubles, the host group has raised a record amount
in private cash and services, $25 million, and said they're hopeful
a Sunday fund-raiser at Riordan's house, featuring President
Clinton, will raise more than $1 million toward about $3 million in
cash that is still needed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
