A3640 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-NY-KENNEDY-CRASH-NYT &LR;      06-23 0344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-KENNEDY-CRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO MECHANICAL PROBLEMS WITH KENNEDY'S PLANE, SAFETY OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Investigators at the National Transportation Safety
Board writing a report about the plane crash that killed John F.
Kennedy Jr. and two others last summer have not found a mechanical
problem, but a conclusion hasn't been reached, according to the
agency.
</P>
<P>
   Because it was a private plane, Kennedy's Piper Saratoga did not
carry a flight data recorder or a cockpit voice recorder, depriving
investigators of detailed information.
</P>
<P>
   In the crash of private planes, investigators look for engine
failure, structural failure or other mechanical or electrical
problems. If they fail to find any, they usually give a ``probable
cause'' that stems from some failure by the pilot specific to the
accident, like not flying high enough to clear the trees, or
failure to maintain sufficient airspeed to keep the plane aloft.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Kennedy, whose plane went down on a hazy night on
its way from New York to Martha's Vineyard, the suspicion by NTSB
officials is a loss of orientation.
</P>
<P>
   The crash killed not only Kennedy, 38, who was at the controls
of his single-engine plane, but also his wife, Carolyn Bessette
Kennedy, 33, and her sister, Lauren Bessette, 34.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Lopatkiewicz, a spokesman for the safety board, said Friday
that although a preliminary report had been sent to the board's
headquarters here from its regional office in Parsippany, N.J., the
report was not final and did not reach a conclusion. That, he said,
was for headquarters staff or the board itself.
</P>
<P>
   The five-member transportation board votes on statements of
probable cause on nearly all airline accidents, but votes only on
about two dozen of the roughly 2,000 general aviation crashes each
year. For the others, a senior staff member signs the report.
</P>
<P>
   Lopatkiewicz said that a report would probably be published next
month, but that the board had not decided whether it would vote on
the findings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
