<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0460 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3645 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-BODIES-KAN &LR;      06-23 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN ROBINSON INVESTIGATORS IDENTIFY ANOTHER BODY AS SHEILA DALE
FAITH  
</HEADLINE>
 BC- BODIES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY TANYANIKA SAMUELS, DIANE CARROLL KNIGHT RIDDER NEWSPAPERS   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Reversing an earlier statement, the task
force investigating John Edward Robinson Sr. on Friday announced
that one of the bodies found in a Raymore storage locker was that
of Sheila Dale Faith.
</P>
<P>
   Faith, of Pueblo, Colo., was identified after the Jackson County
medical examiner's office took a new look at dental X-rays, Cass
County Prosecutor Chris Koster said.
</P>
<P>
   Faith and her daughter, Debbie Lynn Faith, disappeared in the
summer of 1994. Forensic experts are still working to determine
whether the last unidentified body is that of Debbie Faith.
</P>
<P>
   That ``is certainly a distinct possibility,'' Koster said. He
said he expected to have a definitive answer early next week.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement Friday came a week after the task force asked
the public for help finding the Faiths.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, 56, of Olathe, Kan., has been charged in the murders
of five women found in barrels: three in Raymore, including Sheila
Faith, and two in Linn County, Kan. He also has been linked to the
disappearances of three women and a baby in the 1980s. He is being
held in the Johnson County Jail on a $5 million bond.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives who were notified by authorities Friday morning were
trying to cope with the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sickening,'' said Sheila Faith's brother, William Howell
of Chandler, Texas. ``I hate to lose a family member, especially
under circumstances like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Howell said he couldn't help but wonder how his sister died.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was it brutal, was it not?'' he said. ``It's just saddening,
that's all I can say.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier tests, which included comparing old dental records and
X-rays, seemed to indicate that Sheila Faith was not one of the
unidentified bodies.
</P>
<P>
   But lingering doubts by members of the two-state task force
investigating the case prompted Jackson County medical examiners to
take another look.
</P>
<P>
   Koster said Faith had had extensive dental work done since 1981,
including numerous extractions. So the old dental records did not
match up with X-rays of the body.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday, the Jackson County medical examiner's office
took additional X-rays, examining the roots of each tooth, and made
a positive identification, Koster said.
</P>
<P>
   Koster earlier had said that Michael Finnegan, a forensic
anthropologist from Kansas State University, was going to help
investigators identify the two bodies. In light of Friday's
announcement, Koster said he might still seek Finnegan's help in
pinning down how long ago the women were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Faith was one of five children, her brother said. They
grew up in Dallas. Their father died about a half-dozen years ago,
he said, around the same time an older brother with a kidney
problem died. Their mother is in a nursing home, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Howell, a year younger than Faith, said his two other sisters
did not want to comment on her death.
</P>
<P>
   He said his parents divorced when he was 4 or 5 years old. His
mother and the children went to live with the mother's mother, he
said. Their mother then left them, he said, and when she returned,
the grandmother would not let her have the children back.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of a court battle over who should have the
children, the grandmother's house burned down, he said. The boys
went to a boys home and the girls to a home for girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our family has never been super close,'' Howell said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila and Debbie Faith lived in Southern California and moved
to Northern California after Sheila's husband died.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, they moved to Pueblo, Colo., where Sheila Faith met a
man named ``John'' through a newspaper ad. He invited them to join
him in Kansas, friends said. At the time, Sheila Faith was 45 and
Debbie Faith was 16.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the Faiths vanished from the neighborhood. Their mail _
including government aid checks _ was forwarded to a mail center in
Olathe, where it was picked up by Robinson, according to the
center's owner.
</P>
<P>
   Howell said he had not been in touch with Sheila Faith for
years. He and his family have tried periodically to find her, he
said, but never succeeded. Sheila Faith often did not have a
telephone, he said, which made it harder to stay in contact.
</P>
<P>
   The family can't afford much, he said, but they want to give
Sheila Faith a proper burial. He said they might wait to make plans
until after they learn for sure whether the last unidentified body
is Debbie Faith.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel Guerrero, a friend of the Faiths in Pueblo, said he
couldn't get the pictures of the barrels he had seen on television
out of his mind. He first saw the footage of the barrels from the
Raymore storage locker while visiting relatives in Illinois, before
the Faiths were connected to the Robinson investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had (the barrels) taped up on the top with plastic,''
Guerrero said. ``I didn't know what was in them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was them, I guess,'' he said, referring to both Faiths,
even though only Sheila Faith has been identified.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty gruesome.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
