<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOG-DAY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETS AT WORK MAY CATCH ON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON Z. COHEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At offices across the nation, it was a dog's life
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   There was rawhide to be chewed, plenty of floor to sniff at, and
a few spots around the office to be marked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pee happens,'' said West Los Angeles psychologist Judy
Bin-Nun, who organized dog-day activities for her entire
professional building and dressed in a dog costume for the
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Friday was officially the second annual Take Your Dog to Work
Day, an event started last year by Pet Sitters International and
promoted heavily by online retailer Pets.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're vying for top honors,'' said Bin-Nun, whose husband
works in the same building. ``We've got the rudest dog contest,
most beautiful eyes, best fur.''
</P>
<P>
   Her 13-year-old Brussels griffon, Max, might be a shoo-in for
rudest dog. While awaiting the festivities, Max decided to relieve
himself on the floor of the office.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the occasional obvious drawbacks, pets at work can be a
boon to employee morale and productivity, said Pets.com President
Chris Deyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``When dogs come to the workplace, it actually has some
significant benefits. It becomes a more productive work
environment,'' Deyo said. ``People tend to stay at work longer,
because they don't have to rush home so the dog can go to the
bathroom.''
</P>
<P>
   At Pets.com, every day is take-your-dog-to-work day, Deyo said.
</P>
<P>
   The company finds that the practice makes its employees happy,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some proven studies about animals reducing stress,''
Deyo said. ``Also, it's like an icebreaker to a certain extent.
People who work in different departments end up interacting.''
</P>
<P>
   Having dogs around is a fairly regular occurrence at Santa
Monica Studios, said employee Cynthia Rickerd, who brought her
yellow Labrador retriever, Dakota, to work Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you're around them and you see how loyal and loving they
are, everybody just warms up,'' Rickerd said. ``People come up to
your animal, and before you know it, you're just talking.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the goals for Pets.com is to try to get other companies
to adopt pets-allowed policies. Of course, there is the potential
business upside for the company, Deyo admitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not being able to take your dog to work is a barrier to pet
ownership,'' he said. And the more pet owners there are, the more
potential Pets.com customers.
</P>
<P>
   The event has attracted acceptance in some high-profile circles.
Former presidential candidate Bob Dole, now in private law
practice, brought his dog to work Friday.
</P>
<P>
   More than 3,000 companies have requested an information packet
on Take Your Dog to Work Day from Pets.com, Deyo said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
