<DOCNO> NYT20000623.0464 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3650 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-GASPRICES2TAKES-KAN &LR;      06-23 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
GAS TIGHT SUPPLIES, BAD LUCK, OPPORTUNISTS _ AND CRUDE PRICES _
REFLECTED AT GAS PUMP  
</HEADLINE>
 BC- GAS PRICES 2TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY STEVE EVERLY KNIGHT RIDDER NEWSPAPERS  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ On Monday, June 12, a storm swept through
Blue Mound, Ill., disrupting power supplies and forcing an oil
refinery to shut down. It was an event that would soon be felt by
the nation's motorists, especially in Midwestern cities such as
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   New York traders, fearing the refinery shutdown would tighten
supplies even more, bid up the price of future deliveries of
gasoline. Prices for wholesale gasoline followed, and motorists
soon saw prices go up at the pump.
</P>
<P>
   Fears of a shortage, however, were overblown. The small
refinery, which produces only a fraction of the country's gasoline
supplies, restarted in a few days. And when that news broke the
following Monday, it helped bring down futures prices and wholesale
gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   Such wild short-term fluctuations show how tight stockpiles,
production and supply glitches, and market opportunists _ far more
than the price of crude oil _ have pushed up prices recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``These prices didn't reflect a shortage as much as the
perception that there might be a shortage,'' said Urvan Sternfels,
the president of the National Petrochemical &AMP; Refiners Association
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more to the story. By Tuesday morning, prices for at
least some wholesale gas in the Kansas City area were beginning to
go down slightly. Even so, Texaco's company-owned stations in the
area had raised their prices about a dime a gallon, to $1.88 for
regular unleaded.
</P>
<P>
   It's that sort of price increase that raises suspicions among
motorists, especially in the Midwest where fuel prices are
traditionally among the lowest in the country. Recently, they've
been among the highest.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're price gouging us, and the reason they are is because
they can,'' said Kenneth Langley, a Kansas City motorist who said
he had done a lot of traveling recently.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission on Tuesday called the increases
``questionable'' and said it would launch a formal investigation
concentrating on the Milwaukee-Chicago corridor. Cost factors
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there's more afoot in the recent rise in gasoline
prices than the amount of oil that the Organization of the
Petroleum Exporting Countries is willing to sell and the cost of
the commodity.
</P>
<P>
   At its current cost of $33 a barrel, crude oil accounts for
about 79 cents of the price of a gallon of gasoline. Each $1 a
barrel of crude oil's price contributes about 2.4 cents to the
price of a gallon of gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Another part of the cost of gasoline is federal and state taxes,
which total 39.4 cents per gallon in Kansas and 35.4 cents in
Missouri. The balance is refining and marketing costs, which have
claimed a bigger chunk of the price of gasoline in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of crude oil as a percentage of Kansas City gasoline
prices has fallen from 56 percent in January to 45 percent in June.
</P>
<P>
   Oil prices, of course, have had a big effect on gasoline costs.
But if only higher crude-oil costs were reflected in Kansas City
area fuel prices, then a gallon of unleaded gasoline that cost
$1.16 a gallon in January at area service stations would cost $1.30
a gallon today, instead of the $1.79 that was charged as recently
as Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   So what accounts for the rest of spiking prices? There's little
disagreement that the underlying problem stemmed from entering the
summer driving season with gasoline stockpiles that were too low.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1999, the country was awash in gasoline, and that had
depressed prices, according to Valero Energy Corp., the country's
largest independent refiner, in its financial report for the first
quarter of 2000. In fact, gasoline prices adjusted for inflation
had sunk to their second-lowest level in history.
</P>
<P>
   But a year later, according to Valero, stockpiles were at
historically low levels, which pushed prices up. Valero pointed to
reduced oil production from OPEC beginning in March 1999 and
refiners using less of their production capacity to make gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of a customary buildup in preparation for the summer
driving season removed a cushion and soon had consequences,
particularly in the Midwest, said David Costello, an economist for
the federal Energy Information Administration.
(MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
