u p BC-NY-LAZIO-NYT &LR;      06-23 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO'S SENATE CAMPAIGN TEMPO QUICKENING 
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After spending five minutes at a press briefing
following a breakfast with business leaders at the Waldorf-Astoria
Friday, Rep. Rick Lazio bolted down 15 flights of stairs and into
an elevator, a gaggle of reporters in pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's aides scolded the handful of reporters who made it into
the elevator behind Lazio, the Republican Senate nominee for New
York, smiled wanly in the corner, tersely responding to a few more
questions before racing for his car out front. A Lazio staff member
said the congressman was heading back to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The spectacle provided a glimpse into Lazio's first tough week
since he won the nomination May 30. He has spent the week besieged:
by the news media, hungry for comment on an investigation into his
lucrative securities trading; by his opponent, Hillary Rodham
Clinton; and by gay rights advocates angered that he is skipping
the gay pride parade in Manhattan Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has offered minimal public responses as he seeks to
conduct congressional and campaign business in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's campaign aides say that clearly they have seen better
days but they do not think the wave of press coverage and attacks
by Clinton _ in television advertisements and a news conference
Thursday at City Hall _ will make a strong impression on voters. As
they prepared for a campaign swing upstate during the next couple
of days, they spoke of polls showing the race about even and
Lazio's intention to strike at themes popular among voters, like
high gas prices he will attribute to the Clinton administration's
energy policies.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio plans to speak out on the matter even though Hillary
Clinton has criticized him for missing a vote last week in the
House that would have created a heating oil reserve, an idea he
championed months ago to lower heating bills. Lazio caught a plan
to New York for campaigning instead. He also missed a news
conference Thursday scheduled by House Republicans to call on
President Clinton to take action on high gasoline prices. His aides
said he was giving an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Although on the defensive, Lazio largely kept up an upbeat
demeanor Friday. After talking to the business leaders primarily
about education, advocating things like at least one charter school
for every district lagging academically, Lazio walked into a hotel
conference room to a crowd of two dozen reporters and stood in
front of a bouquet of microphones. He then answered questions about
a Securities and Exchange Commission investigation of his
short-term windfall three years ago from the securities of a
company controlled by campaign contributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I spoke to my wife last night about this,'' Lazio
said. ``I was a little concerned when I spoke to her about how it
would affect me. She's just terrific. She said, `Listen, you know
what? We're honest, decent people. I clean my own house. We work
hard. We have nothing to be ashamed of. They're trying to drag you
down into the mud; don't let them do it.' And I'm not going to let
them do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio seemed to struggle with standing tough while keeping his
vow not to sound too negative.
</P>
<P>
   But it did not stop him from obliquely swinging at Clinton.
Asked if he thought the investigation was politically motivated, as
Lazio himself said last week, he replied: ``I think it's fairly
transparent. I think the Clinton camp is going to answer for
itself. And I think the people of New York are going to judge her
behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a reminder that Clinton faced a dose of unfavorable news
herself this week, something Republican strategists said they
feared would be lost in the coverage of the investigation of Lazio.
New polls showed her tied with Lazio. And although Robert Ray, the
independent counsel investigating the Clintons, said he would not
charge Clinton for her involvement in the firing of seven longtime
White House employees in 1993, he suggested she was more involved
than she has acknowledged. The employees were replaced by the
Clintons' supporters and relatives from Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Observers said such rocky times _ whatever the genesis _ were
inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has never been a successful New York public leader who
did not have to go under the microscope and take the heat,'' said
Adam Goodman, a former media adviser to Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's
Senate campaign. ``Rick Lazio has had a couple of things that put
him in the hot seat, and I think he has done well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 2345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
