<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-23 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3652 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-GASPRICES2NDTAKE-KAN &LR;      06-23 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
GAS TIGHT SUPPLIES, BAD LUCK, OPPORTUNISTS _ AND CRUDE PRICES _
REFLECTED AT GAS PUMP  
</HEADLINE>
 BC- GAS PRICES 2ND TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY STEVE EVERLY KNIGHT RIDDER NEWSPAPERS  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In early spring, the Explorer Pipeline Co.'s
line that runs from Tulsa, Okla., to St. Louis to Chicago had
problems and had to be shut down. That further hampered the buildup
of gasoline inventories in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turned out to be a very bad omen,'' said Costello.
</P>
<P>
   There were also some refinery outages. But compounding the
problem was a change in the formula for cleaner-burning
reformulated gas, which such cities as St. Louis and Chicago had to
start using June 1.
</P>
<P>
   There are differing views on the new formula's effect on
stockpiles. But the difficulty appeared to stem from production
problems in using ethanol, a cleaner-burning fuel made from corn,
in the Midwest to meet the stricter environmental standard.
Preoccupation with that problem appears to have affected the
production of conventional gasoline used in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   As Memorial Day approached, gasoline stockpiles in the Midwest
were nearly 20 percent below a year ago. Compounding the problem:
Motorists were in no mood to conserve, with gasoline consumption
expected to grow 3 percent compared with last summer.
</P>
<P>
   The simple solution to higher prices will be replenishing
gasoline inventories, which is unlikely this summer, Costello said.
</P>
<P>
   Stockpiles may be the underlying reason. But other factors may
also be in play, particularly when trying to explain the wild price
swings of recent weeks. The Mid-Continent wholesale gasoline market
priced regular unleaded gasoline at $1 a gallon June 6. That
climbed to $1.23 on June 15 and by June 21 had returned to $1.05,
according to Bloomberg Business News.
</P>
<P>
   Some point to futures and commodity traders as the cause of some
of the volatility.
</P>
<P>
   The futures are publicly traded on the New York Mercantile
Exchange and are seen as a good market indicator of what gasoline
can be sold for on the wholesale market. Any change in supply or
demand is quickly reflected in the futures.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just the messenger,'' said Craig Pirrong, an assistant
professor of finance at Washington University in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   And when supplies are tight, as they are now, said Pirrong, even
a fairly minor disruption of gasoline supplies is going to have a
big effect.
</P>
<P>
   The past few weeks provided examples. The Blue Mound refinery
shutdown was one. Another was blockage in a Louisiana waterway that
temporarily stopped oil from being delivered to a refinery. And
there were some difficulties with a pipeline in Michigan. Refining
profits
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the refiners. They're in a sensitive position.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime next month, refiners are expected to announce fatter
profits when they report second-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Ting, an analyst for Salomon Smith Barney, recently said
that profits for refiners in the Midwest had increased to $8.24 a
barrel _ or about 20 cents a gallon _ from about $3 a barrel in the
second quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the chairman of Conoco Inc. said in a statement that
increases in crude oil prices and a rebound in its ``downstream
business,'' which includes the company's refineries, could produce
second-quarter profits among the best in the 125-year-old company's
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rebound we've seen in downstream is very encouraging,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   There are no indications that the oil companies have plans to be
defensive about the earnings. A year ago, refineries were
struggling and at least some, according to quarterly financial
reports, were losing money.
</P>
<P>
   Big profits are needed to build more refining plants and meet
environmental regulations, said Sternfels of the National
Petrochemical &AMP; Refiners Association. If there's no money to build
additional capacity to make gasoline, he said, then the country is
going to have problems in meeting demand for gasoline for a ``long,
long, time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry needs to have a long run of profitability,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But for now the oil companies can expect greater scrutiny of
their every move. A federal official this week asked why gasoline
prices in Chicago, which have been over $2 a gallon, had not
declined after a 25 cent a gallon drop in the wholesale market.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a question being asked in Kansas City. On Tuesday at
least some wholesale gasoline was being made available to service
stations for 6 cents a gallon less than the day before.
</P>
<P>
   But by midday Tuesday, company-owned Texaco stations had
increased their prices to $1.88 a gallon. The stations are operated
by Equiva Services LLC, a joint venture of Texaco and Shell Oil.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors, particularly QuikTrip, which sells more gasoline in
Kansas City than anyone else, didn't follow the increase. On
Thursday, the lower wholesale prices flowed through to consumers,
with some stations, including QuikTrip, reducing pump prices to
$1.63. Texaco reduced its prices to $1.66.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Equiva was asked why Texaco prices had gone up to
$1.88. Myra Jolivet, a spokeswoman for Equiva, said costs had
increased.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crude prices have gone up,'' she said.
(30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
