<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRS. </SLUG>
 CLINTON-ADBOX  
 CLINTON CAMPAIGN LAUNCHES 5th AD ATTACKING LAZIO  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This is a 15-second commercial that Hillary Rodham
Clinton's Senate campaign began broadcasting Friday in upstate New
York.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER
</P>
<P>
   DeVito/Verdi, along with Mandy Grunwald, the media consultant,
and Mark Penn, the pollster.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SCREEN
</P>
<P>
   The commercial opens with the word ``update'' in white capital
letters on a black screen. The background remains black as the
script of the ad, read by an announcer, scrolls down the screen to
the sound of a Teletype machine. At the end, a small
black-and-white photograph of Clinton appears next to the tag line
showing the ad was paid for by her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCRIPT
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress just defeated a plan _ by only two votes _ to lower
home heating oil costs for New York and the Northeast. How did Rick
Lazio vote? He didn't. He skipped the vote. Rick Lazio. The more
you know . . . the more you wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   ACCURACY
</P>
<P>
   Lazio did miss the June 15 vote on a budget amendment that would
have set aside $10 million to establish an oil reserve that could
be tapped to limit surges in heating oil prices in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio was giving an interview during the vote. The measure,
which he had championed, was defeated, 195 to 193, but the ad does
not mention that five New York City Democrats also missed the vote.
</P>
<P>
   SCORECARD
</P>
<P>
   The commercial is the fifth in a barrage of attack ads released
by Clinton's campaign in recent days. The cost of heating oil is a
sensitive issue, especially in the colder regions of the state, and
the ad may well raise questions about Lazio with some voters.
</P>
<P>
   But the ad itself, a quick 15 seconds of text on the screen,
leaves no lasting visual impression. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
