<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-O'DONNELL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS' O'DONNELL TAKEN IN DRAFT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sean O'Donnell, the rugged defenseman who served
as a Los Angeles Kings alternate captain for three seasons, was
selected Friday by the Minnesota Wild in the 2000 NHL expansion
draft.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Steve McKenna also was taken by the Wild, who will join
the Columbus Blue Jackets as new teams this season.
</P>
<P>
   But it was O'Donnell who contributed most to the Kings' 94-point
showing last year, fourth best in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sean was here for six years and he will be missed,'' Kings
general manager Dave Taylor said from the expansion draft in
Calgary. ``We went to Minnesota several times with trade proposals
in an effort to keep him, but in the end they went in a different
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who now shifts his attention to today's entry draft for
amateur players, realized he had lost two of his more physical
players Friday, but he said the NHL is more geared toward speed and
defense.
</P>
<P>
   But Taylor also faces the prospect of losing both members of his
second defensive unit. Garry Galley, who played alongside
O'Donnell, is an unrestricted free agent. At age 37, Galley is not
expected to return.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell, 28, was drafted by Buffalo in June 1994 but joined
the Kings later that summer. Although he was a steady defenseman,
O'Donnell might be best known for a penalty he took during Game 3
of the Kings' 1998 first-round playoff loss to St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings trailed the series 2-0, but led the game 3-0 in the
third period when O'Donnell pummeled the Blues' Geoff Courtnall for
taking a shot at goaltender Jamie Storr. O'Donnell received a
five-minute major penalty and St. Louis scored four goals during
the man advantage before going on to sweep the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very difficult time after that, but I will never
forget how supportive my teammates were,'' said O'Donnell, who
could not be reached Friday. ``I never regretted what I did because
it was the right play, but I certainly regret the outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell, who earned $1 million last season, had two goals and
14 points. He did, however, score the winning goal in overtime
against Calgary on Feb. 14. O'Donnell also scored a goal in Game 2
of the Kings' first-round playoff loss to Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Off the ice, his father Emmitt suffered a stroke at the family
home in Ontario, forcing O'Donnell to miss one game and make
several trips back on off days.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings had hoped the 6-foot-7 McKenna, 27, would play an
enforcer role on the fourth line, but he was limited offensively
and played just 46 games.
</P>
<P>
   During the season, the biggest intrigue with McKenna was whether
he would participate in 40 games, which would have forced the team
to either protect or expose him to the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Even though McKenna was made available for expansion, the Kings
had scheduled him to play in Italy this summer for conditioning
purposes. Last season, he had just five assists, but his 125
penalty minutes were third on the club.
</P>
<P>
   Note: The Kings have the 20th pick in the first round. There are
nine rounds spread over two days. In addition to Taylor, Kings
coach Andy Murray and top amateur scout Al Murray are representing
the club in Calgary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-00 2351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
